<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-BIAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE CAPTAIN IS MADE POLICE CHEF TO SETTLE N.J. BIAS SUIT 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By DAVID M. HERSZENHORN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWAR, N.J. _ Settling a discrimination lawsuit in U.S.
District Court here, the city of East Orange agreed Tuesday to the
forced retirement of its first black police chief and to the
immediate promotion to chief of a white police captain who had
accused the city of illegal discrimination eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The captain, Richard Wright, a 30-year veteran of the East
Orange police force, became acting chief at noon Tuesday, minutes
after the settlement was read into the record before Judge Nicholas
Politan in U.S. District Court in Newark. In settling the case on
the day it was scheduled to go to a jury, East Orange agreed to
give Wright $50,000 in back pay, less than the actual difference
over eight years between the salary of a captain and a chief and
far less than what a jury might have awarded had it found in his
favor.
</P>
<P>
   At the crux of the settlement is the forced retirement of Chief
Harry Harman, a former lieutenant who became East Orange's first
black police chief when he was appointed by Mayor Cardell Cooper in
1990. Under departmental pension rules, Harman is not eligible for
retirement until later this month, and he has been placed on
administrative leave until then. The current mayor of East Orange,
Robert Bowser, helped arrange Tuesday's settlement.
</P>
<P>
   For Bowser, a black mayor of a predominantly black city, the
case was perhaps the thorniest political issue left behind by his
predecessor, Cooper. Several witnesses testified during the trial
that Cooper, who is also black, had been under pressure from black
ministers and black members of the City Council to appoint a black
police chief. Those pressures are felt in cities around the
country, where tensions can exist between minority residents and
mostly white police forces.
</P>
<P>
   In testimony Monday, Cooper defended his appointment of Harman,
saying he was proud to have made it even as he maintained that race
had not been a factor. But he also testified that he never
considered other candidates, a decision easy to criticize
considering Wright's credentials: highest in his class at the
police academy, and consistently a top scorer on exams for
promotion, including the exam for chief. Out of the 11 people who
passed the chief's test, Harman placed sixth.
</P>
<P>
   While the city did not acknowledge wrongdoing in settling the
case and was not required to apologize to Wright, Bowser and other
officials said they decided to settle because they expected to lose
the case, largely because of the testimony of Cooper, and wanted to
avoid the possibility of heavy damages and a costly appealing.
``Given all the factors involved in this case, it is better to cut
our losses at this point,'' Bowser said.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Tuesday evening outside City Hall, where he
was joined by the new police chief, Bowser announced the city's
decision to settle what he called a ``reverse racism lawsuit,'' and
said he feared the case could have been fiscally devastating.
``Following my predecessor Cardell Cooper's testimony yesterday at
the trial, we realized that any effort by the city to prolong this
case would have placed the taxpayers in a position of losing
millions of dollars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The case has already cost the city hundreds of thousands in
legal bills, he said. Bowser said the settlement would cost East
Orange more than $180,000, including $106,000 to cover Wright's
legal fees. After Harman's forced retirement, Bowser said he would
appoint Wright chief, for which the salary is $91,000 a year. Once
the appointment is confirmed by the City Council, Wright will serve
as chief through 1999, the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
   During a two-week trial, Wright's lawyer, Stephen Klausner,
presented several witnesses who testified that Cooper had pledged
to appoint a black police chief and had expressed an unwillingness
to consider anyone for the job who was not black.
</P>
<P>
   Bowser said Tuesday that Harman stood to lose the most if a jury
ruled against the city, because he might have been returned to his
previous rank of lieutenant. If the jury had found the city liable,
it also would have complicated things for Cooper, the former mayor,
who was nominated by President Clinton in July to be assistant
secretary for community planning and development at the Department
of Housing and Urban Development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
