<SLUG> BC-BBA-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DAVID WELLS _ AN OUTSIDER WHO BECAME AN INSIDER 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He chose this uniform as his symbol of the
establishment, the mark of excellence. He was the outsider, and he
loved the New York Yankees, the classic insiders.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night, David Wells kept moving toward major long-term
Yankee status, beating the Cleveland Indians, 7-2, in the first
game of the American League Championship Series. Wells now has a
6-1 record in post-season and had not given up a run in his last 23
innings in the post-season until yielding a two-run homer to Manny
Ramirez in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a rudimentary mustache and goatee, against the
clean-shaven Steinbrennerian standards, Wells struck out seven
batters. Each strikeout was noted by a No. 39 shirt hanging from
the upper deck, a tribute to the recuperating Darryl Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks went into the game still spluttering to themselves
about the inside pitches earlier this year from Cleveland's Jaret
Wright, who learned his intimidating tactics from his father,
Clyde, also a major league pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   If memory serves, there was also a knockdown mentality in
Seattle early this season, with Junior Griffey being low-bridged
two or three times by none other than David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the pitches that forced Griffey to perform the
limbo, and then glare balefully toward the mound, Wells snorted and
replied, ``If he can't take a joke, the heck with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells is a throwback to the grumpy pitchers of three and four
decades ago, but he practices a certain egalitarianism that
occasionally leads him to head-butt his own manager and gesticulate
when his own fielders botch a ball behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boomer is Boomer,'' Joe Torre says, rather frequently.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of major leaguers who carry a sense of
entitlement through their fathers, who learned the game as children
scuttling around big-league clubhouses _ the Stottlemyres and
Griffeys, the McRaes and Bondses, the Hundleys and Boones.
</P>
<P>
   Wells did not meet his father until he was an adult, by which
time he had developed his own blunt, sometimes bumptious
personality. He grew up around San Diego, familiar with the vroom
of motorcycles and the splash of poured beer, and his baseball
loyalties extended across the continent to the team with the
history of October bunting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Growing up in San Diego, being a Padre fan, being a Yankee
fan, I had to have an American League team,'' Wells said the other
day, adding that he had ``started early, just watching old films of
Yankee baseball, the tradition, all the winning teams they have
had, and to me it was awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, how can you not be a big fan of Yankee tradition with
all the greats they have had?'' Wells added. ``Just watching old
films of all the players and just the way things have happened for
this organization, and just the way they have played.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been very aggressive. Everybody hated them and, as a
kid, people hated certain teams that I liked. I was totally the
opposite. But just wanting to be in this city and hearing so many
stories about New York just made it even better.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells chose to come to the Yankees in 1997, and the Yankees took
awhile to warm up to him, but there was no missing his childlike
zest at being a Yankee. He even slipped on an authentic Babe Ruth
cap he had bought from a collector and wore it for an inning
against these very same Indians, until the Cap Police noticed him
and set off the warning Klaxons.
</P>
<P>
   ``That shows how much of a Yankee fan I am,'' he said. ``Not
only Babe Ruth, but the Yankees in general.''
</P>
<P>
   He loved pitching in Yankee Stadium, even before his perfect
game last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I had the opportunity, I got goose bumps walking out here
because you walk out to that monument, you see all the legends that
have played in this stadium,'' Wells said Monday. ``I was saying to
myself, hopefully, one day I can be in that monument and be part of
this. But I am a part of this, and I feel that every time I go out
there, it just helps me out, mentally and physically.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells made a huge leap in 1998, the perfect game being only a
side product. As David Cone said Tuesday night: ``We saw a
different David Wells this year. He battled the whole year long.
Never gave in and he really worked on his craft. I think he is a
much more cerebral pitcher _ if that is possible to say about David
Wells.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells put the Texas Rangers in an instant slump in the division
series. Tuesday night he may have set a tone for this series, in
the ball park of his childhood dreams.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
