</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SEAHAWKS-FLAP-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CORNERBACK PUTS PERSONAL TOUCH ON FAN INTERACTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Fred Thomas rises from the Kingdome Astroturf after
making a big play for the Seahawks, crosses his wrists and starts
wiggling his fingers.
</P>
<P>
   Fans imitate him, roaring their approval.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who plays cornerback and choreographer, has christened
this move ``the Seahawk Flap.'' For once, the term doesn't describe
a franchise shift, car accident or other legal skirmish.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the symbol of the team,'' Thomas said. ``It's like
something out of the movie `Killer Bees' or `The Birds' _ we're
always swarming.''
</P>
<P>
   Should this signature salute persist, and it has become more
visible with each home victory during the Seahawks' 3-2 start, a
patent or copyright might be in order. At the very least, an
explanation.
</P>
<P>
   The Seahawk Flap was created in, of all places, an Oakland hotel
room.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   T.J. Cunningham and Thomas, then special-team members, rookies
and roommates, decided the Seattle team needed something
demonstrative to signify big hits and big plays. In high school and
college, Thomas had danced to celebrate an electric moment but
finally conceded he was a bad dancer. Feet were out, hands were in.
</P>
<P>
   In their hotel room, the two Seahawk players experimented with
different routines. Try this, said Cunningham, a safety no longer
with the team. No, try this, responded Thomas. The Flap was born.
</P>
<P>
   They used it the next day, against the Raiders in a 28-21
victory, with little fanfare. Thomas alone flashed the Flap at
times last season. Again, nobody noticed. A lack of success, for
both the defensive back and his NFL team, had a way of obscuring
cuteness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many people didn't know what it was,'' Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   This season, that is changing. The Seahawks are not only have
been unbeatable at home so far, but Thomas, a second-round draft
pick who had been previously considered an underachiever, has
flourished.
</P>
<P>
   Fans are following his lead with the Flap. Teammates have jumped
on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's unreal,'' fellow cornerback Shawn Springs said. ``We're
going to have a whole city doing it. We're going to do commercials.
Fred started it.''
</P>
<P>
   Flap approval appears widespread among the Seahawks. As for
participation, holdouts remain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it fires up Fred and the crowd likes it, I'm for it,''
linebacker Chad Brown said. ``You probably won't catch Chad doing
it. Me, I'm not one for the dance.''
</P>
<P>
   For Thomas, the Seahawk Flap has been a nice diversion after two
seasons of unwanted attention. He struggled as an apprentice pro
defensive back, drawing much media criticism.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas was taken to task during the most recent preseason for
getting beat deep more than once, hitting a punt returner well
before arrival of the ball and offering a grisly, throat-slitting
gesture.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago, after the final exhibition game against the San
Francisco 49ers, Post-Intelligencer columnist Art Thiel dubbed
Thomas as the ``dumbest Seahawk player,'' and offered up the
following suggestion: ``Time for the NFL to consider SAT scores as
a job qualification.''
</P>
<P>
   The article was hand-delivered by teammates to Thomas, who found
it highly motivating and has played well since. Thomas claims he is
smarter than he appears.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want (Thiel) to know I made 875 on my SAT, and that's well
above the required number,'' he said emphatically.
</P>
<P>
   The throat-slitting gesture, he admits, was indefensible. A
couple of Seahawk club officials were equally unimpressed, and told
him so. Thomas was ordered not to do it again. No arguments from
No. 22. In hindsight, he realized he was promoting violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looked at as role models and kids are watching us,''
Thomas acknowledged. ``I sat back and thought, `It's not a good
thing,' so I don't do it anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   As an alternative, the Seahawk Flap was dusted off and given
another test run.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas always has been a creative sort. Before joining the
Seahawks, he went to four colleges in five years. He played the
1994 season in the Southeastern Conference, for the University of
Mississippi, returning an interception 83 yards for a score against
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   His stint with Ole Miss ended after his arrest on a felony
forgery charge for allegedly writing a check on another person's
account. Rather than accept a five-game suspension as punishment,
he transfered to Division II Tennessee-Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Thomas is a model citizen, father of one, improved NFL
cornerback and inventor of the Seahawk Flap. Regarding the latter,
people have suggested he take a serious look at marketing
possibilities. Already, he is thinking T-shirts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's becoming very contagious,'' the defensive back said.
``It's my own little personal thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is more than happy to discuss his creation. That way, no
copycats will emerge from the NFL's other bird-like teams, the
Eagles, Cardinals and Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   That might cause a Flap flap.
</P>
<P>
   HAWK TALK: The Seahawks lost DT Carl Hansen on Tuesday when the
New York Jets signed him off Seattle's practice squad. Hansen was a
sixth-round draft choice and although he wasn't able to beat out DT
Riddick Parker or DE Mike Croel for a spot on the 53-man roster, he
was signed to the practice squad because of his versatility and
potential. To fill Hansen's spot, the club plans to re-sign DT
Ralph Hughes, who was on the practice squad earlier this season.
... Sunday's game against the Broncos is essentially sold out,
meaning it will be the first home game this season to be shown on
Seattle-area TV and probably the first since 1993 to be sold out
before the Thursday blackout deadline. The last home game to be
shown on local TV was last year's season finale against the 49ers.
But KCPQ-TV guaranteed the sell out. The last game to be sold out
by the Thursday afternoon blackout deadline was against the Chiefs
and Joe Montana on Dec. 5, 1993. Only eight of 34 home games since
then have been televised locally, and in each case a sellout was
guaranteed by a TV station or sponsor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
