</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX CALLS AN AUDIBLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Just when USC appears on the cusp of a quarterback
controversy, the Trojans have added another quarterback to the mix.
</P>
<P>
   John Fox, who switched to tight end before the season, moved
back to quarterback Tuesday after telling coach Paul Hackett he
wanted to return to his original position.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's experiment began Aug. 14, the first week of training camp,
but he said that he began having doubts ``the second day'' after he
switched to tight end.
</P>
<P>
   When Fox first moved to tight end, he said, ``I'll never play
quarterback again.'' But Tuesday, he was back as USC's No. 3 signal
caller.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my love. That's really why I came here,'' Fox said of his
move back to quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been concerned about No. 3 (quarterback) all along,''
Hackett said. ``John felt comfortable making the move, so I said
fine. No more tight end.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox, who started nine games last season, appeared rusty as he
ran the scout team Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``(My goal is) to get better and just be there and prepare for
the spring,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   As for the other two USC quarterbacks, Hackett remained firm
that Mike Van Raaphorst was the starter but said Carson Palmer
might now enter a contest as soon as the second quarter. Hackett
also refused to rule out that Palmer might eventually start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to preclude that he's not going to start before
the end of the season,'' Hackett said. ``But I'm not going to say
that I expect him to, because I don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Raaphorst said he wasn't bothered by the third-quarter boos
when he came onto the field against Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fans are fans,'' he said. ``I guess they think I wasn't
producing. I just have to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The sophomore said it was reassuring that the starting position
is determined by Hackett and not the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's nice to know the guy in football operations
understands what's going on,'' Van Raaphorst said.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett also had a message for fans who clamor for Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to take a poll on how many years they've coached
quarterbacks,'' Hackett said. ``And then I'd like to put that
against how many years that I've coached quarterbacks, which is
about 29 now, and I would like to tell them to have patience and
trust me.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Morton still questionable: Tailback Chad Morton sat out
practice, and Hackett said he was hopeful the speedy runner would
return today or Thursday. Freshman Frank Strong strained his knee
near the end of practice, but Hackett said it was not serious.
</P>
<P>
   __ Veterans reclaim starting jobs: Hackett said senior
linebacker Mark Cusano and strong safety Grant Pearsall would
probably start Saturday against California. Their replacements _
linebacker Zeke Moreno and strong safety Ife Ohalete _ will
continue to play.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 0010EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0007 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 00:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3203 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT     10-07 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNSTOPPABLE YANKS CRUSH INDIANS IN ALCS OPENER 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Scoring lots of runs early would be nice, New York
Yankees manager Joe Torre mused before Tuesday night's playoff game
with Cleveland, as if he were considering a room service menu. And
the Yankees delivered.
</P>
<P>
   They pummeled the Indians' best pitcher, Jaret Wright, for five
runs in the first inning and went on to a 7-2 victory in the
opening game of the American League Championship Series. A crowd of
57,138 on a brisk fall evening at Yankee Stadium basked in the glow
of this seemingly unbeatable team, which needs three more victories
in this four-of-seven-game series to reach the World Series for the
second time in three years and the 35th time in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   Game 2 will be played Wednesday afternoon at the Stadium, with
David Cone pitching for the Yankees and Charles Nagy for the
Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Following a regular season in which they won 114 games, the most
in American League history, the Yankees are doing everything right
in the post-season. They swept Texas in the division series,
limiting the heavy-hitting Rangers to one run in three games, and
Tuesday night they rocked the Indians, with an immediate burst of
offense, consistently superb defense and more great pitching from
David Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who won 18 games this season, including a perfect game in
May, has allowed only 2 runs in 16 innings this post-season. The
Yankee left-hander had not been scored on in his last 23
post-season innings, dating to last year, before Manny Ramirez
unloaded a two-run home run off Wells in the ninth inning Tuesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians managed only four other hits off Wells, who was
removed after pitching to two batters in the ninth. The Yankees,
who have allowed just 3 runs and 18 hits in 36 innings in the
post-season, have now won 118 games in the regular season and
playoffs combined. That matches the total achieved by only one
other team in baseball history, the 1906 Chicago Cubs, in a
154-game season and a six-game World Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees, Torre agreed, are playing with great confidence.
Wells arrived at the Stadium on Tuesday afternoon seeming loose and
self-assured, wearing dark sunglasses, high-top basketball
sneakers, blue jeans and a T-shirt. Fans outside the players'
entrance screamed for him, and Wells nodded: No problem.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, he playfully donned a black jersey, with the
name of the heavy metal band Metallica stripped across the front,
and slipped into the dugout, jokingly suggesting that he might wear
this particular uniform on the field. If Wells felt nervous in any
way, he masked his feelings expertly.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe he and the Yankees have come to believe they are going
to win every game. It must have seemed that way to the Indians
right off the bat.
</P>
<P>
   Wright started for Cleveland, having beaten the Yankees twice in
the playoffs last year; this year, he was one of only five pitchers
who beat the Yankees twice in a regular season in which they lost
only 48 of 162 games. But the Yankees dismissed Wright on Tuesday
night as if they were wiping away an annoying insect.
</P>
<P>
   Tim Raines, their designated hitter Tuesday night, said on
Monday that the Yankees wanted to get runners on base and make
Wright throw from the stretch position, rather than have him
deliver from a full windup. ``We just don't think he's as
comfortable with runners on base,'' Raines said.
</P>
<P>
   They tested this theory immediately. Leading off the bottom of
the first, Chuck Knoblauch lined a single over second base, and
Wright had to work from the stretch. Derek Jeter then lined a
single through the middle, Knoblauch stopping at second.
</P>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill battled Wright to a full count _ Wright would throw
36 pitches in the first inning _ and then, with both runners moving
on the 3-2 pitch, O'Neill golfed a single to right, scoring one
run. When Bernie Williams lined a single through the middle, Jeter
raced and Chad Ogea scrambled to start warming up in the Cleveland
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Four batters into their lineup, the Yankees had a 2-0 lead and
two runners on base.
</P>
<P>
   After a force-play grounder to second by Tino Martinez left
runners at first and third, Martinez stole second on Raines'
strikeout. Now there were two out, and with another out, Wright
would be in good condition if he could get out Shane Spencer. But
he threw a curveball when it appeared the catcher Sandy Alomar was
expecting a fastball and the ball bounced between Alomar's legs for
a wild pitch. O'Neill crossed the plate from third with the
Yankees' third run. Spencer walked.
</P>
<P>
   Everything was going wrong for Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada lined a single to right, another run scoring, and
Wright was finished. Because one of Wright's close pitches broke
the left hand of Luis Sojo of the Yankees in spring training, the
Yankees have little regard for Wright, and fans at the Stadium
showed their disdain; as Wright walked off the field, head down,
the crowd roared mockingly, thanking him for his effort.
</P>
<P>
   After Scott Brosius singled off the reliever Chad Ogea, driving
in another run, Wright's line was complete _ two-thirds of an
inning pitched, five hits, five runs, one walk, one strikeout.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, the only Yankee pitcher who acknowledges the personalized
chants from the right-field bleachers when he is on the mound, had
a big lead and used it to his advantage. Usually aggressive anyway,
Wells challenged the Indians with fastballs, some sinking and some
riding high in the strike zone. Omar Vizquel got Cleveland's second
hit of the game in the third inning, and Wells then struck out both
Kenny Lofton and Joey Cora, two batters who have hit him hard in
the past.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Fryman bounced a grounder into the shortstop hole for
what appeared to be a two-out hit in the fourth. But Jeter, the
Yankees' shortstop, speared the ball as he moved toward the
third-base line, jumped and fired across the infield, the throw
beating Fryman to first by the width of a shoelace.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are doing everything right. They added runs in the
sixth and seventh innings, with Posada hitting a home run in the
sixth and O'Neill and Williams belting consecutive doubles in the
seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have acknowledged the inherent pressure in playing
the post-season after their stunning performance in the regular
season; they must win the World Series to assure their legacy, to
be recognized as one of baseball's greatest teams. If they lose in
the post-season, they will be remembered as a great team that never
achieved its goal.
</P>
<P>
   But there is inordinate stress on the Cleveland Indians, as
well. After winning 89 games, 25 fewer than the Yankees, during the
regular season; after seeing the Yankees' pitching dominate the
best-hitting team in the American League in the Division Series,
what is going through the minds of the Indians after the Yankees
knocked out their best pitcher in the first inning?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
