<HEADER>
A3212 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS &LR;      10-07 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LOCKOUT-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MURPHY  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
Instead of convening for training camp Tuesday, a number of NBA
players appeared at Westside Tennis Club in a show of solidarity
with their union, which is involved in an increasingly bitter labor
dispute with team owners.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among those in attendance were the Rockets' Hakeem Olajuwon,
Mario Elie, Othella Harrington, Brent Price and Joe Stephens; New
Jersey's Sam Cassell; Denver's Nick Van Exel; San Antonio's Avery
Johnson; Boston's Ron Mercer; Cleveland's Derek Anderson; Golden
State's Clarence Weatherspoon; and Phoenix's Mark Bryant.
</P>
<P>
   Because the owners have imposed a lockout, the players who
should have been preparing for the 1998-99 season instead got
together to hold a series of pickup games, sign autographs and
address the assembled media about the state of discussions between
the union and the owners.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's bad,'' said Price of the most recent proposal, of which
the Chronicle obtained a copy. ``It's very discouraging.''
</P>
<P>
   Players who discussed the matter Tuesday were unhappy with
several key points in the owners' latest proposal, among them:
</P>
<P>
   The gradual elimination of the Larry Bird exception, which
allows teams to re-sign their own free agents for any amount
regardless of the salary cap, which is the No. 1 issue in the
debate. According to the owners' proposal, the Bird exception would
be phased out over a period of three years, with a decreasing rate
of payment to those Bird-eligible players over that three-year
span, creating a hard salary cap at the end.
</P>
<P>
   An alternative plan would keep the Bird exception on the
condition that should salaries rise above 54 percent of
basketball-related income, players would pay the difference back
into an escrow account that would be jointly funded by the NBA and
the players. Should the salaries fall below that first-year number
of 54 percent, the difference would be paid out of the account.
That percentage would drop to 52 percent in the second year and 50
percent in the third year.
</P>
<P>
   Individual player salaries would be tied to a percentage of the
salary cap. Specifically, no new salary could exceed 30 percent of
the salary cap at the time the contract is signed or, if the player
were already making more than 30 percent of the cap, 105 percent of
the player's previous salary.
</P>
<P>
   The league office would provide teams with the amount offered to
free agents by other teams. The union thinks this provision would
severely curtail free agents' bargaining power.
</P>
<P>
   Possible elimination of the $1 million salary-cap exception.
</P>
<P>
   A period of offseason training under team supervision would be
required.
</P>
<P>
   The current three-year rookie salary scale would be lengthened
by one year for each year a player is under age 20 when drafted.
For example, if an 18-year-old high school player is drafted in the
first round, he would be bound to the team that owns his rights for
five years. In addition, teams would have an option for an
additional two years at the end of any rookie-scale contract.
</P>
<P>
   Most player contracts would be limited to five years, including
an option year.
</P>
<P>
   Performance bonuses would be limited to 5 percent of a player's
salary. That would eliminate a contract like the one Dennis Rodman
signed with the Bulls last season, where he had a salary of $4.5
million but earned almost $6 million in bonuses based on
performance and behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Union president Billy Hunter flew in last week to go over the
latest proposal with the Houston-area players, and few were happy
after the briefing.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal we received last week upset a lot of players,''
said former Rocket Purvis Short, now director of player programs
for the players association. ``The players were very unhappy with
the demands that were made. The league is basically asking for a
lot of concessions by the players _ a lot of unreasonable
concessions.''
</P>
<P>
   Concessions the players are unwilling to make.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are awaiting the result of an arbitration hearing
that will decide whether owners are obligated to pay about 220
guaranteed contracts while the lockout is in effect, a ruling that
should come no later than Oct. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proposal, if you guys (the media) could see a copy of it,
was really not a proposal,'' said Johnson, a former Rocket who
lives in the Houston area. ``I think the situation is getting
worse. It's like anything _ you have so much pride and so many egos
involved that maybe one side is not doing what's best for the game
of basketball. When they send us a proposal (like the one) they
sent us last time, that's not even negotiating.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we're disappointed about. We're trying to address
all of their (the owners') needs (like) salaries outpacing
revenues. We're trying to address those issues and come up with
creative ways to get them comfortable, but they don't even want to
talk about it unless it's a hard cap.''
</P>
<P>
   Now that the exhibition season has been canceled and training
camps have been delayed indefinitely, some players are bound to
start getting antsy about what lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last proposal we got was worse than the first one,'' Elie
said. ``I don't blame the players association for rejecting it. But
I do think that both sides just have to meet each other halfway.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real disappointed. Hopefully, something can get resolved
soon. There's a big (arbitration) ruling next week, so we're just
keeping our fingers crossed that both sides can agree on
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, I didn't think it was going to be this
serious,'' he said. ``But now it's getting so big that I think both
parties need to sit down like gentlemen so they can compromise and
work things out. That's the only way I think people resolve
problems, by sitting down and working it out.''
</P>
<P>
   But time is running out.
</P>
<P>
   Many players are beginning to wonder if there is a point of no
return at which the regular season has to be wiped away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the real deadline (for reaching an agreement) was
Oct. 1, and that's over,'' Johnson said. ``Now, the real deadline
is Nov. 3 or 4, when the regular season was supposed to start. I
don't really want to play an abbreviated season, (playing only) 60
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we have to get a deal done and (NBA commissioner) David
Stern and his people have to be more open to our creative ways of
addressing their problems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
