<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA WILL BE SANS LEWIS AT ARIZONA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Third-ranked UCLA will face No. 10 Arizona on
Saturday without starting tailback Jermaine Lewis, who has been
suspended indefinitely for his involvement in a weekend fight.
</P>
<P>
   A Lancaster native, Lewis was not seriously hurt. He has not
been arrested and told coach Bob Toledo it wasn't his fault. But he
was identified in a campus police report, prompting the suspension
on Tuesday. It will remain in effect until the investigation is
complete.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a police report, and when it gets to that point,
there's a suspension,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jermaine cried (upon being told about the suspension), and he
felt bad. He's sorry and, supposedly, it wasn't his fault. But I
don't want guys in positions where they get in fights. If it
starts, you have to walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Toledo suspended starting nose guard Damon Smith for
fighting several days before the USC game. Smith missed that game
and did not start the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   A sophomore, Lewis is UCLA's top rusher at 90 yards per game,
and he leads the Pacific-10 in scoring with eight touchdowns.
Junior Keith Brown will start at Arizona _ where the Bruins have
not won in 10 years _ with true freshman DeShaun Foster moving to
second string and walk-on Mark Reynosa to third.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a whole different game now,'' Foster said.
</P>
<P>
   According to campus police, the incident occurred at
approximately 1:30 a.m. Sunday at 525{ Landfair, near fraternity
row. The police report was filed Monday afternoon and the case will
go to detectives this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, at this point, it's somebody filing a report and
we're investigating it,'' said Nancy Greenstein, a spokesperson for
campus police.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo said the male, who is not a UCLA student, needed several
stitches. Several UCLA players broke up the fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``The players claim it ended real fast,'' Toledo said. ``Then
all of a sudden on Monday there's a police report. The guy didn't
do anything Sunday. But you can't continue to fight. You have to
walk away.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins treated Lewis' suspension with a mix of sadness and
steadfastness. For perspective, Toledo told them about a similar
situation in 1995, when UCLA defeated USC without star tailback
Karim Abdul-Jabbar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just going to treat this like an injury,'' said
offensive tackle Kris Farris. ``We've been in a lot of big games
without good players.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster and Brown have combined for 188 yards this season _ 82
fewer than Lewis _ but each played his best game of the season
Saturday against Washington State. Brown rushed for two touchdowns;
Foster gained 77 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a starter and DeShaun's not a starter, and there's
concern about whether we can get the job done,'' said Brown, a
Phoenix native. ``Of course, I think we can.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of weight on me. As soon as I heard (about the
suspension), I felt a little pressure. But it's my opportunity to
show what I can do. You live for situations like this. I can't wait
to get on the field and show my thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster credited his playing time for reducing the pressure. In
addition to 25 carries this season, he has returned six punts and
five kickoffs in place of the injured Freddie Mitchell. A few words
of encouragement from Foster's offensive line Tuesday didn't hurt,
either.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had just gotten reps here and there, I'd probably be
nervous,'' he said. ``But I feel comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   If anything, Tuesday's practice was more spirited than usual. It
culminated with Foster scoring a touchdown and getting mobbed by
his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't change things too much,'' said quarterback Cade
McNown. ``We've got three tailbacks. You like to have all the
weapons you can. But Keith and DeShaun are guys that have both
proven themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
