<P>
   OFF-THE-MENU (Undated) _ When Michael Eisner, the chairman of
Disney, goes to La Grenouille, he doesn't look at the menu. Doesn't
have to. The chef, Daniel Orr, designs a meal just for him. And
when Ronald O. Perelman, the chairman of Revlon, dines at Harry
Cipriani he almost always has roasted halibut served with a slab of
tomato, capers and oregano. It is prepared for him alone. At the
same restaurant, Oscar de la Renta, the clothing designer, orders
riso alla valenziana every single time he comes. Never mind that it
doesn't happen to be on the menu. In fact, that may be the point,
as some restaurant observers believe: treat the royalty royally and
they will return time and again, adding a less than subtle glitz to
the restaurant's cachet. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
