<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: YANKS QUICKLY DISPEL DOUBTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In lightning-like fashion, the New York Yankees
deflated all of the talk and answered all of the questions.
</P>
<P>
   How would they fare against Jaret Wright, who beat them twice
last October? Who had the greater incentive to win this American
League Championship Series, they or the Cleveland Indians? Would
the hitters at the top of the Yankees' lineup wake up or slumber
their way through the post-season? Could the Yankees' pitchers
continue the dominating performances that left the league's other
best-hitting team wondering who put those holes in their bats?
</P>
<P>
   With an awesome array of first-inning singles and another
head-shaking effort by David Wells, the Yankees dispatched the
Indians, 7-2, Tuesday night and took a commanding one-game lead in
the prelude to the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Commanding lead? After the first game in a four-of-seven-game
series? Given the developments at Yankee Stadium, that assessment
might not be premature.
</P>
<P>
   The significance of the first-inning eruption cannot be
emphasized too strongly. The Yankees' hitters did not win the
division series against the Texas Rangers. Sure, they produced
enough runs to win the three games, but if the pitchers had allowed
the Rangers to hit as they did all season, nine runs would not have
been sufficient.
</P>
<P>
   A similar hitting effort might place too much responsibility on
the Yankee pitchers, even though pitching had really been the
team's strength most of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to pitch,'' manager Joe Torre had said before the game
when he was asked what his concerns were approaching the series.
``When we have pitched well during the course of the year, we have
won or at least had been there to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But in this game, before the Yankees knew for sure that Wells
would pitch brilliantly again, the hitters did their part. Not that
Wells wouldn't have pitched the same game with the same success,
but the first-inning breakout made his job easier. With the
exception of some closers, pitchers would much rather pitch with a
big early lead. That's what the Yankees gave their starting pitcher
for the first time in this post-season.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, who batted .091 in the Texas series, led off
the first inning by lining a single to right field. Derek Jeter,
who batted .111, lined a single to center. Paul O'Neill lined a
single to right, driving in the first run. Bernie Williams, who
didn't get a hit in 11 at-bats against the Rangers, lined a single
to center, and the Yankees had two runs against Wright, who beat
them in the second and fifth games of last year's five-game
division series.
</P>
<P>
   Wright was also one of only five pitchers who gained two
victories against the 114-48 Yankees this season. Had the Yankees
allowed him to continue his mastery over them, the series could
have taken on a tone they hadn't anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   But they turned out to be right and Wright wrong. After throwing
only 36 pitches, hardly enough to develop a sweat on a 51-degree
night, and getting only two outs, Wright was gone, having
registered the briefest outing for a starting pitcher in a league
series game in 22 years.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1976 playoff series between the Yankees and the Kansas
City Royals, Dennis Leonard left the fifth and decisive game after
facing the first three batters in the Yankees' lineup and retiring
none of them. If that game sounds distantly familiar, it was the
one that Chris Chambliss won with a ninth-inning home run,
catapulting the Yankees into their first World Series since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   The combination of the explosion against Wright and the Indians'
inability to hit Wells indicated that the Yankees' progression to
the next step this year won't be as dramatic.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who triggered the sweep of the Rangers by pitching eight
shutout innings, extended his post-season shutout string to 23
consecutive innings before Manny Ramirez hit a two-run home run in
the ninth inning. Until the home run, the Yankees' starters had a
1998 post-season record of one run allowed in 28 2/3 innings and
the pitching staff over-all a record of one run in 35 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' staff, in other words, had a post-season earned run
average of 0.26. Earned run averages don't get much more minuscule
than that.
</P>
<P>
   In holding the Rangers practically scoreless, the Yankees became
the first team to allow only one run in any of the 169 post-season
series that have been played. They can't duplicate that feat in
this series, but Wells sure made a good beginning.
</P>
<P>
   The left-hander, who had produced one of the most eye-opening,
seasonlong performances of 1998, added to his post-season luster by
allowing the Indians only three hits, all harmless singles, until
the ninth. Between the second and third singles, he set down 11
batters in order.
</P>
<P>
   Only once did the Indians put two runners on base in the same
inning, and then the irrepressible left-hander ended it with a
flourish, striking out Richie Sexson.
</P>
<P>
   If this series should continue as the first one did after Wells
foiled the Rangers, Wells may not get to pitch again until the
World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But then, the Yankees can't be too premature in their plans.
Maybe they should wait until they play Wednesday's second game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
