<HEADLINE>
Y2K COMPUTER PROBLEM A CAMPAIGN ISSUE IN CONNECTICUT 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ Candidates who thought they had their fall rap
down pat _ smaller class sizes (good), health insurers (bad), new
taxes (really bad) _ suddenly find themselves fielding a new issue:
the millennium bug.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2000 problem, popularly known as Y2K, has programmers
hustling to rework computers that recognize years by their last two
digits, so that '00 means 1900 and possible mayhem when 2000
arrives. Now the bug is being used by challengers for offices
around the country to suggest that incumbents are too slow to
defuse a time bomb that could result in late checks, or worse.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the high yawn factor, one problem with the year 2000
problem as a campaign issue is that it will not be a problem for a
while. But that does not stop candidates from trying to capitalize
on it.
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, state Rep. Christopher Scalzo, the Republican
candidate for comptroller, has been offering himself as ``a fighter
for working families,'' and his main issue has been the handling of
payments for the state employees' health insurance by Democratic
incumbent Nancy Wyman.
</P>
<P>
   This is the typical fare of a down-ballot campaign. Wednesday,
though, Scalzo plans to enliven the comptroller's race by holding a
news conference to assail Mrs. Wyman's efforts to get her office
ready for the millennium _ ``Y2K compliant,'' as the computer
experts say _ and to help city and town officials with their own
conversions.
</P>
<P>
   Scalzo says that at the press conference he will release a
consultant's report indicating that Mrs. Wyman's office has not
finished updating and testing its computers. ``Either Nancy Wyman
doesn't know what's going on in her office, or she doesn't
understand what's going on in her office,'' he said Tuesday,
limbering up his millennial sound bites.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Wyman said in response that she had never claimed that the
job was finished. ``We're up and running with two of our three core
financial systems,'' she said. ``The third one will be complete in
the early part of 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Faucheux, the editor in chief of Campaigns and Elections
magazine, said the year 2000 problem has been brought up in several
statewide races this year, mostly by candidates who say they will
do their best to fix it. Their opponents usually agree that is a
good idea, and so it has not been an issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not something people are going to draw blood on this
year,'' Faucheux said. ``This will be an issue in 2000 or 2002 if
something goes wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   In Connecticut, though, Mrs. Wyman has been discussing the topic
for months and promising that when 2000 comes, the state will be
able to send out checks on time. She had been considered a safe bet
for re-election, but her campaign workers have become nervous as
polls showed the top of the Democratic ticket, U.S. Rep. Barbara
Kennelly, flailing in her campaign for governor.
</P>
<P>
   In August, Mrs. Wyman announced that by using her own staff, she
would be able to convert her office's computers for $750,000
instead of the $6 million that one consultant had demanded. In
September, she announced she was creating a ``Year 2000 municipal
help desk'' and a Web site for local governments.
</P>
<P>
   ``My agency could not keep our valuable year 2000 knowledge and
experience to ourselves,'' she said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   That was more fodder for Scalzo, 34, a former currency broker
who lives in Fairfield County. ``She's throwing the gasoline of
political rhetoric on the fire of Y2K,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Wyman, 52, said that she should receive credit for her
foresight in solving a problem that still perplexes many
businesses. ``It's an issue, and a proud issue,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
