<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-OFFENSE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS WHO LAGGED EARLIER NOW COME OUT SLUGGING 
</HEADLINE>
 (bl) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Paul O'Neill listened to one question about why there
had been such a paucity of production from the first five Yankees
in the lineup, and then another and another. Finally, O'Neill
raised his hands in protest and posed a question of his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't get what the big story is about our lineup,'' O'Neill
said. ``We won, didn't we?''
</P>
<P>
   The scene took place after Monday's workout, and O'Neill was
correct: the New York Yankees had won three straight games over the
Texas Rangers. But the type of answer that O'Neill really wanted to
supply came Tuesday night in the first inning, as the first five
Yankees all reached base, with four of them scoring during a
five-run effort. It was a major reason why David Wells and the
Yankees sprinted to a 7-2 victory over Cleveland in Game 1 of the
American League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees who had been invisible against the Rangers were back
for one nifty inning and beyond Tuesday night. Chuck Knoblauch, who
had gone 1 for 11 in the division series, poked a single to right
field to start the game. Derek Jeter who went 1 for 9 against
Texas, did not wilt after falling behind in the count, 0-2, and
lined a single to center.
</P>
<P>
   Wright had barely dug a hole in front of the rubber, and already
he was sweating.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, the ornery respondent, had actually been a respectable
4 for 11 in the first round, and he gave the Yankees a 1-0 lead
Tuesday night by stroking a single to right. Bernie Williams, who
had spent the three games against Texas looking lost, going hitless
in 11 at bats, followed O'Neill in search of one measly hit.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre had intimated that Williams might be placing
too much pressure on himself because the post-season can be so
fatal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's anything other than being in a short series
and wanting to win,'' Torre said. ``It's not like during the season
when you have a couple of hitless games and you can come back
because you have 160 games left. It takes a lot to tell yourself
not to put too much emphasis on each at-bat.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams' first time at-bat Tuesday night was very
important, because he belted a single to center to lose the .000
average and put the Yankees ahead, 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   The hit was probably the most important of the night for the
Yankees, because Williams had been 6 for his Tuesday 52 in the
post-season, and the Yankees need him to contribute more than that.
Williams continued to unwind later, combined with O'Neill on
back-to-back doubles in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   When asked beforehand whether he would alter anything for
Tuesday night's game, Williams had sounded like a seventh-grader
who had been told his science project was awful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't know what to change,'' he said. ``I have the same
swing I've had all year.''
</P>
<P>
   It worked. Even though Tino Martinez, who was 3 for 11 against
the Rangers, followed Williams' first-inning hit with a tapper to
second for a fielder's choice, it was a fresh beginning for the
first five players in the batting order. They were fabulous once
more, at least for one inning. Jorge Posada and Scott Brosius added
run-scoring singles, and another run scored on a wild pitch to give
the Yankees and their quintet a 5-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to see us get out early and get some production from
the top half,'' Torre had said. ``Just to get everyone
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, everyone was comfortable. Maybe even Williams. For
many Yankee fans, the lasting image of the 1997 division series is
not O'Neill's scorched double off the right-center-field fence in
the ninth inning of the final game. It is of Jose Mesa's next
pitch, the pitch Williams flicked to left for the final out of the
game. There was scant time to rejoice in O'Neill's hit, because
Williams did not deliver the tying run, and the stunned Yankees
were sent home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know one thing, that last year Bernie was very disappointed
when he made the last out,'' Torre said. ``Let's admit it, the year
before, everything Bernie made contact with was a homer or a hit.''
</P>
<P>
   But Williams said: ``Last year is last year. This is a new year.
There are two teams that are both different.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it was impossible to ignore the obvious. Williams was in
such a depression after making the final out against the Indians
last year that Torre called him in Puerto Rico and spoke to him in
the soothing, simplistic way that explains why he is the perfect
manager for this often perfect team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told him he can't expect to get a hit every time up,''
Torre said. ``He had to let it go.''
</P>
<P>
   Has Williams let the recent post-season trouble vanish? Maybe on
Tuesday night did it for him. The center fielder who could be
playing his final three weeks with the Yankees finally had some
hits and some relief. Just like the rest of the teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I've been pressing,'' Williams had said before
the game. ``It's kind of tough to answer that right now, but I
don't think so.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
