<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA FANS HAVEN'T FORGOTTEN POLI-DIXON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Brian Poli-Dixon does not expect a warm welcome
Saturday night in his hometown. In fact, reaction might be
downright hostile for the Tucson native, who starts at split end
for UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a college town and the whole town gets behind the team,''
Poli-Dixon said. ``This game is a big milestone for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon, who attended Sabino High, is one of three Bruins
with Arizona ties. Freshman guard Mike Saffer, another Sabino grad,
is sitting out this season as a redshirt. He won't travel because
of the 60-man limit for conference games. Asked if he'll go on his
own, Saffer quipped: ``Too hot for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tailback Keith Brown, who will start in place of suspended
Jermaine Lewis, attended Mountain Pointe High in Phoenix. His
brother, Curtis, attended Arizona, and Brown estimates he'll have
45-50 friends and family members in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   Poli-Dixon's departure might have stung Tucson most, since the
Wildcats have long lacked elite receivers. He considered Arizona,
even took an official recruiting visit, but eventually passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good school, a good team, and it's home,'' he said.
``But at the same time I wanted to get away from Tucson, get out of
the state.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ring the Bell: Cornerback Chris McAlister gets the accolades,
but linebacker Marcus Bell could be Arizona's best defensive
player. Certainly, he joins Rob Waldrop and Joe Salave'a on the
list of lightly recruited players who have blossomed under Wildcats
coach Dick Tomey.
</P>
<P>
   Bell played football and wrestled at tiny St. Johns (Ariz.)
High, and he never lost a competition. He was recruited by Arizona,
Northern Arizona and Brigham Young. After two years as a reserve,
he leads the Pac-10 with 11.6 tackles per game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's what's wrong with (recruiting services),'' Tomey said.
``He's just a great player.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Falling in place?: A close examination of UCLA's schedule
reveals several examples of potentially beneficial timing for the
Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   They play Arizona just a week after the Wildcats' emotional win
at Washington.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 17 the Bruins play Oregon, one week after the Ducks
visit Washington State.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 24 they play Cal, a week after the Bears visit Husky
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   They play Stanford a week after it faces Arizona State in Tempe.
</P>
<P>
   And they play Washington a week after the Huskies visit Oregon,
perhaps the fiercest rivalry in the league.
</P>
<P>
   __ Schedule update: Kickoff for the Oct. 17 UCLA-Oregon game at
the Rose Bowl is 12:30 p.m. It will be televised by ABC. Kickoff
for the Oct. 24 game at Cal probably will be announced Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
