u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKEES-INDIANS-B     10-07 0932
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKEES-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES DELIVER KNOCKOUT PUNCH IN FIRST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Our forebears likened rooting for the Yankees to
rooting for US Steel.
</P>
<P>
   How now, at the end of the millennium, to express that sentiment
in a way our progeny will understand?
</P>
<P>
   Rooting for Microsoft? For the IRS? Or, as Pedro Martinez in a
Yoda mask might say, for the Dark Side?
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say, the Yankees were at their invincible best in
beating the Cleveland Indians, 7-2, Tuesday night in Game 1 of the
American League Championship Series, a truly frightening spectacle,
given their track record of laying waste to everything in their
path this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored five runs in the first inning, then added a
sixth-inning home run by Jorge Posada and back-to-back doubles by
Paul O'Neill and Bernie Williams in the seventh to build a 7-0 lead
for lefthander David Wells, the tattooed perfectionist who did not
allow an Indian to reach third base until Manny Ramirez's
upper-deck home run with a man aboard in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Wells did not miss a spot until the ninth inning,'' said
Indians manager Mike Hargrove, who was left in an untenable spot
when his starter, the 22-year-old Wright, missed precious few
Yankee bats while lasting just two-thirds of an inning.
</P>
<P>
   That was rough treatment for a kid who last season beat the
Yankees twice in the postseason, beat them again twice this season,
and had made himself something of a marked man here because of
charges of headhunting after he broke Yankee infielder Luis Sojo's
hand with a pitch in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message to the fans was, heh-heh, unbelievable,'' Wells
said. ``They deserved that. They're such dedicated fans, they hold
grudges more than we do. To see Jaret go out in the first inning
was _ I don't know how to say this; I don't want to say this _ very
gratifying.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells, who had permitted just four singles before Ramirez
connected, struck out seven, walked one, and set down 11 in a row
between Omar Vizquel's single with one out in the third and David
Justice's single to open the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nelson replaced Wells after Ramirez's 12th postseason home
run and got the final two outs, his game-ending strikeout of Jim
Thome the cue for dozens of police officers in helmets to come
sprinting onto the field, followed shortly by more than a dozen
cops on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   Such a show of force typically occurs only when there is a
championship clinching in the offing. Maybe this was a dress
rehearsal for a celebration to come, or perhaps that unabashed
Yankee booster, Mayor Rudy Giuliani, was expecting the Indians to
call it a series after just one game.
</P>
<P>
   Given what lies ahead, perhaps they should. Wells is to be
followed this afternoon by 20-game winner David Cone, then
lefthander Andy Pettitte, who has won more games (55) in the last
three years than any other pitcher in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most teams only have one No. 1,'' Hargrove said. ``The Yankees
are a little more blessed than others.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians have now lost the first game in their last eight
postseason series, including last week's Division Series against
the Red Sox, and while they came back to prevail against the Sox,
to do the same against the Yankees stretches credulity.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have now won a season-high 11 in a row and have
allowed just three runs in four postseason games.
</P>
<P>
   They might be talking about winning their third straight World
Series, Cone said, if the Indians hadn't bounced them in the
Division Series a year ago. The Yankees were five outs away from
eliminating Cleveland in Game 4, only to have Sandy Alomar hit a
series-turning home run off Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   But manager Joe Torre shredded the notion that the Yankees were
under any extra pressure to exact revenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always have pressure,'' Torre said before the game. ``Any
time you wear pinstripes, you start spring training expecting to go
to the World Series.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the pull of history should be greater than settling an
old score for the Yankees, who have matched the 1906 Cubs for most
wins by any team in a season, playoffs included. The Cubs won 116
games in the regular season, then two more in a World Series they
lost to the crosstown White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   For Red Sox fans, the spanking administered to Wright should
have looked familiar. Just last week, the Sox had opened single,
single, Mo Vaughn home run against Wright, the pitcher Indians
general manager John Hart refused to trade for Pedro Martinez last
fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' six singles in the first, the first five of which
came against Wright, set an ALCS record for singles in an inning.
The first four Yankees to come to the plate _ Chuck Knoblauch,
Derek Jeter, O'Neill, and Williams _ all hit safely, plating two
runs.
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez grounded into a force play for the first out, but
a third run scored when Alomar couldn't smother Wright's wild
pitch. Tim Raines whiffed, but Wright walked Mantle stand-in Shane
Spencer, and Posada singled home Martinez to make it 4-0.
</P>
<P>
   Wright was done, but the Yankees weren't. Scott Brosius greeted
reliever Chad Ogea with a run-scoring single to make it 5-0 before
Knoblauch, batting for the second time in the inning, finally
tapped out.
</P>
<P>
   It was the 36th time this season the Yankees had batted around.
</P>
<P>
   Wells, meanwhile, took the mound to the sounds of one of his
head-banging favorites, Van Halen's ``Running With the Devil.''
Call it theme music for the Dark Side.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
