<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALCS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WRIGHT STUFF IS LACKING AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 SIDEBAR-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Can Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove give the ball to
Jaret Wright for another start in the American League Championship
Series?
</P>
<P>
   Wright was routed in the first inning of Tuesday night's 7-2
loss to the Yankees in Game 1. He gave up singles to the first four
hitters and was unable to complete the inning. Hargrove needed long
man Chad Ogea to finish the first, which ended with the Yankees
leading, 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we get to Game 5, all bets are off,'' said Hargrove when
asked about bringing Wright back in turn. ``I'd have to look to
anybody. I would have to consider all the options.''
</P>
<P>
   The pummeling of Wright comes on the heels of his shaky
performance against the Red Sox in the first game of the Division
Series. Against Boston, Wright gave up hits to the first three
batters, including Mo Vaughn's three-run homer. He did not survive
the fifth inning of an 11-3 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, Derek Jeter, Paul O'Neill, and Bernie Williams
opened the bottom of the first with back-to-back-to-back-to-back
singles. After a ground out and a strikeout, Wright walked
wonderboy Shane Spencer and surrendered an RBI single to Jorge
Posada. He was lifted after throwing only 36 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a combination of bad things,'' said Wright. ``The
location of my fastball was off. I was trying to make good pitches
and I didn't _ that's about it. I wasn't out there too long. I fell
behind in the count, and then you have to come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove said Wright's basic problem was twofold.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was up in the strike zone and he was in the middle of the
plate,'' said Hargrove. ``I don't care how hard you throw; if you
do that, you aren't going to last very long. Jaret went out and
gave us his best shot. I've seen him better. But am I angry at him?
No.''
</P>
<P>
   There is some bad blood between the Yankees and Wright that made
last night's easy win that much sweeter for the Yankee Stadium
crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Wright beat the Yankees twice in four days of last year's
Division Series to knock the New Yorkers out of the tournament. In
a spring training game this year, he broke the hand of Yankees
infielder Luis Sojo with a pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday night's Yankees starter, David Wells, painted the
22-year-old Wright as a classic headhunter, and New York's tabloids
used the revenge motive to inject some emotion into this series.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking with the media Monday, Wright, son of former Angels
lefthander Clyde Wright, said, ``It's about the third time I have
been asked if I'm hitting people or not. I'm out there trying to
get outs. I'm out there trying to keep my team in the ballgame.
It's baseball, and people get hit sometimes. But it is nothing. It
is not a revenge factor, I don't think.''
</P>
<P>
   It might not have been a revenge factor for Yankee players, but
the raucous Bronx crowd booed Wright with gusto during
introductions and hooted madly when he was hooked with two outs in
the first.
</P>
<P>
   In five innings over two starts in this postseason, Wright has
surrendered 11 runs and caused batters to swing and miss only seven
times. He appears to have lost some velocity since his impressive
1997 postseason.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still fairly young,'' said Wright. ``I look to learn from
this. There have been worse days. Sometimes it happens. Sometimes
you lose. It wasn't my day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
