<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 00:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3235 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-INDIANS-NYT &LR;      10-07 0681
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS, PARTICULARLY WRIGHT, ARE HUMILIATED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A humbled Jaret Wright shuffled off the field as the
crowd hurled insults and taunts at him high and tight. All he could
do was duck.
</P>
<P>
   Crestfallen and stunned, Wright slipped into the Cleveland
Indians' dugout early Tuesday night. The pitcher who had been
labeled a headhunter and cast as Public Enemy No. 1 before his
start in Game 1 of the American League Championship Series had just
dissolved, much to the delight of a crowd that packed every blue
inch of Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   He simply came undone, lasting just two-thirds of an inning in
the Cleveland Indians' 7-2 loss to the Yankees. He gave up five
runs _ an ALCS record for one inning _ under a barrage of lined
singles.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was the pressure of the moment, the hostility
surrounding his start or the focus of the revenge-seeking Yankees
that caused Wright to buckle so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, the Yankees' nemesis, armed with an
unapologetic attitude and a dangerous fastball, was gone after 36
pitches in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   Wright not only had been the young charmer who popped up to beat
the Yankees twice in the division series a year ago, he had been at
the center of a feud that began seven months ago. In the spring,
Wright hurled a high and tight fastball that left a ducking Luis
Sojo with a broken left hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jaret is not a headhunter,'' Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove
had said on Monday, defending his Game 1 pitcher. ``But for Jaret
to be effective, he has to pitch inside. And that is part of the
game.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the way Wright looked at it, too. After he hit Sojo,
there was no apology, not even a sympathetic nod from Wright, who
hit a dozen batters this season. Leading up to Game 1, Wright's
response to hitting Sojo was, ``That's baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Sojo said: ``The way it happened, he was going for my head. And
you can't do that. It's one thing to be aggressive, but you don't
go for my head.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation was only made worse when Wright hit Paul O'Neill
on June 19; and Wright picked up the victory in that game. During
the regular season, Wright's playoff success of 1997 carried over.
He was one of only four pitchers to beat the Yankees twice this
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Win, and that's our revenge,'' Sojo said. ``That's how you get
back at someone.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees got back at Wright on Tuesday night, and in a hurry.
Maybe the Yankees had him thinking about avoiding that inside
corner, because just about every fastball he served up was out over
the plate or wide of it. Mostly the latter. Wright was behind in
the count, 2-0, to four of the eight batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   When he threw strikes, he grooved them right down the heart of
the plate, tantalizing the Yankee hitters. Chuck Knoblauch, Derek
Jeter, O'Neill and Bernie Williams began the game by smacking
consecutive singles to give the Yankees a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old Wright was visibly shaken, so much so that he
threw a wild pitch into the dirt that allowed the third of the five
runs he gave up to cross the plate. Before Wright could make it to
the bottom of the Yankees' order, Hargrove swooped down to lift
Wright out of his misery.
</P>
<P>
   This was not the night Wright had envisioned. Before the game,
he was thinking about last year, about how he had walked into a
raucous Yankee Stadium and tamed the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, sitting here, I was a lot more nervous,'' Wright
said. ``I think this year it is a little more easygoing for me, and
I can concentrate solely on pitching and trying to do my job the
best way that I can this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Wright was an unknown. This time, after all the talk
of feuds and paybacks, there was not a fan in the stadium who did
not know who he was. They booed him as he took the mound, and when
he handed the ball over to Hargrove, it was not over.
</P>
<P>
   Wright had to exit through a barrage of jeers coming from every
direction, high and tight, as he ducked into the dugout for safety.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
