<SLUG> BC-FBC-COUGARS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS QB SMITH LEADS HOT FLOCK TO PULLMAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ANGELO BRUSCAS  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two years ago, when he was the nation's top junior college
football recruit, Akili Smith called a news conference in his
native San Diego during the Holiday Bowl festivities to announce
his intentions.
</P>
<P>
   Washington State coach Mike Price had him high on his list, but
the Cougars had another quarterback in the way and Smith didn't
want to take a back seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always been impressed with Akili Smith, ever since high
school,'' Price said. ``I recruited him real hard out of high
school, and I think he was real interested in coming here. But we
had a quarterback, Ryan Leaf, at the time, so I suggested he go
someplace else.
</P>
<P>
   ``But not Oregon, for crying out loud. Someplace like New Mexico
or someplace where we wouldn't have to play him.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith raised some eyebrows when he announced he was heading for
Oregon for the 1997 season, only to end up splitting duties in a
two-quarterback system with junior Jason Maas. Smith finished
second to Maas in passing yards (1,631 to 1,385) and touchdowns (18
to 13), but now Smith is second to no one.
</P>
<P>
   He leads the nation in passing efficiency and is tops in the
Pac-10 in total offense, averaging 295 yards a game. He has thrown
12 touchdown passes in the Ducks' 4-0 season. Oregon seeks its
first five-win start since 1964 when it plays at WSU Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was expected to share the job with Maas but seized the job
for good in Oregon's Sept. 5 opener against Michigan State. He
threw four first-half touchdown passes, including a 53-yarder to
Tony Hartley, and completed 15 of 25 passes for 266 yards as the
Ducks romped 48-14.
</P>
<P>
   In three successive wins since then, Smith has thrown for 295
yards against Texas-El Paso, three touchdowns against San Jose
State and 357 yards and four touchdowns against Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I'm locked in,'' the 6-foot-3, 215-pound senior
declares.
</P>
<P>
   It's enough to cause the Duck promotions staff to start a
Heisman Trophy campaign. Oregon mailed 1,000 postcards Tuesday to
college football writers around the country.
</P>
<P>
   It includes this Bellotti quote: ``At this point in time, Akili
is playing at a level that's possibly unmatched here at the
University of Oregon.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith, however, downplays any of the hype that follows his
statistics, and even makes light of the competition between himself
and Maas. He credits Maas with making him a better player this
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason Maas is a great quarterback and we're still competing
all during practice every week,'' Smith said. ``He's constantly
pushing me.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's visit to Pullman Saturday will be his first since his
WSU recruiting trip. He hopes to avenge a 24-13 loss in Eugene last
year. Maas started that game, but was only 4-of-14 passing and
threw three interceptions before Smith replaced him.
</P>
<P>
   Smith rallied the Ducks by completing 14 of 30 passes for 204
yards and one touchdown, and running for 47 yards, but the Ducks
couldn't recover from a 21-3 halftime deficit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, we had a lot of opportunities to win the football
game and we didn't pull it out,'' said Smith, who beat Washington
four weeks later with a fourth-down pass in the game's final 2{
minutes. ``Hopefully, this year we can pull some of the close games
out and just continue to work toward the Rose Bowl. Everybody is
focused and ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   For Smith, the 1998 season has been everything he hoped it would
be when he settled on his choice of schools after playing the 1996
season at Grossmont Junior College.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to play Pac-10 football since I was little, but a lot
of teams told me that if I didn't get out early, I would have to
redshirt,'' Smith said. ``Oregon was the only team that wasn't
saying that.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he felt comfortable with Bellotti and his coaching
staff. He credits much of his success this year to working during
the spring and summer with offensive coordinator Jeff Tedford, who
has helped Smith make the transition from a running quarterback to
a pocket passer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't been asked to scramble too much this year,'' Smith
said. ``Last year I had to scramble a little bit more because I was
sitting in the pocket and going through my full progression. Last
year, I would start on the wrong side and then try to come back to
the other side. By then, the defensive line would be bearing down
and I would have to scramble.
</P>
<P>
   ``This year, coach Tedford has done a heck of a job of letting
me know where to go pre-snap, so everything is going pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Tedford notes that Smith is no longer bound by doubts of being
placed in a two-quarterback system, and now has the game experience
to go with his natural athletic ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's playing with a lot of confidence right now, and doing a
great job putting the offense into successful situations with his
play-calling at the line of scrimmage,'' Tedford said. ``The rest
of the offense is making it easy for him.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean Smith won't free-lance on the run when he has
to.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game has changed so much now, it's so much faster and you
have to be able to move out there,'' Smith said. ``Sometimes,
something breaks down and you have to get out of there.''
</P>
<P>
   When Price looks at film of Smith now, he sees a legitimate
Heisman Trophy candidate much like Leaf was last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He sits in the pocket a little longer and goes to his second
and third read,'' Price said of how Smith has matured. ``He is much
more accurate throwing the football, and is more of the total
package this year than he was last year. That just comes with
experience.''
</P>
<P>
   In hindsight, Price only wishes he had been able to sway Smith
to come to WSU.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty much how I thought he was going to be _ pretty
darn good,'' Price said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
