<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS FINALLY STARTING TO SETTLE IN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ Much has been made in recent months of the
boom in Southern California real estate. Perhaps an overlooked
contributor to that boom has been the improvement in the fortunes
of the Los Angeles Kings.
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, when the team resided in the depths of the
National Hockey League standings, players came and went with such
regularity that some barely had time to sign leases, let alone
close home loans.
</P>
<P>
   These days, things are a little different. The Kings are coming
off their first playoff appearance since 1993 and are looking ahead
with high hopes to the new season, which begins Saturday night in
Edmonton. And for the Kings, success has been accompanied by their
own, small real-estate boom.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Rob Blake recently bought a place in Manhattan Beach _ a
fine idea for someone who earns more than $5 million a year. Among
the others on the team who have joined in the recent home-shopping
spree are winger Glen Murray, center Jozef Stumpel and defensemen
Steve Duchesne and Mattias Norstrom.
</P>
<P>
   Blake sees a correlation between success on the rink and the
Kings' off-ice acquisitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first time in the last six or seven years that
people are going out and buying houses on this team,'' Blake said.
``Before, no one would buy a house because they weren't going to be
here or they shouldn't have been here. Now ... we have a nucleus
that's going to grow, and that's the biggest thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that's a comfort level,'' general manager Dave Taylor
said of all the action on the home front. ``We are trying to
establish more stability here in L.A. We don't want a lot of
turnover. Certainly a lot of our players we like very much. We'd
like them to stay with the club. We've had a lot of turmoil and a
lot of change over the years. Hopefully from now on we can have a
little more stability.''
</P>
<P>
   The team the Kings have built since trading Wayne Gretzky nearly
three years ago has been constructed through a variety of sources.
Of the 24 players expected to be on the final roster, five were
signed as free agents, 14 were acquired in trades and five were
draft choices. Two of the free agents (Duchesne and fellow
defenseman Garry Galley) and one of the players they traded for
(left wing Luc Robitaille) originally were drafted by the Kings.
</P>
<P>
   But what stands out the most is the Kings' youth. Their average
age is 27{. But of the 24 players, only six are older than 30, and
13 are 26 or younger.
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old Norstrom is a prime example of the type of
player the Kings have added. Recently, he purchased what he calls a
``fixer-upper'' in Manhattan Beach. But he should do fine with his
new home. After all, when he came to the Kings in a multiplayer
deal with the New York Rangers in 1996, the team itself was a
fixer-upper.
</P>
<P>
   One might expect Norstrom would have been disappointed to leave
a team such as the Rangers, who had won the Stanley Cup just two
years earlier. But Norstrom relished the chance to leave New York,
where thirtysomething veterans crowded him out of ice time, to come
to the Kings, where he knew he'd get to play.
</P>
<P>
   And guess what? Last season, the Kings made the playoffs and the
Rangers didn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``They made it clear from the start when I came here,'' Norstrom
said. ``They said, `We're rebuilding the team. We don't expect to
win the first year.' They said, `We're willing to really let things
take their time. We like the group of young players we have. And
further down the line we're going to make some additions.'''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor has done just that. Since becoming the general manager
after the 1996-97 season, he has used the draft to build the
foundation of the franchise and used trades and free agency to add
such veterans as Galley, Duchesne, Robitaille, Stumpel and Russ
Courtnall.
</P>
<P>
   But the brightest spot for the Kings is that the future has yet
to arrive. Only one rookie, winger Josh Green, has made the roster
to start the season. The organization is rife with draft choices
from the last few years who, if they eventually fulfill their
promise, will give the Kings a level of depth they never before
have enjoyed in their checkered three-decade existence.
</P>
<P>
   The approach the Kings have taken in building this team is, for
them, a complete historical departure. From 1969 to 1979, for
instance, the Kings traded their first-round draft choice each
year. Taylor says that won't happen during his tenure, even though
it probably would take a major trade to add a marquee forward who
would put fans in the seats and pucks in the net.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody wants to win, and win every game,'' Taylor said.
``We all want to do that. But we have a long-term plan here. Our
plan is not to give up our younger players but rather to develop
those younger players and make them into good NHL players and stars
down the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got a lot of good prospects in our system and we want to
continue to develop them. That doesn't mean if we get the right
offer that we might not move some of those young guys if there's an
established player available. But I don't think you're going to be
seeing us trading away first-round picks or good, young players for
a guy in his mid-30s.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Decision time: Josh Green's time is now. Olli Jokinen will
have to wait awhile longer.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings announced that the 19-year-old Jokinen, a
center/forward, will begin his season with their American Hockey
League affiliate in Springfield, Mass. Also Springfield-bound is
center Eric Belanger, who is sidelined with a broken wrist. Headed
to Long Beach to join the Ice Dogs are center Jason Morgan and
winger Dan Bylsma.
</P>
<P>
   Jokinen's demotion means the 20-year-old Green, a rookie left
wing, will start the season with the Kings, probably making his NHL
debut Saturday night in the season opener in Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's moves reduced the roster to 26, two above the
regular-season limit. The Kings are set in goal with Stephane Fiset
and Jamie Storr, and also appear set at forward, where all 15 spots
are taken. There look to be two extra defensemen, probably Jaroslav
Modry and Mark Visheau, both of whom are injured.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 0056EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 01:03 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3244 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-H     10-07 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ROBERTSONCOLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
DaleRobertson
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE biggest problem is this: There isn't one.
</P>
<P>
   A simple, wave-the-magic-wand solution for what caused the
Astros to go splat, to fall squarely upon their swords against San
Diego, blowing their best opportunity in 37 seasons to earn a trip
to the World Series, does not exist.
</P>
<P>
   As constituted, they were already good enough to beat the
Padres, had they not hit like Madres. They were also good enough to
beat the Braves and probably the Yankees, too. They just flat-out
failed to give themselves the chance.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, we do realize the Astros weren't a fully rounded
club. Like most teams, even the rich ones, they could use stronger
relief pitching and a stud lefthanded hitter. However, given the
fiscal realities confronting general manager Gerry Hunsicker,
assuming Drayton McLane Jr. continues to demand the Astros be run
as a business rather than a hobby, they can't count on plugging
many holes over the offseason.
</P>
<P>
   They might not plug any of them, should Randy Johnson deign to
return.
</P>
<P>
   But cripes, even the Braves, with their seemingly limitless
resources, haven't pulled off a perfect tweaking. Remember, as bad
as you feel about your fallen heroes, Atlanta's kings of
underperformance, who begin their seventh consecutive NLCS against
San Diego tonight, have only one more set of World Series rings in
the '90s than the 'Stros do.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves are mated for life to the concept that starting
pitching is the truth, the light and the way, the road to eternal
happiness and salvation. And it's a concept that, given the
inordinate importance we place on pitching in the playoffs, we can
hardly quibble with.
</P>
<P>
   But in every Atlanta postseason except 1995, it has ultimately
led only to damnation _ usually because the Atlanta hitters have
failed at the wrong moments, or a jittery bullpen couldn't handle
its rare moments of grave responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   If the Astros believe they let everybody down, imagine the heat
that's on the Braves. Alone among all teams in baseball _ the
Yankees included _ they will be judged total failures if they don't
win the Series.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the misery-loves-company department, look at the
Rangers, whose payroll dwarfs that of the Astros. Texas' own
fearsome offense, which scored 5.8 runs per game in '98 and batted
.289, wound up with faces as red as its caps, finagling but a
single run in three defeats against a Yankees rotation that, for
all the New York hype, didn't post an ERA under 3.49.
</P>
<P>
   The knee-jerk reaction in Houston is to favor a core-deep
shake-up. After the way the Killer B's-turned-B-team performed in
another mission-aborted postseason, we ask if anybody should really
be untouchable. In these moments of extreme frustration, the
temptation is always there to turn the clubhouse upside down.
</P>
<P>
   Yet for 162 games, the Astros' lineup proved itself the National
League's most productive, the internal chemistry was sound, and you
customers reciprocated with record turnstile appreciation. Night in
and night out, the Astros proved a fun team to watch. As a result,
the franchise actually took tangible steps toward profitability
with 10 crowds of more than 50,000 and a 45,655 average for
Johnson's five home starts.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, next season's Astrodome farewell tour doesn't
guarantee even an encore. We know only too well, based on the two
Division Series losses, that the loudest of bats can be made to
fall suddenly silent, which is why re-signing Johnson, or obtaining
another of his ilk, stands as the offseason priority. It's the
safest bet to stay a satisfying April-to-October course.
</P>
<P>
   But until the Astros themselves (and the Rangers) figure out a
way to handle the elite pitchers _ Brown, Smoltz, Maddux, Glavine,
Wells, etc. _ with the ligament-stressing weight of playoff
pressure on them, there will be no Lone Star World Series. To date,
four postseason sessions since 1996 have resulted in a combined
2-12 record for Texas' backward two-steppers.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Dierker was already twitching a couple weeks ago, sensing
something wasn't right. He brought up the subject in St. Louis the
last Wednesday of the regular season after a 7-1 win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, we hit OK tonight,'' Dierker said. ``But I've seen a
change in the way we're swinging our bats. We've lost our
aggressiveness.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the Astros' final 13 games, seven of which were defeats,
they averaged a mere three runs per. During the previous 13, when
they went 11-2 and made the 100-victory plateau reachable, their
nightly norm was six.
</P>
<P>
   Straightening out a flummoxed hitter may be the most difficult
task in coaching, because making solid contact with a baseball is
the hardest job in sports. Sometimes it simply goes, and that's
that.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros stopped hitting, so they stopped playing. End of
story, and season. But with Johnson, there can be a next year for
this bunch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
