<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3247 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES-BRAVES-HNS     10-07 0667
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-BRAVES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1998, Houston Chronicle  
ATLANTA _ If the San Diego Padres like a good challenge _ and they
seemed to indicate that was the case while they were brushing aside
the Astros in the Division Series _ they're liable to fall in love
with the predicament they're in now.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The team of the decade is standing between the Padres and their
first World Series appearance since 1984, and history is not on San
Diego's side.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves are appearing in their seventh consecutive
National League Championship Series, and they've reached the World
Series four times during that stretch. The last time they were
defeated in the NLCS (1993), they reached the World Series in each
of the following two years in which there was a postseason, winning
it all in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   That does not bode well for the Padres, considering the Braves
lost the NL pennant to the Florida Marlins in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   So what does it all mean? It means it's time for the Braves to
make another run at the Fall Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect to win,'' Braves pitcher Greg Maddux said.
</P>
<P>
   So does just about everyone else who has an opinion on the
subject, and that's just the way the Padres seem to like it. San
Diego reached the NLCS by surprising the Astros in the first round,
and the Padres believe there is enough magic left in their season
to pull another shocker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just won a series nobody gave us a chance to win, and now
we're playing Atlanta,'' Padres right fielder Tony Gwynn said. ``In
spring training, our goal was to try to get to the World Series and
win it. It has not changed. This is the biggest thrill of my
career. Going to the World Series in 1984 was great, but the long
wait in between makes this really nice right now.''
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz and Andy Ashby, a pair of pitchers who each won 17
games in the regular season, will be on the mound tonight when the
series begins at Turner Field. But it's clearly a case of two
pitchers headed in opposite directions. Smoltz was one of the
hottest pitchers in the league when the season ended, and Ashby was
slumping miserably.
</P>
<P>
   The fact Ashby is starting Game 1 instead of ace Kevin Brown
already has some observers second-guessing Padres manager Bruce
Bochy. But because Brown made his last two starts on three days'
rest _ one day less than is customary _ Bochy decided to give the
ball to Ashby and hope tonight is the night he rediscovers his
first-half form.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's our horse,'' Bochy said of Brown, who will start Game 2.
``But you don't want to kill him.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just fine with the Braves, who don't want to face Brown
any sooner than they have to. He allowed the Astros only one run
and struck out 21 batters in 14 innings during the Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this whole series hinges on whether we beat Kevin
Brown or not,'' Braves third baseman Chipper Jones said. ``Facing
him is not one of the more enviable tasks in the National League.
He's nasty and dominating and as tough a competitor as anybody
there is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves probably feel like Brown has a little payback coming
his way. The veteran righthander won two NLCS games against them as
a member of the Marlins last season, although the Braves hit him
well enough to win. Brown allowed 16 hits and seven runs in 15
innings during the 1997 NLCS.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of payback, Padres super-sub Jim Leyritz also
should be on the Braves' list. Leyritz blasted a dramatic,
game-tying, three-run homer against the Braves in the 1996 World
Series, which Atlanta eventually lost to the New York Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz has been at it again lately, smacking three
game-changing home runs against the Astros in the Division Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, (Leyritz) has been a thorn in the side around here,
probably more so than anywhere else,'' Braves pitcher Denny Neagle
said. ``Well, I take that back. I'm sure he's ringing in the ears
of a lot of Houston Astros fans right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
