<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-CLINTON-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON DEMANDS FUNDS FOR IMF 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton called on financial leaders
Tuesday to take ``urgent steps'' to address what he called the
world's ``most serious crisis in half a century.''
</P>
<P>
   Addressing officials from the 182-member nation International
Monetary Fund and the World Bank, Clinton warned that the financial
chaos is undermining world prosperity and faith in free-market
democracies.
</P>
<P>
   The global economy ``simply cannot live with the kinds of vast
and systemic disruptions that have occurred over the past year,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   After a long battle, the House appeared ready to join the Senate
in acceding to Clinton's demand for an additional $14.5 billion
injection of U.S. funds into the IMF once certain conditions are
met.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has come under attack by other nations for
recommending global financial reforms and new emergency lending to
Brazil, while at the same time refusing to bolster the resources of
the IMF, the agency responsible for managing the world financial
system.
</P>
<P>
   IMF member nations have agreed to a $90 billion expansion of its
reserves, and Clinton pressured the House again Tuesday to approve
the U.S. share.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can debate how to reform the operations of the fire
department, but there is no excuse for refusing to supply the fire
department with water while the fire is burning,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition to the U.S. contribution has been led by House
Majority Leader Dick Armey, R-Texas, who wants the IMF to set
market interest rates on its loans and limit them to one year. ``We
must have these reforms, or there cannot be any increase in
funding,'' Armey said.
</P>
<P>
   Although apparently willing to accept at least some of Armey's
conditions, the administration argues that the United States cannot
unilaterally dictate terms to a multination agency; IMF officials
have said that the agency answers to 182 nations, not the U.S.
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Other critics contend that Armey's plan to set market terms on
IMF loans would remove the rationale for IMF lending: Countries
turn to the IMF during a balance-of-payments crisis when there is a
loss of market confidence. If countries could raise money on the
international capital markets, critics say, they wouldn't need IMF
loans in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appealed mainly for long-term changes to financial
markets, saying they need the kinds of regulatory frameworks long
operating in industrialized countries _ many adopted after the
Depression _ such as strong banking supervision, ``transparent,''
or open, accounting standards and bank deposit insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Although international markets differ from domestic markets,
``some of the same functions clearly need to be performed,''
Clinton said. ``We must address not only a run on a bank or a firm,
but also a run on nations.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton reiterated the administration's call for an emergency
line of credit to help Brazil avoid a foreign-exchange crisis
triggered by panicked investors fleeing all emerging markets after
Russia's August 15 default.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's proposals mirrored a speech last week by U.S. Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin, the former Goldman Sachs investment banker
who is the architect of Clinton's economic policies and a strong
advocate of open financial markets.
</P>
<P>
   Despite disagreements, world financial leaders appeared to be
moving toward at least a vague consensus on the steps necessary to
prevent the further spread of the financial meltdown that began in
Thailand 14 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Group of Seven industrialized nations _ the United States,
Canada, France, Italy, Britain, Japan and Germany _ agree that they
must sustain growth in Europe and the United States, although there
still is no plan for a coordinated cut in interest rates. However,
U.S. Federal Reserve officials said this week that further U.S.
cuts in interest rates may be on the way given the shaky global
outlook and the credit crunch now gaining steam as domestic lenders
grow more cautious.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principal goal of policymakers must be to promote
growth,'' Clinton said. ``The most important thing we can do is to
keep our economy growing and open to others' products and
services.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also rising alarm and frustration over Japan, seen as
the keystone to reviving world growth. Clinton pointedly singled
out Japan, saying the ``health of Asia and indeed the world'' rests
on reviving its economy.
</P>
<P>
   IMF managing director Michel Camdessus referred to Japan as
``the crisis at the heart of the crisis.''
</P>
<P>
   Japanese officials seem unwilling to adopt the deep, permanent
tax cuts that economists widely believe are vital to pulling Japan
out of its worst recession since World War II, or to take bold
action to fix its banking system, which is essentially insolvent.
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Times of London reported Tuesday that the Japanese
government is considering two unorthodox stimulus schemes: giving
30,000 yen, equivalent to $220, in pocket money to each of its 125
million citizens, and declaring a series of ``Happy Monday''
holidays for citizens to spend shopping instead of working.
</P>
<P>
   Such steps are unlikely to be perceived as the serious
macroeconomic and banking remedies financial markets are seeking.
</P>
<P>
   Finance ministers also are increasingly moving toward
significant changes to global financial structures advocated,
albeit in different forms, by Britain, France and the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin favors a more market-based approach to disciplining
capital flows, emphasizing open bookkeeping in developing countries
so that investors better understand risks, along with stronger
banking systems, accounting standards and other measures to
strengthen the rules and institutions that support capital markets.
The idea is that better information will allow market discipline to
minimize wild bouts of euphoria or panic, and higher financial
standards will keep banks and corporations on a sounder footing.
</P>
<P>
   Britain and France favor a more regulatory approach. British
chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown has called for a
``Standing Committee for Global Financial Regulation'' to establish
standards for capital flows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
