 ENTERTAINMENT SUMMARY No 405 - October 7, 1998   ENTERTAINMENT
SUMMARY -- No. 405 -- Oct. 7, 1998 We are offering the following
articles for sale. Please contact us for availability your country.
Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. JONI MITCHELL FOR THE '90S At 54, Joni Mitchell has suddenly
found herself in possession of a daughter she gave up for adoption
in the '60s, a grandson and a desire to write light songs. But
she's still an iconoclast - and a dazzling egoiste. By Neil
Strauss. From The New York Times Magazine. Full-length article
(3,100 words) + edited version available. 2. PLAYING PAMMY
Ann-Margret plays the late, great, courtesan/diplomat Pamela
Harriman in a new TV movie. ``I keep saying, how did she do so many
things with her life and have so many men? It was like five
lifetimes,'' says Ann-Margret, who's been married for 31 years to
the same man, former actor Roger Smith. Roger's illness,
Ann-Margret admits, forced her to take a stronger role in both
business and life, granting her a new freedom. By Louise Farr. From
W magazine. 1,500 words + photo. 3. HOLLYWOOD REDISCOVERS THE
HEREAFTER Hollywood seems to be taking note of the fact that the
century is racing to its conclusion. And just like the Victorians
at the end of the 19th century, with their seances and their
interest in the occult, movie makers are preoccupied with some very
strange things. Witness the current and future spate of movies
dealing with death, dying, angels, the afterlife, heaven and hell.
By Ivor Davis. 1,000 words + photos. (N/A Great Britain and
Australia.) 4. OPRAH WINFREY'S LONG JOURNEY TO 'BELOVED' Even
multi-millionnaire television stars have dreams, and for 11 years,
Oprah Winfrey's has been to make a movie of Toni Morrison's
award-wining - but apparently unfilmable - novel, ``Beloved.'' Now
that dream has been realized, with Winfrey as producer and star of
the film. In this interview she tells why she devoted more than a
decade to getting it made, how she approached her first-ever sex
scenes and how she thinks making ``Beloved'' has changed her
forever. By Cindy Pearlman. 1,400 words + photo. 5. FACE VALUE :
DEARLY ``BELOVED'' - OPRAH WINFREY CARTOON Artist Ricardo Castaneda
offers an intriguing cartoon of Oprah Winfrey, shown in a
character-filled drawing as seen in her upcoming film, ``Beloved.''
</P>
<P>
   6. IAN MCKELLEN TAKES ANOTHER WALK ON THE WILD SIDE Sir Ian
McKellen has played a lot of villains, from Richard III to Death
himself, but ``Apt Pupil'' may be his scariest ever. Based on a
Stephen King novella, the film casts him as an elderly ex-Nazi who
has been living quietly in a small American town for decades, until
a high-school student learns his secret and demands inside
information about the Nazi atrocities he committed. ``This is a
nasty little story, and it will have reverberations,'' McKellen
acknowledges. In this interview he also talks about his outspoken
advocacy of gay rights in Britain, why he has had no long-term
relationship in his life for many years and why, as he approaches
60, this universally admired actor is driving himself harder than
ever (he even has his own website which he designed and created.)
By Jean Oppenheimer. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________ 7.
DENNIS FARINA DOES 'FARO' The name might not ring a bell, but
you've definitely seen this veteran actor as either the cop, the
private investigator or the bad guy in films like ``Midnight Run,''
``Get Shorty'' and ``Manhunter.'' This autumn Dennis Farina returns
in ``Buddy Faro'' as a Los Angeles private investigator who
vanished in the 70s. He resurfaces in the '90s to find the city a
much-changed place. By Joshua Mooney. BPI. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 8.
JOAN ALLEN : THE ACTRESS'S ACTRESS Joan Allen doesn't play
good-hearted prostitutes, sexy murderesses or screaming stalkees,
but a lot of people think she's the best actress in Hollywood - and
she has two Oscar nominations, for ``Nixon'' (1995) and ``The
Crucible'' (1996,) to back them up. Her latest film,
``Pleasantville,'' is an offbeat comedy-drama in which she plays
the mother in a fictitious 1950s television sitcom. In this
interview Allen talks about ``Pleasantville,'' why she is so
notoriously choosy about the films she makes, how she handled her
two Oscar losses and why Hollywood's favourite serious actress is
looking for the right comedy. By Ian Spelling. 1,400 words + photo.
_______________________________________________________________
</P>
