u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEARST-NEWS-ADVISORY-     10-07 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEARST-NEWS-ADVISORY-HNS </SLUG>
  
 Wednesday, Oct. 7, 1998    
 Editors:     
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hispanics, long dismissed as a marginal force in U.S. politics,
are now being avidly courted by Republicans and Democrats alike.
The reason: The number of Hispanics is climbing so rapidly that by
2005 they will be the nation's largest minority and by 2050 will
make up one-quarter of the U.S. population.
</P>
<P>
   The Hearst News Service and The San Antonio Express-News examine
this trend in a package of stories on the new political clout of
Hispanics in America. The stories are for release starting Sunday,
Oct. 11. Graphics from the San Antonio Express-News have been
posted on the Wieck database. Photos from the Hearst Newspapers'
Washington bureau will be posted on Wieck Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   For questions about stories, please call Susie McBee of The
Hearst Newspapers' Washington bureau at 202-298-6920 or David
Sheppard of The San Antonio Express-News at 210-250-3216. For
questions about graphics or photos, please call Hallie Paul at
210-250-3301.
</P>
<P>
   Here's the story lineup:
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday, Oct. 11:
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-CLOUT (Washington) _ Republicans and Democrats are
making an unprecedented effort to win Hispanic support, not only
for next month's election but for 2000 and beyond. Strategists for
both parties are amazed at Hispanics' zooming population growth and
believe that Latino voters are willing to switch party allegiance,
depending on candidates and issues. By STEWART M. POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   With graphics slugged HISP-LOGO, HISP-GROWTH, HISP-REGISTERED,
HISP-VOTERS and HISP-PRESIDENTIAL-ELECTIONS.
</P>
<P>
   With HISP photos.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-HISTORY (Washington) _ For Hispanics, the long march to
political power began shortly after World War II. We trace the
effort, looking at such leaders as Cesar Chavez, who won national
attention with his efforts to organize migrant farm workers in
California, and Dr. Hector Garcia, who stirred outrage across the
country at the refusal of a Texas town to bury a deceased World War
II veteran in the local cemetery because he was a Mexican American.
By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   With HISP photos.
</P>
<P>
   For Monday, Oct. 12:
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-GOVERNORS (Del Rio, Texas) _ Texas Gov. George Bush
gets a warm welcome in Hispanic communities. Some Latinos say he is
more sympathetic to their concerns than other Republicans,
especially Gov. Pete Wilson of California, who has taken harsh
stances on immigration and affirmative action. The men's
differences illustrate the mixed messages the party sends to
Hispanics. By LAURA TOLLEY. With HISP-LOGO graphic.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-TEXAS (San Antonio) _ A look at the rising power of
Hispanics in various cities including San Antonio and Corpus
Christi, where Hispanics have city council majorities, and El Paso
and McAllen, which have Hispanic mayors. We also look at the
campaigns of Mexican Americans running for statewide offices. By
LAURA TOLLEY.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic slugged HISP-TEXAS.
</P>
<P>
   For Tuesday, Oct. 13:
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-CONTESTS (Washington) _ From the streets of Salt Lake
City to the lake lands of Minnesota, Hispanic candidates are
running for office in state and congressional races that would have
seemed almost impossible for them to enter only a few years ago.
The development comes at a time when more Hispanics are running for
national and statewide posts generally. By MARK HELM and STEWART M.
POWELL.
</P>
<P>
   With HISP-LOGO graphic.
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-DIFFERENCES (Washington) _ Republican and Democratic
politicians are learning that they cannot regard Hispanics as a
monolith. We look at the cross-currents between certain groups and
within the groups themselves. Republicans believe they have a
chance to take many Hispanic votes away from the Democrats. By MARK
HELM.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 0946EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3547 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-CLOUT-2TAKES     10-07 1215
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-CLOUT-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROWTH OF THE HISPANIC VOTE: A POLITICAL EARTHQUAKE IN THE MAKING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 11)   (EDs: graphics and photos available on the Wieck database.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hispanics, long dismissed as a marginal force by
both political parties, are now being avidly courted by Republicans
and Democrats alike.
</P>
<P>
   What the pols have discovered _ much to their amazement _ is
that the number of Hispanics is climbing so rapidly that by 2005
they will overtake African Americans as the nation's largest
minority and by 2050 will make up a quarter of the U.S. population.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Cisneros, a former San Antonio mayor who was housing
secretary in President Clinton's first Cabinet, sees a political
earthquake in the offing as Hispanics emerge as a swing vote in key
states.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have just now begun to achieve critical mass with enough
votes to make a difference,'' says Cisneros. ``It's a powerful
development.''
</P>
<P>
   He adds that the zooming population growth _ coupled with
politicians' belief that Hispanics are willing to switch allegiance
depending on candidates and issues _ means that ``we have within
our reach the ability to influence'' the outcome in 10 states
accounting for 214 of the 270 electoral votes needed to win the
White House.
</P>
<P>
   So both parties are making an unprecedented effort to woo
Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   On the Republican side, House Speaker Newt Gingrich told a
national gathering here of Hispanic leaders: ``We want to work with
you.'' The group had been convened by a longtime civil rights
organization, the nonpartisan League of United Latin American
Citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Gingrich invited a prominent Mexican American from
Texas, Republican Tony Garza, who is running for a state railroad
commission seat, to be his guest at President Clinton's State of
the Union address. The speaker hired Sandra Hernandez, a public
relations specialist, as his assistant press secretary to handle
the Spanish-language media.
</P>
<P>
   In California GOP gubernatorial candidate Dan Lungren and
Republican Matt Fong, a U.S. Senate candidate, are campaigning in
barrios and targeting TV ads to reach Hispanic voters. They are
trying to counter the antipathy fostered by the outgoing California
governor, Pete Wilson, who swept to a second term in 1994 by
playing to anti-immigrant sentiment.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last four years Wilson has backed GOP-sponsored ballot
initiatives that sought to bar most public services for
undocumented immigrants, halt affirmative action in state
contracting, hiring and public college admission, and end bilingual
education in schools.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, Texas Republican Gov. George W. Bush is ``perceived
in every way as a friendly Anglo'' among Hispanics, according to
Valerie Martinez, a political science professor at Texas Christian
University.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the perception stems from Bush's refusal to endorse a
number of GOP anti-immigrant measures. This year he has repeatedly
campaigned for reelection in areas with high Hispanic populations _
San Antonio, El Paso and the Rio Grande Valley _ and is expected to
win with strong Hispanic support. Aides say at least 25 percent of
his TV budget is devoted to ads, some in Spanish and English,
targeted to Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Republicans scored a major coup this summer by
enlisting former Democratic Rep. Herman Badillo to their cause.
Badillo was the first Puerto Rican native elected to Congress, and
he helped found the Congressional Hispanic Caucus in 1976.
</P>
<P>
   Charging that Democrats ``take their historic constituencies for
granted,'' Badillo has embarked on a ``marathon'' campaign around
the country to encourage Hispanics to vote for Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Another prominent Hispanic, Republican Rep. Henry Bonilla of
Texas, is also leading a GOP outreach effort. For months he has
been on the campaign trail seeking to boost Hispanic turnout for
Republican candidates in Texas, New Mexico, Arizona, Nevada and
California.
</P>
<P>
   Recognizing the potential of the Hispanic vote, the Republican
National Committee began in March to sponsor a Spanish-language GOP
response to President Clinton's weekly radio address each Saturday.
The response provides a national podium to Hispanic politicians,
whose speeches go to more than 200 Spanish-language radio stations
and networks.
</P>
<P>
   Lorenzo C. Lopez, co-director of the GOP's New Majority Council,
which honchos the party's efforts to reach minorities, says the
Spanish-speakers deal with issues in Hispanics' neighborhoods
``that affect their daily lives _ crime, drugs and education. ...
Republicans are not changing our message, but we are tailoring it
so that it connects with the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the GOP is appealing to Hispanics by including San
Antonio, a city of a million people that is 55.6 percent Mexican
American, as one of the sites it is considering for its 2000
national convention. A decision is expected late this year.
</P>
<P>
   On the Democratic side, party strategists see the rising number
of Hispanics as critical to their comeback in the South and West,
where for more than a decade they have lost House, Senate and
gubernatorial races.
</P>
<P>
   Democratic National Chairman Roy Romer, the governor of
Colorado, says, ``The growth of the Hispanic population is key to
our ascendancy in those states ... that are currently seen as
Republican strongholds.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton has led his party's courtship of Hispanics,
who, except for Cuban Americans, have traditionally given at least
60 percent of their vote to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has appointed more Hispanics to high-profile jobs than
any other president, appeared before numerous Hispanic audiences
and advocated policies that they like, such as support for
affirmative action, funds for inner city schools, greater access to
health care and aid for legal immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Among the Hispanics Clinton has appointed to key posts are
Federico Pena, first as transportation secretary and then energy
secretary; Bill Richardson, first as U.S. ambassador to the United
Nations and then as energy secretary when Pena resigned, and Maria
Echaveste, first as White House liaison with interest groups and
then as one of two deputy White House chiefs of staff, the highest
White House post ever held by a Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   The president also named Aida Alvarez to head the Small Business
Administration, Mickey Ibarra as White House intergovernmental
affairs director, George Munoz to lead the Overseas Private
Investment Corporation and Louis Caldera as secretary of the Army.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has spoken at the annual Congressional Hispanic Caucus
dinner in Washington, D.C., every year since he has been president.
When he proclaimed National Hispanic Heritage Month from Sept. 15
to Oct. 15, the president vowed to ``ensure that all Hispanic
American families have the tools and opportunities they need to
make the most of their lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Following the GOP's lead, the Democratic National Committee in
May launched weekly Spanish-language broadcasts to appeal to
Hispanic audiences. The DNC hired communications expert Evangelina
Garcia as deputy press secretary to deal with Hispanic news
outlets.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 0950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0047 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
