<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 09:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3554 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEWEL-THIEF-COX     10-07 0019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWEL-THIEF-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 0954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0049 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 09:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3555 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-CLOUT-2NDTAK     10-07 1027
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-CLOUT-2NDTAKE-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON:news outlets.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Committee also hired political consultant Armando Gutierrez,
based in Albuquerque, N.M., to bolster Hispanic voting in 13 House,
8 Senate and 6 gubernatorial races.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year congressional Democrats declared all-out war
on GOP lawmakers over Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   The House Democratic Policy Committee attacked what it called
the ``anti-Hispanic Republican Congress'' in a report denouncing
alleged GOP efforts to intimidate Hispanic voters, restrict access
to education, undercount minorities in the 2000 census and
eliminate the social safety net for legal immigrants. It also
attacked Republicans who are pressing for English-only legislation,
restrictions on immigration and an end to affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   Later, House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt notched up the
attack, calling the GOP ``the most anti-immigrant, the most
anti-Hispanic, party that has ever existed in the history of the
country.''
</P>
<P>
   Both parties are calculating the importance of Hispanics based
on their skyrocketing growth.
</P>
<P>
   Now they make up 25.8 percent of California's population and
25.5 percent of that in Texas. The percentages are 38.2 percent in
New Mexico, 18.8 in Arizona, 12.9 in Colorado, 12.3 in New York,
12.2 in Florida, 9.6 in New Jersey, 7.9 in Illinois and 4.8 in
Massachusetts. These are the 10 states with 214 Electoral College
votes.
</P>
<P>
   By 2010, Hispanics are projected to be 37.8 percent of the
population in California, 32.5 percent in Texas, 42.3 percent in
New Mexico, 26.3 percent in Arizona, 19.1 percent in Florida, 18.1
percent in New York, 16.5 percent in Colorado, 15.6 percent in New
Jersey, 13.1 percent in Illinois and 9.6 percent in Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists in each party are also taking a second look at voter
turnout. Many politicians have long dismissed Hispanics as a group
that doesn't vote much.
</P>
<P>
   But that perception is based on the fact that for decades
analysts have compared the number of Hispanic voters with the
entire Hispanic voting-age population. Using that measure, only
26.7 percent of the Hispanic voting-age population cast ballots in
the 1996 presidential election, compared with a 54.2 percent total
turnout of the nation's voting-age population that year.
</P>
<P>
   However, the U.S. Census Bureau emphasizes _ and many
politicians now appreciate _ that the traditional gauge of Hispanic
political turnout is skewed. Census officials explain that about 40
percent of the 18.4 million Hispanics who were 18 or older in 1996
were ineligible to vote because they were not U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, almost all of the 178.3 million non-Hispanic whites
and blacks of voting age in 1996 were U.S. born and eligible to
vote.
</P>
<P>
   To get a more accurate picture of turnout, The Hearst Newspapers
compared the number of actual voters with the number of registered
voters. Using that gauge, Hispanic voter participation is much
closer to that of the other groups: 75 percent of registered
Hispanic voters cast ballots in 1996, compared with 82.7 percent of
registered non-Hispanic white voters and 79.8 percent of black
voters.
</P>
<P>
   The turnout of registered Hispanic voters has exceeded the
turnout of registered African-American voters in three presidential
and three midterm elections since 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the parties' greater interest in them, Hispanics are,
in turn, getting more involved in politics. This year a record
number are running _ 25 for the House, one for the Senate and 43
for statewide offices.
</P>
<P>
   Clara Rodriguez, a sociology professor at Fordham University in
New York City, says, ``There is a growing sense among Latinos that
we have been invisible for too long and it is important to stand up
and be counted.''
</P>
<P>
   Another boost to their political consciousness comes from
Hispanics' growing awareness of their impact on the 1996 election.
</P>
<P>
   They gave Bill Clinton 72 percent of their vote and Republican
Bob Dole only 21 percent. GOP nominees had long counted on at least
25 percent. President Ronald Reagan set the high-water mark with 37
percent of the Hispanic vote in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Exit polls on election day showed that Hispanics helped deliver
Arizona to Clinton _ the first time that a Democrat had carried the
state in 48 years. At the same time Cuban Americans broke ranks
with the GOP in Florida, splitting their vote between Clinton and
Dole. It was only the third time since 1964 that a Democrat was
able to capture the state. Mexican Americans tilted heavily toward
Clinton in New Mexico, helping him to win the state for a second
time.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics themselves also scored dramatic gains across the
nation. The number elected to state legislatures grew by almost 20
percent to 131 lawmakers, according to the Los Angeles-based
National Association of Latino Elected and Appointed Officials.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead to the November election, a number of experts say
that Hispanic voters are not locked into one political party.
</P>
<P>
   Harry P. Pachon, head of the Tomas Rivera Policy Institute, a
nonpartisan think tank in Claremont, Calif., notes that many
Hispanics are first-time voters, having just turned 18 or just won
their citizenship. ``The roots of their partisan attachment are
very shallow,'' Pachon says. While Republicans' anti-immigrant
rhetoric ``pushed Latinos into the arms of the Democrats in 1996, I
don't know if that will be permanent.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, many Hispanics are taking a wait-and-see attitude.
Raul Yzaguirre, head of the National Council of La Raza, which
lobbies Congress and state legislatures on behalf of Hispanics,
charges that both parties' efforts are ``essentially public
relations,'' rather than policies targeted to the everyday lives of
Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Juan Andrade, head of the U.S. Hispanic Leadership Institute in
Chicago, which has helped register 1.5 million new Hispanic voters
since 1982, says the parties ``need to do more work'' to win
Hispanics' attention and loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parties and the politicians haven't sorted out their
strategies yet,'' says Andrade. ``For 30 years one party did not
want us, and the other party took us for granted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 0954EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 09:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3556 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JOURNAL-BARBADOS-$ADV     10-07 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOURNAL-BARBADOS-$ADV08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BARBADOS: DELIGHTFULLY SIMPLE AND EFFICIENT, BUT NO MCDONALD'S?
 &HT;    With photo mug of Emling in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (k) Commentary
categories.
 &HT;    For Use Thursday, Oct. 8 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By SHELLEY EMLING 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGETOWN, Barbados _ Bajans, as people here like to be called,
have a sense of their own style. So much so that even McDonald's
couldn't invade the culture. The fast-food chain went bust after
just six months of operation because no one ate at the place.
</P>
<P>
   Barbados is different from some other Caribbean islands in that
things just seem to work better here. The roads are good, the
phones connect, and appointments are kept. And, the island is
infested by millionaires the way some are infested by mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Bajans will tell you that their country has been blessed by God,
and this is no idle boast.
</P>
<P>
   Barbados hasn't been touched by a hurricane since 1955 and the
sun shines nearly every day.
</P>
<P>
   But it's more than just that.
</P>
<P>
   Bajans (pronounced ``Bah-jonz'') are the most affluent and most
educated people in the Caribbean, and they have the highest
literacy rate _ nearly 98 percent _ in the English-speaking world.
</P>
<P>
   In the United Nations Development Program's annual ``human
development index'' that evaluates countries in terms of life
expectancy, income and education, Barbados ranks 24th, ahead of all
other Caribbean countries and even better than countries such as
Portugal, Luxembourg, and Costa Rica.
</P>
<P>
   And if Barbados appears lacking in the vast poverty found on
other islands, it is because agriculture, commerce, and sugar cane
production provide most with work.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about their island's success, government officials
will say it's rooted in religion and a strong education system.
</P>
<P>
   The 166-square-mile island supports a population of 266,000
people and more churches than days in the year.
</P>
<P>
   One Pentecostal church holds five services each Sunday, all of
them packed with worshippers.
</P>
<P>
   It is also home to 125 religious sects, with everyone from
Baptists to Buddhists on the island.
</P>
<P>
   The island is divided into 11 parishes all named after a saint,
except for the parish called Christ Church.
</P>
<P>
   On Sundays, stores and businesses are closed. The radio
broadcasts almost 30 different religious programs. And, almost
everyone attends church as well as other gatherings such as gospel
concerts and prayer recitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``People go to church, and then they go home to eat and rest,
that's all,'' said Fran Evelyn, a tour operator. ``Everything's
closed because people consider Sunday to be a day of rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides religion, education also is serious stuff in Barbados,
and discipline is strongly enforced in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   If a student is bad, he or she might be paddled. Girls can't
wear makeup, flashy jewelry, or skirts above the knee. Boys can't
wear earrings or tattoos. Days begin and end with prayer. School
assemblies feature the reading of Bible passages and the telling of
stories about morality.
</P>
<P>
   Education is so highly valued here that the government spends
nearly a fifth of its budget on it every year, as is evident by the
computers that adorn most of the classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   Even better, students have something to strive for because, if
grades are good, students can get a full scholarship to their
college of choice, no matter what country it is in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel education should be made available free of charge to
anyone who wants it,'' said Glenroy Cumberbatch, deputy chief for
the Ministry of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Not that this island doesn't have its share of troubles.
Drug-related violence is up, and drug traffickers from South
America are increasingly using the island as a stepping-stone to
transport cocaine and heroin to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But, still, there are only nine or 10 murders here a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a very law-abiding society, so much so that police do
not even carry weapons,'' said Barbados Sen. Phillip Goddard.
``Parents instill in their children the importance of God and
education at a young age.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbados is a very British island, hence its nickname ``Little
England.''
</P>
<P>
   People here drink beer in pubs, watch cricket on the weekends,
drive on the left side of the road, and visit Trafalgar Square in
downtown Bridgetown, just as they do in London.
</P>
<P>
   The English settled here in 1625 and continued to rule for 339
years, until the island became independent in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bajans have certainly been influenced by the British culture,
even though today we are being increasingly influenced by the
United States through television programming and that sort of
thing,'' Goddard said.
</P>
<P>
   But compared to the United States, life here is delightfully
simple.
</P>
<P>
   Most houses in Barbados have no numbers, but are instead marked
only by names. For example, a house might be called something like
Comfort, or Woodlawn, or Henry's Place.
</P>
<P>
   With little crime, the newspaper's front page features stories
on things like the country's declining sheep industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we do so well because our temperament is good,'' said
Barbados Attorney General David Simmons. ``We think before we speak
and don't go in for excesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Excesses that seemingly include even Big Macs and
Quarter-Pounders. So much for American influences.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
