<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 09:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3561 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-HISTORY-2TAK     10-07 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-HISTORY-2TAKES-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANICS LOOK BACK ON A LONG ROAD TO POLITICAL PROMINENCE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 11) , (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For Hispanics, the long march to political power
began shortly after World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Like many Americans, tens of thousands of Hispanics who joined
the military found that the war had forever changed their outlook.
Sent to bases across the country and overseas, they saw a world
outside their barrios in the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, they were able to see how people lived and
were treated outside of California and Texas,'' says John Garcia,
an expert on Hispanic politics at the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In those days Mexican Americans in Texas could not serve on
grand juries or draft boards, and most attended de facto segregated
schools. Many were refused service in restaurants, and few voted
because of a poll tax. In California, they found segregation _
except in housing _ less widespread, but discrimination was
rampant. ``Pachuco'' was a common epithet that they heard. It was
the equivalent of ``nigger'' or ``wop.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, thousands of Hispanic veterans took advantage of the G.I.
Bill and went to college, forming the nucleus of a small
professional class. Self-help groups sprang up. One was the
Community Service Organization (CSO), founded in 1947 in Los
Angeles to fight discrimination in the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   CSO quickly became involved in local politics. For example, it
conducted a strong voter registration drive that was key to the
election of Edward R. Roybal to the Los Angeles City Council in
1949. He was the first Mexican American elected to the council in
the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Texas a physician named Hector Garcia and other
veterans in Corpus Christi had started the American GI Forum to
protect the rights of Mexican-American veterans.
</P>
<P>
   A 1949 incident in the town of Three Rivers, 65 miles northwest
of Corpus Christi, outraged Garcia and led him to launch a national
campaign against discrimination. Through his efforts, media from
around the country focused on Three Rivers, where a funeral home
director had refused to let the family of a deceased veteran, Felix
Longoria, hold a wake. As a result of the publicity, Longoria was
buried with honor in Arlington National Cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Americans, although shunned by Democratic and Republican
party bosses, continued to run for office during the 1950s. But
with little money, most of their campaigns failed.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the decade, some Hispanic leaders recognized that
their candidates needed more help from their own communities if
they were to succeed. So in 1959, 150 activists gathered in Los
Angeles and founded the Mexican American Political Association.
MAPA, which later established branches throughout the Southwest,
sought to get Mexican-American candidates from either party
elected.
</P>
<P>
   Then in 1960 the Viva Kennedy campaign began.
</P>
<P>
   Realizing that the election between Democrat John Kennedy and
Republican Richard Nixon was going to be close, Kennedy aides
fanned out in the Southwest setting up Viva Kennedy clubs to bring
out the Hispanic vote.
</P>
<P>
   On election day, these voters proved crucial to Kennedy's
victory in Texas. Some precincts in El Paso, for instance, went 100
percent for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the Anglo vote split fairly evenly in Texas, the Latino
vote carried the day for Kennedy,'' says Louis DeSipio of the
University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, an expert on Hispanic
political movements.
</P>
<P>
   The next year Henry B. Gonzalez of San Antonio won a special
election to become the first Hispanic congressman in modern times.
In 1962 Roybal won a U.S. House seat from Los Angeles. The Senate
already had Dennis Chavez of New Mexico, who served from from 1935
to 1964, when he stepped down and was replaced by Joseph Montoya.
</P>
<P>
   While some Mexican Americans celebrated these victories, others,
particularly young people, charged that both the Democratic and
Republican parties were still refusing to back Hispanics
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   The young activists tried a more confrontational approach. Some
pointed to the federal funds given to African Americans following
riots in black neighborhoods during the 1960s and argued that
Hispanics needed to use similar methods to attract national
attention and government aid.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most important groups formed in that period was La
Crusada Para La Justicia. Started in Denver in 1965 by Rodolfo
``Corky'' Gonzales, a poet and former boxing champion, the group
supported high school strikes, organized demonstrations against
police brutality and protested against the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Many non-Hispanic whites saw Gonzales' organization as a
dangerous threat to society, but some militant Hispanics felt it
didn't go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, Reies Tijerina and about 40 armed supporters took
control of the Rio Arriba County courthouse in the northern New
Mexico town of Tierra Amarilla. Tijerina released 11 prisoners who
had been arrested in connection with his plan to take over lands in
the Kit Carson National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   After a shootout with police, Tijerina and his supporters fled
into nearby mountains. Eventually, the National Guard captured him
and 17 of his supporters. He was later acquitted of the charges
resulting from the raid.
</P>
<P>
   Ethnic militancy also was showing up in the political arena. In
1970, Jose Angel Gutierrez and other activists at St. Mary's
University in San Antonio founded a third party called La Raza
Unida. It sought to gain political control of Texas communities
with significant Mexican-American majorities.
</P>
<P>
   The LRU, which called for instruction in Spanish in all American
schools and increased government aid for the poor, found its
greatest success in Crystal City, about 100 miles southwest of San
Antonio. There, the party's candidates won control of the city
council and board of education in 1970. The LRU also managed to get
candidates elected in 22 Texas counties that year. Two years later,
an LRU candidate, Ramsey Muniz, ran for governor but won only about
6 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MORE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During this time, Hispanics saw that unity was essential to
their advancement. An important example was a labor movement that
was reaching the peak of its power in the fields and orchards of
Central California.
</P>
<P>
   It had started in the early 1960s when Cesar Chavez, along with
Dolores Huerta and Gilbert Padilla, began to organize the area's
migrant workers, urging them to join their United Farm Workers
Union.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez had gained national attention in 1965 when he began La
Huelga (The Strike), which used nonviolent methods such as fasts
and boycotts of lettuce, grapes and wine to fight for the rights of
migrant laborers.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez also publicized the general plight of Mexican Americans
to the nation. His work was so well known that in 1968,
presidential candidate Robert F. Kennedy met with him to discuss
working conditions for migrant workers.
</P>
<P>
   Many Hispanics regard Chavez as akin to Mohandas K. Gandhi in
India and the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. in the United States
because of his belief that nonviolent protests could lead to social
change, according to Professor Garcia of the University of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chavez's work caused many Latinos to realize that something
could be done to help their community, which led many of them to
join political groups fighting for Latino rights,'' Garcia says.
</P>
<P>
   Although the militant groups captured much of the media's
attention in the late 1960s and early 1970s, other organizations
were started that quietly worked within the system.
</P>
<P>
   They sought to boost political awareness. Two of them, the
Southwest Voter Registration Project (SVRP) and the Mexican
American Legal Defense and Educational Fund (MALDEF), would prove
crucial to moving Hispanics into the mainstream of American
politics.
</P>
<P>
   Created in 1968, the SVRP sent representatives into Hispanic
communities throughout Texas and California, registering voters and
then seeing that they actually cast ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Formed later in 1968, MALDEF concentrated on legal battles over
boundaries of political districts and the rights of Hispanic
voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the SVRP and MALDEF got going, they become the most
important groups in Mexican American political history,'' says
Rodolfo de la Garza, a political science professor at the
University of Texas in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   But getting the SVRP going wasn't easy, says its president,
Antonio Gonzalez. The first SVRP volunteers who went into Hispanic
communities to register voters met a demoralized people who had
lost hope in the political system, Gonzalez explains, adding:
``There was a sense that you couldn't win. People thought a Mexican
American couldn't win an election. So why vote? But we just kept
pushing the line that if you participate, change will come. And it
did.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez says victories of Hispanic candidates throughout the
Southwest in the early and mid-1970s were a turning point.
``Nothing gets out the vote like winning,'' he notes.
</P>
<P>
   But Hispanic leaders also saw that they needed to attract more
attention in statehouses and in Washington, D.C. So the National
Council of La Raza was formed in 1968 to lobby Congress and state
governments on behalf of Hispanics. In 30 years, it has grown to
include 200 affiliates in 37 states.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an older group, the League of United Latin American
Citizens (LULAC), gained new energy. Created in 1929, LULAC had
long fought for Hispanic rights in education, housing and the
workplace. By the late 1960s, the organization began serious
efforts to persuade different Hispanic ethnic groups to work
together.
</P>
<P>
   Then in the early 1970s some of the militant Hispanic groups
began to lose steam, weakened by internal dissent and a general
decline in minority rights movements. Many in the radical groups
``went to more mainstream groups,'' says DeSipio of the University
of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, he says, the Democratic and Republican parties
also began to recognize Hispanic voters as a growing force. By the
mid-1970s, Mexican Americans in California and Texas were seen as
important swing votes in statewide and presidential elections. In
South Florida, Cuban Americans were beginning their surge in local
and regional politics. In New York and New Jersey, candidates for
statewide office were starting to court Puerto Ricans.
</P>
<P>
   But while the Democrats and Republicans could no longer ignore
Hispanics as voters, Latino candidates still had to struggle for
major-party support.
</P>
<P>
   According to Garcia, the Democrats and Republicans were willing
to back Hispanic candidates in overwhelmingly Hispanic districts
but were reluctant to support them for wider offices.
</P>
<P>
   Those fighting for full support of Latino political candidates
finally saw victories in the late 1980s and early 1990s when
thousands of Hispanic candidates _ most of them Democrats _ began
to run for local, state and national offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the 1990s,'' says DeSipio, ``Latino candidates in the
Southwest were also being thought of for statewide offices, where
they needed a substantial amount on non-Latino voters to win.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the number of Hispanics elected to state offices
nationwide increased 28 percent from 1989 to 1994, growing from 133
to 184. And from 1989 to 1996, the number of Hispanic members of
Congress rose from 10 to 18.
</P>
<P>
   The increase, and especially the rise of Hispanic candidates
``in places you wouldn't expect it ... is really a sign of
success,'' says Selena Walsh, director of policy and communications
for LULAC. ``In many ways, it's a sign of political maturity.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 0957EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0054 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 09:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3569 &Cx1f; tad-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECOLI-KIDS-RPT-COX     10-07 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECOLI-KIDS-RPT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    E. coli's long-term effects remain difficult to assess
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie and Virginia Anderson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Predicting long-term health for survivors of severe
cases of E. coli O157:H7 is not easy. And the reasons seem
contradictory.
</P>
<P>
   While the potentially killer organism is now viewed as
widespread _ showing up in more places _ it hasn't been around long
enough to give doctors hard and fast data. It wasn't until the Jack
in the Box outbreak in 1993, that sickened more than 700 people
over four states, that scientists accelerated their research.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent study of E. coli survivors has just been
published in the medical journal Pediatric Nephrology. Specialists
at Seattle's Children's Hospital and Medical Center are tracking 29
Washington children who became severely ill after eating Jack in
the Box hamburgers. All suffered hemolytic uremic syndrome, or HUS,
which can lead to temporary kidney failure, and can cause havoc in
other organs.
</P>
<P>
   The findings so far? Better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pleasantly surprised by how well all of them are
doing,'' said Dr. John Brandt, a pediatric nephrologist. ``But at
the same time, we're cautiously optimistic about how they'll be
doing in 10, 20 and 30 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the 29 patients, some of whom are now teenagers, none has
required kidney transplants, the gloomiest forecast put forth five
years ago. Eight show signs of kidney abnormality, such as blood or
protein in their urine, Brandt said, but their kidneys are
continuing to filter and function normally.
</P>
<P>
   The most serious condition noted was gallstones. Three children
had surgery to remove their gallbladders.
</P>
<P>
   However, more serious complications may still unfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we still don't know about HUS is this: How much residual
injury are you left with? Kids might be better right now, but we
still don't know what happens to them down the road,'' says Brandt,
who teaches and practices at the University of New Mexico Health
Sciences Center. ``It's everyone's concern they might suffer
permanent kidney failure, but it's not yet proven.''
</P>
<P>
   While none of the Washington children needed a kidney
transplant, an Idaho teenager did. She is the only one so far of
the Jack in the Box outbreak known to have permanent renal failure,
said Bruce Clark, an attorney who formerly sat on the defense
corporate side of E. coli cases but now represents plaintiffs suing
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Predicting the long-term health of E. coli victims is not only a
medical concern but also a legal one.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, several multimillion-dollar settlements
have been paid out by food product insurance companies for numerous
young victims who may face a lifetime of health and wage-earning
complications.
</P>
<P>
   While some kids end up with relatively minor afflictions such as
chronic anemia and hypertension, others face deterioration of the
major organs and learning disabilities caused by central nervous
system trauma.
</P>
<P>
   Shelby Hotz, a kindergartner in Petaluma, Calif., just underwent
a kidney transplant, four years after she survived an E. coli
illness that also sickened her cousin, Jennifer Joseph. Both
suffered HUS and both underwent dialysis, but Shelby's condition
worsened, requiring two months of intensive care. Twenty months old
at the time, Shelby seemed to be recovering well until November,
when her kidney function rapidly declined.
</P>
<P>
   Now 5, she received one of her mother's kidneys during a
transplant in March. ``The kidney is not perfect. It's too big for
her and it bulges out on her one side,'' said Shelby's mother,
Catherine Hotz. ``But there's no signs of rejection so far. But
she'll have to undergo this same surgery again. The kidney could
last 30 years or it could last for five or 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hotz family is suing Costco, where the tainted frozen
hamburger patties were purchased. Medical costs of the transplant
surgery and aftercare have topped $225,000, said the family's
Seattle lawyer, William Marler. Frequent colds and infections,
respiratory problems, nightmares and panic attacks are just a few
of the physical and emotional scars parents say their children have
suffered in the years following severe E. coli O157 attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Dillon Land, 10, of Lubbock, Texas, has particularly rough
nights. That's when he seems most gripped by the memories of the
illness that kept him in a Dallas hospital for Christmas, New
Year's Day and his seventh birthday. He suffered severe
pancreatitis, liver damage and was strapped to a dialysis machine
for a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It terrifies him when he gets sick,'' said his mother, Lisa
Land. ``One night last week he woke up with a cough, and he
couldn't breathe because he was having a panic attack.''
</P>
<P>
   For Elizabeth Tikriti, 7, of Yakima, Wash., her memories of
starting first grade will always be shaded by being hospitalized
for E. coli a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``An event like that just rips you,'' said her mother, Sarah
Tikriti. ``We all grow up thinking the world is a pretty safe
place, but her view of the world is a little different now. Her
fear of being ill is huge.''
</P>
<P>
   Doctors did not give Elizabeth any pain medication because it
would slow down her diarrhea, which was vital to eliminating the E.
coli from her body. She lay writhing in a hospital bed, doubled
over for hours each day, her mother recalled.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most active illness I've ever seen, it's like they
are in labor,'' Tikriti said. Her daughter still sees a kidney
specialist, but is doing well for now. The mothers said they would
like to help parents of other children who have suffered HUS and to
alert the public to the dangers of E. coli. In many cases, their
kids are best at telling it like it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Elizabeth knows a lot about E. coli,'' Tikriti said. ``She's
the first to walk up to someone eating pink hamburger meat and say,
`Do you know what you're doing?'''
</P>
<P>
   Patricia Guthrie and Virginia Anderson write for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
