<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 10:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3576 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-GOVERNORS-$A     10-07 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-GOVERNORS-$ADV12-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS AND CALIF. GOVERNORS SEND MIXED MESSAGES TO HISPANICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, Oct. 12)   (EDs: HISP-LOGO graphic available on the Wieck database.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL RIO, Texas _ In a crowded South Texas shelter, Gov. George
W. Bush makes his way across the room shaking hands, providing
reassuring hugs and offering words of comfort to shaken flood
victims who lost everything.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, an elderly woman, hard of hearing, cries gently
when Bush greets her, overwhelmed by the moment. And when a
reporter wonders if someone could ask her in Spanish for her name,
it's Bush who obliges, bending down close to her ear and asking
loudly: ``Como se llama?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very nice of him to come here and care for the people. I
think it shows his humanity,'' comments Diane Ortiz, another flood
victim, as she watches the emotional scene.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's recent trip to this border town wasn't out of the
ordinary _ governors routinely visit disaster areas to console
victims and survey damage. But the warm welcome he received
demonstrates the Republican governor's popularity among Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   Some of them say he is more sympathetic to their concerns than
some other Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   California's Republican governor, Pete Wilson, for instance, has
incurred the wrath of many Hispanics with his harsh stances on
immigration and affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   The two men's differences illustrate the mixed messages the
Republican Party sends to the Hispanic community, a growing voting
force in both states.
</P>
<P>
   The two have taken disparate political paths.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who cannot run for re-election because of term limits,
supported Proposition 187, a measure that would deny most public
services to undocumented immigrants. A federal judge blocked the
measure after it was approved by voters, and Wilson has appealed
the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said repeatedly he would oppose a similar effort in
Texas, and he is against attempts to make English the nation's
official language, preferring what he calls ``English-plus''
programs. He supports efforts to stem the tide of illegal
immigration but is against the idea of installing a fence or wall
along the U.S.-Mexico border, as some Republicans have advocated.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson also supported propositions halting bilingual education
in schools and ending many state affirmative action programs. Bush
opposes quotas but has backed bilingual education so long as
proponents can show that the programs work.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson did not respond to interview requests for this story.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor routinely stresses the importance of strong
ties with Mexico, often plays host to Mexican officials and endears
himself to his neighbors to the South by trying _ and often
succeeding _ to talk to them in Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   While others may draw dramatic distinctions between the two GOP
governors, Bush declines to make comparisons or pass judgment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into a debate with Governor Wilson,'' he
said in a recent interview in Austin. ``He's a friend of mine and I
like him. He made decisions that he thought were right for his
state and I made decisions I thought were right for Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush also said the GOP needs to do more to attract Hispanic
voters. ``And I hope to show how to. I'm working hard to send a
message that ... says, `You're a part of the future.' He says his
``leadership style ... has been to unite people rather than divide
people.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who is running for re-election this fall against
Democratic Land Commissioner Garry Mauro, has maintained
double-digit leads over him in state polls.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro has had overwhelming support in past elections in the
Hispanic community, and he is counting on it this time. But Bush's
camp believes the incumbent can make inroads. Some even talk about
Bush getting 40 percent of the Hispanic vote, compared with 24
percent four years ago. Mauro rejects that prediction.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile in California, some Republicans worry about the
fallout among Hispanics from Wilson's stands on immigration and
affirmative action. Some analysts say an increase in Hispanic
political activism in California may be the deciding factor in key
elections this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Particularly, Democrats are hoping Hispanic voters will aid them
in winning back the governorship.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP isn't conceding the Hispanic community to the
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Hernandez, a visiting political science professor at St.
Mary's University in San Antonio, says, ``For the most part,
Republican candidates who have done well (with Hispanics) have been
moderate Republicans who have been supportive of a number of issues
_ they don't go out of their way to bash immigration, they make
education a major priority and they don't run as Republicans in the
Hispanic community. They run as individuals (or) they run as
Republicans who aren't as bad as the other guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'll see (some California GOP candidates making) a
lot of comparisons to Wilson, who has some of the highest negatives
in the Hispanic community. They'll say they're not like him. His
position is clearly viewed as anti-immigrant among Hispanic
voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez said Bush's stands on issues important to Hispanics
may serve him well on election day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's doing well. ... He is a moderate in our
community,'' the professor said. ``He's been right on enough issues
that people are predispositioned to give him a fair hearing. He'll
probably get 35 percent (of the Hispanic vote) when (other GOP
candidates) will get 20 or 15 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   In California, Dick Dresner, a Republican consultant who worked
for Wilson, staunchly defends him, saying: ``I don't think the
governor did any of those things to punish Hispanic voters. It was
a matter of fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet Dresner conceded that the passage of the propositions on
affirmative action and undocumented immigrants has cost the
Republican Party votes in the Hispanic community.
</P>
<P>
   ``If (the propositions) hadn't happened, yeah, we'd be talking
about winning the Hispanic vote,'' said Dresner, who is working for
Dan Lungren, the GOP nominee for California governor.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Bashur, a GOP consultant in Austin, says he thinks other
Republicans should follow Governor Bush's lead in dealing with
Hispanics. ``He clearly understands the importance of Hispanics,''
said Bashur, who once worked for Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Party, whether it be in Texas or California,
needs to embrace inclusion,'' Bashur added. ``The Hispanic vote is
critically important both in Texas and California, and policies
shouldn't be offered that alienate (Hispanics) or punish or just
make no sense. ... We have to open the party if we want to become
the majority party.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
