<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 10:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3583 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-GOVERNORS-$A     10-07 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-GOVERNORS-$ADV12-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC LEADERS FLOURISH IN TEXAS POLITICS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, Oct. 12)   (EDs: HISP-TEXAS graphic available on the Wieck database.)  
 (EDs: In 9th graf, Friday (Oct. 9) is correct.)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA TOLLEY  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ A glance at the not-so-distant past illustrates
the headway Hispanics have made in Texas politics.
</P>
<P>
   In a historic election, Henry Cisneros became San Antonio's
first Hispanic mayor IN 1981 _ and the first Hispanic to lead a
major U.S. city. San Antonio had long been controlled by an elite
group of Anglo power brokers, but Hispanics made their voices
heard, with Cisneros getting an incredible 90 percent of their
votes.
</P>
<P>
   Today, their voices are being heard around Texas, from city
halls to the Capitol in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, Hispanics hold a majority six seats on the
10-member city council. McAllen and El Paso have Hispanic mayors,
and Hispanics hold a majority on the Corpus Christi City Council.
</P>
<P>
   On up the political ladder, Richard Raymond, a Mexican American,
is the Democratic nominee for Texas land commissioner, and Tony
Garza is the Republican candidate for a spot on the Texas Railroad
Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the early '90s, we referred to the Mexican-American
community as a sleeping giant,'' said Jerry Polinard, a political
science professor at the University of Texas in Edinburg. ``It is
still a giant. It's just no longer sleeping,''
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics' increasing political clout is evident even in the
governor's race, where Republican incumbent Gov. George W. Bush has
launched an expensive television campaign in Spanish and English to
try to pull Hispanic votes from Democratic opponent Garry Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   Bush and other Republican candidates have been beating a path to
areas rich in Hispanic votes, while Democrats are working hard to
maintain Hispanics' traditional ballot-box loyalty.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Bush and Mauro had their only televised debate
Friday in the border city of El Paso, which is 70 percent Hispanic.
The candidates for lieutenant governor _ Republican Rick Perry and
Democrat John Sharp _ also chose El Paso for their only debate.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, there were some 700 elected Hispanic
officials in Texas. Today, about 2,400 Hispanics occupy the
estimated 6,000 elected posts.
</P>
<P>
   And the potential for further gains looms large.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of sheer numbers, Hispanics have a huge opportunity to
influence Texas politics for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mexican-American population is growing _ the
Mexican-American educated population is growing,'' Polinard noted.
``With education comes a greater propensity to vote, and with
voting comes political power, particularly when you have the
numbers on your side.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of both parties recognize the importance that Hispanic
voters could have on this election and future ones. Republicans
have been making significant strides toward becoming the clear
majority party in Texas, but they need to win over more Hispanic
voters if they want to clinch that coveted role.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats once had an ironclad hold on government _ from the
county courthouses to the governor's mansion. But their power is
eroding, and Hispanics are vital to the party's survival in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A generation can make a world of difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Texas was just a Democratic state, no one paid much
attention to the Mexican-American vote because it didn't really
matter,'' Polinard said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But with the emergence of the Republican Party, Democrats have
increasingly had to rely on the Mexican-American vote to win,'' he
added. ``South Texas holds the key to whether a Democrat can win a
statewide race, and Mexican-Americans hold the key to South
Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy Casanova, a one-time Democrat who is now legislative
director of the Republican National Hispanic Assembly, a
conservative advocacy group, said the GOP is trying to make inroads
into that heavily Democratic territory but conceded it is a major
mountain to climb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be the Republican Party wrote off anything south of
San Antonio and gave it to the Democrats,'' he said. But in the
last 10 years, that has changed, and we're intent on changing it to
the point where the people of South Texas are offered a choice,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Garza, the GOP's railroad commission nominee, is an example of
that effort. He was the first Republican judge in Cameron County in
South Texas but in 1994 lost out in the crowded GOP primary for
attorney general, giving Democrats fodder at the time to say that
Hispanics were not welcome in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in 1995 he became Gov. George W. Bush's first appointee _ as
secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans concede that policies they have supported on
immigration and bilingual education have hurt them in gaining
Hispanic support. But they are trying to downplay those stances to
broaden their support.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro, currently the Texas land commissioner, knows the value of
the Hispanic vote to him _ and his party. He has carried that vote
in his previous races, and he is counting on it in his uphill fight
against Bush, who is nearly 50 points ahead of him in the polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hispanic vote is key to whichever party survives,'' Mauro
said.
</P>
<P>
   A recent U.S. Census Bureau report said that Hispanics are the
fastest-growing ethnic group in the state. Texas, with 5.7 million
Hispanics, ranks second to California.
</P>
<P>
   At last count, there were 1.5 million registered Hispanics
voters in Texas, said Andy Hernandez, a visiting political science
professor at St. Mary's University in San Antonio. Hernandez, a
former president of the Southwest Voter Registration and Education
Project, said the organization predicts the number will be about
1.8 million by the Nov. 3 election.
</P>
<P>
   If that projection becomes reality, he added, the number of
Hispanics who cast ballots could total as much as 20 percent of the
overall vote, up from 16 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   By 2025, Hispanics are expected to total 38 percent of the Texas
population of 27.2 million. An estimated 3.8 million Hispanics will
be of voting age, which would be about 27 percent of all Texans of
voting age.
</P>
<P>
   Already, Hernandez said, ``Hispanics are having more of an
impact in state races. They're winning more city council races and
they're having an influence in the mega-cities such as San Antonio,
Dallas, Houston _ the cities that will determine the future of
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a cumulative effect in terms of Hispanic voters being
able to influence elections and being at the table where the
decisions are made and being able to put forward an agenda that
other people have to respond to,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
