<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-CONTESTS-$ADV13-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANIC CANDIDATES RUN FAR FROM TRADITIONAL STRONGHOLDS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Tuesday, Oct. 13)   (EDs: HISP-LOGO graphic available on the Wieck database.)
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM and STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ From the streets of Salt Lake City to the lake
lands of Minnesota, Hispanic candidates are running for office in
state and congressional races that would have seemed almost
impossible for them to enter only a few years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In Utah, Lily Eskelsen, a Democrat of Panamanian descent, is in
a tight struggle for the state's second congressional district seat
_ covering Salt Lake City _ against Republican Rep. Merrill Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``Utah is not the first place people expect a Latina
candidate,'' Eskelsen says. But being Hispanic has been a major
asset to her campaign, she insists. ``Salt Lake City is becoming a
diverse city, and the voters are looking for someone who can deal
with the city's different communities.''
</P>
<P>
   She says her district's Hispanics, who make up 5 percent of its
population, could be the deciding factor in the race, which
currently is too close to call. The district's non-Hispanic voters
are evenly split between the two candidates, and Eskelsen says,
``Right now, I'm doing very well with Latino voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Eskelsen is not alone in her quest. Throughout the country,
Hispanic politicians are running for offices that are far from
their traditional strongholds. This development comes at a time
when more Hispanics are running for national and statewide posts
generally _ 25 for the House of Representatives, one for the Senate
and 43 for state offices.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we're seeing is unprecedented,'' says Rosalind Gold, a
spokeswoman for the National Association of Latino Elected and
Appointed Officials. Referring to those running in areas where few
Hispanic voters live, she said, ``We see this as a watershed.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Eskelsen, Edwina Garcia, who seeks to become secretary of
state in Minnesota, is running in a place with few Hispanics. They
make up only 1.2 percent of the state's population., Garcia, a
Democratic state representative from Richfield, faces Republican
Mary Kiffmeyer of Big Lake, who helps run a medical service
company.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, Democrat Tom Sawyer, whose mother is Mexican
American, is running for governor against Republican Gov. Bill
Graves. In that state's race for senator, Democratic state Sen.
Paul Feleciano Jr., a Puerto Rican, is in an uphill fight against
incumbent Republican Sen. Sam Brownback.
</P>
<P>
   Feleciano says the fact that he and Sawyer are running ``has
given Hispanics here a message of hope and a sense of
empowerment.''
</P>
<P>
   In other statewide races, Republican Santa Mendoza is seeking to
become Connecticut attorney general, and Republican Eduardo Lopez
is running for Rhode Island secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   In Illinois, Cook County Treasurer Miriam Santos, a Democrat,
faces a stiff battle against incumbent Republican Jim Ryan for
state attorney general.
</P>
<P>
   And in states where Hispanics have traditionally been strong
locally, more are running for higher office.
</P>
<P>
   In California, for instance, former speaker of the state
Assembly, Democrat Cruz Bustamante, is running for lieutenant
governor. Republican Ruben Barrales, a son of immigrants from
Mexico and a member of the San Mateo Board of Supervisors, is
running for comptroller. Democrat Diane Martinez hopes to become
insurance commissioner, and Republican Gloria Matta Tuchman is
seeking the nonpartisan post of superintendent of public
instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Hispanics running for office elsewhere include Democrat Martin
Chavez, who is running for governor of New Mexico; Democrat Ken
Salazar, who is seeking the post of attorney general of Colorado,
and Republican Tony Garza, who is running for a Texas railroad
commission seat.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 43 Hispanics running for statewide office, 26 are
Republicans and 17 are Democrats. Of the 25 Hispanic House
candidates, 9 are Republicans and 16 are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Arturo Vargas, executive director of the National Association of
Latino Elected and Appointed Officials, says these candidates ``are
experienced public servants who have demonstrated to everybody that
they are not just people for our ethnic group.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The key to winning in predominately non-Hispanic districts,
according to a number of the Hispanic politicians running in those
areas, is to stick to the issues.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia of Minnesota says the voters ``want somebody who will get
the job done and work on things that people care about in their
neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Eskelsen adds that she has seen little difference in the issues
that concern Hispanic and non-Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surprise, surprise,'' she says. ``Latino families are worried
about education, Social Security and crime _ the exact same things
that other people are worried about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
