<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 10:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3592 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HISPANIC-DIFFERENCES-     10-07 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HISPANIC-DIFFERENCES-$ADV13-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HISPANICS UNITE ON CERTAIN ISSUES BUT NOT ALL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Tuesday, Oct. 13)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Republicans and Democrats both claim that Hispanics
naturally fit into their camp.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats point to recent elections _ most notably President
Clinton's victory in 1996 with 72 percent of the Hispanic vote.
</P>
<P>
   However, Republicans say most Cuban Americans continue to be
steadfast members of their party and contend that the GOP's focus
on family values, religion and work ethic will eventually draw more
Hispanics to their side.
</P>
<P>
   Neither party is right, says John Garcia, a professor at the
University of Arizona who contributed to the book ``Latino Voices:
Mexican, Puerto Rican and Cuban Perspectives on American
Politics.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others warn that Hispanics, like many groups, defy
stereotyping.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia says Republicans and Democrats should avoid thinking of
Hispanics as a monolith and remember that they have a number of
political cross-currents.
</P>
<P>
   The first thing to understand, he says, is that the label Latino
or Hispanic covers people who come from two dozen countries and who
can claim mixtures of Spanish, Portuguese, Indian, African,
Italian, German and Italian ancestry.
</P>
<P>
   ``People need to remember that the word Latino or Hispanic
includes a large variety of people from many different countries
who have very different histories in this country,'' Garcia said.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, according to a 1992 political survey of Hispanics by
Temple University's Institute for Survey Research, most didn't even
like being called Hispanic, preferring instead to be identified in
national-origin terms such as Mexican American or Puerto Rican.
</P>
<P>
   Only about one in five of those surveyed preferred to be
identified as Latino or Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This desire by the press and politicians, and even us in
academia, to lump Latinos into one group really doesn't reflect the
views of a majority of the people out there,'' said Louis DeSipio,
an expert on Hispanic politics at the University of Illinois at
Urbana-Champaign.
</P>
<P>
   An important obstacle to creating a coalition of Hispanics is
geography. The community's three largest ethnic groups _ Mexicans,
Cubans and Puerto Ricans _ tend to live in different parts of the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican Americans, who make up almost two thirds of Hispanics in
the United States, are concentrated in the Southwest. Cuban
Americans live primarily in South Florida. Puerto Ricans have
settled mostly in the Northeast, particularly New York City and New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   The result is that each of these ethnic groups dominates
Hispanic politics in its particular region. Although this has
helped Hispanics to become political players, it also has hindered
the development of a national Hispanic political movement.
</P>
<P>
   DeSipio notes that ``industrial issues important to Puerto
Ricans in New York City don't have much to do with the rural or
suburban issues of Mexican Americans in California.''
</P>
<P>
   In some cases, analysts say, communities of identical ethnic
background can differ politically depending on where they live.
</P>
<P>
   Rodolfo de la Garza, a political science professor at the
University of Texas at Austin, insists that Mexican Americans
living in Texas tend to hold more conservative views on social
issues than Mexican Americans living in California. ``The
environment makes a difference,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Selena Walsh, director of policy and communications for the
League of United Latin American Citizens, a Hispanic advocacy
group, adds that Mexican Americans in Texas tend to be tougher on
crime and more supportive of anti-abortion measures than Mexican
Americans in California.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is just a more conservative state and that comes across
in many communities, including the Hispanic community,'' Walsh
says.
</P>
<P>
   Like other groups, Hispanics have widely varying income and
educational levels, and that creates another obstacle to political
unity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In essence, Latino political leaders have the difficult task
of keeping together a wealthy Mexican American whose family has
lived in United States since before it was the United States and a
poor Salvadoran immigrant who arrived in the country last week,''
DeSipio explains.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign policy also continues to divide Hispanics. A majority of
Cuban Americans insist that the U.S. government should continue its
economic embargo of Cuba and other efforts to drive Fidel Castro
from power.
</P>
<P>
   However, DeSipio says, ``Mexican Americans care about
U.S.-Mexican relations but could care less about Cuban relations,
with the same being more or less true for the Puerto Ricans,
Salvadorans, etc.''
</P>
<P>
   While Hispanics often are politically fractured when it comes to
candidates and parties, they often come together on certain issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Education, civil rights, immigration and English-only drives
are areas that have the ability to override income, geography and
ethnic differences,'' says Lisa Navarrete, deputy vice president of
the National Council of La Raza, a Washington-based Hispanic
advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Navarrete says if candidates _ regardless of their parties _
fall on the wrong side of these issues, Hispanic voters will turn
away from them at the polls.
</P>
<P>
   She says Republicans have been hurt among Hispanic voters by
recent Congressional legislation that curbed benefits for legal
immigrants and by a GOP-led 1994 initiative in California,
Proposition 187, that would have made undocumented immigrants
ineligible for public schooling and most other government services.
</P>
<P>
   Although Prop. 187 was passed by the voters of California, a
federal judge blocked its implementation, saying almost all of it
was unconstitutional. Gov. Pete Wilson has appealed the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immigration is one thing that every Latino can relate to in
one way or another, and politicians need to remember this,''
Navarrete says.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh adds that while Hispanics often disagree on how many
immigrants should be allowed in the country, they have always
pulled together and fought for better treatment of immigrants
already on American soil.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that we're all here as immigrants,'' she says.
``People either remember what it was like when they started
themselves or can imagine what it was like for their parents or
grandparents.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Navarrete adds that the GOP has also lost favor with many
Hispanic voters over the issue of education. ``Most Latinos are
poor or working class, and they see public education as the only
hope for their kids. They see Republicans as trying to take money
away from their schools.''
</P>
<P>
   But she says the Republican Party shouldn't write off Hispanics
because the vast majority of them fall in the middle of the
political spectrum, where they tend to vote for candidates on the
basis of their stands on issues, not their party.
</P>
<P>
   She notes that the goal _ perhaps elusive _ of many activists is
to bring Hispanic voters together as a single political bloc that
can use its power to push issues important to Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more we act as a solid group, the more politicians will
pay attention to our needs,'' Navarrete says.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
