<SLUG> BC-RAC-RACING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAILY RACING FORM PREPARING `RELAUNCH' 
</HEADLINE>
 FORM-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Daily Racing Form, recently purchased for $40 million by the
Alpine Racing Group, Tuesday announced a ``relaunch,'' to begin
with Saturday's edition, which will be available Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The publication will introduce a series of changes on two
fronts, editorial and statistical,'' said publisher Steve Crist.
``There will be a new look to the newspaper. We have redesigned
Page 1, with a news summary index column which reflects that there
is a lot more in the newspaper than there used to be. There will
also be a new Page 2, which will be a national leaderboard. It will
be a completely statistical page, with rankings in every category
you can imagine. It will look more like the Wall Street Journal
than a page in an average newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for past performances, we have a lot of long-range plans
for enhancements. The biggest one is that for major race meetings,
there will be 12 lines instead of 10. We will also indicate
blinkers on or off, first-time Lasix, and trainer changes. There
will be a lot more changes coming. We will list yearling purchase
prices for 2-year-olds and 3-year-olds, which we should have ready
to go by the end of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Crist addressed the problem of distribution, which has long
plagued the Form.
</P>
<P>
   ``Distribution as it currently exists is terrible,'' said Crist,
a former New York Times racing columnist, editor of The Racing
Times, and vice president of the New York Racing Association.
``That is the No. 1 complaint, and to fix it is Job One around
here. ... We're going to work to get our product out there. We hope
in six months it won't be a problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
