<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOWERS-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FLOWERS OF SHANGHAI': DISCREETLY VEILED BROTHELS OF OLD SHANGHAI 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(gm) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Taiwanese film ``Flowers of Shanghai'' arrived late for its
critics' screening at the New York Film Festival. It wasn't
particularly worth the wait.
</P>
<P>
   Set in 1884 in the brothels of the English concession in
Shanghai, the director Hou Hsiao-hsien's tale of peevish
prostitutes and their gentleman callers is a sumptuous-looking film
that may please the eyes of connoisseurs of chinoiserie but is
unlikely to satisfy audiences in search of nuanced characters,
emotional engagement, dramatic momentum or reverberant history.
</P>
<P>
   Structured like a soap opera with a thin overlay of sociology,
the film switches among its accounts of the lives of lovely young
women in the so-called flower houses of the city _ women with names
like Crimson, Jade, Jasmin and Emerald.
</P>
<P>
   Sold to the brothels at the age of 7 or 8, they have been raised
for their careers, and since the film is discreet about the sexual
component of their lives, they are seen mostly attending moneyed
Chinese men as they feast, gamble and drink.
</P>
<P>
   But some of these women hope to buy themselves out of the
brothels or to marry their clients, perhaps even to attain the
lofty status of first wife in a society where more than one is
clearly not frowned upon.
</P>
<P>
   As for their clients, like the handsome young Wang (Tony Leung
Chiu-wai), relationships are not always without difficulty. The
longtime patron of Crimson (Michiko Hada), he has thrown her
emotional and economic life into chaos by taking up with Jasmin
(Wei Hsiao-hui). Meanwhile the astute Emerald (Michele Monique
Reis) is negotiating to buy her freedom, and Jade (Fang Hsuan) is
refusing other clients because she believes young Zhu Shuren (Simon
Chang) will marry her.
</P>
<P>
   So women weep and backbite, men trash rooms and deal with
questions of honor, poisonous potions of raw opium are prepared,
servants scold and gossip, and elders plot and scheme.
</P>
<P>
   ``Flowers of Shanghai,'' based on ``Hai Shang Hua,'' an 1894
novel by Han Ziyun, and adapted for the screen by Chu Tien-wen, is
obscure about the relationships among its male characters and
reveals little about their activities outside the brothels. Lavish
in its depiction of surfaces _ clothing, furniture, lighting
fixtures _ ``Flowers of Shanghai'' proves deficient in its
revelation of inner lives.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTIONS NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   FLOWERS OF SHANGHAI
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Hou Hsiao-hsien; written (in Mandarin, with English
subtitles) by Chu Tien-wen, based on the novel ``Hai Shang Hua'' by
Han Ziyun; director of photography, Mark Lee Ping-bin; edited by
Zhong A-cheng; music by Yoshihiro Hanno; production designer, Hwang
Wern-ying; produced by Yang Teng-kuei and Shozo Ichiyama. Part of
the 36th New York Film Festival. Running time: 125 minutes. This
film is not rated.
</P>
<P>
   WITH: Tony Leung Chiu-wai (Wang Lingsheng), Michiko Hada
(Crimson), Lee Yu-ming (Azhu), Carina Lau Ka-ling (Pearl), Luo
Tsai-erh (Hong), Fang Hsuan (Jade), Lin Yu-han (Treasure), Simon
Chang (Zhu Shuren), Michele Monique Reis (Emerald) and Wei
Hsiao-hui (Jasmin).
</P>
</TEXT>
