<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED: Q: Who are the actors who portray Bill Clinton and
Monica Lewinsky on NBC's ``Tonight Show With Jay Leno''?
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did the government ever issue a final report on the cause of
the crash of Commerce Secretary Ron Brown's plane? Was a ``black
box'' aboard?
</P>
<P>
   A: The crash in Croatia of the CT-43A, a military version of the
Boeing 737, was caused by a ``failure of command, air crew error,
and an improperly designed instrument approach,'' according to a
report headed by Air Force Maj. Gen. Charles Coolidge Jr. In
effect, the report blamed the 86th Airlift Wing commanders, the
pilots of the plane carrying Brown and 34 other people, and the
Croatian civilians who designed the airport's instrument landing
procedures.
</P>
<P>
   The plane, on its way from Tuzla in Bosnia to fog-shrouded
Dubrovnik, slammed into a mountainside April 3, 1996. A critical
pilot error, Coolidge said, came beforehand when the crew failed to
realize that an instrument landing at Dubrovnik would require a
two-channel receiver to gain directional headings from two
ground-based beacons that used 1930s technology. The CT-43A was
equipped with a one-channel receiver. The plane hit the mountain at
160 mph without wavering from its incorrect course.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force acknowledged that the 23-year-old plane was not
equipped with a so-called black box flight data recorder. In July
1996, the Air Force disciplined about 15 personnel, including at
least two generals, in connection with the crash.
</P>
<P>
   Q: A recent article reported that aspirin may ward off colon
cancer, and researchers are going to test the pills on hundreds of
at-risk people. My mother, father and grandmother all died of colon
cancer, so I would like to be involved . Where can I get
information?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Aspirin Study likely will be approved by the National
Cancer Institute in early 1999. For information about it, call Deb
Rose of the Familial Colorectal Cancer Registry, 215-955-0026.
Participants for the study will be selected from the registry.
Additionally, as published recently in Annals of Internal Medicine,
there's also an apparent reduction of risk of colon cancer among
people who drink orange juice and eat lots of vegetables rich in
the B-vitamin folate, such as spinach, broccoli and romaine
lettuce. Folic acid is the form of folate present in multivitamin
supplements.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the not-too-distant past, England had a big sex scandal
involving a member of Parliament named Profumo. The scandal went on
for months. Whatever happened to him, and to the woman involved?
</P>
<P>
   A: The 1963 case of John Profumo, British war minister at the
time, is believed to have been the first to bring details of a
leading politician's sexcapades to newspaper pages. Profumo, then
48, was a rising star in the Conservative government of Prime
Minister Harold McMillan when the ``Profumo affair,'' as it came to
be called, began to unfold. It seems his mistress, Christine
Keeler, then 21, also was carrying on with Yevgeny Ivanov, a Soviet
diplomat and KGB agent in London.
</P>
<P>
   Profumo was forced to resign from government after admitting
that he lied to Parliament when he denied the affair. McMillan also
resigned, and the Conservative Party, which had been in power for
13 years, lost the election shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Profumo, now 83, keeps a low profile and doesn't grant
interviews, although in 1975 he appeared in public with his wife,
former actress Valerie Hobson, to receive a medal in recognition of
his social work. After ``the affair,'' Keeler became a celebrity of
sorts, making top-dollar cabaret appearances before serving time in
prison for perjury. Now 56, she has struggled with drug addiction
and has been divorced twice. Ivanov died in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Q: CNN recently featured someone named John Whitehead as an
expert opinion-giver on the Clinton impeachment proceedings. He
worked for something called the Rutherford Institute in Washington.
I also recall seeing that a John Whitehead was an attorney for
Paula Jones. Are they one and the same?
</P>
<P>
   A: They are one and the same. The Rutherford Institute, a
nonprofit group based in Charlottesville, Va., took up the Paula
Jones case and found lawyers in its membership network to represent
her. In the past, the Rutherford Institute most often has taken up
the defense of religious rights. Its founder, John Whitehead, was
raised in Clinton's home state of Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How can the average citizen find out just how much in
campaign donations a particular candidate received from a specific
insurance carrier, which could possibly influence the candidate's
legislative direction?
</P>
<P>
   A: The easiest way to learn who contributed to any candidate for
the U.S. Senate or House is to look up the candidate's name on one
of these Web sites on the Internet: the Center for Responsive
Politics, (www.crp.org); FECInfo (www.tray.com/fecinfo); or the
Federal Election Commission (www.fec.gov).
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that an organization will block out
telemarketing calls to a person's home. Do you have any
information?
</P>
<P>
   A: One way to have your name removed from telemarketing lists is
to write: Telephone Preference Service, Direct Marketing
Association, P.O. Box 9014, Farmingdale, N.Y. 11735--9014.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've always wondered about Whoopi Goldberg. Is that her real
name?
</P>
<P>
   A: The actress-comedienne tries to keep her identity secret. The
reason, she once told a reporter, is to protect her family. ``I can
go home and live as this other person, and even though I look like
Whoopi Goldberg on the street, I can whip out my driver's license
and say, 'Hey, but I'm not.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's known, however, that she was born Caryn Johnson in 1950 in
New York, where she and a younger brother lived with their mother,
Emma Johnson, in the Chelsea section of Manhattan. Goldberg claims
that she is ``half Jewish and half Catholic,'' and that one day she
received her invented name by divine revelation. Of the name, the
performer said, ``It was a joke. First it was Whoopi Cushion. Then
it was French, like Whoopi Cushon.'' Her mother told her no one
would respect her with a name like that, she said, so she decided
to use Goldberg instead. ``Goldberg's a part of my family somewhere
and that's all I can say about it,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Why did we have an apparent foreign name, Georges, for a
hurricane?
</P>
<P>
   A: Some of the names have an international flavor because
hurricanes affect other nations and are tracked by countries other
than the United States. One of the major purposes of naming
hurricanes is to help in the exchange of detailed storm information
between hundreds of widely scattered stations, airports, coastal
bases and ships at sea. So, to make international communications
easier, we have Georges, Chantal, Pablo, Gustav, Ernesto, Tomas and
Virginie, among others. The names are selected from library sources
and agreed upon by nations involved during international meetings
of the World Meteorological Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is it true that Kenneth Starr, appearing on ``60 Minutes'' in
1987, said public media should not contain explicit or implied
descriptions of sex acts, and referred to people as perverts who
provide the media with pornographic material while pretending it
has redeeming social value.
</P>
<P>
   A: Kevin Tedesco, spokesman for ``60 Minutes'' at CBS in New
York, said he knew that tale was making the rounds on the Internet,
because CBS had been swamped with inquiries. But it's not true, he
said. The network checked its records and discovered that Starr has
never even been on ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Track star Florence Griffith Joyner's obituary stated that
the cause of death was a heart seizure. What exactly is that?
</P>
<P>
   A: Heart seizure is a term used to describe an ``acute
irregularity'' of the heartbeat which can result in its not
functioning properly, said Carole Bullock of the American Heart
Association. It's not the same as a heart attack, she added. Two
years ago, Griffith Joyner suffered a seizure while on a flight
from California to St. Louis, said Bob Kersee, who coached Griffith
Joyner and was related to her by marriage. The report that her
death was believed to have been caused by another seizure came from
a family spokesman. But a day later, Kersee backed away from that,
saying, ``We have no idea why Florence left us.''
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
