eaten in the store; vitamins or medicines; pet foods; and any
nonfood items (except seeds and plants), such as toiletries.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I would like a yes or no answer. Was Kenneth Starr named
special prosecutor by three judges on a higher court who were
nominated by conservative or Republican presidents?
</P>
<P>
   A: The answer is two-thirds yes, one-third no. The members of
the three-judge panel of the U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington
who appointed Starr were David Sentelle, a judge of the U.S.
Circuit Court of Appeals in Washington; John Butzner, senior judge
for the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in Richmond; and Joseph
Sneed, senior judge on the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San
Francisco. Sentelle was appointed by Ronald Reagan; Butzner by
Lyndon Johnson; Sneed by Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How has John Glenn been performing his elected duties as a
U.S. senator from Ohio, such as voting, attending committee
meetings and so on, since he has been in training for his October
NASA launch?
</P>
<P>
   A: Earlier this year, Glenn was able to take part in Senate
sessions and then went to Houston's Johnson Space Flight Center for
training during recesses, said spokesman Jack Sparks in Washington.
More recently, however, Glenn has given his NASA training priority
over his Senate duties, and therefore has had to miss some of the
Senate sessions. Glenn now is in training full time for the
scheduled launch Oct. 29, Sparks added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of skier Picabo Street? I know she was
injured.
</P>
<P>
   A: A month after Street won the Olympic super-G title in Nagano,
Japan, she tore the anterior cruciate ligament in her right knee
and broke her left leg when she crashed during the downhill in the
World Cup finals at Crans Montana, Switzerland. Although she has
said publicly that she won't be racing for another year, Street
hopes to be back on skis in November. ``I'm coming out of a hole,''
she said last month before speaking during the U.S. Ski and
Snowboard Association congress in Park City, Utah. ``I'll ski for
the winter, then decide what's next.'' She is continuing therapy,
which includes a combination of training in a pool and on a bike
and treadmill. Earlier in the summer Street was asked by a Mountain
Zone magazine interviewer about her timetable for competitive
skiing. Street said, ``2001 and 2002 are probably the seasons that
I'll go back to skiing and compete in Salt Lake (2002 Olympics) and
retire after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Has Supreme Court Justice Clarence Thomas ever voiced an
opinion about the Clinton sex scandal?
</P>
<P>
   A: He isn't known to have made any direct public comments about
President Clinton and his relationship with Monica Lewinsky. At a
question-and-answer session Sept. 14 after a speech before the
National Restaurant Association convention in Arlington, Va., the
justice was asked pointedly about Clinton's problems. As reported
by The Associated Press, he declined to respond directly, only
saying, ``The president of the United States is the president of
the United States.'' He then urged his audience to devote
themselves to being good citizens.
</P>
<P>
   Observers thought Thomas came closer to expressing an opinion in
late September when he spoke to a group of Catholic judges and
lawyers at the 31st annual Red Mass, a blessing of the legal
profession, at St. Vincent College in Latrobe, Pa. While he didn't
mention Clinton or Lewinsky by name, Thomas said, ``Does character
matter? The answer is, emphatically, yes. Character always matters.
But it is your character that matters, not your neighbor's.'' He
continued by saying the best way to teach virtue is to lead by
example and not by pointing fingers. He said it's easy to criticize
moral failures of others, yet tough for people to demand and
maintain their own ethical character and high moral standards.
``Somehow we find it more comfortable and safer to attack someone
else's problems than our own.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently saw an article mentioning that the late Colonel
Sanders of fried chicken fame ``got one of those honorary Kentucky
colonel certificates.''What is a Kentucky colonel?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's an honorary title bestowed by the commonwealth of
Kentucky. The tradition began in 1813, during the second term of
Gov. Isaac Shelby, when he bestowed the title of colonel on Charles
Todd, his son-in-law and a member of his staff. Shelby later issued
commissions to all who enlisted in his regiment in the War of 1812.
Later governors commissioned colonels to act as their protective
guard, and the practice was continued until 1932, when then-Gov.
Ruby Laffoon added ``Honorable Order'' to the name to reflect the
honorary status of its members. The Honorable Order of Kentucky
Colonels was incorporated as a charitable organization and bylaws
were written to designate the organization as ``nonpartisan,
nonprofit and dedicated to good works within the commonwealth of
Kentucky.'' People as varied as Winston Churchill, Bing Crosby,
Lyndon Johnson and Red Skelton have been given the title.
</P>
<P>
   Q: As I prepare to e-mail this question to Q&AMP;A, the Dow Jones
Industrial Average is down 91 points. In reviewing the stocks that
comprise the 30 industrials, I don't see this amount. How is the
change in the average calculated?
</P>
<P>
   A: Stock splits must be taken into account, said Myron Greene,
publisher of Mutual Fund Timing Guide. When Dow Jones and Co. first
began computing the Dow Jones Industrial Average in 1896, it was a
simple average of the prices of 12 of the leading stocks of the
day. Such an average is easy to calculate, but a problem arises
when one of the component companies splits its stock.
</P>
<P>
   Consider a simple index consisting of only two stocks, both
priced at $30 a share. Obviously, the average price is $30. Now
suppose that one of the stocks is split two for one. Each
shareholder ends up with two shares for each one previously held,
but each share is worth only $15, so nothing has really changed for
the shareholder. The split will affect the index, however, because
the new value is the average of $30 and $15, or $22.50. If no
adjustment is made, it will appear that the average has dropped
sharply when, in fact, nothing has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Greene explained that the method used by Dow Jones to adjust for
stock splits is to change the divisor used in calculating the
average. In this example, the sum of $30 plus $15 is divided by 1.5
rather than 2, giving the same result as before (or $30). The
divisor also is adjusted when the number of stocks in the average
changes, as was the case in1916 and 1928, and when a stock in the
average is replaced. To calculate the value of the Dow Jones
Industrial Average today, add up the prices of the 30 Dow stocks
and divide by the current divisor, which is roughly 1/4.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported recently that Edith Stein will be canonized
soon by Pope John Paul II. What did she do?
</P>
<P>
   A: A miracle involving a child is an important element, along
with writings revealing her willingness to embrace death and her
``mystical'' identification with Jesus Christ. In April 1997, the
Vatican authenticated a miracle attributed to Stein's intercession
in the case of a 2-year-old girl who had swallowed poison. The
child was the daughter of the Rev. Emmanuel McCarthy of Brockton,
Mass., a Melkite Rite priest who had long revered Stein as a symbol
of ``nonviolent love'' (the Melkite Rite permits married men to be
ordained). When the child was born in 1984, she was given Stein's
Carmelite name, Benedicta, in order to place her under Edith's
protection. Benedicta was born Aug. 8, which would have been Aug. 9
in Europe, the anniversary of Stein's death in 1942 at Auschwitz,
the infamous Nazi death camp in Poland. Three days after the
McCarthys prayed for Stein's intercession in the poisoning,
Benedicta began to recover. Vatican medical committees determined
that her healing had no scientific explanation, and ruled that it
was an authentic miracle attributable to Stein's intercession.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish-born Stein converted to Catholicism in 1922 and
entered a Carmelite convent in Cologne, Germany, the next year. She
was beatified in 1987 in Cologne by Pope Paul II. She is scheduled
to be canonized Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Who are the actors who portray Bill Clinton and Monica
Lewinsky on NBC's ``Tonight Show With Jay Leno''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Tim Watters is the Bill Clinton character and Kellye Rowland
plays Lewinsky. A third performer is Teresa Barnwell as Hillary
Rodham Clinton. They're all regulars appearing in continuing skits
about the White House, said ``Tonight'' spokeswoman Jennifer
Barnett.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
