<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-LEYRITZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEYRITZ A PLAYOFF SPECIALIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Rangers and Boston Red Sox gnash their teeth at
what might have been. The Houston Astros weep at what was done to
them.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta Braves tremble at his approach.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyritz is in town with the San Diego Padres, a one-man
wrecking crew ready to wreak havoc on the Braves in the National
League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   If he gets off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's unbelievable,'' Braves pitcher Denny Neagle said. ``Some
guys seem to rise to the occasion. He's one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres' backup catcher/first baseman, who isn't in tonight's
starting lineup, is suddenly being ranked with Reggie Jackson,
Mickey Mantle and Babe Ruth as one of the greatest clutch hitters
in postseason history. Six home runs in just 36 at-bats will do
that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always joked that I get paid for April and October,''
Leyritz said. ``April, most of the guys are hurt out of spring
training and I get to play a little more, and October I've had some
success. I've never been an everyday player and every game I've
been in has been kind of a World Series for me personally because I
had to perform if I wanted to play again.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz's latest heroics were three key home runs in the Padres'
division series against the Astros. It didn't go unnoticed that his
two previous teams, the Rangers and Red Sox, were knocked out in
the first round in part because of a lack of offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have an excuse. They used Leyritz to acquire 19-game
winner Aaron Sele and wouldn't have been in the playoffs without
him. The Red Sox dumped Leyritz on June 21 for three
minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boston might have wanted me to be there,'' Leyritz said. ``A
couple of guys on the team I talked to before the playoffs, they
said, `We wish you were still here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   But Leyritz clashed with manager Jimy Williams because he felt
he wasn't getting enough playing time. After being taken out of one
game, Leyritz was reportedly heard going up the tunnel to the
clubhouse screaming, ``Hasn't he heard of Mark Wohlers?''
</P>
<P>
   Wohlers is the Braves' reliever who gave up a three-run homer to
Leyritz in Game 4 of the 1996 World Series. The eighth-inning blow
erased the Braves' 6-3 lead and the Yankees won the pivotal game in
extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think his makeup allows him to do what he does in
postseason,'' Padres manager Bruce Bochy said. ``It's obvious he's
very relaxed and wants to be up there when the game is on the line.
He enjoys the moment. He's not affected by anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
