r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-NLCS-NOTES-TEX     10-07 0537
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOCHY GOES WITH ASHBY OVER BROWN IN GAME 1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Padres manager Bruce Bochy decided to go with All-Star
right-hander Andy Ashby in Game 1 instead of bringing back Kevin
Brown on three days' rest. Bochy used Brown in the division series
against the Houston Astros on three days' rest but didn't want to
push his ace any further. Brown is scheduled for tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the way to go here was Andy Ashby,'' Bochy said. ``A
big reason we're in this situation is because the year Andy has
had. He's fresh, he's ready to go and I don't see any reason to
push Kevin Brown too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Rain is a possibility for today, meaning if the game is
postponed, Bochy could start Brown in Game 1 tomorrow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying anything about rain right now,'' Bochy said.
``I'm not thinking about that. Andy Ashby, he's going the first
game, and that's where we're at right now.'' &QL; 
BRAVES DOWNPLAY EXPERIENCE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Braves have played 75 postseason games since 1991. The
Padres have played seven. But the Braves insist that experience
won't be a big advantage, perhaps remembering what happened last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was our sixth consecutive League Championship
Series, and we were playing the expansion Florida Marlins and it
didn't matter,'' general manager John Schuerholz said. ``It just
depends on who's playing the best, who's pitching the best, who's
hitting the best, who's making the fewest critical mistakes and
errors. An inexperienced team like the Padres who are playing good
and have their confidence up can make up for whatever lack of
experience they have.''
</P>
<P>
   Padres outfielder Tony Gwynn said, ``It's going to be a
challenge. I said all year the road leads through Atlanta and
you've got to find a way to beat them. It's not going to be easy,
but it hasn't been easy all year.'' &QL; 
TICKETS AVAILABLE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Pennant fever is not overwhelming Atlanta right now. As of
yesterday, 5,000 tickets were available for each LCS game.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is the Braves are having to share the October
spotlight with the 3-1 Atlanta Falcons, 3-1 Georgia Tech and the
undefeated Georgia Bulldogs, who are ranked seventh in the country
and play No. 4 Tennessee on Saturday. The biggest story in Monday's
``Atlanta Constitution'' sports section was the season-ending
injury to Tennessee running back Jamal Lewis. &QL; 
KEY TO VICTORY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Braves manager Bobby Cox said there's one key to stopping the
Padres' offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep them off base in front of Tony'' Gwynn,'' Cox said.
``That's what Hank Aaron said this morning, so that's good enough
for me.'' &QL; 
COX MIFFED &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cox seemed miffed yesterday about all the attention being given
to Padres pitcher Kevin Brown and super-sub Jim Leyritz because of
their past successes against the Braves. Brown beat the Braves
twice in the NLCS last year, and Leyritz had a big home run against
them in the 1996 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about Brown, Cox said, ``Kevin Brown is a thorn in
everybody's side, but so is our starting rotation.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he has seen anybody who gets up for the playoffs like
Leyritz, Cox said, ``Yeah, 25 guys on our side.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
