<HEADLINE>
PLAYOFF SUCCESS MAY DECIDE PADRES' FUTURE IN SAN DIEGO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The San Diego Padres take heart knowing the Florida
Marlins knocked off the Atlanta Braves last year in the National
League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres also know what happened after the Marlins won the
World Series. Without any chance of getting a new stadium, Marlins
owner Wayne Huizenga turned around and dismantled his team to the
point where they were the worst in baseball this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, as they prepare to face the Braves tonight in the
NLCS, know their franchise could face upheaval if a new stadium
isn't approved in a Nov. 3 referendum. They've been banking on a
strong run through the playoffs to help push the vote through.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you'll ever see what happened in Florida,''
Padres general manager Kevin Towers said yesterday while watching
his team workout at Turner Field. ``My biggest fear is I don't
think there's a better city in the country than San Diego and I'd
hate to see the franchise have to move. But without putting words
into someone's mouth, I would imagine we'd be in a race with
someone for Northern Virginia if this thing doesn't pass.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres currently play at Qualcomm Stadium, a multi-purpose
facility they share with the NFL's San Diego Chargers. They're
asking voters to approve a $400 million downtown baseball-only
ballpark that they insist will secure a competitive future in San
Diego.
</P>
<P>
   If the vote fails, they fear the work that has been done to
transform the Padres from one of baseball's worst franchises into a
respected one will come unraveled. Remember this is the franchise
that had Roseanne Barr sing the national anthem and pitcher Rich
Gossage accuse owner Joan Kroc of poisoning the country with
McDonald's hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres have come far under owner John Moores from the days
when owner Tom Werner, the Hollywood mogul who made Roseanne
famous, had to unload Fred McGriff, Gary Sheffield, Benito
Santiago, Andy Benes, Bruce Hurst and Randy Myers to keep the books
balanced.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres hit rock bottom from 1993 through 1994 with a record
of 108-171 that was the worst in baseball. Moores took over the
team on Dec. 21, 1994, installed former Orioles boss Larry Lucchino
as club president and within two years, the Padres were NL West
champions.
</P>
<P>
   A 12-player trade with the Houston Astros brought in outfielder
Steve Finley and third baseman Ken Caminiti. First baseman Wally
Joyner was acquired from the Kansas City Royals, second baseman
Quilvio Veras from Florida and pitcher Sterling Hitchcock from the
Seattle Mariners. Greg Vaughn was acquired from the Milwaukee
Brewers during the 1996 pennant drive.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest move made by Towers came last off-season. Fighting
off competition from almost every other big-market club, he
acquired pitcher Kevin Brown from the Marlins for three
minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   That showed the Padres, who had fallen to 76-86 in 1997, were
serious about doing everything they could to win this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kevin Brown has had an enormous impact on this team,
pitching-wise,'' outfielder Tony Gwynn said. ``That's why we're
better suited for a run in the playoffs this year.''
</P>
<P>
   But Brown is a free agent, along with Finley, Joyner, Caminiti
and catcher Carlos Hernandez. The Padres need to either re-sign
them or replace them with comparable talent to remain competitive.
The stadium issue could decide that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it does pass, it's unlikely we'll be able to re-sign
all five,'' Towers said. ``But the stadium is very important for
the ballclub to stay competitive and attract top-notch free agents
and keep the payroll in the $50 million range. Once again, you look
at the playoffs and it's the clubs with at least $50 million
payrolls who are in.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres have already created enough excitement this season to
boost their chances of getting a new stadium. A trip to the World
Series wouldn't hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do hopefully does help out,'' manager Bruce Bochy
said. ``We know a winning season can create more interest in San
Diego. But these are things we can't be concerned with. Our concern
has to be on the field, and that's what we're thinking about.
Hopefully the stadium issue is settled in November and when people
vote, they vote for the right reasons.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
