<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS PERPLEXED BY POWER OUTAGES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By MIKE HEIKA 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The numbers are both stunning and perplexing.
</P>
<P>
   Either the Stars have the most talented power play in the NHL,
one that could challenge franchise and league records this season,
or they have a group that has to prove it can score when games
really matter.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is probably a little of both.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got a chance to be really, really good this year, there's
no doubt,'' winger Pat Verbeek said of the power play. ``At the
same time, it was really, really good last year until the end.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars led the league last season with 77 power-play goals in
82 games, hitting on 20 percent of their scoring opportunities with
the man advantage. In the end, though, when the Stars' needed their
NHL-leading power play to match the Detroit Red Wings in the
Western Conference playoffs, the result was a 1-for-30 outing over
six games.
</P>
<P>
   In the low-scoring series, the Stars were outscored 15-11, and
at the heart of that difference was a 4-1 disadvantage in
power-play situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a huge part of the game, especially if they're calling
more penalties this year,'' said Brett Hull, the newly acquired
winger who could be the key to improving the power play this season
and postseason. ``Every time you're out there, it's a chance to
change the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And the Stars seem ready to change a number of games this
season. Through eight preseason games, the Stars scored 13
power-play goals on 53 chances with the man advantage. That's a
jump from 20 to 24.5 percent. More amazingly, it's a jump in
power-play goals per game of 72.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Now, those numbers have to be taken with a grain of salt. The
Stars played four games against Tampa Bay and Nashville, two of the
worst teams in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   That said, they scored at a pace that would have produced 133
goals in 82 games. That would have shattered the NHL record for
power-play goals in a season, the 119 by the Pittsburgh Penguins in
1988-89.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty incredible what they've been able to do,''
defenseman Derian Hatcher said. ``And when you consider what will
happen when Joe /RNieuwendyk/S comes back, it'll be pretty tough to
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   Key to the unit is defenseman Sergei Zubov, who quarterbacks the
power play from the right point and uses his passing skills to get
the puck into the scoring areas. Defenseman Darryl Sydor mans the
left point and offers a simple alternative to Zubov's slick passes.
Sydor makes quick plays and takes a lot of shots on goal. Rebounds
off those shots often turn into easy goals for the forwards.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Modano will likely man the ``half wall,'' a spot outside
the right circle near the boards, while Jere Lehtinen will be
relied on heavily to dig loose pucks and pounce on rebounds in
front of the net. That leaves Hull to free-lance, setting up in the
slot to release one of the hardest shots in the league from 20 to
30 feet or ``flashing'' in front of the net to deflect shots from
Zubov or Sydor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way he buzzes around in there, /Ran opposing defenseman/S
can lose him real easy,'' Sydor said. ``He doesn't just set up; he
moves in front of the goalie, and you never know where he's going
to be next. Plus, he's got great hands and can make some incredible
tips.''
</P>
<P>
   If that unit of five doesn't get the job done, coach Ken
Hitchcock can send out a second line that will likely include
Nieuwendyk, Verbeek and Jamie Langenbrunner. Sydor and Zubov can
stay at the points or Shawn Chambers, Derian Hatcher or Richard
Matvichuk can step in. What's more, the 6-foot-5, 225-pound Hatcher
can be moved to the front of the net to set one of the biggest
screens in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like the Atlanta Braves' pitching staff, with so
many options,'' Sydor said. Management has ``worked hard to put
together a lot of good pieces and now we have to go out and do
something with that.'' &QL; 
BRIEFLY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Stars assigned wingers David Roberts and Jon Sim to their
International Hockey League affiliate in Kalamazoo, Mich., and sent
goalie Manny Fernandez to a seasonlong assignment with the Houston
Aeros of the IHL. Fernandez, 24, remains the Stars' No. 3 goalie
and can be called up in case of an emergency.
</P>
<P>
   Center Brian Skrudland is scheduled to have arthroscopic surgery
on his left knee today and is expected to be out of the lineup for
two weeks. Skrudland caught his skate in a rut on the ice in
Monday's preseason game with the Tampa Bay Lightning and wrenched
his knee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
