<SLUG> BC-BKN-MAVS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NBA LABOR STRIFE PUTS MAVERICKS' NELSON ON HOLD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 
By RICHIE WHITT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ For the first time in 37 years as an NBA player,
general manager and coach, Don Nelson yesterday opened a training
camp alone.
</P>
<P>
   Sort of.
</P>
<P>
   Just as he was supposed to on the first official day of the NBA
season, the Mavericks' coach took the court at the Baylor-Landry
Center and barked instructions to a group of young, eager players.
But in these uncharted waters of a league-wide lockout, the
whistle-blowing was playful instead of piercing, and the players
were fifth-graders instead of multimillionaires.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mind and body are ready to go, like they always are this
time of year,'' Nelson said. ``It's frustrating because there's
nothing to do. It's boring.''
</P>
<P>
   With his Mavericks either playing overseas, drumming up support
by signing autographs, or picketing NBA sites across the country,
Nelson was host to a clinic for more than 200 Dallas-area children
with outstanding academic achievements. With the labor strife
having already canceled all 114 preseason games and severely
threatening the Nov. 3 start of the regular season, Nelson knows he
better invent ways to keep himself occupied.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll try to stay busy and bide our time by doing some
positive things like this out in the community,'' said Nelson, who
spent yesterday morning playing in a charity golf tournament. ``But
our preparations are done. We're just ready and waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   While players and ownersnegotiate today and wait for arbitrator
John Feerick's crucial ruling, which will come before Oct. 18, the
Mavericks try to conduct business as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Phones are being answered, team programs are getting finishing
touches and tickets are being sold at Reunion Arena. In fact,
despite last season's 20-62 disaster and the uncertainty of the
lockout, the Mavericks expect an increase in season tickets (from
last season's 8,600) for the first time since 1995-96. Those
tickets, of course, will have to be refunded if the lockout cancels
games for the first time in the NBA's 52-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson, as per lockout rules, hasn't had contact with
second-year forward Chris Anstey, spending the summer playing in
Australia. Or with rookie Dirk Nowitzki, a first-round draft pick
averaging 12 points per game playing for a team called the X-Rays
in Germany. Nor has Nelson been able to put new point guard Steve
Nash on the court or negotiate with desirable free agents Kurt
Thomas or Cedric Ceballos.
</P>
<P>
   The only indirect contact teams may have with players is the
forwarding of their mail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until either side starts losing money, nothing will get
done,'' Ceballos said. ``Like everybody else, I'm just waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   The impasse _ basically over the owners' desire for a hard
salary cap and the players' demand to retain their lucrative cap
loophole _ could turn on Feerick's decision. If he rules that the
220 players with guaranteed contracts be paid even during the
lockout, the owners could quickly crumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``They sure won't pay us to sit around and be locked out will
they?'' said Seattle SuperSonics point guard Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   But if Feerick rules for the owners, solidarity in the players'
union could begin cracking as players making minimum salaries start
missing paychecks. While owners will soon receive monetary relief
in the form of the first installment of their new $2.6 billion
television deal, the players' union is busy organizing exhibition
games in Europe and Japan to generate emergency funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still pretty laid-back,'' Orlando Magic guard Penny
Hardaway said. ``But we're starting to get on the edge of our
seats. We're getting antsy to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Dallas wasn't one of the targeted cities _ like Houston, New
York and Portland, Ore. _ for player picketing yesterday. Instead,
it was the site of a clinic Nelson hopes to hold every Tuesday and
Thursday through this month, ultimately reaching 2,000 youths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised it's at this point because all the news has
been bleak,'' said Nelson, who arrived in town from his annual
summer sabbatical in Maui on Sept. 18. ``Scared isn't a good word.
We're just some of the members in waiting.''
</P>
<P>
   When _ and if _ an agreement is reached, teams probably will
need three weeks to sign free agents, make trades and get players
in shape for a regular-season that could be sliced to as few as 50
games. The Mavericks, who have already had two preseason home games
canceled and were forced to pull out of two summer leagues, are
scheduled to open the season in Orlando, Fla., in less than four
weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1217EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
