<SLUG> BC-APPLE-CIDER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE APPLE OF YOUR EYE: SPLASH OF CIDER ADDS CREATIVITY TO COOKING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DOUG BLACKBURN  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ We all know what an apple a day is purported to
do, but apples are much more than the foundation of good health
care. They are also one of the most versatile fruits _ a juicy,
flavorful ingredient in everything from chutneys to pies.
</P>
<P>
   Guess what? That cider sitting in your refrigerator is almost as
adaptable, and probably more underused than the apples from which
it was created.
</P>
<P>
   Cider isn't only a beverage. It can be a wonderful addition to
cooking.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think apple cider is inexhaustible,'' said Greg Patent,
whose book, ``A Is for Apple,'' is scheduled to be published by
Broadway Books next year. ``It has incredible potential as an
ingredient in marinades and sauces.''
</P>
<P>
   Patent, a contributing editor at Cooking Light magazine, wrote a
story on cooking with cider for the October issue. Cider, he
contends, works in a variety of ways.
</P>
<P>
   Call these the cider-house rules. Cider is both sweet and
acidic, which makes it extremely accommodating, Patent said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It works really well with meats. I like to use both the sweet
and hard as a marinade,'' he said. ``If I'm using the sweet cider
as a marinade, I'll finish off the sauce with hard cider. It tends
to accentuate the sweetness of a meat like lamb. I've also used it
with goose, pheasant, pork and beef.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think hard cider would be a good basis to use in a soup. You
have beer and cheese soup. I think if you replace the beer with
hard cider the results would be similar, yet refreshing. The hard
cider acts more like a champagne, because it's effervescent and has
an undercurrent of sweetness.''
</P>
<P>
   Cider also works with greens, especially if it's boiled down,
Patent said. He provided a recipe for New Age Waldorf Salad that
calls for two cups of apple cider to be boiled down to one-half cup
before it is mixed with yogurt and celery seeds for the dressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boiling cider can really concentrate its flavor, making it
taste more apple-like than anything else,'' he said. ``Reduced
ciders open up a whole new realm of cooking possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooking with cider may be a centuries-old New England tradition
that is being revived, if Patent's research is on target.
</P>
<P>
   The Pilgrims arrived at Plymouth Rock in 1620 with barrels of
cider in tow, and Presidents John Adams (a pitcher of cider every
morning) and William Henry Harrison (in 1840 he ran on the slogan
``log cabin and hard cider'') ensured the beverage remained
popular.
</P>
<P>
   While most of their cider was consumed by drinking it, Patent is
convinced it was also used for sauces and marinades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know for certain that the old New England method of making
an apple pie included a cider syrup, that called for boiling down
two cups or so of cider,'' Patent said. ``This gave the pie a rich,
carmelized flavor.
</P>
<P>
   ``By using boiled-down cider, the syrup that surrounds the
apples is thicker and sweeter and more succulent than flour. I like
the approach of using apple with apple.''
</P>
<P>
   Patent admits he is continuing to experiment with different ways
of cooking with cider even though he has completed his upcoming
cookbook (co-authored with his wife, Dorothy Hinshaw Patent). ``All
of these uses for cider was a revelation to me,'' he said. ``I feel
I've barely touched the surface for all the ways cider can be
used.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are the cider recipes Patent provided:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW AGE WALDORF SALAD
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 8)
</P>
<P>
   1 8-ounce carton plain low-fat yogurt
</P>
<P>
   2 cups apple cider
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon celery seeds
</P>
<P>
   5 cups chopped apple (such as Granny Smith, Rome and/or Gala)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped peeled celeriac (celery root)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup coarsely chopped pecans, toasted
</P>
<P>
   8 Boston lettuce leaves
</P>
<P>
   Spoon yogurt onto several layers of heavy-duty paper towels and
spread to one-half-inch thickness. Cover yogurt with additional
paper towels and let stand five minutes. Scrape into a bowl using a
rubber spatula; cover and chill.
</P>
<P>
   Bring cider to a boil in a medium, heavy saucepan over high
heat; cook until reduced to one-half cup (about 20 minutes). Cool
completely.
</P>
<P>
   Combine the chilled yogurt, cider and celery seeds in a large
bowl, stirring yogurt mixture well with a whisk. Add the chopped
apple, celeriac and toasted pecans, tossing gently to coat. Serve
salad on lettuce-lined plates.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SAVOY CABBAGE COOKED IN HARD CIDER
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 4)
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 large yellow onions, cut in half vertically and sliced
one-quarter-inch thick
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 pound savoy cabbage, cored and cut into one-half-inch thick
slices (about 8 cups prepared)
</P>
<P>
   1 large tart apple (eight ounces), quartered, cored, peeled, and
thinly sliced crosswise
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup hard cider
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chicken stock or other poultry stock
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon fennel seed, crushed
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Heat the olive oil in a large skillet or saute pan over medium
heat. When hot, add the onions, vinegar, and sugar. Stir well and
cook, covered, until the onions are softened, about 10 minutes. Add
the cabbage, apple, hard cider, chicken stock, fennel seed,
one-half teaspoon salt and one-quarter teaspoon pepper. Stir well
and cover the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, stirring occasionally, until the cabbage is completely
tender, about 30 minutes. At the end of cooking, there should be
very little liquid left in the pan. If there is too much, cook
uncovered over high heat, stirring and tossing the cabbage mixture
to evaporate excess moisture and to concentrate the juices. Add
salt and pepper to taste and serve hot.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Savoy cabbage is milder and sweeter than regular green
cabbage, and it pairs exceedingly well with onions and apples.
Apples get used three ways here: sliced, as hard cider and cider
vinegar. It's important to use a tart apple, such as Granny Smith.
Serve this with pork roasts or with just about any stew or ragout.
Double the recipe if you have a large enough pan. Leftovers taste
even better the next day.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _____ &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICKEN SCALLOPINI WITH TOMATOES AND RAISINS
</P>
<P>
   (Serves 4)
</P>
<P>
   6 boneless and skinless chicken thighs
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Flour, for dusting
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup hard cider
</P>
<P>
   2/3 cup chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   2 medium Roma tomatoes, peeled, seeded, juiced and diced
</P>
<P>
   1 medium tart apple (about 6 ounces), quartered, cored, peeled,
and diced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup raisins
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons finely chopped flat-leaf parsley
</P>
<P>
   Pound the chicken thighs between sheets of wax paper to a
one-quarter-inch thickness. Cut each thigh into two pieces and coat
both sides lightly with salt and pepper. Dust with flour just
before cooking. Heat half the butter and half the oil in a large
heavy skillet over medium high heat. When hot, add half the chicken
pieces and saute on both sides until golden brown and cooked
through, four to five minutes total. Remove chicken and add
remaining butter and oil to the pan. Saute remaining chicken the
same way. When cooked, add to the first batch; cover and keep warm.
Pour the cooking fat out of the skillet. Replace the pan over
medium-high heat and add the hard cider. Cook, scraping up the
browned bits from the bottom of the pan, until the sauce is syrupy.
Add the chicken stock, tomatoes, and raisins. Cook, stirring, until
the sauce is slightly thickened, about two minutes. Taste and
adjust seasoning with salt and pepper. Add the chicken back to the
pan and baste with the sauce. Cook briefly just to reheat the
chicken. Sprinkle with the parsley and serve at once.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with buttered noodles.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
