<HEADLINE>
VOLUNTEERS SEEK TO IMPROVE OLD CEMETERY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MIKE FRICANO  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TROY, N.Y. _ Volunteers are trying to spruce the nation's
third-oldest rural cemetery, where shrub-obscured resting places
reveal the aging cemetery's need for help.
</P>
<P>
   A newly formed group calling itself the Friends of Oakwood
Cemetery plan to help clean up and raise money for a volunteer
maintenance program.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really is museum of history and art. We'd love to bring the
whole thing back to national prominence,'' the group's president,
Terry Page, said of the nearly 150-year old cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   The 625-acre Oakwood Cemetery was built from 1848 to 1850. Its
nearly 29 miles of roads, 56,000 graves and 350 acres of lawn make
even cutting the grass a daunting task for the four full-time
employees and seven summer part-timers, said Craig Bryce,
vice-president of the cemetery's board of trustees.
</P>
<P>
   Among the group's plans are an adopt-a-plot program where
volunteers would go to the cemetery at least twice a year to remove
weeds and clean grave sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really pretty remarkable they're able to do what they
do,'' said an optimistic Bryce, who added the efforts should
relieve the demands on full-time staffers, who already dig the
graves besides care for the grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it could be wonderful if we get enough people
interested,'' Bryce said, who hopes to schedule more cleanings
depending on how well this first one goes next week.
</P>
<P>
   Generating volunteer interest is important, Bryce said, because
the not-for-profit cemetery's annual budget is $312,000. This comes
from interments, the sale of plots, interest from the $1.2 million
endowment and fund-raising.
</P>
<P>
   The Friends of Oakwood Cemetery hope to raise additional money
through fund-raising and grants, Bryce said.
</P>
<P>
   Renovating the Gardner Earl Crematorium/Chapel is a major
project currently on the agenda. Opened in 1890, it was the first
crematorium in New York State and one of the first in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Today, about 30 services are held each year in the castle-like
structure. And although the retorts (cremation furnaces) lay
dormant in a back room, every year there are about 400 cremations
in an adjacent building, Bryce said.
</P>
<P>
   From the hand-carved oak pews to the five stained-glass windows
in the main chamber, the Earls spent lavishly in designing the
crematorium, said Terry Page.
</P>
<P>
   The windows are believed to be from Tiffany but that cannot be
verified, because there are no records, Page said. Rumor has it
that the Earls asked contractors to destroy them, Page said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were embarrassed at how much they had spent,'' Page said.
</P>
<P>
   The Earl's directive of ``spend as much as you need'' has paid
off some 100 years later. The building's structural integrity is as
solid as the day it was built, Bryce said.
</P>
<P>
   However, not even Tiffany windows can endure years of exposure
to the elements. The cost to fix three of the five windows, is
$48,000, Bryce said. Because, the crematorium's endowment is only
$50,000, and the cemetery only spends the $4,500 annual interest on
upkeep, grants will be needed to fix the windows, Bryce said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Page and Bryce said they would like to see more services
and tours at the crematorium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a shame that people don't come in here. It's a
gorgeous building. It's a gorgeous cemetery,'' Bryce said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
