<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 12:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3887 &Cx1f; tth-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ECONOMY-COLUMN-RAMSEY     10-07 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ECONOMY-COLUMN-RAMSEY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPORT-DEPENDENT WASHINGTON IS VULNERABLE TO RECESSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By BRUCE RAMSEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Official economists are often among the last to
predict recessions. Thus it was notable Monday when Oregon's
economist, Paul Warner, said the chance of a U.S. recession ``is
definitely growing and is getting close to 50 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a month ago, our own state economist, Chang Mook Sohn, put
that chance at 35 percent. Sohn takes cheer in the Federal
Reserve's recent cut in interest rates and says the United States
may still be spared a downturn. But he adds, ``We recognize the
uncertainty.''
</P>
<P>
   Recession has been raging in Asia for a year, and has now spread
to Russia. And though it has mainly not spread here, every time one
looks at the crisis, it seems to get worse.
</P>
<P>
   This state is particularly vulnerable to infection because it is
dependent on trade. The Boeing Co., our largest exporter, has just
reported that it has 36 undelivered aircraft in storage, partly to
customers in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   We are also vulnerable in ways common with other states. If
stocks go down, fewer employees cash in options. Last year, Warner
said, Oregon residents reported $4 billion in capital-gains income,
double the amount of 1995. He expects a much lower figure this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Warner doesn't have a capital-gains figure for Washington
because we don't tax income. But the income, or lack of it, is just
as real.
</P>
<P>
   Warner takes comfort, however, in low interest rates. ``We have
no experience with a recession that is preceded by falling interest
rates,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Warner appeared on a panel in Seattle organized by The
Associated Press. The panel was disturbing in its contradictions.
Representatives of agriculture and forest products painted a
picture of gloom, while a representative of the software industry
was exuberantly bullish.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Wilcox, president of the Washington Software Alliance,
said her members rely more on exports to English-speaking countries
than to Asia. Her members are doing great. Employers here,
including non-software companies such as Boeing and Safeco, predict
that software jobs will increase by 46,000 workers in the next
three years, she said. Software salaries in this state, she said,
are the highest in the nation, and average $65,000.
</P>
<P>
   On the same dais was Jim Jesernig, director of the state's
Department of Agriculture, who said this year has been ``one of the
most difficult times farmers have faced in the state's history.''
</P>
<P>
   The apple harvest is coming in at 93 million to 94 million boxes
_ not the 110-million-box flood that growers feared, but a deluge
in any case. Asia, which had been absorbing 35 percent of
Washington's harvest, has cut back. Russia, which had been taking
lower-quality fruit, has imploded. And, Jesernig said, ``China has
glutted the world market in juice. It's almost not worth it to
juice apples anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's other big farm crop is soft white wheat. Of this, 87
percent has been shipped to Asia to be made into noodles. Asians
are not going to stop eating noodles. But Tom Mick, CEO of the
Washington Wheat Commission, said they have cut back on Washington
wheat. Government grain boards in Canada and elsewhere have
undercut U.S. dealers, and the U.S. government has shut off the
market in Pakistan by refusing to extend commercial credit. We
continue to embargo another good customer, Iran.
</P>
<P>
   Washington wheat farmers are being paid about $2.40 per bushel,
which Jesernig reckons to be about $1 below cost. Grain elevators
are full, and 32 million bushels are going to be stored on the
ground, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Then there's forest products. Forest exports to Asia are ``in a
huge nose dive'' this year, said Rosemarie Braden, research analyst
with the Center for International Trade in Forest Products at the
University of Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Logs, lumber and chips have made up most of the industry's
export revenue in the 1990s, but almost none of its growth. These
traditional exports plunged in 1997 and continue downward. The '90s
growth had come in the much smaller but promising value-added
products: prefab buildings, joinery, wooden windows, cabinets and
doors. These are luxury items in Asia, and sales have dropped
sharply. Braden said some companies have walked away from the
market, so that when good times return they will have to start all
over again.
</P>
<P>
   No one spoke from the fishing industry, and it was just as well.
And yet the central Puget Sound area continues to hum along at full
employment.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Seattle, we think of ourselves as sophisticated and
connected to the world. Actually, it is in places like Forks,
Dayton and Wenatchee where connection is more direct and obvious.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Ramsey is a P-I reporter and columnist. His e-mail address
is bruceramsey(at)seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
