<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3902 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-FALLOUT     10-07 1695
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-MICROSOFT-FALLOUT-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHEATING DEATH-BY-MICROSOFT-UPGRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   (ART ADV.: A graphic is being sent to NYTNS clients. 
Non-subscribers can make individual purchases by calling
212-556-4204 or -1927.) 
 By HIAWATHA BRAY   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four years ago, Artisoft Inc. was riding high. Since then, it
has shrunk from 700 employees to 150. In the last two years it has
tumbled from a $13.6 million annual profit to a combined loss of
more than $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Corp.'s popular operating system and its successor,
Windows 98, have caused life-threatening crises at Artisoft and
many other software companies, simply because Microsoft keeps
adding features to Windows that computer users once had to buy
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   The practice has drawn fire from the US Justice Department. For
instance, Microsoft's addition to Windows of free software to
browse the Internet helped spark the current federal antitrust
lawsuit against the software giant.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's upgrade strategy is nothing new. Since the early
1980s, the company has frequently added featuresat no extra charge
_disk repair utilities, networking support, and Internet
compatibility, to name a few. Tod Nielsen, general manager of
software-developer relations at Microsoft, insists that the
Redmond, Wash., company adds features to improve the product, not
to hurt smaller competitors.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft's slightest move can cause serious hardship for
small companies that suddenly see their markets disappear.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies react with fury, demanding that the federal
government set limits on Microsoft's ability to add free upgrades
to its software.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely unfair,'' said Zvi Alon, president of
NetManage Inc., a California maker of networking software that has
lost key markets to Microsoft. Alon believes that Microsoft should
be compelled to charge for significant additions to its products.
</P>
<P>
   He insists that there won't be much of a software industry left
if Microsoft has carte blanche to add features to its operating
systems. ``If we use that logic and keep it moving forward,'' said
Alon, ``essentially we might as well all go home and stop
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Other software companies, such as Symantec Corp. and Quarterdeck
Corp., are finding ways to survive and even prosper by cooperating
with Microsoft. And still others dramatically shift their focus,
aiming to find new success in a market segment that Microsoft
hasn't conquered _ at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   Artisoft, at one time based in Tucson, Ariz. but now in
Cambridge, Mass., is one company that's being forced to adapt or
die.
</P>
<P>
   Artisoft had once carved out a small but profitable niche. By
the mid-1980s, businesses had discovered the power of computer
networking, connecting desktop machines to share files or use the
same printer. But it was hard to link computers that ran
Microsoft's then-popular MS-DOS operating system.
</P>
<P>
   Artisoft responded with LANtastic, software that made it easy
for small businesses to tie their PCs into networks. In fiscal
1994, Artisoft raked in revenues of more than $107 million and
profits of $13.6 million, primarily on the strength of -LANtastic.
It was the last good year the company had.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Microsoft rolled out its replacement for MS-DOS _
Windows 95, which had networking software built in.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Thomas, Artisoft's chief operating officer and president,
realized that the firm was in big trouble. ``You're competing
against a company that not only has a huge marketing operation, but
also is installing its product on every PC made,'' said Thomas.
``In late '95, early '96, it was clear this was going to have a
huge impact on the revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   It was time to find a new business model. Artisoft decided to
plunge into the market for software that controls the operation of
complex business telephone systems. The market for
-computer-telephone integration is supposed to grow to $6 billion a
year by 2000, according to market research firm Dataquest.
</P>
<P>
   Artisoft moved to Massachusetts in September to take advantage
ofa high concentration of expertise in its newfield. Says Thomas:
``I don't think you can find a better place than the Boston area
for computer telephony.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another local firm has decided to seek relief through
merger. Last month, FTP Software Inc. of Andover, Mass. was
acquired by Alon's NetManage Inc. Both have struggled to reorient
their businesses after key products were rendered irrelevant by
Windows 95.
</P>
<P>
   NetManage invented WinSock, a program that enabled users of PCs
to communicate over the Internet. In the early 1990s, when
consumers and businesses began going on line, NetManage scored
considerable success with its Chameleon Internet software, which
includeda primitive Web browser and WinSock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a substantial market share, 60 plus percent,'' said
NetManage president Alon.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side of the country, FTP was also prospering from
the sale of Internet software for PCs, as well as its OnNet
corporate networking software based on TCP/IP, the Internet data
protocol.
</P>
<P>
   But both companies were unprepared for the arrival of Windows
95. Microsoft had included its own software, similar to WinSock,
and the first crude but usable version of Microsoft's Internet
browser. Suddenly, NetManage Chameleon didn't have a market any
more.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's operating systems weren't NetManage's only source of
trouble. Another successful NetManage product was Ecco Pro,a
popular personal information manager, a program used by individuals
to plan their activities. But Microsoft began including a competing
product, Outlook, with its Microsoft Office software suite. Office
is by far the most popular business software package, and Alon
decided that few Office users would pay an additional $139 for Ecco
Pro. Last December, NetManage discontinued the product.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, on the East Coast, FTP was also struggling. Why
should businesses buy OnNet to create internal TCP/IP networks?
Windows 95 had similar features built right in. Soon FTP saw its
sales wither. The firm posted a 1997 net loss of $56.6 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were competing with a free offering bundled with operating
systems'' sold by Microsoft, FTP general counsel Douglas Flood told
Bloomberg News last year. ``That clearly had some impact.''
</P>
<P>
   It all looked familiar to Alon at NetManage. ``FTP was in
exactly the same boat,'' he said. Their common hardship made an
acquisition seem appealing.
</P>
<P>
   Both companies also shared a strong background in creating
software for linking PCs to diverse computer systems. By focusing
the new NetManage on these markets, Alon hopes to stay clear of
future operating systemchanges from Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Makers of utility software are especially vulnerable to
death-by-Microsoft-upgrade. Utilities perform unglamorous but
important functions, such as fixing minor disk-drive problems,
restoring accidentally deleted files, or hunting for computer
viruses.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterdeck Corp. of Marina del Rey, Calif., came to prominence
selling QEMM, which makes more efficient use of memory on
Microsoft-based PCs. But Windows 95 featured vastly improved memory
management that made products like QEMM far less useful.
Quarterdeck's revenues fell from $117.6 milllion in 1995 to $83.8
million last year, and 1995's $11.25 million profit became a 1997
loss of more than $18 million.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Dickson, Quarterdeck's vice president of marketing, said
her firm is rolling out utility products to solve problems that
Microsoft still hasn't addressed. For instance, it's notoriously
difficult to remove unwanted software from a Windows machine.
Quarterdeck is one of several companies touting uninstaller
software to make the job easier. The firm has also entered the
antivirus market and has a new disk-cloning product to help people
add bigger hard drives to their machines.
</P>
<P>
   Far from being angry with Microsoft, Dickson said, Quarterdeck
sees Microsoft as an ally. Microsoft engineers consult with
Quarterdeck's people, keeping them informed of changes in Windows
that might affect sales of a Quarterdeck product. Quarterdeck uses
this guidance to design new utilities that meet needs that
Microsoft has overlooked.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a symbiotic type of relationship,'' said Dickson. ``We
wouldn't even have a utilities business if it weren'tfor the
operating system.''
</P>
<P>
   A similar relationship exists between Microsoft and Symantec
Corp., maker of the popular Norton Utilities. Each new version of
Windows has added features like disk repair that were once a prime
reason to buy Norton Utilities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're the quintessential example of a company that
ought to hate Microsoft.'' said Symantec president Gordon Eubanks.
Instead, Eubanks is a close Microsoft ally and has helped to form
the Association for Competitive Technology, a -software-industry
group that supports Microsoft in its antitrust battles.
</P>
<P>
   Partly it's because many of the improved utilities found in
Microsoft products, such as disk--repair software, were actually
created by Symantec and licensed to Microsoft. But aside from that,
Eubanks said that Microsoft works closely with Symantec to ensure
coexistence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it shocks people,'' said Eubanks. ``They're not a bunch
of raving maniacs who want to put everybody out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems to be working. Symantec is the hottest company in PC
utilities, with fiscal 1998 sales of $578 million and profits of
$85 million.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's Tod Nielsen says his firm runs aggressive programs
to inform software developers about Microsoft's upgrade plans.
``Any developer that's impacted, he's going to know way before it's
shipping,'' Nielsen said.
</P>
<P>
   He conceded that some companies have been squashed by Microsoft
upgrades, but he argued that these are mainly firms that weren't
prepared to compete in one of the world's toughest industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are companies that say, `It's not fair; we have a
birthright,''' said Nielsen. ``Those are the companies that get
impacted negatively.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-09-30-98 1352EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1317EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
