<HEADLINE>
SCIENTIST SEES POWER DRAIN IN SWITCHED-OFF APPLIANCES  
 ARCHIVES WIN REPRIEVE IN STORING ELECTRONIC RECORDS  
 MEDITATION IN A WIRED WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Alan Meier would like people to mean ``off'' when they say
``off.''
</P>
<P>
   Meier, a scientist at the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory
in California, estimates that U.S. consumers spend $3.5 billion a
year powering electronic devices and household appliances that they
think are turned off, when actually those appliances are in a
suspended state called stand-by mode.
</P>
<P>
   TVs and VCRs are among the biggest culprits, as are high-end PCs
chock-full of power-sucking chips and gadgetry. While a TV, for
example, might use 50 watts of power when it is on, it may still
use as much as 10 watts when it is off. This stand-by feature makes
possible the much-revered remote control, among other things.
</P>
<P>
   Battery chargers, like those used for cellular phones, continue
to use energy even when there is no phone plugged in. Even
microwaves consume energy when they are not in use, mostly to power
the electronic keypad. And Intel's Pentium chip, the brains inside
most PCs sold today, is a huge stand-by energy hog, Meier says.
</P>
<P>
   Though the wasted electricity amounts to only a few cents per
appliance, the total being wasted is enormous: equivalent to the
amount produced by eight power plants. That comes to about $50 a
household per year, Meier says.
</P>
<P>
   The solution? Meier says it is unreasonable to expect consumers
to unplug, particularly when they have come to appreciate the
conveniences made possible with stand-by mode, as in remote-control
garage-door openers.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the responsibility lies with manufacturers, who are
simply not paying much attention to energy use. Using an
energy-saving power supply adds nothing to the cost of producing a
device, according to the makers of energy-efficient power
technology, like Power Integrations of Sunnyvale, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Meier says he and his colleagues hope to avoid promoting
government regulation to deal with this problem, by getting
manufacturers to agree voluntarily to build products that use only
1 watt in stand-by mode.
</P>
<P>
   The other side of the problem, he says, comes from misuse of the
word ``off,'' which in electronics has come to mean neither off nor
on. Someday, if Meier's efforts pay off, the ``off'' button will,
once again, actually mean ``off.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   Archives Win a Reprieve in Storing Electronic Records
</P>
<P>
   As technology marches forward, so do the paper handlers in the
United States' capital.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a U.S. District Court judge sided with the National
Archives and Records Administration in an 11th-hour plea for more
time _ more time, that is, to figure out how to deal with the
voluminous e-mail and other electronic records produced daily by
federal agencies.
</P>
<P>
   The government now has no system for storing electronic records
except to print them out and file them. In the process, a vast
majority simply get deleted.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two years ago, a group that included researchers,
librarians and Ralph Nader's group Public Citizen sued the
Archives, contending that allowing the deletion of electronic
records leads to the loss of valuable public information.
</P>
<P>
   The plaintiffs contend that paper records are not as useful to
the public as electronic ones, which can be easily searched. (The
nation got its first taste of the increasing importance of
electronic records during the Iran-contra trials, when some of the
most important evidence against Oliver North came from e-mail
records.)
</P>
<P>
   Last year the judge agreed with the plaintiffs in the lawsuit
and ordered the National Archives to devise guidelines for the
storage of electronic records by Sept. 30, 1998. But when that
deadline passed, the Archives were given extra time to come up with
a master plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, it is business as usual in Washington, as
agencies continue to push the delete button.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated plaintiffs accused the Archives of stalling,
primarily to cover up the fact that they have not made any
progress. The archivist of the United States, John Carlin, says the
problem is simply too complex to rush a solution.
</P>
<P>
   But Eddie Becker, a Washington researcher who is a plaintiff in
the suit, said: ``They're more concerned with how to get rid of
stuff, not preserve it. They want to preserve only the material the
agencies want to keep.''
</P>
<P>
   _ LAURIE J. FLYNN
</P>
<P>
   Meditation in a Wired World: Stare at the Screen and Relax
</P>
<P>
   It is easy for Mark Abouzeid to preach inner harmony and balance
for today's highly stressed business people. He lives in a house in
Castelmuzio, Italy, population 250, where the view from his window
_ a hundred olive trees and the church featured in the movie ``The
English Patient'' _ is a picture of tranquillity.
</P>
<P>
   But with the help of two high-speed phone lines and nine
employees scattered in Europe and the United States, Abouzeid, a
transplanted American, keeps in touch with angst, '90s style.
</P>
<P>
   His business, Voice of Wellness, creates sites on the World Wide
Web intended to help the average, non-Tuscan-dwelling individual
learn to stay centered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't make much sense sitting in an office, stressed out,
trying to convey those principles,'' he explained.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the summer, the site began offering a guided meditation
exercise, which was culled from a CD-ROM project that never quite
got off the ground. So far, 12,000 people have come to
Aboutliving.com to download the free audio, at least half of them
doing so from work, Abouzeid said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We decided to give away the software and see if anyone would
use it,'' he said, explaining that meditation has a bad image and
therefore needs free promotion. ``People think they have to shave
their heads and become gurus just to take a few minutes to relax.''
</P>
<P>
   Chilling out, Web-style, involves staring at images on the
screen while a calming voice leads a user into meditation. ``The
primary focus is becoming aware of everything around you, more
mindful of how you act and react,'' said Abouzeid, who worked in
mergers and acquisitions as an investment banker in Asia in the
1980s. ``I've got a lot of karma to work off.''
</P>
<P>
   Abouzeid recognizes that he also has a lot of work to do. Making
a viable Web business with a wellness magazine that plans to
survive off advertising sales and electronic commerce is a
challenge to anyone's inner peace.
</P>
<P>
   _ LISA NAPOLI
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-04-98 2356EDT &QL;
</P>
