<HEADLINE>
BUSH TO DECIDE ON PRESIDENTIAL BID NEXT SPRING 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: Filed in national, ``a,'' and national politics, ``p,''
categories)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAIME CASTILLO  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ George W. Bush, virtually assured a second term as
governor of the nation's third largest state, says he will decide
next year whether he will seek the Republican nomination for the
presidency in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, son of the former president, is seen as a leading force in
the Republican Party and a candidate with broad appeal among
moderates and minorities. Polls indicate he has a resounding lead
over Garry Mauro, his Democratic opponent in next month's
gubernatorial race.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with reporters and editors of the San Antonio
Express-News on Tuesday, Bush said he did not think a potential
White House run would hurt his effectiveness as governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I wasn't interested in running for president, I would've
said so. And I told the truth nearly a year ago when I said I don't
know whether I will or will not run for the presidency, and people
are going to have to factor that in when they get to the voting
booth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, 52, said he learned at the side of his father the kind of
toll the intense spotlight of a presidential campaign can take on a
president's family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it's like to be the son of a president, since I've
been one. I've just got to weigh it out in my mind whether or not I
want to put my girls and my wife, who I adore and who is a great
first lady for Texas, into ... a different life.''
</P>
<P>
   Contradicting several recent news reports, Bush said he was not
afraid of the inevitable media scrutiny that would focus on him if
he became a candidate in the national arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``My life's been scrutinized. It was scrutinized in 1992 to the
point of a six-column story in the Wall Street Journal and I wasn't
even a candidate. It's been scrutinized in 1994'' during his first
campaign for governor, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can assure you my life was scrutinized during my entire time
as governor and I'm really being scrutinized now because of all
these rumors,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the Mauro camp, who have criticized Bush for not
committing himself on the presidential question, urged the governor
to level with Texas voters.
</P>
<P>
   They point to the millions of dollars Bush has raised this year
outside of Texas as a sign of his intention to seek the presidency
in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is running for president. He knows it and
everyone else knows it,'' said Billy Rogers, a spokesman for Mauro.
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he was intent on focusing his energies on winning the
governor's race.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no focus group or poll that I can possibly run to
determine whether or not I want to make the commitment to leave
Texas and run for higher office,'' he said. ``I never ran for
governor to be president. I ran for governor to be the best
governor I could be.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next spring I'll make up my mind _ not on polls, focus groups
or whether I can withstand the scrutiny. It will really be based
upon whether I want a change of lifestyle with a family I love a
lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
