 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
Hunting game misses mark 
By Yusuf Davis  
c. 1998 Cox News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Rocky Mountain Trophy Hunter''
</P>
<P>
   (For PCs, by Wizard Works, http://www.wizworks.com, $24.99)
</P>
<P>
   David Sponaas of Duluth says ``Rocky Mountain Trophy Hunter''
might be good for some gamers, but not for him. He said the CD-ROM
hunting program was neither educational nor a challenge to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of corny, and it wasn't that much fun,'' the
15-year-old reviewer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trophy Hunter,'' an interactive hunting game, lets players
track and shoot big-game animals in the wilds of the Rocky
Mountains. Players hunt for bighorn sheep, bear, elk and moose in a
variety of environments and may select from weapons including
shotgun, rifle, compound bow, muzzle loader and six-shot revolver.
</P>
<P>
   As in real life, hunters track animals using calls, bait and
binoculars and must deal with extreme weather conditions such as
rain, snow, and thunder and lightning.
</P>
<P>
   Tracking methods also include aerial maps, with hot-spot
markers, compass and wind indicator, path and bedding areas, and
rubbing and droppings. There are even blood trails, for when errant
shots don't bring an animal down immediately. Players must always
be mindful of wind direction and choose location accordingly,
because if the animals detect a hunter's scent, they will turn and
run.
</P>
<P>
   Successful hunters get to display their kills in a trophy room.
</P>
<P>
   David said that despite the maker's claim of an ultra-realistic
hunting environment, the graphics of ``Trophy Hunter'' were ``not
all that good, and the scenery and the animals sometimes didn't
seem to match.'' He didn't like the sounds either.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was too time-consuming trying to find the animals, and the
game got kind of repetitive,'' David said.
</P>
<P>
   -- Age: Teens
</P>
<P>
   -- Minimum requirements: Windows 95, Pentium 75, 16 megabytes
RAM, 60 MB free hard disk space, Direct X-compatible video card
(high-performance card recommended), Direct X-compatible sound
card, CD-ROM drive, mouse
</P>
<P>
   -- David's grade: D-
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   New sites promote
</P>
<P>
   safer Net surfing
</P>
<P>
   Despite possible hazards, there are many great ways young people
can use the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Some simple rules for surfing the Net or participating in chat
areas can help kids preserve their innocence and possibly save
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   A number of ways to make Web surfing safe for kids are outlined
on a new Web site, called SafeKids.com, http://www.safekids.com,
which premiered last month. The site is the brainchild of Larry
Magid, child online safety advocate, technology journalist and
national Internet expert. Magid is also the author of the National
Center for Missing and Exploited Children's popular booklets,
``Child Safety on the Information Highway'' and ``Teen Safety on
the Information Highway.''
</P>
<P>
   SafeKids.com provides specific steps parents can take to teach
their children critical thinking about safety and privacy and to
improve communication with children and teens about what is or is
not good for them.
</P>
<P>
   SafeKids.com includes links to informative sites for kids,
parents and teachers, links to child-safe search engines and a
complete directory of parental control programs, or ``filters,''
which automatically determine the sites a youngster may access.
</P>
<P>
   A site for teens, SafeTeens
</P>
<P>
   .com (http://www.safeteens
</P>
<P>
   .com), was also launched in September.
</P>
<P>
   The two sites will be updated regularly and serve as a resource
for the America Links Up Campaign, which started Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   Magid says that while filtering software is an option,
parent-child communication is a more critical component to
protecting children in cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to talk with your kids about how to behave in
cyberspace,'' Magid said. ``The purpose of SafeKids.com and
SafeTeens.com is to help users better understand the issues and
their options and take responsibility themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about critical thinking. The judgment skills kids
learn surfing the Net will serve them in all aspects of life,''
Magid said. ``Filters, like crossing guards, have their place. But
eventually kids have to learn to look both ways when the crossing
guard isn't around.''
</P>
<P>
   SafeKids.com and SafeTeens
</P>
<P>
   .com approach cyber-safety in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``While young children usually pay attention and obey what their
parents teach them, teens have a tendency to push up against
authority,'' Magid said. ``At SafeKids.com, we educate parents
about how to work with their children. At SafeTeens
</P>
<P>
   .com, we communicate directly with teens to empower their
Internet skills, encourage them to avoid the unsavory side of the
Internet and help them educate their parents about the online
world.''
</P>
<P>
   September was also the premiere of the SafeKids newsletter
(subscribe(at)safekids.com), a free weekly e-mail that informs
parents and teachers about new sites and Internet child-related
developments. It is compiled for SafeKids.com by the staff of
SageWay.com, a leading child advocacy site.
</P>
<P>
   The sites' initial corporate sponsors include America Online,
Disney.com, Network Solutions and SmarterKids.com. Yahoo!, Lycos,
TalkCity, Link Exchange and 1WEBCAST are providing promotional
support. Additional assistance is provided by the National Center
for Missing and Exploited Children.
</P>
<P>
   Magid can be reached at magid(at)latimes.com or by calling
605-813-9478.
</P>
<P>
   _Yusuf Davis
</P>
