<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GERMANY-FOREIGNERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHROEDER'S STANCE HEARTENS WOULD-BE GERMAN CITIZENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ Like all seven million foreigners living in Germany,
Nazim Gucer couldn't vote in the recent general election. But he
cheered Gerhard Schroeder on to victory.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder, who ousted Helmut Kohl as chancellor on Sept. 27,
campaigned on a promise to ease Germany's stringent citizenship
laws, which since 1913 have been based on blood, not place of birth
or allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   Under these laws, which other European nations consider
anachronistic, the descendants of Germans who settled in the United
States or elsewhere centuries ago are still of German blood and can
return to claim citizenship. But the children and grandchildren of
the Turkish ``guest workers'' who arrived here in the 1960s must
remain ``guests,'' as they are legally defined.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to become a German citizen,'' said Gucer,
standing behind the counter of his small East Berlin restaurant,
the Kastanian Grill. ``This is my home now.''
</P>
<P>
   Gucer, 27, came here from Turkey three years ago, taught himself
passable German and opened one of Germany's ubiquitous
``imbisses,'' or cafes, that offer good, cheap food.
</P>
<P>
   Aout two million Turks live in Germany _ the largest ethnic
group other than native Germans. But interaction between Turks and
native Germans is limited almost exclusively to the transactions
conducted in imbisses or other businesses run by Turks.
</P>
<P>
   Schroeder has vowed to make changing the citizenship laws one of
his top priorities. He hopes it will improve the integration of
immigrants with the 75 million Germans born here. Critics of the
citizenship law charge that it smacks of the same Aryan superiority
complex that wrought so much suffering in the first half of the
century and has contributed to much of Germany's internal problems
in more recent years. They add that it also has provided a legal
underpinning to racism and xenophobia.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, there was a rash of attacks against Turkish
families. At the height of the violence, Kohl was criticized for
not attending the funerals of a Turkish family, including three
children, who were killed when neo-Nazis firebombed their home.
</P>
<P>
   Kohl refused to liberalize the citizenship laws, in part because
his coalition was under pressure from far-right parties whose calls
for the expulsion of foreigners resonate across a broad swath of
the population.
</P>
<P>
   Critics charged that Kohl's Christian Democratic Union party
refused to change the laws because they are prejudiced. But Kohl
had political reasons too. Citing recent polls showing that up to
70 percent of foreigners supported Schroeder over Kohl, Kohl's
party charged that Schroeder's haste to change the law amounts to a
power grab.
</P>
<P>
   Some studies have suggested as many as 4 million new voters
could be created by changing the citizenship laws - and as many as
85 percent of them have indicated they would vote for Schroeder's
party or the environmentalist Green Party, which will be junior
partner in a coalition government led by Schroeder's Social
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition partners differ on who should benefit from the
change. The Social Democrats favor citizenship for third-generation
immigrants - those with at least one parent born in Germany. The
Greens argue that second-generation immigrants should get it. Both
parties agree that any child born in Germany should be a citizen.
</P>
<P>
   Cem Ozdemir, 33, a Green Party member, is one of only two ethnic
Turks in the 670-seat Bundestag, Germany's parliament. Born here of
Turkish parents, Ozdemir had to renounce his Turkish nationality to
become a citizen. He says the denial of dual citizenship denies the
foreign-born opportunities for training and jobs that would improve
integration and cross-cultural understanding.
</P>
<P>
   Foreigners are excluded from teaching, the civil service and
many professions. Some of the prohibitions are protectionist, while
others are simply unfathomable. Until last April, for example,
chimney sweeps had to be German.
</P>
<P>
   But even if Schroeder changes the law, he cannot legislate the
way people feel. While the stereotypical German racist is a
neo-Nazi skinhead, many ordinary Germans also resent what they
consider the exploitation of the welfare system by immigrants or
the expropriation of jobs from Germans by working for less money.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to persuade middle-class Germans to articulate
their feelings about foreigners because they don't want to be seen
as racist. Standing outside Gucer's imbiss, Jens and Karin Scholler
had no such reservations. They candidly identified themselves as
supporters of extremist parties that spout blatantly racist slogans
against foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   Jens Scholler, 27, wore a tee shirt that said, ``Into the German
Millenium, the German Fatherland.'' Their 7-month-old son Odin,
named after a German god, sat gurgling in his stroller, dressed in
a baby's version of a U-boat crew member.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are German construction workers unemployed and there are
foreigners working at all the construction sites for 3 marks an
hour, a fraction of what the Germans should be paid,'' said Jens
Scholler, who drives a streetsweeper for the municipal government.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, 30, said foreigners routinely work for reduced wages,
taking jobs from Germans. She complained that she had recently lost
her job in a day care center. When pressed, she acknowledged her
layoff had nothing to do with foreigners.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with foreigners who come here and work, but
there are many who don't,'' she said. ``I grew up in East Germany,
and there were always foreigners who came in, learned skills, then
went back to their own countries. That's how it should be here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schollers maintain that most foreigners don't want
citizenship, but prefer to undercut German wages or milk the
welfare system.
</P>
<P>
   Conservatives here have refused to countenance altering the laws
on the grounds that such a change would flood the country with more
immigrants and trigger the collapse of a social welfare system
already strained. But more liberal Germans believe that it is time
to become more like the rest of Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Connie Saupe, 21, a student from East Berlin, said she favors
easing the requirements for foreigners to become citizens providing
they make an effort to learn German. Saupe, who lived in Texas for
a year, said she was struck by the cultural melange in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Germany, there is no mixing. The Turks stick to their own
people and culture. Germans just eat their food,'' she said. ``I
think if you change the law, there would be more of an incentive
for foreigners to mix with Germans, and for Germans to accept
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
