 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 Keeping Your E-Mail Address From Spammers  
 By David Einstein   
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; Q:  &LR; I've been getting more and more junk e-mail lately. Can you
tell me where these spammers are getting my address, and is there
anything I can do to protect my privacy?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; There are several ways a Web site can get your e-mail
address. It can ask you for it as part of an information form
required to receive an online service. Or it can plant a ``cookie''
in your system that transmits your address every time you visit a
certain Web page. Unless a Web site states up front that it won't
sell your address, nothing prevents it from doing so.
</P>
<P>
   A good way to prevent dissemination of personal information is
to use an anonymous Web-surfing service such as Anonymizer
(www.anonymizer.com) or Lucent Personal Web Assistant
(www.lpwa.com). They act as middlemen between your browser and the
Web, replacing your e-mail address and IP address with anonymous
ones. Lucent's service is free, but Anonymizer, which has some
extra security features, costs $15 for three months. (You can try
it for free, however.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Q: &LR;  I've been thinking about getting a digital camera, mostly
because it would let me send photos of my kids to my parents, who
live on the East Coast. But the wide choice of cameras is a little
daunting. They run from $200 to more than $1,000, and the
technology is bewildering. Is there a way to get advice on buying
one?
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A:  &LR; A good source of information on digital cameras and
computer products is www.computershopper.com/, a Web site run by
Ziff-Davis. There's a how-to-buy guide, plus info on different
brands of cameras.
</P>
<P>
   If you want my advice (or even if you don't), the first things
to look for in a digital camera are the level of picture resolution
and the quality of the lens. Entry-level cameras have a resolution
of 640-by-480, which isn't really enough for sharp pictures on a
computer screen and is much less than you need if you plan to print
your photos. Insist on at least 1024-by-768, which is now widely
available on cameras costing more than $500.
</P>
<P>
   The lens is equally important. Less-expensive cameras often use
plastic lenses, and even the glass lenses on some high-end models
are tiny compared with the lens on a P4''ZAN)Q%w &QC; i}w;&AMP;W &UR; s. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-05-98 2259EDT &QL;
</P>
