<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ORE-SUICIDE-OPTIONS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DATA SHOW CARE IMPROVED FOR AGED, DYING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALEM, Ore. _ Authorities have reported 10 incidents of legally
sanctioned doctor-assisted suicide to date, far fewer than some
critics had predicted when the statute took effect.
</P>
<P>
   One principal reason appears to be a pronounced but
little-heralded consequence of the law: It has focused such sharp
attention on the needs of the dying that doctors, hospice workers,
and legislators _ including those who oppose assisted suicide _
have accelerated health-care improvements.
</P>
<P>
   As a consequence, according to a range of health professionals,
a growing number of critically ill patients are comfortable enough
that they don't need to end their lives. ``By any measure, our
state has really made substantial changes for the better on pain
and suffering issues relating to the end of life,'' said Dr.
Patrick Dunn, who headed the task force that drew up guidelines for
carrying out assisted suicides.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Susan Tolle, director of the Center for Ethics in Health
Care at Oregon Health Sciences University, said extensive
conversations with doctors and other empirical evidence also
indicate fewer physicians are helping people die in Oregon today
than before the law took effect.
</P>
<P>
   She said that there are now legal criteria they can follow,
whereas before they had to help dying patients surrepticiously and
without guidance. Tolle, who stressed that she has taken no
position on assisted suicide, added that medical authorities who
used to look the other way now have a specific statute to follow
and enforce.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to buttressing medical assistance for the aged and
the terminally ill in Oregon, there are several other barometers
that appear to bolster the assertion that the assisted-suicide law
has stimulated improvements in the treatment of patients during
their final days. Among them are:
</P>
<P>
   -- The number of Oregonians choosing to die in hospitals has
fallen each year since the statute was enacted, apparently because
home care has improved. Thirty-one percent died in hospitals in
1997, the lowest rate in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   -- The number dying in hospice care also has risen annually,
climbing to 30 percent last year. The only states that rival this
rate are Florida, Texas, New Mexico, and Arizona _ all of which
have disproportionate numbers of retirees, which Oregon does not;
the elderly utilize hospices more than any other demographic group.
</P>
<P>
   -- Since 1994, Oregon has moved from 11th to first among states
in prescription rates for morphine. Moreover, doctors across the
country say they have increased their use of the powerful narcotic,
partly because of Oregon's experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Physician-assisted suicide is not a simple issue, but ... a
symptom of a much bigger national problem of adequate care at the
end of life,'' said Ann Jackson, executive director of the Oregon
Hospice Association. ``When patients discover that their last days
aren't necessarily going to have to be painful, they're empowered
to make different decisions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
