<SLUG> BC-GOVERNMENT-ISSUES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT'S EFFECTIVENESS QUESTIONED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For months, questions have swirled around
Washington over whether the White House could effectively address
crises of policy while trying to overcome President Clinton's
crisis of character. Officials in the Congress and the
administration said the answer may begin to become apparent this
week.
</P>
<P>
   As the House casts a likely vote tomorrow in favor of an
impeachment inquiry, Clinton faces a litany of grave international
and domestic issues, from a world economic crisis that has spread
to Wall Street to possible battle in Kosovo to the potential
shutdown of the federal government in a budget standoff with the
Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Some Clinton allies and political enemies said the president
appears to be strapped beyond compare, in a situation made worse by
the imminent departure of his chief of staff, Erskine B. Bowles,
and the role of deputy chief of staff John Podesta, who appears
consumed by efforts to stave off impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no question that the president is crippled by the
impeachment process,'' said Leon Panetta, Clinton's former chief of
staff. ``You just can't ignore it. The very psychology of the
moment doesn't help the president confront all these other crises
out here. You're trying to put out these other fires, but all the
fire engines are focused on the impeachment fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Will Marshall, president of the progressive Democratic
Leadership Council: ``The prospect of being impeached is a
monumental distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the White House, officials said Clinton has devoted his
unswaying attention to the problems of the country and the world,
rather than his own political future. Aides said Clinton penned his
own speech Tuesday on the world economy, during which he warned the
Congress to approve an $18 billion payment to the International
Monetary Fund and urged other nations to take ``urgent steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Those officials also said Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin is
carefully monitoring economic indications, including the potential
collapse of Japan's leading banks. They added that Secretary of
State Madeleine K. Albright, who is currently in the Middle East
helping to prod along the peace process, is serving as an able
point person on foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The strategic decisions are being made that need to be made,''
said Ann Lewis, the White House communications director. ``When you
have secretaries of the stature of Rubin and Albright, the work of
the country is getting done.''
</P>
<P>
   But, countered Panetta, Lewis's former boss: ``The problem is
focus. All these crises individually demand almost the full-time
attention of the president to deal with them. It's reached that
stage. This is something you no longer pitch to staff and cover
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics also contend that Clinton has always created and
overseen policy from the White House rather than the Cabinet
agencies and, indeed, rarely takes time to meet with the various
secretaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has met with his Cabinet twice this year: once to tell them
they shouldn't believe the stories about Monica Lewinsky and the
second time to say he was lying,'' said Clifford May, the
communications director for the Republican National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The number of domestic and foreign problems, friends and foes
alike said, is staggering, ranging from the spreading worldwide
recession to the plunging US stock markets to the budget showdown
with Congress. By last night, it remained unclear whether Clinton
and the Republican leadership would come to agreement on any
appropriations for the federal budget, with a likely deadline
looming by week's end, when the members of the House and Senate
plan to return home to their districts for the year to campaign for
reelection.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Albright is overseeing the most significant
push toward peace between Israelis and Palestinians in the last two
years. Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat are due in Washington for a pivotal working
summit next week.
</P>
<P>
   And in Europe, US envoy Richard Holbrooke appears to have made
little progress in bringing stability to Kosovo, where attacks on
ethnic Albanians have left tens of thousands of people homeless as
winter nears. State Department officials said Tuesday that it
appears increasingly likely that NATO will authorize military
strikes to stem the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under normal circumstances, the commitment of American troops
is a full-time job for a president,'' said Marshall Wittman, the
director of congressional relations at the Heritage Foundation.
``These are extraordinary times.''
</P>
<P>
   As these crises unwind, Clinton is staring into the abyss of the
first full-fledged impeachment inquiry since Richard M. Nixon
resigned his office in 1974. The president, as well as Hillary
Rodham Clinton, are known still to be making telephone calls to key
legislators on his behalf. He has recently hired new staff to help
his cause on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Some Clinton allies dismissed any notion that sound US policy
decisions are imperiled by Clinton's predicament, and said it is
the Republican congressional leadership and the news media who have
become obsessed by the Lewinsky affair.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kosovo is a serious problem that has nothing to do with
American politics,'' said Representative Barney Frank, a
Massachusetts Democrat. ``You have an alliance locked into use of
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the economic situation, our ability is not being held up,''
Frank added. ``The rest of the world does not think less of the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Others said Clinton is now doing what he has so often done in
the past: redoubling his attention to policy issues when confronted
with personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is characteristic of him to bear down on his work when he's
beleaguered,'' said Marshall, of the Democratic Leadership Council.
</P>
<P>
   Others assessed blame on the Congress, which has devoted much of
its attention to the Lewinsky affair. Still other analysts said
there is a void of leadership in Washington _ filled by political
gamesmanship.
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem to have lost control of the events,'' said Joe Silbey,
a presidential scholar at Cornell University. ``This week, and
these days, are tough, really tough. It calls for all kinds of
statesmanship, and no one wants to work together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
