<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN '98 ORBITS INTO CYBERSPACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ANDREW J. GLASS   
 c.1998 Cox News Service   
 &HT;    WASHINGTON _ As the November elections near, candidates are
planting their virtual battle flags in record numbers across
cyberspace.
 &HT;    While 1998 is the first election year in which the Internet is
widely regarded as a mass medium, it's still uncertain what impact
these powerful new digital tools will have on individual campaigns,
or more broadly, on the country's future political course.
 &HT;    ``This is really a test year for the Internet and politics and
we expect to learn a lot from this effort,'' Steve Case, chairman
and chief executive officer of America Online (AOL), said Tuesday
as he helped launch a major initiative to mesh the established
political world with the fluid World Wide Web.
 &HT;    Hosted by AOL, the new Web, White and Blue site
(http://www.webwhiteblue.org) offers one-stop political shopping to
some 45 major non-partisan political databases. The selected sites,
replete with their own clickable links, dispense voter information,
campaign schedules, issue papers and state-by-state political news.
 &HT;    Zoe Baird, president of the Markle Foundation, a co-sponsor of
the cyberproject, said 450 commercial Internet sites had so far
agreed to carry a Web, White and Blue icon on their own home pages.
 &HT;    As Case put it in a conference call with reporters: ``We're
giving people the tools and resources to do their own research _ to
learn about the candidates and issues and to connect with the
political process on their own terms and timetable.''
 &HT;    The candidates also seem to be getting the message.
 &HT;    A survey of candidates, key staff members and consultants in 270
current campaigns published last month in Campaigns &AMP; Elections
magazine last month found that nearly nine out of 10 respondents
saw the Internet as a vital medium that is changing, or soon will
change, political campaigns. Less than 12 percent voiced a
skeptical viewpoint.
 &HT;    The new explosive political demographics of the Internet became
evident last month when, within 24 hours, about 20 million
Americans accessed the impeachment report on President Clinton that
was referred to Congress by Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr.
NetRatings, a cyberspace traffic measuring firm, found that each
online visitor spent an average of 30 minutes reviewing the report.
 &HT;    ``Just as television has all but eliminated observational
reporting, the Internet threatens interpretive and beat
reporting,'' said Michael Cornfield, who teaches courses on
politics and the new media here at George Washington University's
Graduate School of Political Management.
 &HT;    Cornfield, who also co-publishes an online political review,
noted that the advent of such massive document dumps puts extensive
source material for the first time directly in the public's hands.
 &HT;    As a result, he added, ``journalists are being forced to
accommodate to the Internet by devoting more of their efforts to
guiding their audiences into, and through, publicly relevant
documentation.
 &HT;    ``The public becomes an intimate part of the story itself, and
the dynamic and the role of the media changes from being mere
'reporters of fact' to 'guides to context'.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The sheer growth of cyberspace is another factor impacting the
political process.
 &HT;    In California, where the Internet has grown extensive roots, a
recent Field Poll shows that 41 percent of likely voters now use
e-mail and that 67 percent use a computer regularly at home, work
or school. Such high numbers offer largely unplowed soil for
political operatives.
 &HT;    A nationwide telephone survey conducted last February found that
the proportion of people who used the Internet for political
activity had doubled since a similar survey conducted before the
1996 elections.
 &HT;    But the growth path has a ways to go. According to Bruce Bimber,
a political science professor at the University of California,
Santa Barbara, who conducted the February poll, only 17 percent of
respondents used the Internet to express political views, to learn
about political issues, to browse for political information or to
get in contact with elected officials or candidates.
 &HT;    That is the kind of activity encouraged by Project Vote Smart, a
nonpartisan nonprofit group founded 40 years ago by former senators
and presidential candidates Barry Goldwater of Arizona and George
McGovern of South Dakota.
 &HT;    ``We're averaging more than a half million hits a day,'' said
Richard Kimball, the group's president. ``I fought against going on
the Internet three years ago,'' he added, ``but it's become huge
for us.''
 &HT;    No so huge, however, that the Internet stands a chance of
displacing television as the prime contact point for voters in the
near future.
 &HT;    Political consultants note that, unlike television, the Internet
is still not universally available and that online information
reaches only self-selected interested voters.
 &HT;    ``On TV, you decide you want to watch 'Seinfeld,' and you get
our ad,'' says Mark Mellman, a Washington political consultant
whose clients have included Democratic Sens. Tom Daschle of South
Dakota and Barbara Boxer of California. ``But when you go to the
Web, you have to want to go to a political site.''
 &HT;    Still, AOL's Case remains undeterred from his middleman function
of creating another viable ``portal for democracy.''
 &HT;    ``This is politics Internet-style: interactive, contextual,
informative, and, above all, optimistic,'' he concluded in touting
the new Web White &AMP; Blue site. ``While we cannot predict how the
Internet will change politics, we can say with certainty that it
will.''
 &HT;    
 &HT;    WEB ADDRESSES FOR POLITICAL INFORMATION
 &HT;    With INTERNET-POLITICS. Moving in (w) Washington and (f)
financial categories.
 &HT;    Eds: Please note that in some addresses below, symbols are
replaced by (tilde) or (underscore) for transmission purposes.
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Launched Tuesday as online public service campaign
to raise voter awareness, Web White &AMP; Blue
(http://www.webwhiteblue.org) also serves as a one-stop portal to
other political sites.
</P>
<P>
   Here are some other useful political Internet gateways:
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   1998 Election Connection: A full listing of campaign web sites
from the Graduate School of Political Management at The George
Washington University. (http://www.gspm.org/election/)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Alliance for Better Campaigns: Furnishes information on
candidate and media standards in political campaigns.
(http://www.bettercampaigns.org)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Campaign Web Review: Biweekly newsletter that examines the use
of the Internet by political campaigns in the 1998 elections.
(http://www.campaignwebreview.net/)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   The Democracy Network: A community-based, interactive political
Web site that also provides an open forum for candidate debates.
(http://www.democracynet.org)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   ELECnet: An extensive index of links to state and local election
offices with specific details on polling hours and locations.
(http://www.iupui.edu/(tilde)epackard/eleclink.html)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   League of Women Voters: Offers links to local voter guides and
information gathered by state and local chapters throughout the
nation. (http://lwv.org/electioncentral/main.htm)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Mining Co. Issues: Non-partisan directory site that provides
access to other Web sites dealing with political causes and issues
as well as related news events. (http://home.miningco.com/issues/)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   NetVote '98: Online service site for persons seeking to register
to vote in every state except Mississippi, New Hampshire, North
Dakota, and Wyoming. (http://www.netvote98.mci.com/)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Pew Research Center for the People and the Press: Non-profit
site provides political public opinion polling on current and
topical issues. (http://www.people-press.org/index.htm)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Politics1: Provides links to statewide, local legislative, and
congressional candidates for all 50 states.
(http://www.politics1.com/states.htm)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Project Vote Smart: Offers in-depth candidate data, campaign
finance history, issue positions, performance evaluations and
voting records. (http://www.vote-smart.org/ce/)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo!'s 1998 Elections: A thorough index of election Web sites
at all political levels. 
(http://www.yahoo.com/Government/Politics/Elections/1998(underscore)
 U(underscore)S(underscore)(underscore)Elections/)
</P>
