<HEADER>
A3940 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CPT-IDOT-COMPUTERS-HN     10-07 1742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-IDOT-COMPUTERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
START-UP PC MAKER iDot BUILDS ON THE MADE-TO-ORDER MODEL 
By DWIGHT SILVERMAN  
c. 1998 Houston Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ Start-up personal computer maker iDot.com may be small.
</P>
<P>
   It may even be impossible to find a store that sells its
products.
</P>
<P>
   But in some ways it shares many similarities with the more
established PC companies.
</P>
<P>
   Like Compaq Computer Corp., iDot was conceived by technology
industry veterans who met in a restaurant, sketching out ideas on a
napkin. Like Dell Computer Corp., iDot sells its wares directly to
customers, rather than going through a reseller. And like Gateway,
iDot goes after home and small-business customers.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Compaq, you can't buy iDot's computers in stores.
Unlike Dell and Gateway, iDot employs no workers in call centers to
take phone orders.
</P>
<P>
   If you want an iDot system, there's only one place to get one:
the World Wide Web.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which started doing business on April 21, bills
itself as ``the first PC company built for the Web.'' By selling
only over the Internet, iDot hopes to wring maximum efficiency out
of the process of building and marketing personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to think of it as a beneficial conspiracy theory,''
says Jeremy Mark Marlow, one of the co-founders of iDot and its
senior vice president of marketing. ``If our customers will support
this very efficient business model, then we can give them excellent
prices.''
</P>
<P>
   In this way, iDot is more like Amazon.com, the Web-only
bookseller, and CDNow, which pioneered the sale of music compact
discs online. Crucial to its business is the company's technology,
a sophisticated piece of software that lets its customers configure
and then purchase a PC.
</P>
<P>
   An order placed on iDot's Web site and paid for with a credit
card can be instantly approved electronically. Within minutes, the
invoice for a new PC rolls out of a small Lexmark printer in iDot's
parts room _ the first time a human touches the order in the
process.
</P>
<P>
   The Web site and electronic commerce software was written by
programmers hired by iDot after the company couldn't find software
that did all this automatically. The software runs on a half-dozen
PCs built by iDot and linked by a fast connection to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have the potential to be the next Dell. Or, they could be
gone from our experience in the next month,'' said Rob Enderle,
director of desktop and mobile technology at Giga Information
Group, a market research company in Norwell, Mass. ``But, they are
redefining what a low-cost PC manufacturer can be.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, iDot owes a lot to its larger Austin neighbor. Dell's
phenomenal success selling computers on the Web _ it has online
sales of $6 million a day _ has proven that people will buy PCs
over the Net. Founder Michael Dell has said he thinks his company
may have as much as 50 percent of its sales online by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, Dell still relies heavily on sales personnel who
both take calls and solicit business over the phone. iDot's
founders hope to build a business without that expense.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Dell was started, phone sales were the next big thing,''
Enderle said. ``Michael Dell stepped in and created the direct
business model around these call centers. But the new model is the
Web, and it has an intrinsically lower cost over call centers, just
as call centers do over a sales force in the field.''
</P>
<P>
   The company also takes advantage of its Texas location. The same
parts and service suppliers that work for Dell and Compaq also have
deals with iDot. As a result, iDot can use the same just-in-time
inventory techniques _ in which parts are shipped by suppliers as
they are needed from nearby warehouses to the assembly floor _ as
the big guys.
</P>
<P>
   The company was started by a group of computer industry veterans
like Marlow, who had been working for Austin-based Power Computing,
one of the most successful makers of Macintosh clones. When Apple
Computer took action to shut down the clone makers, Marlow was
brought in because of his experience as an executive at AST
Research, which makes Windows-based systems. Power wanted to
convert to selling similar systems.
</P>
<P>
   But Power's attempts to remake itself fell apart, and Marlow
found himself unemployed. He talked to several Austin-area
companies, including Dell. He eventually hooked up with Neil
Bremner, a former executive of the direct PC seller CompuAdd, and
C.P. Lee, a Taiwanese entrepreneur. Lee also owns a company that
sells peripherals and monitors under the familiar name Digital
Research Technologies. (At the dawn of the personal computer
revolution, a company called Digital Research offered the early
CP/Moperating system for personal computers, as well as an MS-DOS
clone called DR-DOS.)
</P>
<P>
   One evening last November, the men were having dinner at an
Applebee's restaurant in the shadow of Dell's headquarters and
sketched out the plans for a Web-based company on a dinner napkin.
</P>
<P>
   Lee used his contacts to secure $3.5 million in seed money from
Mag Technologies, makers of the Mag Innovision line of computer
monitors, and iDot formally opened its doors in offices in north
Austin in January.
</P>
<P>
   The company has targeted three specific markets _ students,
gamers and small businesses. All three are considered to be
computer-savvy, which cuts down somewhat on technical support
calls, Marlow said. To hammer home just who iDot's customers are,
the company uses the slogan ``PCs for Smarties.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's as opposed to, `for Dummies,' '' said Marlow, referring
to the popular line of books aimed at computer novices.
</P>
<P>
   The gamer segment is its best so far, and the most profitable.
Marlow said 40 percent of gamer systems are state-of-the-art, going
out the door with 450-megahertz Pentium II processors, lots of
memory and big hard drives.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the company aims most of its marketing at this
group. iDot recently completed a tour of Texas college campuses _
including Rice University and the University of Houston _ where it
set up multiplayer game tournaments. Students could compete by
playing the popular Quake II game, and the winners from each
university will meet for a match of champions at iDot's offices
later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Fredrick Marckini, iDot's very first customer, is typical of the
kind of people the company is trying to reach. The Weston, Mass.,
Internet consultant bought a $2,300, 400-megahertz system on April
23, just two days after the site first went up.
</P>
<P>
   Marckini said he ``lives on the Web,'' and was impressed enough
by iDot's site to buy a computer from an unfamiliar company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their Web site said they were clearly a well-funded company.
It was nothing even a sophisticated developer could put together on
his own. They weren't going away tomorrow,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the first iDot computer sold arrived with a flaw.
Marckini said there was a ``hard-disk issue'' and he had to send
the machine back. It was returned fixed, he said, and he's been
pleased with it. He's since bought two monitors from iDot.
</P>
<P>
   Because it's going after technology-savvy buyers, it also
attracts affluent ones. About 78 percent of people pay by credit
card, the rest by purchase order or check. The high number of
credit-card sales means iDot has a steady flow of cash. Company
executives won't say how many PCs they've sold, only that they are
doing better than expected.
</P>
<P>
   The company has borrowed another page from Amazon.com, setting
up virtual storefronts on other companies' Web sites. Amazon.com
will pay a commission to a business if it generates sales of books
via a link back to Amazon. An oil company, for example, could tout
Amazon.com books on geology or the petrochemical industry in
exchange for a cut of the sales.
</P>
<P>
   In an early marketing coup, iDot set up one of these storefronts
on the home page for Dilbert, the popular United Media cartoon
character (www.dilbert.com). iDot is now the ``official computer''
for the Dilbert Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's perfect for us,'' said Marlow. ``Engineers love Dilbert,
and they're part of our market. Also, Dilbert represents the
underdog. We're an underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's executives relish and encourage this image as an
underdog. They know they are in the shadow of computer-industry
giants like Dell on the Web. Thus, they have another slogan:
``Don't buy PCs made by billionaires,'' referring to Michael Dell's
net worth.
</P>
<P>
   Even their offices smack of an irreverent attitude. Visitors who
wait in a spartan lobby must sit on day-glo beanbag chairs _ and
there are only two. The decor is decidedly early '60s kitsch.
</P>
<P>
   That look is also part of iDot's emphasis on efficiency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We look for ways to cut costs everywhere,'' said co-founder
Bremner. ``We even look for deals on office supplies. When someone
goes for pencils, they don't just buy the first thing on the
shelf.''
</P>
<P>
   That efficiency pays off in aggressive pricing. An iDot system
with a 450-megahertz Pentium II chip, a 16.8-gigabyte hard drive,
128 megabytes of memory, a 56K fax modem, an 8-MB video card and a
DVD-ROM drive costs about $2,099. A similarly equipped Gateway
system, priced at that PC maker's Web site, sells for $2,326. A
comparable Dell system is $2,252. Monitors for each of these
systems are extra.
</P>
<P>
   So far, there are 50 employees at iDot, which had only four
employees when it began. Its executives plan to keep things tight _
Bremner expects there will be only about 100 employees a year from
now.
</P>
<P>
   He said the next step in the company's growth is to raise more
private capital, $10 million to $15 million, ``to get us through
the next two years, and at that point we'll be cash-flow
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   The company's executives realize that iDot's current niche won't
be enough to sustain it. Eventually it will have to begin offering
notebook computers and servers, and begin selling products to the
more lucrative corporate market.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, iDot begins seriously competing with Dell,
Compaq, IBM and other major players.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, there are some very large, behemoth vendors like
Dell and Gateway out there, and iDot operates under their radars at
this point,'' said Bruce Stephen, head of personal systems research
at International Data Corp. in Framingham, Mass. ``They are in the
fun part now, the start-up phase.'' &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-10-06-98 1415EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
