<HEADLINE>
MIT HELPS OKLAHOMA-PROOF A MEMORIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Designers of a memorial to the 168 victims of the April 1995
Oklahoma City terror bombing are turning to Massachusetts Institute
of Technology ceramics specialists for help meshing their plans
with Oklahoma's volatile weather.
</P>
<P>
   When it opens about 18 months from now, the centerpiece of a
memorial to the victims of the truck bomb attack on the Alfred P.
Murrah Federal Building will be an array of 168 glass and bronze
chairs on a grassy plain where the building stood. They will
overlook a reflecting pool, playground, and a lone ``survivor
tree'' that miraculously endured the blast.
</P>
<P>
   However, the aesthetic vision of memorial designers Torrey and
Hans Butzer, who work out of Cambridge, has run up against a vexing
physical fact: Oklahoma is prone to 115-degree summer days with
sudden, chilly thunderstorms that, MIT tests showed, could crack
the chairs.
</P>
<P>
   With help from Yet-Ming Chiang, an MIT professor of materials
science and engineering, the Butzers and colleague Sven Berg have
been testing samples of various types of glass to see whether they
could withstand the sudden temperature drops _ called ``thermal
shock'' _ likely to occur in Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was delighted to be able to work on this,'' Chiang said last
week. ``It's quite different from much of the other work we do
around here, and I think it's a stunning design. I can see why it
would appeal so much to all the victims' families.''
</P>
<P>
   The chairs will feature brass seats mounted on lit glass blocks,
conveying a sense of floating, with the name of a victim etched on
each one and smaller chairs representing the 19 toddlers and
children killed there. A groundbreaking on the $24.1 million
project is set for Oct. 25.
</P>
<P>
   Last April, the Butzers called MIT seeking suggestions for a
specialist to help advise them on choosing materials for the
memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Laboratory tests conducted this spring by Chiang and one of his
graduate students, Benjamin Hellweg, found that the artists' first
choice for glass would be subject to cracking under a 59-degree
temperature change _ not implausible on a summer Oklahoma day when
the chairs might reach 120 degrees and get sprayed by 60-degree
rain.
</P>
<P>
   Since late July, two sample chairs have been sitting on top of
MIT's Building 13, already showing the development of some cracks
from exposure to heat and rain.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the artists have gone back to two industrial glass
companies, Corning and Lancaster, to find a different glass that
could withstand dramatic temperature changes but could still be
worked in their casting furnaces. Later this autumn, samples are to
be sent to MIT for more tests.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Chiang has advised the artists to cast several extra
replacement chairs, given the statistical near-certainty that no
matter how well crafted, some of the chairs are likely to develop
cracks from exposure to weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``The work that MIT has been doing has been real, real
critical,'' said Kari Ferguson, communications director for the
Oklahoma City National Memorial Trust. ``It will help us perfect
the glass so that we don't have problems later on.''
</P>
<P>
   Each glass chair base _ a cube made of 2-inch-thick panels _
will be cast separately with its own unique swirl of bubbles and
ripples, Ferguson said, symbolizing ``the individuality of every
life'' that was lost.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
