<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONOUGH-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIKINGS THE TEAM TO BEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It is not a stretch to say this morning that the Minnesota
Vikings could be the best team in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   The Denver Broncos might disagree, but not even they, with their
offensive brilliance, have gone undefeated through the exhibition
games and regular season, and done the near-impossible by spanking
the Packers in Green Bay on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you consider all of the parameters,'' says Vikings
offensive coordinator Brian Billick, ``in Green Bay ... Lambeau
Field ... the Packer crowd ... Monday night football ... undefeated
... No. 1-ranked defense in the league ... you have to say this was
a great victory. A very important win for our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Fritz Shurmur has been in the NFL for more than two decades.
When he was defensive coordinator for the Los Angeles Rams in the
1980s, he had to go up against the fabulous San Francisco 49ers
offense twice a year. Joe Montana, Jerry Rice, John Taylor, Roger
Craig, and that bunch. When he moved to Arizona to run the
Cardinals defense, he caught the three-time world champion Dallas
Cowboys twice a year, with Troy Aikman, Emmitt Smith, Michael
Irvin, Jay Novacek, et al.
</P>
<P>
   But, as best he could recall, Shurmur never remembered taking a
beating like the one he got from the Vikings in their spectacular
37-24 victory in a driving rain Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do have selective memory,'' said Shurmur, trying
unsuccessfully to chuckle, ``but I never remember getting involved
with something like this. This team is dangerous. As dangerous as I
have ever seen. They can do some things that I haven't ever seen
any other team do. This team has an offense that can make you
spread out on defense more than any team I have seen. They make you
defend the whole field, and that is not easy to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams were undefeated going into the game, but everyone _
except the Vikings _ thought Green Bay was going to win. Though
Minnesota plays them better than any other team in the NFC Central,
the Packers always seem to win out at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have played them so many times,'' says Billick, ``that we
know just how good they can be on defense. Fritz Shurmur, to me, is
the best defensive coordinator in the game. Reggie White this year
has been playing better than he has in years. In this league, there
are certain guys _ our own John Randle, Bruce Smith, and Reggie _
that you have to make sure you have two men available to block
them. They are that good. We took that into account in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``new'' Randall Cunningham and his incomparable corps of
wide receivers _ Cris Carter, Jake Reed, and blossoming superman
Randy Moss _ obliterated the Packer secondary for 442 passing yards
and four touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did all of that,'' says Shurmur, ``and we didn't have a
single blown coverage. They just made all of the plays, and our
guys didn't. We didn't play very well, but the guys we were playing
against had something to do with that.
</P>
<P>
   ``When they put those three wide receivers out, you have to
worry about matchups more than you want to. Whether you use a
nickel or dime, it doesn't make any difference. All of them are
tough matchups.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we used to go against San Francisco, they had two running
backs in there. Dallas was the same. It's a smaller field to defend
when the other team has two running backs on the field. These guys
use one back and three wides. To go with that, they have the best
offensive line in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been building to this for two or three years. We
couldn't get near Cunningham all night. He just sat in the pocket
and made throws. He didn't used to do that. He wanted to run
around, and you can't throw the deep balls with accuracy, like he
did in this game, running around.''
</P>
<P>
   This Cunningham is not the quarterback who couldn't throw
straight with the Eagles, or the one no one wanted when he quit to
go on television three seasons ago. But after being revitalized by
Minnesota coach Dennis Green, who needed another quarterback after
Warren Moon went to Seattle, Cunningham is playing better than
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Coming into this season as the backup for Brad Johnson,
Cunningham's personal quarterback rating for his career stood at
78.4. Anything under 80.0 is not considered good.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, he has a phenomenal 127.8 rating, best in the
league. In the last two games, he has eight touchdown passes, 717
yards, and zero interceptions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the last three games he has not run the ball once,'' says
Billick. ``Before (Monday's) game, I told him _ half-kidding but
half-serious _ to run the ball when he had the opening. He never
ran it once all game. Our offensive line did a tremendous job of
protecting him. I think he got knocked down once all night and that
was on a blitz.''
</P>
<P>
   As good as Cunningham has been, what sets this Viking team apart
are its wide receivers: Carter, Reid, Moss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moss is the guy that makes them different,'' says Patriots
head coach Pete Carroll, who got a taste of how good the Vikings
are when they whacked his team, 28-0, in Foxborough during the
exhibition season. ``We had only played five or six plays in that
game, and I said to myself, `Hey, this kid really is special.' I
don't know for sure exactly what made me think it, but I remember
telling our guys at the half that we better pay special attention
to Moss because I was so impressed. Then he still went out and
caught a bomb for a touchdown on us.''
</P>
<P>
   If you have followed pro football for any length of time and
watched Moss perform vs. Green Bay, you had to come away feeling
that this was the beginning of a likely Hall of Fame career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moss has a knack of just going right over the defender and
catching the ball that is special,'' says Carroll. ``I talked with
Foge Fazio (the Vikings defensive coordinator and a friend of
Carroll's) and he told me Moss does it all the time in practice to
their defensive backs. They have him covered. He makes the catch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been around an athlete like Randy Moss,'' says
Billick. ``He can make plays that seem impossible. Don't forget, he
also had an 80-yarder for a touchdown called back in that game, and
another time he was open for a long touchdown and the wind gave the
ball a push and it was just out of his reach.''
</P>
<P>
   Seldom does a team go after another in the NFL the way the
Vikings invaded Green Bay Monday night. In terrible weather, which
usually leads teams to play conservatively, they went for all of it
all night long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told our offensive guys we were going to go vertical all
night,'' says Billick. ``We wanted to spread them out and hit them
deep. You can't do that unless your offensive line gives you time.
We let our guys know that. We needed more time. We had two guys on
Reggie at times, and used tight ends and backs to chip away. But,
when they blitzed, we had to take him man to man and Korey Stringer
did a good job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Randall was patient. He held the ball and waited to make the
plays. When he put the ball out there, our guys went up and got it.
Our receivers are bigger than their defensive backs. We wanted big
plays. We felt their offense was going to score points, and we
couldn't match them by stringing together long drives of 12-14
plays. Our strategy was to hit them down the field. Eventually,
teams are going to back off, and when they do, our running game is
going to get better than it has been, and it hasn't been bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota's next game is against Washington a week from Sunday.
The Redskins are last in the league on defense, giving up 33.8
points per game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Will McDonough is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
