<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-RACES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCANDAL TAKES A BACK SEAT ON THE CAMPAIGN TRAIL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL KRANISH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALLENTOWN, Pa. _ William Heydt, the Republican mayor of this old
steel town, remains amazed at his city's subdued reaction to
President Clinton's relationship with Monica S. Lewinsky. ``If I as
mayor put my hand on somebody's shoulder, I'd be run out of town on
a rail,'' he said, decrying the lack of outrage.
</P>
<P>
   If any congressional district in America should be affected by
the Clinton-Lewinsky story, it is Lehigh Valley, a socially
conservative area where Democrats narrowly outnumber Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The district's retiring congressman, Representative Paul McHale,
became the first Democrat in Congress to call for Clinton's
resignation. The dominant newspaper, the Morning Call,
wholeheartedly agreed with McHale, publishing an editorial
headlined: ``Disgraced President Must Resign.''
</P>
<P>
   But the candidates to succeed McHale believe that the voters of
Pennsylvania's 15th congressional district _ like many across the
country, according to the polls _ aren't nearly as concerned about
what happened in the back corridors of the White House as they are
about what is happening in their own back yard.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the candidates hoping to succeed McHale are striving to
ignore the scandal. Neither has echoed McHale's call for Clinton's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't think there is going to be an effect at all,''
said Roy C. Afflerbach, the Democratic state senator seeking the
seat. Indeed, when a Democratic congressional candidate from a
neighboring district made headlines by refusing to go to a
Philadelphia fund-raiser with Clinton on Friday night, Afflerbach
promptly accepted an invitation and attended.
</P>
<P>
   Afflerbach's Republican opponent, Patrick Toomey, also has no
interest in making the president's conduct an issue. He said he is
``seldom'' asked about the Clinton scandal, and he would rather
talk about his plan to cut taxes.
</P>
<P>
   All of this is important far beyond the rolling landscape of the
15th district, which analysts consider a ``swing'' area that is one
of the best indicators of the national mood. With the House likely
to vote on articles of impeachment after the November election, the
makeup of the House is vitally important to the president's future.
The election or defeat of a few Democrats such as Afflerbach could
determine whether Clinton is impeached.
</P>
<P>
   To understand what is happening here, residents point to the
words of pop singer Billy Joel, who memorialized this region's long
decline in his hit song, ``Allentown'': Well, we're living here in
Allentown, and they're closing all the factories down. Now, while
some Bethlehem Steel and Mack Truck are bare shells or their former
presence, the region seems to grow industrial parks like topsy. The
district has a low unemployment rate of 4.3 percent. Clinton gets a
healthy share of the credit for this unsung sequel, similar to the
way the economic uplift has benefited the president across the
country. Still, the departure of union members and influx of
entrepeneurs is making the region more Republican.
</P>
<P>
   So when Afflerbach and Toomey go campaigning, they hear more
about the economy than Lewinsky. On Friday, for example, Toomey, an
earnest 36-year-old who owns two sports-themed restaurants called
``Rookies,'' knocked on doors in a townhouse subdivision that
stradled a highway humming with traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The first resident that Toomey met, Deborah Trucksess, an
Independent, seemed happy to meet the Republican candidate and
pledged to vote for him. Asked by a reporter if the Clinton scandal
concerned her, she said: ``Not at all.''
</P>
<P>
   But a little later, Toomey ran into Susan Bilder, an elementary
school teacher who bluntly told Toomey that she couldn't vote for
him. Toomey inquired whether she had studied the individual
candidates in the race. Bilder replied that it made no difference.
As Bilder subsequently explained, she is so angry at Republicans
for the investigation of Clinton that she plans to vote for
Democratic candidates down the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not his fault,'' Bilder said, motioning to Toomey.
Moreover, Bilder added that the Allentown economy has recovered and
``my children are all doing well.'' So Afflerbach has her vote.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the most crucial voter that Toomey met on his regular
door-knocking venture may have been another Democrat down the
street. She explained that she would back the Democrat, but she
didn't plan to vote. Toomey's private polls show that Republicans
will turn out in good numbers while many Democrats _ perhaps
depressed by the Clinton scandal _ will stay home. It is pattern
repeated in polls across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, an ABC-TV News poll released last week contained some
possibly misleading good news for Democrats. It showed that
Democratcs are pulling ahead in the national ``generic'' vote for
congressional candidates. The poll found that registered voters
favored Democratic candidates over Republicans by 49 to 44 percent.
But when pollsters put the same question to likely voters, the
results were reversed, with Republican candidates favored by 49
percent to 46 percent. While these results were close to the poll's
3.5 percent margin of error, they are in line with the predictions
of many analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the poll found that 71 percent of those surveyed
approved of the job being done by their representative in Congress,
a good sign for the Republican-held House.
</P>
<P>
   All of this has led to wildly conflicting predictions about the
outcome of the Nov. 3 election. In interviews last week, several of
the nation's most seasoned political analysts said it was most
difficult and unpredictable midterm election they have ever seen.
Predictions range from a Republican walkover, in which the GOP
would ascend to historic majorities in the House and Senate, to a
anti-Republican backlash, in which the Democratic would regain
power at least in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some of the most respected analysts agreed that Clinton
scandal hasn't hurt Democratic candidates quite as they thought
after Clinton made a poorly received speech to nation on Aug. 17 in
which he failed to apologize for his relationship with the former
White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the landscape had shifted after the Aug. 17
speech,'' said political analysts Stuart Rothenberg. ``But we never
really saw the shift working its way through the country. Now I am
starting to wonder if there really was a shift. I just don't think
there is a big shift.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles Cook, another top observer of congressional races, still
thinks Democrats would be better off if Clinton resigns. But Cook
said that he has looked at every race in the nation and has found
little shift due to the Clinton scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could say if you went from Alabama to Wyoming, you would
come up with virtually no change,'' Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not necessarily good news for Democrats. Rothenberg
and Cook agreed that Republicans are almost certain to maintain
their control of the House and Senate.
</P>
<P>
   In the House, controlled 228-206 by Republicans, several
analysts have scaled back their predictions of a 25-seat pickup by
the GOP, but still expect a 10 to 15 seat gain.
</P>
<P>
   Even Democratic Party officials, aware that the party
controlling the White House sometimes loses 35 seats in an off-year
election, are not predicting that they can win back the House. But
Democratic officials are hoping to win enough seats to make it more
difficult to impeach the president. Republicans would need only a
one-vote margin of victory to approve articles of impeachment in
the Clinton case.
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, controlled 55-45 by the GOP, Republicans could
pick up from three to seven seats. A seven-seat gain, for example,
would give the GOP a 62-seat majority, still five short of the
two-thirds vote needed to convict a president in an impeachment if
all 100 senators cast their ballot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
