<HEADLINE>
WASHINGTON MUTUAL TO CLOSE BRANCHES, CUT JOBS IN CALIFORNIA 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WENDY TANAKA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Washington Mutual Inc., the nation's largest
savings and loan, is planning to close 161 branch offices in
California and lay off between 3,000 and 3,500 workers throughout
the state by next spring.
</P>
<P>
   The move results from the Seattle-based thrift's $6.9 billion
acquisition of H.F. Ahmanson &AMP; Co., the parent of Home Savings of
America. Banking officials said they needed to eliminate duplicate
operations from the merger, which was completed last week.
</P>
<P>
   Tim McGarry, a spokesman for Washington Mutual, said the
heaviest job cuts would likely occur in the Los Angeles area
because the largest number of office closings, 40, are slated for
that region. The thrift plans to close 22 offices in San Diego, 21
in Orange County and seven offices in Alameda County.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we've identified which branches are consolidating,
branch and regional managers will have to sit down and determine
branch needs,'' McGarry said after the plans were announced
Tuesday. ``Until the consolidations go through, we'll have normal
attrition, which is relevant to the number of people we'll have to
lay off.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once the process is completed in next year's second quarter,
we will have a highly efficient and effective network in
California, with 541 branch locations and more than 1,400 ATMs,''
Deanna Oppenheimer, a Washington Mutual spokeswoman, said in a
prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Mutual said the consolidations would happen where
branch offices of the two banks are within a few miles of each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it is in consumers' interest,'' said Linda
Sherry, spokeswoman for Consumer Action, a San Francisco-based
watchdog group. ``It means fewer and fewer branches in
neighborhoods. People will have to go out of their way to find an
ATM machine'' where they won't have to pay a fee for withdrawing
cash.
</P>
<P>
   But Sherry noted that Washington Mutual has attempted to
position itself as a consumer-friendly bank with its humorous TV
ads that started airing in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington Mutual is trying to be a buddy bank,'' said Sherry,
referring to the bank's whimsical ads that portray bank tellers as
sought-after celebrities. ``It doesn't help to close more and more
branches in neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the bank took a whimsical advertising approach to
start building name recognition in a geographic territory dominated
by BankAmerica Corp. and Wells Fargo Bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1352EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0129 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 13:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4015 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-GOV-TAXES-BOS &LR;      10-07 1284
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-GOV-TAXES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO VOTERS, TAX ISSUE MAY NOT BE THE KEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Forget death and taxes. In modern politics, it's
considered a near certainty that taxes mean death to political
candidates. &UR;  &LR; Raising taxes, that is.
</P>
<P>
   But that may be a simplistic view, despite attempts by
candidates in Massachusetts to make the fear of increased taxes an
election-year issue.
</P>
<P>
   Acting Governor Paul Cellucci used Democratic rival Scott
Harshbarger's refusal to sign a no-new-taxes pledge as a bludgeon
to batter his foe in Monday's gubernatorial debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you remember the last time we had a governor who wouldn't
take the no-new-taxes pledge?'' Cellucci asked. ``It was a
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   That was a reference to 1989 and 1990, when former governor
Michael S. Dukakis won tax increases to stanch budgets hemorrhaging
in the recession.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday, Harshbarger, who noted that his first campaign proposal
had been a call for a large tax cut, called Cellucci's pledge ploy
``stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Harshbarger said Cellucci's own legislative record, which
includes several votes for a higher gas tax and a Boston parking
tax, as well as votes to continue cigarette and alcohol levies,
belies his tough anti-tax rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never voted for a tax increase, unlike Paul Cellucci, who
voted for hundreds of millions of dollars in tax increases while he
was in the Legislature, then changed his position when he ran for
statewide office,'' said Harshbarger. ``So the pledges he asked you
to support are not worth the paper they are written on.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rob Gray, Cellucci's campaign manager, said Cellucci had
proved his anti-tax bona fides over the last eight years, and
insisted the no-new-tax pledge is a legitimate issue, even in an
era of dueling tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a way of telling the difference between the two
candidates,'' Gray insisted. ``It makes clear to people that Paul
Cellucci is tough on taxes and Scott Harshbarger would be a
governor who would not be tough on taxes.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Harshbarger considers such a pledge an abdication of
leadership, others argue that drawing a public line in the sand
actually strengthens a governor's hand in negotiating with the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``It became the cornerstone of much of the fiscal and economic
success in Massachusetts over the last eight years because
everybody knew that raising taxes was off the table,'' said
Republican consultant Charles Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Reinforced by that pledge, former governor Bill Weld forced the
Legislature to cut spending to balance the budget.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as Harshbarger argues, other programs _ even programs
that Cellucci cites on the campaign trail _ would have been
impossible without some of the narrow tax hikes approved by voters
or the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are proud of having health care for kids, how do you
justify vetoing the (1996) tobacco tax,'' which funds some of that
care? Harshbarger asked. ``How in good conscience can you talk to
the business community and tell them to watch out for this risky
guy when you vetoed the convention center (legislation) simply
because it raises fees on tourists?''
</P>
<P>
   Although tax-and-spending charges occupied much of Cellucci's
time during Monday's debate, the most recent Boston Globe poll,
taken in August, suggests that the tax issue _ let alone anti-tax
pledges _ isn't as potent with Massachusetts voters as Cellucci
apparently believes.
</P>
<P>
   The Globe survey found that while taxes is the issue most often
cited by likely Republican primary voters, it ranked only third
with likely Democratic voters. And in neither group did the issue
command anything approaching a majority: 24 percent of GOP voters _
which represents less than 5 percent of the total registered voters
in the state _ said taxes mattered most, compared to 13 percent of
Democrats who thought so.
</P>
<P>
   Even during the voter rage in recessionary 1990, the year in
which Weld established a no-new-taxes pledge as the cornerstone of
GOP election strategy, taxes hardly rocketed off the charts as an
issue, despite two straight years of tax increases.
</P>
<P>
   In August of 1990, a Globe poll found that 19 percent of all
voters cited taxes as their most important issue, followed by 18
percent who said education, and 16 percent who cited the economy.
</P>
<P>
   History also tells a much more complex story on both taxes and
anti-tax promises. In 1964, John Volpe, the Republican candidate
for governor, ran as an open advocate of a 3 percent sales tax,
which, he said, would allow the state to lessen the burden of
property taxes. Once elected, Volpe led a long battle for the sales
tax. Each time one version was voted down, Volpe proposed another.
Finally, in March of 1966, after months of vehement opposition,
lawmakers passed the tax. Volpe was handily re-elected that same
year.
</P>
<P>
   Running for governor in 1974 in the face of a growing budget
deficit, Michael Dukakis offered the so-called ``lead-pipe
guarantee'' that he would not raise taxes. But by November, Dukakis
had signed a $362 million tax package, including a 7.5 percent
surtax on the income tax.
</P>
<P>
   Dukakis lost the 1978 Democratic primary to conservative Edward
J. King, who hammered him on taxes, crime, and the death penalty.
But that loss has long been attributed as much to Dukakis's
wholesale alienation of the left, which was angry over
social-program cuts, as to the tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   ``He lost in the primary because the liberals stayed home,''
said David Bartley, then the Democratic speaker of the
Massachusetts House.
</P>
<P>
   On the national level, the most famous no-new-taxes pledge was
the ``read my lips'' promise George Bush offered in 1988 _ and
broke two years later.
</P>
<P>
   Reneging on his pledge hurt Bush's credibility, and gave
conservative challenger Patrick Buchanan an issue to embarrass Bush
with in the 1992 GOP primary. Still, Bush was again talking tax
cuts by the 1992 general election, while Bill Clinton, the man who
beat him, had staked out a dual position, proposing both a
middle-class tax cut and a plan to hike taxes on the wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Republican predictions of disaster, Clinton won passage
of much of his tax-increase plan, then cruised to a relatively easy
re-election in 1996 over Kansas Senator Bob Dole, who was promising
large tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   But in New Hampshire, when Democrat Jeanne Shaheen took an
anti-tax pledge in 1996, she clearly neutralized an issue that had
plagued her party's previous gubernatorial nominees for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``By taking the pledge, Jeanne Shaheen was able to take the
topic off the table and become the first woman governor of New
Hampshire and the first Democratic governor in ages,'' said
Democratic consultant Mary Anne Marsh.
</P>
<P>
   Just how the issue plays out in 1998 remains to be seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is especially effective in Massachusetts in the
1990s because people have the tax increases of the late 1980s fresh
in their minds,'' said Gray.
</P>
<P>
   But a new public-opinion poll by Opinion Dynamics shows that
Dukakis, whom Cellucci uses as a political Darth Vader, is now
viewed favorably by 51 percent of Massachusetts voters, with only
29 percent seeing him unfavorably.
</P>
<P>
   And, looking back from the perspective of four decades observing
Massachusetts politics, Bartley scoffed at the notion that voters
will flee from a candidate simply because he refuses to take an
anti-tax pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is certifiable nonsense,'' said Bartley. ``No one gets beat
by that rhetoric _ or even by raising taxes if people know they are
for going to schools ... or to clean up the environment. They have
consistently supported those taxes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
