<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4021 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-SUSHI-ART-BOS &LR;      10-07 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-SUSHI-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN SETTLES FOR A LESSER SUSHI 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (i and f coding)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; TOKYO _ By 5 a.m., the world's biggest fish market is going
full throttle, alive with the noisy off-loading of 450 kinds of
seafood and the banter of thousands of wholesalers, middlemen and
restaurant owners.
</P>
<P>
   In the pre-dawn pallor, men in rubber galoshes creep through the
mist rising from endless rows of frozen tuna. It would be hard to
mistake these buyers, inspecting the three-foot carcasses with
metal prods and flashlights, for the high-flying bidders at an art
auction. But Japanese take their fish very seriously, and when the
beefy, tank-topped auctioneers call out bids at Tokyo Central
Wholesale Market, the stakes can be just as high as at Sotheby's.
</P>
<P>
   Or, at least, they used to be.
</P>
<P>
   As Japan muddles through its recession, even sushi, the ultimate
Japanese gastronomical obsession, is taking a bite.
</P>
<P>
   Next to rice, fish is perhaps Japan's most basic foodstuff, and
the decline in fish sales has paralleled the nation's economic
slump. Five years ago, the market sold $20.6 million of seafood
each day; this year sales dropped to $14.7 million. A single,
top-quality tuna to be served raw once commanded $20,000; on a
recent visit, the big earner was a 385-pound tuna for $8,346.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's economy has now contracted for three straight quarters,
and in this climate of anxiety, all but the wealthiest Japanese are
now saving instead of spending.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the worst I've seen in 40 years in this business,''
said Makoto Ishida, managing director of Tohto Suisan Co. Ltd., an
auction house at the market.
</P>
<P>
   Today, compared with the height of the bubble economy 10 years
ago, ``price and volume is about 30 to 40 percent down,'' he
estimated.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan's halcyon days of the 1980s, many people splurged on
the finest delicacies; the most conspicuous consumers sprinkled
gold leaf on their sushi before eating it. Today, while Japanese
staunchly resist cutting sushi out of their diets, many are looking
for ways to adjust their appetites.
</P>
<P>
   ``During this recession, many people are downsizing their
eating, cutting back or eating cheaper sushi,'' said Hirotoshi
Kosode, a senior auctioneer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cheaper fish is selling more, more expensive fish is selling
less, and some shops are selling cheaper fish, but charging the
same,'' he said darkly.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, cut-rate sushi bars are booming, stealing business
from moderate establishments by catering to gourmands adapting to
leaner times. Chefs at the priciest ``sushiyas,'' meanwhile, are
guarding clientele by maintaining top quality, and confide
gratefully that not everyone has run out of money.
</P>
<P>
   But for most people, lower-quality sushi at ``rotation''
restaurants, where customers serve themselves from a conveyor belt
and pay by the number of plates, has a new appeal. Many snubbed
those restaurants in the profligate 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Another approach is the all-you-can-eat philosophy, promoted by
the Edokko Zushi chain of restaurants, which offers enormous
portions of high-quality fish at low prices. In a no-frills
environment, Edokko profits from high volume by moving customers
through fast and limiting drinks.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Japanese people, sushi is very traditional and very
important compared to any other food. So even if normal people
can't get expensive stuff, we can still afford to buy cheap
sushi,'' Ishida said.
</P>
<P>
   Hirako Haruko, the owner of the medium-priced Kitahama sushi
bar, arrived early at the wholesale market so she could get the
best fish from middlemen. She said that the number of her customers
has dropped 30 percent since last year, and that each one eats less
than before.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't buy lower quality,'' she sniffed indignantly at the
suggestion that she economize, saying its more important to
preserve the reputation of her 47-year-old family-run restaurant.
``I prefer that my salary is down.''
</P>
<P>
   Reputation and quality are the mainstays of high-end
restaurants, like Sushi Kyubey, whose outlet at the Hotel Okura has
served the rich and famous for years. Here, the cheapest fare is a
12-gram piece of octopus sashimi for $2.30, while the dearest is a
tiny, mouth-melting morsel of fatty tuna belly &UR;  &LR; for $11.50. Dinner
for one costs about $150 without drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Head chef Makoto Shigihara says the price reflects not only the
highest-quality fish _ a slab of the best tuna breast costs the
restaurant $300 to $600 _ but also stringent quality control, with
two shifts of workers cutting, feeling and tasting the fish, and
sending it back if it's not the finest.
</P>
<P>
   Shigihara admits his is a ``high-society'' restaurant that has
catered to prime ministers and visiting dignitaries, including
President Clinton, who the chef recalls favored maguro tuna and
steamed abalone. But he said that instead of ``expecting customers
to just shut up and eat it ... we make sure the customer is
satisfied.''
</P>
<P>
   So Shigihara says he buys the best fish in town. He says some
regulars stayed away for a few months to try cheaper locales, but
many are back, because ``once you get used to sushi that suits your
tongue, it's very difficult to adjust your tastebuds just because
of price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sushi is practical and there's no waste,'' Shigihara said.
``You order what you want to eat, you eat everything you order, and
you pay for what you eat. It suits the Japanese lifestyle. That's
why maybe not every sushi restaurant is doing well, but ours still
is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
