u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILLENNIUM-CONUNDRUM-     10-07 0801
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILLENNIUM-CONUNDRUM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMING DECADE DIFFICULT TO NAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the countdown to 2000 ticking away, debate continues to
rage over the three great millennial questions.
</P>
<P>
   Will all our computers crash at 12:01 a.m. on Jan. 1, 2000 (the
2YK crisis)?
</P>
<P>
   Does the new century start then or at 12:01 a.m. on Jan. 1,
2001?
</P>
<P>
   And does anybody really care?
</P>
<P>
   A fourth question, arguably even more vexing, has largely gone
unnoticed. Forget about centuries and millennia: what exactly do we
call the next decade?
</P>
<P>
   We were in the '80s. We are in the '90s. We're going to enter
... the Zeros? The Double Zeros? The Double Ohs? The Zeds? The
Aughts? The Naughts, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   Word maven William Safire has proposed the ``Zippy Zeroes'' _ a
name as unlikely to be adopted as two others that have been bruited
about, ``The Zilches'' and ``The Uh-Ohs.''
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times editorial page, never one to miss an
opportunity to fill a vacuum in authority, has already plumped _
twice, no less _ for ``The Ohs.'' Wrote the Times in its best
high-Pollyanna mode in '83: ``The Ohs, with a connotation of
wonder, would be fittingly optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when Roy Blount Jr., the humorist and a member
of the usage panel of the American Heritage Dictionary, liked the
sound (if not the spelling) of the Times' candidate. Back in the
days of ever-deepening budget deficits, Blount proposed the next
decade should be called the ``owes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had this all figured out a while back,'' he sighs.
But budget balancing, having closed the fiscal floodgates, has
reopened the linguistic.
</P>
<P>
   Blount reels off an impressive list of tongue-in-cheek
possibilities. ``The Woes.'' ``The Woesome O's.'' On the other
hand, ``The Awesome Aughts.'' Or ``The So-So O's.'' The
``post-Nineties.'' The ``From-Scratch,'' ``The Clean Slate,'' ``The
``Blank Check,'' the ``Tabula Rasa Decade.'' ``The Big O's.'' Or
``The ``Little O's.'' ``The Ne-O's'' _ or ``Neo-O's.'' ``The
``Two-Thou's.'' ``The ``20-O's.'' ``The Nulls.'' ``The MMO's''?
``The 2K's''? I guess that would apply to the whole next thousand
years.''
</P>
<P>
   As Blount suggests, going the numeric route doesn't really
settle anything. Calling the decade ``The 2000s'' simply creates
more confusion, since that's also the name of the century (the
millennium, too).
</P>
<P>
   Julia Child has a sentimental attachment to ``naughty-naughts.''
That's what the celebrated cookbook author's mother and her fellow
members of the Smith College class of '00 called themselves. Such
implied raciness has an obvious, fun-loving appeal as a name for
the next decade, but Child notes an interesting drawback.
``Naughty-naughts'' might bring back memories of the present White
House mess,'' Child laments.
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, if ``naughty-naughts'' conjures up images of Bill
Clinton makin' Oval Office whoopee, then another contender,
``aught-naughts,'' carries overtones of Kenneth Starr chasing after
him.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Disch, a novelist and poet whose most recent book is ``A
Child's Garden of Grammar,'' offers a compromise solution: ``The
naughties.'' ``There'd be a kind of psychology in going from ``The
naughties'' to the teens,'' he points out.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, another name that's been suggested (albeit none too
seriously) is ``pre-teens.''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Mish, editor in chief at Merriam-Webster, the Springfield
dictionary publisher, argues for a progression that's numerical
rather than developmental. ``If you follow the pattern of '20s,
'30s, '40s,'' he says, ``I suppose you have to call it `the units.'
I don't know what else you would use between 0 and 10. Then, of
course, after that, we're off the hook, since everyone can agree on
the teens.
</P>
<P>
   The root of the problem is that there wasn't any established
name a century ago, either. ``People in the 1890s were intensely
decade conscious,'' says Michael Kammen, a Pulitzer Prize-winning
historian at Cornell University. ``They would refer to the '90s as
the Mauve Decade, for example. Yet once 1900 rolled around there
was no universally agreed-upon term for that new decade.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Wallraff drew the same conclusion two years ago in her
Word Court column in The Atlantic Monthly. For herself, she's
perfectly content with the lack of any universal name for the next
decade and sees no need to prescribe any.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's an opportunity to say, `it's not yet settled and you
get to vote,''' says Wallraff, who's preparing a compilation of her
columns for Harcourt Brace. ``It seems sort of unpleasant of me, in
this case, to be saying what I want it to be called. So, actually,
I have an interest in staying out of it, letting people settle it
for themselves, which is an awfully nice process.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1357EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 13:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4028 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-07 0743
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLAROID FOUNDER WANTED A SNAPSHOT, NOT A PORTRAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   During his lifetime, Polaroid Corp. founder Edwin Land actively
discouraged would-be biographers. When Mark Olshaker was finishing
up an unauthorized biography in 1978, Land sicced his lawyers on
the young writer. Ten years later, when a former colleague told
Land he too was planning to write a biography, Land replied, ``Why
would anyone want to read such a book?''
</P>
<P>
   Now Victor McElheny, a veteran science writer who worked with
Land, has published ``Insisting on the Impossible; the Life of
Edwin Land.'' This time Land has reached from beyond the grave to
thwart the efforts of a sympathetic biographer. In his first
chapter, McElheny reports that after Land's death in 1991, ``a
laboratory associate spent three years shredding his papers,
presumably on the inventor's instructions.''
</P>
<P>
   Insiders say the document purge was carried out by Land's
longtime executive assistant, Natalie Fultz, under the supervision
of Land's son-in-law, Philip DuBois. Fultz declined to speak with
me. DuBois reiterated Land's aversion to biography _ ``I made it
clear to Victor what our feelings were'' _ and wouldn't discuss the
destruction of any papers; ``That's a matter of his personal
life.'' He indicated that outside of corporate documents kept at
Polaroid, and scientific publications, there would be no Edwin Land
archive for scholars to peruse now or in the future: ``We are
respecting Dr. Land's wishes.''
</P>
<P>
   That's probably true. But in this instance, perhaps the family
should have over-ruled the secretive and imperious entrepreneur.
What has been lost is 60 years' worth of material documenting the
career of America's greatest inventor since Thomas Edison. Although
creating instant photography was no mean task, Land earned 535
patents in his lifetime, working on everything from the theory of
color vision to the U2 spy plane. A former Polaroid executive
called the loss of Land's files ``a catastrophe ... a tragedy for
future historians.''
</P>
<P>
   McElheny is the immediate victim of Land's machinations. His
467-page biography artfully recounts Land's many scientific
accomplishments, from his work on light polarization to the
grandiose, smashing failure of his instant movie system,
Polavision. But the book is virtually devoid of personal detail.
``It's a bit dry, this biography,'' comments Publishers Weekly in
an advance review.
</P>
<P>
   Land said he regarded the kind of biographical details that
writers hunger for _ stories about his family, his upbringing, his
religious formation _ as so many ``interchangeable variables.'' But
of course it is just those ``variables'' (what a cold, stupid
term!) that make us humans, and not machines.
</P>
<P>
   Land employed a small palace guard to shield his anonymity.
Multi-million dollars gifts to Harvard, and to the American Academy
of Arts and Sciences, are for the first time revealed in McElheny's
book. Fearful of kidnapping attempts _ and a trifle paranoid _ Land
paid a policeman to stand guard outside his home in Cambridge,
Mass., making it instantly recognizable to the world at large.
</P>
<P>
   Why the secrecy? Former Polaroid staffers say Land, a self-made
man who insisted on being called ``Dr. Land'' although he never
earned a PhD, feared the ridicule of academic scientists who often
spitballed his successful inventions. McElheny hints of difficult
relations between the assimilated Land and his observant, Jewish
parents: ``Anecdotal evidence suggests that some of (Land's)
relatives, perhaps including his father, resented how little they
shared in Land's ultimate wealth.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Polaroid veterans note that the workaholic Land hardly had
a life in the conventional sense. ``We'd say, `Have a nice weekend'
to each other on Sunday night at midnight and start working the
next morning at 6 a.m.,'' recalls Lucretia Weed, an executive on
the SX-70 camera project. ``His life was his science, and he wanted
it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   I interviewed Land on the subject of biography in 1987. After
re-stating his distaste for ``personal'' biography, Land jauntily
closed out the conversation with this quote from the Bible: ``By
their works, ye shall know them.'' Here is a man whose works we
know and celebrate, yet our knowledge of him is sadly incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Alex Beam's e-mail address is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
