<HEADLINE>
DO MEN WANT UNDIES IN A CAN? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUZANNE C. RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ever forget to bring extra underwear on vacation? Or you're so
sweaty you need spare boxers at the gym. Or you're so busy that the
laundry just doesn't get done and you're stuck wearing Tuesday's
briefs?
</P>
<P>
   Rejoice! Next month, the underwear maker Joe Boxer Corp. plans
to unveil the unthinkable: underwear vending machines, where men
and women can buy undies with a swipe of a credit card.
</P>
<P>
   The company plans to install the machines nationally in places
like airports, fitness centers, university halls, and tourist
spots.
</P>
<P>
   The $14 to $18 products come compressed and sealed in aluminum
cans.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to briefs, customers will get entertainment. A
comedian's voice will tell a joke from the machine. And even if
you're just passing by, the machine, equipped with a motion sensor,
may speak to you. So now laundry haters, there's no excuse for
going bare.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Okay, it's a little early to think about the holidays (even
though Macy's has had a dancing Santa Claus displayed for weeks).
But the cosmetic brand Clinique plans to make shopping easier this
year with a new registry service that will allow women to make wish
lists of the lotion, soap or lipstick they really want.
</P>
<P>
   Using a Clinique web site -- which will begin selling products
next month -- women can list their favorite products as well as the
e-mail addresses of the people they hope to receive gifts from.
Clinique will then send e-mails to those people informing them of
the list. If these potential customers are interested, Clinique
says it will sell the goods to them on-line and then ship them to
the original party in time for the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Viola! It's shopping made simple at www.clinique.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Spring fashion week in Paris starts Sunday, Oct. 11, and for
those of you who can't wait even for CNN to show the collections,
now you can have instant gratification.
</P>
<P>
   Elle magazine is reporting live from Paris via the Internet.
Just log on to www.elle.com for video clips from the catwalk, as
well as backstage footage and other news.
</P>
<P>
   The shows run from Oct. 11 to Oct. 20. Enjoy.
</P>
</TEXT>
