<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4031 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUTHOR-CASABLANCA-ART     10-07 1378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUTHOR-CASABLANCA-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAY IT AGAIN, SAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL BLOWEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Michael Walsh made sure his letters of transit were in order
before he started the daunting task of writing an extension of
``Casablanca,'' the 1942 Warner Bros. movie classic that remains
hugely popular.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh's novel ``As Time Goes By,'' which arrives in bookstores
today, is a book as moneymaker. A marketer's dream. A Warner book
based on a Warner film. The copyright, usually owned or shared by
the author, is completely retained by Warner Books. The publisher,
with a worldwide printing of 1.1 million copies, hopes to make a
fortune.
</P>
<P>
   The publishing world is abuzz over the prospect. But it's a
risky proposition to tamper with a classic. The last time they
tinkered with ``Casablanca,'' about a decade ago, Ted Turner
colorized it. Fans were outraged, and it's nearly impossible to
find a colorized video of the film at any video store in town.
Alexandra Ripley, who wrote ``Scarlett,'' a sequel to ``Gone With
the Wind,'' America's other untouchable movie, was scorched in the
press. Readers and viewers are often outraged by tampering with
icons.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first question I'm always asked is, `How dare you?,'''
said Walsh, the novelist who was Time's classical music critic for
16 years and is now a visiting professor of journalism at Boston
University. ``It's a question like, `Well, aside from that, how did
you enjoy the play, Mrs. Lincoln?''' he said during an interview at
BU last week. ``The easy answer is that they asked me. The second,
more complicated one, is that I was intrigued. After watching the
movie three to six times, in whole or in part, and getting
permission to quote from the screenplay, I outlined my basic ideas
and sent it to Warner books. That was in the late spring or early
summer of 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   While everyone involved is reluctant to discuss figures, it's
clear millions of dollars are involved in the publishing effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a writer for hire,'' said Walsh. ``They have a valuable
franchise, and they weren't about to share it with me. If the book
does well, I will, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by a strong ad campaign, including the center spread in
Sunday's New York Times Book Review, and by an upcoming publicity
tour that will land Walsh on everything from the network morning
shows to CNN, ``As Time Goes By'' is expected to hit the bestseller
list. But, in order to stay there, the novel will have to satisfy
both occasional readers and dedicated fans.
</P>
<P>
   Every major movie poll rates ``Casablanca'' as one of the top
three films of all time. Not a week goes by that we aren't hit from
a reference to the film. From classic lines such as ``Round up the
usual suspects'' to images of Bogie's Blaine advertising products
ranging from soft drinks to automobiles, Warner's is milking the
franchise.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the 1942 release, Julius and Philip Epstein,
the twin-brother screenwriters most responsible for the film's
script, were asked by studio head Jack Warner to write
``Brazzaville'' as a sequel.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were tired of it. We didn't like `Casablanca' much in the
first place and thought we put all we had to offer in the
original,'' said Julius Epstein. ``Once she got on the plane, and
he walked off into the fog, we'd had it. We were on to other
things.'' ``Brazzaville never got made.''
</P>
<P>
   For decades, what drove Warner executives wild is that they had
a mine but they couldn't extract the gold. Two television series,
one in 1955 and another in 1983, starring David Soul as Rick,
bombed. Several writers attempted penning movie sequels. They
failed. Howard Koch, a screenwriter who's credited with writing
some of the original, tried to peddle a sequel in 1988. It didn't
generate interest. Several authors, whom Warner Books refuses to
name, tried writing ``As Time Goes By'' before Walsh was attached.
They failed. There was even some talk that Steven Bogart, son of
Humphrey and Lauren Bacall, might write it. Several revivals of the
play ``Everyone Comes to Rick's,'' the inspiration for the film,
have been mounted. They bombed.
</P>
<P>
   But Walsh has written something that may work, and well.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know why they selected me,'' he said. ``My
first novel, `Exchange Alley,' had a great deal of sex and violence
and seemingly nothing in common with `Casablanca.' But Maureen
Egan, an executive at Warner Books, asked me if I'd be interested
in taking a shot at a sequel to `Casablanca,' and I was intrigued.
I took the shot and here we are. I was never a huge fan of the
movie. And I think that was an advantage. I found the characters
and the situation intriguing, but I didn't worship the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   What Walsh manages to do is to respect the original without
treating it as gospel. He elucidates the mystery while keeping it
mysterious. He answers questions while retaining that foggy
ambiguity that's so integral to the movie's longevity. He
dramatizes what happened to Rick and Ilsa in Paris and expands the
character of Sam the piano player. He draws parallels between the
ideological intensity of freedom fighter Victor Laszlo and the
Nazis. And Ilsa plays a much more active role in the World War II
political intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   Many fans of the movie, a new edition of which will be released
Tuesday (Oct. 13) on video, believe that the bittersweet ending,
set in fog with Ilsa leaving with Victor and Rick beginning his
beautiful friendship with Louis, is perfect. And, in many ways it
is. But, without destroying that sense of ambiguity, Walsh creates
a postwar ending to his tale that maintains the spirit of the
film's finale.
</P>
<P>
   The book's ending was the fruit of a serendipitous moment. Early
on in the writing, Walsh, while waiting in his car outside an Ames
Department Store in upstate New York, hit an inspirational
bullseye.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh My God,'' he said of Rick Blaine, ``he's a Jewish
gangster.'' Walsh names him Yitzik Baline, appropriating Irving
Berlin's real last name.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that three of the four writers were Jewish,'' he said,
``it makes sense. It also explains his background. Explains how
he's so good with a gun. He ran a New York nightclub for the Jewish
gangsters. It all started to come together after that.''
</P>
<P>
   From there, Walsh took off as fast as a '40s Warner Bros.
melodrama. Working most nights from 11 until 4, he zipped through
the story. Instead of just a sequel, he made the movie the
centerpiece and added two side panels _ the beginning on one side
and the ending on the other. In five weeks he completed a first
draft. And, after discussions with editors, including answering a
query from his German translator, ``What's a knish?'' Walsh
completed the novel in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``The book needed the right tempo,'' said Walsh, who lives with
his wife, Kate, and two daughters, Alexandra, 15, and Clare, 9, in
Boston and in their weekend home in Canaan, Conn. Walsh puts his
musical knowledge to good use in the literary form. ``I started
thinking of it as a Raoul Walsh film. It needed that tempo. I type
very fast, but I couldn't keep up with the ideas. Once I started,
it really took off.''
</P>
<P>
   While the story is big _ cutting between occupied France and the
New York underworld _ Walsh never forgets the two crucial elements
the Epstein brothers brought to the movie _ details and humor.
</P>
<P>
   Incorporating both the fictional characters and the personae of
the actors who portray them, he plays around with some fun touches.
In one, Ilsa plays the Kruetzer Sonata, a piece Ingrid Bergman
performed in another of her films, ``Intermezzo'' (1939). In
another, Rick declines an invitation to see ``High Sierra'' (1941),
a Bogart movie, saying he prefers musicals.
</P>
<P>
   Walsh skillfully blends the reader's preconceptions about the
characters and the stars into a form of iconography _ the movie
star as cast in a novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think `Casablanca' has become part of a shared cultural
myth, and I used that in the book,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No word on whether Warner Bros. plans to ruin everything by
making ``As Time Goes By'' into a movie.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
