u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-CINDERELLA-BOS &LR;      10-07 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-CINDERELLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARTOLI BIOGRAPHER KNOWS THE SCORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
CINDERELLA &AMP; COMPANY 
Backstage at the Opera with Cecilia Bartoli 
By Manuela Hoelterhoff 
Knopf, 259 pp., illustrated, $25 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Manuela Hoelterhoff has burned her bridges behind her and
written a hilarious, revealing, and sometimes malicious book about
operatic intrigue on and off the stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cinderella &AMP; Company'' apparently began as an attempt to write
a biography of Cecilia Bartoli, an attempt that was bound to fail
because the world's most popular young opera singer is too young,
too private, and too normal in every respect except her voice.
Hoelterhoff, the Pulitzer-winning music critic of The Wall Street
Journal, gave up her seats on the aisle to spend a year hanging out
backstage with Bartoli. This assignment and other factors gave her
an entree rarely granted to any journalist, and Hoelterhoff didn't
miss a thing during her travels.
</P>
<P>
   The book is centered on Bartoli, but that isn't the really
interesting part. Bartoli is at least as devoted to her family as
to her career, and her brother's illness and death became the major
issue in this period of her life. We learn that she drives her
manager and her record company crazy because she's not a workhorse
like Joan Sutherland _ she won't get on an airplane if she can
possibly help it (``I need to feel the ground under my feet,'' she
says), and she doesn't enjoy touring, especially in America, far
from home. She does like to eat, and Hoelterhoff repeatedly refers
to the discrepancy between the figure Bartoli cuts in her publicity
photos and her actual figure. To her credit, the mezzo-soprano
appears utterly indifferent to efforts to create an image for her.
``For her first albums and publicity shots, Bartoli dutifully put
on slinky clothes and a lot of lipstick, taking them off the minute
she could afford to say no, which wasn't long into her career. The
recital of Rossini arias ... shows her wearing trollop-red gloves
and rhinestone clumps dangling from her ears. That was in 1989.
This year, the cover was digitally transformed to give the mezzo
black gloves and tiny earrings.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoelterhoff establishes a context for Bartoli by tracing the
activities of Luciano Pavarotti, Placido Domingo, Carol Vaness,
June Anderson, Deborah Voigt, Renee Fleming, Jane Eaglen, Patricia
Racette, Roberto Alagna and Angela Gheorghiu, James Levine, and
other opera figures in the same time frame; there are also
portraits of managers, conductors, stage directors, administrators,
girlfriends, fans, and other elements of the operatic support
system, even a composer. There's also a lot of the racier gossip of
the period. Hoelterhoff's style is tartly amusing, but she
occasionally overplays her hand. Accompanying Bartoli at the piano,
James Levine ``scampered cheerfully over the keyboard when not
blowing her kisses between sets, or placing his hand over his heart
in a manner that could make a strong man heave into a bucket.''
</P>
<P>
   A few figures emerge with credit, particularly Voigt and
Fleming. Pavarotti is seen as an almost-tragic figure, bravely and
foolhardily soldiering on to the fast-approaching end of his
career. By comparison, his principal rival gets trashed. ``Domingo
was standing in the auditorium facing a camera and a microphone,
having managed to fit a TV interview into a short break, which
would now not be wasted. ... He was smiling, so I had to assume no
one was asking him what his wife of thirty-seven years, Marta
Domingo, thought about the twenty-one-year-old Romanian nymph he
had been squiring around Vienna, where she studied voice. Was he
giving her private tutorials?''
</P>
<P>
   Alagna and Gheorghiu, ``the love couple,'' emerge as monsters of
caprice; they are like opera singers in a cartoon. When Alagna sang
Rodolfo opposite the Mimi of another Romanian soprano, Leontina
Vaduva, ``Gheorghiu amused herself miming Mimi's music from the
wings while. ... Vaduva went through the bother of singing it.
Vaduva was hopefully getting used to these appearances. `My dear,
best be careful! Your high C is sounding a little low tonight,'
Gheorghiu was overheard telling her as the weary woman was sitting
in her dressing room during a performance of `Romeo et Juliette'
with Alagna a few months before at Covent Garden.'' The Met's
Joseph Volpe earned immortality when he threatened a balky
Gheorghiu on tour in Japan. ``That wig,'' he thundered, ``is going
on, with or without you.''
</P>
<P>
   Cumulatively ``Cinderella &AMP; Company'' presents a portrait of
world-class opera that will delight everyone who thinks of opera as
an elitist activity in the hands of greedy egomaniacs _ many of
whom are lechers, drunks, parasites, opportunists, and fools. The
book is a damning indictment, though it will please that portion of
the opera-house audience which relishes operatic intrigue for those
very reasons. After a while, most of it will enrage anyone who
thinks opera is worth taking seriously (thank God for Renee
Fleming, who does). In that respect Hoelterhoff's book is a little
like the now-notorious British television documentary series about
the administration of the Royal Opera House, Covent Garden, which
became a lightning rod for criticism of arts funding and indeed the
arts themselves. Hoelterhoff's book will probably not lead to
important changes the way those television programs did. The only
change ``Cinderella &AMP; Company'' is likely to precipitate is that no
one in the operatic world will ever speak freely around Manuela
Hoelterhoff again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1402EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
