<HEADER>
A4035 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MICROWAVE-FOOD-HNS &LR;      10-07 1578
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROWAVE-FOOD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROWAVE FEARLESSLY, CONQUER PHOBIA BY LEARNING TECHNIQUES THAT
WORK 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ANN STEINER 
and CICI WILLIAMSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you backed off from using your microwave because you're
afraid of it? Perhaps you've heard Halloween-style stories of
exploding eggs, squash or potatoes. Or, maybe you're like the chef
who confided to us, ``I don't cook in the microwave, ever. I just
use it to heat and warm. I will not replace my current machine when
it goes; I'd rather have the counter space.''
</P>
<P>
   He's definitely not on our wavelength. We couldn't live without
our microwaves. But many people who can track infinity on the
Internet may be totally intimidated by the microwave. If you are
using yours just to heat and warm, you're missing out on some great
cooking. Besides being fast, microwave cooking is easy, cool and
clean.
</P>
<P>
   Many foods are actually better when microwaved, we believe:
vegetables, sauces, fish fillets, some candies and snacks. You can
discard your double boiler because the microwave makes
smooth-as-silk sauces and custards without constant stirring. It
melts or softens chocolate, butter, cheese, jelly, jam, fruit
syrups, honey, peanut butter, ice cream and ice cream toppings. It
warms tostadas, tortillas and taco shells, softens hard brown sugar
and overset gelatin. You can use it to candy citrus peel and
pineapple, to soften or toast nuts and coconut, or to blanch
almonds.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SEAFOOD &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's best to have the family or guests gathered near the table
when you begin to microwave seafood. In less than 5 minutes, you'll
be ready to serve a delicious entree. Fish doesn't reheat well _ it
tends to toughen _ so plan to cook the amount that will be eaten.
Use high power to microwave fish. Place thicker portions towards
the outside of the dish and cover with wax paper. To avoid
overcooking, remove fish from microwave when the outer edges are
opaque but the center is still slightly translucent. A few minutes
of standing time will finish the cooking.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
GROUND MEATS &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you're fueling your fast-laners by grabbing a pound of frozen
ground meat at the last minute, here's one of the best ways we know
to get dinner on the table pronto. First, did you put it in the
freezer as a brick shape or make a doughnut of it? A brick shape
takes about twice as long to defrost because the center resists
thawing. When you form ground meat into a doughnut shape, the
microwave can have that ring of meat thawed and ready to cook in 3
to 4 minutes, partly because there's no frozen center.
</P>
<P>
   No need to open the package to shape a doughnut. Just push down
gently in the center of the plastic wrap and coax the meat away
from the center.
</P>
<P>
   When defrosting it, that's the time to remove all packaging and
place meat in the utensil to be used for your recipe.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   METHOD I: SPEEDY DEFROST AND SAUTE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Use this method only if the meat is to be cooked immediately
because the meat becomes warm, which encourages bacterial growth.
</P>
<P>
   Remove all packaging and place the pound of ground meat into a
dishwasher-safe plastic colander. Set colander in utensil to be
used for recipe. Microwave on high 1 minute. Use a fork to flake
defrosted portion onto wax paper; set it aside.
</P>
<P>
   Return frozen portion to microwave and repeat process two times.
Break up remaining meat and place all meat back into the colander.
If your recipe includes sauted onion, celery or bell pepper,
sprinkle the chopped raw vegetables on top of the meat. Stirring
midway through cooking, microwave on high 6 to 7 minutes. Discard
fat that drained into utensil and place meat mixture into same
utensil to complete recipe.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL; 
 &LR; METHOD II: DEFROSTING GROUND MEAT &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remove all packaging and place the pound of ground meat in a
glass mixing bowl. Microwave on medium-low (30 percent) 4 minutes.
Use a fork to flake the defrosted portion onto a piece of wax
paper; set it aside. Return frozen portion to microwave and
microwave on 30 percent 2 minutes. Flake meat again. If any frozen
portion remains, microwave on 30 percent 1 to 2 minutes. By
removing thawed meat, the outer edges don't begin to cook, and the
defrosting is accelerated since microwaves can now reach the frozen
portion.
</P>
<P>
   Microwaving ground meat in a plastic colander is the most
efficient way to remove the maximum amount of fat from the meat
because the fat drains through the holes during cooking. Be sure to
suspend the colander over a casserole to catch that fat. Microwave
5 minutes per pound for ground chicken, turkey and beef and 6 to 7
minutes per pound for ground pork.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
RICE &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The best rice cooker we know of is the microwave oven. If your
microwave can do multiple cooking with one programming, there's no
need to look back once you turn the oven on. No pot watching or
boil-overs. Here's how we like to do it.
</P>
<P>
   Combine 2 cups hot tap water and 1 cup raw regular rice in a
2-quart utensil; adding salt or butter is optional. Cover with lid
or vented plastic wrap and microwave on high 6 minutes, reduce
power to medium-low (30 percent) and microwave 12 to 14 minutes.
Fluff rice with a fork and let stand covered 5 minutes. Makes 3 to
3{ cups.
</P>
<P>
   For 7 cups cooked rice, double the above method and use a
3-quart casserole. Increase initial cooking time to 9 minutes on
high, then cook 16 to 18 minutes on 30 percent. Refrigerate or
freeze the extra rice for later use. Allow 1 minute on high to
reheat 1 cup refrigerated rice and 2 minutes on high for 1 cup
frozen rice.
</P>
<P>
   Another step-saver in microwaving casseroles that include rice
or noodles is to combine the raw rice or noodles with the other
ingredients. Of course, enough liquid needs to be included to cook
the rice or noodles.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SOFTENING AND MELTING &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cheesecake: The San Francisco Chronicle did a taste test of our
Chocolate Turtle Cheesecake a few years ago. They baked the recipe
in the oven and the microwave. The microwave version won the
tasting. Cheesecakes that are made in the microwave come out
creamy, moist and smooth. It's faster and easier, too. You don't
have to set the pan in a water bath, and it's done in barely 15
minutes vs. more than an hour in an oven. Making the batter also is
easier.
</P>
<P>
   Cream cheese: You don't have to set the cream cheese out on the
counter to soften. Instead, microwave an unwrapped 8-ounce package
on medium (50 percent) power 1{ minutes; 2 (8-ounce) packages, 2{
to 3 minutes; or 3 (8-ounce) packages, 3 to 3{ minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Chocolate: Melting chocolate in the microwave beats using a
double-boiler on top of the range. It's much faster and reliable if
you use medium (50 percent) power. Chocolate continues to hold its
shape when microwaved. So, stir it to complete the melting process.
For 1 (1-ounce) square baking chocolate, microwave 1{ to 2 minutes
on medium. One cup chocolate morsels takes 2{ to 3 minutes on
medium. If melting chocolate with butter or cream, use medium-high
(70 percent) power.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
VEGETABLES &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Retaining the vitamins and bright color. Keeping the crunch.
Speeding the cooking. What better reasons to cook fresh veggies in
your microwave?
</P>
<P>
   Many vegetables are cooked without the addition of water or
other liquid _ there's enough within the vegetable itself.
Nutrients stay in the food instead of floating down the drain with
the liquid needed for conventional cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Three vegetables in particular microwave much faster than
cooking them conventionally: artichokes, potatoes and winter
squash. Cooking these conventionally takes 45 minutes to an hour.
An artichoke microwaves in less than 5 minutes; potatoes and winter
squash take about 6 minutes per pound.
</P>
<P>
   An ear of corn microwaves in about 3 minutes. It sure saves time
and heat in the kitchen as an alternative to boiling corn
conventionally in a large pot of water.
</P>
<P>
   To microwave corn in the husk: Remove tough outer husks, leaving
two layers of light green husk and silks intact. If microwaving
more than 2 ears at a time, arrange wagon-wheel fashion with the
tip of the ears at the hub and the base to the outside. Microwave
on high (100 percent) 2{ to 3 minutes for one ear; 4 to 6 minutes
for 2; 7 to 9 minutes for 4; and 10 to 12 minutes for 6.
</P>
<P>
   To cook a single ear in plastic wrap: Remove all husks and silk.
Wrap each ear in microwave-approved plastic wrap (such as Saran
wrap; use times listed above). Microwaving items wrapped in wax
paper is not recommended because it can impart a waxy taste.
</P>
<P>
   To cook corn in a casserole: Place in rectangular 2-quart glass
casserole and cover dish with plastic wrap. No need to add water.
Microwave for the same length of times listed above. Turn corn
upside down and re-arrange in casserole midway through cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few guidelines for microwaving your vegetables to
perfection:
</P>
<P>
   Choose vegetables that are similar in shape and size so they
will cook more evenly.
</P>
<P>
   Pierce vegetables that are microwaved in their own skins with
the tip of a paring knife to prevent bursting _ potatoes, sweet
potatoes, winter squash or tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   Weigh vegetables to determine the correct amount of time to
microwave.
</P>
<P>
   Cover vegetables that aren't cooked in their own skin. This
traps the maximum amount of heat and moisture to promote quick,
even cooking.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange items such as potatoes and corn on the cob in
wagon-wheel fashion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
