<HEADLINE>
`CHARMED' NEEDS MORE EYE OF NEWT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
CHARMED 
Starring: Shannen Doherty, Holly Marie Combs, Alyssa Milano 
On: The WB 
Time: Wednesday at 9 p.m. 
Rated: TVPG 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The prospect of reformed TV brat Shannen Doherty playing a witch
on the new series ``Charmed'' has wry potential. Especially since
the show is the latest brainchild of executive producer Aaron
Spelling, the authority figure Doherty most offended during her
years on another one of his shows, ``Beverly Hills 90210.'' But
aside from the title of tonight's premiere episode, ``Something
Wicca This Way Comes,'' this new series is a mostly straight-faced
hour set in San Francisco that blends sisterly melodrama with the
supernatural. It's ``Party of Five'' meets ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer,'' but with less angst and pathos than the former and more
adult pretension than the latter.
</P>
<P>
   The concept behind ``Charmed'' is that three feuding sisters are
united against evil when they discover they are witches. ``The
power of three will set us free,'' they chant against a nasty
warlock, causing him to combust into dust in their attic. Doherty
is the oldest, and the most temperamental; Alyssa Milano is the
irresponsible, boyfriend-stealing one; and Holly Marie Combs is the
innocent who wants to be a chef. As on ``Party of Five,'' parents
are out of the picture; their mother is dead and their father is
as-yet unaccounted for. Based on tonight's bland premiere, the
series could use more wit and suspense in its supernatural doings,
or at least a dose of Doherty-driven soap opera to juice up the
human dramas. As it is, ``Charmed'' is a pretty bland-tasting brew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
