<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4037 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRAVEL-NAPA-VALLEY-HN     10-07 1271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-NAPA-VALLEY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAPA VALLEY AFFORDS MOMENT OF SERENITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MICHAEL LONSFORD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I've been visiting California's Napa Valley for more than 20
years; honeymooned there once, in fact. And despite the too-often
materialistic trappings of Disneyland, it remains _ in part and
certain parcels _ a magical place for folks like me from the muggy
flatlands.
</P>
<P>
   Tourists invade the valley to the tune of maybe 2 million a
year. Traffic along the main, and two-lane, Highway 29 can remind
you of an L.A. freeway at 5:30 on a bad Friday afternoon. Tour
buses have their own parking spaces at Robert Mondavi Winery, and
the grounds of Niebaum-Coppola Winery look like a Hollywood set
designed by _ guess who? _ film director Francis Ford Coppola. The
columns and fountains are actually tastefully done, but the fact
that they detract from the beauty of the old Inglenook winery is
enough to give any history lover a bad edifice complex.
</P>
<P>
   Napa is a contrast. Speaking of the Mondavi Winery, the tour
guides there are a friendly lot. But go across the highway to Opus
One _ jointly owned by Mondavi and the the owners of Chateau
Mouton-Rothschild of Bordeaux _ and the tour personnel are a
hoity-toity lot. Too bad.
</P>
<P>
   Another contrast: Napa, perhaps jaded by the tourist hordes, can
cop an attitude, especially at certain high-profile restaurants.
But don't include the new Bistro Jeanty in Yountville among the
snooty few. Good food, good martini, decent wine list _ and nice
folks. Turn off Highway 29 down Chambers Lane by Tra Vigne
Restaurant and go to the Napa Valley Olive Oil Co. and load up on
good, inexpensive extra-virgin olive oil, excellent Genoa salami,
positively cheap sun-dried tomatoes and friendly folks to take your
cash.
</P>
<P>
   You know how you can tell that times and trends have changed?
One of the main cut-throughs between the parallel Highway 29 on the
western side of the valley and the Silverado Trail on the eastern
side is Zinfandel Lane. Not Cabernet Lane or Chardonnay Lane, but
Zinfandel Lane. Fact is, there used to be a lot of zinfandel grown
in Napa. But much of it is gone, the $40,000-an-acre vineyard land
planted over to the more popular _ and more profitable _ cabernet
sauvignon, not to mention chardonnay, the Big Mac of California
white wines.
</P>
<P>
   I've stayed at many places in Napa, from B&AMP;B's to tony
hostelries. Alas, gone are the days when the art deco El Bonita
Motel charged $25 a night! But none could beat the ambience of the
guest house at Stags' Leap Winery on the southern Silverado Trail.
There may be more majestic views in Napa, but I've never seen any
prettier.
</P>
<P>
   Napa Valley is a 30-mile-long, 4- to 5-mile-wide valley, and
frankly I thought I had seen just about everything there was to see
there when I first visited Stag's Leap Winery a couple of years
ago. But I was awestruck by the beauty of the 107-year-old
Victorian Manor House and the beautifully landscaped grounds. How
had I missed this spot for so many years?
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, Stags' Leap is not open to the public; you have
to make an appointment. For another, it's hard to find. There is no
sign on the Silverado Trail, just a mailbox with an address on it,
and the driveway entrance is shared between Stags' Leap and Shafer
Vineyards next door.
</P>
<P>
   Stags' Leap Winery was founded in 1893. In time it would become
a resort and cattle ranch in addition to a working vineyard. In
1970, Carl Doumani, a bear of a man with a quick laugh and
catcher's-mitt hands, bought the property and eventually got the
winery back up and running. Although he sold the winery to Beringer
not long ago, winemaker Robert Brittan has stayed on.
</P>
<P>
   (There is another winery in the area with a similar name: Stag's
Leap Wine Cellars. Believe me when I say there is no similarity or
connection
</P>
<P>
   between these two wineries.)
</P>
<P>
   Historically, Stags' Leap did no tours and no tastings. So far
under the Beringer banner, it still doesn't. I hope it stays that
way. Let the thirsty tourists go visit Beringer's Rhine House a few
miles away or take the tram up to Sterling Vineyards. Great view
there. But stay away from Stags' Leap. Don't ruin a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Let me tell you about a perfect morning in paradise:
</P>
<P>
   My friends have gone off to play golf, and I have the place to
myself, so a scenic jaunt is in order. It's about a mile jog from
the house down a walnut-tree-lined blacktop to the Silverado Trail
highway, and despite the clean, crisp and invigorating air, I'm
gasping on the return lap because it's slightly uphill. At least
that's my official excuse.
</P>
<P>
   After a quick shower, I take the Sunday paper outside and
collapse _ er, recline _ in a chaise lounge underneath two small
shade trees in front of the house, built in the 1920s. Where I'm
sitting overlooks a large, Italianate terraced garden full of
peppers and tomatoes and squash and onions and strawberries and god
knows what else two steps down in front of me. A row of 40-foot
palm trees, all with woodpecker holes in them, is about 50 feet
beyond the garden. In fact, one of those industrious (or bored?)
birds is rat-tat, rat-tat-tatting around back, doing its best to
topple an oak tree. Silly bird ...
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the palms are vineyards on a gentle slope. And beyond
that, a small, tree-covered hill.
</P>
<P>
   And there I sit: No cars, no pollution, and a velvet silence _
just the gentlest of breezes, and I am basking in peacefulness. In
the distance, a hawk sails silently upward on a thermal. This must
have been the way Napa was when wine was made by farmers, not
weekending socialites or nouveau riche refugees from San Francisco.
When wine was an affordable beverage to have with a meal, not a
$200 trophy in an etched bottle.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of those moments when, if we're lucky, we stumble
across real serenity, and we wrap it around ourselves and hold it
dear. Because its time must be short.
</P>
<P>
   Soon my friends will return, and I'll be glad to see them. Be
happy to share in their tangible tales of golf victories and
defeats.
</P>
<P>
   But I'll have little to say. How can I share my little secret _
that a morning as pure and priceless as anyone could want has just
been handed to me? And that I have quietly exulted in it. The
snapshot of that morning will go into my memory scrapbook, to be
recalled with quiet pleasure when the pace of life back home gets
too fast, too frenetic.
</P>
<P>
   Remember in ``Casablanca'' when Rick tells Ilsa, ``We'll always
have Paris''? Well, I'll always have that morning, with its tingly,
dry breeze and warm sun, the picture-perfect view _ and the gift,
however brief, of peace.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it's a shame that Stags' Leap isn't open to the
public. Something that beautiful should be shared. But since it
isn't, my suggestion is this: If you want to visit Napa and want to
get a real feel for the place, try to find lodging in _ or beside _
a vineyard; it's not hard to do. And forget about home for a while
and sit outside, or take a walk at sunset or sunrise, and feel the
breeze and admire the beauty of the earth.
</P>
<P>
   And listen to the vines. And when you really listen, and hear
them speak to you and only you, you'll know the next time you open
a bottle of fine wine that more goes into it than grapes and a
little sweat. I think it's called romance.
</P>
<P>
   And speaking of wine: May I suggest the 1995 Stags' Leap Petite
Syrah? Somehow it seems appropriate.
</P>
<P>
   And that's the truth _ straight, no chaser.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can send e-mail correspondence to: michael.lonsford at
chron.com &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
