<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-NOVA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLVING THE PUZZLE OF LONGITUTE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRUCE MCCABE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Longitude lunatics.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how the 18th-century English painter William Hogarth
depicted his contemporaries who sought to solve the riddle of
longitude, or east-west position on the earth's mapping grid.
</P>
<P>
   You can see Hogarth's vivid representation of these ``lunatics''
_ and enjoy an engrossing story _ on ``Nova'' episode, ``Lost at
Sea: The Search for Longitude,'' which also launches the estimable
series's 25th season this week on PBS. It's based on the
best-selling book ``Longitude,'' by Dava Sobel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lost,'' narrated by Richard Dreyfuss, shows Britain's top
scientists, admirals, and members of Parliament as they grapple
furiously in a determined, sometimes wacky quest to rule the seas
by keeping their ships from getting lost. The government offered a
prize of 20,000 pounds (millions of dollars today) to the person
who could solve the intractable problem of navigation.
</P>
<P>
   The unlikely hero of the story is John Harrison, played by
British actor Patrick Malahide, a young, obsessive, determined,
self-taught rural English clockmaker who turned out to be, as one
observer put it, ``150 years ahead of his time.'' Derided as a
``joiner's son from Lincolnshire,'' he'd never been to sea. Yet in
spite of the efforts to ignore him and his work, he was the driving
spirit in the understanding of longitude. To our good fortune,
Harrison kept a fascinating account of his relentless 43-year
struggle to surmount the myopia of the British establishment. The
powers that be focused stubbornly and solely on astronomy as the
key to the puzzle (one proposal required 30 warships in a row
successively firing ``sky rockets''). They derided the importance
of the accurate measurement of time, which turned out to be
essential.
</P>
<P>
   The efforts continued despite failure and discouragement. In
France, Louis XIV complained that he'd lost ``more territory to
astronomers than to my enemies'' when they measured the French
coast for him. The most resonant images show Harrison's meticulous
experiments. They include his devising of a large, intricate clock
in 1722 that still functions today. We see the inspired Harrison
standing excitedly in a doorway while listening to clocks in
adjoining rooms simultaneously to help him calibrate time and
temperature.
</P>
<P>
   The climax of ``Lost'' is set on the tropical island of
Barbados, where the plot thickens. Ultimately, King George III, to
whom Harrison and his son wrote in supplication, must decide where
the prize money will go. The ending proves that, in the words of
the narrator, ``knowing where you are is knowing what time it is.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1406EDT &QL; 
