<SLUG> BC-STONEWALL-THEATER-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REALITY SHIFTS IN `STONEWALL' AS PLAY EXAMINES HISTORICAL, MODERN
PERCEPTIONS OF RACE RELATIONS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By EVERETT EVANS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Stonewall Jackson's House'' takes playgoers on a tour through
the minefield of race relations, historical perceptions and
political correctness. In Jonathan Reynolds' acclaimed off-Broadway
play, making its Houston debut at Main Street Theater, it's a trip
full of unexpected detours, ingenious surprises and provocative
insights.
</P>
<P>
   The play begins in the manner of a brightly sardonic cartoon. A
perky young African-American tour guide, dressed in Civil War-era
costume, is leading a group through the historic home of the
legendary Confederate general. She recites her spiel like a
mechanical doll, pausing to answer questions from two couples: a
genial, middle-age pair from Ohio, and two outspoken Alabama
``rednecks.'' The latter, history buffs, know far more about
Jackson than the guide and are obsessively concerned with the
authenticity of the house's furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   At intervals, the group freezes while LaWanda (the guide)
reveals her true feelings: her life is a wreck, she hates her
dead-end job and she can barely tolerate the patrons' inane
questions about Civil War arcana.
</P>
<P>
   The play then shows LaWanda's fantasy of the Civil War era, with
herself as a grateful slave and the innocuous middle-age couple as
her benevolent masters. When she re-awakens to the tour and her
miserable reality, LaWanda shocks the Goshens (the older couple) by
proposing that she return with them to Ohio as their property, in
``uncruel but abject'' slavery. She looks forward to never having
to make another decision (``I'll never have to choose an HMO'') and
having her owners take all responsibility for her life.
</P>
<P>
   The play's reality shifts again. The characters are revealed as
the actors and staff of an off-Broadway company trying to decide
whether to include ``Stonewall Jackson's House'' in an upcoming
festival of one-act plays. Tracy, who has been playing LaWanda, is
the theater's literary manager, who argues that any play about a
black woman who yearns to retreat into slavery is racist and should
be dropped. The man who has been playing the redneck husband is Joe
Rock, the play's author; he argues in its defense. The genial older
couple turn out to be Oz and Gaby, husband-and-wife directors of
the company and Tracy's professional mentors.
</P>
<P>
   As the group discusses the play's point and purpose, ``Stonewall
Jackson's House'' becomes a forum on history, race, political
correctness and artistic principles. ``It's about the need for the
welfare state,'' one character insists, while another argues the
play ``can't be racist because the rednecks also want to be
slaves.''
</P>
<P>
   The situation evolves into a metaphor for another kind of
freedom vs. slavery. Can artists remain free to follow their
vision? Or must they always enslave themselves by compromising with
some funding source or power structure, just to make their art
happen?
</P>
<P>
   Particularly in its brisk first act, Reynolds' play is full of
fresh ideas and sardonic riffs on history, as well as current
attitudes. There is a witty paraphrase of the famous joke asking
Mrs. Lincoln's reaction to ``Our American Cousin''; in this case,
the line comes out as ``Aside from the racism, how did you like the
play?''
</P>
<P>
   The second act does not quite sustain the promise of the first.
The theater staff's debate, for all its clever references and
theatrical in-jokes, goes on too long and grows repetitive. One
misses the frequent shifts and surprises of the first act, though
Reynolds does have some ironic turns reserved for the play's
slightly overdue conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   Director Charlene Hudgins does well maintaining the sly satiric
tone, especially in the often giddy fantasy of the first act _ even
if she cannot quite disguise the static quality of the second act's
long debate.
</P>
<P>
   Cheray D. Martin plays LaWanda, and later Tracy, with
intelligence and energy. Veering from eager-to-please ebullience to
exasperation and desperation, she gives the production a strong
center.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Menzel, formerly director and star of Houston's Comedy
Workshop troupe, is ideal as the avuncular tourist from Ohio and as
the waffling company director Oz. As his partner, Ellen Suits makes
an ever-beaming Ohio wife, then a prickly spouse and bossy
co-director.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph E. Hudson is amusingly loutish yet shrewd as Junior
Nuckolls, the redneck Confederacy expert; he later doubles as the
playwright nursing his wounded pride. Brooke Baumer is brash and
broad as the redneck wife Mag, more restrained in her second role
as the sophisticated Claire, the Brit scheming to usurp Tracy's
place as Oz and Gaby's successor to direct the company.
</P>
<P>
   Though it runs out of steam for part of its second act,
``Stonewall Jackson's House'' boasts the kind of invention and
outrageousness one would like to encounter more often. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1408EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 14:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4050 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNDS-QUARTER-BOS &LR;      10-07 1665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-QUARTER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUTUAL FUNDS: DOWN THE DRAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNNLEY BROWNING  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; BOSTON _ How the mighty &UR;  &LR; have fallen. Shackled with the worst
quarterly losses since Wall Street's spectacular run began eight
years ago, mutual fund shareholders and portfolio managers have
gone from record market highs to nightmarish losses in the bat of
an eyelash.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks, throughout the 1990s the investment of choice, now seem
as appetizing as the Plague _ especially after the average US stock
fund lost 15 percent in the third quarter, a period that included
Wall Street's all-time high. So far in 1998, gains have pulled a
disappearing act, socking most investors with year-to-date losses
for the first time this decade.
</P>
<P>
   So why are strategists so divided over whether the market
correction is conjuring up the ghost of bear markets past? Why
haven't investors run screaming for the exits? And why do mutual
funds still appear to be a good bet, despite the fact that many
fund managers compounded the third-quarter pain by losing even more
than the broader market?
</P>
<P>
   The answers lie both in the particularities of the US stock
market's downturn, which strangely comes amid a generally strong
domestic economy, and in new evidence of how American investors
have acted during the worst market volatility in 60 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very unique bear market _ in fact, we still can't
call it a bear market,'' said Larry Horwitz, managing director of
Primark Decision Economics in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   One doesn't often find a depressed stock market in an economy
lacking reams of bad news. With low inflation and unemployment,
good growth, and strong consumer spending, the US economy has
largely escaped the global financial crisis that began in Asia.
Still, an increasing number of economists see potential signs of
strain; to keep things humming, the Fed cut interest rates last
week, a move that may boost stocks.
</P>
<P>
   A bear stock market is technically defined as broad losses of 20
percent or more relative to highs. By such criteria, last quarter's
10.3 percent drop in the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index, the widest
measure of the US market, puts a volatile Wall Street in a
correction, the bear's milder cousin. While a rollercoaster
September did much to buffer losses, the index is down 10.4 percent
through last Friday from its July 17 peak.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as many investors will see when they open their next
statements, many mutual funds lost far more than 10 percent for the
quarter ended Sept. 30; those that invest in small-company and
mid-sized stocks declined an average 19.8 percent, according to
Lipper Analytical Services, the fund tracker that computes returns.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the only investment objectives with gains last quarter
were gold funds, which rose 4.3 percent, and domestic long-term
bond funds, up 1.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Even more pointed is the difference in performance between the
popular, unmanaged funds that mirror the composition and returns of
the S&AMP;P 500, and actively-managed funds that invest in those same
blue-chip, large-company stocks but hold others as well. S&AMP;P 500
index funds lost 10 percent in the quarter. By contrast, growth
funds, which buy a wider range of stocks, had far more outsized
losses of 13.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When one considers that the average New York Stock Exchange
issue is now 40 percent below its high earlier this year, according
to William Markos of Ipswich Capital Managment, Wall Street looks
even more in the bear cave.
</P>
<P>
   Most fund managers have lagged their benchmarks in recent years.
But the disparity became greater last quarter _ sometimes by as
much as three or so percentage points _ as an increasingly narrower
range of stocks showed gains. The further a fund manager bought
stocks outside the S&AMP;P 500 or in ratios dissimilar to the makeup of
that index, the greater the losses. Factor in fees and expenses for
actively-managed funds, and the red ink is even brighter.
</P>
<P>
   In a world flirting with a downturn, there was no refuge abroad.
Europe, whose stock markets were flying high earlier this year, is
in the doldrums; European region funds were down 17.3 percent last
quarter. Funds invested in Latin America were an investor's idea of
hell, sinking 29.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are bear market funds, which rise when markets
fall but slip when stocks swell. Such funds lost out during the
eight-year bull market but reaped gains in the last quarter. The
Prudent Bear fund rose 21.9 percent, the industry's best performer.
</P>
<P>
   But with the vast majority of actively-managed funds now showing
losses for the year, the rhetoric of performance has shifted. The
only broad diversified equity funds with gains for 1998 are S&AMP;P 500
index funds, ``passive'' funds that involve no stock picking. They
are up 5.6 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Most money managers are now concerned about return of principle,
rather than return on principle.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's 10 or 20 names that are doing all the work for the
market,'' said Thomas O'Neill, Fleet Financial Group Inc.'s chief
equity strategist. ``It's hard to find good stocks. The best stock
pickers I know are having the worst time right now.'' Against this
backdrop, portfolio managers might be forgiven for feeling trapped
inside a horror house.
</P>
<P>
   As the unwinding of hedge fund losses threatens to wreak more
global economic havoc, debt markets shudder at Russia's lurch
toward the title of world's biggest defaulter, and US companies
issue profits warnings, fund managers face plenty of traumas not of
their own handiwork. After betting big on stocks, especially on the
big stocks that until recently had produced all the gains, money
managers have little leeway these days to do anything except ride
out the downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Big equity funds, and even more conservative growth and income
funds, which invest in bonds as well as stocks, aren't about to
make a major shift into bonds, even if those markets do pick up.
That is because most large mutual funds are in long-term corporate
retirement plans, whose investment strategies are basically
engraved in stone and whose owners frown on change.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, large funds can generally buy only the most liquid,
biggest stocks. That worked well in recent years, when
large-company stocks were in favor. But many of the Nifty 50 once
deemed sure-fire earners in any climate have fallen off their
pedestals, issuing profit warnings as Asia's downturn spreads.
Gillete, for example, said last week third-quarter profits would
drop 20 percent on lower sales in Russia and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Still, nine of the 10 largest stock funds lost less than their
investment objective averages last quarter _ a relatively
impressive performance that suggests their bets on the biggest
stocks helped buffer losses. For example, Fidelity Investment's
$62.3 billion Magellan, the world's biggest fund, slipped 11
percent, nearly 3.5 percent better than the average growth fund.
More impressively, the fund is up nearly 6 percent for the year,
compared to the average growth fund's 0.2 percent loss.
</P>
<P>
   Had Tolstoy been thinking about mutual funds, not the Russian
aristocracy, in his famous opening to ``Anna Karenina,'' he might
have swapped the concept `family' for `fund' and written, ``All
funds are unhappy, but each is unhappy in its own individual way.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, not all of the third-quarter carnage is alike.
</P>
<P>
   Case in point is the $41.7 billion Washington Mutual Investment
fund, the biggest stock and bond fund around. It lost 7 percent
last quarter, over five percentage points less than the average
growth and income fund, and has positive year-to-date returns of
4.8 percent. By contrast, the troubled $16.3 billion Vanguard
Windsor fund, also a growth and income fund, lost 19.5 percent last
quarter, and is down 11.2 percent so far this year.
</P>
<P>
   Amid all the gloom, what have investors done? Many have put new
money into more conservative money market and bond funds. In
August, when the market was at one point 20 percent below its July
17 high, investors yanked $11.2 billion out of stock funds, the
most ever and the first monthly outflow in eight years. Still, that
sum represents only five out of every $1,000 invested in equity
funds, and less than half a percent of the fund industry's total
assets, which now stand at $4.7 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The confidence of the investor in the mutual fund concept
remains constant,'' said Avi Nachmany, an analyst at Strategic
Insight in New York, a fund consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   Nachmany thought it unlikely investors would exit stocks and
plow full scale into bonds, since the long-term gains from stocks _
about 10 to 12 percent a year, on average _ are historically
greater. Still, new money is increasingly favoring fixed-income
funds. Bond fund sales over the first nine months of this year are
up 387 percent to $51.36 billion compared to year-ago levels,
according to the Investment Company Institute, the fund industry's
trade group.
</P>
<P>
   All that points to a major shift in investor psychology _ but
not one that involves, at least at this point, a mass exodus from
the stock market. While painful, the third-quarter declines bring
five-year returns in line with historic averages.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the coming months will be crucial. Two and a half months
ago, stock investors were close to bagging a 20 percent-plus annual
gain for an unprecedented fourth straight year. Now they are
staring at a market in which, for the first time in eight years,
bonds are the best bet. And October has a historical precedent for
being volatile.
</P>
<P>
   But the last two bear markets for stocks, in 1987 and 1990, were
brief, lasting only several months.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have now is harsher than a correction,'' said John F.
Ballen, president of Massachusetts Financial Services and an
investment professional often called a stockpicker's stockpicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think it's going to be pretty short-lived.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
