<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BELIEF-IN-HEALTH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTHOR SAYS ILLNESS DOES NOT HAVE TO DEFINE YOUR LIFE 
 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BARBARA KARKABI 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   From the time she was 5, Kim Nelson suffered from painful
rheumatoid arthritis and felt she could never be a vigorous person.
</P>
<P>
   It was a belief that colored her whole life. But during a
four-day therapy workshop led by psychologists Blair and Rita
Justice in the Colorado Rockies, Nelson discovered what a powerful
effect belief has on the body.
</P>
<P>
   She had always thought she had to get rid of her disease to
enjoy life. She believed that her pain and inflamed knee meant it
was impossible to climb a mountain, as the group was assigned to do
on the workshop's last day.
</P>
<P>
   She was more than a little surprised when Justice advised her to
``let her pain sing,'' advice he borrowed from the playwright
Arthur Miller. But as Nelson slowly made her way up the mountain,
she tapped into a sense she never knew she had.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kim's identity shifted from pain and illness to an inner sense
of health and strength,'' Justice writes in his new book. ``She
discovered her health when she connected to a wholeness beyond the
body, to the flowers and mountains, to the group that sang with her
and to a new and deeper sense of being well inside herself.''
</P>
<P>
   An award-winning former science writer and professor of
psychology at the University of Texas-Houston School of Public
Health, Justice has written ``A Different Kind of Health: Finding
Well-Being Despite Illness'' (Peak Press, $22). The book challenges
the traditional notion that being healthy also means being free of
disease, chronic illness or pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was struck by adult health surveys where they ask people
about their health, that they were coming around to the view that
the most powerful question which needs to be asked is: `In general,
what type of health do you think you are in?' '' Justice said. ``Do
you think you are a healthy person, very healthy, sick, very sick?
They were really intrigued to find that even though 50 percent of
the population say that on any given day they had a medical
condition, 80 percent said `I'm a healthy person'. ''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Justice said, there is another kind of health than the
one physicians look for in their examinations. And he does not
believe sick people who say they feel well are in denial:
</P>
<P>
   ``They all acknowledge their illness; it's just a demonstration
that pain and a sense of well-being can exist side-by-side if you
are complete enough in other aspects of your life,'' Justice said.
``If you look at the self, it is made up of physical parts, mental,
emotional, relationships with people and animals. So, if you have
got your life together in these other parts, you can feel at your
core that you are whole _ which is what health is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   A person's view of his own well-being is known as ``subjective
health.'' Objective health confirms the presence or absence of
disease; it is not health as much as the absence of disease, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For the 33 million Americans who suffer from chronic and
recurring illnesses such as cancer and AIDS, the growing belief
that you can be ``sick but well'' should prove to be a lifesaver.
The introduction by Naomi Judd, who was diagnosed with Hepatitis C
in 1990, says that though the book may not save your life, it will
``transform the quality of how you live it, right up to the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Porter Storey, medical director of The Hospice at the Texas
Medical Center believes we definitely need a wider view of what
health is. ``I see many people who are healing old wounds despite
progression of disease,'' he said. ``I am convinced that health has
much more to do with the interaction between our mind, body and
spirit than what the X-rays and lab tests show.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice's personal journey to overcome chronic depression and
deal with his daughter's drug addiction and eventual death, is the
thread that holds ``A Different Kind of Health'' together.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started my first episode of clinical depression in my 20s as
a reporter with the Fort Worth Star Telegram,'' Justice said. ``I
didn't really know what was wrong, and even though I received
treatment, I didn't really lose the gut ache that was part of it.
Then when I got into something more physical, like surgery on a
cluster of basal cell carcinomas on my chest that left a huge hole,
I began to see the strong connection between the mind and body.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice noticed that his wound would be healing fine until he
had a bout of depression about his daughter's battle with drug
addiction or concern about something else. Then the healing would
stop. After his daughter Liz almost died in the intensive care unit
of a New York hospital, Justice realized her death was only a
matter of time, since numerous programs had been unable to help.
</P>
<P>
   He began going to a series of seminars on death and dying. That
led to volunteer work with The Hospice at the Texas Medical Center.
In the '80s he began mountain climbing, which helped him deal with
his depression. His office at UT, where he is also associate dean
for academic affairs, is filled with photographs of beautiful
mountain scenes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never have started to climb without getting caught up in the
beauty,'' Justice said. ``You can just lose yourself in it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the mid '90s, Justice was asked to work on a pilot research
project with a group of women who had just completed treatment for
breast cancer, studying the effects of imagery and support on the
immune system. Many reported health in the presence of disease, he
said and were proof of what he calls Fordyce's Law. Named for
Willard Fordyce, the father of pain research in this country, the
axiom says that people suffer less when they find something to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are happiest when they are outside themselves and not
thinking about themselves,'' Justice said. ``So much of getting out
of the self and not suffering is having a real well-defined goal
that you can come back to.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice listed a number of ways to find subjective health and an
abiding feeling that life is good in spite of illness: perceiving
some value in the experience, letting go of old resentments,
volunteer work, meditation and strong religious connections, as
well as using a freeze-frame technique to deal with stress.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like having a video camera and pushing the pause
button,'' Justice said. ``What they have trained people to do is
when you start feeling angry and really uptight or stressed, just
stop yourself and reflect on something you appreciate in life. It
has a remarkable calming effect and you reduce the stress hormones
that can damage the immune system.''
</P>
<P>
   But there is a difference, Justice said, between being healed
and being cured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Curing is getting rid of something and usually requires some
external intervention,'' Justice said. ``With a chronic illness
that is not going to happen. The definition of healing is making
whole something inside yourself. Whether we live or die, we have to
use that inner health to bring ourselves peace.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
