<SLUG> BC-PAGER-MAIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAGING FIRMS BANK ON THE ABILITY TO TALK BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RONALD ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The wireless pager that delivers a simple phone number is
growing up, becoming a hip-hugging e-mail messenger.
</P>
<P>
   Pagers have been used widely since the 1980s by salespeople,
doctors, electricians, and others who needed to stay in touch while
on the go. But even though more than 50 million people nationwide
now use them, the devices have been overshadowed during most of the
1990s by cellular phones. The paging industry in recent years has
struggled with steep losses, corporate consolidations, and
cut-throat pricing.
</P>
<P>
   But paging companies are trying to battle back with a new
weapon: two-way paging. The technology solves traditional paging's
biggest limitation: one-way communication. With two-way paging,
instead of running to a phone to respond, users can receive and
send messages by tapping on a miniature keyboard _ no need to pick
up the phone.
</P>
<P>
   Two-way pagers, which are about the size of a deck of cards,
also can be used as address books and appointment calendars. They
can provide access to data over the Internet and to news reports
and weather updates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hold the pager in my hands and use my thumbs to tap out a
message like, `I'm in a meeting, will call you back in an hour,'''
said Kenneth Hyers, an industry analyst at Cahners In-Stat Group's
wireless PCS research group. ``This kind of paging capability will
attract certain business users who may be tied to a cellular phone
but want another option _ one where they can communicate quickly
and less intrusively.''
</P>
<P>
   David Gregson, a technical support manager at Ropes &AMP; Gray, the
large Boston law firm, says he responds to more than 20 messages a
day using an alphanumeric keyboard pager from SkyTel Communications
Inc., the leading two-way paging provider based in Jackson, Miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can respond ... far faster with a two-way pager than I could
using a mobile telephone,'' said Gregson. ``In fact, I've reduced
my business cell phone bills from $120 a month to around $40 now.
Plus, people respond to me far faster by electronic mail than they
did by phone, so I get a &UR;  &LR; lot more done.''
</P>
<P>
   For all its promise, however, two-way paging is pricey. The new
pagers _ made by Motorola Inc., Glenayre Technologies Inc. of
Charlotte, N.C., and Research in Motion Ltd., a Canadian company _
can cost from $195 to $360. That's as much as 10 times more than
one-way numerical pagers.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, the monthly service charge starts at 2 1/2 times
the cost of basic paging, with some two-way users spending more
than $35 per month, depending on the volume of messages.  &UR;  &LR; But
unlike cellular phone calls, there are no roaming or toll call
charges.
</P>
<P>
   Still, it's far from a sure bet that two-way paging can revive
the industry. Consumer prices for such service are still high, and
it's unclear how many users of one-way paging will move up. The
industry is looking to Skytel's two-way technology to gauge
customer demand. And the cost and technical complexity of a
nationwide two-way network to relay signals could hamper full
adoption.
</P>
<P>
   In the Boston area, two-way paging service has been catching on
in recent months with the introduction of more compact pagers that
allow users to directly get Internet electronic mail.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  The main providers locally are Skytel, Page Network,
BellSouth, and Arch Communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``The driving force for us and the entire paging industry is
full-text messaging _ the ability to get simple messages and more
complex ones _ like pulling down data off the Internet or the
corporate intranet, no matter where you are,'' said C. Edward
Baker, chief executive of Westborough-based Arch Communications
Group Inc., which is acquiring MobilMedia Corp. of Fort Lee, N.J.,
a deal that will make it the nation's second-largest paging
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years the paging industry has not had a technology that
could add more value for the customer ... We all used the same
one-way paging system and could only grow by cutting prices,'' said
William F. Lenahan, president and chief executive of BellSouth
Wireless Data LP, formerly RAM Mobile Data, which was acquired by
BellSouth Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly forgotten by Wall Street, the leading paging companies
are betting their futures on wireless electronic mail services for
business customers. Motorola, the leading manufacturer of pagers
and developer of two-way paging technology, estimates that 25
million mobile business professionals are away from the office more
than 25 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Several paging companies are offering customers new types of
customized services, including news headlines, stock quotes, travel
information, and sports scores.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, at a recent convention in Tampa on wireless
personal communications, users of two-way paging could obtain the
latest tracking information on Hurricane Georges from the National
Weather Service _ and make a quick getaway before the storm was
expected to hit. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Since not everyone can afford two-way paging, the leading
carriers have each developed lower-priced services known as ``1.5''
paging.
</P>
<P>
   Designed to replace one-way paging, it's aimed at business users
who want the assurance that their their messages were delivered
along with the ability to respond with one or two-word
pre-programmed responses. Skytel offers a service that enables its
1.5-paging customers to scroll through their messages and push a
button to activate up to 15 commands, such as ``yes,'' ``no,''
``thank you, ``on my way,'' and ``will arrive 15 minutes later.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankee Group estimates that the number of people using 1.5
paging services will zoom from nearly 375,000 nationwide this year
to nearly 1.5 million next year and more than 14.3 million by the
end of the 2003.
</P>
<P>
   In yet another fancy wrinkle, a few paging carriers are
promoting voice messaging _ the ability to hear the caller's words
through a pager instead of relying on text. In effect, voice paging
technology serves as a portable answering machine. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   In September Conxus Communications Inc. of Greenville, S.C.,
introduced Pocketalk a Motorola-built pager, in metropolitan
Boston. It can deliver and store up to three minutes of voice
messages or about a dozen 15-second messages. Unlike two-way
paging, however, there is no way of responding except for running
to a phone.
</P>
<P>
   Conxus is looking to reach business and residential customers
with its $49 voice pager and its $19.95-a-month service that offers
unlimited voice messages.
</P>
<P>
   ``With 80 percent of the nation's telephone households having
answering machines, we see a large potential market for a portable
device,'' said Julie K. Greene, vice president of marketing for
Conxus. The company says it has signed up 45,000 customers, mostly
on the East Coast, since it began shipping its units earlier this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Wireless voice messaging, however, has a checkered history. Take
the failure of Voicenow, a service from Dallas-based Paging Network
Inc., the nation's largest paging company. After investing $600
million in Voicenow, &UR;  &LR; the company &UR;  &LR; last year acknowledged &UR;  &LR; that
customers found the pager too large, the service too expensive, and
the geographical range for receiving voice messages too limited.
The company no longer actively promotes Voicenow.
</P>
<P>
   But two-way paging's boldest promise may lie in data more than
voice. Some carriers are developing new two-way services for
industrial use, such as electric or gas meter reading and home
security applications.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Such services could help the industry return to profitability,
achieve high profit margins, and reach customers willing to pay for
additional services in the form of software.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will still be company consolidations, but if we as an
industry are as successful with two-way paging as we think in
getting higher revenues and more growth, Wall Street will notice,''
said N. Ross Buckenham, president of Dallas-based Pagemart Wireless
Inc.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
