<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCHUMER ATTACKS D'AMATO'S ENVIRONMENTAL INITIATIVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES M. ODATO  
 c.1998 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ The Sierra Club and Rep. Charles Schumer slammed
the environmental record of Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, who is
promoting an acid rain reduction bill aimed at cutting pollution in
the Northeast.
</P>
<P>
   Both the Sierra Club and Schumer, a Democrat who is challenging
D'Amato in the race for U.S. Senate, said Tuesday that D'Amato's
election-year gimmickry can't mask his career of anti-environment
votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a classic case of election-year environmentalism,''
said Kathryn Hohmann of the Sierra Club.
</P>
<P>
   John Stouffer, legislative director of the club's Atlantic
Chapter, added that the acid rain bill sponsored by D'Amato and
Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., isn't as far-reaching as
necessary to control air pollution. Further, he said the bill did
not have a chance of passage during this congressional session _
meaning D'Amato could ignore it if he is re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato testified during a Senate hearing Tuesday that he wants
cleaner emissions from smoke stacks in Midwestern states, the
``airborne terrorism that must be stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   D'Amato said his bill would lead to substantial reductions in
pollutants from coal-burning plants nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Stouffer said the positive sign from D'Amato can't wipe out
nearly two decades of bad votes by the Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Other environmental groups testified at the Senate hearing
supporting the proposed legislation, including The Adirondack
Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``We praise the efforts of Senators Moynihan and D'Amato on this
issue,'' said Timothy Burke, leader of the 18,000-member council.
</P>
<P>
   A D'Amato spokesman said Schumer is trying to politicize an
issue important to upstate New York. She also defended D'Amato's
environmental record, which includes working to increase the number
of buses with cleaner emissions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, D'Amato's campaign released another ad about Schumer,
based on votes as long ago as 1975 when Schumer was a young state
Assemblyman. The ads suggest Schumer is no friend of upstate New
York.
</P>
<P>
   The ads depict the Brooklyn Democrat as a proponent of high
taxes while working to move education dollars to downstate schools
and blocking funds for upstate commuter air service.
</P>
<P>
   Schumer's campaign released the first positive ad of the general
election and shot down D'Amato's points as misleading.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, the ads say Schumer has worked to cut air fares
upstate, to improve federal education spending, and he never voted
in favor of statewide property taxes but rather a measure to allow
local communities to raise taxes to pay for education.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1409EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
