<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0150 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 14:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4058 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FUNDS-WORLD-BOS &LR;      10-07 1465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FUNDS-WORLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS THE ECONOMIC WORLD TURNS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KIMBERLY BLANTON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The world's emerging economies were slammed once again
in the July through September quarter, causing their stock markets
to lose half their value during the past year. Russia has lost
nearly all of its market value.
</P>
<P>
   Investors who ventured into faraway markets have learned, too
late, that it would've been best to keep their money at home.
Russia's bear market was let loose on a vulnerable world this fall,
and the financial damage spread to Europe and then Latin America.
Brazil's economy, just months ago the robust heart of Latin
America, is unstable. In a footnote to Asia's collapse a year ago,
Indonesia and Malaysia have been virtually closed off to Western
investors.
</P>
<P>
   These once-booming markets will surely recover. Cycles are the
law of capitalism, to which many of these ravaged countries still
aspire. But even experts are hard-pressed to divine when recovery
will come. It may be too early to predict, because it is unclear
whether the worst is over.
</P>
<P>
   How long will recovery take?
</P>
<P>
   ``A long time,'' said Nancy Kimelman, chief economist for
Thomson Global Markets, a Boston research firm. ``Did I say long? I
meant long.''
</P>
<P>
   Kimelman does not predict recovery before the year 2000: ``In
Asia, the improvements in the standard of living that took 20 or 30
years to build were erased in a year. That shows the depth and
magnitude of the contraction. It will be difficult for these
economies to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The International Monetary Fund, in its semiannual report,
sharply reduced its forecast of world growth for 1998. The IMF,
which in May said world growth would be 3.1 percent this year,
trimmed its forecast to 2 percent. That compares with world growth
rates of 4.1 percent in both 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main reason for this,'' explained the IMF's chief
economist, Michael Mussa, ``is the downturn in Asia, including
Japan, which has turned out to be significantly deeper and more
widespread than was anticipated'' five months ago.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF's report may be optimistic: some economists fear
worldwide recession is unfolding. US job growth is slowing.
</P>
<P>
   The developing world's trouble in the latest quarter was
centered in Russia, and spread to Latin America as investors grew
nervous about all developing countries' prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's stock market, which had the &UR;  &LR; biggest gain of any
emerging stock market in 1997, lost about 90 percent amid
devaluation of the ruble and a near-collapse of the country's
economic infrastructure. The two worst performing funds in the
third quarter were Lexington Troika Russia, down 64.89 percent, and
Vontobel's Eastern European fund, down 40.48 percent, according to
Lipper Analytical Services Inc.'s quarterly report on mutual fund
returns.
</P>
<P>
   Diversified emerging markets funds, which may hold Russian
stocks, fell 23.57 percent in the quarter and 46.46 percent for the
year &UR;  &LR; ended Sept. 30.
</P>
<P>
   Although Russia looms large politically, its economy is not as
important to the developed world as that of Latin America.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil is the primary concern of international economists. The
country, adhering firmly to its stable-currency stance, doubled
interest rates in September to slow the outflow of capital. The
government is now grappling with how to pay debts coming due as the
economy softens. If Brazil unravels, it could take a major trading
partner, Argentina, with it.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America-invested funds, which are half a world away from
Russia yet were shaken by that country's instability, plunged 29.4
percent in the quarter ended Sept. 30, Lipper reported. The funds
are down 50.2 percent in the past year.
</P>
<P>
   In Asia, a weak Japanese economy and teetering banking system
continued to sap nearby economies that do business with Japan or
borrow from its banks. For the quarter, Lipper reported
Japan-invested funds were down 9.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Single-digit losses in Asian markets in the recent quarter came
on top of huge declines in the prior period. China-based funds
declined 8.5 percent in the recent quarter. Funds invested in
Southeast Asia, excluding Japan, declined 6.6 percent. (Fund
performance is calculated in dollar terms.)
</P>
<P>
   ``With each month, the situation seems to have gotten worse and
each country has gotten sucked in,'' said Pierre Ellis, a managing
director in the New York office of Primark Decision Economics.
``It's very precarious. A lot of the world is already in great
difficulty. The rest is tied to the part of the world that is in
great difficulty.''
</P>
<P>
   US markets took their first real hit from a downturn that had
been contained in the developing world. US stock mutual funds
tracked by Lipper fell 15 percent in the third quarter, and there
is talk that a recession could follow.
</P>
<P>
   Although European economies have held up, stock markets were hit
hard just as the continent prepares for monetary union. Countries
such as Spain, a huge participant in Brazil's economy through its
banks, and Germany, which has ties to Russia, were punished by the
global meltdown. European funds fell 17.3 percent, but did not wipe
out gains posted over the past year.
</P>
<P>
   In predicting the turnaround time for emerging markets,
economists said the problems are more intractable than the currency
crises caused by the 1994 devaluation of Mexico's peso. The peso's
decline made exports more attractive on world markets and pulled
Mexico out of its slump in about 18 months. Although other Latin
American currencies fell, the crisis did not spread to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``1994-95 had been preceded by several years of easy Fed policy.
They had supplied a lot of liquidity to us and to the world,''
Primark's Ellis said. ``But it was not the global slowdown that
seems to be happening now.''
</P>
<P>
   Confirming the Federal Reserve Board's concerns about the
breadth of the world's problem, chairman Alan Greenspan last week
reduced interest rates by a quarter point to improve liquidity not
just in this country but worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   But Daniel Peirce, head of emerging markets research for
BankBoston Corp., which operates in Brazil, sees plenty of
underlying strength in Latin America. Mexico and Argentina are
expected to grow more than 4 percent this year, while Brazil should
grow 1 percent; only Venezuela's economy will decline.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that it is difficult to have economic growth when
short-term interest rates in Mexico and Brazil are above 30
percent, Peirce believes long-term prospects are good because of
the huge progress in structural reforms of their economies and in
curbing corruption.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there's all this market turmoil, they're still
moving on a very steady path of sound policies, sound monetary
policies, and sound fiscal policies,'' he said. ``You've got some
real live, breathing, genuine institutions'' in the region.
</P>
<P>
   As investors tote their second-quarter losses in the southern
hemisphere, Edward Bozaan, &UR;  &LR; president of Waterford Partners, a
boutique firm in New York that invests in emerging markets only
after they decline, is scouring the world for bargains. South
Korea's market is showing some benefits from concerted attempts at
bank reform. Thailand has rallied.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mood has definitely shifted, and we're hearing a lot of
fund managers starting to aggressively buy Thailand since they
can't buy Malaysia and they think Singapore is still going to
fall,'' Bozaan said.
</P>
<P>
   But professional investors and economists are crossing their
fingers.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we focus just on Asia and hold that the world economy is
not going to fall off a cliff, there's a tenable macro (economic
argument) that says Asia could get out of its own way,'' said
Thomas Haslett, chief of emerging markets investment for
Boston-based Putnam Investments.
</P>
<P>
   Haslett avoided making near-term forecasts. ``I'm not saying
they're going to turn around on a dime. Every indication is
deflationary forces are at work,'' he said. ``But if you take a
medium-term view _ two or three years _ values have been created
through this meltdown.''
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, the dire condition of the world's second-biggest economy,
Japan, is key to recovery in Southeast Asia. This region's
fortunes, in turn, are key to the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese lawmakers in recent days agreed to steps to deal with a
banking crisis in reaction to criticism the country has papered
over the problems for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do manage to reform their banking system, put more
fiscal stimulus in the pipeline, and stimulate monetary policy,
there is the prospect of an upturn next year,'' said Salomon Smith
Barney emerging markets strategist Brian Gendreau.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' Gendreau added, ``that's a lot of `ifs'.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
