<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4060 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MILAN-FASHION-HNS &LR;      10-07 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MILAN-FASHION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
READY-TO-WEAR LINES EXCEL IN POCKETING FANS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  with art 
 
By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c. 1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MILAN, Italy _ The women's wear collections that usually are
most closely aligned with U.S. styles got under way this week with
wide swings of the fashion pendulum, from ultra-feminine to
ultra-utilitarian.
</P>
<P>
   Italian fashion generally mirrors styles American women choose,
including fine tailoring for career and sportswear and feminine
styles for evening and special-occasion dressing.
</P>
<P>
   The earliest Italian ready-to-wear collections for spring 1999,
however _ mostly designer secondary lines _ ranged from milkmaid
innocence to surfer chic to the blatantly sexual.
</P>
<P>
   Trends on runways have so far left audiences underwhelmed. Other
news, however, has left them breathless.
</P>
<P>
   Will Italian designers follow through with plans to show earlier
than U.S. designers next fall? Italian spring fashions could take
to the runways sometime around Labor Day, when women are still
wearing their spring and summer clothes.
</P>
<P>
   In today's shaky worldwide economy, will young or small design
houses be able to compete with giant fashion houses such as Calvin
Klein or Ralph Lauren? Will they even be able to survive? Fashion
followers in Milan expressed shock over the announced closing of
U.S. designer Isaac Mizrahi's business.
</P>
<P>
   One young line that appears to be doing just fine, grazie, is
Miu Miu, Prada's secondary line. For spring, designs revolve around
practical pouches and vests. And why shouldn't they? Prada is,
after all, a house whose recent phenomenal success has been
bankrolled by sales of industrial-strength accessories.
</P>
<P>
   For spring, a Miu Miu sleeveless vest, belted low on the chest,
can be removed and worn folded over the belt at the back waist in
the manner women have been tying sweaters about their waists. Other
pouches resembled zippered envelopes worn on wide belts that
resemble seatbelts.
</P>
<P>
   Colors fall into khaki and earth tones with lots of mossy green
and brown, with fabrics from crisp poplin shirting to buttery-soft
suede. Fabric ``shirts,'' zipped in front and with the look of
surfer Neoprene, top even the evening wear.
</P>
<P>
   Feminine touches on Miu Miu's utilitarian styles include ruffle
and tablecloth-fringe edging, short shorts and skinny walk shorts.
</P>
<P>
   D&AMP;G, another hip secondary line, took a detour from strictly
club clothes, albeit with some stretch-satin corset dresses, silver
and gold metallics, and tight black cire numbers that are now
considered almost classics in the line.
</P>
<P>
   Designed by Domenico Dolce and Stefano Gabbana of Dolce &AMP;
Gabbana fame, D&AMP;G also includes sporty options of acid bright
stripes, cargo pants and pouch belts. Tops still run small over
straight-legged pants but are topped with hold-everything envelope
pouches for spring. These are designed to be worn bandoleer-style
(over one shoulder and under the opposite arm), an alternative to
the safety-minded practice of wearing backpacks as chest packs.
</P>
<P>
   One imagines a milking stool as an accessory to the innocent
cotton dresses of Philosophy di Alberta Ferretti. The secondary
line plays not only to a young client but also, for spring at
least, to anyone who covets crisp, cool and comfortable cottons.
</P>
<P>
   In bright white, khaki, black, brown and blue, cottons feature
oodles of pleats, tucks and ties and often run to ankle-length.
Cover-ups are the simplest of zippered leather jackets, and there
are nontraditional color schemes _ robin's-egg blue with brown, for
example.
</P>
<P>
   For evening, Ferretti chose duo-colored pinstripes on a white
background, often beading the stripes and adding sweater cover-ups.
The summer ballgown is black with a long quilted coat to top a long
sleeveless dress.
</P>
<P>
   At the opposite end of the fashion scale are Donatella Versace's
designs for Versus. With tops slit down the front from collarbone
to navel and beyond, or breasts bared by see-through striped knits,
these were beach or club clothes for ``la dolce vita.''
</P>
<P>
   The Versus show was staged in an abandoned warehouse in the
city's seedy Porta Genova area. Models stalked a runway created by
a purple liquid that oozed underfoot like globs in a Lava Lamp.
Thank heaven for the sleek, white, matte leather jackets that serve
as cover-ups for the sheers and Venetian-blind knits.
</P>
<P>
   Romeo Gigli, in his second season with new financial backers,
staged a return to the romantic looks that he does best.
</P>
<P>
   While he did incorporate plastic and net, he brought back his
signature shapes, such as the cocoon jacket that sparked a
long-lived trend in the '80s. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
