<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PROTEST _ MOSCOW _ Long-suffering Russians took to the
streets Wednesday amid the country's economic crisis in nationwide
protests full of anguish, but not anger. Thousands called for the
resignation of President Boris Yeltsin in the restrained and
peaceful marches. But their numbers did not match the expectations
of Communist Party and labor union leaders, who had predicted that
tens of millions would rally. The reason is plain, said a TV news
director in Vladivostok: No one believes in Yeltsin, but few
Russians believe in the opposition either. ``People understand the
uselessness of these actions. The union leaders and Communists are
left over from the Soviet period. That's why they couldn't get
their people out. People don't believe in such demonstrations.''
(Holmes, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   JOURNAL-BARBADOS _ Barbados _ Compared to the rest of the
Caribbean, where a 9 a.m. appointment rarely begins before 10,
Barbados is the model of efficiency. The literacy rate of 97
percent is the region's highest, while murders are nearly
non-existent. Barbadians say their success is rooted in two places:
church and school. Here, in a country of 260,000, there are more
churches than days of the year. Schoolchildren even begin and end
their days with a prayer. Girls can't wear short skirts, while
disobedient boys are paddled. (Emling, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGE-COST _ WASHINGTON _ The College Board issues a report on
the ``Cost of College'' that includes expanded information from
schools regarding the nature of cost increases. (Monroe, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATION
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-SHOOTING _ A gun brought to an elementary school in
Jonesboro, Ga., Wednesday went off accidentally. There were no
injuries. (Elberton, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   VOTERS _ In 1992 Ohio voters wanted change and they went to the
polls in the greatest numbers of the last 20 years. In that year
Ohio was a key state in Bill Clinton's winning the presidency. But
since then voter participation has dwindled, especially in
non-presidential election years. With Clinton mired in scandal,
some experts fear that the number of people who choose to vote this
year will be the lowest ever. That spells trouble for the
Democratic Party and perhaps for our form of government as well.
``What we are witnessing is a progressive meltdown in civic
engagement, a major danger to American democracy,'' said Curtis
Gans, director of the Committee for the Study of the American
Electorate, a not-for-profit public policy center. (Dempsey, Dayton
Daily News). 20. WITH GRAPHICS
</P>
<P>
   NOBLES-EXECUTION _ Jonathan Nobles is scheduled to die at 6 p.m.
for the 1986 stabbing deaths of two Austin women. He has gained
fame while on death row by trying to become the first condemned man
in Texas to donate organs to strangers. (Quiin, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-PRISON-GANGS _ Texas prison officials are looking to
implement new gang-renouncement programs to get convicts out of
gangs while they are in prison. Reaction to the gang problem we
have been writing about. (Ward, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   REFORMED-GANGMEMBER _ Austin residents will get an opportunity
next week to hear a former hitman for the Mexican Mafia prison
gang. Up close. Art Blajos, who was a member of the gang and spent
17 years in California prisons, speaks at two Austin churches.
(Ward, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-BLANCA-PROTEST _ A delegation of Mexican officials
visited Austin on Wednesday to urge the Bush administration and
lawmakers to block a proposed disposal site for radioactive waste.
The West Texas site would be about 18 miles from the Rio Grande, a
major water source and the U.S.-Mexico border. HAURWITZ.(Haurwitz,
Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
