<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDUCATIONAL-DIVERSITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVEY SHOWS CALIFORNIANS SUPPORT DIVERSITY IN EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By VENISE WAGNER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A new survey indicates that Californians support
the notion of diversity in higher education and multicultural
educational programs, despite voter approval for the state's
anti-affirmative action initiative two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, released Tuesday by the Association of American
Colleges and Universities, found that 81 percent of those polled
believed universities and colleges should offer courses that help
students understand bigotry and its historical and contemporary
implications on U.S. society.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, sponsored by the Ford Foundation, polled 200
registered voters between July 14 and Aug. 4.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco State University President Robert Corrigan, a
member of the Association of American Colleges and Universities,
said the survey results indicate that Californians support
affirmative action even though 54 percent of California voters
approved Proposition 209 in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are comfortable with supporting a diverse student
body,'' Corrigan said. ``People did not understand all the
implications of 209. Their support cannot be construed as an
anti-affirmative action mandate.''
</P>
<P>
   Proposition 209 banned preferences based on race or sex in state
contracting, hiring and admissions to public colleges and
universities.
</P>
<P>
   Corrigan said the survey numbers also indicated overwhelming
support for ethnic studies programs.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 80 percent of those polled agreed that the country's
shifting demographics make diversity education an imperative.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we have done over the last 30 years is we've changed our
understanding of the nature of the past,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Genaro Padilla, vice chancellor at the University of California
at Berkeley and an association member, said scholarship in ethnic
studies had ``widened our thinking about encounters between
different groups. It's deepened our thinking about racial
relations.''
</P>
<P>
   Of those surveyed, 31 percent had household incomes of more than
$60,000. About 46 percent identified themselves as very
conservative to more conservative than liberal. Conversely, 38
percent described themselves as very liberal to more liberal than
conservative.
</P>
<P>
   The results can be projected to voters statewide with a 7.1
percent margin of error, but a 95 percent confidence level, the
authors of the survey said.
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that people like the idea of the college
campuses having ethnically and culturally diverse student bodies.
The survey did not explore the means by which such a goal should be
reached and would be acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the numbers may illuminate Californians' internal
conflict with wanting culturally and ethnically mixed student
populations without having to give anyone ``preferences,'' which
some argue affirmative action does.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if efforts to have a diverse student body have a more
positive or negative effect on students' education, 44 percent of
those surveyed said ``somewhat positive''; 26 percent answered
``very positive''; 20 percent responded ``negative.''
</P>
<P>
   But asked if education that emphasizes differences in cultures
breeds conflict, 46 percent said yes. And while 44 percent agreed
that said diversity in education was added just to make some
students feel included, 44 percent dismissed the notion that
diversity was used as an excuse to admit and graduate students who
otherwise wouldn't make it.
</P>
<P>
   Debra Humphreys, director of programs for the association, said
the results show that people are pragmatic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know society is becoming diverse and that can bring
conflict,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, she said they support diversity programs
in higher education.
</P>
<P>
   ``They recognize the economic importance of this work so it's
not all from an altruistic point of view, that we should all get
along,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1433EDT &QL; 
