<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 14:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4094 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PROTEST-1008-C     10-07 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PROTEST-1008-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A MAJOR, BUT MILD, PROTEST AS ECONOMIC CRISIS PERSISTS
 &HT;    Moving in both the (i) International and (f) Financial
categories.
 &HT;    By CHARLES W. HOLMES 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Long-suffering Russians, buffeted by their nation's
economic crisis, took to the streets Wednesday in nationwide
protests full of anguish, but not anger.
</P>
<P>
   In restrained and peaceful marches across Russia's 11 time
zones, hundreds of thousands called for the resignation of
President Boris Yeltsin and for billions of dollars in overdue
wages to be paid.
</P>
<P>
   But the numbers of protesters did not match the expectations of
Communist Party and labor union leaders, who had predicted as many
as 40 million Russians would demonstrate against declining living
conditions after the ruble crashed and the banking system collapsed
in August.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, thousands of Communist Party loyalists unfurled their
red Soviet-era flags, emblazoned with the hammer and sickle, and
marched to the Kremlin to call for Yeltsin's resignation.
</P>
<P>
   It was a scene repeated in cities and towns across Russia,
maintaining the pressure on the unpopular president who has been
unable to improve the post-Soviet economy.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the ranks of demonstrators came from the aging
die-hards of the Communist Party, students and working-class
Russians. The newly unemployed, especially the tens of thousands of
middle-class Muscovites, did not show up as organizers had hoped.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin, 67, his authority diminished since the crisis erupted
in August, spent what his spokesman called a ``normal working day''
at his office behind the thick Kremlin walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the friend of the financial magnates and the bankers and
bosses. He's their friend, not ours,'' said protester Pavel
Kostayetsky, 58, a Moscow biochemist whose salary equals about $100
a month since the ruble's 60 percent decline in value over the last
two months.
</P>
<P>
   In the Siberian city of Krasnoyarsk, nationalist Alexander
Lebed, the regional governor and a presidential aspirant, also
called for Yeltsin to step down.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today Yeltsin is alone,'' said Lebed. ``People are pushed to
the extreme. Western investors have become fierce and are angry
with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Some protesters carried large photos of Soviet founder Vladimir
Lenin beside Yeltsin, with Yeltsin's face stamped with a large red
X.
</P>
<P>
   Irina Norvelyka, 52, an unemployed trading company manager from
Moscow, participated in her first public demonstration since the
Soviet Union collapsed in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   She lost her job in a similar economic crash in 1994. This time,
her life savings of about $1,600 was frozen in a bank that has
closed its doors. She wonders if she'll ever see it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``There should have been economic reforms, instead there was
theft,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Across Russia, some media estimates put the turnout Wednesday at
nearly 1 million, though the Kremlin said only about 600,000
attended the demonstrations. Thousands of police and interior
ministry troops were deployed to keep order.
</P>
<P>
   A similar day of protests last year drew an estimated 2 million
people.
</P>
<P>
   A television news director in the eastern port of Vladivostok
explained the low turnout: No one believes in Yeltsin, but few
Russians believe in the opposition either after years of political
and economic upheaval, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``People understand the uselessness of these actions. The union
leaders and Communists are left over from the Soviet period. That's
why they couldn't get their people out. People don't believe in
such demonstrations,'' Valery Bakshin, director of TV-Radio
Vladivostok, said in a telephone interview.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party has been forced to temper its antagonism
against the government since endorsing Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov's appointment last month.
</P>
<P>
   Primakov has included Communist officials in his cabinet and
given them a leading role in formulating economic policy, though a
plan to deal with the crisis has yet to be announced.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the economy has not improved.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very simple to blame someone else for our problems, but
we're all to blame,'' said Sergei Chalyeanhe, deputy chairman of
the 152,000-member municipal workers union in Moscow. ``After 70
years of Soviet rule, the country inherited a heavy load of
problems and the government has not been able to improve people's
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
