<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOME-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Home Section stories in sight at this hour from The N.Y. Times
News Service for Thursday, Oct. 8:
</P>
<P>
   BRANDED-FURNITURE (Undated) _ ``Branding'' _ attaching a name or
trademark to a product to give it an aura of value and a sales hook
_ is familiar strategy to fashion, luxury goods and entertainment.
But it is about to hit consumers where they sit. And the pitch has
got an odd new role-call, with famous names from the four corners
of the cultural map, Coca Cola to Greta Garbo and Ernest Hemingway.
By William L. Hamilton.
</P>
<P>
   JERDE-ARHITECTURE (Undated) _ ``Jon Jerde,'' Steve Wynn declared
grandly, ``is the Bernini of our time.'' And, he continued, ``these
are the cathedrals of our time. This is the future of
architecture.'' The ``cathedrals'' touted by Wynn _ a pontiff of
the material world _ are Disneyland, the Mall of America and his
own casino extravaganza, Bellagio, due to open next week in Las
Vegas, Nev. All three are landmarks of the trend for fusing
architecture, commerce and fantasy, of which Jerde is a pioneer. By
Frances Anderton.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   TOY-BALLS (Undated) _ With a Super Bowl victory to his credit at
last, pro quarterback John Elway holds another record, widely
publicized by the OddzOn toy company. He has thrown the finned
Koosh Vortex Mach 110 more than 110 yards. OddzOn began as the
maker of the Koosh ball. Today, as part of toy giant Hasbro, it
belongs to the same family as its distant rival Nerf. Together,
Koosh and Nerf are building better balls - and the guns to fire
them. Both Nerf, the ball of one generation, and Koosh, that of the
next, quickly evolved into other products - hoops for backboards
and bedroom-closet doors, for instance. By Phil Patton.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-PHONE-KIOSKS (Paris) _ Blues in the night. A purple heart
for the lovelorn. Peter Eisenman's new design for a Parisian
telephone kiosk is oddly poignant, coming from an architect noted
for such cold-blooded formal explorations as the Wexner Center for
the Arts in Columbus, Ohio, and that city's convention center, with
its metal roof that undulates like a bed of snakes. Commissioned by
J.C. Decaux, the French firm best known for deluxe sidewalk pay
toilets, the kiosk is one of several prototypes being considered
for placement throughout the city. Designs are also being submitted
by Norman Foster, Jean Nouvel, Charles Gwathmey, Robert A.M. Stern,
James Stewart Polshek, and Tod Williams and Billie Tsien. Decaux
plans to eventually distribute 5,000 of the kiosks, perhaps in a
mix of designs. By Herbert Muschamp.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-CHEAP-FURNITURE (Paris) _ I arrived in Paris with two
suitcases and soon learned how to live among other people's things,
in a rented room decorated with Japanese white paper lanterns and
nondescript plasterboard shelves. By the time I graduated to my own
studio, I had the requisite bed, desk and couch from Ikea, but I
needed everything else. Determined to fill the apartment with
Parisian treasures, I ruled out the notoriously overpriced Left
Bank antique stores and Parisian flea markets like the Marche aux
Puces at Porte de Clignancourt. Instead, I began at the flea
market's poorer cousins, the brocantes, which are less publicized
roving antiques fairs. Like Parisians, most brocantes head south
for the summer, but they are back in full flower for the rentree in
the fall. By Kristin Hohenadel.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-Q&AMP;A (Undated) _ Garden questions answered. By Leslie
Land.
</P>
<P>
   HOME-IMPROVEMENT (Undated) _ The Home Improvement column. By
Edward Lipinski.
</P>
<P>
   (With howto graphic)
</P>
