<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4135 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-U.S.-SPENDING-H     10-07 0471
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-U.S.-SPENDING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENDTHRIFT U.S. DOES BETTER THAN THRIFTY JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BERNARD D. KAPLAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ In the 1970s and '80s, economists wagged an admonishing
finger at Americans for saving too little money and argued that
they should follow the example of the Japanese, who saved far more
than they spent.
</P>
<P>
   The economists claimed that Japan's thriftiness was the key to
the enormous strides that had turned it into America's major
economic challenger. Instead of wasting cash on expensive gadgets
they did not need, the prudent Japanese put their money into bank
deposits and corporate shares, thus bolstering the national economy
as a whole.
</P>
<P>
   The government, meanwhile, helped the process along by making
Japanese consumer goods, including housing, so highly priced that
few people were tempted to spend more than absolutely necessary.
The one big exception was on foreign travel. But that was because
Japanese tourists could get around with less abroad than at home.
</P>
<P>
   Now this theory appears to have been seriously flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Their penchant for not spending enough of what they earn has
driven the Japanese to the wall.
</P>
<P>
   During the past few years, as the Tokyo stock market slumped and
banks crashed, the average Japanese spent even less than
previously. So, of course, the country's domestic economy sank
further into the doldrums.
</P>
<P>
   Now a desperate government has unveiled a proposal to give each
citizen ``gift vouchers'' worth $225 _ provided they're spent
within a specified time. A similar scheme was suggested in
California during the Great Depression of the 1930s, but it failed
to win voter approval. Tokyo's plan offers some idea of how
distraught the Japanese have become.
</P>
<P>
   It also reflects the fact that some of our favorite theories of
recent times have burst at the seams under the shock of the
dramatic reversal in the worldwide economic outlook that is
currently taking place.
</P>
<P>
   Saving may be no guarantee against a slump if, as in Japan, the
practice hinders normal free-market activities. Americans, who
spend while they have the cash, may wind up better off than the
Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the long-held and comforting belief that august
institutions like the International Monetary Fund have done away
with the threat of financial panics has proved to be a chimera. The
IMF showed at its conference with the World Bank in Washington this
week that it has run out of fresh ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Seldom has economics, known as the ``dismal science,'' looked
more dismal and less scientific than it does right now.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton may sincerely think that a few billion more
dollars furnished to the IMF would cushion or even end the crisis.
Good luck to him. But he is wrong.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1457EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
