<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0161 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4164 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EXPLOSIVE-CHILD-ART-B     10-07 1833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EXPLOSIVE-CHILD-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEFUSING THE `EXPLOSIVE CHILD' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating for all needing; moved originally 10/1 in 2 takes)  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALISON BASS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Your tousle-haired 10-year-old has just told you to buzz off
when you tell him _ for the third time _ to turn off the TV and set
the dinner table.
</P>
<P>
   Your first impulse is to swat him. Your second is to banish him
to his room for a week. The last thing you, as a parent, want to do
is empathize with the little brat and talk through the impasse with
him.
</P>
<P>
   Yet that is exactly what child psychologist Ross Greene suggests
you do, if you have a child who is known in the professional
lexicon as difficult or oppositional. What Greene counsels parents
to do is divert such children from even worse behavior (a violent
meltdown), by using empathy, logic, and judiciously applied
compromise. Punishing a child like this for swearing, he says, will
only make matters worse.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's approach to taming what he calls the ``explosive
child'' is a radical departure from the standard strategies for
dealing with disruptive children, and he is the first to admit that
this new approach won't make him popular among many parents or
other mental health professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are parents and teachers who say I'm going to spoil kids
with my approach,'' says Greene, who spells it all out in a
detailed new book called ``The Explosive Child.'' ``After all, it's
the way most of us were raised, with punishment and rewards, and
it's hard to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene is quick to acknowledge that rewards and punishment, when
done properly, are effective with most disruptive children. Such
children, after all, are the majority; specialists estimate that
only between 2 and 16 percent of all children fall into the
category of explosive, and the majority of those are boys. It's
these explosive children for whom the conventional strategies don't
work, Greene argues, and a more nuanced approach is necessary.
</P>
<P>
   Many psychologists would take issue with him.
</P>
<P>
   These children do not know how to express themselves, and ``they
don't learn a lot from talking about their behavior,'' says Thomas
Phelan, a Chicago-area psychologist who has refined the ``1-2-3
Magic'' formula, which involves counting to 3 when children are
misbehaving and giving them an automatic timeout if the count
reaches 3.
</P>
<P>
   Phelan lectures to parents around the country, winning quick
converts to his formula wherever he goes. He has little patience
with mental health professionals like Greene, who attempt a more
complicated approach.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to dig a hole and jump in it, you can discuss
things with these kids,'' says Phelan, who is himself the father of
a hyperactive child. ``But it doesn't work; you need something
where you're drawing the line.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene, of course, has heard this all before _ from skeptical
parents and colleagues at Massachusetts General Hospital, where he
works. So when a reporter also challenges him on his technique,
asking whether it's really such a good idea to compromise on
important issues, such as whether a child should be allowed a
sleep-over on a school night, Greene doesn't even sigh. He smiles
to himself, sits farther back in his chair, and calmly explains his
philosophy one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not giving in, this is parents proposing a problem and
helping a child collaborate on a solution,'' Greene says. ``Look at
this way: What's more important, blind adherence to authority or
resolving conflict?''
</P>
<P>
   Ross Greene is nothing if not persuasive. But beyond those
powers of persuasion and an endearing lack of defensiveness, it is
easy to see why Greene gets along so well with troubled children
and desperate parents: At first glance, he looks like a child
himself, with an elfish grin, a mop of curly dark hair, and warm
brown eyes.
</P>
<P>
   But at age 40, Greene has been working with troubled youths for
almost 20 years, and his experience shows, in the self-assured way
in which he fields critical queries. And it doesn't hurt that by
the time most parents arrive at his office, a tiny and rather
sterile cubicle near the summit of Mass. General's ambulatory care
tower, they are ready to try anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's walking in the door are people who've learned that
teaching the kid who's boss isn't working,'' says Greene, who grew
up in Miami, the well-behaved middle child of parents who did make
clear who was boss. ``They're already so frustrated they're open to
something different.''
</P>
<P>
   Most of these parents, keep in mind, have children who are at
the extreme end of the behavioral spectrum. These are not kids who,
after whining how unfair it is they have to go to bed, will
eventually capitulate in the face of persistent threats. (``You are
going to timeout if you don't get up the stairs this instant.'')
</P>
<P>
   These are children who go from flat resistance to a parental
request _ ``No, I won't!'' _ to an outright meltdown in a matter of
minutes, screaming, cursing, throwing things, even destroying
property and (occasionally) attacking people physically. They don't
melt down all the time, of course, and some of these children may
lose control only with their parents and not in school, but when
they do, it's a horrifying sight.
</P>
<P>
   It's also dangerous, to themselves and to others around them.
Greene says some of the children he has worked with are suicidal,
and a few have threatened to hurt other people. In the most extreme
scenario, a child who shares this profile and is not given the help
he needs could become the next Kip Kinkel, the 15-year-old Oregon
boy who shot his own parents to death and then walked into his
local high school and killed two of his classmates, wounding dozens
of others.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are easily frustrated kids who become antagonistic
toward their parents and other adults, and they can become very
alienated,'' Greene says. ``Alienation expresses itself in many
ways, and it could lead to a kid walking into school and shooting
somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   While most people would look at a teenager like Kinkel and see
an antisocial loser who became violent to get his way, Greene sees
the kind of child who, often because of inherited problems
(attention deficit disorder, learning disability, Tourette's
syndrome) is easily frustrated, has a difficult time shifting
gears, and just doesn't know how to react in a more civilized way.
</P>
<P>
   On Page 30 of his new book, Greene sums up the mindset of these
children in a cartoon showing a dog being directed to sit by his
master. And the dog is thinking, ``I may want to sit. Just give me
a chance to process this.''
</P>
<P>
   If these children are pushed too hard before they can process
the new command, they explode. ``When your child explodes, you
can't talk to him,'' says a Boston educator whose 12-year-old son
suffers from Tourette's syndrome and has been explosive all his
life. ``It's like trying to break up a bar fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Greene makes a distinction between the child who throws a
``coherent'' tantrum _ he stops when he notices his mother isn't in
the room anymore and then starts up again when he finds her _ and
children who throw ``incoherent'' tantrums _ ``they go crazy and
really lose it,'' whether or not the mother is still there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more I worked with these disruptive kids, the more I
became convinced that their oppositional behavior is
unintentional,'' Greene says. ``Parents think the kids are just
doing it to yank their chain; but they usually aren't throwing
tantrums on purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   For the many children who are throwing tantrums on cue, the
standard system of rewards and punishment may indeed be very
effective. A parent who consistently sets limits on misbehavior
through a strategy like 1-2-3 timeout, should be successful in
eradicating tantrums in time, Greene and other psychologists agree.
</P>
<P>
   But for the children Greene sees, the standard strategies have
failed, and that has a lot to do with their brain chemistry. A
unique chemistry explains why medications are often part of the
solution, Greene says: Ritalin for attention deficit disorder,
Prozac for depression, Risperadone or clonadine for Tourette's
syndrome. But in many cases, medication is not sufficient to turn
the tide.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are children whom I couldn't work with, without
medications,'' observes Greene, as a rare cognitive therapist in a
child psychiatry department known to rely on drugs for assistance.
``But medication is frequently not the sole answer to a child's
problems, and in some cases, it isn't meeting their needs at all.''
</P>
<P>
   What Greene does, with the parents he advises and in his book,
is to provide a detailed road map for parents to follow before
their child melts down. If it's time for 9-year-old Sally to get
ready for bed, Greene suggests that instead of demanding that Sally
come inside or face punishment, a parent might stay calm in the
face of deafening resistance and say, ``Whoa, slow down. I don't
really think this is one to get all upset about. I may actually be
willing to compromise about this if you could chill a little.'' And
then the parent could discuss with Sally ways to reach a mutually
satisfactory compromise.
</P>
<P>
   Greene recommends this kind of negotiation in all but
circumstances where the child's safety is at stake. For instance,
parents would decide that some behaviors, such as riding a bike
without a helmet, are never acceptable and thus nonnegotiable. But
with an explosive child, at least initially, all other behaviors,
even ones that most parents cling to, such as getting homework done
by bedtime, should be left open to compromise, in an effort to
avert meltdowns.
</P>
<P>
   When this approach is applied consistently by parents, teachers,
and other adults in the child's world, Greene says he has seen even
the most explosive child learn to temper his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Parents who have worked with Greene agree, with the fervor of
born-agains.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our son is as explosive as ever, but the frequency of his
explosions has diminished considerably,'' says the mother of the
boy with Tourette's. ``This strategy has worked as well as
anything, but boy, was it hard to do. We had to give up every
sacred cow of parenthood.''
</P>
<P>
   And there's the rub, some say. The approach outlined in Greene's
book may eventually be effective, for some children some of the
time, but it requires a superhuman effort by parents. After all,
when a child calls you a ``(expletive)-poor excuse for parents,''
how many parents can curb their tendency to roar back?
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Greene insists the majority of parents he has worked with are
able to achieve this paradigm shift in behavior. Even so, Greene,
who is now the father of a 2-year-old himself, considers himself
fortunate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we lucked out,'' he says. ``Our daughter has a sweet
temperament.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
