A4173 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHERIFF-DIVERSITY-HNS     10-07 0614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHERIFF-DIVERSITY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHERIFF'S DEPARTMENT FINDS DIVERSE FORCE WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JIM HERRON ZAMORA  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In an effort to recruit more female deputies,
Sheriff Michael Hennessey once sent letters to every member of the
San Francisco Women's Rugby League urging them to apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at that (mailing) list and thought here are some
women who don't mind mixing it up,'' Hennessey said. ``We got two
employees out of that mailing who probably wouldn't have applied.
It was worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   That was one of many recruiting efforts Hennessey cited Tuesday
as responsible for making the San Francisco Sheriff's Department
perhaps the most diverse urban law enforcement agency in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   The 713 sheriff's deputies are 65 percent non-white and 22
percent female _ higher ratios than any other big-city law
enforcement agency, according to Hennessey's office.
</P>
<P>
   The report compares the Sheriff's Department to the San
Francisco Police Department and 11 other law enforcement agencies
throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The only other agency that had fewer than 50 percent white
officers was the Los Angeles Police Department, with 49 percent.
Hennessey's department was also the only agency with women making
up more than 20 percent of its staff.
</P>
<P>
   The increased diversity of the Sheriff's Department has come
with little of the controversy and bitterness that accompanied
efforts to integrate the police and fire departments in San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Both those departments spent nearly 20 years being monitored by
the federal courts after the city settled discrimination suits in
the 1970s by adopting consent decrees to encourage integration.
Last Friday, a judge lifted the federal consent decree from the
Police Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had no lawsuits. ... We've never had a consent decree,''
Hennessey said. ``We've been able to do this without any
opposition. ... It wasn't a forced issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Al Waters, president of the San Francisco Deputy Sheriffs'
Association, agreed. ``We have never had to fight any of those
battles. That doesn't mean that everything has been perfect. But
we've never had that kind of dispute. ... We've never had issues of
that magnitude.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, unions representing officers in the San Francisco
Police Department have challenged every round of promotions in that
department for 20 years, accusing management of reverse
discrimination against white male officers. Meanwhile, many black
police officers found themselves at odds with their own union.
</P>
<P>
   Waters said that is not a problem in the Deputy Sheriffs'
Association.
</P>
<P>
   Although the rank and file in the Sheriffs' Department has not
always agreed with the promotional process, ``we've never had a
protest of the promotional exam based on race or gender,'' Waters
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at our Asians, look at our Hispanics, look at people who
are gay and lesbian, you see everyone reflected in this union,''
Waters said. ``There are a lot of different communities who are
comfortable in our ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   In San Francisco, sheriff's deputies operate the city jail,
provide security at the courts and handle evictions. Most other law
enforcement duties _ such as responding to 911 calls and
investigating crimes _ are handled by the police.
</P>
<P>
   Both Hennessey and Waters agreed that it is important to have
jailers who, to some decree, are as diverse as the inmates.
</P>
<P>
   ``From my perspective of running jails, it is going to run
better if you have people who somewhat reflect the population
inside,'' Hennessey said. ``It reduces tension and it's safer for
everyone.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
