<P>
   Science and health stories in sight at this hour from The New
York Times News Service for  &UR; THURSDAY &LR; , Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-LIZARD-RAFT (Undated) _ Fifteen iguanas on a tangle of
waterlogged trees, tossed into the Caribbean Sea by a hurricane,
have apparently sailed 200 miles from Guadaloupe to Anguilla,
scientists reported today. Their report has wowed a community of
scientists that has been arguing since early in this century about
whether such journeys were even remotely possible, let alone
observable. By documenting the voyage of fifteen large, land-loving
creatures _ enough to form a new population _ the study provides
the first clear-cut evidence in support of those biologists who
argue that seemingly impossible journeys like this could be
important avenue for the disperal of species around the words. By
Carol Kaesuk Yoon.
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-U.S.-SPACE (Undated) _ NASA officials go before the House
Science Committee to present their plan to give the Russian space
agency $60 million in return for slots on the international space
station. The plan has already drawn criticism from lawmakers; at
least one called it no more than a ``leveraged buyout'' of the
Russian space program. By Warren E. Leary.
</P>
<P>
   For information and repeats call the News Service at (888)
346-9867 or (212) 556-1927. And be sure to look for other science
stories from our partners: Bloomberg News, The Boston Globe, Cox
