<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4321 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     10-07 0646
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT MOTIVATIONS: TELL THE TRUTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Republicans in the U.S. House of Representatives want to
impeach the president of the United States, they certainly have the
authority to do it. Constituents command no veto power over the
actions of their elected representatives in Congress _ except at
the ballot box, of course, where voters exercise the ultimate veto.
</P>
<P>
   Public-opinion polls indicate that somewhere between 60 and 70
percent of Americans are happy with the job that President Clinton
is doing. Significant majorities in most polls oppose the idea of
removing Clinton from office through the process of impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   As the House forges ahead with impeachment proceedings, it will
be interesting to see how the voters use their veto when the
opportunity presents itself Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   The pro-impeachment crowd has been saying that congressional
decisions on impeachment should not be dictated, or even
influenced, by public opinion. When it comes to the serious
business of impeaching a president, they say, Congress must
exercise its constitutional responsibilities without regard for
polls or elections.
</P>
<P>
   Sounds good. Sounds like the very definition of political
integrity.
</P>
<P>
   But that is not what's happening here _ not by a long shot.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, the pro-impeachment forces in Congress are doing
exactly the opposite of what they'd like us to think they are
doing. They are pandering to public opinion, but they are pandering
to a small percentage of the public rather than the majority.
</P>
<P>
   There are people in this country who just plain hate Bill
Clinton. They were outraged when he was elected president, more
outraged when he was re-elected, and more outraged yet when they
learned of his White House philandering with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   The 21 Republican members of the House Judiciary Committee who
voted Monday to initiate an impeachment inquiry _ and members of
both parties who will endorse the committee's decision in a full
House vote _ are representing the nation's Clinton-haters.
</P>
<P>
   Those representatives have the authority to do so, unless the
voters remove them from office in next month's elections. But if
they really care about integrity in government, why don't they tell
the truth about what they're doing?
</P>
<P>
   They all sat in front of the TV cameras Monday, gushing
sanctimonious platitudes about protecting the American judicial
system from the felonious prevarications of William Jefferson
Clinton. They embraced much of Ken Starr's laundry list of
allegedly impeachable offenses and added several of their own _
alleged violations that had eluded even the fertile imaginations of
Starr and his minions at the independent counsel's office.
</P>
<P>
   Starr was grasping at straws when he accused Clinton of
obstructing justice in the Paula Jones civil suit. The committee
majority's counsel, David Schippers, now has conjured up a
widespread conspiracy of obstruction involving Clinton, Lewinsky,
presidential pal Vernon Jordan and Clinton's secretary, Betty
Currie.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have set out to impeach Clinton because they are
offended by his sexual proclivities _ and because he is despised by
a small percentage of Americans whose influence over the
congressional majority far exceeds their actual numbers.
</P>
<P>
   These Republicans have the authority to do what they are doing,
even at the risk of angering the anti-impeachment majority of
Americans. But they really ought to tell the truth about it instead
of hiding behind high-sounding but dishonest rhetoric about their
reverence for the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. (Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
