<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`VENGEANCE' WON'T BE THINE FOR LONG ON THURSDAYS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Juicy premise, shaky execution. ``Vengeance Unlimited'' wants to
be a ``Stingray,'' the drama series that aired in the 1980s and
chronicled the adventures of a mysterious do-gooder who helped
people turn the tables on their tormentors.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Vengeance Unlimited,'' which premiered last Tuesday but
slides into its regular slot at 7 p.m. Thursday on ABC, Michael
Madsen is Mr. Chapel, who devotes himself to meting out punishment
to those who dance around the legal system. He figures the usually
white-collar sleazebags use high-priced lawyers to work the system
to their advantage; Mr. Chapel merely bends it on behalf of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   Pay? ``One million,'' he tells would-be clients, who often look
at him as though he's insane. But he doesn't actually want money,
only the right to request a favor in return, at a later time,
depending on what you do and what service you can provide him. He
then applies that service to aid someone else. The cycle continues;
Mr. Chapel's Rolodex grows.
</P>
<P>
   Madsen, who has done more than 35 films, is well-cast here as a
somewhat brooding character with the kind of sinister nature that
makes you feel good only if he's on your side. He refers to himself
only as ``Mr. Chapel'' and gets away with it because people are
deathly afraid to ask whether a first name goes with that.
</P>
<P>
   Why is he doing this? ``We live in a world where people can kill
someone and get a book deal out of it because they have the right
lawyer,'' he says at one point.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vengeance Unlimited'' is up against the NBC Thursday-night
machine, which cranked up its debut last week, simply hammering the
competition. ABC insists that this will be an alternative.
</P>
<P>
   With the low-brow drama presented in the pilot, I don't think
so. Plus, ``Nothing Sacred'' and ``Cracker,'' last season's
sacrificial lambs, were infinitely superior shows. Is a network
president in Mr. Chapel's Rolodex?
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
