<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4348 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-49ERS-OWNERSHIP-H     10-07 0959
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-49ERS-OWNERSHIP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 DeBARTOLO'S FUTURE WITH NINERS REMAINS UNCERTAIN  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC BRAZIL and CHUCK FINNIE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ Edward J. DeBartolo Jr.'s guilty plea in a
Louisiana extortion case will keep him out of prison, but may not
put him back in control of his prized 49ers football franchise.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo pleaded guilty Tuesday to a felony and won leniency
from prosecutors in exchange for becoming the federal government's
star witness in its case targeting Edwin Edwards, the former
Louisiana governor.
</P>
<P>
   While prosecutors and DeBartolo's lawyer portrayed him as a
victim of an extortion plot by Edwards, documents filed in court
also show the 49ers co-owner used the former governor to get
Louisiana's 15th and last riverboat casino license.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, DeBartolo asked Edwards to obtain, and received, a
confidential report detailing the background of his competitors for
the casino license; he later paid Edwards $400,000 to make sure
there were no problems.
</P>
<P>
   Outside U.S. District Court in Baton Rouge Tuesday, a somber
DeBartolo acknowledged that standing before the judge, listening to
the facts of his crime and pleading guilty ``was like visiting a
little piece of hell.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a very, very long ordeal for me and my family,''
DeBartolo said.
</P>
<P>
   Though he is now a felon, DeBartolo said, ``I am going to seek
to retain the (49ers) franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo and his sister, Denise DeBartolo York, co-own the
49ers through their joint ownership of the Edward J. DeBartolo
Corp., the Youngstown, Ohio-based shopping center development
company established by their late father.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo stepped down last December as director and an officer
of the corporation and relinquished management control of the
football franchise after he was told he investigated in the Edwards
case.
</P>
<P>
   NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue, who plans a review of the case
and DeBartolo's other business dealings, issued a written statement
that could scarcely give DeBartolo much hope of a quick return to
heading the football team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mr. DeBartolo's decision to enter a plea in Louisiana is not
based on any understandings with or commitments from this office
regarding his future status with the 49ers or the NFL,'' Tagliabue
said.
</P>
<P>
   He said York and the team's new interim president, Larry
Thrailkill, would run the franchise through the end of the season _
including the decision about whether to proceed with a new stadium
to replace Candlestick Park.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, 51, who has co-owned the 49ers since 1977, pleaded
guilty to a single count of the rare federal crime of misprision of
felony _ a failure to report what authorities called an extortion
scheme perpetuated against him by Edwards. He was sentenced to two
years on probation and fined $1 million by U.S. District Judge John
V. Parker.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo's attorney, Aubrey Harwell, said his client has
suffered anguish because of his failure to report the extortion
attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Harwell said the charge DeBartolo pleaded to is ``so minor and
insignificant we hope that Mr. Tagliabue will not take a harsh
position'' on his return to the 49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This man deserves no more punishment,'' Harwell said.
``(DeBartolo) is more of a victim than culpable.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But a seven-page outline of the evidence supporting DeBartolo's
guilty plea shows he engaged in a perilous scheme to snare insider
information on the award of valuable Louisiana riverboat casino
license.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo Entertainment had joined with Hollywood Casino Corp.
to win a casino license for a riverboat in Bossier City, La.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo talked with Edwards as early as October 1996 about
whether Edwards had the votes on the Louisiana gambling commission
to swing the license in favor or DeBartolo.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 24, 1997, with the commission's decision less than a
month away, DeBartolo asked Edwards to get a copy of a confidential
state police report on the backgrounds of all those vying for the
casino license.
</P>
<P>
   On the same day, Edwards talked to a state senator about
obtaining the document. ``If ... I were able to get a copy of that,
it would certainly solidify my position with some people,'' Edwards
said, according to the court documents.
</P>
<P>
   A day later, Edwards told DeBartolo, ``Hey, I'll have that
summary in my hands about 5 this evening, you want me to Fed Ex it
to you?'' Edwards added, ``I still have ... assurances from the
right people that if and when they ever have the vote, we're, we've
got it.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks later, before the vote, Edwards is depicted as
pressing DeBartolo in a Baton Rouge hotel for a $400,000 payoff to
secure the casino license. DeBartolo, who wondered how he would get
the cash to Louisiana, then met with the former governor on March
12, 1997, and paid the money.
</P>
<P>
   On March 13, 1997, DeBartolo's group was awarded the casino
license.
</P>
<P>
   York, DeBartolo's sister who is chairwoman of the DeBartolo
Corp., issued a statement Tuesday making sure everyone understood
her brother's legal troubles were his own and unrelated to the
49ers.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a personal level, I know that this has been, and continues
to be, a very difficult time for my brother. My thoughts and
prayers are with him, his wife and children,'' York said. ``On a
business level, I have never been involved in the California-based
DeBartolo Entertainment Corporation and I cannot comment on issues
relating to that organization.''
</P>
<P>
   At team headquarters in Santa Clara, General Manager Dwight
Clark said, ``We're all hoping the best for Mr. D. We're hoping
this is one more step to getting this behind him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
