</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATES-Y2K-NAT </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;  MAINE GROUP OFFERS SOLUTION TO YEAR 2000 COMPUTER CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   By Mary Ellen Butler
</P>
<P>
   States News Service
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Oct. 7 -- A representative from a small Maine
manufacturers' group told Congress Wednesday he had proof that the
year 2000 computer problem could be solved, but not on his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't be making a dent unless it's a national cure. Many
Maine manufacturers have to rely on other states,'' said Rod
Rodrigue, director of Maine's Manufacturers Extension Program.
</P>
<P>
   Without a cure, Maine's businesses could be facing $250 million
in additional computer and electronics repair costs, which Rodrigue
estimated would force employers to cut costs by laying off more
than 9,000 workers early next century.
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigue told a special Senate committee about a computer-based
assessment tool that identifies the areas of a computer system that
are vulnerable to year 2000 glitches.
</P>
<P>
   The tool, called Conversion 2000, takes an inventory of a
computer system, assesses potential threats, develops a contingency
plan, and attempts to fix the problems. It also provides links to
information about small business loans to assist with year 2000
costs.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide, the year 2000 problem could cost as much as $200
billion, Rodrigue said.
</P>
<P>
   Many computers, both for government and in the private sector,
will not be able to recognize ``00'' as the year 2000 -- or the
computer will read it as 1900. That problem could wreak havoc on
small businesses across the globe, and the glitch might not be
corrected until 2003.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our nation's 23 million small businesses create two out of
three new jobs, represent over 99 percent of all employers, and are
responsible for more than half of the nation's technological
innovation. In my home state of Maine they are truly the backbone
of our economy,'' said Sen. Susan Collins, R-Maine, a member of the
Senate special committee.
</P>
<P>
   Conversion 2000 was developed several months ago by the
Department of Commerce's National Institute of Standards and
Technology and 2,500 of the programs were distributed to
Manufacturers Extension Programs, a network that represents small
companies in each state.
</P>
<P>
   However, only the Maine MEP is making use of the tool, Rodrigue
said.
</P>
<P>
   In the past months, Rodrigue and his group have gone around to
all the manufacturers in Maine offering and explaining the program.
So far, more than 100 businesses have used the diagnostic tool.
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigue urged the Senators to get the rest of the nation
involved and to help the groups find additional funding. To bring
the program to the more than 600 manufacturers in Maine, the cost
would be $800,000 to $1 million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Education, healthcare, government agencies, agriculture and food
processing were the U.S. industries least prepared to deal with
year 2000 computer malfunctions, said Lou Marcoccio of the Gartner
Group, a research consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   About 66 percent of companies in those industries will
experience major system failures in the year 2000 or in the three
to four years following.
</P>
<P>
   About 15 percent of companies in the most prepared industries,
such as insurance, banking and investment services, will experience
major system failures, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There will also be severe implications around the world. Less
developed countries could have significant periods of power
outages, loss of telephone service, interruptions to government
services and unrest.
</P>
<P>
   And businesses need to act sooner, rather than later. It will
take an average of 30 months for a mid-size company to secure all
of their critical operating equipment for the year 2000 bug,
Marcoccio said.
</P>
<P>
   Rodrigue stressed the need for his program to reach companies by
June of 1999 so they have a chance to implement it in time for the
new year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come here on bended knee asking (Congress) not only to help
the 80,000 to 90,000 men and women who work in manufacturing in
Maine, but the 12 million across the nation,'' Rodrigue said.
</P>
<P>
   -30-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1636EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
