<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 16:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4387 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PARIS-CHEAP-FURNITURE     10-07 1054
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARIS-CHEAP-FURNITURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PARIS, EVEN JUNK HAS A CLASS SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By KRISTIN HOHENADEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I arrived in Paris with two suitcases and soon learned how to
live among other people's things, in a rented room decorated with
Japanese white paper lanterns and nondescript plasterboard shelves.
By the time I graduated to my own studio, I had the requisite bed,
desk and couch from Ikea, but I needed everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to fill the apartment with Parisian treasures, I
ruled out the notoriously overpriced Left Bank antique stores and
Parisian flea markets like the Marche aux Puces at Porte de
Clignancourt _ where it's possible to pick up an armchair for
$200,000.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, I began at the flea market's poorer cousins, the
brocantes, which are less publicized roving antiques fairs. Like
Parisians, most brocantes head south for the summer, but they are
back in full flower for the rentree in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   From vintage leather club chairs to champagne coolers, the
brocantes offer regional antiques at prices below those of Paris.
Admission to most brocantes is free; the few exceptions include the
twice-a-year Grande Brocante at the Place de la Bastille, in early
spring and just before Christmas. It costs 35 francs (about $6.40),
which is reflected in the higher cost of items.
</P>
<P>
   I am fond of the neighborhood brocantes, where decorative
objects are more plentiful than serious antiques. At Place
St.-Sulpice I came upon the gilded mirror ($200) that now hangs on
my wall. On the Pont Louis Philippe at the edge of the Marais I
found the old French flag ($18) that fills the blank space above my
dining room table. On a rainy late fall day on the Place Daumesnil,
I coaxed my entryway rug ($38) from beneath a giant table. On the
Rue St. Charles I got a former milk-bottle carrier ($20) that
serves as a wine rack.
</P>
<P>
   Shopping the brocantes can be intimidating for the uninitiated.
Brocante literally means ``second-hand goods,'' so customers will
have to wade through a lot of junk to find the prizes. Brocanteurs
often display their wares on the ground, leaving them to rain and
dust, not to mention the unsteady feet of those who have had too
much wine at lunch.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the decidedly French items that Pottery Barn isn't
likely to mass produce: ceramic cheese trays in the shape of
France; Napoleon and Josephine cups and saucers; statuettes of
Jeanne d'Arc and Voltaire, and kitchen items for just about every
purpose, from chocolate molds to asparagus servers. And there are
the carafes, ashtrays, sugar tins, coffee mills and garden tools
that are resold at a premium in New York boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   The brocante is an all-day affair, which means that it
inconveniently falls across the sacred lunch hour. Brocanteurs cope
with this schedule either by abandoning their stalls _ for as long
as an hour and a half, the time deemed reasonable for lunch _ or by
feasting at their antique dining tables, with silverware and with
wine. Often, to help pass the afternoon, they drink Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   Browsing the brocante under the chestnut trees one spring
afternoon on the Square des Batignolles with my cousin, I spotted a
green painted tin cafetiere, once used for making coffee, now
merely a decorative item. I picked it up, discussed its merits and
then looked around for the brocanteur. At a nearby table, rowdy
diners clinked glasses and smoked cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``S'il vous plait?'' I asked in their general direction. (In
French, ``excusez-moi'' is not a question, but an apology. To be
avoided.)
</P>
<P>
   One man ambled over.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oui?'' he asked bemusedly. It was, after all, a Sunday, in the
middle of his lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonjour, monsieur,'' I said, holding up the cafetiere, which
in characteristic brocante fashion was missing a price tag. ``Quel
est le prix?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Le prix?'' he said, as if asking himself that question for the
first time. I knew from experience that the price should be around
$20, but in the capricious world of brocante pricing, I also knew
that it could go for as much as $100. He sighed and began a
complicated examination of the cafetiere.
</P>
<P>
   By then it was clear that I was a foreigner. By deploying a few
key phrases, however, it is possible to convey that, stranger or
not, you ``know the brocante,'' and will aid in the war against
paying too much. I knew there was no such thing as a bargain in
France. He told me the cafetiere would be $40, in cash, the
required method of payment at brocantes.
</P>
<P>
   It was best to frown slightly at this point, a gesture
ubiquitous to the French, and to hope he would offer a small
reduction. Some brocanteurs might try convincing you that something
is ``ancien'' or ``rare,'' that it is ``grand'' where it is
normally ``petit.'' They might also mumble something about it being
``style Napoleon III'' or ``style Louis XV,'' and hope you don't
notice the word ``style,'' meaning, of course, that it is a copy.
</P>
<P>
   If the brocanteur doesn't offer you a reduction, you are obliged
to ask the magic question: ``Vous pouvez faire un petit prix?''
(Roughly, ``Can you give me a good deal?'')
</P>
<P>
   This will either disarm them or inspire them to speak English:
``Mais, it's cheap!''
</P>
<P>
   At this point it sometimes works to point out legitimate flaws,
like chips or a bad finish. (If your vocabulary runs out, remember
the art of frowning and pointing.)
</P>
<P>
   If all else fails, try ``Quel est votre dernier prix?'' (``What
is your final price?'') Dropping an overinflated price by at least
10 percent is a gesture, or ``un geste'' and nearly obligatory.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, you can say, ``Je vais reflechir'' (``I'll think
about it'') and walk away.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be offended if he sighs loudly or mutters in your general
direction. He is letting you know that, thanks to you, he is doing
an awful lot of work.
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that he might say, grumpily, ``Allez,'' and
name a better price. In the case of the cafetiere, it was $18.
Which was followed by a tsk tsk and his comment, ``Mais c'est un
cadeau'' (``It's a gift.) I handed over his hard-won francs, and
said ``merci'' for the favor.
</P>
<P>
   For information and schedules, contact the two main
organizations responsible for organizing Paris brocantes: Sadema at
(011)-33-1-40-62-95-95. or Spam, (011)-33-1-45-78-98-26.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
