<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0189 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 16:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4393 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CIR-NANNY-SEEK-ART-NY     10-07 1325
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-NANNY-SEEK-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CYBERAGENCIES MATCH FAMILIES WITH MODERN MARY POPPINSES 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(jt) 
 By BONNIE ROTHMAN MORRIS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Teresa Johnson never wanted to be a nanny. After graduating from
Oral Roberts University, she spent four years teaching band at a
Christian school in Madison, Wis. When she wanted a new teaching
job, possibly one that would take her overseas, she began her job
hunt on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somehow through my searching, nannies just came up,'' said Ms.
Johnson, 30. The site she discovered, I Love My Nanny, advertised
nanny jobs in Europe (www.ilovemynanny. com). Ms. Johnson began to
rechart her future and eventually applied for work through another
agency on line, Apple Pie, U.S.A (www.nanny.com).
</P>
<P>
   There are other nanny-related sites, like www.nannynetwork.com,
which bills itself as a listing of every agency nationwide and lets
families and nannies find phone numbers, addresses and, where
available, Web sites for agencies in their area. To help families
with tax and payroll work, there is www.nannytaxes.com.
</P>
<P>
   Today Ms. Johnson works as a nanny in East Hills, N.Y., on the
North Shore of Long Island, caring for two school-age children. She
has her own room, her own phone line and her own computer. Her
French horn, which she has played for 18 years, is tucked away for
now. She is a new breed of live-in nanny, the kind coveted by many
families and, because of the Internet, increasingly available:
college educated, at least 25 years old and accustomed to being
away from home. She was lured to the profession by the prospect of
a job in a glamorous location.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out that the overseas positions were filled already,
but I thought even if I didn't go overseas, maybe I could be on the
East Coast,'' said Ms. Johnson, who is thrilled to be in affluent
East Hills, a place almost as foreign to her as Europe would be.
</P>
<P>
   In the olden days of the nanny business _ that's about two years
ago _ nanny employment agencies placed classified advertisements in
local and college newspapers in the Midwest, trolling for
prospective workers. That needle-in-a-haystack approach was
expensive and inefficient. Many applicants were too young or too
inexperienced or had sketchy, uncheckable backgrounds. But the Web
is effecting some fundamental changes in nannydom.
</P>
<P>
   About 5 percent of all preschool-age children are cared for by
live-in nannies, governesses and au pairs. That's about one million
child-care workers, 125,000 of whom are placed by approximately 500
nanny employment agencies, said Mary O'Connor, president of the
International Nanny Association (www.nanny.org). Though that
represents a slim slice of the child-care pie, there are still
fewer qualified candidates than jobs. For would-be nannies and the
families who hire them, the Web may help put more employable
candidates into the mix.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Clurman, who runs Apple Pie, U.S.A., a 14-year-old agency,
put her business completely on the Web two years ago. Ms. Clurman,
who places nannies directly with families and recruits them for
other agencies, said she had more qualified nannies today than she
could place. Leigh Billingsley, a mother of two in Tustin, Calif.,
who just hired her second nanny from the Net (her first returned
home), said: ``I've had so much luck with Internet nannies. There's
an abundance of young women who are highly qualified and highly
educated.''
</P>
<P>
   Web-based agencies are increasingly functioning as
clearinghouses for many of the smaller nanny employment agencies
nationwide who rely on them for candidates. These smaller agencies
may have e-mail or simple billboard-type Web sites but many can't
receive applications from candidates and families on line.
</P>
<P>
   The Web-based agencies say they are standardizing the industry
by codifying job descriptions and raising salaries, which average
$350 a week nationwide, according to a survey of 300 readers in
Nanny News, published by Apple Pie for nannies and their employers.
Salaries in the New York metropolitan area and in other major
cities can reach $800 to $1,000 weekly.
</P>
<P>
   Salaries and job standards are well advertised on the more
sophisticated sites, which attract college graduates who, like Ms.
Johnson, may never have considered the career before. Many
candidates view a nanny position as a stop on the way to ``real
life,'' allowing them to pay off student loans and figure out
what's next.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting on line does have a downside: it's a little too easy.
``Right around college graduation, we get tons of applications from
women who don't have jobs yet, and after hours of going through the
process with us, decide they don't want to be a nanny after all,''
said Jackie Williams, owner of I Love My Nanny. Once her agency
decides that a candidate is serious, the matching process begins.
The nannies, and the families seeking them, are screened.
</P>
<P>
   The Web makes it easier for agencies to do background checks,
too. Digging deeply _ tracing a phone number or address of a
reference or verifying a college degree or the length of previous
employment _ is simplified. The International Nanny Association
warns, however, that background checks of criminal records are
limited by state and Federal laws and may not show the whole
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finding nannies on the Internet is the very beginning,'' said
Carol Solomon, owner of the New York Nanny Center
(www.nynanny.com). Rigorous screening still involves
person-to-person contact, Ms. Solomon said.
</P>
<P>
   For qualified candidates, the process doesn't take long.
Jennifer Staszewski, a 25-year-old graduate of the University of
Wisconsin at Lacrosse, applied with Midwest Nannies
(www.mwnanny.com). Her job search lasted one month. Now she works
for a family in Short Hills, N.J.; she plans to be with them for a
year, then go to graduate school.
</P>
<P>
   While many agency owners say most of their clients learn of them
by word of mouth, families in need of nannies are also using the
Web. Some families are from remote areas where nannies and nanny
agencies are nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Stansfield, the manager of the Merrill Lynch office in
Hanover, N.H., and his wife, Amy, administrative director of
Dartmouth's Hitchcock Medical Center, started searching for a nanny
to care for their 6-year-old son through I Love My Nanny.
Stansfield likes to use the Internet, so using it to find a nanny
was natural for him. He was directed to the site by his
sister-in-law, Ms. Billingsley in California. The Stansfields live
on a mountaintop on 60 acres; their driveway is a mile long. They
wanted their nanny to be athletic and not afraid of isolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I give a lot of credit to the technology edge for making the
quicker match,'' said Stansfield, whose college-educated nanny,
Tara Olcott, applied through the Internet. She grew up in Vermont,
where her nearest neighbor lived a half-mile away. Isolation isn't
a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Web is attracting people who are better able to
communicate with their employers, and families are looking for
people who are more economically and educationally like
themselves,'' said Kathleen Webb of Home/Work Solutions in
Sterling, Va. Home/Work Solutions runs three Web nanny sites; one
site carries classified listings for families and nannies who want
to avoid agency fees, which range from $800 to $3,000 per placement
(www.4nannies.com).
</P>
<P>
   But the heads of Web-based agencies concede that their focus on
the Internet might make them miss out on some qualified candidates.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can be an outstanding caregiver and not have any of the
attributes needed to get on the Internet,'' Ms. Webb said. ``Think
of `The Brady Bunch.' Do you think Alice was on the Net?''
</P>
<P>
   And Ms. Williams said, ``You don't need a Ph.D. to give a hug.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
