<HEADLINE>
L.A.   DESIGNER   WINS FASHION AWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARBARA DE WITT 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ &UR;  &LR; Love it or hate it, L.A.'s got style.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in the city of angels, movie stars and ``Baywatch'' babes,
fashion designers are known for clothing with edge and attitude.
</P>
<P>
   One of the front-runners this year is Trina Turk, the
37-year-old L.A. sportswear designer who was named CaliforniaMart's
Designer of the Year at a black-tie gala Sunday night at the
Beverly Hilton Hotel in Beverly Hills.
</P>
<P>
   A young designer who puts a '90s twist on Grace Kelly-esque
classics for clients such as Sharon Stone, Drew Barrymore and Lisa
Kudrow, Turk didn't forget her hometown when she received her
crystal trophy. ``Thanks to the city of Los Angeles. It's a great
place, and I find inspiration here every day,'' she told the
audience. And she means it.
</P>
<P>
   Away from the podium she said, ``The L.A. fashion industry is on
the upswing. It's a place where you can dress to express yourself,
and the city accepts it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since she started her own business three years ago, Turk's line
of sporty womenswear that bears her name has a reputation for fine
fit and workmanship. She admires Calvin Klein's simplicity of line
and Jean Paul Gaultier's original take on classics.
</P>
<P>
   Turk competed against four other high-profile local designers
nominated by members of the fashion press. They were Judy Rabineau
for Mica, William B., Rozae Nichols, and Gregg and Holly Fiene of
XOXO.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate category, Cynthia Vincent of St. Vincent was
honored with the Rising Star Award for growth potential in the
fashion industry. She hugged everyone in sight, waved her trophy
and thanked Ron Herman for giving her a start at his store and
Mayor Richard Riordan for finally recognizing the local fashion
industry by attending the event.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent, who's known for glamorous Valley girl ensembles,
competed against nominees Dana Dartez of 26 Red Sugar, William Sung
and Betty Kim of Bette Paige, Monah Li, and Shawn Janet and Craig
Harwood for State of the Heart.
</P>
<P>
   E! Entertainment Television executive Fran Shae and Ron Herman
of Fred Segal Melrose also were honored with CaliforniaMart's
Performance Awards for their influence and support of the local
fashion industry.
</P>
<P>
   The awards ceremony is sponsored by the CaliforniaMart, which
houses 10,000 clothing lines in its downtown building. Platinum
sponsors included Chatsworth designer David Dart, the XOXO company,
Ojai Valley Inn and Woodland Hills-based hair and cosmetic company
Sebastian International.
</P>
<P>
   The program featured runway shows of each nominee's spring '99
collections and raised more than $20,000 for the Starlight
Children's Foundation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
