<SLUG> BC-CIR-SABRINA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIGITAL MAGIC: FROM TEEN-AGE WITCH TO BARBIE 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(jt) 
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   I was far too young to appreciate the stir that the Beatles
caused when they landed in America, so I missed out on the early
training that might have better prepared me for celebrity worship.
By the time I glimpsed someone famous nearby _ Warren Beatty in a
restaurant _ I was already an adult and felt no urge to (1) scream
hysterically, (2) run up to him and sob, ``I love you,'' or (3) rip
out my own hair.
</P>
<P>
   But one day last spring, I took my daughters to see a Broadway
show and got a firsthand view of how the famous can enthrall even
the very young. As we settled into our seats, Zoe, 9, and Ella, 7,
were sneaking frantic looks over their shoulders. The object of
their attention appeared to be a young blond woman chatting with a
friend in the row behind us.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her,'' Ella gasped.
</P>
<P>
   Zoe whispered through clenched teeth: ``Autograph. Now.''
</P>
<P>
   With a stalker's glint in her eye, Ella turned and blurted:
``Are you 
Melissa-Joan-Hart-from-the-TV-show-and-if-so-can-I-have-your--autogr
aph? Please.''
</P>
<P>
   That was my introduction to ``Sabrina the Teen-age Witch,'' the
popular weekly television show, and its star, Melissa Joan Hart,
whose on-screen attempts to control the forces of magic and
adolescence have earned her the loyalty and adoration of millions
of little girls. Ms. Hart obligingly scrawled ``All My Love,
Melissa Joan Hart'' on the back of an old grocery receipt for my
daughters. For the rest of the evening, Zoe and Ella peeked at the
crumpled paper, which in the months since has been solemnly passed
back and forth between them.
</P>
<P>
   Sabrina clearly had magic powers over my children, which is why
I decided to investigate the character's leap from one
entertainment medium to another. The television witch has become
the star of a $35 computer game for either Macintosh or Windows
machines. While plenty of animated television characters have made
the transition to the desktop, Sabrina leads the charge among
flesh-and-blood sitcom characters. Would she lose something in the
translation?
</P>
<P>
   I hoped not, because I confess that I have become attached to
Sabrina myself in the past few months. I felt some comfort watching
the show with Zoe and Ella, remembering how I had spent my own
childhood in thrall to novels about similarly plucky,
one-dimensional heroines like Trixie Belden, girl detective, and
Cherry Ames, World War II nurse. I loved them because they always
attempted the impossible _ and even when they failed, they were
better off for trying.
</P>
<P>
   So the three of us were excited when we installed the Sabrina
the Teen-age Witch game on my Micron Millenia. We huddled in front
of the screen, listening to the voice of Penn Jillette (the
magician who plays Drell, head of the Witches' Council, on the
show) tell us how to win. The goal is to earn a witch's license by
helping the animated Sabrina cast seven spells, based on clues and
secret ingredients hidden throughout the rooms of Sabrina's house
and school.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, we need to figure out how to turn that pulsating orange
gourd back into Sabrina,'' I said. ``Looks like fun.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Zoe, you're hogging the mouse,'' Ella said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's my turn, Ella.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mom, Zoe is hogging the mouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Figuring they would work it out by following an on-screen
example _ after all, Sabrina's attempts to learn magic are little
more than a thinly veiled metaphor for learning how to get along in
life _ I left them alone for 10 minutes while I picked up my
husband at the train station.
</P>
<P>
   When I returned, I found them on the couch, watching ``Rugrats''
on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to the game?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ugghh,'' Ella said.
</P>
<P>
   Zoe translated: ``Sabrina in the game doesn't look like Melissa
Joan Hart. She looks kind of like Barbie. So we don't want to help
her that much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe you should have had them test the new Rugrats game
instead,'' my husband said helpfully.
</P>
<P>
   I would probably have abandoned the animated Sabrina at that
point if not for the fact that I had been charmed by the amusing
dialogue supplied by the voices of Ms. Hart and Nick Bakay as Salem
the campy Talking Cat, by the faithfulness of the plot line to the
television show and by the hunch I had about where to find the
magic vacuum to free Sabrina from a loveless existence as a gourd.
</P>
<P>
   So the next day, I phoned Ms. Hart to enlist her help in luring
my daughters back to the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you remember who your own role model was when you were
little?'' I asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madonna.''
</P>
<P>
   I decided to try a different tack. ``What advice would you have
for two little girls who love the character of Sabrina but think
the game is too hard and the animated image of Sabrina looks like
Barbie?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I haven't actually played the game myself,'' Ms. Hart
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All right then, what advice would Sabrina give?'' I was
getting desperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, she would say that if she just tried it a couple more
times, she would start to pick it up,'' Ms. Hart said. ``Sometimes
things seem hard and frustrating, but if you keep at them, you
figure out how they work.''
</P>
<P>
   That night at dinner, my daughters wanted to know if I really
got to talk to Melissa Joan Hart and if so, did I ask all the
questions they had written down for me before they went to school
that morning: Was it true she had recently cut her hair? Did she
remember meeting them at ``The Lion King''? Did she want them to
come out and help her with the show?
</P>
<P>
   I said I had talked to her and the answers were yes, yes (not
true, but the truth would have crushed them) and no.
</P>
<P>
   After a couple of minutes, Zoe said, ``Ella, I was thinking that
if you cast a spell on the broom in the kitchen closet, it might
turn into a vacuum.''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, but don't hog the mouse.''
</P>
<P>
   Trixie Belden would have been proud.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
