<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 17:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLEGE-COST08-1STLED     10-07 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-COST08-1STLEDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLLEGE COSTS RISING TWICE AS FAST AS INFLATION
 &HT;    Eds: Recasts final phrase in 6th graf.
 &HT;    BY NICHOLE MONROE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ College costs are rising twice as fast as
inflation, the College Board reported Wednesday, with tuition and
fees up about 4 percent nationwide this fall, and 5 percent at
private schools.
</P>
<P>
   To meet these costs, more students are turning to unsubsidized
student loans, the board said in a report, ``Trends in College
Pricing.''
</P>
<P>
   The report said average tuition for the 1998-99 school year is
$3,243 for four-year public schools and $14,508 for four-year
private schools. That represents an average increase of $132 at the
public schools and $723 at the private schools.
</P>
<P>
   Room and board charges are rising a similar 3 to 5 percent, it
said.
</P>
<P>
   The increases continue a long trend of college costs
outstripping prices in general.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1980, tuition rises have more than doubled the inflation
rate, and the costs announced this fall are twice the 2 percent
inflation rate so far in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   College and university officials attributed soaring tuition to
the increased demand for technology in classrooms and dormitories,
decreases in state funding and colleges' slowness to reduce costs.
</P>
<P>
   The College Board also reported that financial aid reached
record levels in 1997-98. More than $60 billion was available from
federal, state and institutional sources, an increase of 6 percent
over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   However, most of the increase was in the form of unsubsidized
loans rather than grants, placing the heaviest burdens on
low-income students and those who don't complete their degrees,
said Lawrence Gladieux, executive director of policy analysis for
the College Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``The growing reliance on loans puts a disproportionate burden
on our neediest students, who were targeted for grants, not loans,
and never expected to have to borrow when these programs were
created,'' Gladieux said.
</P>
<P>
   Loans have increased in part because grants and their purchasing
power has declined. The maximum federal Pell Grant, which at its
peak in the late 1970s covered three-quarters of the cost of
attending a public four-year college, now only covers one-third.
</P>
<P>
   For families, the rising costs only highlight the importance of
saving early, said John Joyce of the College Scholarship Service,
the financial aid arm of the College Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many families do not realize that there are resources to help
them finance a college education,'' Joyce said. ``With careful
planning and a little homework, most families can gather a wealth
of available information and translate that into a package that
will open the doors of college for their children.''
</P>
<P>
   Joyce added that families should take advantage of newly enacted
tax benefits and other programs aimed at easing the college burden.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, President Clinton signed legislation that reduces
the interest rate on federally backed student loans to 7.46
percent, down more than half a point from last year. The bill would
also allow the maximum amount of Pell Grants for low-income
students to rise from the current $3,000 a year to $5,800 in 2003,
if Congress provides the money.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when more than half of students require financial aid
to pay for college, College Board officials acknowledged that
parents may go into ``sticker shock'' when they look at soaring
prices. However, they said that for most college graduates,
lifetime earnings repay the cost of college many times over.
</P>
<P>
   College Board President Donald Stewart noted that a majority of
students at four-year colleges pay less than $4,000 a year for
tuition and fees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is that the majority of Americans often overestimate
the price of attending college and may be discouraged by those
miscalculations,'' Stewart said.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
