<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0206 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4603 &Cx1f; tab-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LATAM-SMOKES-LATINTRA     10-07 3088
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LATAM-SMOKES-LATINTRADE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRING UP LATIN AMERICA
</HEADLINE>
  (This ``separate buy'' article is from Latin Trade magazine.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times sales representatives OLIVIA
VASQUEZ in Los Angeles at 310-996-0075 or fax at 310-996-0089; or
KARL HORWITZ in Paris at 47-42-17-11, or fax at 47-42-80-44 or
47-42-18-81; or CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or
816-822-8448, or fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (They also have information on how to subscribe to Latin Trade's
service for newspapers _ the magazine's exclusives and other
articles are transmitted every week.) 
 By CLAIRE POOLE, with BRENDAN M. CASE in Mexico City, MERY
GALANTERNICK in Rio de Janeiro and ANDREA MANDEL-CAMPBELL in Buenos
Aires 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    The TV commercial is alluring. Shot in cult-film fashion and in
evocative black and white, the spot shows charming, sexy, casually
dressed 20-something Brazilians going about their carefree days,
reading books and taking leisurely strolls. Then comes the pitch:
``We can be different in many ways, but we all have one thing in
common: Free.''
 &HT;    No, ``Free'' isn't a line of clothing, a detergent or a
political party. It's a brand of light cigarettes made by Brazilian
cigarette giant Souza Cruz, which is controlled by British American
Tobacco, a unit of U.K.-based BAT Industries.
 &HT;    Young Latin Americans like these are the next generation for
many of the world's tobacco giants. While smoking rates in some
industrialized countries are decreasing at about 1 percent a year,
those in developing countries are increasing at around 3 percent
per year, according to a recent article in The Lancet, a U.K.-based
medical journal.
 &HT;    As a result, the big tobacco makers are targeting regions like
Latin America for their next crop of consumers. ``Latin America is
not as important as Asia or Eastern Europe,'' says Marc Cohen, a
tobacco analyst at Goldman Sachs in New York. ``But it is
growing.''
 &HT;    British American Tobacco has been the most aggressive, acquiring
stakes in companies from Mexico to Chile. It now sells more than
186 billion cigarettes a year in the region and controls half of
the market. In Nicaragua, Honduras, Trinidad and Barbados, it
controls almost the entire market. Latin America now makes up more
than 25 percent of its overall sales and almost 20 percent of its
operating profits.
 &HT;    This recent push by the big multinational tobacco companies is
alarming to such groups as the Washington, D.C.-based Pan American
Health Organization (PAHO), which is working to improve the health
and living standards of the people of the Americas.
 &HT;    In a study released in April, PAHO found that 135,000 people die
in Latin America each year from tobacco usage. The study also cited
statistics from the World Health Organization, which estimates that
one third of Latin American and Caribbean adults are smokers. That
puts the region at the same level as Canada but slightly higher
than the United States. Venezuela, the Dominican Republic and
Bolivia rank at the top of the list, while Honduras, Costa Rica and
Paraguay remain at the bottom.
 &HT;    Room to grow. While more Latin Americans smoke than their
counterparts in the United States, they smoke fewer cigarettes per
day _ 12 versus 20, according to PAHO. That gives cigarette makers
a big incentive to boost consumption among current smokers as their
real incomes rise. And with the proportion of female smokers in
Latin America (19 percent) well below that of women in Canada and
the United States (26 percent), PAHO thinks women in the region are
likely to be a prime new target for the big tobacco companies.
 &HT;    ``Women are entering the workplace and finally feel free,'' says
Jeannette Noltenius, executive director of the Latino Council on
Alcohol and Tobacco in Washington, D.C. ``And with it has come this
notion that part of that freedom is the ability to smoke.''
 &HT;    To discourage more people from taking up cigarettes, many
countries in the region have bolstered their regulatory efforts.
Almost all the countries in Latin America require fixed warnings on
the hazards of smoking on their cigarette packs, with the exception
of Brazil and Chile, which post different warnings from time to
time. But only two countries _ Chile and Mexico _ require
information on the levels of tar and nicotine to be placed on the
package.
 &HT;    Regulations on advertising, meanwhile, have been lax. Only three
Latin American countries _ Cuba, Nicaragua and Venezuela _ have
banned cigarette advertising on radio and television, as is the
practice in the United States and Canada. However, most countries
have put restrictions on when the ads may be broadcast, and some
even restrict their content and prospective audience.
 &HT;    It's been difficult to reign in an industry that's also a big
money maker for some Latin American countries. Three in the region
rank among the world's leading producers of raw tobacco: Brazil
(fourth), Argentina (15th) and Mexico (16th). Three more are among
the world's leading exporters of cigarettes, including Brazil
(sixth), Venezuela (16th) and Colombia (20th). Brazil alone earns
almost US$1 billion a year from tobacco exports. And a large
portion of the Dominican Republic's farmland is taken up with
tobacco.
 &HT;    Argentine diehards. But even in a diehard smoking country like
Argentina, where black, Gitane-style tobacco is still popular and
cigarette smoke wafts through the air even at the Ministry of
Public Health, the anti-smoking movement has gradually picked up
steam.
 &HT;    Earlier this year, all Aerolineas Argentinas flights were
declared smoke free.
 &HT;    Legislation has also been recently enacted forbidding the sale
of cigarettes to minors under 18 in the province of Buenos Aires.
The City of Buenos Aires has dedicated $120,000 to an anti-smoking
commission targeted at getting youths to stop smoking and also
passed a by-law forbidding lotteries and games of chance that
promote smoking.
 &HT;    ``The movement is gaining momentum,'' says Leonardo Daino,
director of the anti-tobacco campaign for the Argentine League for
the Fight Against Cancer.
 &HT;    Much of that change has come as a result of the changing legal
environment in the United States. Over the past year, several
lawsuits have been filed in Argentina by citizens _ inspired by
similar U.S. cases _ seeking damages as a result of health problems
related to cigarette smoking. Many offices, particularly those with
U.S. headquarters, are moving toward a no-smoking policy, according
to Daino, who is asked to give motivational talks at many U.S.
multinational companies in Argentina.
 &HT;    Key legislation, however, has been stalled in the Argentine
Congress for months. A proposed law that would make it obligatory
to include the contents of cigarettes on the outside of each pack
has been heavily opposed by cigarette manufacturers, Daino says.
 &HT;    While legislation limiting cigarette advertising to the hours
between 10 p.m. and 8 a.m. already exists, more-far-reaching
regulations are being resisted, particularly by the advertising
industry. The proposed legislation would ban advertising in
publications or at activities targeted at minors. Cigarette
advertisers would also be prohibited from using artistic or sports
personalities popular with minors and would not be permitted to
associate smoking with sports.
 &HT;    In the meantime, cigarette advertising in Argentina remains
high-profile and is largely targeted at young smokers, who
represent one quarter of Argentina's 11 million smokers, or 33
percent of the population. The controversial Joe Camel cartoon ads
that were banned in the United States have been a frequent outdoor
advertisement.
 &HT;    In April, ad agency Verdino Bates launched a new campaign in
which consumers collect four different collector cigarette packs
and then send them in for the chance to win a Harley-Davidson
motorcycle or a Mustang automobile. The winners are announced every
Thursday at midnight during a mini-program featuring a well-known
guest musician.
 &HT;    Camel is manufactured by Nobleza-Piccardo, a subsidiary of
British American Tobacco, which boasts 38 percent of the Argentina
market. The tobacco company's only rival is Massalin Particulares,
a subsidiary of Philip Morris, which claims 62 percent of the 3.2
billion cigarettes sold in Argentina each year. It's Philip
Morris's highest market share in the world, thanks largely to its
Marlboro brand, which alone holds a 37 percent stake in the market.
 &HT;    In 1997, Philip Morris chose Argentina as the first country in
the American hemisphere in which to launch its Chesterfield Brown
cigarette brand, also aimed at younger smokers. Chesterfield Brown
sponsors an alternative radio program, the Chesterfield Music Box,
as well as hitting the Buenos Aires nightclubs with samplings and
giveaways.
 &HT;    But while Philip Morris is clearly targeting the younger end of
the market, it draws the line at cartoons like the Camel Joe
campaign, according to Andres Gomez, senior brands manager for
Massalin Particulares. All models used in Philip Morris ads must be
older than 21. The company avoids promoting cigarettes near high
schools and prohibits the selling of promotional merchandise to
teenagers under 18.
 &HT;    ``No Philip Morris brand would ever be advertised with
cartoons,'' he says. ``We have a strict internal code and we are
fighting so that the industry has a code of self-censorship so that
these things don't happen.''
 &HT;    Brazil smokin'. The anti-smoking brigade has come to Brazil, but
in a much smaller way _ maybe because the industry has such a
dominant effect on its economy.
 &HT;    And it is impressive: Brazil is the leading exporter of raw
tobacco, the fourth-largest producer of raw tobacco and the
sixth-largest producer of cigarettes in the world.
 &HT;    Two companies dominate the tobacco market in Brazil. Souza Cruz
S.A., the subsidiary of British American Tobacco, controls 84
percent of the Brazilian cigarette market with seven of the top 10
brands, including Derby, a discount brand that has cornered 42
percent of the market, followed by Free, Hollywood, Carlton, Plaza,
Belmont and Charm. The three remaining brands _ Dallas, Marlboro
and LM _ are made by Philip Morris, which holds a 14 percent share
of the market.
 &HT;    In 1997, Brazil produced 182.8 billion cigarettes, of which 72
billion were exported, more than seven times the level of 1990.
``Today, our tobacco quality is as good as the Americans and we
sell them at cheaper prices than they do,'' brags Nestor Jost,
president of the Brazilian Tobacco Industry Association, Associacao
Brasileira das Industrias de Fumo (ABIFUMO).
 &HT;    Souza Cruz has three plants in Brazil: Minas Gerais, Sao Paulo
and the Rio Grande do Sul facility, which was completed in December
1996 at a cost of $81 million. It covers 250 acres and is capable
of processing 100,000 tons of tobacco a year, making it the largest
and most modern in the world. Philip Morris, meanwhile, operates
two plants in Brazil, one in Parana and the other in Rio Grande do
Sul.
 &HT;    Despite the export drive, Brazilian consumption is steadily
declining.
 &HT;    After 20 years of steady growth, domestic consumption has
plummeted from 164.1 billion cigarettes in 1990 to 110.8 billion in
1997.
 &HT;    For Jost, the decline is not as dramatic as the figures show.
Although he agrees there are fewer smokers, the figures are
representative of the increase in contraband, which makes up 20
percent to 25 percent of the Brazilian market.
 &HT;    Nevertheless, the consumption decline may also be attributed to
a federal law enacted in 1996 that regulated cigarette
advertisements and banned smoking in public places, except when
separate, well-ventilated smoking sections are provided.
 &HT;    Tobacco manufacturers reacted by running newspaper ads arguing
that both smokers and non smokers have rights and appealed to both
groups to learn to coexist.
 &HT;    But the frontier between smoking and no-smoking areas in Rio de
Janeiro's bars and restaurants is as blurred as the haze of smoke
in the air. ``There seems to be a smoking section and a smoky
section,'' Jaime Cagy, a 53-year-old businessman and non-smoker,
said as he was having a drink at a beach side restaurant in Rio de
Janeiro.
 &HT;    The law also forbids smoking on airline flights of less than one
hour and restricts television advertising of cigarettes between 9
p.m. and 6 a.m.
 &HT;    But legislation against the tobacco industry may become even
more rigorous. A government bill has been sent to Congress
forbidding cigarette advertisements on television before 11 p.m.,
aiming to prevent young people from falling for the industry's
appealing ads. It's expected to be voted on after the October
presidential elections.
 &HT;    The Mexican invasion. Anti-smoking campaigns have hit Mexico,
too. But that hasn't prevented international tobacco giants from
gobbling up Mexican tobacco companies.
 &HT;    Last year, British American Tobacco bought Cigarrera La Moderna
from Monterrey-based conglomerate Pulsar Internacional for $1.7
billion, the largest purchase ever of a Mexican company by a
foreign one. Just before that, Philip Morris upped its stake in
Cigarros La Tabacalera Mexicana (Cigatam) from 29 percent to 49
percent for $400 million. Along with Grupo Carso, Cigatam's
majority owner, Philip Morris also opened a Mexico City office to
handle the marketing for Marlboro and its other brands.
 &HT;    The acquisitions marked the end of an era. For years, La Moderna
and Cigatam were cash cows for their respective owners, helping to
make Pulsar's Alfonso Romo Garza a major corporate player and
powering the rise of Carso Chairman Carlos Slim. Both made Forbes
magazine's list of billionaires this year.
 &HT;    But stagnant demand and the recent economic crisis brought flat
sales and thinning margins, taking the fire out of the $1.4 billion
tobacco market.
 &HT;    The foreign invaders hope to change that with better marketing
and industry know-how. They believe the Mexican market has room to
grow. Mexicans still smoke substantially less than consumers in
rich countries.
 &HT;    ``Penetration in Mexico has not reached the levels it has in the
U.S.,'' says Urban Larson, who tracks Grupo Carso at Santander
Investment in Mexico City. ``Cigarettes are a luxury.''
 &HT;    Rather than snaring first-time smokers with Joe Camel, the
multinational tobacco companies appear to be going after Mexican
females, only 14 percent of whom smoke. Indeed, some of the most
recent ads from several brands show suave, stylish women enjoying a
good cigarette _ much as Virginia Slims did in the United States in
the 1970s.
 &HT;    Cigarette makers are also targeting Mexico's young, upwardly
mobile middle class. Cigatam's Broadway, for example, shows
commercials of hip Mexicans in their 20s and 30s going out to
nightclubs, kissing each other and playing with puppies.
 &HT;    But the cigarette makers also want to retain their 38 percent
hold on Mexican males. Cigatam's macho Marlboro Man is a visible
and popular figure south of the border. Moderna's Boots also uses a
cowboy theme.
 &HT;    So far, their efforts are being felt. Altogether, cigarette
consumption in Mexico has grown during the first five months of the
year.
 &HT;    It helps that Mexico has a looser regulatory structure. Smoking
is currently banned on all airline flights of less than two hours.
But compared with the fierce anti-smoking sentiment in the United
States, Mexicans are relatively tolerant of the burning weed.
 &HT;    Philip Morris's efforts appear to be paying off, at least in
terms of volume. Cigatam sold 9.5 million cigarettes over the first
five months of the year, up 13 percent over the same period last
year. That pushed Cigatam into a virtual tie with La Moderna, whose
sales of 9.6 million cigarettes actually fell 0.3 percent over last
year.
 &HT;    Cigatam's 1997 price cuts and the ongoing economic recovery are
driving the revival. Lower prices have coaxed consumers back to
Marlboro country from cheaper brands and nearly eliminated
counterfeit Marlboros. A pack of Marlboros now goes for an average
of nine pesos, or about $1 _ substantially less than the 12 pesos
it used to cost and not much higher than down-market Cigatam brands
such as Broadway, Faros and Delicados, and La Moderna brands such
as Boots and Montana.
 &HT;    ``Marlboro sales are very responsive to prices, so Cigatam has
made up ground in market share this year,'' says Leonardo Zinser,
an analyst at Deutsche Morgan Grenfell in Mexico City.
 &HT;    If the economic recovery continues, sales volume could continue
to grow and margins in the high teens _ compared with traditional
levels in the high 20s before the crisis _ might get a small boost
as well.
 &HT;    Colombian contraband. Colombia could be the next frontier for
some of the multinational cigarette giants.
 &HT;    The country's tobacco industry is controlled by two companies:
Coltabaco, which trades on the Colombian stock market, and Pro
Tobacco, which is privately held. Both companies have been hammered
by contraband, which makes up between 50 percent and 60 percent of
the market.
 &HT;    ``It's a longstanding problem,'' says Rue Swabey, an analyst at
Santander Investment in Bogota. ``Contraband has kept a roof on
prices, and over the years, it's worn down the tobacco companies.
The industry is really depressed.''
 &HT;    Enter the foreign tobacco companies. Philip Morris considered
acquiring Contabalco in 1995, but never consummated the deal. It's
now said to be in discussions with Pro Tobacco. British American
Tobacco has also expressed interest in entering the Colombian
market.
 &HT;    In the meantime, Coltabaco has combated the problem by
diversifying, buying up chunks of banks, insurance companies and
construction firms. For example, it has a joint venture with
U.S.-based Kimberly Clark, which makes tisue, cigarettes and
writing paper. Its investment portfolio was recently worth around
$300 million.
 &HT;    If the contraband problem and the anti-smoking movement
continues, perhaps other tobacco companies in the region should
consider doing the same.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.1998 Latin Trade 
