<SLUG> BC-AIDS-RECRUIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIDS CONSORTIUM TO RECRUIT VOLUNTEERS FOR TESTING OF AIDS VACCINE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN BAVLEY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City AIDS Research Consortium was bracing for phone
calls Wednesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   At 8 a.m., the consortium was to begin accepting applications
from area residents for the first large-scale test of a vaccine
against AIDS. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City is among the first 10 cities to participate in a
nationwide study of AIDSVAX, the only AIDS vaccine to reach the
final stage of testing, the consortium announced Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 150 volunteers will be recruited locally for the three- to
four-year study. About 5,000 people in several dozen cities in the
United States and 2,500 people in Thailand will participate. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If the test shows AIDSVAX prevents AIDS infection, its
manufacturer, VaxGen of Brisbane, Calif., will ask the U.S. Food
and Drug Administration to approve its general use. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting numerous, numerous phone calls over the next
few weeks,'' said Jan Meier, the consortium's clinical director and
supervisor of the vaccine study. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The consortium seeks men and women for the study who are at high
risk of contracting AIDS but currently free from HIV, the AIDS
virus, Meier said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, that includes men who have sex with men and women
who have had a sexually transmitted disease and more than one male
sex partner in the last year. Intravenous drug users are
ineligible. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Subjects will receive seven injections _ three shots of the
vaccine and four booster shots _ in a 30-month period. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To make a valid comparison between vaccinated and unvaccinated
people, two-thirds of the subjects will get the actual vaccine,
while one-third will receive a placebo, an inactive substance that
looks the same as the vaccine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All subjects will undergo periodic blood tests and receive
frequent counseling on safe-sex AIDS prevention. Studies have
shown, however, that people at high risk of AIDS generally do not
follow safe-sex advice. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Researchers will not know whether the vaccine works unless some
of the participants engage in sex with HIV-infected partners, but
test subjects will be urged not to assume that the vaccine will
protect them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Although we suspect AIDSVAX will work, we don't know for a
certainty,'' said David McKinsey, the principal physician involved
in the Kansas City study. ``Even in the best-case scenario, the
vaccine is not going to be 100 percent effective.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If after three years results show the vaccine is highly
effective, the study will be stopped and all participants on
placebos will get the vaccine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The consortium will begin distributing fliers announcing the
trial to coffeehouses, bars and stores. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We're basically going to blanket as much of the community as
we can,'' said Patti Abshier, the consortium's outreach
coordinator. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AIDSVAX testing began June 23 in Philadelphia. Since then, test
sites have opened in Los Angeles, St. Louis, Chicago, Washington
and several other cities. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To bring the vaccine trial to Kansas City, the consortium and
community leaders. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt like because we're not one of the largest populations
in the country we really had to show our interest,'' said Gary
Johnson, executive director of the consortium. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AIDS vaccine research has suffered recent setbacks. Scientists
who tested a vaccine made from weakened but live HIV on monkeys
found it eventually caused illness and offered limited protection
from infection. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The AIDSVAX vaccine does not use HIV itself. Instead, it
contains a protein the virus uses as a biological ``key'' to enter
and destroy human cells. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By priming the body's immune system to recognize this protein,
scientists hope that people exposed to HIV will be able to mount a
successful fight against the virus. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The scientific community has met AIDSVAX with skepticism because
the National Institutes of Health decided in 1994 that a vaccine
based on the protein was too weak to study. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VaxGen says it has improved the vaccine so that it is effective
against the two HIV strains most common in the United States. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a test on chimpanzees, AIDSVAX was effective in preventing
infection. And in small trials on people in the United States and
Thailand, more than 90 percent of subjects who received the vaccine
developed antibodies, an indication the vaccine may protect against
HIV. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like being on the leading edge,'' said Nzeera
Virani-Ketter, senior director of medical affairs at VaxGen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There are groups of people who think it will never work. There
are groups of people who are sure it will work. And there are
people who think a good study is needed. I'm in that middle
group.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Roger Gooden, a Kansas City resident and chairman of the
National Association of People With AIDS, said he was thrilled the
vaccine would be available locally. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He cautioned, however, that even if the vaccine worked, more
research must be done. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take away our commitment to end the epidemic,''
Gooden said. ``We won't rest quietly until we have a cure.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Persons interested in participating in the AIDSVAX study may
call the AIDS Research Consortium at 931-5477. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1749EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
