r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUMMY-KITTEN-KAN &LR;      10-07 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUMMY-KITTEN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BELIEVED A FAKE, MUMMIFIED KITTEN IS PROVEN TO BE REAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LYNN FRANEY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, Mo. _ For decades, scientists thought a 2,000-year-old
mummified kitten from Egypt was a fake. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But on a computer screen Tuesday at the University of
Missouri-Columbia, the truth was clear: There really was a cat
inside the wrappings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh! It's real! Cool!'' exclaimed Patricia Podzorski, an
Egyptology scholar at MU. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A CT-scanner's computer image, just a few millimeters thick,
showed the inside of the mummified kitten. The black space
representing the inside of a skull and the bright white images of
bones showed that this was a real kitten that had been wrapped in
linen and probably offered to an Egyptian god. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought there might have been a mistake,'' said Jane Biers,
curator of ancient art at the MU Museum of Art and Archaeology,
where the kitten and two other animal mummies _ a baby crocodile
and a hawk _ are on display. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``That's great!'' exclaimed Luann Andrews, the museum's curator
of education, as she witnessed the scientific discovery in an
imaging room in the Veterinary Medical Teaching Hospital. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It had been her idea to follow the lead of other schools and put
the animals through the CT-scanner so they could be explored
without disturbing their ancient wrappings. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The three mummified animals are on loan to MU from the Field
Museum of Chicago. Andrews has planned three programs for children
on Halloween to explore the animal mummies and the computer
images. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an effort to help kids understand that science and
technology can help us,'' Andrews said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How science can help was evident Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Podzorski and Biers were shocked to learn the truth about an
object they had always accepted as a fake, and that researchers
thought had been sold to an unsuspecting Egyptian who wanted to
please the gods thousands of years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Field Museum and MU have displayed the kitten in earlier
exhibits, but with the understanding that there wasn't a kitten
inside. With the scanning images recorded Tuesday, researchers can
try to determine the cat's age, its physical condition, how it died
and whether anything was wrapped with it. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The same evaluations will be done on the baby crocodile, which
is less than a foot and a half long, and the baby hawk, whose beak
and one talon partly peek out of the wrapping. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Lattimer, associate professor of veterinary medicine and
surgery, expected to spend several weeks analyzing hundreds of
computer images of the three animals. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Already, he said, the project has proven its value: The
discovery of the real kitten ``makes the whole project
worthwhile.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Researchers analyze mummies to find out more about ancient
Egyptian culture and religion. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Egyptians mummified animals for different reasons for more than
1,000 years before the birth of Christ, Podzorski said. Pets often
were mummified and buried with their owners. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other animals that represented certain gods were mummified and
offered as votive gifts to the gods at temples. For example, cats
were associated with the goddess Bastet, a good protectress, or the
lioness-goddess Sekhmet, a ferocious goddess of war, plague and
pestilence. Cat cemeteries have been found throughout Egypt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The kitten studied Tuesday probably was wrapped in linen between
664 and 30 B.C. The baby crocodile probably dates to between 323
B.C. and 200 A.D. and was dedicated to the god Sobek, who took the
form of a crocodile. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Major crocodile cults existed along the Nile River. The
crocodile's linen wrappings are in several shades of brown and tan,
woven in a geometric pattern that resembles a shortbread cookie. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The mummified hawk probably was dedicated to one of several gods
associated with falcons, such as the sky god Horus, the war god
Montu and the sun god Re. In Memphis, Egypt, nearly a half-million
falcon mummies, identified with Horus, were found in huge burial
galleries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, the MU researchers hope to try to determine the three
animals' ages and sexes. They also will try to determine whether
the animals died naturally or were killed before being wrapped, and
whether their internal organs were removed or left inside. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope when we start slicing and dicing in different
directions, (these characteristics) will become more obvious,''
Lattimer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
