<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFTWARE-INTERNET-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOFTWARE COMPANY'S IMAGE WILL GET A BOOST WITH INTERNET
`SHOPPING' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bobbie Dreis-Ayers needed a high-end piece of computer equipment
to start her business. The company that built the equipment would
deal only with established businesses. It was a classic Catch-22. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Dreis-Ayers found a solution that was part ``Saturday Night
Live,'' part Rube Goldberg. She went to her brother's business and
recorded office sounds _ a phone ringing here, a person typing at a
computer keyboard there. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Then she went back to her home and called the computer company,
playing the recorded office noise in the background. She got the
equipment. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That was $5 million and eight years ago. The glorified closet
that once was the headquarters of Visual Applications Inc. is now
just one of a suite of offices that houses the growing software
company in North Kansas City. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A couple of recent developments could make that growth spurt
look almost puny. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visual Applications recently cut a deal with a major partner
that could expand the company's software sales exponentially. The
agreement with Macmillan Digital Publishing USA could more than
quadruple the number of retailers who carry the company's Imagine
home improvement software. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That would be big news for any small software company, but the
agreement with Macmillan almost takes a back seat to something else
the company is doing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visual Applications is taking on the Internet, and company
officials think they have software that's a step ahead of anything
else on the ever-developing on-line network _ something they think
might even change the way people use the Net. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The software, called cMyVision, will be available free on the
Internet early next year. It uses new technology and allows
computer users to easily move images from Internet Web sites into
any digital photograph or drawing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Furniture can be moved into a photograph of a living room.
Consumers using a photograph of themselves could try on clothing
without going to the mall. Homebuyers could see if their
landscaping vision for that new home would really work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Users of the Web-based software will be able to experimentally
make changes without altering anything. The new technology allows
the Internet to become a virtual database of design ideas,
Dreis-Ayers said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the only way to move images from the Internet into a
photograph is save the image onto a computer's hard drive and then
use relatively complex software to merge the two images. For
routine work, it isn't practical. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Visual Applications software allows users to click on an
image at an Internet site and drag that image into the company's
software. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Kansas City is the last place someone would expect for
somebody to come out with technology that will lead the industry,
but we did it,'' Dreis-Ayers said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An elevator ride sold Barry Friedman on Visual Applications. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friedman, a top software agent who says he's on a first-name
basis with Bill Gates and whose company represents other businesses
that sell $100 million worth of software a year, met Dreis-Ayers at
a software publishing convention in California. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard them talking about what they had on the elevator, and
I started talking to them,'' Friedman said. ``I doubted that they
had what they said, but as soon as I saw it, I immediately asked to
represent them. I usually turn down 99 of the 100 software
publishers who come to me.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friedman brought in others to look at the cMyVision software,
setting up an advisory board for Visual Applications that includes
top software and business executives from across the country. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an obvious technological advancement they've made
that's applicable to other fields of business,'' said Friedman,
president of the International Computer Group. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Visual Applications Web site, where the software will be
tested, initially will feature only home remodeling and decorating
products. The company is planning to expand quickly with apparel
and other products. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Visual Applications officials are unveiling the software in
private showings this week at Internet World, one of the industry's
top trade shows. The show starts today in New York. Next month, the
company will have a booth in Las Vegas at Comdex, the world's
leading computer trade show. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Initially, the cMyVision product is likely to be little more
than a fun software toy on the Internet. Users will be able to
alter pictures of their homes and friends, save the photos, print
them out and even send them by e-mail. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That alone could make cMyVision a valuable product to retailers
and manufacturers because it will keep people on Web sites longer
as they look for images to use in their photographs, Dreis-Ayers
said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Visual Applications officials think cMyVision has other,
more significant potential. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What this does is take a seller's product into a potential
customer's home and allows them to view them and try them,'' said
Charles Macan, executive vice president of Visual Applications.
``It increases the likelihood of a sale. They can buy it on line,
or print the picture off and say, `I want this.' '' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Macan said the process could revolutionize commerce on the
Internet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Home centers, paint and wallpaper manufacturers, clothing makers
and other businesses could open up a whole new kind of Web-based
advertising, Dreis-Ayers said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Visual Applications will be allowing consumers to
download the software free, there are plenty of opportunities for
the company to make money, Dreis-Ayers said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company charges retailers or manufacturers a small fee to
``enable'' their products to be easily incorporated into the
cMyVision software. The potential for electronic commerce could
bring in more revenue. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although cMyVision is essentially a free, on-line version of the
company's basic in-the-box software product, Visual Applications
officials think sales of their core product won't be affected. In
fact, they think the opposite will happen. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The company's deal with Macmillan will put the software in
large, traditional retailers, not just computer stores and software
sellers. Sales, which grew by 75 percent this year, are projected
to grow by 250 percent next year. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``What we've sold in retail in four years, they're going to sell
in two months,'' Dreis-Ayers said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Friedman said the Macmillan agreement was important because
Visual Applications' two largest competitors _ Sierra On-line and
Broderbund Software _ are billion-dollar companies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to have Visual Applications compete against a
billion-dollar company,'' Friedman said. ``So the answer was to
partner with a billion-dollar company.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
