<HEADLINE>
BLACK BEAN SOUP WOULD MAKE MISS ELLIE PROUD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doreen Bryan of Bellevue, Neb., e-mailed looking for the recipe
for the black bean soup served at Miss Ellie's Deli at Southfork
Ranch in Dallas. Executive chef Bill Bush was kind enough to break
down the recipe and send it along to us.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHFORK RANCH BLACK BEAN SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Serves 10-12
</P>
<P>
   1 pound dry black beans
</P>
<P>
   20 cups water
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup diced raw bacon
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   1 cup diced fresh tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon chili powder
</P>
<P>
   6 chicken bouillon cubes OR 4 tablespoons chicken base, see Note
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons fresh garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt, optional
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon cayenne pepper, optional
</P>
<P>
   Check beans for small stones, then rinse, place in water and
boil until tender (about 1 1/2 hours).
</P>
<P>
   Saute bacon and onions until brown, adding fresh garlic when
bacon is almost done. Add sauteed mixture to beans, along with
remaining ingredients. Simmer for 15-30 minutes until broth
thickens.
</P>
<P>
   Note: Base is bouillon in a paste form and is frequently used in
institutional cooking. It is available in larger grocery stores,
usually in chicken and beef flavors.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 158 calories, 2 grams fat, 25
grams carbohydrates, 10 grams protein, 3 milligrams cholesterol,
637 milligrams sodium, 14 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   ANOTHER FAMOUS SOUP: A couple of readers sent in the recipe for
the peanut bisque served at ``some restaurant in Waxahachie.'' The
restaurant was the Durham House, and what follows is the recipe,
courtesy of Arlene Haynes of Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   DURHAM HOUSE PEANUT BISQUE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 8
</P>
<P>
   6 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped celery
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chopped onion
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons flour
</P>
<P>
   4 1/2 cups strong chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1 cup smooth peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1/8 teaspoon white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon Hungarian sweet paprika
</P>
<P>
   2 1/2 cups half-and-half
</P>
<P>
   3 drops Tabasco sauce
</P>
<P>
   Chives, for garnish
</P>
<P>
   Melt butter. Add celery and onions and cook until tender. Puree
in blender. Return to pan and add flour, stirring with a wire
whisk. Gradually add chicken stock and cook until thickened and
mixture comes to a boil. Stir in peanut butter, salt, pepper,
paprika and Tabasco. Remove from heat and add cream; return to heat
and bring to serving temperature but below a boil. Sprinkle with
chopped chives when serving. Will refrigerate for 1 week and
freezes well if you omit the cream until ready to serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 383 calories, 33 grams fat, 14
grams carbohydrates, 11 grams protein, 52 milligrams cholesterol,
144 milligrams sodium, 78 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE SWEET SIDE: A reader writes looking for a recipe for
chocolate gravy. Our most recent Virginia import, reporter Larry
Bingham, says he grew up eating his granny's chocolate gravy _
actually, it was canned Hershey's syrup. (Sometime I'll tell you
about my friend who didn't realize until she went to college that
spaghetti sauce is not ketchup.) At any rate, this is a staple of
some regions of the South, and here's the recipe from ``Smokehouse
Ham, Spoon Bread and Scuppernong Wine: The Folklore and Art of
Southern Appalachian Cooking'' by Joseph E. Dabney (Cumberland
House, $27.95).
</P>
<P>
   KENTUCKY CHOCOLATE GRAVY
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   1 cup European-style cocoa
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   2 cups milk
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 teaspoons vanilla
</P>
<P>
   In saucepan, combine cocoa, sugar and flour. Stir until well
mixed and flour and cocoa lumps disappear. Pour in milk gradually.
Bring mixture to boiling, simmer 1 minute and stir in vanilla.
Remove from heat. Serve over open biscuit halves.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 200 calories, 5 grams fat, 40
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 11 milligrams cholesterol, 44
milligrams sodium, 21 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   Requests:
</P>
<P>
   Roxanne Weaver would like a recipe for Canadian cheese soup.
</P>
<P>
   A reader would like the recipe for bread pudding that includes
egg bread from the Shady Oaks Country Club in Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
