<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 17:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4640 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEAFOOD-PETERSON-TEX     10-07 0790
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAFOOD-PETERSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO BUY THE FRESHEST SEAFOOD, COURTESY OF COOKBOOK AUTHOR JAMES
PETERSON
</HEADLINE>
 
(EDS: Accompanied by SEAFOOD-RECIPES) (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH, Texas _ James Peterson came to town recently to
market his new cookbook, ``Vegetables'' (William Morrow, $35). But
this is Texas, and we know our vegetables _ well, the white one
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   So we decided to avail ourselves of some of Peterson's other
knowledge. In 1996, Peterson won an International Association of
Culinary Professionals cookbook award for his ``Fish &AMP; Shellfish''
(William Morrow, $40). So, to get his tips on buying fish, we took
him to a local fish counter.
</P>
<P>
   For a New York boy, he was pretty impressed. In this day and
age, it's not necessary to live by an ocean or river to get good
seafood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Salmon is very cheap now because so much of it is farmed,''
Peterson says. ``In a lot of ways, the farm-raised salmon is better
than wild salmon. It's fattier, for one thing, and so has more
flavor. And because it's farmed, it's fresh, because there is a
system in place of getting it from the water to the consumer. It's
packed in ice immediately and moved out.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he lives near the Fulton Fish Market, the Valhalla of
fish wholesalers, he finds the fish there not always as
well-handled as it could be, and so is hardly disapproving of the
farm-to-market approach.
</P>
<P>
   The Paris-trained chef and teacher says the French are blessed
with their bounty from the sea. Because they have the Mediterranean
Sea and the English Channel, they can reap both cold-water and
warm-water offerings. But we have offerings that Peterson says we
ignore.
</P>
<P>
   What we've done, Peterson says, is turn what was naturally a
cheap food source into an expensive luxury. By concentrating on
tuna, swordfish, salmon, red snapper and halibut, Americans have
bypassed fish like mullet, which can be just as satisfying. As a
New Yorker, he must go to ethnic markets to find even catfish.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians, the Spanish, the English, the French all have
histories as big fish eaters. But after a few generations of being
in America, their diets are assimilated into the national table of
beef, pork and chicken. That's why Peterson recommends shopping in
ethnic markets for seafood.
</P>
<P>
   But not all change is bad. Peterson is glad to see one fish fad
fade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orange roughy; thank God that's gone,'' he says. ``Someone did
a great sales job on that fish. It's caught and frozen, then
brought in and thawed and filleted and then frozen again to send to
stores, where it gets thawed out again.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are James Peterson's tips for buying seafood:
</P>
<P>
   1. Buy whole fish if you can. It's easier to judge quality.
</P>
<P>
   2. The old rule of checking for clarity of the eyes doesn't
always wash. Some fish simply have cloudy eyes. Instead, look for
eyes that protrude, as if the fish is animated.
</P>
<P>
   3. Look under the gills. They should be bright cherry red.
</P>
<P>
   4. Smell the gills. They should smell like the ocean.
</P>
<P>
   5. The tail should not be dried out.
</P>
<P>
   6. When buying lobster, ask how long they've been in the tank.
Once they're in a tank at the supermarket, they're not fed, so it's
as if they're on a diet, and the meat begins to melt away.
</P>
<P>
   7. Whole fish should have a sheen. If the skin is leathery or
has wrinkles, the fish has lost enough moisture to be past its
prime.
</P>
<P>
   8. Some whole fish have color striations when they are extremely
fresh. Mahi-mahi, for instance, has yellow and blue in its skin
when it is right out of the water. Not having the color doesn't
mean the fish is too old; it's just not right out of the water.
Mackerel, too, can be quite beautiful, with blue and green
markings.
</P>
<P>
   9. Fillets are harder to judge, but one place to look is along
the bone line. The color there should be red, not brown.
</P>
<P>
   10. When buying tuna, the flesh should look almost beefy and
full. When tuna is marked as ``sashimi quality'' _ meaning it can
be eaten raw _ it's an indication of freshness.
</P>
<P>
   11. When buying shrimp, ask to smell them. They should smell
like nothing _ and particularly not ammonia.
</P>
<P>
   12. Peterson prefers to buy shrimp uncooked because it is so
easily overcooked. Also, he prefers to buy shrimp in the shell,
because it has more flavor.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to Beverly Bundy, Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, Texas 76101. Or E-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
