<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAFOOD-RECIPES-2ndTake-TEX </SLUG>
 
UNDATED: calories from fat. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROILED STRIPED BASS OR MAHI-MAHI FILLETS WITH MUSTARD AND
TOMATO SAUCES
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4 as first course
</P>
<P>
   2 (8-ounce) striped bass or mahi-mahi fillets, skin and small
bones removed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Mustard sauce:
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon whole-grain mustard (moutarde de Meaux)
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup heavy cream, whipped
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground white pepper
</P>
<P>
   Tomatoes:
</P>
<P>
   2 ripe tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Cut each fillet into two 3-inch squares. If fillets are more
than 1/2-inch thick, butterfly them by cutting sideways almost all
the way through with a sharp knife and folding them open so they
end up between 1/4 and 1/2 inch thick.
</P>
<P>
   Whisk together mustard and whipped cream. Season to taste with
pepper; refrigerate until needed.
</P>
<P>
   Cut tomatoes in half crosswise, squeeze each half to eliminate
seeds, and chop coarsely. Cook tomatoes over medium heat in small
saucepan, stirring every few minutes to prevent sticking. When
tomatoes have cooked down to a thick paste, after about 15 minutes,
work through strainer with the back of a small ladle. Season tomato
sauce with salt and pepper to taste.
</P>
<P>
   Light broiler and heat large dinner plates in 200 degree oven.
(If you have only one oven, leave the door open so plates don't get
too hot.) Arrange fish fillets _ most attractive side up _ on a
baking sheet brushed with olive oil, and spread about 1/2
tablespoon of mustard sauce on top of each fillet. Heat tomato
sauce on low heat or in bowl in microwave.
</P>
<P>
   Slide baking sheet under broiler so tops of fillets are within 2
inches of heat source. You may have to move baking sheet around so
each fillet cooks evenly. Broil until sauce on each fillet sizzles
and browns lightly, 1 1/2 to 3 minutes. (The fish cooks most of the
way through under the broiler; the underside cooks on the plates.)
</P>
<P>
   Spread the tomato sauce in a circle in center of each of the hot
plates. Place a hot fillet in center of sauce and serve
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 217 calories, 15 grams fat, 3
grams carbohydrates, 18 grams protein, 58 milligrams cholesterol,
125 milligrams sodium, 61 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Fish &AMP; Shellfish'' by James Peterson (William Morrow, $40)
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FOR ``FRESH'' FISH, TRY ASIAN MARKETS
</P>
<P>
   Although mainstream supermarkets offer a solid selection of
seafood, area Asian markets are swimming with the stuff _ often,
quite literally.
</P>
<P>
   Most Asian markets get their big shipments of fish on Fridays,
making it fresh for the weekend. Often, crates are piled on the
floor, filled with live blue crabs, periwinkles, iced-down king
fish, milk fish and black pomfret. There are whole squid bodies,
cleaned of their pins and tentacles, and there are plastic bags
full of octopuses.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the usual supermarket offerings are also available _ but
with a difference. The shrimp are often sold with their head on,
perfect for stock or bisque. The catfish are often alive in a tank.
Ask the fish man, and he'll plop the catfish on the floor so you
can see how lively it is. If it's lively enough for you, he'll
dispatch it in front of your eyes. Now that's fresh.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   The seafood diet
</P>
<P>
   The average American ate just over 12 pounds of seafood in 1997.
Here's how it breaks down by species:
</P>
<P>
   Tuna, 3.1 pounds
</P>
<P>
   Shrimp, 2.7 pounds
</P>
<P>
   Pollock from Alaska, 1.6 pounds
</P>
<P>
   Salmon, 1.3 pounds
</P>
<P>
   Cod, 1.0 pound
</P>
<P>
   Catfish, 1.0 pound
</P>
<P>
   Clams, 0.5 pound
</P>
<P>
   Crab, 0.4 pound
</P>
<P>
   Flounder/Sole, 0.3 pound
</P>
<P>
   Halibut, 0.3 pound
</P>
<P>
   Source: National Fisheries Institute
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
