<HEADER>
A4644 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SEAFOOD-RECIPES-840(2     10-07 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEAFOOD-RECIPES-840(2Takes)-TEX </SLUG>
 
(EDS: Accompanies SEAFOOD-PETERSON) 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BEVERLY BUNDY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that you've picked it out, here's how to cook it.
</P>
<P>
   WHOLE BAKED RED SNAPPER
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   One (3- to 4-pound) or two (1 1/2- to 2-pound) red snappers,
gutted, gills removed and scales left on
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   Extra-virgin olive oil and lemon wedges, for serving
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Rub fish with olive oil and place
in an oiled oval pan, gratin dish or sheet pan. Bake for about 15
minutes per inch of thickness at thickest part. Check for doneness
by carefully sliding a paring knife into the back at the thickest
part, gently lifting top fillet and peeking inside to make sure
fish pulls away from the bone and the flesh is opaque (but still
moist), rather than translucent and raw.
</P>
<P>
   Serve on hot plates in dining room. Let guests season their own
fish with salt, pepper, olive oil and lemon.
</P>
<P>
   Other fish: This technique also works with such whole fish as
blackfish, black sea bass, freshwater bass, drums, porgy, rockfish,
sea robin, sea trout, tilapia and weakfish.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 287 calories, 10 grams fat, 0
carbohydrates, 46 grams protein, 84 milligrams cholesterol, 145
milligrams sodium, 31 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   SALMON FILLETS WITH WHITE WINE, BUTTER AND PARSLEY
</P>
<P>
   Serves 2
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons unsalted butter
</P>
<P>
   Two 6-ounce center-cut salmon fillets, about 1 1/2 inches thick
at the thickest part, skin and pin bones removed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons dry white wine
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon finely chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper
</P>
<P>
   With a third of the butter, butter a square microwave-safe
casserole dish with lid. Place salmon in the casserole, folding
stomach flaps under salmon fillets so the fillets are of even
thickness, and sprinkle with wine. Dot salmon with remaining
butter. Sprinkle on parsley, salt and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Set 2 wide soup plates in microwave. Cover casserole and place
it in microwave on top of soup plates. Heat on high for 5 minutes
(less if the fillets are thinner than 11/2 inches). If your
microwave does not have a turntable, give the casserole 3 quarter
turns, one every minute, so the salmon cooks evenly. Remove
casserole and let sit for 2 minutes _ don't open it _ before
serving.
</P>
<P>
   Use spatula to transfer fish to hot plates. If you wish, peel
skin off salmon steaks. Spoon on the liquid left in the casserole,
and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 300 calories, 17 grams fat,
trace carbohydrates, 34 grams protein, 110 milligrams cholesterol,
77 milligrams sodium, 51 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   THAI SHRIMP, CUCUMBER AND CARROT SALAD
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6 as first course
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 pounds headless extra-large or jumbo shrimp (5 shrimp per
serving), peeled and deveined if desired
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons safflower oil
</P>
<P>
   2 regular cucumbers OR 1 long European cucumber, peeled
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   2 large carrots, cut into 3-inch lengths
</P>
<P>
   2 Thai (bird) or jalapeno peppers, seeded and finely chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 large garlic cloves, finely chopped and crushed
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup unsweetened coconut milk
</P>
<P>
   3 teaspoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons crunchy peanut butter
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh cilantro
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons fresh lime juice (from about 1 1/2 limes)
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons rice wine vinegar OR white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons Thai fish sauce (nam pla)
</P>
<P>
   6 fresh cilantro sprigs
</P>
<P>
   Saute shrimp in oil over high heat for about 3 minutes and let
cool.
</P>
<P>
   Cut cucumbers in half lengthwise and scoop out the seeds with a
spoon. Slice halves into 1/8-inch-thick crescents and toss with
salt until all slices are well-coated. Let drain in refrigerator
for 30 minutes in a colander set over bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Finely grate carrots lengthwise down to woody core. Discard
cores and reserve grated carrots in small mixing bowl.
</P>
<P>
   In separate bowl, whisk together remaining ingredients, except
cilantro sprigs, to make a smooth sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Squeeze cucumber slices, a handful at a time, to eliminate as
much liquid as possible and place in small mixing bowl. Toss
cucumbers, shrimp and carrots with sauce in separate bowls. Arrange
cucumbers in middle of chilled plates, place small mound of carrots
in center, and top each plate with shrimp and a cilantro sprig.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 242 calories, 11 grams fat, 14
grams carbohydrates, 23 grams protein, 144 milligrams cholesterol,
527 milligrams sodium, 41 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
