<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT WEIGHS ENVIRONMENT AGAINST PROPERTY RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0228 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 18:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4681 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COURT-PROPERTY-RIGHTS     10-07 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COURT-PROPERTY-RIGHTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPREME COURT WEIGHS ENVIRONMENT AGAINST PROPERTY RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Supreme Court on Wednesday took up the question
of how far a city can go in infringing on property rights to
protect an endangered butterfly and the area it needs to live in.
</P>
<P>
   At issue was the use of regulations by the city of Monterey,
Calif., to block the development of privately-owned land in order
to save habitat for the Smith Blue Butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   The court's decision could provide new guidelines on the
government's obligation to compensate landowners when it limits the
use of their property.
</P>
<P>
   Michael M. Berger, representing the former owner of the land,
Del Monte Dunes at Monterey, Ltd., said the firm had tried to work
with the city to develop the land in a way that wouldn't hurt the
habitat but that the city had refused to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said his client had been ``simply strung along and abused
at the city's whim. ... What you have here is a pattern of abuse''
to ``protect a butterfly that nobody's ever seen there.''
</P>
<P>
   Berger told the justices that although the city had said that
the land could be developed, it rejected five plans offered by Del
Monte Dunes to build residential housing on the tract. He added
that each of the plans, which were submitted between 1983 and 1986,
had provisions to protect the area's buckwheat plants, which are
needed by the butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   But Monterey's lawyer, George A. Yuhas, contended the Del Monte
Dunes development plans never adequately addressed how the company
would protect the environmentally-sensitive area. That failure, he
said, left the city with no choice but to reject the plans.
</P>
<P>
   He said the company was unwilling to accept the city's zoning
regulations, which would have allowed the firm to build on 5.1
acres of the 37.6-acre tract.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Smith Blue Butterfly, Yuhas said the city relied on a
study by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, which said that
although the development did not threaten the existence of the
butterfly, it would destroy the important buckwheat habitat, which
could be used by later generations of the butterfly.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, after being turned down for the fifth time, Del Monte
Dunes sued the city, claiming Monterey had violated the so-called
``takings clause'' in the Constitution's Fifth Amendment, which
says that ``private property shall not be taken for public use
without just compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for the company argued before a U.S. District Court jury
that although Monterey had not physically taken the land away from
Del Monte Dunes, the city's regulations had made it impossible for
the firm to do anything with it. The company finally sold the
property in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The federal jury awarded the firm $1.45 million dollars in
damages. Monterey appealed the decision to the U.S. 9th Circuit
Court of Appeals and lost the appeal in 1996. Now the Supreme Court
must decide whether the jury's award can stand.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Antonin Scalia appeared to agree with Berger when he
questioned why the city had refused five separate plans to develop
the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though there's a reasonable explanation for the fifth
denial, or the third denial, or the second denial, after a while,
you begin to smell a rat,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yuhas argued that when environmental issues arise in connection
with land development, the decisions should be made by the
government, not private industry.
</P>
<P>
   Every government decision on environmentally-sensitive areas
would be jeopardized if ``all a developer needs to say is that `we
have an expert that says the regulation is excessive,''' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Del Monte Dunes in friend-of-the-court briefs
included the American Farm Bureau Federation, National Association
of Home Builders, National Association of Realtors and National
Cattlemen's Beef Association.
</P>
<P>
   Backing the city of Monterey were the National League of Cities,
National Conference of State Legislatures, National Association of
Counties, U.S. Conference of Mayors and 29 states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1812EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
