<SLUG> BC-TV-HOLDING-ON-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`HOLDING ON': UNWELL, CLINGING, DRIFTING AND BINGEING
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(nk) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Holding On'' is a determined exercise in nonjudgmental
documentary making. In what he calls ``A Love Story From the
Street,'' producer and director John Baynard delivers scenes from
five years of the hazy driftings of Donna Mercier and Luis
Santiago, from a tent on a Boston street to briefly occupied
apartments to campgrounds; the two hold on to each other except
when Santiago is doing time for shoplifting.
</P>
<P>
   He is a recovering crack addict who complains of hypertension,
diabetes, epilepsy, too much cholesterol, a failing lung, you name
it. She is being treated for chronic depression. They live on
disability checks, occasional help from her family and his
panhandling. When they come into some money, they binge; there they
go, all suited up, zooming off on their new motorcycle.
</P>
<P>
   They smoke a lot, weigh too much, don't manage their household
accounts very tidily and seem to be in an endless and failing fight
to get their lives together. They are as unprepossessing a pair as
has ever appeared in a television romance.
</P>
<P>
   Baynard's achievement is to offer viewers a close-up of lives
that do not usually invite inspection; at their most sympathetic,
they can be off-putting. Santiago in particular, though he shows
symptoms of self-regard, has little charm to spare. ``We're there
for each other,'' he says, but mainly he seems to be there when Ms.
Mercier can do something for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm all out of whack,'' he says in a plausible diagnosis. He's
a whiner, whose main redeeming quality, as evidenced here, is his
appeal to the infatuated Ms. Mercier. She just can't get enough of
him. Her father says, ``We're very sorry she's involved with such
an idiot,'' but she remains chronically or clinically loyal.
</P>
<P>
   The viewer, like her father, may see Santiago's jail term as an
opportunity for her to be rid of him, but no such luck. ``I miss
him a lot,'' she says. He may not be much, but what really scares
her is the prospect of losing her man.
</P>
<P>
   In their moments of cuddling, she looks more like his mother
than his squeeze. ``The worst that could happen to anybody,'' she
says, ``is to be alone.''
</P>
<P>
   The kindly disposed viewer may find a saving grace in their
relationship. Without Santiago, Ms. Mercier, aging fast, would be
on her own with the demons of depression; without her, it seems
doubtful that he could survive his impulse to self-destruction.
</P>
<P>
   The more hard-boiled or judgmental viewer may see dysfunction
running rampant. If Ms. Mercier could find the strength to shake
off Santiago, maybe her existence would take on some order. But
loneliness is probably too high a price to pay for that.
</P>
<P>
   BROADCAST NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HOLDING ON'
</P>
<P>
   A Love Story From the Street
</P>
<P>
   10 p.m. ET Thursday on PBS.
</P>
<P>
   Produced, directed and photographed by John Baynard. Denny
Houghton, associate producer; Tom Ryder, editor. A John Baynard
Production in association with Independent Television Service and
Eastern Educational Television Network. Presented by WGBH, Boston.
Judith Stoia, executive in charge for WGBH.
</P>
</TEXT>
