<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-RAP08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jay-Z knocks the money myth
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   At first, this doesn't seem like such rough living: Posing with
a black Bentley on the cover of the follow-up to your
million-selling album, screaming out ``Money Ain't a Thing'' as you
switch lanes in your Range Rover, and dedicating a song to all the
money and women you supposedly have.
</P>
<P>
   But what distinguishes Jay-Z from the plethora of other material
rappers is that his material goes much deeper, dealing smartly and
melodically with the untrustworthy people and trouble such
pleasures attract.
</P>
<P>
   As catchy as the bubbly ``Can I Get a ...'' is, stop moving a
minute and listen to it and what you'll hear is a paranoid rant:
``Can I hit it in the morning without giving you half of my dough?
And even worse if I was broke would you want me?'' he begins. ``A
Week Ago,'' with Atlanta's Too Short, details how longtime friends
can turn on you. This ends up really being a ``Hard Knock Life.''
But the inclusion of a lithe beat usually means that no song weighs
as heavy as some of the themes, nor are ``Paper Chase''-like tunes
as transparent as the diamonds they go on about. Like the work of
the late Notorious B.I.G., Jay-Z proves that one tune can be both
something you can dance to and something to think about.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vol. 2 ...Hard Knock Life''
</P>
<P>
   Jay-Z. Roc-A-Fella/Def Jam.
</P>
<P>
   14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A ``Hard Knock Life'' that's easy to like.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
