<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0235 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4695 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS08-COX     10-07 0418
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-REVIEWS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Audio Reviews: The latest word on the latest sounds
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton, Sonia Murray, and Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   -- ROCK
</P>
<P>
   ``John Mellencamp''
</P>
<P>
   John Mellencamp.
</P>
<P>
   Columbia. 12 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   The eponymous title of journeyman rocker John Mellencamp's 17th
album, and his first for Columbia Records, is clearly meant to
signal a fresh start. But while 1996's ``Mr. Happy Go Lucky''
showed flashes of adventurousness, including a stab at heartland
hip-hop with the tune ``Emotional Love,'' the new album mostly
covers familiar ground. That said, it's a solid collection of
songs, with the standouts being the reggae-flavored ``I'm Not
Running Anymore'' and the somber ``Eden Is Burning,'' which offers
a not-so-happy ending to that little ditty about ``Jack and
Diane.''
</P>
<P>
   -- CONTEMPORARY GOSPEL
</P>
<P>
   ``The Nu Nation Project''
</P>
<P>
   Kirk Franklin.
</P>
<P>
   Gospo Centric. 17 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   In the opening skit, Kirk Franklin is charged with being a
secular artist posing as a Christian. Surely a man unafraid to
incorporate rap (``Revolution''), rock guitars (``Riverside'') and
bump-and-grind man R. Kelly (``Lean on Me'') on one album and call
it gospel is guilty of such an accusation? Well, no. The force
behind the best-selling album in this genre (1997's ``God's
Property'') can only be found capable _ not culpable _ of crafting
an incredibly inspiring effort bigger than its seemingly
conflicting parts.
</P>
<P>
   -- POP
</P>
<P>
   ``Supernatural''
</P>
<P>
   dcTalk. 13 tracks. Virgin.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   Christian pop acts have for so long been blandly derivative of
slightly moldy trends that the time is finally ripe for crossover
successes. Not because the bands are becoming more original, but
rather because modern rock formats, especially, have encouraged so
many cookie-cutter grunge and Hootie-type bands to flourish that
they suddenly fit right in. Just add Jesus, and some poor
articulation for ambiguity's sake, and you've got a platinum-seller
like Creed. The trio dcTalk is perhaps the slickest in the genre.
Its new album, a commercial breakthrough, doesn't miss a move. Most
accomplished when seamlessly generic (the Seal-sleek ``Wanna Be
Loved''), the music only occasionally is awkward or obvious (the
accusatory ``My Friend (So Long)''). Yet you wonder when such
overtly earnest performers will ever speak in their own words.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
