<HEADER>
A4696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VIDEO-MURDER-COX     10-07 0261
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-MURDER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chic, twisty `Murder' is guilty fun
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``A Perfect Murder'' (R)
</P>
<P>
   This B-movie remake of ``Dial M for Murder,'' shot in the deep
mahoganies of a Rembrandt painting and decked out in Fifth Avenue
fashions, isn't exactly perfect. But it's guilty fun. Its thrills
come equally from the twisty plot (no-good Michael Douglas schemes
to off his trust-fund wife, Gwyneth Paltrow) and our vicarious
pleasure in prowling around the troubled couple's oh-so-chic
penthouse.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas plays his signature role: scum-sucking sicko with caviar
tastes, flawlessly attired by Barney's. Viggo Mortensen portrays
the classic starving artist, whom Douglas approaches to murder his
wife. The twist? Mortensen happens to be Paltrow's lover. Let's
just say things don't work out quite as planned.
</P>
<P>
   The film's second half involves the murder scheme's aftermath,
when the stakes are raised considerably by the arrival of David
Suchet as the police detective assigned to the case. (The movie
could have benefitted from more of his piercing, intelligent
presence.) Basically a plot machine, ``Murder'' puts its attractive
cast through a plot line that's twisty enough to keep us guessing.
It's a little too pat and airless to be a total kick. But you might
pick up some decorating ideas. Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Other videos from director Andrew Davis: ``The Fugitive,''
``Steal Big, Steal Little,'' ``Chain Reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
