<HEADER>
A4697 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-07 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
11 GAMES TO GLORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It used to be so easy in Ye Olden Days. Finish the
season Sunday. Start the World Series Wednesday. Blow 'em out and
you could have your celebration Monday.
</P>
<P>
   No longer. Baseball has gradually morphed into basketball or
hockey. It is time to start referring to the Second Season in our
oldest organized team sport.
</P>
<P>
   No old-timer can possibly appreciate what it takes to win a
championship nowadays. People scoff when they are told that Duke
getting to the Final Four seven times in nine years in a six-game,
64-team tournament is just as impressive as UCLA winning 10 times
in 12 years in a four-game, 25- to 32-team tournament, but it is.
People similarly scoff when they are informed that the Bulls
winning six times in eight years in a four-tier NBA postseason is
an equal achievement to or better than the Bill Russell Celtics
winning 11 times in 13 years in a mostly two-round postseason, but
it is.
</P>
<P>
   And no old-time baseball guy wants to hear that it is
exponentially harder to win a World Series nowadays than it was
before the American and National Leagues split into divisions and
instituted a playoff system in 1969. But it most definitely is.
This is without even discussing the problems inherent in keeping a
team together in the era of free agency and arbitratration.
</P>
<P>
   John Schuerholz knows. He is the executive vice president and
general manager of the most successful major league baseball team
of the '90s _ the Atlanta Braves. Once again, he finds himself in
an apologetic mode as he attempts to explain how it is that a team
as continually successful as Atlanta has been since 1991 has only
one championship to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the general public has an appreciation of how
hard it is to win it all in this climate,'' he maintained, ``and I
know some people in the media don't, and they affect people's
attitudes. It is more and more difficult every year, and it is even
more difficult now just to get yourself into a position to win. The
whole thing is just more difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   During the Braves' reign as the National League's premier team,
they have faced six teams in the NL Championship Series. The
roster: Pittsburgh in '91 and '92, Philadelphia in '93, Cincinnati
in '95, St. Louis in '96, Florida in '97, and now San Diego in '98.
</P>
<P>
   It is an intriguing list. The Pirates fight a continuing battle
for survival. The '93 team was Philadelphia's only plus-.500 team
in the past decade. Cincinnati is a crumbling professional
also-ran. The Cardinals, Mr. Swat notwithstanding, aren't close.
And Florida? Oy!
</P>
<P>
   But Atlanta rolls on.
</P>
<P>
   All Schuerholz can do is put the Braves in a position to win.
Once you get to the postseason, what happens happens. There are
always memorable what ifs? It is part of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that Schuerholz has done one of the great general
managing jobs in history. Operating in a world that the Branch
Rickeys and George Weisses could never even comprehend, Schuerholz
has kept stirring the pot. The extent of the Atlanta turnover is
staggering.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1991 team that lost one of the handful of greatest
World Series ever played, two (2) players remain: Tom Glavine and
John Smoltz. From the 1993 club that lost to those star-crossed
Phillies in six games, add Greg Maddux. There was, of course, no
1994. Move to 1995 and add Chipper Jones, Javy Lopez, and Ryan
Klesko. From the 1996 team that came from 3-1 down to defeat St.
Louis in the NLCS, we have Andruw Jones, Eddie Perez, and Denny
Neagle.
</P>
<P>
   That means there are only nine players remaining from the team
that competed for the world championship just two years ago. That
represents some heavy-duty wheeling and dealing.
</P>
<P>
   There is no secret that the foundation of the team's success is
the magnificent starting pitching nucleus of Glavine, Smoltz, and
Maddux. It all begins with them, no question. During the '90s,
these three have combined to go 355-182 in the regular season. Not
bad. Led by Smoltz's 11-3 record, they are 30-19 in the postseason.
They clearly rank with any trio of starters you can name at any
point in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   With the starting pitching anchored, Schuerholz juggles. The
Braves are a big-money team, and Schuerholz has never been hampered
by a skimpy checkbook. But money alone cannot guarantee success.
You need judgment, and Schuerholz has that.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the primary additions to the 1998 team, first baseman
Andres Galarraga and shortstop Walt Weiss. ``They have given us a
balance we needed,'' Schuerholz said. ``We were too lefthanded.''
</P>
<P>
   Replacing the aging Fred McGriff at first base with the
explosive Galarraga, a k a the Big Cat, was a coup in more ways
than one. The 37-year-old Venezuelan slugger is one of those
imposing clubhouse presences. The Braves have taken on a distinct
Latin American flavor (eight players from five countries), and the
Leader of the Pack is Senor Galarraga.
</P>
<P>
   Weiss, a switch hitter, is one of those ballplayers who will
undoubtedly fall through the cracks of history but will be
remembered by his teammates and employers as a reliable
professional who never cracked under pressure. He is battling leg
injuries, but when healthy, he has given the Braves a significant
leadoff presence while making all the requisite plays at short.
</P>
<P>
   The Atlanta bullpen is an Encyclopedia Brittanica entry unto
itself, but suffice it to say the problem has been addressed to the
apparent satisfaction of manager Bobby Cox. The Braves are ready to
go.
</P>
<P>
   Are they readier, or better, than in either '97 or '96? Who
knows? ``I feel good about this team,'' said Schuerholz, ``but I
don't know that I feel better than I did in other years. We have a
lot of experienced, levelheaded people. We are very capable of
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   So are New York and San Diego. But this is 1998, not 1968.
Somebody has to win 11 games, not four. It's not easy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
