<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4701 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KACZYNSKI-REWARD-HNS &LR;      10-07 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KACZYNSKI-REWARD-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX-EXEMPT STATUS OF KACZYNSKI REWARD DELAYED UNTIL NEXT YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ David Kaczynski wrestled with his conscience, but
in the end told authorities that he believed his brother, Theodore,
was the Unabomber.
</P>
<P>
   Now he is wrestling the IRS.
</P>
<P>
   An aide to Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, said Wednesday that the
House would not take up a measure that would exempt from taxes the
$1 million reward paid to David Kaczynski, who has said he will
give the money to his brother's victims. Archer is chairman of the
House Ways and Means Committee, which oversees tax policy.
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for Archer, said the proposal came
too late as the House is scheduled to adjourn this week until
January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it's just too late in the year for any new
provision like this to move forward,'' Fleischer said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a timing problem,'' he added. ``At this time of year, we
are literally flooded with billions of dollars worth of meritorious
tax proposals. When you open the gates to say yes to one, you open
the gates to say yes to all.''
</P>
<P>
   Fleischer declined to say whether Archer supported the measure
in principle. ``The chairman has not addressed the merits of it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Archer's decision throws a wrench into the works for Sen. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, D-N.Y., who sponsored the tax-exemption measure
in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were hopeful that this would happen in the fall,'' said
Mike Waterman, a spokesman for Moynihan. ``It's disappointing, but
we're going to doggedly pursue this.''
</P>
<P>
   Waterman said Moynihan may add the exemption to other pending
tax measures in the Senate before the current session ends. But
without the House's concurrence, the tax measure would die.
</P>
<P>
   Kaczynski and his wife Linda Patrik, of Schenectady, N.Y.,
received the reward from the FBI in August for providing
information that led to Theodore Kaczynski's April 1996 arrest in a
remote Montana cabin.
</P>
<P>
   In a wrenching decision, Kaczynski turned in his brother, a
former mathematics professor who had become a recluse. He contacted
the FBI after recognizing the Unabomber's published manifesto as
similar to Theodore Kaczynski's anti-technology musings.
</P>
<P>
   The Unabomber was responsible for an 18-year string of bombings,
beginning in 1978, that killed three people and wounded 23 others.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities dubbed the serial criminal the Unabomber because his
initial targets were university officials and airline offices.
</P>
<P>
   David Kaczynski has pledged that after paying taxes and lawyer
fees used to defend his brother from the death penalty, the
remaining sum would go to his brother's victims and their families.
</P>
<P>
   Because taxes alone could top $300,000, Moynihan introduced a
bill in the Senate on Sept. 25 seeking to make the reward
tax-exempt so that more of the money would go the victims and
families.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be ironic and I believe unjust if the federal
government were to diminish this selfless act by taxing the
Kaczynskis or those to whom they have agreed to pay the reward
monies,'' Moynihan said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1821EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0240 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 18:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4702 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COOKING-SCHOOLS-COX     10-07 0998
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOKING-SCHOOLS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cooking 101
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA_Pastry chef Kirk Parks demonstrates how to core a
pineapple with a melon baller, then darts over to advise exactly
when to add the sugar to the egg whites.
</P>
<P>
   He turns just in time to offer a tip for fishing a chip of
eggshell out of a batter. ``Use a larger piece of eggshell. It will
cling to it,'' he explains over the cacophony of whirring mixers
and cackling compatriots.
</P>
<P>
   He's the master of a three-ring circus, but it's not in his
usual kitchen at Nava, the popular Southwestern-chic restaurant in
Buckhead. Rather it's in a small model kitchen at the Wollaston
Smith Kitchen Design Center on DeKalb Technology Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   And the performers are students in a cooking class, one of
several offered at Wollaston Smith each month. Within two hours,
the nine students will be savoring toasted almond poundcake with
plum chardonnay sauce and coconut macaroons, a milk chocolate tart
with caramelized banana sauce and grilled red chile pineapples with
tequila poached peaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing like three desserts for dinner,'' quips Sherie
Watkins, 41, a graphics designer who loves to cook. She left her
husband and son to fend for themselves this Tuesday evening so she
could learn from Parks.
</P>
<P>
   Around the metro area, Watkins is among thousands _ from kitchen
klutzes to accomplished gourmet chefs _ who are flocking to cooking
classes to work side by side with a kitchen pro or sit back, watch
and sample the end results. Classes cover everything from
appetizers to desserts, pastas to pastries, American standards to
international exotica.
</P>
<P>
   And the quest for culinary prowess continues to rise. With an
average of about 20 students a class four nights a week, Wollaston
Smith's sessions are selling out with increasing frequency,
especially for popular cuisines like sushi, said culinary center
director Deborah Evans.
</P>
<P>
   At the Kroger School of Cooking in Alpharetta, which opened
three years ago, more than 3,000 students took a class last year,
up 7 percent from the previous year. When Ursula Knaeusel started
offering classes here in 1971, she averaged five students a class;
now she has to limit them to 40.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are a little tired of fast food all the time,
and it can be so expensive to eat out in nicer restaurants, so they
are learning how to cook that beef tenderloin at home,'' said
Knaeusel, who offers single-session demonstration classes at her
Cheshire Bridge school on practical good cooking that doesn't
``require driving all over town to find the ingredients.''
</P>
<P>
   While she does all the cooking in her classes, opportunities
also abound for prospective students eager to get their hands
floury.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Consuegra, 43, of Roswell has been participating in a
four-week ``basics'' series at the Alpharetta Kroger. In the first
class, he and his classmates chopped, sliced and diced onions and
carrots to hone their knife skills. They also watched chef Matthew
Sheeter prepare several different stocks, to be used in subsequent
classes when students would made pasta, cook a variety of meats and
plan a dinner party.
</P>
<P>
   Consuegra is considering a kitchen redesign in his home, so he
said he was attracted to a ``basics'' course because ``I wanted a
good foundation in cooking to help us make those decisions.''
Throughout the series, he was exposed to all aspects of a kitchen,
from top-of-the-line ovens and countertops to cutting boards and
pasta machines. But his favorite activity was ``definitely sampling
all the class projects.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his classmates, Melanie Flanders, 44, is driving more
than two hours each way from North Augusta, S.C., for the series,
even though she's already an experienced cook. But ``I can always
use new ideas,'' she said. ``I used to live here and always wanted
to take the classes but never had the time. Now I do, so I decided
to make the drive and visit with friends afterward.''
</P>
<P>
   The social aspect is not lost on Philippa Kingsley, who teaches
Thai cooking classes in a kitchen designed for instruction attached
to her home. Kingsley offers some demonstration, but then gets
students involved in chopping lemon grass, dicing hot chile peppers
and patting out fish cakes. The five-hour class culminates with a
sit-down feast of such Thai classics as chicken and cashew nuts,
red curry roast duck and pad Thai noodles. The dinners usually turn
into jovial gabfests.
</P>
<P>
   Kingsley trained in Thailand and taught in the Netherlands
before moving to Atlanta to teach nearly three years ago. ``Most of
my students have eaten Thai food in restaurants or have been to
Thailand and want to re-create the experience,'' said Kingsley.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than rely on one instructor, Wollaston Smith and Cook's
Warehouse in Midtown draw largely on chefs from area restaurants.
The chefs who make the best teachers, says Wollaston Smith's Evans,
are those who are personable as well as knowledgeable. Their
success also depends on their ability to translate large-scale
restaurant recipes into home dishes that can be prepared with
supermarket ingredients and everyday kitchen equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Shaun Doty, chef at Mumbo Jumbo, relishes that challenge. He
recently told a class at Cook's Warehouse that he likes to try out
new recipes with cooking classes to see how well they might work
with customers. For instance, a turnip piccata with braised greens,
country ham and red lentils that he demonstrated at a cooking class
in August just showed up on his new fall menu.
</P>
<P>
   Knaeusel likes to experiment as well; she's never taught the
same recipe twice in the past 25 years of teaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``The variety keeps people coming back,'' she said. ``Just like
some people go to the movies or a sporting event, people come here
to be entertained, to meet people and to learn a little something
in the process.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
