<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Forget evil spells _ use garlic for good taste, health
 &HT;    By Betty Parham
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It is not an exaggeration to say that peace and happiness
begin geographically where garlic is used in cooking.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Marcel Boulastin, French chef
</P>
<P>
   ``One must be very suspicious of anyone who does not eat
garlic.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Romanian proverb
</P>
<P>
   Like fire and salt, garlic is elemental to cooking. We know it
was mentioned as far back as 3000 B.C., in the earliest Sanskrit
writings. We know it was there when the Pyramids were being built.
We know it was not there when the Israelites were wandering the
Sinai desert, because they complained bitterly about its absence.
We know the Vikings, the Phoenicians and the Crusaders all ate it.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike fire and salt, which people tend to take for granted,
perhaps there is no other food component that, through the eons,
has inspired as much passion as garlic.
</P>
<P>
   It has been revered as a protection against known and unknown
evils, and no less personages than Homer, Aristophanes, Virgil,
Pliny, Celsius, Hippocrates, Confucius and Mohammed have praised it
and hailed its reputed wondrous curative powers. Besides protection
against evil spells, garlic has been said to cure everything from
toothache to baldness. Some of these health claims have held up to
modern science, which in recent years has conducted numerous
studies showing that garlic is indeed curative in many areas.
</P>
<P>
   But, even apart from any association with good health, people
are as passionate about garlic today as ever, simply because of the
wondrous alchemy it evinces when used in cooking. The Internet has
some wonderful sites dripping with mouthwatering garlic recipes, as
well as health information, growing tips, gifts, festivals, history
and lore.
</P>
<P>
   -- If you're interested in the latest health news about garlic,
check the health section at http://www.garlicpage.com, where you'll
find links to university studies and other information. Another
good health source is http://www.mistral.co.uk/garlic, a site
maintained by the Garlic Information Center. In addition, if you
have a specific question about any health aspect of garlic, the
Cornell University Medical Center staffs a telephone hot line at
1-800-330-5922, where your questions can be answered from 9 a.m. to
5 p.m. weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   -- For a marvelous and detailed history of garlic, check
http://www.christopher-ranch.com.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``Everything Garlic'' at
http://MasterMall.com/garlic/ftx1.htm lists garlic-related
specialty items and gifts for the garlic lover on your gift list.
For a catalog, call 1-800-668-6299.
</P>
<P>
   -- If you're a joiner, you'll want to call up http:
</P>
<P>
   //www.garliclovers.com for membership info about the Garlic
Lovers Society and the Garlic Seed Foundation. There are also
detailed listings of upcoming garlic festivals.
</P>
<P>
   -- Like the other sites, http://www.christophergarlic.com is
loaded with mouthwatering garlic recipes.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Basque Style
</P>
<P>
   Eggplant Casserole
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 25-30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   6tablespoons vegetable or olive oil, divided
</P>
<P>
   1onion, cut into strips
</P>
<P>
   2green peppers, cored, seeded and cut into strips
</P>
<P>
   5large mushrooms, sliced
</P>
<P>
   1celery rib, sliced diagonally
</P>
<P>
   5cloves garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   6tomatoes, peeled and diced
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon fines herbes
</P>
<P>
   1large eggplant
</P>
<P>
   2eggs, beaten with 1 tablespoon water and a pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   1cup grated Swiss cheese
</P>
<P>
   In a large skillet, heat 3 tablespoons oil. Add onion, green
pepper, mushrooms, celery and garlic. Saute until tender. Add
tomatoes. Bring to a boil. Add salt and fines herbes. Reduce heat
to low and simmer sauce for 30 minutes. Preheat oven to 350
degrees. Peel eggplant and slice into 3/4-inch slices. In a
skillet, heat remaining 3 tablespoons oil. Dip eggplant slices into
egg mixture and fry until tender. Arrange eggplant in a
9-by-13-inch baking dish. Sprinkle with Parmesan cheese. Pour
tomato sauce over the top and sprinkle with Swiss cheese. Heat in
oven until cheese is melted and eggplant is heated through, about
10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 442 calories, 18 grams protein, 35 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 70), 18 grams carbohydrates, 140
milligrams cholesterol, 376 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Christopher's Baked Garlic With Rosemary Feta Dip
</P>
<P>
   Makes 12 appetizer servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 1 hour
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE BAKED GARLIC:
</P>
<P>
   6whole garlic bulbs
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper and herbs to taste
</P>
<P>
   Water or chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE ROSEMARY FETA DIP:
</P>
<P>
   18-ounce container plain yogurt
</P>
<P>
   1cup crumbled feta cheese
</P>
<P>
   Leaves from 2 sprigs of fresh rosemary, coarsely chopped
</P>
<P>
   To bake the garlic: Gently remove outer layers of skin from
garlic bulbs, leaving bulbs intact. Place in a small baking pan and
drizzle with 1 tablespoon olive oil. Sprinkle with salt, pepper and
herbs. Preheat oven to 450 degrees. Add water or chicken broth to
pan until bulbs are about half covered. Seal pan with aluminum foil
and bake for 1 hour or until garlic cloves are soft.
</P>
<P>
   To make the dip: Place yogurt, feta cheese and rosemary into a
food processor or blender and blend until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   To serve: Break garlic clove off bulb and squeeze pulp out onto
a slice of French bread. Top with a dab of Rosemary Feta Dip and a
slice of sun-dried tomato if desired.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 46 calories, 2 grams protein, 4 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 69), 2 grams carbohydrates, 11 milligrams
cholesterol, 114 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   from http://www.garlicpage.com
</P>
<P>
   SIDE DISH
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Garlic Pasta
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons minced garlic
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon red pepper flakes
</P>
<P>
   1pound linguine or spaghetti, cooked and drained
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons grated lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   2teaspoons coarse salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   1/2cup chopped fresh Italian parsley
</P>
<P>
   In a medium skillet over medium heat, heat oil. Add garlic and
red pepper flakes and cook until fragrant, about 3 to 5 minutes.
Pour over cooked pasta in bowl. Add lemon zest, lemon juice, salt,
pepper and parsley. Toss well to coat. Adjust seasonings with salt
and pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 367 calories, 10 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 25), 58 grams carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 600 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
