<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Light on milk, poundcake big on taste
 &HT;    By Marcia Langhenry
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A request for a Crisco Poundcake using evaporated milk brought
in several variations ... all heavy on the eggs and shortening and
light on the milk.
</P>
<P>
   The most common was this one, sent by William Moeser of
Tallapoosa, Georgia, which called for only 1/4 cup evaporated milk.
Our tester was skeptical but approved the end result.
</P>
<P>
   For a little more flavor, you could add a teaspoon each of
vanilla and almond extract, in the style of Martha Hunter of
Greensborol, Ga..
</P>
<P>
   ``This may not be the recipe Ann Parker is looking for, but it
is out-of-this-world good,'' Hunter wrote.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Crisco Poundcake
</P>
<P>
   Makes 20 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 2 to 2 1/2 hours
</P>
<P>
   3cups granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2cups (1 pound) Crisco
</P>
<P>
   10large eggs
</P>
<P>
   3cups cake flour, divided
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup evaporated milk, divided
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 300 degrees. Grease and flour 10-inch tube pan.
Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   In a large bowl, cream together sugar and Crisco. Add eggs, one
at a time, beating after each. Add 1 cup flour, stir to combine,
then add half the milk. Add another cup flour, remaining milk and
stir to combine. Add remaining flour. Stir to combine well.
</P>
<P>
   Pour batter into prepared tube pan. Bake 2 to 2 1/2 hours or
until knife inserted into cake comes out clean.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 414 calories, 6 grams protein, 25 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 54), 42 grams carbohydrates, 160
milligrams cholesterol, 51 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Requests
</P>
<P>
   -- Frances Allen of Atlanta is looking for a recipe her family
called Italian Salad that included tomatoes, soda crackers and
olives but no lettuce.
</P>
<P>
   -- Debra DeVoll (e-mail) wants a recipe for a pork and beans
casserole with hot dogs and pineapple, topped with bacon slices.
She thinks it came from the label of the A&AMP;P store brand of pork
and beans.
</P>
<P>
   Where to write
</P>
<P>
   Recipes or requests should be sent to Recipe Swap, Food
Department, Cox News Service, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, GA 30302.
E-mail: mlanghenry(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
