<SLUG> BC-VIDEO-ERINGEL08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Pre-release fuss often a tempest in a teapot
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes a movie's bark is worse than its bite.
</P>
<P>
   Meaning, something arrives in theaters amidst a storm of
controversy _ it's too sexy, too violent, sacrilegious. Then, after
all the noise has died down and the movie has long since gone to
video, you realize you remember the fuss more than you do the film.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, the remake of ``Lolita,'' which opens
Friday. For over a year, the news focused on its initial failure to
find an American distributor, forcing its premiere _ oh, the shame
of it _ on cable TV (Showtime, last August). But lightning didn't
strike Showtime, and now ``Lolita'' is getting theatrical
play-dates around the country.
</P>
<P>
   As for the movie itself? Not great. Not terrible. Certainly
worth a look if you're interested; easily ignored if you're not.
</P>
<P>
   Another cloud of controversy has gathered around ``Happiness''
(set to open in Atlanta on Nov. 6), which explores pedophilia.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, you can check out these titles that caused more
of a stir off-screen than on:
</P>
<P>
   -- ``STROMBOLI''
</P>
<P>
   Sore point: Adultery.
</P>
<P>
   Ingrid Bergman, a near-saint in the public's eyes thanks to
roles in ``Casablanca,'' ``The Bells of Saint Mary's'' and ``Joan
of Arc,'' left her husband and child to live in sin with Italian
director Roberto Rossellini. And to have his children (one of whom
is Isabella Rossellini). And to make movies with him, the first of
which was ``Stromboli.`` Bergman plays a World War II refugee who
marries a fisherman to escape the brutality of an internment camp.
The film and its star were denounced by clergymen, congressmen and
Georgia state Sen. Frank Lunsford, who managed to pass a resolution
banning all movies either made by Rossellini or starring Bergman
from public airing in Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``BASIC INSTINCT''
</P>
<P>
   Sore point: Homophobia.
</P>
<P>
   Gay and lesbian demonstrators disrupted both the filming and the
opening of this suspense thriller, starring Michael Douglas as a
police detective with personal problems who becomes involved with
the prime suspect in a murder case: a glamorous and potentially
lethal bisexual played by Sharon Stone. The protesters' point _
remember, this was long before ``Ellen'' _ was that so few movies
even bothered to portray non-straight characters that to assign a
big star and a big budget to one that trafficked in largely
negative images was, well, insensitive at best. Writer Joe
Eszterhas, who had already pocketed his $3 million fee, said he
supported the protests and that the director, Paul Verhoeven, had
ignored his suggested changes. These days, about all anyone
remembers about the picture is the scene where Stone crosses _ and
uncrosses _ her legs.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``THE LAST TEMPTATION
</P>
<P>
   OF CHRIST''
</P>
<P>
   Sore point: Religion
</P>
<P>
   All hell broke loose, so to speak, when Martin Scorsese decided
to film Nikos Kazantzakis' novel about Christ, which includes a
fantasy scene in which Jesus forsakes his mission and embraces a
``normal'' (i.e., sexual) life with Mary Magdalene. Not
surprisingly, this didn't go over well with traditional-minded
Christians. What was surprising _ and a bit sad _ was that some
demonstrators added an ugly anti-Semitic tone to their protests.
Lew Wasserman, chairman of MCA, the parent company of Universal,
found protesters outside his home while a plane circled overhead
with the banner, ``Wasserman fans Jewish hatred with Last
Temptation.'' Upon its release, the movie, starring Willem Dafoe as
Christ, caused a flurry of critical interest _ most of it related
to the nasty tone of the protests _ then disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   -- ``HUSBANDS AND WIVES''
</P>
<P>
   Sore point: Art imitates life.
</P>
<P>
   See, Mia Farrow, Woody Allen's longtime significant other, had
just discovered that he was having an affair with her 21-year-old
adopted daughter, Soon-Yi Previn (whom he has since married). Media
feeding frenzy ensued. Then came the release of his new film, about
the breakup of a marriage and a middle-aged guy's (Allen)
relationship with one of his students, a much younger woman
(Juliette Lewis). Farrow plays the part of the spurned spouse,
though in the movie the Allen character nobly doesn't act on Lewis'
infatuation (i.e., no sex). Allen insisted that the script had
nothing to do with his real life and that he had originally
considered playing the role filled by Sydney Pollack. Regardless of
which came first, the affair or the screenplay, this one is the
exception to the rule: a first-rate movie that should outlive its
``scandalous'' overtones.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
