<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOSCOLL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BC HOPING TO STEAL THURSDAY NIGHT SHOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Forget ``Seinfeld'' and ``Cheers'' and ``Wings.'' They
have signed off from their coveted Thursday night slots and gone to
syndicated TV heaven. For college football fans, ESPN Thursday
night games have emerged as part of their must-see TV lineup.
</P>
<P>
   You can count Boston College coach Tom O'Brien and his Eagles
among those who have made watching ESPN Thursday night games a
weekly ritual.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah, I always watch Thursday night football,'' O'Brien
said. ``There's always something that I might see that I might
like. Something that someone is doing on offense or defense.
College coaches steal from each other. I mean, we're the biggest
thieves in the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, when the numbers of Heisman Trophy winner Doug
Flutie and Outland Trophy winner Mike Ruth will be retired, O'Brien
hopes his Eagles (3-1 overall, 2-0 Big East) can steal the
spotlight from No. 17 Virginia Tech (4-0, 2-0) when they take
center stage in this ESPN matchup of conference unbeatens at Alumni
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   After absorbing a 52-28 beating at Louisville Sept. 26, the
Eagles are pointing toward this as a statement game. An impact
game. An absolute must-win conference game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've prepared ourselves pretty well the past few
days,'' said senior running back Mike Cloud, the conference's
leading rusher (169.0 yards per game), who will run head-on into
Virginia Tech's No. 1 defense, which has allowed 216 yards per
game, including 58 rushing. ``Everyone loves to play at night,
under the lights, and to be the only team on TV. We're the only
(college) game on that night. The fact that we're playing a ranked
team, a very good team, basically, we just want to prove to America
that we're a legit team.''
</P>
<P>
   While BC's first loss of the season gave rise to many questions,
there have been few, if any, about the legitimacy of Virginia
Tech's defense, which has not allowed a rushing touchdown all year.
From the start of the season, the Hokies' defense has set the tone,
recording a 37-0 shutout at Clemson, limiting Miami to 37 yards
rushing in a 27-20 overtime victory at the Orange Bowl Sept. 19,
and holding Pittsburgh to 28 yards in a 27-7 victory Sept. 26 in
Blacksburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most frightening thing about Virginia Tech is their
special teams,'' said O'Brien. ``You never know what's going to
happen. Two weeks ago at Pitt, they fumbled near their own goal
line and gave Pitt the ball at their own 1. Then they backed up
Pitt to the 8 and forced them to kick a field goal and wound up
blocking it.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Hokies had a blocked punt against Pitt, marking
the 10th time in the 12-year tenure of coach Frank Beamer that they
have had two blocked kicks in a game. They now have 65 blocked
kicks in 130 games under Beamer.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech's injury-riddled offense, however, has been
another matter.
</P>
<P>
   The Hokies had three starters injured against Miami: quarterback
Al Clark (sprained foot), fullback Cullen Hawkins (broken foot),
and offensive guard Josh Redding (knee). Against Pittsburgh,
Clark's backup, sophomore Dave Meyer, suffered a separated
shoulder, forcing Beamer to deploy Nick Sorenson as an emergency
replacement.
</P>
<P>
   Sorenson, a 6-foot-3-inch, 206-pound redshirt sophomore who
served as Clark's backup last season before switching to free
safety this year, has been tabbed by Beamer as the probable starter
Thursday night. Beamer, however, indicated Clark will be available.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al's been back and he's practiced,'' said Beamer, whose team
scored a 17-7 victory over BC last year on Clark's dazzling 42-yard
TD run with 12:29 left. ``I do think Al will be available to play
in this game, but we'll plan to start Nick because I'd just like
things to be settled and leave no question marks out there.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other lingering question: How will BC respond after its
drubbing at Louisville, the Eagles' worst loss since a 52-20
thumping at Notre Dame last year? It was a shocking setback in
which the Eagles were pistol-whipped by quarterback Chris Redman,
who passed for 362 yards and a school-record five TDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Louisville game is something that happens,'' said junior
free safety Pedro Cirino. ``They out-game-planned us and they
outplayed us. But now we go into this Virginia Tech game, a Big
East game, with a big chance for us to make a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   What might that be?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' Cirino said, pausing. ``We'll see if we're ready
for the big time or not.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
