<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lillian Smith Awards honor Lewis, Cox
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. John Lewis (D-Ga.), whose memoir ``Walking With the
Wind'' recounts his role in the civil rights movement, and North
Carolina novelist Elizabeth Cox, author of ``Night Talk,'' are the
1998 winners of the Lillian Smith Book Awards.
</P>
<P>
   John Edgerton, chairman of the awards jury, praised ``Walking
With the Wind'' (Simon &AMP; Schuster, $26) as ``a story of quiet
courage of this self-effacing hero of the civil rights movement;
the narrative resonates with his voice, and the familiar story has
never been told so compellingly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Night Talk'' (Graywolf Press, $23) is the story of a black
girl, Janey Louise, and a white girl, Evie, who grow up in the same
house in the small-town South of the 1950s. Cox, a Tennessee native
who divides her time between Massachusetts and North Carolina,
explains that she wrote the book ``trembling in my boots.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I started out to write a book about a girl whose father had
left home, but when Janie Louise and her mother moved into the
house, they took over the book,'' says Cox, 56, whose previous
novels are ``Familiar Ground'' and ``The Ragged Way People Fall Out
of Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Several times while she was writing the novel she stopped
because she didn't feel qualified to write about race.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only way I could continue was to tell myself I was writing
about human intolerance.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in the South, Cox witnessed intolerance. She entered
the University of Mississippi in the same semester that James
Meredith integrated the all-white school. ``I was always tolerant
about race,'' she says, ``but I was silent until I got to college.
That's when I began to speak my mind. In this book I was trying to
expose intolerance in a human way without trying to blame anybody
for being racist.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lillian Smith Awards, which celebrate their 30th anniversary
this year, honor books that contribute to a better understanding of
human rights and other social issues _ matters that were of concern
to Georgia author Lillian Smith a half-century ago. The 1944
publication of Smith's ``Strange Fruit'' _ about an interracial
love affair _ thrust the author into the spotlight as a champion of
human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The awards, sponsored by the Southern Regional Council, will be
presented at a Nov. 6 luncheon at the Sheraton Colony Squarein
Atlanta. Information: 404-522-8764.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT FACE: Sometimes it pays to watch television. Atlanta
writer Iris Johansen was watching the Discovery Channel a couple of
years ago when it aired a program about forensic sculptors who
reconstructed skulls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be really interesting to do a book about
the subject,'' Johansen says.
</P>
<P>
   Months of research later, Johansen began ``The Face of
Deception'' (Bantam, $23.95), the story of forensic sculptor Eve
Duncan. Eve creates faces from skulls to help law enforcement
officials and grieving families crack unsolved crimes and missing
person cases.
</P>
<P>
   The face that the Georgia scientist is constructing, however,
makes her a target for a killer. As she searches for the identity
of the victim, she learns that the face she created belongs to a
very important man who happens to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   A former romance novelist with 9 million copies in print,
Johansen switched to suspense with ``The Ugly Duckling,'' which
became a million-copy best seller. She followed that with two other
thrillers, ``Long After Midnight'' and ``And Then You Die.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like doing suspense novels,'' says Johansen, whose first
novel, ``Stormy Vows,'' was plucked out of a publisher's slush
pile. ``I like being able to put in all of these surprises.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be a sequel to ``The Face of Deception,'' Johansen
says, but no more after that. ``I don't want to limit myself. There
are too many stories I want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Johansen will sign books at 2 p.m. Saturday at Waldenbooks, 400
Barrett Parkway at Town Center Mall, Kennesaw. 770-427-7810.
</P>
<P>
   REVIVED BOOKS: Hill Street Press, the new publishing house in
Athens, is looking for a few good ideas from readers about what to
publish. The press is offering the Palimpsest Prize to anyone who
comes up with the name of a favorite out-of-print book to be
reissued. Readers can nominate fiction or nonfiction titles
published at any time, from a hundred years ago to last year, as
long as they are out of print. The only other stipulation is that
the nominated books be connected to the South, through the author
or the subject matter. The person who nominates the selected title
will receive a $100 prize and the opportunity to participate in
Hill Street's promotion. Nomination forms are available at
bookstores. The deadline is Nov. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
