<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Stop driving? I'll steer clear of that notion
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 11: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Celestine Sibley
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Somebody wrote me a note in the Vent the other day. It said,
``Celestine, I think it's time you stopped driving.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to being flattered to get mentioned in that column,
I suffered mightily from the possible inference that I may not be a
good driver. I am, oh, I am.
</P>
<P>
   Ask my children and grandchildren. I taught every last one of
them to drive, and considering that I drive many miles in the
course of a week, I have had a pretty fair driving record.
</P>
<P>
   There was that truck on I-75 a few years ago. (He drove me into
the wall. I didn't nick him, but, of course, I did have to have an
operation on my shoulder and the truck driver didn't.)
</P>
<P>
   I recall that one of our sportswriters mentioned that it was the
kind of operation baseball players often have. He added, ``But
you'll never pitch for the Braves again.'' That restriction pains
me almost as much as the prospect of not driving at all. It's true
the Braves haven't called on me, but if they did, I'd hate to say a
little old accident impaired my pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the time a woman in a formidable van whammed into
the rear of my car at a four-way stop sign. Could happen to
anybody, couldn't it? The truck driver she drove me into ramming
said somebody was always hitting him that way. The impulse to
attack a big truck at a stop sign probably rages in many an
otherwise humble heart.
</P>
<P>
   I am, if I do say so, a peaceable driver. I don't make menacing
gestures at other drivers, and I gave up name-calling when a fat
lady in another car rolled down her window and finished what was
apparently a spicy tirade by saying, ``And you're ugly besides.''
</P>
<P>
   I just drive _ and drive _ and drive. About 60 miles to and from
work, with some side trips on various errands to pick up children
or deliver children to schools. I drive to the mountains when I'm
asked, and to the beach when I have the time. That comes to
hundreds of miles.
</P>
<P>
   I started driving at age 14. (Mobile County put no restrictions
on you at that time.) My father thought a Model T was abundantly
safe and that I demonstrated wisdom beyond my years by making my
schoolmate passengers get out and walk when we came to the narrow
bridge across Seymore Creek.
</P>
<P>
   I think he was pleased that when we played hooky from high
school that time and went downtown, I parked beside St. Joseph's
Catholic Church instead of next door to the bawdyhouse, which the
aunt of one of my co-hooky-players ran. I confess that I didn't
have in mind the character of respectability at the time. There was
just more traffic near the bawdyhouse, and I was a brand-new
driver.
</P>
<P>
   I'm still respectful of heavy traffic, which seems to
proliferate every day. But a couple of weeks ago, when I came back
from having an accident _ rare, I vow _ near Columbus, I felt
warmed and welcomed by Atlanta's traffic.
</P>
<P>
   I knew the exits and the street names and the landmarks. There
was the gold-domed Capitol and old Grady Memorial Hospital and the
turn for Crawford Long Hospital, where some of our births and
deaths occurred. There was the 14th Street bridge, which we saw
a-building, and our very own home street for 17 years. The spire of
our church was just beyond Patterson's, where we had so many
funerals. It was good to be home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
