<HEADER>
A4713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOOD-RECIPES08-COX     10-07 1158
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-RECIPES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Take these lessons home to enjoy
 &HT;    By Reagan Walker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   One look at a list of cooking classes and you'll get the idea.
Are you a beginning cook? There's a class (or a series) for you.
Want to go vegetarian? Check out the options. From ethnic to
down-home, confections to haute cuisine, there'll be a class
sometime in the coming months that will satisfy your whim. Here are
some recipes we culled from classes, ranging from a 10-minute party
dip to a three-part dessert. Your assignment: Try them, and eat.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Prosciutto Dip
</P>
<P>
   Makes 25 hors d'oeuvres
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Ursula Knaeusel has been teaching cooking classes in Atlanta for
25 years, never using the same recipe twice. This recipe comes from
her monthly newsletter and is indicative of her easy style. It
makes a great dip or a topping for baked potatoes.
</P>
<P>
   8ounces cream cheese, room temperature
</P>
<P>
   8ounces sour cream
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon dry chives
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon dry onion
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2teaspoons lemon pepper
</P>
<P>
   3to 4 ounces thin sliced prosciutto, cut into small pieces
</P>
<P>
   In a small bowl, mix together the cream cheese, sour cream,
chives, onion, lemon pepper and prosciutto and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 57 calories, 2 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 84), less than 1 gram carbohydrates, 16
milligrams cholesterol, 77 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Homemade Pasta
</P>
<P>
   With Wild Mushrooms, Arugula
</P>
<P>
   and Extra-Virgin Olive-Oil
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 35-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rising time: 30 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 7-9 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Mumbo Jumbo chef Shaun Doty demonstrated this dish for a class
recently at the Cook's Warehouse on Amsterdam Avenue in Midtown.
Making pasta proved to be easier than many thought, and this dish
was both simple and fabulous.
</P>
<P>
   3cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   4yolks and 1 whole egg, beaten together
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup plus 1 tablespoon extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon salt
</P>
<P>
   1cup wild mushrooms, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon red pepper flakes, or to taste
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon garlic, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup chicken stock
</P>
<P>
   1cup arugula, washed and stemmed
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup Parmagiana Reggiano
</P>
<P>
   Salt and pepper to taste
</P>
<P>
   2tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   3tablespoons diced tomato
</P>
<P>
   1tablespoon parsley, chopped
</P>
<P>
   Sift flour into a large metal bowl. Make a well in the center of
the flour by pushing it to the sides in a ring. Add the eggs, 1
tablespoon oil and salt. With a fork, slowly stir liquid
ingredients in a circular motion, incorporating some of the wall of
flour without breaking through it. When the mixture begins to come
together, incorporate just enough flour to form a loose ball. Be
careful not to add too much flour; you will not use it all. Remove
dough from the bowl and knead thoroughly to a smooth consistency.
The dough should not stick to the surface or your hands. Cover with
plastic wrap and let rest 30 minutes at room temperature. You can
make this in the morning and put in the refrigerator; pull out an
hour before putting through a pasta machine. Roll and cut into
fettuccine according to manufacturer's instructions that come with
your pasta machine.
</P>
<P>
   Bring large pot of salted water to a boil. In large skillet over
medium heat, heat 1/4 cup oil and add mushrooms, red pepper flakes
and garlic. Cook, stirring constantly, until mushrooms have
released some liquid. Add chicken stock and cook until reduced by
half. Add arugula, reduce heat to a simmer and cook until arugula
is wilted. Add fresh pasta to boiling water and cook 1 to 2 minutes
until al dente. Drain and add to sauce. Add cheese, salt and pepper
to taste and combine thoroughly. Finish with butter, tomato and
chopped parsley and serve immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 631 calories, 16 grams protein, 32 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 45), 69 grams carbohydrates, 285
milligrams cholesterol, 774 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   DESSERT
</P>
<P>
   Toasted Almond Pound Cake With Plum Chardonnay Sauce and Coconut
Macaroons
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   This really is three recipes served up as one outstanding
dessert, compliments of Kirk Parks, pastry chef at Nava restaurant.
The great thing is, each of the three parts can stand on its own,
so don't be afraid to steal one part or another for your own
inventions.
</P>
<P>
   Toasted Almond Pound Cake
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes Cooking time: 45-55 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1/2pound butter (two sticks), softened
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2cups all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon almond extract
</P>
<P>
   4large eggs
</P>
<P>
   1cup almonds, toasted and ground
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Butter and flour a 9-by-5-inch loaf
pan. With a mixer, cream the butter and sugar until light in color,
about 3-4 minutes. Scrape down the sides of the bowl a few times to
make sure everything gets incorporated. Sift the flour and baking
powder together and set aside. Add the almond extract and eggs to
the butter mixture and continue to mix until just combined. Pour in
the flour mixture and work until all the flour is absorbed. Fold in
the almonds, pour into the prepared pan and bake for 45-55 minutes.
Test with a toothpick to make sure cake is done. Let cool slightly
and take out of the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Plum Chardonnay Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes Cooking time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   1pound plums
</P>
<P>
   1cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   2cups chardonnay
</P>
<P>
   Pit the plums and place in a saucepan with the sugar and wine.
Bring to a boil and turn down to a simmer. Cook for about 10
minutes. Let cool slightly and blend in the blender until smooth.
Let cool.
</P>
<P>
   Coconut Macaroons
</P>
<P>
   Makes 18
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15-20 minutes Cooking time: 12-14 minutes
</P>
<P>
   2egg whites
</P>
<P>
   Pinch of salt
</P>
<P>
   2/3cup granulated sugar
</P>
<P>
   1/4cup all-purpose flour
</P>
<P>
   1/4teaspoon baking powder
</P>
<P>
   1/2teaspoon vanilla extract
</P>
<P>
   1cup flaked coconut
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 350 degrees. Line a cookie sheet with parchment
paper. In a clean mixer bowl add the egg whites and salt. With the
whip attachment, whip the whites on medium speed until foamy. Turn
the speed to high and add the sugar a little at a time until all
the sugar is in the mixture, and continue to whip until stiff,
shiny peaks are achieved, about 2-3 minutes. Sift the flour and
baking powder together; set aside. When the peaks are shiny, fold
the vanilla extract, flour mixture and coconut into the egg whites.
Spoon portions onto sheet and bake for about 12 minutes. They
should be golden.
</P>
<P>
   To assemble: Place about 1/3 cup of the Plum Chardonnay Sauce on
a dessert plate. Add a slice of Toasted Almond Pound Cake and
garnish with the Coconut Macaroons. Serve.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 764 calories, 10 grams protein, 39 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 45), 97 grams carbohydrates, 169
milligrams cholesterol, 423 milligrams sodium.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
