<HEADER>
A4714 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STYLE-BIGKIDS-COX     10-07 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STYLE-BIGKIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fitting in
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 11: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's one thing to have legs that go on for days or feet the size
of an NBA player if you're Elle Macpherson or Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   But when you're 12 years old and still growing, it's enough to
make the fashion police give up their beats.
</P>
<P>
   Finding youthful apparel for kids who have adult-size bodies can
be a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents rely on department stores such as Sears and
JCPenney that carry plus lines for girls and husky styles for boys.
Both stores sell sizes up to 20 and offer styles and colors that
make a kid look like a kid. Some parents, however, have resorted to
sewing their children's clothing, while others order from specialty
stores and catalogs such as J. Crew, Lands' End and L.L. Bean.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, options are limited.
</P>
<P>
   Parents and kidswear experts say the key to finding the
trendiest looks in clothes or shoes is to shop around. They
recommend going before your child needs a special occasion outfit,
to cut down on the stress of last-minute shopping. Another
suggestion is to find knowledgeable sales assistants and inform
them of your child's clothing needs. Developing a relationship with
store personnel can go a long way to make shopping easier and
keeping up with incoming styles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I find that that's often more helpful than a personal shopper
because you're working with someone right in the department who
knows the merchandise better,'' said Cindy DiCaprio, children's
wear buyer for Nordstrom. Shopping for kids _ no matter their size
_ can be a parental test of skill often mixed with trial and error.
</P>
<P>
   But Latonya Winfrey has become a pro at finding clothes for her
10-year-old daughter, Denesie, who wears a misses size 14. Winfrey
keeps it simple: jeans and loose-fitting T-shirts. When Denesie
needs an outfit for church or a special occasion, Winfrey usually
picks something from her own closet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we can find dresses that fit her, we buy them,'' Winfrey
said. ``That's not an easy process.''
</P>
<P>
   Susan Johnson has such a hard time finding jeans with a 36-inch
inseam to fit her 6-foot-2-inch daughter, Rachel Holm, 12, that she
orders direct from Levis.
</P>
<P>
   And Debra Hickson puts a lot of miles on her car looking for
size 18 shoes for her 12-year-old, 240-pound son, D'Angelo. Cathy
Fleming used to go on shopping expeditions until she discovered
that Nordstrom has a good selection of shoes to fit her 12-year-old
daughter Laura's size 11 1/2 feet.
</P>
<P>
   But children's shoe and apparel manufacturers don't make
shopping easy.
</P>
<P>
   Girls have the hardest time finding youthful, sporty looking
clothing because junior departments typically target young women in
the size 2 to 12 range. Larger sizes in the women's or misses
styles often look matronly and are not as colorful as some of the
smaller sizes.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a hole in the market for teens that is just not being
met,'' said Cara Kagan, editor of Girl, the younger version of Mode
magazine for plus-size women. Girl debuted on newsstands last month
and is scheduled for quarterly publication in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our research found that about 50 percent of teen girls wear
size 11or above. We're hoping that more and more manufacturers of
children's clothing produce sizes above 9. Everybody should have
beautiful, fashionable clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Tips for shopping for an adult-size child:
</P>
<P>
   -- Tunic-length tops that cover the bottom are safe bets for
kids who are tall.
</P>
<P>
   -- For stocky children, look for pants with an elastic waist or
half-elastic waist. Tops should be loose fitting.
</P>
<P>
   -- Browse the children's and junior department to check out
trends. Then mimic those styles in misses/men's departments to give
children a youthful look.
</P>
<P>
   -- Check out big and tall shops.
</P>
<P>
   -- Elongate an outfit for a short, stocky child by sticking with
one color.
</P>
<P>
   -- Loafers or lace-up oxfords look best on long feet. Girls with
large feet should also look for something with a little heel.
Athletic shoes with a dash of color look better in larger sizes
than all white.
</P>
<P>
   -- Purchase brands that tend to be cut longer or wider, such as
Lane Bryant's Venezia line _ trendy garments aimed at women between
17 and 25 who wear sizes 14 to 28.
</P>
<P>
   -- Get to know the salesclerks at your favorite apparel or
clothing store. A good clerk will inform you when merchandise ideal
for your child comes in.
</P>
<P>
   -- Call manufacturers to find out if sizes can be special
ordered.
</P>
<P>
   where to go
</P>
<P>
   Here are some stores to check out when shopping for larger
</P>
<P>
   sizes:
</P>
<P>
   -- Nordstrom: Children's shoes ranging from size 4 to 14, widths
double A through double E. Boys/men's shoes from size 5 through 20,
double A through
</P>
<P>
   5E.
</P>
<P>
   -- JCPenney and Sears: Plus sizes for girls, husky sizes for
boys through size 20.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
