<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4718 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRANDED-FURNITURE-ART     10-07 1060
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRANDED-FURNITURE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 HOME FURNISHINGS CALLED HEMINGWAY OR GARBO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By WILLIAM L. HAMILTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Papa's got a brand new bag.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 15, Ernest Hemingway will become a home-furnishings
brand. The Ernest Hemingway Collection _ 96 pieces of living room,
dining room and bedroom furniture and accessories _ will be
introduced at the International Home Furnishings Market in High
Point, N.C., the wholesale furniture exposition.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Bruccoli, a Hemingway scholar, isn't surprised.
``Hemingway was the most astute self-publicist that America has
ever known,'' he said. ``His brand name has outlived him by 37
years. People who have never read a book recognize him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Branding'' _ attaching a name or trademark to a product to
give it an aura of value and a sales hook _ is a familiar strategy
in fashion, luxury goods and entertainment. But it is about to hit
consumers where they sit. And the pitch has an odd new roll call,
with famous names from the four corners of the pop-cultural map,
Coca-Cola to Greta Garbo.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Mackie, the Hollywood costume designer, will be at High
Point, too, with his own spin, as will the Central Park Conservancy
and the Professional Golfers' Association.
</P>
<P>
   Mackie will bring to seating the glamour he brought to Barbie.
Central Park hopes to hit pay dirt, initially with rugs from a
``casual age of innocence.'' For the PGA Tour, ``styling which we
hope will be popular with 26.5 million golfers'' could be straight
fairway or pure sand pit.
</P>
<P>
   The Cole Porter Memories collection _ including $1,900 copies of
zebra-cloth chairs from Porter's Paris apartment and a $142,000
replica of the Steinway piano he played at the Waldorf-Astoria _ is
being introduced Thursday by J. Peterman Co. at the opening of its
Grand Central Terminal store in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Source Perrier furnishings arrived at Pierre Deux stores in
August. The company has restocked twice.
</P>
<P>
   With a strong economy producing a record $59 billion in sales in
the year ended in July for the furniture industry, a gold rush of
unlikely licensing agreements is now under way.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Lauren, the Moses of cross-merchandising, was just the
beginning. He moved into furnishings 15 years ago. Retail sales are
now $700 million annually. Next year could be the year when the way
furniture is marketed changes forever.
</P>
<P>
   For spring, expect the Faith Popcorn Cocooning collection. Ms.
Popcorn, the trend forecaster, is negotiating with Barcalounger on
the initial product: a recliner for women that will include
features for nursing mothers and aromatherapy.
</P>
<P>
   For fall 1999, meet the Beatles. The Yellow Submarine, a
franchise being launched next year by the three surviving band
members, will include inflatable children's furniture. (``We all
live ....'') ``The Beatles said fine,'' said Del Furano, the
president of Sony Signature, the Beatles' merchandising
representative. ``I wouldn't rule out lamps and sofas. We
encouraged them in home furnishings _ it's an exploding category.
Everyone's nesting, and they want images from their past.''
</P>
<P>
   Home furnishings, humble stay-at-homes, are one of the last,
wide frontiers for the hard celebrity sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big, uncharted territory for branding,'' said Juliet
Schor, a Harvard economist and the author of ``The Overspent
American: Upscaling, Downshifting and the New Consumer'' (Basic
Books, 1998). ``Home furnishings don't yet have the level of brand
identification that so many industries do, like cars and soft
drinks.''
</P>
<P>
   Licensed branded products, including apparel, cosmetics and
toys, account for $80 billion annually in retail sales in the
United States, according to the Licensing Industry Manufacturers
Association. Home furnishings now represent $1 billion of that.
``It's one of the hottest segments of licensing,'' said Charles
Riotto, the executive director.
</P>
<P>
   Working with living celebrities, the estates of deceased
celebrities (or ``living legends,'' as licensing agents prefer to
call them) and big trademarks like Coca-Cola, which introduced its
bedding at a trade show this month, the furnishings industry is
banking on the hope that branding will help sales to its core
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Baby boomers, notorious for refusing to grow old, will be
encouraged to buy middle-aged merchandise like furniture by
identifying it with the eternal youth of popular culture.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have many heroes today, as the millennium
approaches,'' said Marla Metzner, president of Fashion Licensing of
America. She created the Ernest Hemingway brand with Hemingway's
three sons, Jack, Gregory and Patrick. ``We're going back to the
great icons of the century, as heroic brands.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Metzner also represents F. Scott Fitzgerald's grandchildren,
who have asked for a Fitzgerald brand. ``I see a line that would be
a mix _ from art deco to Ivy League,'' she said. ```The Great
Gatsby' is America's favorite novel _ and there's going to be a
made-for-television movie next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Monroe, Amelia Earhart and Greta Garbo _ an early
cocooner _ are under serious review, too. ``Symbols like brands
have become a part of reality, a halo,'' said Dr. Richard Shweder,
a cultural anthropologist at the University of Chicago. ``In India,
where I work, people believe water from the Ganges has a potent
positive power.''
</P>
<P>
   Does star power really give furniture sales a boost? The Arnold
Palmer furniture collection, introduced in 1996, is doing well. So
is Eddie Bauer's. Alexander Julian, the fashion designer, is a hit,
with $70 million to $90 million in wholesale business.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Blass' stripped-down interpretations of his own
antiques have been labeled lemons by the industry. And Norman
Rockwell painted himself out of the picture with licensed designs
that didn't sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``The failure rate's pretty high,'' said Warren Shoulberg,
editor of Home Textiles Today, an industry publication. ``For every
successful Ralph Lauren program, there are two or three who fall
flat on their faces.'' The losers' circle is more crowded than the
winners' circle.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
