<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From `ER' to `Donny': Some random notes
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television is the land without context, a place where randomness
rules. In the age of the clicker, this is more true than ever, as
restless viewers construct their own mosaic of mini-blips of shows.
</P>
<P>
   If it's good enough for television, it's good enough for the
Channel Surfer. Today's TV mosaic of random observations:
</P>
<P>
   -- In its first two weeks back, ``ER'' has been ``The Lucy
Show,'' as the series has focused on newcomer Lucy Knight (Kellie
Martin). She's cute as a button, but let's get back to the old
characters. Starting, say, tonight.
</P>
<P>
   -- Anybody worried that UPN's ``The Secret Diary of Desmond
Pfeiffer'' would topple the republic can rest easy. The debut
episode Monday night drew only 2 million viewers, a measly 1.6
percent of the TV audience, according to Nielsen. That's with big
articles in Time and Newsweek about the show.
</P>
<P>
   -- That new CNN set is so cool it makes you realize how cheesy
the old set was.
</P>
<P>
   -- NBC's new sitcom ``Will &AMP; Grace'' (9:30 p.m. ET Mondays) is a
moderate hit. It would be even better, though, if they got rid of
Will and Grace and made the show about the two wacko supporting
characters, Jack (Sean Hayes) and Karen (Megan Mullally).
</P>
<P>
   -- The second episode of ``Felicity'' (9 p.m. ET Tuesdays on WB)
was as wonderful as the pilot, cementing its rep as the best of the
new season's shows.
</P>
<P>
   -- A literary wag once said of Henry James' novels that he
chewed more than he bit off. For TV's equivalent, see CNN's
``Burden of Proof.''
</P>
<P>
   -- The new syndicated Osmond talk show ``Donny &AMP; Marie'' (check
local, listings) makes ``The Rosie O'Donnell Show'' seem relatively
nihilistic.
</P>
<P>
   -- Hail to Comedy Central's ``The Daily Show'' (11 o'clock ET
weeknights), which has started calling its coverage of the
Clinton-Starr-Lewinsky-Congress story ``Make It Stop.''
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Amanpour awaits visa
</P>
<P>
   CNN's star correspondent, Christiane Amanpour, has been frozen
out of Kosovo, Yugoslavia, the one place she and CNN most want her
to be right now. While Amanpour waits in London, the Yugoslavian
government is refusing to grant her an entry visa, says Eason
Jordan, president of CNN International. The government is upset
over a report Amanpour did about an alleged Serbian war criminal,
Jordan says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governments play games with visas sometimes,'' Jordan says,
``but there's still some hope.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, CNN's Brent Sadler is in Yugoslavia providing
Kosovo coverage for CNN.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
