<HEADER>
A4719 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BRANDED-FURNITURE-ART     10-07 0674
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRANDED-FURNITURE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: winners' circle.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Cher, the actress and singer, lost her tattooed skin four years
ago with ``Sanctuary,'' a direct-mail catalog that included
Gothic-style home furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was ahead of my time,'' she said of the self-financed
effort, which was brought down, she said, by mismanagement and
order-fulfillment problems. The collection will be reintroduced on
the Internet in November at www.cher.com.
</P>
<P>
   But Cher has no illusions about the allure of a name in the
furniture business. ``I don't think that has much to do with
furniture,'' she said. ``People look at something that's going to
come into their home and it either touches them or it doesn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Her friend and colleague Bob Mackie agreed. ``I'm not going to
pretend I'm this closet furniture designer,'' he said. Sketches of
the Louis XV-style furniture for his collection were presented by
the manufacturer, American Drew, a division of Ladd Furniture Co. A
five-piece bedroom suite will sell for a suggested $5,000 to $6,000
when it arrives in stores next spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope people will be buying the collection for the
furniture,'' Mackie said. ``Buying it because somebody's name is
attached _ that's a bad idea.''
</P>
<P>
   With the success of ``lifestyle'' home-furnishing retailers like
Pottery Barn and Crate and Barrel, celebrity lifestyle retailing
may not be an awkward reach; it is familiar ground to an adult
population used to cultural souvenirs like T-shirts and baseball
caps.
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Horn, director of home furnishings for Walt Disney
Consumer Products, will be at High Point this month, shopping for
licensees for a Disney home collection. ``Guests staying at the
theme hotels want to be able to buy the sofas and tables, so they
can couple their memories with the furniture around them at home,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   How dear are your memories? And at what price fame, for
furnishings manufacturers?
</P>
<P>
   The typical royalty rate is 1 percent to 5 percent, depending on
the power of your pull. ``Living legends'' like Marilyn Monroe can
go as high as 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Does the consumer get something original? More or less. Most
celebrity collections are much like the rest of the companies'
furniture, often at the higher end. The actual cost of developing a
medium-size celebrity collection like Mackie's is largely the same
as it would be for a group of unbranded furniture, which is
generally $200,000 to $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   The ``brand name'' _ living, dead or incorporated _ has a veto
on designs presented by the company, and a voice to suggest or
change. It is rarely exercised.
</P>
<P>
   ``PGA Tour had a consultant who looked at our ideas,'' said
Shelby Pulino-Pigot, the vice president of merchandising at
Vanguard Furniture and a designer of the PGA Tour collection.
``They never changed a thing.''
</P>
<P>
   What is one getting, then, at the end of the day, as one settles
into one's identity?
</P>
<P>
   ``Confidence and passion, and a romance mixed with life and
death,'' Ms. Metzner, the licensing agent for Hemingway Ltd., said
of the new brand that will have its premiere at High Point.
Thomasville Furniture Industries, the manufacturer, is introducing
four theme collections: Kenya, Key West, Ketchum and Havana. There
is no farewell to armoires: two are being offered. Sturdy but not
unstable.
</P>
<P>
   Thomasville conducted a focus group to gauge the market for the
brand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Negativity came up from about 5 percent,'' said James Adams,
senior vice president for sales and marketing. ``He married four
times _ this is Hemingway. He was a handsome guy. But there's an
edge to this, that kind of blows the bad stuff away.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one ever asked about what the furniture looked like. That's
a great collection.''
</P>
<P>
   Brian Carroll, an editor at Furniture Today, said: ``The
industry has been chastened. No matter whose name you have, you're
going to have to pay careful attention to the product. If the
product's not exquisite, it's going to fail.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the sun also sets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
