<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Oct. 8, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A slow-moving cold front will lift an ample supply of moist air
covering the East on Thursday, resulting in widespread rainfall. To
the north, the axis of heaviest rain with embedded thunderstorms
will shift from the central and northern Appalachians early
Thursday to the coastal plain by midday, and finally offshore late
Thursday night as the front gradually moves off the Middle Atlantic
and Northeast coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Given the slow movement of the front, rainfall amounts of
between { and 1 inch of rain are expected, with isolated higher
values.
</P>
<P>
   Farther south, clusters of showers and thunderstorms will
accompany the front through the Southeast. As the tail end of the
front stalls over the Gulf of Mexico, tropical moisture will be
drawn onshore, resulting in storms with locally heavy rains.
</P>
<P>
   Breezes from the north will send cooler and drier air through
the Ohio Valley to the western slopes of the Appalachians in the
wake of the front. Patches of residual moisture, however, may
trigger a few light showers near the eastern Great Lakes. Drier air
will spread across the Appalachians toward the coast late Thursday
night.
</P>
<P>
   Sprawling high pressure will provide ample sunshine from the
upper Midwest to the western Gulf states, then westward to the
central Rockies and Southwestern states. Parts of the western
Plains will be 10 to 20 degrees warmer than on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Moist winds from the Pacific Ocean will follow a cold front in
the Northwest. Patchy coastal showers are expected across
Washington and Oregon, with snow possible above 6,000 feet in the
northern Cascades.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Ozone Hole
</P>
<P>
   Ozone, mainly a stratospheric gas that shields earth from
ultraviolet rays, has undergone its annual springtime depletion
over Antarctica. The ``ozone hole'' has been born again. During
Southern Hemisphere winter, air currents steer ozone to the South
Pole. There it sinks into the lower stratosphere, where chlorine _
a building block of man-made chemicals called chlorofluorocarbons _
lurks. As the sun appears, it photochemically frees chlorine to
devour ozone. Destruction tapers off and ozone rebounds after
October as the stratosphere warms and chlorine becomes dormant.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
