<SLUG> BC-DEPRESSION-SCREENING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS SCREENING FOR DEPRESSION SYMPTOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD SALTUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you visit your doctor Thursday, you could be handed a simple
pencil-and-paper test in the waiting area to check for unsuspected
clinical depression, as National Depression Screening Day enlists
thousands of primary-care physicians in an effort to detect the
often-missed disorder.
</P>
<P>
   With less fuss than filling out an insurance form, the
10-question test asks about feelings and symptoms that could
indicate significant depression. Three additional questions probe
for signs of manic-depression.
</P>
<P>
   By the time you see the doctor, he or she or an assistant will
have scored the test, developed by Harvard Medical School
psychiatrists. If the results suggest depression, the physician can
ask more questions and get a better picture of the problems. With
today's generally safe and effective antidepressants, many
primary-care doctors will prescribe them as a first-line treatment,
while others will refer the patient to a mental-health
professional.
</P>
<P>
   Over 4,000 clinicians across the country will be screening an
estimated 100,000 people, said Barbara Kopans, associate director
of National Depression Screening Day, now in its ninth year. The
annual effort to bring more depressed people into treatment was
launched at Quincy (Mass.) Hospital in 1991 by Dr. Douglas G.
Jacobs, a Harvard psychiatrist who heads the National Depression
Screening Project.
</P>
<P>
   Another 100,000 people are expected to take a similar, but
longer, test and be interviewed at 3,000 public screening sites.
(Call 1-800-573-4433 to find the nearest site.)
</P>
<P>
   While some patients are aware that they may be depressed, others
come in with headaches, stomach pain, appetite and weight changes,
and other symptoms that can't be traced to a physical problem and
suggest the possibility of depression, said Dr. Meyer Bornstein, an
obstetrician-gynecologist. The test has been validated in
large-scale trials so that a positive or negative score can help
make the diagnosis or rule it out.
</P>
<P>
   Bornstein said that in most cases he refers patients who suffer
from depression to psychologists or psychiatrists. ``I really feel
I don't just want to put them on medication,'' he said. ``It
doesn't solve the whole problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Many primary-care doctors, however, are comfortable prescribing
an antidepressant and monitoring the patient's response over time.
If the patient doesn't get better, referral to a mental-health
professional is a second option.
</P>
<P>
   The screening day and the participation by primary-care doctors
are being sponsored by the American Medical Association, the
American Psychiatric Association, McLean Hospital, and several
other medical and mental-health organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Herbert S. Waxman, a vice president at the American College
of Physicians, one of the sponsors, said the organization has been
well aware that ``you find that a lot of people who are
significantly depressed in primary care practice, and the
proportion of that group that's been recognized is distressingly
small.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; The college represents 100,000 doctors. Waxman said they have
been urged to look for signs of depression when patients visit, and
they have tried a number of different assessment tests. ``But they
need something that's simple and reliable that's suitable'' for the
brief time doctors have with patients in an outpatient setting. For
that reason, he said, the college was glad to join in with the
screening program.
</P>
<P>
   It's estimated that 17 million Americans suffer from depression
annually, but only half of them receive treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the signs of depression that the test targets are a loss
of pleasure, hope and interest, changes in sleeping and eating
patterns, trouble concentrating or making decisions, and thoughts
of suicide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
