<SLUG> BC-CIR-GEEK-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: WASH.)  
 INTERNET HEROINE TAKES AIM AT TV  
 A NEW ELECTRONIC PAPERBACK TO READ ON PLANES AND TRAINS  
 A LIBRARY CARD FOR TECHIES FROM MACMILLAN'S WEB SITE  
 A COMPUTER ANTI-THEFT ALARM THAT SQUEALS LIKE A STUCK PIG   
 WITH NEW DISK DRIVE, INVENTOR OF FLOPPY COMPETES WITH ITSELF  
 GENERAL CONSUMERS ARE SIMILAR TO THOSE PLUGGED INTO WEB  
 THE DOCTOR IS IN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's a bird. It's a plane. No, it's a television development
deal for a caped Internet heroine who flies to the rescue of broken
hearts and fractured relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Breakup Girl, the clever creation of Lynn Harris, 29, a
freelance writer and stand-up comedian, and Chris Kalb, 31, her
roommate-artist-friend, blazed onto the World Wide Web 10 months
ago.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking through online dating advice columns, essays and a cute
and quirky comic strip, Breakup Girl (www.breakupgirl.com) has
become a star on the Net, drawing 45,000 visitors a month.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Morton, a former producer for David Letterman, said he
wanted to swell Breakup Girl's following to millions by making her
a star on a television network, starting with ABC. Morton's
company, Panamort Television, has a first-look arrangement with the
network.
</P>
<P>
   ``For years, movies and novels and other different media
influenced television,'' Morton said. ``As time has gone on, now
it's the Web.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Harris, who does a monthly live comedy club performance
based on her character, said plans were to create a 30-minute
situation comedy around the young woman who creates the Web site
and her cyberspace alter ego, Breakup Girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``What would be ultra cool is to show the internal tension by
toggling between the real character and the superhero,'' Ms. Harris
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hopes are to have a pilot ready by spring for network
consideration, said Morton, who noted that the show might combine
live action and animation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Michel Marriott
</P>
<P>
   A New Electronic Paperback To Read on Planes and Trains
</P>
<P>
   The maker of a new electronic book is hoping it will become the
dog-eared paperback of the digital age. Weighing in at less than a
pound and costing under $200, the grandly named Millenium Reader,
scheduled for release this fall by Librius Inc. of Bellevue, Wash.,
will be lighter and less expensive than its current competitors.
Users will be able to go to the Librius storefront on the Internet,
browse the virtual shelves and download encrypted texts to the
Reader. The company estimates that each title will cost about 30
percent less than bound copies of the same text. The Reader can
hold up to 4,000 pages, and other purchases can be stored by the
user on the Librius server.
</P>
<P>
   Librius texts can also be downloaded to Windows CE and 3Com Palm
devices, but Librius still believes that an argument can be made
for the Reader. ``A Windows CE device can cost over $300,'' said
Don Bottoms, president of Librius. ``The Rocketbook (a competing
electronic book) costs $400. We think that for electronic books to
be accepted, they have to be less expensive.''
</P>
<P>
   There had been published reports that the company was focusing
on the romance novel market to jump-start sales, but Bottoms said
there was more to Librius than midnight trysts, heaving bosoms and
cleft-chinned heroes named Dag.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure we're in serious discussions with romance publishers,''
Bottoms said. ``We're in serious discussions with all kinds of
publishers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Librius database has 4,000 titles, Bottoms said, most of
them books in the public domain, but there are some serious
contemporary works, like Frank McCourt's ``Angela's Ashes.'' By the
launching date, the company hopes to have increased the databank to
10,000 titles.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you walk through an airplane, you see that people have
their office reading and their leisure reading, usually a
paperback,'' Bottoms said. ``That's the market we're after.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Bruce Headlam
</P>
<P>
   A Library Card for Techies From Macmillan's Web Site
</P>
<P>
   More than 200,000 people are taking advantage of full-text
computer books offered on line by the Macmillan Personal Bookshelf
(www.mcp.com/personal) to coach themselves through glitches or
explore new digital worlds, the company announced last week.
</P>
<P>
   Each subscriber is allowed access to up to five books at a time
from the 175 books available. But because subscribers can move
books on and off their list at will, that's not much of a
restriction.
</P>
<P>
   The books from Macmillan and other publishers range from a
Windows 98 tutorial to teach-yourself-programming guides and
advanced manuals. And at least one of the books teaches
self-defense: ``Maximum Security: A Hacker's Guide to Protecting
Your Internet Site and Network.'' That one's by Anonymous.
</P>
<P>
   _ Karen Freeman
</P>
<P>
   A Computer Anti-Theft Alarm That Squeals Like a Stuck Pig
</P>
<P>
   Car alarms have become an annoying, if necessary, part of the
American soundscape, and a company wants computer alarms to join
the racket.
</P>
<P>
   The Bluvenom Anti-Theft Device, a computer security alarm made
of polycarbonate plastic, is locked to a desktop computer through
the floppy disk drive (the $70 model) or to a laptop through the
parallel port ($75). If the computer is moved after the device is
locked and set, Bluvenom will, in the words of the company's
co-founder, Gary Moser, ``squeal like a stuck pig.'' In fact,
Bluvenom will squeal a like stuck pig at 120 decibels, enough to
damage eardrums at close range, for seven hours or until the unit
is deactivated by a coded key.
</P>
<P>
   BluVenom has some advantages over car alarms. Users can adjust
the sensitivity to account for accidental bumps, and if the device
is jostled, it will emit a warning hiss.
</P>
<P>
   Moser hopes another feature will attract corporate clients. When
one alarm goes off, others within electronic earshot will go off in
sympathy, creating an entire roomful of 120-decibel stuck pigs.
Let's hope the car alarm industry doesn't hear about this.
</P>
<P>
   _ Bruce Headlam
</P>
<P>
   With New Disk Drive, Inventor Of Floppy Competes With Itself
</P>
<P>
   The inventor of the 3.5-inch floppy disk is joining the already
crowded battle to dislodge it as the removal computer storage
device of choice. This week, Sony and Fujifilm officially unveiled
HiFD, a floppy disk on steroids that holds about 140 times more
information than a conventional disk, and the HiFD disk drive.
</P>
<P>
   HiFD's capacity is double that of the popular Zip disk but well
below the 1 gigabyte offered by the Syquest Sparq drive which uses
a more costly, hard drive technology for its disks. ``We believe
that the HiFD has the capacity to be the next standard,'' said
Scott McNulty, Fuji's group product manager for computer products.
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't mean that the two companies are turning their backs
on conventional floppies. Sony's new drive also works with the
old-style disks it introduced 12 years ago. Of its competitors,
only the 120-megabyte Imation Superdisk offers such dual service.
And, in a lapse of corporate synergy, there were two announced
prices for the disks: $14.99 for disks with the Sony label, $13.99
for Fuji. The drive, made by Sony, costs $199.
</P>
<P>
   Fuji is heavily promoting HiFD's theoretical ability to transfer
data about 2.5 times faster than a Zip drive. But the drive that
will be in stores by the end of next month will be an external
model that plugs only into computer printer ports, greatly limiting
its top speed. Users hoping to store time-sensitive materials such
as full motion videos on HiFD drives will have to wait for the
arrival of internal models.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ian Austen
</P>
<P>
   General Consumers Are Similar To Those Plugged Into Web
</P>
<P>
   It sometimes seems there are two parallel universes, one with
tech-savvy Netizens on the front lines of the digital revolution,
and one with plain old folks who think calculators, in-person
conversation and paper-based organizers work just fine. One new
study finds those universes are not as far apart as they appear.
</P>
<P>
   Interactive Solutions Group, a division of Market Facts Inc.,
finds that the general consumer population and Internet users
``mirror one another in most buying habits.''
</P>
<P>
   The study of 3,000 households found that when the group of
Internet users are controlled to reflect the demographics of the
general population, they report similar responses to questions
about lifestyle, travel, health issues and media habits.
Interactive Solutions Group, which researches buyer habits on the
Web, hopes the survey will demonstrate to major corporations that
they can rely on the validity of marketing surveys taken via the
Net.
</P>
<P>
   _ Matt Richtel
</P>
<P>
   The Doctor Is In
</P>
<P>
   Think of it as a doctor's office with the world's largest
waiting room. America's Doctor Online is a new service provided to
members of America Online. Found on AOL's Health channel, America's
Doctor Online (keyword: amdoc) will provide AOL users with free
access to certified primary-care physicians either through e-mail
correspondence or through real-time conversations in chat rooms.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL is always talking about the online community.'' said Dr.
Scott Rifkin, the service's founder. ``Well, to have a community,
you need medical information. I just thought there ought to be docs
talking to users.''
</P>
<P>
   There are no diagnoses, prescriptions, record-keeping or
follow-ups. The more than 40 ADOL physicians can dispense general
medical information only.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1827EDT &QL; 
