A4729 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-REDSOX-BOS &LR;      10-07 0538
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REDSOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL, DOMINICAN RELIEF, MIX AT PRESS CONFERENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It didn't take long for the first baseball question to
come, even though Dan Duquette said the focus of Wednesday's Fenway
Park press conference was not about signing Mo Vaughn, acquiring
another big-name pitcher, or adding someone to hit behind Nomar
Garciaparra.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not here to talk about Mo, we're here to talk about
Joe,'' the Red Sox general manager said, referring to
Representative Joseph Kennedy. The congressman, Catholic Charities,
Pedro Martinez, and Red Sox chief executive officer John Harrington
have collaborated to help send supplies to the Dominican Republic
for victims of Hurricane Georges. The storm killed more than 200
people in the Dominican, left nearly a half-million homeless, and,
according to Catholic Relief Services, led to economic losses that
could exceed $3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, a Dominican from Manoguayabo, donated $100,000 through
his own foundation and pledged an additional $10,000 when he heard
of the Sox' involvement. Citizens Energy Corporation gave $10,000
to help local organizers ship 10 40-foot containers filled with
supplies from Lawrence, Hyde Park, and Worcester to the Dominican.
The Sox also donated $10,000. Kennedy's office estimates that it
will cost about $2,200 to send each container to the Dominican.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez, known throughout the island for his philanthropy,
could not attend Wednesday's conference.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Sox are less than a week removed from their playoff
exit at the hands of the Indians, there were some inevitable
baseball comments and questions. Kennedy got a few laughs when he
said, ``I called up my Uncle Teddy and asked him if he wanted to
place a call to Sammy Sooser ... and I think he reached out to Mac
McGwire as well.'' Last month, Ted Kennedy badly mispronounced the
names of home run leaders Sammy Sosa and Mark McGwire at a
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Duquette, of course, also was asked about baseball. He said he
spends ``every waking moment'' thinking that the Sox could have
been in the American League Championship Series against the
Yankees. ``We were looking forward to Game 5: Pedro Martinez vs.
Jaret Wright. The Indians weren't looking forward to Game 5,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, he was asked about Mo rather than Joe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to make an effort to re-sign him, and hopefully,
he'll re-up with the Sox,'' he said of free agent Vaughn. Asked
when negotiations would begin, Duquette answered, ``Soon.''
</P>
<P>
   There were questions about third base coach Wendell Kim's
decision to send John Valentin home during a key Game 4 play.
Valentin was thrown out at the plate by outfielder David Justice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We needed to score runs to win that ballgame, and it was a
reasonable gamble _ the bottom part of our order hadn't produced
the whole series, and that's what was coming up,'' Duquette said.
``So Wendell Kim made his best judgment to send Valentin and
Valentin made his best effort to score.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Information on making supply donations to the Dominican can be
obtained by calling Catholic Charities at 617-482-5440.)
</P>
</TEXT>
