<HEADLINE>
CULTURE NOTES: SECOND ACT, AUTHOR! AUTHOR!, WAR DRESS,
DESECRATION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: GERMANY, FRANCE, Calif., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By LAWRENCE   VANGELDER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The curtain rises Thursday at the Mark Taper Forum in Los
Angeles on previews of a version of Stephen Sondheim's revue
``Putting It Together,'' with Carol Burnett, Bronson Pinchot, Susan
Egan, John McCook and John Barrowman. Sondheim has revised the
show, which attracted a mixed reception in 1993 at the Manhattan
Theater Club. New songs drawn from the Sondheim canon have been put
in and others have been taken out in altering this show about
relationships for audiences in Los Angeles. The piece is also being
tailored to Ms. Burnett's dramatic abilities as well as her musical
and comedic talents. The official opening will be on Oct. 25, and
the run has been extended for a week through Dec. 6. Ticket sales
are the best in the Taper's 31-year history.
</P>
<P>
   Author! Author!
</P>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany _ Celebrating its 50th anniversary, the
Frankfurt Book Fair opened Wednesday amid undertones of political
controversy and expectations of attracting 300,000 visitors to see
the wares of 6,500 exhibitors from 105 countries. Ayse Nur
Zarakolu, a Turkish author, was expected Thursday after Turkish
officials lifted a ban preventing her from traveling to Germany to
accept the $6,000 prize accompanying the new International Freedom
to Publish Award. She served nearly 16 months in prison for
publishing books on the conflict with Kurdish rebels and human
rights violations in Turkey. The British author Salman Rushdie put
in an appearance. Other authors participating include Ken Follett
and Patricia Cornwell.
</P>
<P>
   War Dress
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Armor worn by Renaissance kings and captains, who
hoped to project an aura of power and virtue by arraying themselves
like the heroes of Roman history and mythology, goes on display
Thursday at the Metropolitan Museum of Art. The exhibition is
billed as the first comprehensive survey of the classically
inspired parade armor created by Filippo Negroli, the most
celebrated Italian armorer of the 16th century, and his
contemporaries in Milan, Mantua and Brescia. The show, ``Heroic
Armor of the Italian Renaissance: Filippo Negroli and His
Contemporaries,'' features more than 60 works, including the
personal harnesses of the Holy Roman Emperor Charles V, Henry VII
of France and the dukes of Urbino. The exhibition continues through
Jan. 17.
</P>
<P>
   Desecration
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ Vandals have stolen the head of a statue at Notre Dame
Cathedral in Paris and damaged five others. According to the French
Culture Ministry, the damage was not immediately discovered because
the western face of the Gothic cathedral, where the statues stand,
has been shrouded in scaffolding during a restoration. The head was
taken from a 13th-century statue, and the damaged statues date from
the 12th, 13th and 19th centuries. The case is being investigated
by police units that deal with gang activity and the theft of
cultural treasures.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - &QR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1829EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0264 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 18:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT &LR;      10-07 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-TALK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERIAL SLEUTHS, SPREADING GLEE 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By MARTIN ARNOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few things bring a merry heart to a fiction publisher quicker
than the coming of a character who will endure in novel after novel
and, if truly lucky, in movie after movie. Most such characters are
in murder inventions or other thrillers, usually noir. But
sometimes they perpetuate and flourish in adventure make-believes.
</P>
<P>
   Often their creators turn out a novel every 15 months or so. For
the lucky publisher and the addicted reader, when the new book
comes out in hardcover, the previous one hits in paperback.
Publishing bliss.
</P>
<P>
   The meticulously logical and thoroughly implausible Sherlock
Holmes was the first internationally famous serial private eye, and
the idea of following one detective from tale to tale spread all
over the English landscape, often with tweedy older ladies as
detectives. The genre exploded more robustly in the United States
with Raymond Chandler's Philip Marlowe, moralist, avenger, tough
guy. The stories went from appealing to the puzzle-solvers to
becoming morality tales. They didn't need much logic. When
Chandler's great ``Big Sleep'' was made into the Bogart-Bacall
movie, the director, Howard Hawks, couldn't figure out who had
murdered a character. He asked Chandler and the novelist told him
he didn't know either. The genre is about character, not plot. You
care about Marlowe, not the story.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, American novelists have created a yeasty muster of
private investigators and other enduring apprehenders of evildoers.
Fans now are not only fascinated by the murder cases these
characters have solved but also enjoy chewing over the psyches and
the familial details of such as Spenser, Dr. Kay Scarpetta, Sgt.
Lloyd Hopkins, the National Park Service Ranger Anna Pigeon and
that great Moscow chief investigator, ``Gorky Park's'' Arkady
Renko, to name but a few.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, continuity and familiar characters account in part for
the popularity of the ``Star Wars'' and ``Star Trek'' series and of
Patrick O'Brian's cracking good Aubrey-Maturin sea stories. Irywn
Applebaum, president and publisher of Bantam Books, said of these
series books that the reader pleasure was so great ``because it's
like going to a family reunion without having to bring your own
stories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With the good writers,'' he said, ``the character's
psychological growth doesn't get in the way of the story; in fact,
you're more interested in what's going on in Spenser's life or Kay
Scarpetta's life than anything else.''
</P>
<P>
   The author's kinship is often quite different. Robert B. Parker,
author of the Spenser novels (Putnam), said that Spenser ``is less
real to me than to readers,'' adding: ``I know more than anyone
that he's created, made up. I don't throw him into the open page
and let him lead me along. Some writers say that because they have
nothing else to say.'' Spenser is in his early 60s and ``has my
memories.'' The private investigator has a long life ahead, Parker
said, but the writer has developed a younger serial character,
Jesse Stone, 35, subject of two novels, and is writing a novel
about a woman who is a private investigator, Sunny Randall, who
will be played by Helen Hunt in the done-deal movie.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Cruz Smith, on the other hand, has real affection for
Arkady Renko, his Moscow detective, who is now en route to Havana
for his fourth appearance in a (Random House) novel. Smith
alternates between Renko and other stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Renko's a strong enough character to withstand my
personality,'' Smith said. ``He's bright and a great guy to work
with because you sense he's not finished yet. He's done a lot of
maturing and is still maturing, but you can't entirely control
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Gritty women are popular sleuths, not surprisingly since women
buy most books. Besides Patricia Cornwell's Scarpetta, Putnam has a
series by Nevada Barr starring Anna Pigeon, a forest ranger
detective. Ms. Barr, a former ranger, said that she channels her
own feelings through Pigeon, whom she allows to ``get older and
learn because if she doesn't, then pretty soon you're just moving
paper dolls.''
</P>
<P>
   A master of the genre and one of the most interesting and
probably ego-driven novelists around is James Ellroy. His ``L.A.
Confidential'' (Mysterious Press, 1990) became an acclaimed movie.
</P>
<P>
   Ellroy ended his serial policeman, the unlikable Sgt. Lloyd
Hopkins, after three books that were republished recently in one
volume titled ``L.A. Noir'' (Mysterious Press). ``I didn't care
whether my readers liked Lloyd Hopkins as long as they liked the
books he was in,'' Ellroy has said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I just want to write bigger, richer, larger, deeper books,
20th-century historical novels,'' is the way Ellroy explains the
disappearance of Hopkins. Still, characters from ``American
Tabloid,'' a historical novel depicting the underbelly of the
Kennedy era, will reappear in two sequels.
</P>
<P>
   As Ellroy more or less jumps out, novelist Dean Koontz is
leaping in with a night-prowling serial character named Christopher
Snow, who will make his second appearance for Bantam late in
December. There's no mystery why. But publishing does have its
inscrutables, particularly in this esoteric genre.
</P>
<P>
   What is the masters' master up to? Ellroy has called Thomas
Harris' ``Red Dragon'' (Putnam) the ``greatest suspense novel ever
written.'' In it, he introduced a brilliant FBI tracker of serial
killers, Will Graham. Harris was able to do what great writers do:
psychologically inhabit Graham in the same way that the fictional
Graham was able to inhabit the serial killer he was hunting.
</P>
<P>
   A character who made a slight, almost cameo, appearance in ``The
Red Dragon'' was the brilliant psychopath Dr. Hannibal Lecter.
</P>
<P>
   Graham, a very appealing character indeed, did not make it into
Harris' next novel, ``The Silence of the Lambs'' (St. Martin's
Press). But Hannibal Lecter certainly did. Somewhere the reclusive
Harris is busy writing another novel, this one for Delacorte. It is
said he is once again inhabiting Hannibal Lecter.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1831EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0265 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 18:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4750 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TELESCOPE-BOOK-REVIEW     10-07 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELESCOPE-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SEEING AND BELIEVING': THE HEAVENS CAME TUMBLING TO EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.)  
(lb) 
 By CHRISTOPHER LEHMANN-HAUPT   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the many pleasures of Richard Panek's elegant new book,
``Seeing and Believing: How the Telescope Opened Our Eyes and Minds
to the Heavens,'' is its epigraph by John Cheever: ``The children
have built something out of an orange crate, something preposterous
and ascendant. ...''
</P>
<P>
   This poetically captures the technical side of Panek's story,
the children being mankind, the orange crate being the telescope,
and the ``something preposterous and ascendant'' being audacious
new theories about the universe that time and again defied what
passed for common sense.
</P>
<P>
   Panek's story begins, of course, with Galileo in November 1609,
improving a rumored novelty involving the correct alignment of two
lenses in a leaden tube and his use of it to discover other planets
in our solar system. From here the author traces the technical
progress of the telescope through lengthening, the addition of a
magnifying eye piece and the placement of measuring devices within.
</P>
<P>
   A crucial discovery along the way was that observing the heavens
had less to do with magnification than with the gathering of light,
and this led to the use of telescopes with mirrors, photography and
spectroscopy or the passing of telescoped light through a prism to
analyze its sources.
</P>
<P>
   Only with the development of the radio telescope was it
discovered that ``visible light covered only 2 percent of the
electromagnetic spectrum,'' Panek writes. But with the coming of
the computer and the space satellite, astronomers could drill a
``hole ... through the heavens,'' as Panek puts it.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1995, the Hubble Space Telescope revealed that the
universe comprised not 10 billion galaxies, as had been previously
thought, but some 50 billion.
</P>
<P>
   All this amazing technical evolution is described here with
clarity and ease. Panek is a freelance reporter, an award-winning
short-story writer and the author of ``Waterloo Diamonds,'' a
social history of an Iowa community told through its baseball
fortunes. He writes about science with practiced fluency. If you
haven't yet gotten matter like quasars, pulsars and gamma rays
entirely straight in your mind, this book will prove invaluable.
</P>
<P>
   But what makes ``Seeing and Believing'' most unusual is the way
Panek treats the implications of his history, the way he shows how
the telescope's development moved in advance of mankind's
understanding. To convey this as vividly as he does requires a
skill just as demanding as the ability to explain new developments,
namely a capacity to imagine and make clear how people saw things
in the past.
</P>
<P>
   The metaphor he uses to describe how the telescope affected
human consciousness begins with the discovery of perspective in
Italian Renaissance art, which served to eliminate what he calls
``the sacred backdrop of old, the golden or black curtain against
which saints and Savior had enacted their symbol-drenched dramas.''
</P>
<P>
   He continues: ``The uniform backdrop of old was a presence that
didn't fully reveal itself until it was absent. Only then did it
yield its secrets: how it had represented an unwavering, unthinking
assumption; how its uniform surface of gold or black provided a
sensibility unto itself; how that sensibility reflected a singular
point of view, saints of a certain size, Virgin of another, Jesus
of a third, all arrayed according to a hierarchy that could belong
only to the mind of God. But now it was gone, and what replaced it
was a point of view that could belong only to the human eye _ and
only to an eye seeing the world as if for the first time.''
</P>
<P>
   Two centuries later, with Galileo's use of the telescope in
1609, ``man had completed the intellectual journey he had begun''
with ``the introduction of perspective into art,'' Panek continues.
The sacred backdrop had become a curtain to be opened, and ``man
had gone from being the apple of God's eye to being God's eye.''
</P>
<P>
   With similar verve, ``Seeing and Believing'' describes the shock
of all the revolutions created by the telescope. As Panek sums up:
``The flatness of Earth, the immobility of the globe, the perfectly
circular paths of the planets, the earth's position at the center
of the Kosmos, the sun's position at the center of a new cosmos,
the fixed positions of the stars, the stars themselves as the
extent of the universe, the universe as all that we could ever hope
to see, and all we could ever hope to see as all there is _ all the
assumptions safely based on observation were gone.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the tool that swept these assumptions away: ``Now, in the
aftermath of the New Astronomy of invisible light, to say nothing
of the dark matter revolution, it turned out that the instrument in
any incarnation came with its own inherent set of limitations, not
on what to expect or where to look, but on how to look, not on the
available information, but on the nature of the information
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the children have built something out of an orange crate,
something preposterous and ascendant. And Panek has shown how those
who built ascendant things kept falling down, only to discover that
the place they had fallen down to was wonderfully different and
very strange.
</P>
<P>
   As he himself sums up the case he has so persuasively made in
``Seeing and Believing,'' ``The relationship between the telescope
and our understanding of the dimensions of the universe is in many
ways the story of modernity.''
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `SEEING AND BELIEVING'
</P>
<P>
   How the Telescope Opened Our Eyes and Minds to the Heavens
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Panek
</P>
<P>
   198 pages. Viking. $21.95.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
