<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 18:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4802 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NASA-STATION-HNS &LR;      10-07 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NASA-STATION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NASA CHIEF TELLS LAWMAKERS THAT SPACE STATION SHOULD BE SCRAPPED IF
IT CAN'T BE FUNDED PROPERLY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Under fire for his plan to bail out Russia for its
participation in the international space station, NASA
administrator Dan Goldin told lawmakers Wednesday that the
ambitious project should be scrapped if it cannot be properly
funded.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin's comments came during a testy meeting of the House
Science Committee, where lawmakers sharply criticized NASA
officials for their latest effort to deal with the delays in
receiving Russian parts, a problem precipitated by the economic
crisis there.
</P>
<P>
   NASA has proposed paying the Russian space agency $660 million
to complete its work on the station, including $60 million
immediately to ensure it does not fall further behind on its part
of the project. In return the Russians have agreed to give to the
Americans some of their research time on the space station.
</P>
<P>
   But the committee's chairman, Rep. James Sensenbrenner, said he
could not endorse a plan to bail out the Russians, arguing that
Americans should never have become so reliant on their
participation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plain truth is the White House is addicted to the
Russians,'' he said.``The administration needs to take the Russian
government out of the critical path _ now. Congress expected that
four years ago, and the administration promised we wouldn't become
dependent on Russia. It lied.''
</P>
<P>
   NASA also is expected to request an additional $560 million to
construct a propulsion module and other units to reduce long-term
U.S. reliance on the Russians.
</P>
<P>
   While lawmakers blasted Goldin for giving the Russians such a
critical role in building the station, the NASA chief retorted that
budget restraints placed on the agency had made it harder to reduce
the reliance.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin said that as a result of the balanced budget agreement
between the White House and Congress, NASA has been forced to cut
$40 billion from its annual budgets. He warned if those budget
restraints continue, the space station could be doomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we cannot fund this properly because of this budget deal,
then maybe we should cancel the space station,'' Goldin said. ``We
can't create money out of magical places.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., said that Congress had agreed to fund
NASA at the full level requested by the Clinton administration next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has insisted that NASA take any additional money
it needs for the station out of other space agency programs.
</P>
<P>
   Sensenbrenner warned that if the administration does not work
with Congress to come up with a solution to the Russian problem, he
will begin drafting his own legislation next year.
</P>
<P>
   However, Sensenbrenner did not explicitly threaten to block the
$60 million that NASA is requesting to send over this month to
Russia. Those funds, which would be transferred from a space
station reserve fund, must be approved by House and Senate
appropriators.
</P>
<P>
   While one expert questioned Russian capability to build the
station, Goldin said that the problem is solely financial. The
Russian government, strapped for funds, has not been paying its
space agency for months.
</P>
<P>
   He added that it would be wrong to further penalize Russians who
have already been working under difficult conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come from the school that says if someone is in trouble you
don't extract blood from them,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Goldin's assessment was backed by Jay Chabrow, who chaired a
task force that recently estimated that space station costs are
escalating.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a big mistake to throw them aside. They are there.
All they need is cash flow,'' said Chabrow.
</P>
<P>
   But another expert, Judith Twigg, an assistant professor at
Virginia Commonwealth University, argued that even with more money
the Russians may not have the technical capability to continue
their work on the space station. She said that Russia had suffered
a brain drain, particularly among younger people, and had not
invested in its aerospace industry. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
