<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0286 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4812 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLENN-NASA-HNS &LR;      10-07 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLENN-NASA-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLENN, DISCOVERY ASTRONAUTS TRAIN FOR EMERGENCY ESCAPES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAPE CANAVERAL, Fla., _ Mercury astronaut John Glenn may be 77,
but he braved the sweltering heat of the mosquito-infested Florida
swamps like a youngster Wednesday, as part of his campaign to
return to space.
</P>
<P>
   He is among seven astronauts preparing to blast off Oct. 29 from
the Kennedy Space Center aboard the shuttle Discovery. For Glenn,
twice a grandfather, the nine-day mission is a long- awaited encore
to the five-hour Mercury flight in 1962 that distinguished him as
the first American in orbit.
</P>
<P>
   So what do swamps and space have in common?
</P>
<P>
   Early Wednesday, shuttle commander Curt Brown, Glenn and the
rest of the Discovery crew took turns careening over the gravel
trails that wind around their coastal launching pad in a mustard
yellow armored personnel carrier.
</P>
<P>
   Their driving skills could be life saving if something went awry
during the final minutes of Discovery's countdown. Unlike Glenn's
tiny Mercury capsule, the shuttle is not equipped with an escape
rocket that could lift the astronauts quickly away from the
launching pad in the event of a fuel leak, fire or explosion.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, endangered shuttle crews must climb from the cockpit
unassisted, sprint across the launch tower while 200 feet above the
ground, then jump into a metal steel cage for a harrowing, 21
second slide down a 1,200 foot stretch of steel cable to the
ground. Then the astronauts either dive into a concrete reinforced
underground bunker or leap into a waiting Army M113 armored
personnel carrier, crash a security fence and speed toward the
safety of a nearby helicopter pad. The escape should take five
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Although every shuttle crew goes through the training, none has
been required to actually execute it during the 91 missions dating
back to 1981.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did real well,'' declared George Hoggard, the 61-year-old
fire captain at Kennedy who has supervised launch pad escape
training for three decades.
</P>
<P>
   With all his experience, Hoggard has the instruction down cold.
</P>
<P>
   Hoggard straps himself to the outside of the M113 and shouts 30
seconds of instruction to his astronaut driver, who pokes his head
through an opening in the top of the personnel carrier. Suddenly,
the diesel-powered vehicle growls to life and disappears in a cloud
of dust as it rolls over a 1 { mile course, reaching speeds of 45
mph.
</P>
<P>
   The controls include an accelerator pedal and two brake levers,
one for the continuous tracks on the right and the other on the
left. The personnel carrier is steered with the application of
brake pressure on either side.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, he did a great job,'' Hoggard said of Glenn, who
steered the course in a respectable three minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm real proud to see him do this,'' said Hoggard, who feels a
kinship with Glenn because of their age. ``I admire him a heckava
lot for his efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   None of Brown's crew discussed their adventure with the 50
reporters who gathered to observe the exercise. But they seemed to
enjoy the outing in spite of the mosquitoes.
</P>
<P>
   Discovery's flight engineer, Scott Parazynski, proved the
speediest of the M113's drivers, navigating the course in two
minutes, 40 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   The start and finish line for Wednesday's S-shaped course
provided at least small testament to the importance of the
training. The astronauts have dubbed it Lake Ochoa, in honor of
astronaut Ellen Ochoa who accidently steered the M113 through a
stand of scrub trees and into the swamp during an instruction drive
a couple of years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, all the people are really bright,'' Hoggard said of
his student drivers. ``The next time they may have to drive could
be in an emergency situation. They won't have time to think about
things. They need to jump in and drive.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
