<SLUG> BC-PELOSI-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPS. PELOSI, CARDIN CRITICIZE CLINTON INQUIRY AS UNFAIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service Clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of Thursday's House vote on whether to
begin a probe that could lead to President Clinton's impeachment,
two Democratic lawmakers called the process unfair compared with
the ethics inquiry they helped conduct on charges against House
Speaker Newt Gingrich.
</P>
<P>
   Reps. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., and Benjamin L. Cardin, D-Md., who
sat on the eight-member panel that in 1997 fined Gingrich $300,000
for ethics violations, said in a news conference Wednesday that the
investigation of the speaker was much fairer than the one of
Clinton by Independent Counsel Kenneth W. Starr and the House
Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi said the difference was that the House ethics panel
``worked on a presumption of innocence and tried to look at both
sides'' and the current probe of Clinton is not doing that.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics subcommittee investigating Gingrich also was charged
with examining ``a very slim charge against the speaker'' _ whether
he violated tax laws on nonprofit organizations that funded a
college course he taught and a TV workshop he held _ compared with
``the fishing expedition that has been out there against Clinton,''
Pelosi said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the panel investigating Gingrich also shared its
evidence with the speaker and his lawyers before releasing it to
the public in order to give him a chance to respond, whereas the
president was simply told when a load of boxes with evidence had
arrived on Capitol Hill.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi also said that during the panel's investigation of
Gingrich the evidence against him was sealed and there were no
leaks during the investigation. In the Clinton case, she said, a
huge volume of information on Clinton has been widely leaked and
released in ``a helter-skelter form.''
</P>
<P>
   Cardin said the Gingrich investigation was bipartisan while in
the Clinton investigation ``there has been no effort, none at all
to bring out a bipartisan process.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Gingrich inquiry was seen as impartial and
bipartisan, the fine and reprimand against him were widely accepted
as fair, Cardin said, adding tht he is ``fearful the Judiciary
Committee has missed an opportunity to do it right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been no effort by Republicans to engage the
Democrats in a proper process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Pelosi and Cardin said they intend to vote Thursday against the
Republican proposal to conduct an open-ended investigation of
Clinton. Two dozen or more Democrats are expected to vote for the
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think these charges rise to the level of an
impeachable offense,'' Pelosi said. ``This isn't about protecting
the president. This is about protecting the Constitution.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
