<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4834 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS &LR;      10-07 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON BOWS TO DEMOCRATS VOTING FOR IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton abruptly abandoned efforts
Wednesday to recruit House Democrats for the showdown over a House
impeachment inquiry, publicly freeing his allies to support an
open-ended investigation a month before the midterm congressional
elections.
</P>
<P>
   White House aides said the president hoped his recommendation
for the 206 Democrats in the 435-seat House to ``cast a vote of
principle and conscience'' would bolster Democrats' chances with
voters on Nov. 3, helping them return to Capitol Hill in strength
for the next phase of the impeachment struggle.
</P>
<P>
   The president _ along with First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton,
White House Press Secretary Joe Lockhart and Rep. Vic Fazio,
D-Calif., the third ranking Democrat in the House _ underscored the
administration's decision to release House Democrats to vote for
the wider impeachment inquiry favored by the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican-led House is scheduled to vote Thursday on a
recommendation by the House Judiciary Committee to open a
wide-ranging impeachment inquiry into Clinton's conduct during his
presidency. The Judiciary Committee voted 21-16 along party lines
Monday to launch a broad investigation into the president's actions
in the Monica Lewinsky affair and other activities during his
presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said the coordinated White House message is that the
president and his aides will continue to work with any House
Democrats ``who for whatever reason decide to vote to move forward
under the proposal put forward by the Republicans.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Democratic insiders estimate that between 40 and 60 House
Democrats may support the GOP-backed proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton had been quietly trying to coax Democrats to vote as a
bloc against the open-ended impeachment inquiry, enabling the White
House to portray the investigation as a partisan venture.
</P>
<P>
   But the White House abandoned the approach on Wednesday in the
face of complaints from some House Democrats that they need to vote
for the inquiry in order to survive the November election.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think everybody should cast a vote of principle and
conscience,'' Clinton told a photo session in the Oval Office with
Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orban.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Clinton told 25 first-term House Democrats at a separate
gathering inside the White House that ``we know that you have to be
able to defend your position.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart, relaying Mrs. Clinton's remarks, said the first lady
``made the explicit point that this White House stands ready to
work with Democrats and support Democrats, help them get elected,
work into the future, no matter how they vote,'' Lockhart added.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is not trying to speak to House
Democrats ``in code,'' Lockhart said, adding: ``I think members
understand what we're saying. And if others don't, I don't think I
can explain it any further.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton signaled that he has shifted his gaze beyond the House
vote to bolstering his fortunes in the fall election.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens to me, I think, ultimately will be for the
American people to decide,'' Clinton said during the Oval Office
photo session. `` I owe them my best efforts to work for them, and
that's what I am going to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Fazio, the chief vote counter for House Democrats, consulted
with Clinton at the White House. Fazio tried to dim the spotlight
on the House's expected approval of an impeachment inquiry _ only
the third time in American history that the House will have
launched an impeachment investigation of a sitting president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think tomorrow's vote is a question that members are having
to respond to in the context of an election,'' Fazio said. ``The
vote that comes next is far more important than simply teeing up
this investigation, which is really what we're talking about
tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic strategists are banking that their candidates, by
focusing on issues that affect the daily lives of Americans, can
stem the traditional losses suffered in the sixth year of the
presidency by the party that holds the White House.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Clinton spotlighted the approach again on Wednesday by signing a
higher education package that cuts the interest rates of college
student loans to the lowest level in 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the way America should work; this is the way Congress
should work,'' Clinton told a bipartisan of lawmakers in the East
Room of the White House. ``We put the progress of the country and
the people of the country ahead of our partisan differences and
reached a principled resolution of the matters in dispute.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans are hoping to broaden the bipartisan complexion of
the 363 to 63 vote on Sept. 11 to release material from special
prosecutor Kenneth Starr's report of potentially impeachable
offenses by Clinton. The House has 228 Republicans, 206 Democrats
and one independent who usually votes with the Democrats.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
