<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0295 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4836 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POL-ADS-COX     10-07 0787
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-ADS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    National campaign ad targets Clinton
 &HT;    By Ken Foskett
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Washington _ A liberal tax-exempt group here has launched the
first national ad campaign of the 1998 elections aimed at tapping
into potential voter backlash over impeachment proceedings against
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   People for the American Way, a left wing counter-point to the
Christian Coalition, began airing the ad in California, Illinois,
New Mexico, Nevada and Florida on Wednesday after a national debut
on CNN's ``Larry King Live'' Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The ad features mug shots of Independent Counsel Ken Starr,
House Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.) and Christian Coalition founder
Pat Robertson and the voice of Carole Shields, president of People
for the American Way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's move on,'' Shields says in the ad. ``That's what the
American people are saying loud and clear. But some in Washington
are listening to the religious right -- not the people...It's time
to get back to what really counts. First-rate schools, Medicare and
social security, not just for our parents for them too. We have a
voice and a vote. November 3 is election day. Let's tell them it's
time to move on.''
</P>
<P>
   The $1 million ad campaign comes as the House of Representatives
is scheduled to vote today on opening a formal impeachment inquiry
into Clinton's affair with one-time White House intern Monica
Lewinsky and his efforts to conceal the relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Shields said in an interview that impeachment was ``sucking the
oxygen out of issues that people care about,'' such as the patients
bill of rights and funding for education.
</P>
<P>
   The main goal of the ad is to increase turnout among voters
opposed to the religious right, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they are the only people voting, they are going to set the
agenda,'' she said. ``The good guys have to show up.''
</P>
<P>
   Genevieve Wood, a spokeswoman for the Republican National
Committee (RNC), said the ads were ``offensive to people of
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly, they are trying to stir up their base,'' Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   The organization's campaign initially ignited some criticism
from some Democrats, who accused the White House of attempting to
orchestrate the effort to help the president at the expense of
House and Senate candidates who needed the support.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats worried that a coordinated get-out-the-vote
campaign centered around Clinton's problems could siphon money away
from congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   Shields said the White House was never involved in her
organization's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   While publicly critical, no Democrats called the group to
complain directly about the ad campaign, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1980 by television producer Norman Lear, People for
the American Way boasts some 300,000 members.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the top financial contributors are from Hollywood and
active in Democratic politics. Actors Alec Baldwin, Kim Basinger
and Kathleen Turner are all top contributors.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Podesta, a member of the board of directors, is the
brother of John Podesta, Clinton's deputy chief of staff.
</P>
<P>
   The group has been one of the most vocal critics of the
Christian Coalition, publishing an on-line newsletter called
``Right Wing Watch Online.''
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks ago, the organization delivered a report to the
Internal Revenue Service charging the Christian Coalition with
violating its IRS tax-exemption.
</P>
<P>
   People for the American Way is itself a tax-exempt, operating a
501(c)(3) foundation that collects tax-deductible contributions and
a 501(c)(4) social welfare organization engaged in lobbying.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the group also started a political action committee
(PAC) that endorsed 45 congressional candidates _ all but three
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Though the group's new ad does not tell listeners to vote for
any candidate in particular, the media markets chosen for them
cover many of the districts of candidates whom the group has
endorsed.
</P>
<P>
   Ads running in Moline, Ill., for example, will reach voters in
incumbent Rep. Lane Evans' western Illinois district, where Evans
is locked in a tough re-election fight.
</P>
<P>
   The ads are running in two California markets, where the group
has endorsed 7 Democrats for House and Sen. Barbara Boxer
(D-Calif.), who is fending off a stiff challenge from California
Treasurer Matt Fong.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Lux, director of the organization's PAC, said the ads were
not running in Washington state or Wisconsin because the group is
providing direct support to Democratic candidates there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are doing our best to play by the rules,'' Lux said. ``We
take a very conservative interpretation of election law.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
