<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-RALLY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROTEST RALLY MORE A CALL FOR PEACE, ORDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It took over six hours, and a lot of beer, before the
thing that Russians feared would happen during a nationwide protest
finally happened.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time police and demonstrators clashed Wednesday
evening in the Russian capital, it looked less like a revolutionary
uprising than an unruly crowd of several hundred young people being
cleared off the street in typically brusque fashion by Moscow's
finest.
</P>
<P>
   Thus ended a day of protest that drew hundreds of thousands
across the country. It was bound to have disappointed Communist and
labor union leaders, who had promised that as many as 40 million
Russians would turn out to demand better living standards and the
resignation of President Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the people whose 20th Century was defined by revolution
chose to stay home in a resonant plea for peace and stability. That
seemed to echo the message of some of the tens of thousands of
Muscovites _ police put the number at around 50,000, while
organizers estimated turnout at 150,000 _ who gathered at the walls
of the Kremlin Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is a normal life. We see how people live in the West,
and we want to live like that,'' said protester Vyacheslav Makarov
as he marched under a sign that made a vulgar pun on Yeltsin's
name.
</P>
<P>
   Others were less prone to conversation with American reporters.
One group of about 30 tough-looking men in camouflage uniforms
sullenly marched by, refusing to identify themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the union of killers!'' one of the men snarled.
``Shouldn't you think about leaving?''
</P>
<P>
   But the mood was surprisingly peaceful in Moscow and throughout
the country, despite a deep economic crisis that has brought a new
bout of inflation and a rapid drop in living standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one wants to die,'' commented a police lieutenant colonel
watching the Moscow protest with a group of officers. ``Everyone is
tired of protesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there were plenty of red flags, portraits of Lenin and
Stalin, and angry, sometimes anti-Semitic slogans _ typical of all
anti-government protests since the 1991 breakup of the Soviet Union
_ Wednesday's rally behind St. Basil's Cathedral featured no
speeches by opposition leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Communist Party leader Gennady Zyuganov, spent the day
as a rank-and-file protestor, except that he was surrounded by
several stern bodyguards, and did not attempt to address the crowd.
Viktor Anpilov, the head of a radical Communist splinter group
whose fiery oratory has been a fixture at protests, Wednesday
arrived late and was not allowed on the platform.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a tape recording droned out slogans like ``Salaries!
Employment! Legality!'' and a series of labor union leaders and
Moscow city officials called for Yeltsin to step down. Some heaped
praise on the city's populist mayor, Yury Luzhkov, who has
indicated he will run for president in the next elections,
scheduled in two years.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov himself stayed away from the protests, but one of his
likely opponents, retired Gen. Alexander Lebed, led a protest march
in Krasnoyarsk, the capital of the massive Siberian territory where
he is governor. Another governor once viewed by Yeltsin as a
possible successor, Dmitry Ayatskov of the Volga region of Saratov,
told a crowd it was ``time to send Yeltsin into retirement.''
</P>
<P>
   A Yeltsin spokesman said the Russian leader, who spent the day
in Kremlin office but did not make any statements, had ``a
disappointed reaction'' to the calls for him to step down. A top
aide, Oleg Sysuyev, said Yeltsin, who he said was able to watch the
rally thanks to special surveillance cameras set up on the square
by the authorities, had no plans to go anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   As the rally outside St. Basil's began to break up after sunset,
about 1,000 protesters, mainly young people, said they were not
going to budge either. A young man in a Nike swoosh hat threatened
a young police officer with a red flag. A group of young men in
leather jackets drank beer and yelled ``Yeltsin is a killer!''
Police told the crowd to get off the square. A cordon pushed, the
crowd pushed back. Someone waved a Confederate flag. The police
pushed some more, prompting more cries of ``Yeltsin is a killer.''
In the ensuing scuffle some 40 people were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Several minutes later it was over, the crowd went home and water
trucks came to wash away the last signs of protest from the square.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
