<HEADER>
A4853 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-PRECEDENT-BOS &LR;      10-07 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-PRECEDENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IDEALS MAY DECIDE THE PRESIDENT'S FATE  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ADAM PERTMAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the end, President Clinton's fate may rest on this question:
Should the occupant of the Oval Office be judged by tougher rules
than the rest of us?
</P>
<P>
   David P. Schippers, the Republican majority's chief counsel on
the House Judiciary Committee, framed the panel's hearings this
week by answering with an unqualified yes. The president, Schippers
asserted, is, ``by virtue of his office, held to a higher standard
than any other American.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a statement that rang true to many Clinton defenders and
detractors alike, according to legal scholars and political
historians, largely because most people tend to _ or at least want
to _ idealize the presidency, and to view the holder of the office
as a role model.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the specialists, however, sharply disagreed with the
substance of Schippers' assertion. They said it seemed to stem more
from a partisan political climate and personal moral outrage than
from a historical or legal precedent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's ridiculous; it's certainly not grounded in
constitutional doctrine,'' said Judy Olans-Brown, a Northeastern
University Law School professor. ``It sounds to me like he was more
motivated by disgust about the obviously self-indulgent, adolescent
behavior of our president.''
</P>
<P>
   Irwin Hargrove, a presidential historian at Vanderbilt
University and a harsh critic of Clinton, said the Republicans in
Congress _ through Schippers' comments Monday _ were ``trying to
make the best argument they can'' in the face of ``evidence that
doesn't necessarily rise to the level'' of the two previous efforts
to impeach a president, against Richard M. Nixon in 1974 and Andrew
Johnson in 1868.
</P>
<P>
   ``Impeachment has to be concrete,'' said Hargrove, who added
that many who would jettison Clinton are driven by disapproval of
his personal behavior. ``There can't be a sliding legal or moral
scale. ... The Constitution wasn't created for a moral witch
hunt.''
</P>
<P>
   While most of those interviewed suggested that Schippers had
overreached, they also agreed that the majority counsel's
rhetorical formula would have little bearing on the ultimate issue,
whether the president did or did not commit impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   In Clinton's various legal controversies, federal judges
straight up to the Supreme Court have ruled, in effect, that the
president does not enjoy special legal status. Most notably, the
courts have held that he is not immune from civil suits while in
office, that he could not invoke executive privilege to keep the
special prosecutor's office from questioning his closest advisers,
and that he could not keep Secret Service agents from testifying
because their job was to protect the president.
</P>
<P>
   Some scholars went further and echoed Schippers' view that the
president should indeed be held to a higher standard.
</P>
<P>
   That is because politicians serve as highly visible models by
which public standards are set, and when they stray, they should be
held to account more strictly, said Todd Gaziano, a senior fellow
in legal studies at the Washington-based Heritage Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Gaziano also said that the president should be judged
differently because he is the only American who takes an oath of
office in which he vows to make sure the nation's laws are
``faithfully executed'' under the Constitution. ``So when he
violates the law ... he also violates his constitutional duty,''
Gaziano said.
</P>
<P>
   The framers of the Constitution specified a different standard
for removing officials of the judiciary. In addition to ``high
crimes and misdemeanors,'' judges can be impeached if they are
deemed to have violated ``good behavior'' while in office, a phrase
that is similarly vague.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars say America's founders deliberately did not specify
which crimes or misdeeds should constitute sufficient cause for
impeachment. They recognized that standards would evolve, and
evidently accepted that political judgments would always play an
important role in the process, for better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   That was the case in both previous impeachment-related
processes, although experts asserted that the Watergate episode _
while including partisan posturing aplenty _ represented the
clearest example of a president's breaking laws while in office.
Andrew Johnson, on the other hand, came within a vote of losing his
job because of overtly political disagreements with the Republicans
who then controlled the House.
</P>
<P>
   The current debate contains aspects of both precedents. And,
despite public cynicism about politics, it reflects the underlying
desire among many Americans that the occupant of the White House be
a role model, as well as a leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people look at the office as very much set by the
greats of the past, so they do have an elevated feeling about the
presidency,'' said James McGregor Burns, a presidential historian
who is working on a book about Clinton. ``But how you convert that
into any legal aspect, whether he should be held to a higher or
different standard, is very much influenced by what's going on at
the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the risk that partisanship can drive an impeachment
effort, even if it means manipulating the standards by which a
president is judged, none of the historians or political scientists
suggested that Congress should draft definitive circumstances under
which impeachment can take place.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats on the Judiciary Committee tried and failed to
establish such guidelines for Clinton, just as Republicans sought
and failed to do so for Nixon a quarter-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   To establish specifics, experts said, could create long-term
institutional problems that would outlive any single dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Gilbert, author of ``The Mortal Presidency,'' said it
would take Congress ``until the end of time if it tried to
enumerate what high standards a president was supposed to live up
to.'' If they did accomplish the task, he added, it would upset the
constitutional balance of powers by giving Congress a winning card
that it could play against the executive branch at its discretion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
