<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 19:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4858 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DOCTORS-CHIRPORACTORS     10-07 1152
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOCTORS-CHIRPORACTORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTS QUESTION VALUE OF CHIROPRACTIC CARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY TYE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chiropractors are no more effective than physical therapists in
treating lower back pain, and both are only marginally successful
at easing their patients' symptoms, according to a controversial
new study published Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   A second report out Thursday on chiropractic care is even more
discouraging, although it affects far fewer patients: spinal
manipulation, researchers concluded, provides ``no benefit'' for
children with mild or moderate asthma.
</P>
<P>
   The two studies are fueling an already fiery debate about the
value of complementary medical treatments like chiropractics, and
about whether it is fair for traditional medical doctors to judge
alternative practitioners. The reports are also drawing charges
from the chiropractic community that the findings were skewed by
the design of the studies, especially the one on lower back pain,
and that they should never have been published in the prestigious
New England Journal of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look overall at why people go to chiropractors,
slightly over half are for back pain. This is at the heart of what
chiropractors do, and these data suggest there probably is some
benefit _ but on average it's relatively small and comparable to
physical therapy,'' said Dr. Richard A. Deyo, a professor of
medicine at the University of Washington and an author of the study
on lower back pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think chiropractors will be disappointed we didn't
demonstrate bigger effects, or saving money in the long run, or
bigger benefits in getting people back to work faster.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerome F. McAndrews, spokesman for the American Chiropractic
Association, not only was disappointed, he also was angry. He said
the journal study failed to recognize that chiropractors generally
combine stretching and other therapies with their spinal
manipulation, rather than doing manipulation alone. The study also
excluded patients that McAndrews said are commonly and effectively
treated by chiropractors, including pregnant women and people who
had back surgery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am surprised really that this rose to the level of
warranting publication in the New England Journal,'' McAndrews
concluded. ``It's highly limited. It's like a lot of research, it
just has failings and the utility of the outcomes is highly
questionable.''
</P>
<P>
   The two reports come at a time when many within conventional and
complementary medicine are looking for common ground and ways to
make their divergent approaches less confusing to patients. But
some traditional doctors think the bridging of gaps has gone too
far by holding alternative medicine to less rigorous scientific
standards than conventional care. And the articles come less than a
month after editors of the New England Journal leveled a broadside
against alternative remedies, charging that they sometimes reflect
``a reversion to irrational approaches to medical practice.''
</P>
<P>
   The study on lower back pain involved 321 adults whose pain
persisted for seven days after visiting a primary care doctor, and
who had never before had physical therapy or chiropractic care.
Forty percent were randomly assigned to a month of physical therapy
with the common McKenzie method that uses stretching and other
exercises to steer pain from the feet, legs or buttocks to the
lower back. Another 40 percent got a month of chiropractic
manipulations of the spine. The remainder simply received a booklet
discussing causes of back pain and ways to treat it.
</P>
<P>
   All patients were followed for two years, at which point
researchers compared short and long-term results of the three
treatment approaches. Those getting chiropractic care reported
remarkably similar results to those getting physical therapy on
everything from symptoms to function to recurrence of pain. In both
cases patients had ``only marginally better outcomes than those
receiving the minimal intervention of an educational booklet,'' the
authors reported. And in both cases the financial cost of care was
almost three times higher than with the booklet group.
</P>
<P>
   There was one measure on which chiropractic and physical therapy
patients scored much higher than the booklet group: patient
satisfaction. About 75 percent of those who got the extra
treatments rated their care ``very good'' or ``excellent,''
compared to just 30 percent of those who got just a booklet.
</P>
<P>
   In the asthma study, 91 children who were getting medical
treatment but had continuing symptoms were randomly assigned to two
groups, one of which got actual spinal manipulation while the other
visited a chiropractor but just went through the motions of
treatment without having their spine adjusted. The results: both
groups showed a substantial reduction in symptoms and the need for
medication, as well as an improvement in quality of life.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that both groups improved is encouraging, but it also
makes clear that spinal manipulation could not have been the
reason, said Dr. Jeffrey Balon, the lead author of the study who is
trained both as a medical doctor and chiropractor and who did his
research at the Canadian Memorial Chiropractic College in Toronto.
The two groups may have done better, he added, simply because they
were reassured by taking part in the study and getting extra
professional attention.
</P>
<P>
   Because the use of chiropractics to treat asthma is far more
common in other countries than in America, it is the back pain
study that is drawing the loudest reaction here, especially among
America's 55,000 chiropractors.
</P>
<P>
   McAndrews, whose group is the largest representing US
chiropractors, said even though his members focus on the
musculoskeletal system they are trained to medically evaluate the
whole patient. And he said his fellow chiropractors welcome more
rigorous studies of their work, although he worried that the study
on back pain was flawed in design while the one on asthma
contradicts decades of clinical observations that spinal
manipulation does help asthmatic children.
</P>
<P>
   McAndrews also worried about what he said was a ``chilling''
backlash against chiropractors and other complementary
practitioners by managed care plans and conventional medical
doctors.
</P>
<P>
   An editorial in the New England Journal, by Dr. Paul G. Shekelle
of the West Los Angeles Veterans Affairs Medical Center, sought to
carve out a middle ground between chiropractors and their critics.
``It is currently inappropriate to consider chiropractic as a
broad-based alternative to traditional medical care,'' he wrote.
``However, for some musculoskeletal conditions, chiropractic care
does provide some benefit to some patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``The challenge for chiropractors is to demonstrate that they
can achieve this benefit at a cost that patients or health insurers
are willing to bear.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
