<HEADER>
A4869 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATL-BAXTER08-COX     10-07 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-BAXTER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY _ Uneasy shifts in presidential selection process
 &HT;    Tom Baxter
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   We turn for a moment from the great drama in Washington (they
won't miss us) to ponder a development which could easily have a
more defining political impact. The ground has literally moved
under the presidential selection process.
</P>
<P>
   There's been a good deal of speculation since Gov. Pete Wilson
signed legislation last week that moves California's presidential
primary from early June to March 7: which candidates will be helped
or hurt, what's the impact on Iowa and New Hampshire, and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   But for Georgia, which also votes on March 7, the impact is
relatively clear. The state's early March primary date, which
allowed it to wield a fair amount of influence in the 1992
primaries, has become the political equivalent of Abernathy Road at
rush hour.
</P>
<P>
   New York, Maryland, Colorado and five New England states already
have their primaries set for March 7. Washington and Oregon appear
likely to approve a West Coast sweep, moving their dates in line
with California. The governors of New Jersey and Pennsylvania, both
of whom are Y2K GOP possibilities, have indicated they're looking
at the date, also.
</P>
<P>
   It makes little sense to bemoan the loss of the fleeting clout
Georgia enjoyed when it was the largest state voting this early.
California's decision to move up in the line, debated in that
state's Legislature for several years before it was enacted,
changes the equilibrium so dramatically that the old rules for
gaining advantage in each party's selection no longer mean much,
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Like the forced evolution of the college bowl system into a
national football playoff, the drift toward a national primary is a
work in progress. California has simply moved the timetable
forward.
</P>
<P>
   The March 7, 2000, primaries won't be the final stage, but they
will change the strategic priorities of the campaigns in such a way
that a national primary would be a logical next step.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Lewis Massey said he plans to attend a
special meeting of the National Association of Secretaries of State
to hear from other Southern and Eastern states about how they view
the impact of the California move. If there is to be any turning
back from the drift toward One Big Primary, it will probably have
to begin in discussions like these over the next several months.
</P>
<P>
   An interesting wrinkle is California's new open primary law,
which allows voters to choose candidates of either party - in their
primaries earlier this year, for instance, a voter could have
selected Democrat Gray Davis in the governor's race and Republican
Matt Fong for U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Because this runs afoul of Republican and Democratic Party
rules, California voters are being asked to approve a proposition
that would exempt the presidential primary from the open rules.
</P>
<P>
   But the whiff of a new idea could have some impact in an
atmosphere in which the old rules for choosing each party's
candidates no longer apply. The two parties are losing their
influence over this process faster than any state. If the idea of a
national, non-partisan primary to select both party's nominees
seems a little la-la right now, give California a little time to
work its influence.
</P>
<P>
   tbaxter(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Tom Baxter is a political columnist with the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
