u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROFS-SUE-MICROSOFT-B     10-07 0969
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROFS-SUE-MICROSOFT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROFESSORS SUE TO PROTECT WORK FROM MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a First Amendment case that could have profound effects on
the academic and business worlds, two Boston-area professors will
go to federal court Thursday to try to prevent Microsoft Corp. from
gaining access to their private research.
</P>
<P>
   David Yoffie from Harvard Business School, and Michael Cusumano
from the Massachusetts Institute of Technology _ are co-authors of
an upcoming book about the travails of Netscape Communications
Corp., Microsoft's chief rival in the market for Web browsing
software. The book, called ``Competing on Internet Time: Lessons
from Netscape and its Battle with Microsoft,'' is due to be
published Oct. 20.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft wants to get its hands on the professors' background
material, including some 200 hours of taped interviews with current
and former Netscape executives, to bolster its defense in a broad
antitrust suit brought by the US Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   The government has accused Microsoft of using its near-monopoly
in computer operating systems to gain an unfair advantange in the
market for Web browsers, where Netscape once was dominant. The
trial begins Oct. 15 in US District Court in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft was heartened by passages in an early
Yoffie-Cusumano manuscript in which Netscape officials admit they
made mistakes in their war with the Redmond, Wash.,-based software
giant. Now Microsoft wants to see more.
</P>
<P>
   The company's attorneys have subpoenaed all of the authors'
research for the book, including 2,000 pages of interview
transcripts and notes.
</P>
<P>
   But Yoffie and Cusumano have refused to cooperate, calling
Microsoft's subpoena ``a fishing expedition.'' They have filed a
motion to quash Microsoft's subpoena, and it will be up to US
District Court Judge Richard Stearns to decide whether they should
be compelled to turn over the material.
</P>
<P>
   Employing the same defense that allows journalists to protect
their sources, the authors contend Microsoft's demand violates
their right to free speech and would compromise their ability to
conduct scholarly research in the future.
</P>
<P>
   As part of their research for books as well as for academic case
studies, professors routinely are given in-depth access to
corporate executives and files _ as long as they agree to allow the
company being profiled to review the manuscript before it is
published. Such non-disclosure agreements are intended to ensure
that proprietary information is not shared with the public.
</P>
<P>
   This type of research, which is the bread-and-butter activity of
many business school professors, depends on building trust with the
companies they are profiling, Yoffie said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real fear I have, and Harvard Business School in general
has, is that if companies are fearful that this information will be
exposed in court, they will simply not want to engage in case
research or book research in the future, which would have a very
chilling effect on management education.'' Case studies, he noted,
are the heart of Harvard Business School's curriculum.
</P>
<P>
   But Microsoft says statements in the book attributed to Netscape
executives are central to the issues in the antitrust case and
Microsoft should be entitled, as a defendant, to present that
evidence in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is very important evidence of Netscape executives in
their own words saying it was their own business mistakes and
failure to execute that have caused their problems, not
Microsoft,'' said Microsoft spokesman Greg Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   The published book itself is not sufficient evidence, Microsoft
believes, because Netscape executives could claim they were
misquoted. The reason Microsoft wants the tapes and the other
background material is to ensure that the quotes are accurate,
complete and not taken out of context.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important to actually be able to hear Netscape executives
in their own words supporting Microsoft's position,'' Shaw said.
</P>
<P>
   The case before Judge Stearns, therefore, pits Microsoft's right
to obtain evidence through the discovery process against the
authors' First Amendment rights.
</P>
<P>
   It's a difficult balancing act, said Joseph D. Steinfield, an
attorney at Hill &AMP; Barlow in Boston who specializes in First
Amendment issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft apparently wants to obtain information that they
think will be helpful to their case. You can't blame a litigant for
trying to do that. And the law in general encourages everybody to
give whatever evidence they may have that is relevant,'' Steinfield
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem,'' he said, ``is that there's a strong competing
value, which is the First Amendment value.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinfield believes Microsoft will have a difficult burden in
court.
</P>
<P>
   ``To say `We want to know everything you know' ordinarily would
not be permitted, other than in an extreme and urgent situation, or
if the party can satisfy the court that the information is crucial
and not otherwise easily obtainable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the authors were able to go out and get the information,
then one would think Microsoft could go out and get the
information,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has an odd familiarity to MIT's Cusumano, whose 1995
book, ``Microsoft Secrets,'' had a central role in a previous
government antitrust case against Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; That book, while mostly positive, disclosed some Microsoft
business practices that could be viewed by some as anticompetitive,
Cusumano said.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Department of Justice tried to subpoena
his &UR;  &LR; taped interviews with Microsoft officials for the same purpose
that Microsoft now seeks the Netscape tapes.
</P>
<P>
   But Cusumano refused to cooperate, and the government dropped
its demand.
</P>
<P>
   Not so Microsoft.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 1933EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
