<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IMF-BRAZIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNCERTAINTY DOGS BRAZILIAN ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD CHACON  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO _ Latin America's largest country marked two
milestones this week: It re-elected a president for the first time
in its history, and its constitution turned 10 years old.
</P>
<P>
   But there is little joy in the streets of Brazil. Instead, there
is deep concern and uncertainty about what will happen next to its
sputtering $800 billion economy.
</P>
<P>
   As more ballots were counted Wednesday from Sunday's national
elections, it was clear that President Fernando Henrique Cardoso
has been given another four years in office. What remains unclear
is when Cardoso will move to repair the economy and how he will
address the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The 67-year-old sociologist has avoided a runoff election
against his left-wing challenger, Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva. But
the victory was not a resounding one. With 91 percent of the votes
counted, Cardoso received about 53 percent. But da Silva did better
than most exit polls predicted by winning about 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, members of da Silva's five-party coalition said
Monday that they won't go along with the president's plan to reduce
Brazil's $60 billion deficit _ about 7 percent of the country's
gross domestic product _ for fear that it would hurt the poor and
lead to higher unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   And worse still for Cardoso was news that many of his own allies
for gubernatorial and congressional seats _ support he'll need to
get controversial fiscal and constitutional reforms passed _ are
stuck in close races that won't be decided until final elections
are held in three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Now, observers say, Cardoso faces a key decision: whether to
please investors by seizing on this week's victory and agreeing
quickly to a loan package with the International Monetary Fund, or
to satisfy his political partners by postponing a plan until after
the final elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``His credibility would suffer seriously if he tried to wait
three weeks before stating his plans,'' said Scott Mainwaring, a
Brazil expert and director of the Kellogg Institute of
International Studies at the University of Notre Dame. ``I think he
has to start talking about the reforms now because he cannot afford
to deceive the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Brazilians, global investors and international
monetary lenders are also waiting to see what Cardoso will do next.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's won his election, so now it's time to get the economy
ticking again,'' said one New York City investment analyst. ``I
don't think the markets are willing to wait much longer for a
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks leading up to the election, Cardoso, a social
democrat, both promised and warned that severe measures would be
taken to fix Brazil's economy, but he hasn't offered specific
proposals yet. Those announcements helped slow the amount of
foreign capital fleeing Brazil's markets, but haven't stopped it.
About $30 billion has left Brazil since early August.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the day after the elections, the Brazilian stock
market, which has lost about 40 percent of its value since the
beginning of the year, fell again. The market fell 179.76 points
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Top Cardoso administration officials, including finance minister
Pedro Malan, have been negotiating with IMF officials over a loan
package of about $30 billion, but nothing formal has been
announced. In return, IMF officials have said they want assurances
that the government deficit will be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Another possibility is that the country's currrency, the real,
could be devaulued soon, a move that might jeopardize a successful
currency- and inflation-stabilizing plan that Cardoso implemented
back in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Cardoso's critics blame him for making Brazil too dependent on
money from investors and too vulnerable to volatile swings in
capital markets. Last week, in a sign the administration may soon
adopt tighter rules, the director of monetary policy for the
central bank told the Financial Times of London that it may limit
the amount of short-term money that comes into the country during
periods of market turbulence.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Cardoso's allies worry that an agreement with the IMF,
an unpopular organization remembered for the strict measures it
imposed here during the battle against hyper-inflation in the
1980s, might prompt a backlash that would jeopardize their
campaigns. But now, even ordinary citizens are ready to hear what
Cardoso's plans are.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know there will be pain, but it would be better to know now
so that we can prepare for it,'' said Mateos Goncalves, a
44-year-old banker in Rio de Janeiro who voted for the incumbent.
``Sometimes it's more painful to sit and wait.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
