<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. AND IRAQ CONTINUE QUEST FOR AGREEMENT ON WEAPONS SEARCHES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By YOUSSEF M. IBRAHIM    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ After 10 days of talks, Iraq and the United
Nations said Wednesday that they had failed to break a two-month
impasse that prevented spot searches for weapons of mass
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   But both sides said they intended to pursue a search for a
peaceful way out that might allow Iraq to have some idea when
economic sanctions might be eased and satisfy the Security Council
that Baghdad has disbanded its nuclear, biological and chemical
weapons systems as well as missiles to deliver them.
</P>
<P>
   Senior diplomats here emphasized that Iraq and the United
States, as well as other key members of the Security Council, were
eager to avoid another confrontation like the one that nearly led
the United States to bomb Iraq in February.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody wants a fight,'' said a senior Arab diplomat who is
familiar with the views of Iraq and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Iraqis want a way to climb down from their ban on
inspections in return for a little gain, as they have done in every
confrontation over the past few months,'' the diplomat said. ``And
the Americans are in no position to wage an attack on Iraq right
now, given the domestic situation in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz of Iraq said, ``We are going to
weigh the situation in its entirety in Baghdad.'' He led an
unusually large delegation to New York that included the foreign
minister, several senior diplomats and top scientists in the
attempt to lobby for a new approach to the weapons inspection
system and ease economic sanctions imposed after Iraq invaded
Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued by Secretary-General Kofi Annan's office
simply said ``both sides agreed that the process of dialogue would
continue.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides now seem to put their hopes on a so-called
``comprehensive review,'' a compromise proposed by Annan. It would
examine Iraq's compliance so far with all aspects of the
elimination of nuclear, chemical and biological weapons of mass
destruction and propose a timetable for easing the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   A senior U.N. official who insisted on anonymity said the
``beauty of a `comprehensive review' is that everybody can put
everything they want in it. It's workable.''
</P>
<P>
   A benefit of the review, from Iraq's standpoint, is that if it
can prove that it has complied sufficiently, it can expect a
schedule for lifting some of the economic sanctions. Those
sanctions are crippling the country's economy and impoverishing its
20 million people.
</P>
<P>
   In return, the Security Council would obtain the immediate
return of the U.N. Special Commission inspectors who were banned by
Iraq from spot checks since Aug. 5, when Iraq mounted its latest
challenge to the inspections. But the U.N. official also said
Iraq's adversaries can ``throw into the pot'' other kinds of issues
like Iraq's compliance with demands for compensation for the Iraqi
occupation of Kuwait and the fate of missing Kuwaiti prisoners of
war.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has said that it would agree to a
comprehensive review only six to eight weeks after Baghdad allows
the resumption of weapon inspections. Aziz said it was
``premature'' to talk of resumption of inspections.
</P>
<P>
   In the attempt to gain more time, the United Nations is sending
Annan's special envoy, Prakash Shah of India, a country on friendly
terms with Iraq, to smooth the way toward an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   In his talk with reporters Wednesday after meeting Annan, Aziz
denied a report in The New York Times on Wednesday that French
tests appear to have found traces of chemicals linked to the nerve
gas VX on Iraqi warheads, but are refraining from making the
announcement.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz said the report was politically motivated and ``timed to
sow confusion and suspicion'' as Iraq pursued its quest to lift
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
