<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 19:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4899 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV1     10-07 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV11-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN THE OLD DAYS, POLS SETTLED DIFFERENCES WITH A GOOD BOURBON 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 11)   (For Use By New York Times News Service Clients)  
 By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ ``Hugo,'' said Harry Truman, ``I don't much care
for your law, but, by golly, this bourbon is good.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus did the 33rd president express his appreciation of the
mellow whiskey served by Supreme Court Justice Hugo Black, who had
just written the court's majority opinion decreeing that Truman's
seizure of the nation's strike-bound steel mills was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Truman, in one of the most controversial decisions of his very
controversial presidency, had sought to have the government run the
mills rather than see them shut down because of a nationwide strike
while Americans were fighting and dying in the Korean War. The year
was 1952 and his action precipitated a constitutional crisis.
</P>
<P>
   To his staff, the plain-spoken Missourian said: ``The president
has the power to keep the country from going to hell.''
</P>
<P>
   But Black, writing for the court's majority, declared: ``We
cannot with faithfulness to our constitutional system hold that the
commander-in-chief of the armed forces has the ultimate power as
such to take possession of private property in order to keep labor
disputes from stopping production. This is a job for the nation's
lawmakers, not for its military authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   Truman was especially irate because five of the six justices who
joined in the majority opinion were Democrats appointed by himself
or his predecessor, Franklin D. Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   Black understood this and, in order to establish better
relations between the president and the court, he invited Truman
and the other justices to his elegant Virginia home across the
Potomac River from the White House.
</P>
<P>
   It was then that the president savored Black's bourbon and began
to mellow toward the justices.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, the constitution was upheld, but at an enormous
price. The shutdown, which lasted for seven weeks after the Supreme
Court ruling, was the costliest steel strike in the history of the
republic.
</P>
<P>
   According to Truman biographer David McCullough, ``Losses in
production, losses in wages were unprecedented _ 21 million tons of
steel and $400 million in wages, as 600,000 steel workers and 1.4
million others in related industries were idle. The military output
scheduled for 1952 was cut by a third.''
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary Robert Lovett lamented: ``No enemy could have
so crippled our production as has this work stoppage. The weird and
tragic thing is that we have done this to ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   As we move ever more deeply into a new constitutional crisis,
this one precipitated by Bill Clinton's personal conduct and the
demand of the Republican hierarchy on Capitol Hill for his
impeachment, it is worth noting how people of good intentions can
differ sharply over the meaning of the timeless document written
211 years ago in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   In the steel case, the president and the court majority were at
odds over the constitutional powers of the president. Partisan
politics did not play a role in the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   But in the impeachment drama centering around Clinton's
misbehavior, politics is a major player, despite the claims of
leaders in both parties that they are not indulging in
partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   Many, but not all, Democrats would rather censure the president
than impeach him. Most Republicans claim impeachment is the only
remedy for presidential misconduct provided by the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats would limit the subject matter of the House Judiciary
Committee inquiry to the Monica Lewinsky affair and set a time
limit on the probe. The Republicans have decreed that they will not
be limited in either the focus or the time of their investigation.
They will adhere to the plan adopted by the Democratic majority in
the Watergate probe of Richard Nixon 24 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   But because the Constitution is ambiguous in defining ``high
crimes and misdemeanors,'' the issue has been debated throughout
the history of the republic. We possess no definitive explanation
of what activities fall under that umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott startled some of his
Republican colleagues and angered a number of Democrats when he
declared last month that a president could be impeached for ``bad
conduct'' that brings ``disrepute'' to his office.
</P>
<P>
   But Iowa Democratic Sen. Tom Harkin responded by recalling that
during the impeachment inquiry into the activities of Richard Nixon
in 1974, Lott, then a member of the House Judiciary Committee,
signed a minority report stating that ``general misbehavior'' was
not grounds for impeachment of a president.
</P>
<P>
   Almost anyone who ever served in the presidency could be accused
by his critics of indulging in bad conduct. The founding fathers
did not list that or any specific act of misbehavior _ except
treason and bribery _ as grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   It is ironic that part the genius of the Constitution is that it
is vague and ambiguous on several key matters that were left to
interpretation by future generations. For example, the Constitution
does not specify that the Supreme Court has the right of judicial
review by which it can declare laws enacted by Congress and signed
by the president unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   But John Marshall, the greatest of the chief justices, assumed
that authority in 1803 in a historic case, Marbury vs. Madison.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall said the Constitution was ``intended to endure for ages
to come and, consequently, to be adapted to the various crises of
human affairs.'' That it has done.
</P>
<P>
   The House has two good men at the helm of the impeachment
investigation _ Judiciary Committee Chairman Henry Hyde of Michigan
and ranking minority member John Conyers Jr., also of Michigan.
Both have vowed to protect the Constitution, but being politicians
they will sometimes be guided by partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   It might help if occasionally they would settle their
differences over some good bourbon just as Truman and Black once
did.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
