<HEADER>
A4903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-IMF-280&AMP;ADD-     10-07 0746
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-IMF-280&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS, ADMINISTRATION SEEK DEAL ON IMF FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Alarmed that their foot-dragging could drive
international financial markets into still deeper turmoil, the
Clinton administration and congressional Republicans said they were
working frantically Wednesday to agree on legislation to provide
$18 billion in new funding to the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   While both sides insisted that a deal was still not a sure
thing, White House officials and congressional leaders agreed on
the urgency of additional funds for the IMF as it attempts to avert
a global financial meltdown.
</P>
<P>
   The most important remaining question, they said, is what sort
of restrictions _ if any _ should be put on future lending by the
IMF, which has been harshly criticized by both Republicans and
Democrats for mismanaging the global economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of IMF funds is central to negotiations intended to
avert a shutdown of the federal government this weekend, when
funding for most of the government is scheduled to run out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still have some distance to go, but I think we're making
some progress,'' said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart when asked
about the negotiations over the IMF funds. ``I think there remain
some stumbling blocks.''
</P>
<P>
   After meeting Wednesday with White House budget officials, Rep.
Bob Livingston, R-La., the chairman of the House Appropriations
Committee, said that ``the tough drafting is over'' on compromise
legislation to provide the additional money to the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   But the top congressional Democrat in the negotiations, Rep.
David Obey of Wisconsin, warned that the negotiations with the
White House could still break down and that ``we're a long way from
signing anything.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Earlier this week, President Clinton criticized Congress for
delaying approval of the new funds to the IMF, saying that failure
to provide the money is like ``refusing to supply the fire
department with water while the fire is burning,'' given the
precarious state of the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate has already approved the full $18 billion line of
credit for the IMF that was requested by the Clinton administration
to replenish reserve accounts that were emptied as the IMF
attempted to bail out the economies of Russia and Southeast Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The House, though, has approved only $3.4 billion of the
requested funding. House Republican leaders, facing pressure from
conservative members of their party who wonder whether the
international economic crisis is proof that the IMF does more harm
than good, say they will approve the rest of the money only if
strict new conditions are imposed on future loans by the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans have demanded less secrecy in IMF lending
decisions, an end to below-market loans to foreign governments and
shorter-repayment terms, with perhaps a one-year maximum.
</P>
<P>
   ``The IMF has the Midas touch in reverse _ virtually every
country it tried to help has become worse off from the
experience,'' said House Majority Leader Dick Armey, who led
efforts earlier this year to block the full $18 billion in funding.
``Full funding of an unreformed IMF would be recklessly
irresponsible.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House has resisted the so-called reform measures,
saying it is improper for the United States to attempt to dictate
policy to a multinational agency like the IMF.
</P>
<P>
   White House and congressional officials said that under a likely
compromise, the IMF would face some restrictions on its lending,
with the Treasury required to certify progress by the IMF in
implementing a variety of loan reforms. But they said the
conditions would not be nearly as onerous as those initially
demanded by House Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Congressional officials say the House leadership has shown a new
willingness to resolve the IMF issue _ and to end a variety of
other funding disputes with the White House _ in hopes of
preventing a government shutdown this weekend that might distract
from the impeachment investigation of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Other nations that lend money to the IMF have warned that if the
United States failed to provide the full $18 billion, they might
well reduce their own contributions, which could leave the IMF
short of the $90 billion that it says it needs to deal with
economic crises sweeping across the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
