<HEADER>
A4912 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-COX     10-07 1036
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTING-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gun boy brought to school fires in front of kindergarteners
 &HT;    By Delbert Ellerton
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JONESBORO, Ga. _ The James H. Brown Elementary fifth-grader
eagerly awaited the times he could help the kindergarteners in his
school. It was his reward _ a privilege he earned by keeping quiet
in class and following the rules.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, as the 11-year-old student stood before his
smaller classmates to read a storybook, he broke one of the most
serious rules a school imposes. Tucked into the back of his pants'
waist was a loaded .357 magnum handgun. As he backed against the
ladder to a loft used by the youngsters as a quiet place to read,
the gun fired downward. The bullet tore through the fifth-grader's
Boy Scout shirt-tail and grazed his buttocks and calf before
peeling away a hole of blue carpet and shattering on the cement
floor underneath.
</P>
<P>
   No one was seriously injured. The boy, whose identity has not
been released because he is a minor, was treated for injuries at
Southern Regional Medical Center and later taken to the Clayton
County Juvenile Detention Center. He has been charged with carrying
a concealed weapon and firearm on school property as well as
possession of a firearm by a minor, possession of a weapon on a
school bus and reckless conduct, said Clayton County police Capt.
Doug Jewett.
</P>
<P>
   The student, who is in his second year at Brown, also received
an immediate 10-day suspension and will likely face a minimum
one-year expulsion, pending the findings of a disciplinary
tribunal, said Walter Pierce, Clayton schools director of student
services. The Georgia Department of Education has a zero-tolerance
policy requiring a one-year explusion for any student found with a
gun.
</P>
<P>
   Just how the fifth-grader got hold of the gun is still a
mystery, one police are continuing to investigate. The boy told
police he found it in the woods near a playhouse behind his home.
The boy's foster parents said they do not own a gun, said Brown
principal Nancy McCorkle.
</P>
<P>
   The boy's older brother, a sixth-grader at Mundy's Mill Middle
School, said the boy had bragged the night before that he had a
gun, said Mundy's Mill Principal Nancy Wells. The brother said he
didn't take the boy seriously because the boy often talks about
guns, Wells said.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a gun. In fact, there were two, though only one
was brought to school. Jewett said the boy told police he also
found a Mossburg 12-gauge shotgun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Officers found the shotgun _ which was loaded with two shells
_ where he said he put it, `` Jewett said. Both guns were taken as
evidence.
</P>
<P>
   The incident at Brown Elementary School, a school of 900
students in Clayton County, preceded a news conference scheduled
for today by the Georgia PTA to focus attention on the National Day
of Concern about Young People and Gun Violence. The event is a
National PTA initiative to reduce school violence. Included is a
pledge by students to not bring weapons to school, said Leisa
Martin, director of the Georgia PTA's District 16, which includes
Clayton County. In some counties, participation is systemwide. In
Clayton County, participation is left up to individual schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a problem with kids bringing guns in,'' said Martin.
``We're not trying to put our heads in the sand. We know there is a
problem. Parents need to know that there's the potential for a
weapon to be brought to school.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said she fears the incident and others like it could lead
to metal detectors in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to spark parent concerns,'' Martin said. ``This
is an elementary school.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this is the first time Brown Elementary has discovered
a weapon on its premises, it is not the first time in Georgia that
elementary students have brought weapons to school. Incidents
reported in the metro area and other parts of the state have
involved students as young as those in first and second grades.
</P>
<P>
   School officials say they believe the Brown Elementary student
brought the gun to school to show off but not to harm anyone.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bright child. He's a smart child,'' said Wendy Zelatel,
the boy's fifth-grade teacher and the one who had signed an
agreement with him, letting him work with kindergartners as a
reward for good behavior. ``It's very surprising to me that he did
this.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes to come down to help the kindergarten boys and
girls,'' said Pam Carey, the kindergarten teacher the boy was
assisting.
</P>
<P>
   When the gun fired, Carey did not know what it was, and she
first suspected that an electrical transformer had just blown.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden I heard this really loud noise,'' Carey said.
``He said, 'What was that noise? I'm going to have a heart
attack.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey thought the lights might be going out any minute, but then
noticed the spot on the floor. That's when she checked his back and
found the gun.
</P>
<P>
   ``He moved his foot and there was this spot,'' said Carey.
</P>
<P>
   School officials reacted quickly to the situation, dispatching a
team of administrators and four additional counselors to the
school. Students were told that something had happened that caused
a loud bang, however, they were not told that a gun had fired in
the school. The kindergartners had thought it was firecrackers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to excite them,'' McCorkle said.
</P>
<P>
   Parents were notified and some came by to get their children.
McCorkle sent letters home to each of the parents informing them of
what had happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just think, 'God, it could have been worse,''' said Lynda
Daniel, who oversees Brown and a number of other schools for the
Clayton school system.
</P>
<P>
   At least one parent was on a routine visit to the school to see
his son when he saw news media and wondered what was going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just found out about it,'' said parent Larry Smith. ``Ah
man, I'm sorry, that's a trip . . . not at Brown, it's a good
school. That's amazing. It's a real shock. You never expect that to
happen here at Brown. Brown's so mild and meek and easy-going.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Staff writer Bill Montgomery contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
