<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-IMPEACH (Washington) _ President Clinton, bracing for
the expected approval of a wide-ranging impeachment probe, shifts
his strategy. Instead of continuing to lobby House Democrats, he
now urges voters to ``make a clear statement'' about his fate in
the Nov. 3 election. He also shows he's carrying on with his
presidential duties. By STEWART M. POWELL. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Democrats who are likely to
vote Thursday in favor of a GOP impeachment-inquiry resolution are
mostly the so-called Blue Dogs, Democrats from rural and swing
districts in the South, border states and the West. Some face tough
re-election challenges. By DAN FREEDMAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   PELOSI-IMPEACH (Washington) _ Reps. Nancy Pelosi, D-Calif., and
Benjamin L. Cardin, D-Md., former members of the House ethics panel
that investigated House Speaker Newt Gingrich, criticize what they
see as a double standard in the coming Clinton impeachment
investigation. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-SHUTDOWN (Washington) _ Congressional leaders keen on
going home to campaign maneuver to find a way to conclude business
by Friday. But the outlook is grim as negotiations with the Clinton
administration continue on resolving overdue budget bills and
thorny issues such as funding for the International Monetary Fund.
By GREG McDONALD.
</P>
<P>
   COURT-PROPERTY-RIGHTS (Washington) _ The Supreme Court takes up
the question of how far a city _ in this case, Monterey, Calif. _
can go in infringing on property rights to protect an endangered
butterfly and the area it needs to live in. By MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NASA-STATION (Washington) _ Under fire for his plan to bail out
the Russian share of the international space station, NASA
Administrator Daniel Goldin says that if Congress won't come up
with an extra $1.2 billion for station, then it should be canceled.
Russia's financial crisis has hobbled ability to contribute to the
huge project. By BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   KACZYNSKI-REWARD (Washington) _ David Kaczynski wrestled with
his conscience, but in the end told authorities he believed his
brother, Theodore, was the Unabomber. Now he is wrestling the IRS.
A move in Congress to exempt David Kaczynski from paying taxes on
his $1 million reward from the FBI _ money he wants to give to his
brother's victims _ may be delayed until next year. By ERIC
ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GLENN-NASA (Cape Canaveral, Fla.) _ Sen. John Glenn, soon to be
the oldest man to fly in space, and his fellow astronauts conduct
rehearsals of escape procedures at the Kennedy Space Center. By
MARK CARREAU. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-U.S.-SPENDING (Paris) _ For years economists wagged an
admonishing finger at Americans for saving too little money and
argued that they should follow the example of the Japanese, who
save far more than they spend. Now it turns out that Americans may
wind up better off. By BERNARD D. KAPLAN. (Already filed.)
</P>
