u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLLEGE-TUITION-ART-N     10-07 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-TUITION-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLLEGE TUITION UP 4 PERCENT, OUTPACING INFLATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
(JT) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The cost of a college education rose by about 4 percent this
year, two and a half times the current rate of inflation, 1.6
percent, maintaining a pattern of the last few years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cost of attending college presents a steadily rising
challenge to many Americans, particularly the most financially
disadvantaged,'' said Donald Stewart, president of the College
Board, a national nonprofit association, which released its annual
survey of college fees.
</P>
<P>
   But Stewart said disproportionate attention to the small number
of elite colleges in the $30,000-a-year range obscured the fact
that most students at four-year colleges and universities paid less
than $4,000 a year for tuition and fees.
</P>
<P>
   The new data show that this year at four-year private
institutions, students are paying an average of $14,508, up 5
percent, while those at four-year public institutions are paying an
average of $3,243, a 4 percent increase. At two-year private
institutions, prices rose 4 percent, to $7,333 and 4 percent at
two-year public institutions, to $1,633 on average.
</P>
<P>
   College administrators made much of the fact that after
double-digit increases for tuition in the 1980s and early 1990s,
this was the fourth year in a row with an increase of 4 percent to
5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But Gary Burtless, an economist at the Brookings Institution,
said he was amazed that the price of college continued to outstrip
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm surprised by this, especially among the more modest
institutions, given the evidence that people in their 20s find it
so much easier to find jobs,'' Burtless said. ``You'd have thought
that with some people deciding not to go to college that would
increase pressure on colleges to reduce costs.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Gladieux, executive director for policy analysis at the
College Board, said he was ``pretty sure a couple years ago that
consumer pressure would pull the cost of private colleges down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But it hasn't,'' Gladieux said. ``The market for higher
education is so robust. People know that the best life chances and
jobs come through college education.''
</P>
<P>
   He and others pointed out that children of the baby boom
generation were coming of college age and that college applications
were up.
</P>
<P>
   George Rupp, president of Columbia University, said one of the
biggest costs for him and other administrators was updating
dormitories and dining halls to keep up with the demands of
students and their parents for standards that increasingly seek to
match those of hotels and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   The College Board data show costs for room and board to have
increased 3 percent to 5 percent this year. Slightly more than
one-quarter of full-time four-year undergraduate students live on
campus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was nice to go for 100 years at a stretch without having to
change the infrastructure,'' L. Jay Oliva, president of New York
University, said of the conditions offered for generations by many
universities.
</P>
<P>
   David Warren, president of the National Association of
Independent Colleges and Universities, said colleges and
universities were looking at ways to reduce fees further but were
worried about affecting quality by increasing student-faculty
ratios and reducing laboratory use.
</P>
<P>
   Among the steps these institutions are using or considering,
Warren said, is hiring contractors for dining services, grounds
maintenance and bookstores. While this approach can be
cost-effective, the resulting job loss disrupts the sense of
community that many colleges consider vital.
</P>
<P>
   Peter McPherson, president of Michigan State University in East
Lansing, Mich., said fees there were up 2.3 percent, the fifth year
that his institution has kept its increases at or near the rate of
inflation.
</P>
<P>
   This achievement has been possible partly through state aid that
has surpassed the inflation rate but also, McPherson said, because
of changes like selling the bookstore to an outside company _ the
store used to lose $500,000 a year but now earns that amount _ and
improving its campus hotel and convention center to attract more
business.
</P>
<P>
   The College Board survey shows significant regional differences
in private college costs, with the highest average, $19,211, in New
England and the lowest, at $10,701, in the Southwest. These
differences were largely matters of the cost of heating and the age
of the institutions.
</P>
<P>
   Financial aid to students is now at a record $60 billion, a 6
percent increase over the previous year after adjusting for
inflation, but most of the increase is in the form of loans rather
than grants and most of the increased borrowing is unsubsidized.
Loans now represent 60 percent of aid, compared with just over 40
percent in 1980-81.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton Wednesday signed into law a rate cut for
student loans, bringing it to 7.46 percent, down from more than 8
percent last year and its lowest level in 17 years. Under the new
law, a typical student borrower at a four-year college, graduating
with $13,000 in debt, would save about $700 over a 10-year
repayment period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
