<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN PREMIER BATTLES COMMUNIST-BACKED THREAT TO POWER 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Arguing that Italy cannot afford a return to political
instability, Prime Minister Romano Prodi pleaded with Parliament
Wednesday to keep his splintering center-left majority intact.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italy cannot enter the monetary union weakened or uncertain,''
Prodi said, referring to the single European monetary unit, the
euro, which is to be introduced on Jan. 1. ``We do not want Italy
to be the weak link.''
</P>
<P>
   The threat to Prodi's government, a center-left coalition that
relies on the support of Communists for its majority in Parliament,
became real last weekend when Fausto Bertinotti, the secretary
general of the Communist Refounding Party, withdrew his support for
the 1999 budget _ and for the government.
</P>
<P>
   But that rejection was undercut by dissension within the
Communist leadership. Armando Cossutta, the more moderate president
of the party, resigned, saying he did not want to be responsible
for opening the door for a center-right government to replace the
current one.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Cossutta urged his followers to stick with Prodi,
saying: ``I believe the party should heed Prodi's appeal to support
the government. Abandoning the government is not a courageous act.
It would mean surrendering our responsibility to defend the
interests of the weakest sections of society.''
</P>
<P>
   Bertinotti, however, made clear he has no intention of wavering,
describing Prodi's request that he reconsider ``insulting.'' And he
threatened to expel any members who followed Cossutta's example.
</P>
<P>
   There are 21 Communist deputies who share Cossutta's view and
who together could bring Prodi within just a few votes of a
majority.
</P>
<P>
   After two and a half years, Prodi's government is the second
longest lasting in the postwar period. By making entrance into the
European currency system his primary goal, Prodi managed to raise
taxes and cut the deficit and state borrowing, and still keep his
fragile coalition intact. But once Italy made the grade last
spring, dissension and power struggles sprang back to life.
</P>
<P>
   The embattled prime minister, who is to return to Parliament on
Thursday, is planning to demand a vote of confidence on Friday.
Should he fail to rally enough votes from dissident Communists, he
would have to resign.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, President Oscar Luigi Scalfaro could either ask
him to try to form a new majority, or could ask another political
leader _ or even a nonpolitician _ to try to patch together a new
coalition. If all that fails, Italy could be plunged into early
elections before November.
</P>
<P>
   Prodi Wednesday used the last-ditch argument with which he hopes
to rally support.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cannot accept this, or believe that you really want this
government to fail,'' Prodi said, speaking directly to Bertinotti.
``I cannot believe you want to hand over the country to the forces
that were defeated in 1996,'' a reference to Silvio Berlusconi, the
conservative former prime minister, and his allies.
</P>
<P>
   Bertinotti, who said he rejected the 1999 budget because it did
not include a 35-hour workweek or sufficient measures to combat
unemployment in the south, apparently was not swayed.
</P>
<P>
   It is not the first time that the Communist Refounding Party, a
group of hard-line leftists who broke with mainstream Communists
after the collapse of the Soviet Union, have pushed Prodi to the
brink. The party forced Prodi to offer his resignation last year
over the budget, but had to backpedal after their own rank-and-file
protested.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
