<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 20:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4927 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RIDGE-THEATER-ART-2TA     10-07 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIDGE-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOWNTOWN TROUPE REVELS IN A NEW SCI-FI OPERA 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Laurie Olnder, Bob McGrath, Fred Tietz, Bill
Morrison nd Howard Thies at the Kitchen is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11)  
 (af)  
 Steven Drukman, a theater critic for Art forum magazine, is an
adjunct professor in New York University's drama department.  
 By STEVEN DRUKMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Ridge Theater is an avant-garde company with the
unbuttoned charm of ex-hippies who have made a name in experimental
theater for staging multimedia spectacles with tidy, Swiss-watch
precision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking at us, you'd think we're aging slackers,'' says Bob
McGrath, 43, the group's artistic director. ``But I take great
pains to get things perfect.''
</P>
<P>
   Finding order in ``Chaos,'' a new opera the Ridge is staging at
the Kitchen, through Oct. 24, seems a suitable task for the
company, which for 11 years has favored stories that accent the
sinister side of popular culture. The strange realm of chaos theory
is the subject of this new science fiction opera, ``with a pop
feel,'' said its composer Michael Gordon, the co-artistic director
of the eclectic Bang on a Can Festival every year at Lincoln
Center. The librettist is Matthew Maguire, co-artistic director of
the experimental Creation Production Company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chaos,'' produced by the Ridge, the Creation Production
Company and the Kitchen, tells a tale in 25 scenes over 80 minutes
of two young physicists who do battle with the nasty Dr. Aguabone
(modeled on J. Robert Oppenheimer). When the scientists Marie and
Pierre Curie come to their rescue in the ``realm of chaos,'' the
younger couple are able to conquer their foe by trapping his image
on a video monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Aguabone shouts, ``It's the devil's pinball!'' _ an apt
description of a Ridge theatrical event. Troupe members may look
like do-nothing denizens of a pinball arcade, but their intricate
shows can evoke the feeling of being inside an enormous pinball
machine.
</P>
<P>
   While the company maintains a roster of artistic associates who
perform in many of their productions, the Ridge is primarily a
design team consisting of Fred Tietz (sets), Laurie Olinder
(slides), Bill Morrison (film) and Howard Thies (lights).
</P>
<P>
   ``No one does what we do,'' said McGrath, who directs the
disparate elements. ``We've found this esthetic where all the parts
cohere to form this hallucinogenic world.''
</P>
<P>
   With no fixed operating budget and no permanent theater space,
Ridge members are in effect stagers for hire who subsist on
occasional teaching jobs and dwindling grant money (they have
received support in the past from the National Endowment for the
Arts and the New York State Council on the Arts). Yet despite
limited funds they have employed dazzling effects rarely seen in
low-budget downtown theater.
</P>
<P>
   A frequent strategy is the use of scrims: screens through which
live action can be viewed or, with a change in lighting, on which
films and slides can be projected. McGrath also tends to double or
triple cast look-alike actors, allowing a character who exits at
stage left to magically reappear at stage right.
</P>
<P>
   In the typical Ridge production, there is the sense that an
observer's gaze is being steered from one center of the action to
another, bringing to mind a circus, if it could be rewound and
played at different speeds.
</P>
<P>
   A recent divorce, however, between the Ridge and a longtime
collaborator, John Moran, has raised questions about who has been
responsible for developing the distinctive look of the troupe's
productions.
</P>
<P>
   A protege of Philip Glass, Moran composes what he calls
techno-operas that Glass describes as ``pure visions.'' Moran has
worked with Ridge on five of his operas over the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Glass first met Moran while giving a concert in Lincoln, Neb.
``This kid from the sticks comes up to me with a book of drawings
and a tape,'' the composer recalled. ``I knew right away that Moran
was a gifted composer, a dreamer of the theater. His vision is
specific, but figuring out who directed these McGrath-Moran
collaborations is difficult, if not impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   Paige Snell, who appeared in two early Moran-McGrath projects,
put it bluntly: ``Moran is a solo original artist who needed a
vehicle to manifest his work and Ridge is an effective theatrical
organization. However, Moran is responsible for the esthetic now
associated with Ridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of that esthetic seems to have been established in 1988
when Ridge first collaborated with Moran on ``Jack Benny!,'' an
opera made up entirely of fragments from the comedian's television
show and played at different speeds.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Moran said, ``I was developing a peculiar
style that I still use, a style where the visuals need to match
every sound, down to the footsteps.'' In his operas, performers
frequently lip-synch to pre-recorded, sampled scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ridge,'' Moran said, ``fought me every step of the way.
But they did `Jack Benny!' the way I demanded. They said, `Look, we
went to theater school, we know this lip-synching stuff won't
work.' Every idea that is associated with the Ridge, I brought to
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Moran went on to present four more operas under McGrath's
direction, including ``The Manson Family'' at the Serious Fun
Festival at Lincoln Center in 1990, ``Everyday Newt Berman'' at La
Mama in 1993 and ``The Cabinet of Dr. Caligari'' at the American
Repertory Theater in Cambridge, Mass., last year.
</P>
<P>
   Glass said he agreed with Moran that ``Ridge was doing something
else entirely before John.'' But: ``Ridge is terrifically talented.
They took the opportunity to make a mark with Moran. They knew how
to deliver it. John has a point, though, because McGrath blossomed
with his work. I admire them both. Credit is due on all sides.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridge members said they regretted the split with Moran,
describing it in a matter-of-fact manner. ``John wanted more
overall control of the visual aspects and to direct,'' said Thies,
the lighting designer, who has worked with Moran on non-Ridge
projects.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   McGrath, acknowledging that much of Ridge's esthetic over the
years has been associated with Moran's imprint, added: ``We had a
great long run with John. It wasn't so great at the end between us,
but I don't want to deal in negatives. John has genius in him. But
I directed those shows. Directing is about being in rehearsal every
day, about making plays come to life. John had staging ideas, but
the whole idea of scrims and slides and films is ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Moran remembers the long collaboration differently: ``I was 23
and naive when I met them. I had no idea how arts funding was
obtained. They tried to create road signs for producers that said,
`Hey, you want Moran's operas? This is the way: hire Ridge
Theater.' They wouldn't let me talk to producers. I was kept like a
sideshow attraction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ridge Theater (named for Ridge Street on the Lower East
Side, where McGrath has lived since the theater's inception) began
performing in the mid-1980s as a collective called Pink at downtown
rock clubs between acts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before `Jack Benny!,' we did our share of punk Moliere, but we
did some very serious visual theater,'' said McGrath, who met
Tietz, the set designer, when they were students at Carnegie-Mellon
University.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath noted that he had always been interested in the Russian
director Vsevolod Meyerhold's actor training theory Biomechanics,
and the nonrealistic, gestural movement that defines its style.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, even before Moran appeared on its horizon, Ridge had
shown an interest in the macabre: it had staged a play entitled
``Pound in the Cage,'' which McGrath called ``a dialogue between
Ezra Pound and John Hinckley Jr., the guy who shot Reagan,'' as
well as ``Czolgosz,'' about the assassin of President McKinley, at
P.S. 122.
</P>
<P>
   Given the group's preoccupation with popular culture and
assassins, McGrath said, the 1988 pairing of Ridge and Moran seemed
fortunate. Based on ``Czolgosz,'' their first play with slides and
films, Mark Russell, the executive director of P.S. 122, ``thought
Moran would be a great match for us,'' McGrath said.
</P>
<P>
   Russell remembered that he introduced Moran to McGrath because
``Ridge was a very sharp, up-and-coming company and they had a
fluid style; I thought they would be intrigued by the lip-synching.
In my view, Moran and Ridge put each other on the map.''
</P>
<P>
   Moran said the final straw in a collaboration that had denied
him directing credit was the production of ``The Cabinet of Dr.
Caligari'' in Cambridge with actors from ART. ``Suddenly,'' he
said, ``I really had no involvement. I'd always done the music,
dialogue and about 90 percent of the staging with detailed overhead
maps. `Caligari' ended up two separate pieces _ what McGrath and
Robert Brustein'' _ the artistic director of ART _ ``put together,
and mine.''
</P>
<P>
   Ridge's production of Moran's opera ``Mathew in the School of
Life'' (also at the Kitchen) had captured Brustein's attention in
1994. He invited McGrath and his designers to stage the American
premiere of Susan Sontag's ``Alice in Bed'' in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Brustein described seeing ``Mathew,'' a science-fiction
techno-opera about an android's education: ``I was blown away by
the remarkable stagecraft. I immediately made rash claims about
Moran and the Ridge together being `the future of the theater.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Writing in The New Republic, where he is the theater critic,
Brustein said that the Moran-McGrath collaboration might be
``potentially as important for American performing arts as that of
Philip Glass and Robert Wilson.'' Subsequently, though, he has said
that the Ridge Theater's artistry is apparent when applied to
material not created by Moran.
</P>
<P>
   In April, McGrath and his company will return to ART to stage an
adaptation of Robert Coover's ``Charlie in the House of Rue,'' a
scenario about Charlie Chaplin that marks their third production at
the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``McGrath has the capacity to be very faithful to a text and
still embroider a whole imaginative life around it,'' Brustein
said. ``He can mold technology and live performance to change a
theater space into a film studio. Through projections and the
doubling of actors, he is able to jump cut, fade and dissolve.''
</P>
<P>
   About the Moran-McGrath split, Brustein said, ``Maybe like
Philip Glass and Robert Wilson, they will go their separate ways
and then work together again.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass agreed. ``Bob Wilson and I worked together, then split for
eight years. McGrath and Moran did beautiful work together, and
they'll do beautiful work apart. I hope it's not the end of this
association.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, McGrath and Ridge are busy. After staging two plays by
Mac Wellman last March, they will do a new Wellman play next year,
based on the paintings of the outsider artist Henry Darger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sought out McGrath,'' said Wellman, ``because he's intensely
visual, but his style is still amenable to language. The company is
fearless in the right way. They don't care if they fit into the
cliches of downtown theater, so they don't. They debunk the
received notion that the avant-garde is dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
