<SLUG> BC-HEDGEFUND-ECONSCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECONOMIC SCENE: KEEPING TABS ON LEVELS OF RISK AT BANKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ga.)  (lb) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Merton and Myron Scholes are smarter than smart. They
know better than anyone else how to think about financial risk. The
proof lies in their Nobel award, which they shared for figuring out
the fiendishly complex math by which to assign precise price tags
to options and other risky investments.
</P>
<P>
   So if Merton and Scholes are so smart, why did the investment
pool that they helped create, Long-Term Capital Management LP,
collapse last month? Apparently the professors are better at
thinking about risk than at managing it.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a scary thought.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the savings and loans bankruptcies in the
1980s, banks have been told to hold a large cushion of capital. If
losses mount and bring a bank's capital below preset levels,
regulators are required to pounce, forcing management to retrench
or even go out of business.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators might like to monitor the overall risk of a bank's
investment portfolio, but the simple truth is that two nanoseconds
after they exit the examination, the bank could pile on risk with
the use of derivatives _ securities that track stock prices,
interest rates or some other market factor and can quickly rack up
huge gains or losses.
</P>
<P>
   So regulators have turned over the task of monitoring risk to
the bank's managers, checking that they adopt sophisticated models
that can assess risk and set off timely alarms.
</P>
<P>
   That raises the question: Can lowly bank managers do what two
Nobel laureates could not? And if not, should banks with federally
insured deposits be allowed to do business with risky investment
pools, known as hedge funds, like that run by Merton and Scholes?
Put another way, are self-monitoring banks safe?
</P>
<P>
   The answer is almost certainly ``yes.'' The weasel word _ almost
_ cannot be stricken. But neither should it dominate conversation.
</P>
<P>
   Take the case of a bank lending money to a hedge fund. ``So
what?'' asks George Benston, professor of finance at Emory
University. Many of the loans appear to be backed by collateral.
But if not, Benston says, the loans are ``no different from dozens
of other loans that banks make.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The hedge fund may default on the loan.'' he added. ``So may
real-estate developers and morticians. Banks are in the business of
making risky loans.''
</P>
<P>
   Christine Cumming of the New York Federal Reserve Bank points
out that bank ``examiners review a bank's appraisal of its entire
loan portfolio.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Loans are classified according to risk, and the bank's capital
cushion judged accordingly,'' she said. In that sense, loans to
hedge funds are nothing special. The answer to risk, Benston points
out, is diversification. Ms. Cumming adds that among the questions
bank examiners ask is whether the bank has overly committed its
loans to one industry, one client or one region. A diversified
portfolio is a reasonably safe portfolio.
</P>
<P>
   But banks also do derivatives trading with hedge funds _ writing
contracts like options, swaps and currency futures. The banks are
supposed to hold an overall portfolio of derivatives with largely
offsetting risks _ some contracts make money if interest rates
rise, and others lose money if interest rates fall.
</P>
<P>
   Building on the work of Scholes and Merton, banks submit their
overall portfolio to stress tests _ models that ask how the bank's
assets would change if, for example, interest rates were to rise or
fall by two percentage points. If the stress tests reveal that the
financial health of a bank is threatened by possible market moves,
then the managers and the regulators know that the bank must
retrench.
</P>
<P>
   Are stress tests up to any challenge? No one knows for sure,
because they have yet to be tested by any challenge. But Benston
points out, ``There has never been a failure of a bank on account
of derivatives.''
</P>
<P>
   The sophistication of stress tests will have to grow along with
the investment strategies of banks. Stress tests will need to
account for the danger that markets can freeze, preventing banks
from shedding and acquiring derivatives as needed to balance its
risks.
</P>
<P>
   But so far, the combination of large capital cushions,
diversified loans, stress tests and prompt regulatory action has
been enough to keep banks healthy. The system works well to protect
banks against isolated failures _ hedge-fund collapses or Russian
bank defaults.
</P>
<P>
   The system is not well equipped to handle what one government
official calls ``financial Armageddon,'' the simultaneous collapse
of banks in Brazil, Korea, China and everywhere in between, or a
national depression. But the fallout from Armageddon is exactly
what the Federal Reserve System is designed to solve.
</P>
<P>
   Alan Greenspan, the Fed chairman, was careful last week to state
that the collapse of Long-Term Capital did not pose a ``systemic
risk'' _ Fedspeak for bank collapse _ but did threaten to ``disrupt
markets'' _ Fedspeak for falling prices of assets, which create
problems for institutions that lack adequate capital, and a
slowdown in bank lending. The upshot is that hedge funds threaten
the nation's banking system only if the regulators fall asleep.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
