<SLUG> BC-COLLEGE-COSTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH PRICE OF COLLEGE STRESSING ALL BUT RICHEST IN US 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KATE ZERNIKE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paying for college has become increasingly difficult for all but
those families in the highest income levels, according to the
College Board's annual survey of college costs, released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tuition at four-year public and private colleges and
universities rose 4 percent for the 1998-99 school year, double the
rate of inflation, and made the price of college about 50 percent
higher than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   While financial aid in both loans and grants rose to $60
billion, students are increasingly relying on loans instead of
grants to cover the cost, meaning debt loads are higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``The share of family income required to pay college expenses
has increased for all families...but it has gone up mostly for
those on the lower rungs,'' said Lawrence Gladieux, an analyst with
the College Board, which also administers college and graduate
school admissions exams. ``Rising costs have a disproportionate
impact on those at the low end of the scale. And most of these
rising costs have to be financed by borrowing. That's what I worry
about as we drift more toward a loan-based student aid system.''
</P>
<P>
   Attending a public, four-year college or university cost 62
percent of a low-income family's earnings and 17 percent of a
middle-income family's earnings last year, the most recent year for
which numbers were available. Sending a child to a private
institution would have consumed 162 percent of a low-income
family's earnings, compared with 44 percent of the earnings of a
middle-income family and 4 percent of the earnings of a high-income
family.
</P>
<P>
   The 4 percent average increase this year means tuition and fees
rose $132 at public four year-institutions, reaching an average of
$3,243. For private, four-year colleges, average tuition and fees
rose $723, up 5 percent to $14,508. Those costs averaged $1,633 at
public two-year colleges, up 4 percent, or $66. A 4 percent
increase also occurred at private two-year colleges, where average
tuition and fees rose $254 to $7,333.
</P>
<P>
   The increase this year is far below the steeper increases of the
1980s, but still means the price of college is much higher than it
was over the past two decades.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past 17 years, the sticker price has risen 107 percent
at public 4-year colleges, and 104 percent at private 4-year
schools, while median family income has risen 12 percent. Financial
aid has risen 65 percent, but that has not kept pace with the cost
of going to college.
</P>
<P>
   And indebtedness continues to grow. Eighteen years ago, about 55
percent of student financial aid came as grants, which don't have
to be paid back. Now, 60 percent comes in the form of loans.
</P>
<P>
   Pell Grants, the federal financial aid grants for low- and
middle-income students, covered about 35 percent of the cost of a
private 4-year college when they began 25 years ago, and 75 percent
of the cost of a public four year college. Now, those grants
provide only about 15 percent of what it costs to go to private
college, and 30 percent of what it costs to go to public colleges.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the cost of college _ public or private, 4 year or 2
year _ remain highest in New England, with tuition and fees adding
up to an average of $19,211 for a private four year college, and
$12,237 for a private two year college.
</P>
<P>
   In Massachusetts, tuition and fees at the 55 schools that make
up the Association of Independent Colleges and Universities of
Massachusetts rose 4 percent from last academic year to the one
that began last month, lower than the national average for private
colleges for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   While they acknowledged the price of college was, in the words
of College Scholarship Service head John Joyce, ``A chunk of change
by any measure,'' college board officials went somewhat on the
defensive, pointing out that most students pay less than $8,000 per
year to go to college, and that the average is skewed by the higher
cost schools like Harvard and Brown Universities. They also said it
costs more to run a college or university than it does most
industries, so comparisons to the rate of inflation, they said, are
somewhat misleading.
</P>
<P>
   And Brown University President Gordon Gee, at the press
conference in Washington, reminded families that a college graduate
still makes more than $1 million more over a lifetime than someone
who earns just a high school diploma.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is worth every penny,'' College Board President Donald M.
Stewart said. ``But as with any investment, a college education
requires foresight, prudent savings, and some sacrifice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
