<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SEMICONDUCTOR-MARKETPLACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: CHIP MAKERS MAY BE TURNING THINGS AROUND 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 BY LAWRENCE M. FISHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Analysts who cover the semiconductor industry have for months
been casting about for some sign that the beleaguered sector had
reached a bottom. So with three or four bits of positive data in
hand, many have seized on the opportunity to declare a turnaround
this week.
</P>
<P>
   Some had already done so last month when Intel Corp. projected
that its third-quarter sales would be 8 percent to 10 percent more
than the $5.9 billion reported in the second quarter, rather than
flat as it had suggested earlier. Intel will report final results
on Oct. 13.
</P>
<P>
   But this week, with Advanced Micro Devices Inc. reporting a
surprise return to profitability, Motorola Inc. projecting new
growth and the Semiconductor Industry Association reporting the
first sequential monthly sales growth since November, the
turnaround chorus gained voices. The association said Wednesday
that worldwide chip sales increased by 1.5 percent in August, to
$9.81 billion, despite continued declines in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, substantial caveats remain. The growth these
companies are reporting is significant, but it is relative to the
severely depressed numbers of recent quarters. Most analysts expect
more positive surprises in the December quarter, particularly for
those companies supplying manufacturers of personal computers, but
no one knows whether a recession will strike next year, and if it
does, whether companies will continue buying PCs to boost
productivity, or shut down all capital spending for the duration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you do have enough pieces of evidence to suggest that
something did change in the June-July time frame,'' said Mark
Edelstone, an analyst with Morgan Stanley. ``PC demand worldwide is
still pretty decent,'' and the glut of inventory that had slowed
microprocessor sales has largely been flushed through the
distribution system, he said. ``I think any semiconductor company
that sells into the PC market will have something upbeat to say,
just as AMD did,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Advanced Micro Devices on Tuesday reported earnings of $1
million, or 1 cent a share, instead of the 11-cent loss analysts
had been expecting. The company attributed its sales growth to its
K6-2 line of microprocessors, which have been gaining market share
from Intel's Pentium and Celeron chips, particularly in PCs priced
less than $1,000. W.J. Sanders III, Advanced Micro's chairman and
chief executive, said that PC sales were healthy almost everywhere,
and that ``the worst is behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Advanced Micro shares slipped 18.75 cents, to
$16.75, anyway, possibly because of investors selling on the news,
possibly because of the perennial worry that the company will not
be able to keep up with Intel in the next product cycle. That is a
serious worry: Intel's manufacturing processes are second to none
and the company outspends Advanced Micro on research and
development by five or six to one.
</P>
<P>
   Intel said Wednesday that its next generation processor,
code-named Merced, is on track for production in mid-2000, and that
its successor, now known as McKinley, will be twice as fast and
available in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's prowess is the reason why Michael Murphy, editor of the
California Technology Stock Letter, is not recommending purchase of
Advanced Micro shares, but he is recommending Intel at current
prices as well as a host of smaller chip companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a unit volume increase going on, and everybody is
saying that prices have stopped declining so rapidly,'' he said.
``That's all it takes to make a turn on a seasonal basis,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The question then becomes ``what happens next year,'' Murphy
said. ``Do we slide into recession and does capital spending just
stop, or does deflation compel people to upgrade PCs, get on the
Internet, and cut costs, before their competitors take them out?''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to find any other part of the economy showing
double-digit unit growth,'' he added, ``so I think money should
come out of the Coca-Colas and Gillettes and into the Motorolas and
Intels.''
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Joseph, an analyst with NationsBanc Montgomery
Securities, said the improvement in the industry's health is
subtle, noting that on a year-to-year basis, worldwide
semiconductor shipments were down 16 percent in August, compared
with 17 percent in July.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, ``it appears as if the semiconductor sector,
aided by stronger demand for microprocessors and memory, has turned
a corner and is now in the initial stages or reaccelerating.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph is also recommending Intel, as well as small networking
chip suppliers like PMC-Sierra Inc., whose prices are down by 50
percent from previous highs. ``The table is really set for a party,
but does anybody care?'' he asked, noting investors' reticence in
buying these stocks. ``Ultimately, investors are going to gravitate
toward value, and to the extent possible, sustainable growth.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
