<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUIT-VISA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
US FILES ANTITRUST SUIT AGAINST CREDIT CARD NETWORKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER G. GOSSELIN   
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK -- The Justice Department sued Visa and MasterCard
Wednesday, charging that the nation's two largest credit card
networks are violating federal antitrust laws by blocking banks
from issuing competing cards and by slowing the spread of new,
high-tech ``smart cards.''
</P>
<P>
   Department officials asserted that the lawsuit will give
consumers more choice by, among other things, lifting rules that
bar banks which issue the two cards from offering alternatives like
American Express and Discover. But industry spokesmen shot back
that consumers are already deluged with card offers.
</P>
<P>
   The suit is the product of a two-year investigation of the card
industry, and is the latest step by the department's recently
reinvigorated antitrust division, which, separately, is suing
computer software giant Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``Credit cards are not just luxuries. They are an important
financial tool for many Americans,'' Attorney General Janet Reno
told a Washington press conference. ``For millions of people,
competition in the credit card industry is vital.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers have unlimited choices when it comes to credit
cards,'' countered Paul Allen, executive vice president and general
counsel for Visa U.S.A. ``There's no avoiding the mail and phone
calls we get almost daily from a multitude of issuers offering new
incentives, rates and special offers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Justice department suit seeks to end joint control of Visa
and MasterCard -- which together account for 75 percent of all
credit card purchases -- by a handful of banking giants that
includes Citicorp and Chase Manhattan Bank USA. But analysts said
that the legal action stops well short of trying to break up the
organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The department is trying to change behavior, not smash
institutions,'' said Robert E. Litan, a former member of the
antitrust division now at the Brookings Institution, a Washington
think tank.
</P>
<P>
   The filing of the suit comes at an awkward time for the
financial industry, which is already troubled by rising credit card
delinquencies, declining profits and a fall from Wall Street favor.
The stocks of several card issuers fell sharply Wednesday, among
them Citicorp, down 5 3/16 to 79 13/16, and Morgan Stanley Dean
Witter &AMP; Co., 3 1/4 to 38 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   Banking analysts said that the government has investigated Visa
and Mastercard repeatedly in the past, but has not been able to
make an antitrust case because of the peculiar structure of the
business. Although the two organizations operate the largest credit
card networks, the cards themselves are issued by individual banks
or financial service companies, which set their own terms and
interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   However, the analysts said, recent changes in the industry,
including a dramatic consolidation among card-issuers and the
emergence of so-called smart cards, are reviving the issue of
whether the dominant card networks are choking competition. Smart
cards use a computer chip to expand the ways consumers can make
purchases.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Justice department has felt there was something wrong here
for 25 or 30 years, but haven't been able to figure it out,'' said
Edward E. Furash, chairman the Washington bank consulting firm of
Furash &AMP; Co. ``The new environment makes it easier for them to make
the case (Visa and MasterCard) are exercising duopoly power,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In their press conference, Justice officials traced the lack of
competition between Visa and MasterCard to the fact that both are
run by the same group of big banks. They quoted a top Visa
executive who testified during the Justice Department's
investigation that ``It is very difficult for us to take a step, an
aggressive step that hurts MasterCard because the same banks who
... are in Visa are also in MasterCard.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials charged that the two card networks do not target
advertising against each other or develop competitive products. And
they push banks to offer both cards, an arrangement that is known
in the industry as ``duality'' and one that officials said gives
banks a financial interest in seeing both succeed and therefore in
minimizing competition between them. The officials quoted a top
MasterCard executive saying ``It is clear that because of duality
you don't see MasterCard and Visa in the marketplace attacking each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno charged during her press conference that the advent of
smart cards ``have been delayed for about a decade'' because the
lack of competition between Visa and MasterCard. But analysts said
that officials' ultimate concern is likely that smart cards'
widespread use in the future could allow the two card networks to
secure even greater control of the industry than they now have.
</P>
<P>
   By combining the functions of an ATM card, credit card and
ready-cash cash, the smart cards are expected to cause a
substantial consolidation that could hurt smaller players like
American Express.
</P>
<P>
   The Justice lawsuit grew out of complaint filed by American
Express, which said Wednesday that the legal action is ``a major
step toward breaking the illegal strangehold that Visa and
Mastercard have had on the card industry for years. This lawsuit
will help bring freedom of choice to consumers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
