<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4951 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-SHUTDOWN-HNS     10-07 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-SHUTDOWN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE REPUBLICAN LEADERS CAVE IN TO CLINTON ON SPENDING ISSUES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By GREG McDONALD 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republican leaders caved in Wednesday to
White House demands that Congress include $18 billion in the
foreign aid bill to help bolster the International Monetary Fund
and strip out provisions that would have prohibited U.S. funds from
being used by overseas groups that promote or perform abortions.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides were close to agreement on the IMF funding
although GOP negotiators still were insisting on tougher IMF
borrowing guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   But the concessions, which angered some conservative GOP members
who were prepared to force a government shutdown rather than
give-in to President Clinton on spending issues, marked a turning
point in the battle between the administration and the Republican
leadership over 1999 appropriations bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process of selling out has begun,'' remarked one GOP
leadership aide after House Speaker Newt Gingrich told Republican
lawmakers that he intends to compromise rather than seek
confrontation with the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Another Republican aide said that about 40 GOP conservatives are
upset that a ``disgraced'' president facing impeachment proceedings
still wields enough power to dictate many of the spending
priorities of the Republican-controlled Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got some angry members,'' this aide continued, ``but
we're trying to get out of here so people can get home to
campaign'' before the Nov. 3 elections.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to wrap up the remaining spending bills for the
new fiscal year that began on Oct. 1, Republican and White House
negotiators began meeting Wednesday to work out differences over a
number of controversial issues that if left unresolved could lead
to a government shutdown when a temporary funding measure expires
at midnight Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Although Congress has passed six of the 13 major appropriations
bills needed to run the government, it still has work to do on the
seven remaining bills. Republican leaders said earlier this week
that at least five of the unfinished measures will have to be
rolled into one large catchall bill in order for Congress to wrap
up its legislative business before its scheduled adjournment
deadline of Friday.
</P>
<P>
   However, House Appropriations Chairman Bob Livingston, R-La.,
said that despite the best efforts of Republicans and the White
House to settle their differences, it's likely Congress will remain
in session through at least the weekend and possibly into next
week.
</P>
<P>
   If it fails to meet its Friday deadline, Congress would have to
pass another short-term stopgap measure to keep all government
departments and agencies running until an agreement is reached on
the remaining spending bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know there's a lot of work to get done,'' said White House
budget director Jack Lew after meeting with Livingston and other
Republicans. He added, however, that there was ``a good spirit of
cooperation'' in the meetings that would hopefully avert the kind
of budget stalemate that led to two partial government shutdowns
three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans got most of the blame for those two closings, and
they seem determined to avoid a repeat of it just a month before
the congressional elections on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``The chances of us having a government shutdown are zero,''
said Senate Majority Whip Don Nickles, R-Okla.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to look for how we can find solutions,'' said Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss.
</P>
<P>
   Livingston said that negotiators were ``getting closer to a
final agreement'' on IMF funding. Republicans have given in to
Clinton's demands that at least $18 billion be earmarked to help
replenish IMF loan coffers, which have been drained by the economic
crisis in Asia. But GOP members led by House Majority Leader Dick
Armey, R-Irving, still are insisting that the administration agree
to a number of reform policies that would require the IMF to
implement tougher borrowing guidelines.
</P>
<P>
   By law, Congress is required to have its work on the budget done
by Oct. 1. But this year, the House and Senate had passed only four
of the 13 major spending bills and President Clinton had signed
only one into law by the time the deadline had come and gone.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats used that statistic to charge that the Republican-led
105th Congress had turned in the worst legislative performance in
24 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republican Congress has been one of investigation rather
than legislation,'' Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D.,
said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to put the best face on a bad situation, Republican
leaders also touted what they consider to be their biggest
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   For example, House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill
Archer, R-Texas, called the 105th ``a remarkably successful
Congress'' for passing a balanced budget last year that has
resulted in an estimated $71 billion surplus. He also cited last
year's tax cut, the first in 16 years, as another example of a
Congress focused on trying ``to help the American people help
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   But in praising the Republican performance, Archer also noted
that Clinton ``deserves credit for joining us'' in working out a
budget agreement and tax relief measures that ``enabled the economy
to move ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there were plenty of signs that compromise would avert
another government shutdown, White House Chief of Staff Erskine
Bowles planned to insist in a late evening meeting with Gingrich
and Lott that Republicans capitulate to Clinton's demand that more
be found for his education priorities of hiring more teachers,
improving after-school programs and building more schools.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans have been willing to give a little in some of those
areas, but have drawn the line so far at giving Clinton all the
money he wants to hire 100,000 new teachers. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
