<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4954 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-UNDECIDED-BOS &LR;      10-07 1146
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-UNDECIDED-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDECIDED IN HOUSE FACE DIFFICULT MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARY LEONARD  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's not every day that first-term Representative
James Maloney gets a call from the White House inviting him to have
coffee with the first lady. It's even rarer that he would turn down
the invitation.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday the Democrat from Connecticut said no thanks to
the White House and its wooing to vote against a wide-ranging House
inquiry over whether to impeach the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just told them I'd have to pass on that,'' said Maloney,
adding that he couldn't easily fit the White House session into a
busy morning schedule. ``This is a decision I have to make on my
own, untainted by politics, partisanship, or party.''
</P>
<P>
   Sitting on the fence may draw unusual attention, but it isn't a
comfortable spot for a freshman Democrat who wants to be a team
player. But at the same time, he also wants to curry favor with
constituents back home in a New England district that is nominally
Democratic but just as happy to elect Republicans. Maloney has an
aggressive, well-funded challenger and is considered one of the 10
most vulnerable House incumbents on Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday Maloney said he was still undecided about his vote. He
said he was uneasy with the open-ended sweep and scope of the
resolution passed Monday by the House Judiciary Committee's
Republican majority but is unable to see how the far narrower
alternative favored by committee Democrats could produce an
adequate and necessary investigation into the allegations against
the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to choose between the lesser of two evils,''
Maloney said, acknowledging he was ``leaning toward'' a vote for
the resolution unless House Democrats could, as the hours ticked
away, craft a new version that looked less like a whitewash and was
more to his liking. By day's end, Maloney had not seen such a
proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Like Maloney, Representative Anne Northup was trying to avoid
the limelight. Northup said she will vote for the resolution, but
as a freshman Republican trying to hold onto her
Democratic-majority district in Louisville, she's proceeding
quietly and putting the emphasis on the inquiry, not impeachment,
for the voters back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the only way to move it forward, fast, and get it over
with,'' Northup said, pointing to Judiciary Committee Chairman
Henry Hyde's prediction that the impeachment investigation could be
done by New Year's. ``So I'm going to vote for it, but I'm not
particularly eager to see this administration fall apart, and I
don't believe a sexual relationship is grounds for impeaching the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   While Congress's focus Wednesday was on the upcoming vote, the
hearts and minds of members like Maloney and Northup were on how it
would play Election Day. There were meetings upon meetings
Wednesday as Democratic leaders tried not so much to find ways to
save face for the president but to figure out how to give cover to
rank-and-file members who face tough reelection fights.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Maloney, a former state senator, upset three-term
Republican Representative Gary Franks in a replay of the 1994
contest that Franks won. The district, which includes the urban
centers of Waterbury, Danbury, and Meriden, is largely middle and
upper class, predominantly white, and a bit more fiscally and
socially conservative than the Democratic Party nationally.
President Clinton won the district in 1996; George Bush carried it
in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney, who graduated from Harvard and got his law degree at
Boston University, is being challenged by Mark Nielsen, a GOP state
senator who got his undergraduate and law degrees from Harvard.
Right now, the race is a dead heat, and Nielsen is pressing hard on
issues such as character and trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very competitive district, and Democrats in these
competitive, uncertain situations are nervous,'' said Stuart
Rothenberg, a campaign analyst. ``So they go for safety, which is
covering their behinds from Republican attacks and assaults that
they are somehow affirming the president's behavior if they don't
vote for a full-blown hearing.''
</P>
<P>
   Polls around the country, including recent ones in Connecticut
and Kentucky, show that voters highly approve of the way Clinton is
doing his job and by about a two-to-one margin do not believe he
should be impeached.
</P>
<P>
   A Quinnipiac College poll conducted at the end of September said
35 percent of Connecticut voters would be less likely to vote for a
candidate who wanted to impeach the president (14 percent would be
more likely). A Louisville Courier-Journal poll published Tuesday
gave Clinton his highest job approval ever among Kentucky voters:
63 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Still, many Democrats, particularly those in swing districts,
are worried that the scandal will energize Republican voters and
depress Democratic turnout, giving an edge to GOP challengers.
Nielsen charged that Maloney, his opponent, will pander to
Republicans with a ``politically expedient'' vote for the
impeachment inquiry, no matter what it costs in good will from the
Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Maloney represents a Republican district, and he is
scrambling in every possible way to masquerade as a Republican on
the eve of the election,'' said Nielsen, who said he would ``not
hesitate'' to vote for the resolution himself.
</P>
<P>
   In Louisville, former state attorney general Chris Gorman is
running a spirited race against Northup, who was the only
Republican in 1996 to win a House seat in a district that Clinton
carried. Though Northup is well-funded and a rising GOP star,
Gorman said he believes she will be punished by voters at home who
are sick of the partisan witch hunt in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``How she votes on launching an inquiry will obviously be an
issue in the campaign,'' said Gorman, who calls the president's
behavior ``wrong'' but not an impeachable offense. ``I do think
there will be a backlash because Americans believe in fair play and
what they see is Republicans overplaying their hands and going over
the top.''
</P>
<P>
   Northup, a mother of six and former state legislator who
political analyst Charles Cook calls ``one savvy politician,'' said
she doesn't expect ``huge consequences'' from her vote today. She
suggested, however, that ``we will change our strategy really
fast'' and run a negative campaign against Gorman if he exploits
her inquiry vote.
</P>
<P>
   Maloney, who is critical of the Clinton sex scandal, said he has
``no idea'' how important the issue will be in his campaign. He
said most candidates ``run to their partisan barricks and proceed
to throw bricks.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The voters want me to do the right things for the right
reasons,'' Maloney said. ``In the end, it's going to be up to them
to evaluate how well I've done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
