</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILSON-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OATHS WITH MORE BITE MIGHT BRING OUT MORE TRUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE WILSON  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - When people testify under oath, they swear to tell the
truth, the whole truth and nothing but the truth. Then they lie.
</P>
<P>
   Judges will tell you the oath doesn't prevent most criminal
defendants from lying in their testimony. According to Ken Starr,
it didn't stop Bill Clinton, either.
</P>
<P>
   His possible impeachment hinges on the question of whether he
testified honestly. More than half of the 15 potential grounds for
impeachment involve charges that he didn't tell the truth. Speaking
to the House Judiciary Committee Monday, majority counsel David
Schippers said the ``sanctity of the oath'' was of paramount
importance. He asserted:
</P>
<P>
   ``If lying under oath is tolerated, and when exposed is not
visited with immediate and substantial adverse consequences, the
integrity of this country's entire judicial process is fatally
compromised.''
</P>
<P>
   Why are so many people willing to risk perjury and swear falsely
to God?
</P>
<P>
   Ethical laxity, rationalizing, little fear of divine or legal
retribution, and immediate self-interest all figure in. Defendants
would rather risk a future penalty from God than spend the next
several years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   One other reason may be the oath itself.
</P>
<P>
   In many courts, it's a less than solemn matter, hastily
administered by clerks who seem bored by the task. The words come
across with a wooden formality and fail to stir the conscience.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe oaths would make a larger impression if judges gave
them or if wording was added to remind defendants that dishonest
testimony can lead to prosecution for perjury. Others would have
the oath signed in court as well as verbally sworn to give it more
impact.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, oaths packed a bigger punch. The potential for
divine punishment was declared emphatically. A 17th-century English
judge sought to encourage truthfulness this way:
</P>
<P>
   ``Now mark what I say to you, friend. Thou has a precious,
immortal soul, and there is nothing in the world equal to it in
value. Consider that the great God of Heaven and Earth, before
whose wise tribunal thou and we are to stand at the last day, will
call thee to account for the rescinding of truth and take vengeance
of thee for every falsehood thou tellest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I charge thee, therefore, that thou do not dare to waver one
tittle from the truth . . . for that the God of Heaven may justly
strike thee into eternal flames and make thee drop into the
bottomless lake of fire and brimstone.''
</P>
<P>
   Another approach to oath-taking was to have defendants swear to
suffer specific consequences if they lied. In an Irish court early
in this century, when lawyers were allowed to present oaths to
defendants, a man was on trial for not paying a debt. The
plaintiff's lawyer asked the accused to repeat after him:
</P>
<P>
   ``If I do not tell the truth in this case . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The defendant repeated the words.
</P>
<P>
   ``May a murrain (an infectious disease) seize my cattle.''
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) ``What's that, counselor? Sure that's not the oath
. . . Oh, glory be to God, may a murrain seize my cattle.'' (end
ital)
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer continued: ``May all my sheep be cliffted (fall over
a cliff).''
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) ``What oath is that you're trying to get me to
take? I never heard an oath like that.'' (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``Go on, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) ``Oh, God help us all! May all my sheep _ arrah,
counselor, are you sure that's in the oath?'' (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``Go on, sir.''
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) ``Oh! God! May all my sheep be cliffted.'' (end
ital)
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer pressed on: ``May all my children get the falling
sickness.''
</P>
<P>
   (begin ital) ``Arrah, counselor, tell His Honor that I admit the
debt, and I only want a little time to pay.'' (end ital)
</P>
<P>
   Now that was an oath with teeth in it. Perhaps Clinton would
have been less equivocating if he had sworn to one that threatened
unbearable consequences, one that went something like this:
</P>
<P>
   If I do not tell the whole truth in this case, may I spend
eternity as the most junior lackey to Newt Gingrich and the most
devoted husband of Linda Tripp.
</P>
<P>
   You can bet the president would have been a veritable fountain
of veracity. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Steve Wilson can be reached at steve.wilson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 2024EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
