<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FED-ECONOMY-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN SAYS OUTLOOK FOR U.S. ECONOMY HAS `WEAKENED MEASUREABLY,'
BUT IN REASONABLE SHAPE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By DAVID IVANOVICH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The U.S. economy remains in ``reasonable shape''
despite financial turmoil overseas, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan said Wednesday, but he warned the global crisis could
dampen domestic demand ``to an unknown extent.''
</P>
<P>
   Greenspan told a group of economists gathered here for a meeting
of the National Association of Business Economics the outlook for
the U.S. economy in 1999 has ``weakened measurably'' since Russia
devalued its currency and defaulted on some of its foreign debt
less than eight weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``What is occurring is a broad area of uncertainty or fear,''
Greenspan said. ``And when human beings are confronted with
uncertainty ... they disengage.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors' heightened fear of risk may have prompted many
Wednesday to dump stocks on the technology-laden and
growth-oriented Nasdaq composite in favor of the better-known names
on the Dow Jones industrial average, economists said.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq lost 3.2 percent of its value, falling 48.28 points
to hit 1462.61, its lowest level in more than 15 months, while the
Dow dipped a mere 1.29 points to close at 7741.69.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a flight to some big names here,'' said Paul Kasriel,
chief U.S. economist for Northern Trust in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Just how dramatic an effect this change in investor attitudes
toward risk will have on the U.S. economy remains an open question.
The nation's economy is still ``quite an impressive sight,''
Greenspan said, enjoying ``good growth and low if not declining
inflation. But the situation ``has become very fluid.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not know how far it will go or how much it will affect
consumer and business spending here at home,'' Greenspan said.
``This is a time for monetary policy to be especially alert.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Fed-watchers interpreted that comment to suggest Greenspan,
as the nation's central banker, may act unilaterally to lower
interest rates in an effort to protect the U.S. economy.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Open Market Committee voted last week to reduce the
federal funds rate _ the benchmark rate commercial banks charge one
another for overnight loans _ by a quarter of a percentage point.
</P>
<P>
   The committee is slated to meet again Nov. 17, but Greenspan has
the authority to lower rates on his own, said Sung Won Sohn, chief
economist for Minneapolis-based Norwest Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to set a more upbeat tone, David Wilcox, assistant U.S.
Treasury secretary for economic policy, reminded the economists the
United States is still in the eighth year of an economic expansion
and that ``the fundamentals of the U.S. economy remain strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment has remained below 5 percent for 15 months, the
longest stretch in 28 years, Wilcox said. Real wages have risen 2.8
percent over the last year _ the biggest increase since the early
1970s _ while inflation has remained almost non-existent.
</P>
<P>
   While the turmoil overseas is believed to be slowing economic
activity here in the United States, ``such a tempering in growth
does not, on its face, pose a major threat to the longevity of the
current expansion and has, in fact, been expected for some time
now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Although the precise impact of the global financial crisis on
the U.S. economy is at this point uncertain, the latest evidence
available to us makes a strong case that the current expansion will
continue,'' Wilcox said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the International Monetary Fund, the Washington-based
financial rescue fund, estimated economic growth in the United
States would reach 3.5 percent this year but drop to about 2
percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   In Japan, the world's second-largest economy, IMF economists are
expecting economic activity to fall 2.5 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Japan's economic woes, the yen _ for months _ has
languished against the U.S. dollar. Suddenly, the dollar dropped
against the yen Wednesday, falling a dizzying 9.50 yen.
</P>
<P>
   Part of that movement, economists said, may have been caused by
encouraging news out of Japan that suggested the government there
may finally be ready to reform its troubled banking system.
</P>
<P>
   But some economists suggested the move may have had more to do
with rumors that two U.S. ``hedge funds'' _ investment funds which
service rich investors and use a wide range of high-risk techniques
in an effort to attract stellar returns _ were altering their
investment strategy.
</P>
<P>
   These funds, many believe, had borrowed heavily from Japanese
lenders at very low interest rates and then used this cash to
purchase U.S. securities. To pay off their Japanese lenders, these
hedge funds then, many believe, had been using U.S. dollars to buy
Japanese yen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, I think the hedge funds unwinding their positions had
a lot more to do with the market (Wednesday) than what the Japanese
may or may not do,'' Sohn said. ``Who knows with the Japanese.
They'll probably let us down again. Frankly, I don't have high
hopes.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
