<HEADER>
A4972 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR &LR;      10-07 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COLUMN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S LARGEST SMALL TOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Phoenix had a chance to act like the big city it's
supposed to be and botched it. (begin ital) You (end ital) botched
it. You proved, once again, that this wildly expanding desert
megalopolis is a ``city'' in name only.
</P>
<P>
   I'm talking about the disappearance and sudden reappearance of
21-year-old Mary Jo Ruiz.
</P>
<P>
   For more than two weeks you couldn't turn on the TV or open the
newspaper or listen the radio without bumping into a story of the
young woman from south Phoenix who'd mysteriously vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz had been dancing with friends at Moon Doggie's dance club
in the Arizona Center in downtown Phoenix on the night of Sept. 3.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, she borrowed the keys to her best friend's 1997
Dodge Neon, parked in a nearby garage.
</P>
<P>
   She went to the car alone, and didn't return.
</P>
<P>
   Before you know it, television crews were camped out outside the
family's home near Southern and 19th avenues.
</P>
<P>
   Ruiz's mother, sisters and other relatives were featured on
newscast after newscast tearfully asking for your help, your
prayers, your money.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the sophisticated city dwellers you're supposed to be,
you gave it.
</P>
<P>
   This probably wouldn't have happened in New York, Los Angeles,
Chicago, Houston or Philadelphia, the five American cities with
more people than us.
</P>
<P>
   In those places, a stranger is a stranger, period.
</P>
<P>
   Here, a woman you don't know disappears and you act as if she's
your daughter or your sister.
</P>
<P>
   Prayer vigils were held. Fliers were circulated.
</P>
<P>
   Car washes were organized to collect reward money for anyone who
could provide information concerning Mary Jo's whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   Then, 16 days after disappearing, Ruiz was stopped by Los
Angeles police on Riverside Drive. She was alone in her friend's
car. She said she'd been abducted by three men and raped. She told
officers she'd been released in California _ with the car _ and
wandered around L.A. for days because she was ashamed about what
happened to her.
</P>
<P>
   Her story confused investigators. When they asked to
re-interview Ruiz, however, she refused to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Police say she hasn't even provided them with enough information
for a composite sketch of suspects.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, one of her sisters said she wishes ``everybody
would just mind their own business. . .She's safe at home, that's
all that matters.''
</P>
<P>
   But, it isn't. The ``reward`` money matters.
</P>
<P>
   After Mary Jo was found, one relative said, ``We're going to use
it (the cash) for her counseling.''
</P>
<P>
   That isn't why it was collected. It was supposed to be a reward,
not a cash-back bonus.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of charities that could put the money to good
use, including those that search for missing persons.
</P>
<P>
   As for ``minding their own business,'' that's exactly what the
Ruiz family asked you (begin ital) not (end ital) to do.
</P>
<P>
   And you went along.
</P>
<P>
   A real big city would never do that. A real big city wouldn't
give a damn.
</P>
<P>
   But, here you are. This place has the skyscrapers of a city. The
restaurants and ball teams of a city. The concert halls, museums
and hospitals of a city.
</P>
<P>
   It just doesn't have the attitude.
</P>
<P>
   The next stranger who turns up missing will get the same
treatment. It's already happened. A mother disappeared recently and
you rushed to support her family, and continue to do so even after
the woman's children were accused of killing her.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of behavior isn't what makes Phoenix the sixth largest
city in America. It's what makes Phoenix the biggest small town in
America.
</P>
<P>
   You have this tendency to want to help people, to give them the
benefit of the doubt. Maybe you're a little too friendly and a
little too naive.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, if we're lucky, you'll stay that way. &QL; 
 &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at ed.montini(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 2029EDT &QL; 
