<SLUG> BC-DEMOCRATS-IMPEACH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOME `BLUE DOG DEMOCRATS' ARE LIKELY TO SUPPORT GOP INQUIRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN FREEDMAN  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ House Republicans are counting on the ``Blue Dog
Democrats'' for support for the GOP impeachment resolution
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Dogs are conservatives from swing districts in the
South, the Midwest and the West. Some face tough re-election
battles Nov. 3 while others, though unopposed or up against token
opposition, worry that any impeachment-related vote favoring
President Clinton might come back to haunt them.
</P>
<P>
   With a 228-206 GOP majority, it's a foregone conclusion that the
House will approve the Republican-sponsored inquiry into Clinton's
conduct in the White House sex scandal and its aftermath.
</P>
<P>
   But the more Democratic votes the GOP gains, the easier it is
for Republicans to cast the impeachment inquiry in a bipartisan
light. The fewer the Democratic votes, the easier it is for Clinton
and party loyalists on Capitol Hill to cast it as a partisan witch
hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Among Democrats either committed to voting for the Republican
resolution or most likely to are Rep. Charles Stenholm of Texas,
Rep. Jim Turner, of Texas, Rep. Gene Taylor, of Mississippi, Rep.
Chris John, of Louisiana, Rep. Tim Roemer, of Indiana, Rep. Jim
Moran, of Virginia, Rep. Paul McHale, of Pennsylvania, Rep. Virgil
Goode, D-Va., Rep. William Lipinski, D-Ill., and Rep. Owen Pickett,
D-Va.
</P>
<P>
   IS THE FOLLOWING TRANSITION STILL CORRECT: `OF THOSE,....' ?
</P>
<P>
   Of those, Stenholm, Turner, Taylor and John are members of the
Blue Dog Coalition, formed in 1995 as a vehicle for conservative
Democrats who favored a balanced budget. With 24 members, the
coalition's name is a variation on the traditional Southern
``yellow dog'' Democrat, a party loyalist who would even vote for a
yellow dog if it were running as a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   The group cast  &UR; sD
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
