<SLUG> BC-ARCHDEACON-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Legendary harness driver dreams his way to success
 &HT;    By Tom Archdeacon
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LEBANON, Ohio _ The dream came to life _ quite literally _ on a
family farm outside of a small western Ontario, Canada, town in the
mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan Campbell was a farmer, who for four decades had had
modest success with a low dollar string of harness horses on the
country fair circuit and small pari-mutuel ovals. As a Mother's Day
present, Duncan once gave a mare to his wife, Bernice. As fate
would have it, that horse produced a foal on April 8,1966.
</P>
<P>
   That day also happened to be the 11th birthday of grandson John,
who immediately fell in love with the colt, which was named Argyle
Chester. Eventually, Bernice decide to give the boy half ownership
in the colt.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a real big deal,'' John Campbell said. ``I was the
only kid in school who owned a race horse. I just loved that
animal. He was chestnut with two white stockings and a blaze on his
face. He was so flashy. I went to all the races I could and took
him to the paddock. He got me dreaming so much. All I thought about
doing was driving horses when I got older. That's all I wanted to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   John Campbell was recalling that story Monday night in a Lebanon
Raceway stop that was proof once in a while dreams do more than
just come true _ they turn into your wildest fantasy. The Canadian
kid who once dreamed of driving grandma's horse at the local track
has become the best harness driver in the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's already got the records and he's just going to keep on
adding to them,'' said Ray Burdette of Old North Dayton, who was
among hundreds of fans lined up to get an autograph or share
chitchat with Campbell before the evening's racing began. ``The
thing about John Campbell, he could take a mule and outrun a
thoroughbred.''
</P>
<P>
   Although just 43, Campbell has won every major race, every
driving title _ and most of them numerous times. He's won the
Little Brown Jug and the Cane Pace each three times, the Messenger
Stakes and the Hambletonian five times. Should he drive Muscles
Yankee to victory in the Kentucky Futurity Friday at the Red Mile
in Lexington, he will become the first Trotting Triple Crown winner
in 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   Already this year, he has won more than $8.6 million in purses,
finishing in the money in 752 of 1,514 races. He's the sports'
all-time money winner with more than $164 million in purses. His
next closest rival is $59 million behind. ``If you don't bet on him
when you're at the track, you should have your head examined,''
said Jim Allen, a Lebanon Raceway patron from Wayne Avenue. ``He's
simply the best of the best.''
</P>
<P>
   In this sport, whenever big money's on the line, the trainers
involved want John Campbell in the bike behind their horse. It's
also why Lebanon Raceway wanted him to make a promotional visit
Monday. Years ago, he raced here twice, but these days _ based in
New Jersey near the Meadowlands and racing the top dollar events
around the globe _ he's beyond the local track circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Yet he hasn't forgotten his roots. And the smaller tracks like
Lebanon _ where the live gate is off nearly 60 percent because of
bumbled state legislation, other gambling and sports draws_ need
the help. Thanks in part to the efforts of the United States
Trotting Association _ of which Corwin Nixon, guiding light of
Lebanon Raceway, is president _ Campbell spent part of the day at
the Warren County track.
</P>
<P>
   Along with a challenge race _ edging local star Mike Wilder _
Campbell also donated $500 of his travel costs to the Warren County
Educational Service School. Nixon then matched the sum.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't find a better guy in racing,'' Nixon said. ``Look
how he's dealt with the public here. He cares about the people.''
</P>
<P>
   That was never more evident than three years ago when Campbell
got a request from a Mt. Gilead man who wanted the racing legend to
drive a race for a terminally ill friend at the Morrow County Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Don Sipe, the dying man, had a few horses and had dreamed of one
day having an animal good enough to lure Campbell into the sulky.
Campbell showed up and as the stunned and tearful Sipe watched,
drove the colt to a second-place finish. Three weeks later, just
hours after Campbell won the Little Brown Jug with Nick's Fantasy,
Sipe died.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like having Babe Ruth come in to fulfil the last
request of someone,'' Jerry Knappenberger of the Ohio Harness
Horseman's Association said.
</P>
<P>
   What made Campbell so good? He shrugged: ``I really think good
drivers are born, not made. I think it was in my family. My dad
trained and my brother does too.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he's been harness racing's top money winner 12 of the
past 19 seasons, he's also had his share of hard knocks. Thanks to
spills early in his career, he's had four operations on one knee, a
back operation and recovered from a broken wrist and a badly
damaged other knee.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more unusual injuries came in a Meadowlands race when
the driver he was battling wheel-to-wheel accidently whipped him
all the way down the stretch. ``He thought he was hitting his
horse, but he was whaling away on me,'' Campbell said. ``You can't
believe the pain. I was screaming the whole way, but he never knew.
Afterward the welts were up a couple inches all across my back. I
yelled at him, but he had had no idea it was me.''
</P>
<P>
   That's kind of the anonymity he receives in the general public.
Harness racing stars don't often make the jump to the rest of the
world. Still with his dominance, Campbell has made various
high-profile appearances, including throwing out the first pitch of
a New York Yankees game at Yankee Stadium this season.
</P>
<P>
   How did he do? ``When I went to the mound, I made sure it wasn't
a rainbow. Nope, it was nothing but high heat,'' he said with a
laugh. ``Hey, I had to make the most of the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like he did as a 11-year-old dreamer with Grandma as a
partner.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
