<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-ROCKETBOYS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    'Rocket Boys' author talks of dreams, stars
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When Homer Hickam Jr. tells a room full of
schoolchildren that ``if you want anything badly enough, and you'll
work for it, you can do it,'' the words ring with hard-won truth.
</P>
<P>
   Hickam, 55, who spoke Monday at the Challenger Learning Center
in Dayton, was only 14 when he and his friends in a small West
Virginia coal town spotted Sputnik winking across the sky one night
and were inspired to build a rocket of their own.
</P>
<P>
   Their unlikely success in joining the 1950s space race has been
chronicled in Hickam's memoirs, Rocket Boys (Delacorte, $23.95),
which has soared to No. 20 on the New York Times' best seller list
after only three weeks in bookstores. Next spring Universal
pictures plans to release a motion picture based on the book,
starring Laura Dern and Chris Cooper and produced by the makers of
Field of Dreams .
</P>
<P>
   With the help of their parents, teachers, clergy and a town of
coal miners torn by union strife, Hickam and his five young pals
eventually lobbed a rocket six miles into space, earning first
prize in the West Virginia Science Fair and the gold and silver
medals at the National Science Fair in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   All six boys _ sons of coal miners in a dead-end company town _
went on to earn college degrees (''That was unheard of in Coalwood
at the time,'' Hickam said), and Hickam himself became a NASA
engineer and now author.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never, never, never, never think you can't do something,'' he
told the 50 students visiting the learning center from Dayton's
Kiser Middle School and Fairborn's Black Lane Elementary. ``The
only person and the only thing that can stop you is yourself.'' As
part of a 23-city promotional tour for his book, Hickam spent an
hour talking to and fielding questions from the sixth-, seventh-
and eighth-graders. Queries included the possibility of life
elsewhere in the universe, the prospects for visiting Mars and how
best to stop a killer asteroid headed for Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Samuels, an eighth-grader at Kiser, wanted to know if a
spaceship would continue to accelerate forever across the universe.
``I didn't know like debris and stuff out there would slow it
down,'' he said later.
</P>
<P>
   Khalila Johnson, also an eighth-grader at Kiser, said Hickam's
talk reaffirmed for her the importance of going to college. ``I'm
not really into space travel, but I'm thinking about being an
engineer,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hickam admits it's unlikely any group of teen-agers will ever
repeat the famed exploits of the Rocket Boys. ``No way,'' he said.
``It was a singular time and place that we six boys were able to do
that _ mainly because we were ignorant of the laws,'' including FAA
rules against launching objects into the path of planes.
</P>
<P>
   Hickam, who retired this year from NASA after working on the
International Space Station and training astronaut crews, is
convinced the time has come to revisit the moon. The recent
discovery of millions of gallons of ice there _ which can easily be
converted to life-sustaining water _ means ``there's some plan out
there,'' he said. ``It means we're going back to the moon.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hickam's brand of can-do optimism doesn't stop at the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe we will go to the outer limits of the solar system
and live there. Your children will live there,'' Hickam told the
students. ``Ultimately, I think we will go to the stars.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim DeBrosse writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
