</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEPRESSED-KIDS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Young children, teens not imune from clinical depression
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ When their mild-mannered 16-year-old daughter
suddenly became the teen-ager from hell _ defiant, belligerent,
into drugs and premarital sex _ Bob and Doris Riley (not their
actual names) blamed the bad crowd she had started running with.
</P>
<P>
   But a family counselor soon found an underlying cause the Dayton
parents had never suspected _ their daughter was suffering from
clinical depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew she had been abused by her stepfather when she was
about 8 or 9, but we didn't realize we were seeing the delayed
effects of that,'' said Bob Riley, who eventually got custody of
his daughter. ``She had been pushing it down all those years.''
</P>
<P>
   After seven months of intensive, daylong therapy through South
Community Behavorial Health Care's youth services program, the
Rileys got their old daughter back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Afterward, she was making much better decisions and doing
better in school,'' her father said. ``And she got rid of her old
friends who were causing a lot of the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   For many years, childhood depression was thought to be a
contradiction in terms. Mental-health professionals had assumed
kids were not emotionally mature enough to suffer from depression.
There wasn't even an official diagnosis for it until 1980.
</P>
<P>
   With more research and better diagnostics, professionals know
now that it does exist, even in very young children, and far more
often than many parents realize. The National Institute of Mental
Health estimates that nearly three in every 100 American children
younger than 18 _ or more than 1.5 million children and adolescents
_ are seriously depressed.
</P>
<P>
   The shame is that so few children are being treated for it, in
part because it is often masked by other behavioral problems, said
Dr. David G. Fassler, co-author of a new book on childhood
depression, ``Help Me, I'm Sad'' (Viking, $22.95). ``It is still
significantly unrecognized and underdiagnosed, which is a tragedy
because it's highly treatable,'' Fassler said.
</P>
<P>
   Untreated depression in children can lead to severe emotional
and developmental setbacks as well as further episodes of
depression. Studies show that half of children with untreated
depression will lapse into the condition again within three years.
</P>
<P>
   In the worst case, of course, depression can lead to thoughts of
suicide. Studies show at least 9 percent of all high school
students have attempted suicide, some more seriously than others,
Fassler says. The rate of suicide has doubled among teens over the
past 30 years, making it the second-leading cause of death among
children ages 15 to 19, according to the Centers for Disease
Control and Prevention.
</P>
<P>
   Now is a good time for concerned parents to act.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday is National Depression Screening Day, when thousands of
sites across the country will be offering free education and
screenings for the disorder. ``Any parent who thinks that their
child may be depressed should get an evaluation, and National
Depression Screening Day is an excellent opportunity to arrange
that in a convenient way with good local resources,'' Fassler said.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned parents also should talk to their child's
pediatrician, says Joy Ott, a psychologist at Children's Medical
Center. The pediatrician will be familiar with the child's medical
history and also can make a referral to a mental-health
professional.
</P>
<P>
   Jim DeBrosse writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
