A5010 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RABBI-PRAYER08-COX     10-07 0707
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RABBI-PRAYER08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rabbi whose prayer Clinton recited urges us to look at ourselves
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The rabbi who wrote a prayer President
Clinton used did not write a sermon about him.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Jack Riemer may be the only preacher in the country who
did not speak about the president's moral problems on Yom Kippur,
the Jewish day of atonement, last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of the day is to focus on our own sins,'' said
Riemer, who leads Congregation Beth Tikvah in West Boca Raton, Fla.
``It is a cop-out to discuss and debate his (Clinton's) sins
instead of our own. I did not speak about what's happening in
Washington for the High Holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   But he did write the prayer, On Turning, that the president read
Sept. 12 at the national prayer breakfast. Clinton used the prayer
about repentance as part of his continuing campaign to confess the
sinfulness of his relationship with Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was given a copy of the prayer by a friend, Miami lawyer
Ira Leesfield, with whom he visited following a money-raising event
in September. Leesfield wanted a gift to give his famous guest and
asked his rabbi, who suggested a copy of the prayer, Riemer said.
</P>
<P>
   When the president read the prayer, Riemer became an instant,
national sensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost every paper in the country called me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But, for the High Holy Days, he resisted using the president's
problems and focused instead on calling for all religious people to
look at their own sinful ways.
</P>
<P>
   He preached four sermons through Rosh Hashana and Yom Kippur.
Each explored a biblical story. None mentioned Clinton. All were
aimed at the congregation.
</P>
<P>
   ``In every case, the biblical story was a mirror in which we saw
ourselves,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Riemer is convinced that Judaism must be relevant to the modern
day if the ancient faith is to be compelling.
</P>
<P>
   He wrote the prayer Clinton found so useful last month as part
of a volume of contemporary prayers when serving a synagogue in
Dayton, Ohio, in the '70s.
</P>
<P>
   On Turning uses nature's cycle to demonstrate the process of
turning. Leaves turn colors in the fall in the same season when Yom
Kippur calls men and women to turn from their sin. Birds turn
south. Animals turn from summer's frolic to storing winter's food.
</P>
<P>
   But nature's process is natural, Riemer wrote. Human turning or
repentance demands an act of the will and is difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means breaking old habits. It means admitting we were
wrong. It means saying: I am sorry,'' Riemer wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The popular prayer is now used throughout the country in the
Gates of Repentance high holidays prayer book of Reform Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   ``My feeling was that if Judaism was going to be meaningful, we
needed new prayers in the language of our day about the issues of
our times,'' Riemer said.
</P>
<P>
   ON TURNING, written by Rabbi Jack Riemer
</P>
<P>
   Now is the time for turning.
</P>
<P>
   The leaves are beginning to turn from green to red to orange.
</P>
<P>
   The birds are beginning to turn and are heading once more toward
the South.
</P>
<P>
   The animals are beginning to turn to store their food for
winter.
</P>
<P>
   For leaves, birds and animals, turning comes instinctively. But
for us, turning does not come so easily.
</P>
<P>
   It takes an act of will for us to make a turn. It means breaking
old habits. It means admitting that we have been wrong; and this is
never easy. It means losing face; it means starting all over again;
and this is always painful. It means saying: I am sorry.
</P>
<P>
   It means recognizing that we have the ability to change. These
things are terribly hard to do. But unless we turn, we will be
trapped forever in yesterday's ways.
</P>
<P>
   Lord, help us to turn _ from callousness to sensitivity, from
hostility to love, from pettiness to purpose, from envy to
contentment, from carelessness to discipline, from fear to faith.
</P>
<P>
   Turn us around, O Lord, and bring us back toward you. Revive our
lives, as at the beginning. And turn us toward each other, Lord,
for in isolation there is not life.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Gushee writes for the Palm Beach Post, West Palm Beach,
Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
