r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SPACEPROGRAM-CLOSING0     10-07 0493
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPACEPROGRAM-CLOSING08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wright Brothers' hometown may see key space program fly away
 &HT;    By Timothy R. Gaffney
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Dayton may greet the 100th anniversary of powered
flight by losing a key part of the space program it pioneered in
the 1960s: nuclear generators and heaters for deep space probes.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Department of Energy announced Friday in the Federal
Register its intent to relocate the work from the Mound Plant in
Miamisburg. This would remove the last remaining DOE mission,
allowing the agency to vacate the site by February 2003.
</P>
<P>
   The year 2003 will mark one century since Daytonians Orville and
Wilbur Wright made the world's first powered flight.
</P>
<P>
   DOE is considering moving the work to one of five sites in
Idaho, Nevada, Tennessee, Texas and Washington. It plans to hold a
public hearing at each site, including at Mound, in November.
</P>
<P>
   Removing the last work involving radioactive isotopes from the
site would strike a blow to commercial redevelopment efforts, said
Michael J. Grauwelman, director of the Miamisburg Mound Community
Improvement Corp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe the program really does fit and support where the
region is going,'' Grauwelman said. Most of the businesses that
have sprung up there have leveraged Mound expertise or equipment to
start high-tech enterprises.
</P>
<P>
   The work itself has involved about 40 highly skilled jobs,
including engineers and scientists.
</P>
<P>
   DOE and program managers at Mound could not be reached for
comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Grauwelman said he isn't bothered by the program's use of
plutonium-238, a radioactive isotope that is not used in weapons
but is extremely toxic. It's already encased in metal capsules when
it arrives on the site, he said, and the two buildings that house
the operations are separate from commercial activities.
</P>
<P>
   The Mound operation assembles devices called RTGs and heat
sources. RTGs _ short for Radioisotope Thermoelectric Generators _
have powered every space probe to the outer planets beyond Mars.
The plutonium gives off heat, and RTGs convert the heat into
electricity. Heat sources use plutonium heat to keep delicate
spacecraft equipment from freezing in the cold of space.
</P>
<P>
   While RTGs made it possible for NASA to send space probes to
Jupiter, Saturn and beyond Pluto, they have also caused
controversy. About 500 people protested the space agency's most
recent launch of an RTG-powered probe, the Cassini spacecraft
launched toward Saturn in 1997, because it carries about 72 pounds
of plutonium.
</P>
<P>
   Cassini's two RTGs have been feeding it electrical power
steadily and should continue to work long after the spacecraft
loops into orbit around Saturn in 2004.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, the facility that made the RTGs may not last so
long.
</P>
<P>
   Timothy R. Gaffney writes for the Dayton Daily News, Dayton,
Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
