r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AUSTIN-VENTURES08-COX     10-07 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUSTIN-VENTURES08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin Ventures adding $250 million to portfolio
 &HT;    By Lori Hawkins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Austin Ventures, Central Texas' largest venture
capital firm, is raising another $250 million to invest in
fast-growth companies in Austin and the Southwest.
</P>
<P>
   The new fund will bring the total amount of money managed by
Austin Ventures to more than $700 million, making it the largest
venture capital firm in the Southwest based on amount of money
under management. Dallas-based Sevin Rosen Funds is second with
$500 million in six funds.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the fund points to the increasing number of
high-tech startup companies in Central Texas and the growing
competition among venture capitalists to invest in those companies.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two years, software, Internet and semiconductor
startups in Austin have raised record amounts of money from a
greater number of venture firms.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fund this large is very good for Austin because it will get
people's attention outside the area,'' said Clark Spurrier, a vice
president with Morgan Stanley's technology group in New York.
``It's a great sign for the Austin tech community that a local VC
firm can raise this kind of money with the intention of investing
it in Austin and the surrounding region.''
</P>
<P>
   Austin Ventures has received commitments for most of the $250
million, and expects to close the fund in early November.
</P>
<P>
   The fund is likely to reach $300 million by the time it closes,
sources said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The breadth and depth of the entrepreneurial and senior talent
in Austin is expanding rapidly, and we believe there are a lot of
promising investment opportunities both on the tech and non-tech
sides,'' said John Thornton, a general partner with Austin
Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Ventures has been a key factor in the growth of many
Austin high-tech startups, investing $161million in 42 Austin
companies since 1984.
</P>
<P>
   It hopes to maintain its role, which is why it is raising a
record amount of money and adding employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are planning for this business to become more
competitive,'' said Joe Aragona, a general partner with Austin
Ventures. ``We don't know if a new firm will move in with five
guys, and we don't know if a West Coast firm is going to come in
and open shop. So if you have that level of uncertainty, what do
you do? We said let's get 18 world-class people and we will compete
straight up on value-added resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Startups use the venture money to develop, market and sell
products. In return, the investors get a piece of the company.
Venture capitalists make money when the company is acquired or
sells stock to the public.
</P>
<P>
   The high failure rate of new companies makes venture investment
risky.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Ventures has declined to reveal its return, but says its
performance is in the top 25 percent of venture funds. Area
companies raised a record $165 million in venture money last year,
and have pocketed $95 million during the first half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 venture firms have Austin offices.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, SSM Ventures, recently closed on a new $113 million
fund, which it will invest in Texas and the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Ventures has increased its investment team to 18 people,
11 of which will focus on high-tech.
</P>
<P>
   The company has hired a new general partner, Ed Olkkola, who was
most recently the vice president of business development and
strategy at Compaq Computer Corp. in Houston. He will lead the
company's communications and computer networking initiative in
Austin and Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   It has also recruited Tivoli Systems veteran Chris Grafft as a
venture partner in the technology group, where he joins Jim Clardy,
co-founder of Crystal Semiconductor and Jimmy Treybig, founder of
Tandem Computers.
</P>
<P>
   At Tivoli, Grafft was a member of the executive committee and
had roles including vice president of development and senior vice
president of products. Austin Ventures expects that over three
years it will invest in 25 to 30 early-stage and more mature
companies in high-tech and nontechnology industries. Investments
will range from $250,000 to $15 million.
</P>
<P>
   Austin Ventures plans to begin investing the new money by
Thanksgiving.
</P>
<P>
   Lori Hawkins writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
