<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Raising breast cancer awareness
 &HT;    By Marylin Johnson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In support of October as Breast Cancer Awareness
month, companies have created exclusive cosmetics and apparel to
wear or give as reminders of this disease, which kills 43,000
American women each year. And stores are offering special
promotions.
</P>
<P>
   Events and items range from a fashion show featuring breast
cancer survivors to a powder compact festooned with a pink ribbon,
the symbol of awareness. A percentage of sales of each item or
promotion goes to breast cancer research or programs.
</P>
<P>
   The company promotions and sponsorships of awareness events,
along with nationwide races organized by the Susan G. Komen
Foundation, have raised awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Though only one cent of every $10 collected in federal taxes
goes to govern-
</P>
<P>
   ment-supported cancer research, breast cancer gets a large share
of that money. The government spent $2.7 billion on cancer research
last year, and about $500 million went toward breast cancer,
compared with $100 million for prostate cancer, which kills an
estimated 40,000 American men each year.
</P>
<P>
   This year's Race for the Cure in Atlanta will be held at 8:30
a.m. Oct. 24, beginning at the Atlanta Civic Center, 395 Piedmont
Ave. N.E. (Information: 770-565-4692.)
</P>
<P>
   A sampling of promotions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Estee Lauder is selling a translucent powder compact accented
with a ``jeweled'' pink ribbon motif ($35) and a ``jeweled'' pink
ribbon-trimmed lipstick case ($10), at Lauder counters. Also, a box
of 12 notecards featuring landscapes photographed by Evelyn Lauder
($12.50) is available exclusively at Macy's. All net proceeds go to
the Breast Cancer Research Foundation. Free pink ribbons and
bookmarks listing hotlines and Web sites of cancer organizations
are also at Lauder counters.
</P>
<P>
   _ Two other Lauder companies are adding support. Available at
Clinique counters is a pink lipstick in a pouch ($7.50), with half
of the proceeds going to the foundation. Origins will donate $1
from the sale of its new pressed powder compact ($22.50) and its
liquid foundation ($15) to the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jeweler Carolee has designed a gold heart pin crossed with an
enameled pink ribbon ($25). At Rich's Lenox Square and Perimeter
Mall; $5 from the sale of each pin goes to the foundation.
</P>
<P>
   _ Crystal manufacturer Swarovski created the Compassion pin _ a
crystal bouquet of flowers tied around the stems with a pink ribbon
($150). The company will donate a minimum of $25,000 to the
American Cancer Society Breast Cancer Network. At the Mole Hole at
Phipps Plaza, Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   _ Avon is introducing a pale pink cosmetics case ($3) with a
pink ribbon-and-rose zipper. All proceeds will go to breast cancer
programs. For an Avon representative, call: 1-800-367-2866.
</P>
<P>
   _ California designer Karen Neuburger has done brushed-cotton
pajamas patterned in a rose-and-pink-ribbon print ($56). A portion
of the sales will be donated to the Nina Hyde Center at Georgetown
University. Nordstrom.
</P>
<P>
   _ When accessories designer Marcia Stevens Sherrill found out
members of her family had breast cancer, she wrote ``Portraits of
Hope: Conquering Breast Cancer,'' (S Editions, $24.95). The author,
who has a boutique in Atlanta, Kleinberg-Sherrill, had Rosie
O'Donnell write the foreword. Among the 52 male and female breast
cancer survivors who tell their stories are former first ladies
Nancy Reagan and Betty Ford and chef and author Julia Child. Two
Georgians are included: Miriam Adamson, Ms. Senior America of Pine
Mountain; and Judy Roberts, a marketing representative of Marietta.
All proceeds will be donated to the National Alliance of Breast
Cancer Organizations. To order: 1-800-932-0070, Ext. 214.
</P>
<P>
   Each time you make a purchase using your American Express card
at Saks Fifth Avenue or Neiman Marcus, American Express will donate
25 cents to the Susan G. Komen Breast Cancer Foundation. Saks will
also make a 25 cent donation to the Komen Foundation when customers
use the store's charge card.
</P>
<P>
   Neiman's is selling a $200 ``Ticket to a Cure.'' Each
participant will be entered for a chance to win a Neiman's shopping
package worth more than $65,000. All proceeds go to the Komen
Foundation.
</P>
<P>
   Marilyn Johnson writes for The Atlanta Journal-Constitution,
Atlanta, Ga.
</P>
