<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ban red? No, make gangs dress better
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ I'm so smart I need an extra skull for all these
bright ideas. I have the solution to the gang/dress code problem.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than make law-abiding high school kids change clothes,
why not make the gang members dress stylishly like they used to?
</P>
<P>
   Instead of taking kids out of class at Round Rock High for
wearing red clothing to school, why not make the gangs spend some
money on proper, traditional, fashionable gang clothing like the
mob goons used to wear?
</P>
<P>
   That way, we would know where the gang members are, and the
other kids could wear what they want. And as a side plus, our gang
members would be better dressed.
</P>
<P>
   It's disturbing, isn't it, the way gang guys these days slob
around in tacky attire. The ball caps cocked sideways, the gym
shoes, the baggy jeans worn at half-mast like these guys have just
been pantsed.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, for the good old days, when manicured hoods wore neatly
pressed, high-dollar clothing purchased from upscale men's clothing
outlets like Hart Schaffner &AMP; Marx.
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when organized crime prided itself on its
threads.
</P>
<P>
   Why, a guy couldn't land a job hanging somebody on a meat hook
unless he was attired in a $500 pin-striped double-breasted suit
with wide lapels, a black shirt with matching $50 white silk tie, a
pair of wingtip shoes from Florsheim and a felt fedora.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, what do you see today among our young criminals?
You got it. Slobby gang members, decked out in equally slobby gang
colors.
</P>
<P>
   The sad part is the rest of us suffer from the gangs' current
lack of elegance. Take the students at Round Rock High, for
example. Since red is a color commonly worn by gangs, the
administration at Round Rock High has outlawed red clothing in
school. Red is a prominent color for the Bloods, Round Rock's
largest gang, school Principal Sherry Blackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Is it fair to pick on red? Of course it isn't. What's next? Are
we going to redo the Lone Star flag and replace the red with, say,
tangerine? Where does it stop?
</P>
<P>
   So instead of making the law-abiding change clothes, why not
make the bad guys wear more attractive clothing?
</P>
<P>
   Instead of making the parents of the good kids spend money on
new clothing that isn't red, why not make the gang members dress
more snappily?
</P>
<P>
   Get with the parents of these duds dummies and tell them to take
the little so-and-sos out to the stores and put them in something
stylish.
</P>
<P>
   This would not necessarily cost an arm and a leg, either. There
are budget polyester alternatives out there that are a major
improvement over current gang attire.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the double-breasted suits,'' said Larry Washington,
manager of Suit City, next to Montgomery Ward at Capital Plaza in
North Austin.
</P>
<P>
   To make that gang member look more fashionable, Washington
suggested ``something like a navy blue, or the gray, or maybe a
brown'' suit, with a ``white, or maybe a cream color'' shirt.
</P>
<P>
   So how much money would this outfit set a gang kid back?
</P>
<P>
   ``Just your basic blue or brown would cost you $119.99 for the
suit alone,'' Washington said. ``You can get a shirt for $15.99,
and you can get a tie set which comes with the hanky for $11.99.''
</P>
<P>
   Shoot, with an outfit like that, a gang kid could even get into
his own funeral.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. E-mail jkelso(AT)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
