<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Since I'm a Daytonian, what will my tombstone say?
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ ``Y'all are the hu-uu-b of the universe,'' my
friend Lynne, a Texan, used to say when she lived here, endlessly
amazed by all the things that had been invented in Dayton.
</P>
<P>
   Lynne was right, of course. The obituary in Monday's paper seals
it. Myron E. Scott, former Dayton Daily News photographer and
advertising manager for Chevrolet, not only started the Soap Box
Derby _ in Dayton, no less _ he gave the Corvette its name. Came
home one day in 1953, after 300 suggested names had been tossed
out, thumbed through the ``C's'' in the dictionary, and stopped at
``corvette'': ``a speedy pursuit ship in the British navy.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine _ having one certifiable accomplishment that could be
engraved on your tombstone, something everybody would understand:
``He named the Corvette.''
</P>
<P>
   I scratched my head, wondering how my most significant
achievements would translate into granite: ``She kept an epically
messy desk.'' ``She got her son to school on time one morning in
1997.'' Ah, to be among that roster of Daytonians, who, though
obscure in name, achieved things that are world-renowned and easy
to summarize.
</P>
<P>
   Ever heard of John B. Morton? In 1930, he changed your life
(arguably, not for the better). Yet what a clean, elegant epitaph:
``He invented the parking meter.''
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder Lynne was impressed with the accomplishments of
Daytonians, and not merely the ones with the famous names.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the following:
</P>
<P>
   In 1942, Dayton artist H. Richard Black penned the drawing for
Smokey the Bear. In 1956, he sketched Mr. Clean.
</P>
<P>
   In 1953, Barrett Green developed the microencapsulation process
that made the world safe for carbonless copy paper.
</P>
<P>
   In the early '50s, Leland Clark Jr. invented the heart-lung
machine, his most famous among more than 80 inventions.
</P>
<P>
   In 1955, Ermal Fraze (he of Pavilion fame) invented the pop-top
beverage can.
</P>
<P>
   Paul McEnroe developed the bar code for IBM in the late '60s.
The idea was born on graduation day at UD in 1959, when, as
valedictorian, McEnroe discussed point-of-sale technology with an
NCR executive receiving an honorary degree the same day.
</P>
<P>
   Pound puppies were born and bred in Martinsville in 1984, and
first marketed in Lebanon, the creation of soft-sculpture artist
Becki Manning.
</P>
<P>
   Then there were famous figures who influenced history in
unlikely ways. Katharine Wright, along with a Frenchwoman who flew
with her famous brothers, created the short-lived French craze for
the ``hobble skirt.'' The women would sit on the edge of the wing,
``and to preserve modesty tied a rope loosely around the skirt, so
it wouldn't billow in the wind,'' explained Wilkinson ``Wick''
Wright of Miamisburg, great-nephew of the Wright brothers.
</P>
<P>
   What a woman: pioneering aviatrix and fashion icon. Makes you
really feel like an underachiever, doesn't it? But maybe being
known for One Big Thing would have its disadvantages. What do you
do if you're Orson Welles and you're 26 and you make the greatest
American movie of all time? What's the next step if you're the ad
man who names the Corvette?
</P>
<P>
   Better to muddle through in mediocrity, and not fret about that
epitaph. This, I think, will do quite nicely: ``Here lies Mary, who
managed to get through life without accomplishing much of anything,
even though she lived in the hu-uu-b of the universe.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
