r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMALLBIZ-COLUMN08-COX     10-07 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMALLBIZ-COLUMN08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In Austin high tech, networking is a must for growing companies
By Kim Tyson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ You might call Bucky Couch an accomplished
networker.
</P>
<P>
   Couch, a founder of Austin-based World.hire, which develops
recruiting software, makes a point to go to at least one lunch a
week with fellow business executives. He goes to networking groups.
He attends trade group meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Basically, he does whatever he can to network _ whenever he can.
</P>
<P>
   And it has paid off. Networking has landed Couch's company
countless clients and business tips. Tuesday, he and an executive
with another software company shared the low-down on a potential
financial backer over a lunch at a local Vietnamese-Chinese
restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though Austin is big, it's a small town,'' Couch says.
Networking _ whether over lunch, at parties or even on the Internet
_ is essential to any business. But in a town like Austin, it can
be key to growing small high-tech businesses like World.hire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you have to force yourself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Thompson, known by some as the ``Networking Queen of
Austin,'' says that unlike some East Coast cities, Austin is known
for its open sharing of advice among small, growing high-tech
companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a relationship city,'' says Thompson, founder of The
Thompson Group, which coaches company executives on everything from
where to make the right contacts to how to talk with key executives
and be taken seriously.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, a company executive has to give information before he
or she can get information, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Austin they want to know more about you before they do
business with you,'' she said. ``Some people get frustrated because
it's a, quote, 'longer dance.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who was chairwoman of the Greater Austin Chamber of
Commerce in 1992 before starting her company, says many Austinites
have lived here fewer than five years. She says the bevy of
newcomers means many are looking to build their base of business
contacts through various professional gatherings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Knowledge is your greatest competitive advantage,'' she says.
But given the little time executives have to spend on networking
while running their small, growing companies, ``it comes down to a
strategic use of time,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson says strategic networking includes being in the right
place to meet the key people and getting invitations to the more
high-profile technology social functions. She says these are
important times to pass out business cards and meet people who may
be helpful later.
</P>
<P>
   Networking can be especially painful for some high-tech
executives, Thompson says. That's because many high-tech executives
are engineers who would rather talk technology with a friend than
about potential sales leads with a stranger. Austin marketing
consultant Laura Ricci says even in the global marketplace, studies
show that most people are only a few personal contacts away from
knowing the person they're trying to meet for their businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more people you know, the shorter the path to being able
to make a personal connection with those decision makers,'' she
says.
</P>
<P>
   For Ricci, networking to increase her high-tech business
includes having four or five business meetings over a meal each
week, going to luncheons, checking out networking Internet sites
and belonging to online groups that exchange e-mail advice. For
example, since she does a lot of government procurement consulting
for clients, she belongs to an online service affiliated with trade
group American Proposal Management Professionals.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Triplett, co-founder of the Entrepreneurs' Association, says
owners of small high-tech companies typically network so they can
discuss particular business or technology issues with others facing
the same concerns.
</P>
<P>
   For example, today the association's 15-member High Technology
Networking group has its monthly meeting. The organization also has
groups that meet each month to network that are specifically for
multimedia companies, inventors, electronic commerce and online
Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not necessarily a good way to find a job if you're job
hunting, but it's a way to find an alliance,'' Triplett says.
``People come up with concrete practical ideas; it's not just
chit-chat.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim Tyson writes for the Austin American-Statesman, Austin,
Texas. Send information to her at P.O. Box 670, Austin, TX, 78767
or e-mail at ktyson(AT)statesman.com
</P>
<P>
