<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-JUSTICE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF IT WINS, JUSTICE DEPARTMENT WANTS TOUGHER PUNISHMENT FOR
MICROSOFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Increasing the stakes in their legal battle against
Microsoft, government lawyers now say that if they win their case
they will seek a special court proceeding to determine a punishment
that would prevent future illegal anti-competitive conduct by the
company.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials would not elaborate on what type of
punishment they expect to seek, but outside observers said the
possibilities could include anything from requiring government
pre-approval of Microsoft contracts and products to requiring a
breakup of the company.
</P>
<P>
   The Microsoft antitrust trial is scheduled to begin Oct. 15, but
the Justice Department and Microsoft are seeking to delay it until
Oct. 19. At the trial, lawyers for the Justice Department, 20
states and the District of Columbia will attempt to prove that
Microsoft has a monopoly on computer operating systems and has
illegally sought to extend that monopoly into the market for
Internet browsers.
</P>
<P>
   The trial is expected to last up to two months, and one lawyer
involved in the case has already predicted that whatever happens,
the case is likely to be appealed all the way to the U.S. Supreme
Court.
</P>
<P>
   To date, the government has sought to only to force
modifications to the company's Windows operating system so that it
does not include Microsoft's Internet Explorer browser or so that
it also includes the Navigator browser manufactured by Netscape
Communications Corp. Few observers have expected that punishment,
if imposed, to have a major impact on Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole issue of relief is a subject unto itself, and the
government would want to reserve the right to open a debate on that
subject because the relief they have prayed for so far doesn't look
terribly effectual,'' said Phil O'Neill, an antitrust lawyer with
Jackson &AMP; Campbell of Washington D.C. ``There's certainly nothing
that would make Microsoft any less of a competitor.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposal for a special punishment proceeding was made by
government lawyers in a court filing released Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on the nature and scope of the violations determined
by the court at trial, plaintiffs will seek such additional
permanent relief as is necessary to restore competitive conditions
and to prevent Microsoft from committing similar violations in the
future,'' the filing said. ``To that end, plaintiffs may request
that the court conduct additional proceedings for the purpose of
hearing evidence concerning such additional relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department and state officials declined to elaborate,
but antitrust scholars said the paragraph had two purposes: to warn
Microsoft of the government's serious intention, and to leave the
door open for more Draconian remedies than have been proposed to
date.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft spokesman Mark Murray said ``We don't think it's
appropriate to even speculate on potential remedies, because we
believe the facts and the law are clearly on our side.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This filing is proof of the government's bait-and-switch
attempt,'' he said, noting that the original penalties sought by
the government related directly to the issue of Internet browsers.
``First they tried to rewrite their allegations against Microsoft,
and now they're trying to rewrite the penalties that they asked for
back in May.''
</P>
<P>
   Four antitrust experts said the punishments could theoretically
include a breakup of the company, but added that such a move would
be highly unlikely because the structure of the company is not
directly related to the company's alleged violations. They said
more likely remedies sought by the government would include the
invalidation of existing Microsoft contracts with computer
manufacturers and others, pre-review by the government of future
integrated products made by Microsoft, and imposition of new
regulations limiting contact between employees working in the
operating system and application divisions of Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should suspect that statement was put in there a shot across
the bow to Microsoft, and indeed to preserve the government's
options,'' said James Ponsoldt, a former senior trial attorney at
the Justice Department during the Ford and Carter administrations
who now teaches antitrust law at the University of Georgia School
of Law.
</P>
<P>
   Warren Grimes, a former Federal Trade Commission attorney who
now teaches antitrust law at Southwestern University Law School,
said, ``This might be a way of trying to psych out Microsoft, and
suggest that anything is open. They might ask for divestiture, but
I don't see that as very likely.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimes said the government also might try to demonstrate that
Microsoft's conduct toward Netscape is part of a pattern reflected
in its conduct toward other companies and necessitating broader
punishment than proposed thus far.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Justice Department has made it clear that it's receiving
additional evidence of other predatory actions, and more than
likely additional relief would relate to that additional
information,'' Grimes said. ``This certainly would increase
Microsoft's level of concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles ``Rick'' Rule, a head of the Justice Department's
antitrust division during the Reagan administration who is now a
lobbyist for Microsoft, said the separate penalty phase may just be
a way for Justice to expand its case.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given that the judge has limited each side to 12 witnesses,
and they're going to have a heck of a time proving their
substantive case, they may be doing this to buy themselves some
extra time and witnesses,'' Rule said. ``The remedies they have
already proposed are preposterous in and of themselves, and if they
are to have any chance of trying to defend them on appeal they
would have to develop a record.''
</P>
<P>
   Rule said of the possibility that the Justice Department might
seek to break up Microsoft, ``I can't believe that they're now
buying off on the approach of doing something really stupid, but
who knows?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 2104EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
