<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAYTHEON-CUTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RATHEON UPS CUTBACKS TO 16 PERCENT OF WORK FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOANN MULLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Raytheon Co. says it will cut 5,300 more defense jobs on top of
8,700 already planned as it steps up &UR;  &LR; its effort to become more
competitive following its buyout last year of two big defense
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; In total, the Lexington-based defense electronics company
plans to eliminate 14,000 jobs, or 16 percent of its work force, by
the end of 1999 through a combination of layoffs and attibution.
That compares with an earlier target of 8,700 jobs, or 10 percent
of its work force, which was announced in January, shortly after
its acquisitions of the defense units of Hughes Electronics Corp.
and Texas Instruments Inc.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is tough news for thousands of people. Let's not
sugar-coat it,'' said Raytheon's new president, Daniel P. Burnham,
who is scheduled to succeed chief executive officer Dennis J.
Picard in December.
</P>
<P>
   But he said by aggressively cutting expenses, Raytheon can bid
more competitively and win more new business. That will be better
in the long run for shareholders, customers and the company's
remaining 115,000 employees, Burnham said.
</P>
<P>
   Burnham, a former Allied-Signal Co. executive who has been on
the job at Raytheon for only 100 days, emphasized that the
company's growth potential is strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not doing this because the markets aren't growing. We're
doing it because we need to be competitive to win.'' He added that
Raytheon _ the nation's third-largest defense company, behind
Lockheed Martin Corp. and Boeing Co. _ is winning a record 75
percent of the programs it bids on.
</P>
<P>
   The defense industry has been consolidating in recent years as
government buying dried up with the end of the cold war.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts, which had been spared the brunt of the cutbacks
in Raytheon's first round of layoffs, was nicked a bit harder this
time.
</P>
<P>
   A total of about 1,200 jobs will be eliminated in Massachusetts,
up from an earlier target of 300 mostly administrative positions.
Some 900 will be through layoffs, 300 through attrition. About
1,000 of the job cuts will come this year, with the remainder
occuring in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Many of those laid off will be manufacturing workers &UR;  &LR; at
Raytheon's Waltham West plant, which will be closed. Although the
work will be transferred to Raytheon's Andover and Tewskbury
facilities, not all of the 1,000 employees in Waltham will get to
move, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the cuts in Massachusetts will occur at
Raytheon facilities scattered throughout greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also new work moving to New England as a result of
Wednesday's announcements. Some work now done at plants scheduled
to close in Texas and South Carolina will be shifted to Andover,
although the job impact is minimal. Also, work done at a plant in
Washington will be shifted to Raytheon's Portsmouth, R.I., plant.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon will also close several other plants in Texas and
California.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to accelerating the cost reductions within its
defense arm, known as Raytheon Systems Co., Raytheon also said
Wednesday that its Engineers &AMP; Constructors unit continues to
struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Mostly as a result of slowing demand overseas for big
construction projects, Raytheon said its third-quarter earnings,
before one-time charges, would fall short of analysts' expectations
of 90 cents a share. For the fourth quarter, however, Raytheon is
still on track to earn about $1.08 per share, the company said. The
announcement came after the stock market closed.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Raytheon stock closed at $58, up 1 3/4.
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon also said its third quarter results, which will be
announced Oct. 20, will include several non-recurring charges
totaling $284 million, or 83 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   The charges include $50 million for additional downsizing of its
engineering unit and a $180 million adjustment in the amount set
aside for lost engineering business. The downsizing in the
engineering unit involves facilities and does not include job cuts
beyond the 1,000 in the engineering and construction unit &UR;  &LR; that
were announced separately last January.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raytheon Engineers &AMP; Constructors is well on its way to
correcting its problems,'' said Burnham, citing new management,
stricter cost controls and shared risks through partnerships.
</P>
<P>
   The financial turmoil in Asia has also taken a toll on
Raytheon's commercial electronics business. The company said it
would take a $54 million charge to exit a Korean joint venture &UR;  &LR; in
commercial electronics.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
