<SLUG> BC-RUN-PIPPIG-DRUG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIPPIG WILL APPEAL ON FAILED DRUG TEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Uta Pippig, whose three straight Boston Marathon
victories made her one of the most revered female athletes in the
city's history, was suspended from competition Wednesday after
failing a drug test.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement was made by the German Athletics Association,
which said a random, out-of-competition test on Pippig April 23 in
Boulder, Colo., where she lives and trains much of the year, showed
an abnormal ratio of testosterone to epitestosterone.
</P>
<P>
   If a review by the federation's legal panel finds Pippig guilty
of taking an illegal substance, she could be banned from worldwide
competition for two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 100 percent confidence that she's innocent,'' said Tom
Ratcliffe, Pippig's agent.
</P>
<P>
   Pippig was not available for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The 33-year-old marathoner known for blowing kisses to the crowd
has been a Boston favorite since 1990, when she finished second to
Rosa Mota in her first race in this country after leaving her
native East Germany. In 1994, she won her first Boston after
shrugging off a bad cold; she repeated in 1995 and solidified her
place in Boston lore the next year when she overcame severe
menstrual cramps, bleeding, and diarrhea for her third consecutive
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Since women were officially allowed to compete at Boston for the
first time in 1972, Pippig is the only woman to win three in a row.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, trying to come back from injuries sustained in the 1996
Olympic marathon, from which she dropped out late in the race,
Pippig was fourth here, her lowest Boston finish in seven
appearances. She did not compete this past April after deciding to
take some time off from marathoning to concentrate on shorter races
but was in town to do television commentary. She recently finished
eighth in the Falmouth Road Race.
</P>
<P>
   Guy Morse, race director of the Boston Marathon, said Wednesday
that post-race drug testing is mandatory for all runners who finish
in the top three at Boston and that Pippig never tested positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes this even more unbelievable to hear, because
our history with her has been perfect,'' said Morse. ``Like a lot
of people, I guess, I was shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   But Morse went on to emphasize that the findings so far are
inconclusive. ``What bothers me about this process, and it's
happened before, is that the drug testing process is an imperfect
one at best,'' he said. ``She's somewhere in the process of
review.''
</P>
<P>
   Pippig's case appears to resemble that of Mary Slaney, the
middle-distance runner who was suspended after a drug test at the
1996 US Olympic trials showed similar results. Slaney has since
been cleared by USA Track &AMP; Field and is free to compete but still
awaits an arbitration hearing by the International Amateur Athletic
Federation, the sport's governing body.
</P>
<P>
   The accepted ratio of testosterone, the male sex hormone, to
epitestosterone, which has no known function, is 6-1; anything
above that t/e ratio is considered to indicate the possible use of
testosterone as a performance-enhancing anabolic steroid.
</P>
<P>
   However, about one in 2,000 people have a naturally higher
ratio, and because most research has been conducted on men, the
reliability of using the ratio as a barometer of drug use in women
has come into question.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ratio as a test has problems,'' said Dr. Gary I. Wadler,
an associate professor of medicine at New York University School of
Medicine and lead author of the textbook ``Drugs and the Athlete.''
Among other factors, he said, ``The menstrual cycle may influence
t/e ratios.''
</P>
<P>
   In drug tests of urine, two samples are always taken. According
to a statement by the German federation, Pippig's A and B samples
both showed an abnormal t/e ratio. In addition to the routine
testing, Pippig's B sample was reportedly subjected to a carbon
isotope test that, although relatively new, is thought to be more
reliable because it is purported to distinguish between
testosterone that is natural and testosterone that is introduced
into the body. Therefore, issues such as the menstrual cycle or use
of birth control would be mitigated.
</P>
<P>
   In a Runner's World magazine story in 1991, Pippig acknowledged
that she had briefly used performance-enhancing substances while
competing for the former East Germany in the 1980s. In interviews
since then, however, she and her coach/companion, Dieter Hogen,
have stressed their devotion to natural competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mary (Slaney) was exonerated, and I have confidence Uta will
be also,'' said Ratcliffe. ``But once she is tainted with this,
it's hard to dispel.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
