<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5067 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSE-IMPEACH-BOS &LR;      10-07 1642
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSE-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON APPEALS TO CONSCIENCE OF LAWMAKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER AND BRIAN MCGRORY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With no hope of preventing a formal impeachment
inquiry, President Clinton issued a last-minute appeal for House
members to cast ``a vote of principle and conscience'' today on
whether to launch the historic proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers, bracing for what many declared the most momentous
vote of their careers, said they would honor Clinton's plea, but
warned that he could be disappointed by the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   By many accounts, a Republican plan for a wide-ranging,
open-ended inquiry is expected to pass the House today with support
from nearly 275 or more of the chamber's 435 members, including a
sizable number of Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   But even as Clinton expressed resignation at the bleakness of
his situation, Vice President Al Gore, Hillary Rodham Clinton and
House Democratic leaders joined him in a final, low-key effort to
contain the damage by swaying as many Democrats as possible to snub
the GOP plan in favor of a Democratic proposal for a narrower
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   In either case, Clinton would be the first president since
Richard M. Nixon in 1974 and second since Andrew Johnson in 1868 to
be subjected to an impeachment ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to others to decide what happens to me,'' Clinton told
reporters in the Oval Office, ``and ultimately it's going to be up
to the American people to make a clear statement there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Republican impeachment plan calls for the House Judiciary
Committee to investigate Clinton on charges of perjury, witness
tampering and obstruction of justice stemming from his liaisons in
the Oval Office with former White House intern Monica S. Lewinsky.
The proposal also would permit the panel to examine other matters,
such as the alleged misuse of confidential FBI files by White House
political operatives.
</P>
<P>
   The committee would be bound by no deadline, although the
chairman, Representative Henry J. Hyde of Illinois, has said he
hopes to complete the inquiry by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic alternative would set Dec. 31 as a formal
deadline. It also would limit the inquiry's scope to the Lewinsky
matter, and the Judiciary Committee could open a full investigation
of the scandal only if it first determined the allegations
constitute legitimate grounds for impeachment if they are proven.
</P>
<P>
   While the 228 House Republicans were virtually unified behind
the GOP impeachment plan, their 206 Democratic counterparts
remained in some turmoil. Most House Democrats are poised to oppose
the GOP plan, but at least 40 to 50 moderates and conservatives are
expected to break party ranks. And a dozen or more liberals plan to
vote against both measures because they believe Clinton's actions
do not warrant impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   All 10 House Democrats from Massachusetts plan to support the
Democratic alternative for impeachment proceedings.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly every House member, however, the vote carries
potential consequences both for the November elections and the
lawmaker's legacy. A generation after Nixon's resignation, for
example, historians are still scrutinizing the actions of House
members who participated in the impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are wrestling with what is the right way to do this,''
said the House Minority Leader Richard A. Gephardt of Missouri,
after a fractious meeting of House Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   One of the leading Democratic defectors, Representative James P.
Moran of Virginia, expressed concern as he nervously approached the
landmark vote. A longtime Clinton ally, Moran said he will break
ranks and support the Republican-sponsored impeachment inquiry
because he believes it will be in the best interest of the
Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   ``The endgame for Democrats should be regaining control of the
House,'' said Moran, a moderate from a district in northern
Virginia. ``But if the November elections are a referendum on the
president's conduct, we lose. And there is a high likelihood they
could become a referendum if we all vote as a bloc against the
inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   Moran added, ``I'm concerned, because if you get too out of step
with your constituency, you might have to look for another
career.''
</P>
<P>
   In another setback for the White House, Representative Tim
Roemer, a moderate Democrat from a swing district in Indiana, said
he will vote for the Republican plan because he believes Clinton's
conduct warrants a full investigation to determine whether it was
``very reckless, immoral and private behavior, or a threat to the
Constitution and therefor an impeachable offense.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This cannot be a vote to protect the president of your own
party,'' Roemer said. ``It has to be a vote that serves your
country and your conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's strongest supporters are liberals such as
Represenative Jose E. Serrano, a New York Democrat who was
re-elected in 1996 with 97 percent of the vote in his
overwhelmingly black and Hispanic district. ``My constituents are
angry, and they are saying, `Drop all of this now, or we are coming
after you,' '' Serrano said. ``I've never heard my constituents
talk to me like that.''
</P>
<P>
   At the White House, officials said publicly and privately there
was no war room on the eve of the vote, no aggressive campaign to
influence Democratic members.
</P>
<P>
   One senior White House official said aides have retreated from
any significant lobbying effort out of the realization that they
could not win and the hope that a Republican victory will prove not
only hollow, but self-destructive.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Clinton and his wife
were not offering any incentive _ fund-raising help, for example _
to sway undecided members to vote against the Republican proposal.
``We believe it is not proper for us, despite what others may
report about what we're doing, to aggressively try to impact or
lobby people on this,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Clinton, at a morning photo opportunity with the prime
minister of Hungary, said he had already returned, or planned to,
what he described as ``a large number of calls from House
members.'' Later in the day, Lockhart placed that number at ``a
handful.''
</P>
<P>
   As Clinton spoke publicly, behind the scenes, Mrs. Clinton
rejected overtures from a group of freshmen Democrats who wanted
the president to publicly acknowledge that the House would approve
the Republican plan and to effectively release Democrats to cross
party lines, according to officials familiar with the meeting. The
appeal came in a meeting on the legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some interchange about other ideas the White House
could pursue about the vote, like acknowledging this would pass and
getting in front of it and geting this over with,'' said an
official.
</P>
<P>
   Such an approach, though, was flatly rejected. ``She made clear
she thought the Democratic alternative that puts the standards
first was the right way to proceed,'' said Marsha Berry, Mrs.
Clinton's spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, White House aides called key Hill Democrats with a
fresh batch of poll numbers that show public disapproval for a
lengthy hearing. ``Everyone is calling old friends,'' said Lynn
Cutler, a deputy director of intergovernmental affairs at the White
House. ``We're all doing that. I don't think that's such an
astounding thing. No one's muscling anyone. More of the calls are
asking `Where is your head at, what are you thinking about, could
you support the Democratic alternative?'''
</P>
<P>
   As for the White House seeking support in the Senate, the
president received some ``friendly advice'' from Senator Robert C.
Byrd, a West Virginia Democrat: ``Don't tamper with this jury.'' If
the House recommends Clinton's impeachment, the Senate would sit as
the jury in an impeachment trial.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Democrats on the Judiciary Committee were touting the
merits of the Democratic alternative to their colleagues.
Representative William D. Delahunt of Massachusetts sent a letter
to House members pushing for the alternative, which he said
protected Clinton's constitutional rights by calling for a
preliminary inquiry of the charges lodged by the independent
counsel, Kenneth W. Starr, before the Judiciary Committee proceeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we shirk that duty, we will have turned the Independent
Counsel Statute into a political weapon with an automatic trigger,
a weapon aimed at every future president,'' Delahunt wrote.
</P>
<P>
   A skirmish also broke out Wednesday over the procedures
surrounding today's votes. Because the GOP plan is a privileged
resolution, House rules call for debate over the measure to be
limited to an hour. And the rules provide no time to debate the
Democratic alternative, which will be voted on as a motion to send
the GOP plan back to the Judiciary Committee with instructions to
adopt the guidelines in the Democratic plan.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat who
serves on the Judiciary Committee, called the one-hour debate limit
``unconscionable,'' ``inexcusable'' and ``indefensible'' for a
matter of such import.
</P>
<P>
   He called on Republican leaders ``to come to their senses'' and
extend the debate. ``We have to do something to bring some sanity
to this process,'' Meehan said.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Stratman, a spokesman for Hyde, said Republican leaders
would agree to extend the debate to ``a reasonable length,'' such
as three or four hours. However, the deal would require unanimous
approval from all 435 House members.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Starr responded to an inquiry from the Judiciary Committee
Wednesday by informing the panel he continues to investigate
matters involving Clinton unrelated to Lewinsky. He did not rule
out forwarding the commmittee additional allegations, which could
lead to an expansion of the impeachment inquiry under GOP plan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
