<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLCS-AARON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AARON LAUDS MCGWIRE, SOSA EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The greatest home run hitter in major league history
tipped his cap Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Aaron, now a senior vice president for the Atlanta Braves,
had nothing but praise for Mark McGwire of the St. Louis Cardinals
and Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs, who staged the home run derby
of the century, hitting 70 and 66, respectively, as they shattered
Roger Maris's 37-year-old record of 61. Aaron also applauded the
man they beat and urged Maris's selection for the Baseball Hall of
Fame in Cooperstown, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they keep hitting 70 home runs in a season,'' said Aaron,
who holds the career record of 755, ``they're going to catch me in
a hurry. In fact, they're going to catch a lot of people. To me,
one of the greatest things ever to happen was just to have this
home run derby. I didn't have a favorite. I just knew it was good
for baseball. As far as I'm concerned, the best man won.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have a commissioner, and the derby put that on the
back page as well as the things that were happening in Washington.
Baseball did a lot to get people to think positive about
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron, who hit his career high of 47 homer for the Braves in
1970, said that in his opinion, expansion was a huge factor in the
big individual numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an expansion season, things can work against you,'' he
said. ``Pitching is going to be thin. But for somebody to have 60,
65, 70 home runs, no matter if it's thin or not, means the hitter
had a very good season. I hadn't noticed it, but Duke Snider told
me the baseball that was used this year was wound very tight. You
had guys hitting home runs who really weren't supposed to be
capable of hitting home runs. I can't say that's the reason. I
don't have to face the pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said that if he were a member of the Hall of Fame Veterans
Committee, he would vote for Maris.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roger Maris was a very good ballplayer,'' he said. ``Almost
everywhere he went, the teams he played for won championships (the
Yankees and St. Louis). I know he had only one great year and you
have to go beyond that. If I was voting, I would have to say, yes,
he belongs in the Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Aaron said McGwire, who has 457 home runs, is a long shot to
break his record. The Cardinals star, now 34, lost several prime
years to injuries. Aaron thinks his main challenger will be Ken
Griffey of Seattle, who hit 56 homers this year and has 350 for his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a possibility that the kid can do it if he stays
focused and healthy,'' said Aaron. ``He's hit over 50 the last two
seasons. I set my record and never hit more than 47. He's very good
and plays in a good home run park. I think he has an excellent
chance of hitting a lot of home runs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
