<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0400 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5075 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NH-KERRY-BOS &LR;      10-07 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NH-KERRY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEMOCRATS IN LARGEST N.H. CITY TO SHUN KERRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOT LEHIGH  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As US Senator John F. Kerry prepares to venture to New Hampshire
to test the presidential waters, the Manchester Democratic City
Committee wants to make one thing clear: Kerry will get no hearing
from them.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, committee members, who charge Kerry has twice committed
to speak at their events only to leave them in the lurch at the
last minute, have passed a motion against offering any further
invitations to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a vote not to allow him any hospitality,'' said
chairman Raymond Buckley, a Democratic state representative from
Manchester. ``In all my years of being involved, I have never, ever
had somebody who was a prospective candidate for president treat
New Hampshire people like this,''
</P>
<P>
   Adds John Gross, the committee's vice president: ``The feeling
is that we were shunned.''
</P>
<P>
   Not so, says Lisa Mead, Kerry's state director, who Wednesday
blamed the mess on poor work by Kerry staffers. ``It was an
inexperienced staff, and the invitation was clearly mishandled from
the beginning,'' Mead said. ``The senator is sorry for that and I
am sorry for that.'' Still, Mead insisted that Kerry had never
actually committed to either event.
</P>
<P>
   That's not the way Buckley, widely credited with rebuilding and
re-energizing the Manchester Democratic City Committee, tells it.
He says Kerry's staff first accepted an invitation to speak at a
city committee fundraiser to honor a long-time Manchester public
official on Saturday, March 14.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been told he would tentatively be coming, so we didn't
invite anyone else,'' said Buckley, who said the commitment was
firm enough that Kerry's staff was getting directions and making
arrangements to bring people from Boston to hear Kerry's speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few days before the event, we found out that he had decided
not to come,'' relates Buckley, who said the committee, suddenly
left without a guest of honor, had to scramble to put together a
call from Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Buckley says his next encounter with Kerry came at a St.
Patrick's Day event at the White House, where, he says, Kerry
apologized for not having made the Manchester fundraiser. Buckley
then told Kerry that the Manchester Democrats -- the state's
largest city committee -- were planning a June 19 fundraiser, and
asked the senator if he would be the guest of honor at that.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `That sounds fantastic, I definitely want to go, work
it out with my staff,' '' said Buckley, who said he proceeded to
talk to top Kerry staffers in both Boston and Washington, who told
him Kerry would come.
</P>
<P>
   Wary about his previous experience, Buckley says, he gave Kerry
staffers a drop-dead date by which Kerry would have to cancel.
According to Buckley, that day passed with no cancellation from
Kerry.
</P>
<P>
   But five days later, on the very day the newsletter containing
the invitations were going out to 1100 Manchester Democrats,
Buckley says, Kerry's staff called to say that Kerry wouldn't be
attended.
</P>
<P>
   That left the committee to prevail upon US Senator Robert Kerrey
(D-Nebraska) to fill in at the last minute -- and to mail another
notice to its members apprising them of the change.
</P>
<P>
   And, says Buckley, it left Manchester Democrats so angry at
Kerry that at their June meeting, the group of about 80
overwhelming voted not to extend any further invitations to Kerry
or to host him if he comes to Manchester.
</P>
<P>
   ``It left a real bad taste in our mouth when it comes to dealing
with Senator Kerry,'' said Buckley. ``It became a personal insult
to the people we were honoring.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those people was former Democratic City Committee member
C. Arthur Sousy. His daughter, Donna Soucy, a committee member and
a former legislator and Manchester alderman, agreed with Buckley
that committee members thought they had a firm commitment from
Kerry, and felt slighted as a result.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are very mad at him and very disappointed that he is
coming back up here, but has made no effort whatsoever to mend
fences,'' said Soucy.
</P>
<P>
   As the Globe reported Wednesday, Kerry has made plans for to
spend Oct. 23 in New Hampshire, raising money for Democrats there,
teaching a university class, meeting with activists, and testing
the presidential waters.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Mead stressed that Kerry was indeed apologetic. ``It
was a misunderstanding, we regret that, and hopefully we can start
anew,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But at the New Hampshire Democratic Party, chairman Jeff
Woodburn accused the Manchester Democrats of having taken ``a
short-sighted and petty'' stand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to be welcoming of any Democratic candidate who wants
to visit our state,'' said Woodburn. ``The last I knew, no one
needed an invitation from Ray Buckley to visit Manchester.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
