<SLUG> BC-SCALLOPS-ABUNDANT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCALLOPS CROWDING SEABED, RESEARCHERS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT ALLEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Scallops have grown so fat and abundant in the part of
Georges Bank closed to fishing that some appear to be dying from
overcrowding, researchers said Wednesday, fueling fishermen's
claims that federal regulators have overstated the fishing crisis,
at least in the scallop industry.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the University of Massachusetts at Dartmouth
said that a new survey of 1,800 square miles of Georges Bank,
closed due to overfishing since 1994, found more than triple the
number of scallops compared to areas being actively fished. In some
spots, many scallops were dead, perhaps a result of overcrowding,
they said, though the scallops could have been killed by predators
or other causes as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's substantially higher quanitities of larger scallops in
the closed area than in the open areas,'' said Brian Rothschild,
director of the university's Center for Marine Science and
Technology, ``At least on Georges Bank, the closed areas and the
open areas ... would sustain a pretty good fishery in perpetuity.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be good news to scallop fishermen who face tightening
limits on fishing from the New England Fishery Management Council.
Federal biologists have argued that too many scallops are being
caught and the region's scallop fleet needs to be sharply reduced
from the current 211 boats.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, fishermen said the survey results prove what they've
been saying all along: there are still plenty of scallops left and
there's no need for more fishing limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fishermen have been going to the council meetings and giving
their input as to there being plenty of (scallop) resource, but ...
we haven't been taken seriously because we're not scientists,''
said Bobby Bruno, a New Bedford-based scalloper who helped on the
study.
</P>
<P>
   But John Boreman at the National Marine Fisheries Service said
it is too soon to conclude that the scallop industry is not in
trouble. He said the closed area survey results, collected under
National Marine Fisheries Service guidance by six commercial
scallop boats, have not even been tabulated yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crisis right now doesn't include that closed area,'' said
Boreman, noting that federal biologists fully expected the scallops
to recover when fishing stopped. He pointed out that the scallopers
harvest 70 to 80 percent of all the scallops annually in open
fishing areas, which would quickly wipe out the Georges Bank
recovery.
</P>
<P>
   The survey _ designed jointly by the University of
Massachusetts, the National Marine Fisheries Service and the
Virginia Institute of Marine Science _ marked the first time
scientists had extensively used fishing boats to study scallops.
Though the National Marine Fisheries Service samples scallops
regularly, scallopers question the accuracy of their gloomy
forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   While not directly contradicting federal findings, the new
survey provides far more detail about the scallops' remarkable
ability to bounce back when fishing stops. While cod populations in
the closed area of Georges Bank have rebounded slowly, individual
scallops in the closed areas are two to three times larger than in
the open fishing grounds, Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   Fishermen, who have watched their catch drop from 17.4 million
pounds in 1997 to 13.2 million last year, want regulators to let
them back in to the closed area immediately.
</P>
<P>
   But National Marine Fisheries Service officials say the
reopening of Georges Bank to scallopers could harm other depleted
marine populations in the once-great fishing ground. During the
experiment in the closed area, scallopers also caught flounder and
other groundfish as they pulled their scallop dredges along the sea
bottom.
</P>
<P>
   A more promising approach, say scallop researchers, might be to
use the information from the survey as the basis for a new system
of regulation where scallop beds are periodically closed to allow
populations to recover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could close some of the open areas and open some of the
closed areas and come up with a rotational scheme for harvesting
these scallops that would be similar to the way forests are
rotated,'' said Rothschild of the University of
Massachusetts/Dartmouth.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
