<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: `EACH FAMILY VOICE MUST BE HEARD'  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Yankee fans split a double-header Wednesday, but
George Steinbrenner lost two.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Yankees lost the argument and the game to the
Cleveland Indians, 4-1, the principal owner and Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani lost in the Bronx County Courthouse up on the Grand
Concourse beyond the Stadium's outfield facade.
</P>
<P>
   In that judicial fortress, state Supreme Court Justice Douglas
McKeon threw Wednesday's best pitch: that a referendum can be on
the Nov. 3 ballot on whether New York City taxpayers want a West
Side stadium in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Peter Vallone, the City Council speaker, suggested
such a referendum a few months ago, Steinbrenner and his political
puppet, the mayor in the Yankee cap and the Yankee jacket, have
opposed it. They fear, understandably, that the public would reject
it.
</P>
<P>
   Court appeals could snarl the situation long enough to keep the
referendum off this year's ballot. But if it's on the ballot, you
can forget about a West Side stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Every baseball fan that wants to keep the Yankees where they are
would vote against it. So would every taxpayer that doesn't want
the city to gift-wrap a $1 billion stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks after the City Council filed a lawsuit against the
mayor's improperly setting a Charter Commission to keep the stadium
issue off the ballot, McKeon Wednesday denied the motion by the
mayor, the Charter Commission and the Board of Elections for a
summary judgment.
</P>
<P>
   In a Sept. 28 proposal, Fernando Ferrer, the Bronx borough
president, offered the most sensible and financially responsible
solution yet _ a $533 million plan to renovate Yankee Stadium, add
120 luxury boxes, ease traffic snarls, create a Metro North
railroad stop behind home plate and redevelop the neighborhood with
a waterfront park, a Yankee Hall of Fame and sports-related stores.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees eventually decide or are forced to remain in a
renovated or new Yankee Stadium, their fans should put a plaque for
Judge McKeon out there in Monument Park in deep left field
alongside those for Babe Ruth, Lou Gehrig, Joe DiMaggio, Mickey
Mantle and so many others.
</P>
<P>
   ``The urgency to find a proposal to blockade the Council's
Yankee Stadium proposal rendered the work of the Commission in 1998
a virtual charade,'' McKeon wrote. ``Perhaps the Council's Yankee
Stadium referendum is part opinion poll motivated by political
considerations. However, Yankee Stadium is uniquely a public
property. And its destiny should be decided by the public.''
</P>
<P>
   McKeon, tall and reddish haired, was born in the Bronx and still
lives in the Pelham Parkway neighborhood. He understands what
Yankee Stadium means to the Bronx and its citizens, and to Yankee
fans everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   As a youngster, the son of a Bronx courthouse officer, he
watched Mantle hit home runs at Yankee Stadium. He saw Ingemar
Johansson knock down Floyd Patterson seven times there in winning
the heavyweight title. He saw the Giants popularize pro football
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``The decision to abandon an athletic stadium involves emotional
and economic factors,'' McKeon wrote. ``Ebbets Field, the Polo
Grounds _ shouldn't the public have the right to say whether Yankee
Stadium meets that same fate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the expenditure of public funds approaching $1 billion is
estimated to build a new stadium on the west side of Manhattan,
does it offend the spirit of the charter to permit the public to
participate in that decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each family, at one time or another, makes a determination
that impacts on its future in a unique and special way. The
purchase of a new home comes to mind, hardly an everyday decision.
For the family of New Yorkers, the decision to construct a new
stadium is akin to the purchase of a new home, for which each voice
in the family must be heard.''
</P>
<P>
   You would think that Steinbrenner, who is always preaching how
the Yankees are a family, would appreciate the judge's ``family''
reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the principal owner had ``no comment'' Wednesday on
McKeon's ruling. Quite simply, he wants a new glitzy stadium on the
West Side or in New Jersey. But the West Side referendum would be
voted down, as a New Jersey referendum was in 1986. And there is no
financing and no site for a stadium in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday you lost, George. Two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
