<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5089 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YANKS-INDIANS-ART-NYT     10-07 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKS-INDIANS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS DEFEAT YANKEES, 4-1, TYING ALCS AT ONE WIN APIECE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
(JT) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Yankees have prided themselves all year on not
taking anything for granted, for playing smart. But Wednesday,
their second baseman, Chuck Knoblauch, allowed a moment of stubborn
frustration to possess him and it cost the Yankees the tiebreaking
run in a 12-inning, 4-1 loss to Cleveland in Game 2 of the American
League Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and Indians, now tied at one game apiece in the
best-of-seven series, will play Game 3 Friday night in Cleveland,
where the Yankees' Andy Pettitte will face the Indians' Bartolo
Colon.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and Indians were tied 1-1 before 57,128 at Yankee
Stadium when Jim Thome singled off Jeff Nelson to open the 12th
inning and was replaced by pinch-runner Enrique Wilson. Travis
Fryman turned to bunt the runner to second and pushed a ball up the
first base line, where the Yankees' first baseman Tino Martinez
fielded it and threw toward first. Knoblauch was covering the bag.
</P>
<P>
   Fryman, however, was running inside the first base line, and
more importantly outside the 3-foot lane that runs the final 45
feet to first base and which batters are required to use while
going to first or risk being called out in the umpire's judgment.
Martinez's throw hit Fryman in the back and the ball rolled behind
first base.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch, sure that Fryman was guilty of interference and would
be called out, stood and pointed to the spot of the alleged
infraction, staring at home plate umpire Ted Hendry. And Knoblauch
stood. And he stood. And he stood.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, meanwhile, rounded second, then rounded third. By the
time Knoblauch finally retrieved the ball and threw home, Wilson
was across the plate with a dive, with the tie-breaking run.
</P>
<P>
   The inning continued. Kenny Lofton eventually hit a two-run
single, increasing the Cleveland lead to 4-1. When Knoblauch was
introduced to bat in the Yankee 12th, he was booed lustily.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, the Yankees don't seem so invincible, tied in the
series, having missed numerous chances to push across the winning
run in the first nine innings; the Yankees went 1-for-12 with
runners in scoring position. Their 11-game winning streak, dating
to the last seven games of the regular season, is over.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland took the lead in the the fourth inning, on David
Justice's home run _ the first time in the Yankees' five postseason
games they had fallen behind. Three innings later, however, Scott
Brosius pulled a two-out double into the left field corner,
enabling Bernie Williams to amble home with the tying run.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and Indians played into the eighth, each side
understanding that one run, one 360-foot journey around the bases,
could settle the outcome. One run would give the Yankees more
confidence, more reason to believe they cannot be beaten. One run
would give the Cleveland Indians reason to believe they can
overcome one of the greatest teams in the last half-century, as
they return home for Game 3, 4 and 5.
</P>
<P>
   With one freakish play in the Cleveland eighth, the Indians
suddenly seemed on the verge of scoring that one run. Omar Vizquel
reached out and fought off a pitch and looped a high pop down the
left field line; Shane Spencer, the left fielder, ran and ran and
ran and dove, but the ball barely eluded him and splashed onto the
white foul line, bouncing past Spencer and into the corner.
</P>
<P>
   By the time Spencer scrambled to his feet, retrieved the ball
and returned it to the infield, Vizquel was standing at third base,
with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Justice was coming to bat, four innings after he had launched
one of David Cone's curveballs over the right-center field wall for
Cleveland's run. Mel Stottlemyre, the Yankees' pitching coach, went
to the mound to discuss the options with Cone. They could walk
Justice intentionally and take their chances with the right-handed
slugger Manny Ramirez. Cone threw three straight balls to Justice,
and it figured they would walk him.
</P>
<P>
   But Cone flipped a curve for a strike, tried another _ and
Justice chopped the ball just in front of home plate. Joe Girardi,
the Yankees' catcher, pounced on the ball, looking back Vizquel at
third and throwing to first. Two out.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez came to the plate against a tiring Cone, who was 113
pitches deep into his day. With a 2-1 count, Cone tried a slider
that spun flatly; Ramirez turned and blasted it high and long and
far foul. Knowing he'd gotten lucky, Cone walked behind the mound,
unhappy. Girardi walked out to visit Cone, to review their options
on the 2-2 pitch.
</P>
<P>
   Cone threw again. Ramirez hit a soft grounder back to Cone, who
grabbed it and gingerly threw the ball to first, an egg toss. Three
outs. Cone took a step toward the dugout, planted his feet and
pumped a fist, like Tiger Woods sinking a 60-foot putt. The gallery
roared. The Yankees and Indians, both even par.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had two out and two on in their eighth, before Tino
Martinez struck out. Tim Raines, leading off the ninth against
Cleveland's Paul Shuey, worked the count to 3-1 before hitting a
high chopper off home plate, sprinting on his 39-year-old legs,
beating the throw to the bag. Homer Bush, the Yankees' pinch-runner
deluxe, replaced Raines and stole second on the next pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But Spencer struck out, failing to advance Bush. Having seen
Brosius come through time and again in the playoffs, the Indians
elected to intentionally walk him and face Girardi. Jorge Posada
pinch-hit for Girardi and skipped a perfect double-play grounder to
second, ending the inning and forcing extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   To that point, the Yankees were 1-for-12 with runners in scoring
position, the Indians 0-for-3.
</P>
<P>
   Cone struggled in the early innings, lacking control of his
slider and trying to find a way through. This is when Cone is at
his best, said Girardi, when he must invent and improvise, a
pinstriped Houdini. Justice hit his home run in the fourth and then
Ramirez walked.
</P>
<P>
   Cone struck out Thome on an inside fastball _ appearing to
benefit from the wide strike zone of the home plate umpire Ted
Hendry _ but Fryman singled. Pitching carefully, Cone walked Brian
Giles, loading the bases. Sandy Alomar reached out and hit a hard
smash toward the right side of the infield, where Martinez knocked
down the ball and flipped to Cone covering first base for the third
out.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Nagy shut out the Yankees for the first six innings,
allowing just three hits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
