<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-TRIBUNAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELGRADE BARS U.N. WAR-CRIMES INVESTIGATORS  (JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MARLISE SIMONS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands _ Yugoslavia has told the war crimes
tribunal here that U.N. investigators will not be allowed to look
into reported war crimes in Kosovo, and it has refused to grant the
visas that the court has requested, tribunal officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the government of President Slobodan
Milosevic had also threatened to close the liaison office of the
tribunal in Belgrade if the court continued to collect evidence on
massacres and other reported war crimes in the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The rebuff to the tribunal was mitigated, however, when
Milosevic, under U.S. pressure, permitted the departure of a man
who says he is a witness to the massacre of ethnic Albanians in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The decision against allowing investigators ``is totally
unacceptable,'' said the deputy prosecutor of the tribunal, Graham
Blewitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will not stop us from what we have a right to do,''
Blewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   If Belgrade persists in banning the investigators, including
those who already have visas, diplomats said, another noisy
confrontation seems unavoidable. The U.N. Security Council, which
created the tribunal to prosecute war crimes in the former
Yugoslavia passed resolutions in March and September to reaffirm
the tribunal's jurisdiction in the Kosovo conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Although Belgrade has refused to recognize the tribunal's
authority, it gradually accepted that investigators could examine
Serbia and Kosovo, because in some instances their investigations
concerned crimes reportedly committed against Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   But tensions came to a head on Friday, when the prosecutor's
staff asked Belgrade why it was delaying four visas that the
tribunal requested more than a month ago. Blewitt said the response
from the foreign ministry in Belgrade was that ``the tribunal has
no jurisdiction to conduct investigations in Kosovo'' and would no
longer be allowed to do so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
