A5093 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOREA-JAPAN-NYT &LR;      10-07 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-JAPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOREAN LEADER, IN JAPAN, URGES HEALING OF OLD WOUNDS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ President Kim Dae-jung of South Korea arrived in Japan
on Wednesday for a long-awaited state visit and immediately called
for a closer partnership and an end to the longstanding tensions
between the neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   At a state dinner Wednesday night, Kim stood up to toast Emperor
Akihito, whose father, Hirohito, presided over Japan for much of
its brutal occupation of the Korean peninsula until the end of
World War II. Avoiding the comments that past South Korean leaders
always made on such occasions about the ``unfortunate past,'' Kim
urged a ``forward-looking partnership.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation surrounding the two countries demands a closer
partnership,'' Kim said. He later added, ``The Korean people and my
administration are willing, open-minded and fully prepared to
exchange and cooperate with our neighbor.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim has called for reconciliation of every kind since he took
office in February, and he has urged that Korea lift the ban on
Japanese music, comics, movies and television programs. That ban is
a measure of the deep hostility to all things Japanese that remains
widespread among Koreans, although the black market in Seoul for
Japanese tapes suggests a bittersweet fascination with Japanese
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese officials, apparently seeing a rare opportunity to mend
ties with their neighbor, seem ready to reciprocate by making an
unusually humble apology for the colonial past.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi is expected to offer the most
contrite formulation yet for a Japanese apology to Korea. The
wording has been under negotiation between the sides for weeks,
which means that it comes as much from committees as from the
heart, but the result apparently will be a more direct official
apology than Japan was ever prepared to make in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Japan and Korea have a long and intertwined history, but Koreans
are still haunted by the Japanese annexation and occupation of the
Korean Peninsula from 1910 to 1945. Japan built roads, schools and
factories, but Koreans were harshly governed and forced to take
Japanese names.
</P>
<P>
   Kim can speak fluent Japanese, but like most Koreans he is
reluctant to use it because of the bitter memories it evokes.
Although in the United States in June, Kim addressed Congress in
English, which he does not speak as well as Japanese, Kim is using
Korean for all his addresses throughout his trip to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in any language a president could scarcely have been more
gracious than Kim was in his toast to Akihito. Kim warmly thanked
Japan for helping during South Korea's economic crisis over the
last year, and his only suggestions that Japan face its past were
veiled in several layers of silk.
</P>
<P>
   ``If our two nations are to succeed in cooperative efforts, we
must first respect each other and open our hearts,'' Kim urged.
</P>
<P>
   Delicately reminding his hosts that many Koreans believe
Japanese society has not yet acknowledged the truth about its past,
Kim added, ``Let us forge a neighborly relationship based on
truthfulness and a cooperative spirit.''
</P>
<P>
   Akihito, whom Kim invited to Korea and who is expected to visit
Seoul in 2001 or 2002, responded with his own expression of regret
about the occupation _ a reference carefully crafted by Japanese
officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of close exchange had a reverse side at one period
when Japan brought great suffering on the people of the Korean
Peninsula,'' Akihito said. ``The deep sorrow that I feel over this
never leaves my memory.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
