<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5096 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JERDE-ARCHITECTURE-AR     10-07 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JERDE-ARCHITECTURE-ART-1000(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CREATURE OF THE GLOBE RESHAPES THE GLOBAL VILLAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mo., Nev., Utah) (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
 By FRANCES ANDERTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Jon Jerde is the Bernini of our time,'' Steve Wynn declared
grandly. And, he continued, ``these are the cathedrals of our time.
This is the future of architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``cathedrals'' touted by Wynn _ a pontiff of the material
world _ are Disneyland, the Mall of America and his own casino
extravaganza, Bellagio, due to open next week in Las Vegas. All
three are landmarks of the trend for fusing architecture, commerce
and fantasy, of which Jerde is a pioneer. Jerde, a self-described
``experiential architect'' in Los Angeles, designed the Mall of
America and, with Wynn's in-house team Atlandia Design, Bellagio.
</P>
<P>
   Bernini, the master of Roman Baroque, might enjoy Jerde's modern
American variant, employing exaggerated color, spatial tricks and
theatricality. Bellagio is one of the few casinos in Las Vegas that
actually looks good in daylight. Solid, three-dimensional, dripping
with landscaped patios and balustraded terraces, it is as charming
and persuasive an Italian idyll as is possible in the shadow of a
looming 36-story, 3,000-room hotel whose gargantuan presence no
amount of scale-reducing applied moldings and friezes can diminish.
</P>
<P>
   At Bellagio, Wynn wanted elegance and romance. Drawing on Lake
Como in Italy and its shore-side town of Bellagio for inspiration,
Jerde's firm, the Jerde Partnership International, planned and
designed a painterly composition of Italianate buildings
surrounding an artificial lake, so richly crafted they could
actually pass for authentic. (Atlandia designed the interiors.)
</P>
<P>
   With Bellagio, Wynn moves his casinos another notch toward the
bourgeois respectability that began with family-friendly glitz at
Treasure Island and the Mirage, and now is culminating in fine art
and architecture at the polite, softly pretty, neon-free new hotel.
Yet Jerde is surprisingly low-key about the project, despite the
fact that his firm spent four years on it.
</P>
<P>
   At his home in Los Angeles, a rustic dwelling in the Santa
Monica Mountains, he explained that Bellagio was ``Steve's
vision.'' It is small fry compared to his Big Idea: the remaking of
cities with entertainment as the core.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Jerde, now 58, recognized that ``the consumption
addiction is what will bring people out and together,'' and he has
made a career of feeding it with his controversial brand of pop
public space.
</P>
<P>
   People who love the messy urbanism of traditional cities may
feel profound discomfort at this apparent repackaging of the urban
realm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Architecture as packaging or playacting, as disengagement from
reality, is a notion whose time, alas, seems to have come,''
mourned Ada Louise Huxtable in her 1997 book, ``The Unreal America:
Architecture and Illusion'' (New Press).
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, Jerde launched his career with Horton Plaza in San
Diego, which wed the conventional suburban mall _ anchoring
department stores, shops and movie houses _ with the specialty
shops, food courts and party ambiance of the quaint festival
centers popularized by the Rouse marketplaces in the '70s. This
six-block profusion of cheap and cheerful buildings and public
spaces helped turn around the fortunes of downtown San Diego. It
also helped to spawn the now ubiquitous ``urban entertainment
center,'' promoted by many developers and city planners as the
panacea for declining downtowns, from Times Square to Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Jerde (pronounced JER-dee) and a team of Los Angeles
designers and architects created Citywalk, an upbeat distillation
of Los Angeles' architectural and graphic landmarks into an
artificial street at the Universal City studios and theme park.
Herbert Muschamp, the New York Times' architecture critic, at its
opening soon after the Los Angeles riots, wrote that with its
``zippy collage of signs and storefronts,'' Citywalk ``is a shiny
new wheel in the pop machine that boosts the city's rhythm.'' He
added that its view ``of harmonized diversity is a hokey Hollywood
ending. Would a sad ending be better?''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after, at the invitation of Wynn, the Jerde firm designed
the ``Fremont Street Experience,'' a transformation of Las Vegas'
downtown main street into a covered ``destination.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Jerde completed Canal City, a futuristic mall
with hotels, shops and explosive fountains in a canyon of buildings
snaking along a newly created canal in a disused industrial area in
Fukuoka, Japan.
</P>
<P>
   While conceptually ambitious, these projects are essentially
privately owned pedestrian shopping malls. Next stop is real
city-making: 24-hour, multi-block, private and public developments
comprising shops, entertainment, houses, offices and, in some
cases, traffic. The Jerde group has such projects underway in
Japan, Taiwan and Warsaw as well as in Kansas City, Mo., and Salt
Lake City. ``We've got some lulus,'' Jerde said, with childlike
excitement. ``All of these middle American cities need it,'' he
added, referring to his brand of urban renewal, ``because they are
the ones with the least to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Jerde was sitting in the garden of his home, the Stone House,
eagerly awaiting the return from school of a young son, the progeny
of his fourth marriage. The house where he lives with his wife,
Janice Ambry, a residential architect, is dark, eccentric, suffused
with the odor of wood floors and paneling.
</P>
<P>
   Built over two decades with raw stone quarried from the
property, it is part Tyrolean hut, part cave, more somber than
Jerde's trademark festive malls, and less high-tech _ materials are
all natural, fireplaces are the only source of heat and there isn't
a computer in sight. But in other ways, it reflects his work, with
its textured surfaces, decorative furnishings and potpourri of
objects _ Buddhas' heads, a silk mandala, a Maori mask, intricate
carved wood columns from Nepal, an Eames chair _ all cast in high
relief by theatrical lighting.
</P>
<P>
   In the garden, behind Jerde, is a stone fireplace he built _ the
``spite-wall'' he cheerfully calls it _ to separate himself from
his third wife, who, on leaving him, took up residence in a house
they owned next door. Like the house, the fireplace appears to have
emerged from the ground; together they embody Jerde's paradoxical
architectural goal: to imbue commercial, modern environments with a
sense of the organic, of having been accreted over time.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Both gregarious and a loner, Jerde considers himself a creature
of the globe: ``I have never had any particular allegiance to any
place, state, town or neighborhood,'' he said. He is the only child
of peripatetic parents, his father a migrant oil-field worker.
``Our family was called oil-field trash,'' he remembers. ``We just
blew into town and we blew out of town.''
</P>
<P>
   On moving to Southern California, he says, he found ``a
wonderful warmness and sense of belonging amongst anonymous folks''
at the Long Beach Pike, an early theme park in Long Beach. He went
on to train as an architect, winning a travel scholarship to
Europe, where he discovered the Italian hill towns, ``an
architecture by nobody and everybody at the same time.''
</P>
<P>
   To simulate this architecture of anonymous communality, Jerde
works ``co-creatively'' on projects with multi-disciplinary teams,
layering on references to local and global, man-made and natural
sources. His projects are not themed, he contends, but rather
capture the ``essence'' of their environments.
</P>
<P>
   Jerde is a trim man with a ruddy complexion, sandy hair and
sharp eyes, who can be an extremely engaging advocate for his
mission. But not everyone is sold.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Cantrell, the architectural writer at The Kansas City
Star, last year attacked Jerde's proposal for reinvigorating the
Kansas City downtown with streetscapes made of existing facades and
what he calls ``synchronous'' new buildings. ``For all the lofty
verbiage,'' Cantrell wrote, `` Jerde is proposing not real
architecture but a collage of facadectomies,'' adding, ``It's a
synthetic jumble, heavy on circa-1900 nostalgia, with an overlay of
shopping-mall glitz.''
</P>
<P>
   Where critics bemoan the commercialization and privatization of
civic space that his work represents, Jerde argues that ``the
public sector stopped making public space a long time ago.''
</P>
<P>
   His admirers include the Los Angeles architect Craig Hodgetts.
``Jon Jerde,'' Hodgetts writes in a forthcoming book, ``is one of
that breed of innovative architects whose contagious vision
redefines an era.'' He adds, ``His designs would, quite frankly, be
unthinkable in a world without television, modems, global brands.''
</P>
<P>
   With movie houses anchoring retail developments, and tricks of
movie-making informing his undeniably successful designs, Jerde has
become impossible to ignore. The Pritzker Prize-winning architect
Arata Isozaki has said that Frank Gehry's Guggenheim Museum in
Bilbao, Spain, and Jon Jerde's Canal City in Fukuoka, Isozaki's
birthplace, are the two most important buildings created in the
last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Norman Klein, a cultural critic and professor at the California
Institute of the Arts, believes that Jerde's work is significant
because it represents ``a transition from one notion of urban space
to another'' _ what he calls the ``metropolitan suburb.''
</P>
<P>
   Given a disappearing tax base, these kinds of malls may be a
necessity to city managers, Klein said, arguing that these
cityscapes are reflections of a latter-day Baroque mercantile
civilization, with corporations rather than popes and aristocrats
for clients.
</P>
<P>
   With his cinematic environments, Jerde's creations ``provide a
kind of camouflage under which large franchise companies can
pretend to be local,'' Klein said.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps the Bernini comparison is apt, in another way.
Jerde's work just may express the reality of the global economy, of
a shrunken public sector, from which people may want to run. But
they cannot hide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
