<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BASELINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONTROVERSIAL SACRIFICE BUNT LEADS TO YANKEES' DOWNFALL  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For six months, baseball lived, indeed thrived, on
offense. The Mark and Sammy show epitomized the theme of the season
and captivated the country. Well, this is the postseason, and it's
the pitchers' turn.
</P>
<P>
   In its most recent display of dominance, pitching ruled
Wednesday as the Cleveland Indians defeated the Yankees, 4-1, and
evened the American League Championship Series at one game each. If
home field advantage means anything, the Indians grabbed another
edge because the next three games will be played at Jacobs Field in
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The pitching on both sides was so stingy Wednesday that the
winning run scored on a play that did not involve a hit or even a
ball that was hit beyond the infield. The game-deciding play
involved a bunt, a thrown ball, a runner running where he's not
supposed to run and a mental lapse _ no, a boneheaded blunder _ by
an infielder who defied a basic rule of baseball. Instead of
following the bouncing ball, Chuck Knoblauch ignored it and decided
instead to play umpire. The only problem was the full complement of
umpires was already on the field, and they didn't ask for
Knoblauch's help.
</P>
<P>
   But for terrifically clutch pitching by David Cone in the eighth
inning, the Indians might have won the game in the regulation nine
innings. At the same time, it was outstanding pitching by
Cleveland's starter, Charles Nagy, and a complement of six
relievers that brought the Yankees back to earth and the Indians
into the 1-1 tie.
</P>
<P>
   Cone allowed only a home run by David Justice in his eight
innings of work. The Indians threatened to score at least one more
run in the eighth, but Cone snuffed out that possibility. With one
out, Omar Vizquel sliced a fly ball along the left field line, and
it eluded the diving effort of Shane Spencer, landing no more than
an inch in fair territory. It bounced toward the fence, and Vizquel
wound up at third with a triple.
</P>
<P>
   Justice and Manny Ramirez, the Indians' best hitters, were the
next two batters, but combined they didn't hit the ball 120 feet
and both were out. Justice topped the ball in front of the plate,
and Joe Girardi pounced on it and threw him out. Then Ramirez hit a
weak grounder back to the mound, and Cone threw him out.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had tied the game the previous inning, finally
getting to Nagy for a run on a two-out double by Scott Brosius. But
Steve Reed relieved Nagy and, with runners at second and third,
induced Girardi to ground back to him for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   The game remained 1-1 until the 12th inning. Jim Thome, who had
taken called strikes three times earlier in the game, led off the
inning by rapping a single to left field. Travis Fryman then bunted
the ball hard toward first base, and first baseman Tino Martinez,
fielded the ball.
</P>
<P>
   He turned and threw to first, but the ball hit the 7 on Fryman's
back and bounded beyond first onto the dirt part of the infield.
Knoblauch, the second baseman, was covering first, but he did not
retrieve the ball. Instead he stood at first pointing at where he
thought Fryman had run from home to first.
</P>
<P>
   As television replays unequivocally showed, Fryman had run
inside the base line. The rule says the runner has to run in a lane
defined by the base line and a white line to the right of the base
line. If an umpire believes the runner has run to the left of the
base line, he is supposed to call him out for interfering with the
throw.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Hendry, the home plate umpire, made no such call.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gave me some kind of reasoning that he had to get out of
those restraining lines to touch the base and I agreed,'' said Joe
Torre, the Yankees' manager, who had disputed the call. ``But he
was never in the restraining lines. It was so blatant. It was a
terrible call. For one guy to say what he saw and for the other
guys to swear by it, and meanwhile you have it on video ...''
</P>
<P>
   Could it be considered a judgment call,'' Torre was asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' he said, ``not when you know the video is going
to embarrass you. He was on the grass all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed the television replays showed that every step of the way
Fryman's feet landed on the grass, which is to the left of the base
line.
</P>
<P>
   All right, even if Hendry was wrong, what was Knoblauch doing?
</P>
<P>
   ``He was arguing with the umpire,'' Torre said. ``You have to
get the ball and then argue. I think he was just shocked.''
</P>
<P>
   As the ball lay untouched on the infield dirt, Enrique Wilson,
running for Thome, raced all the way home with the tie-breaking
run. Fryman reached third and later scored on Kenny Lofton's
two-run single.
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees scoring only one run, the game was the seventh
of the postseason in which one team scored only one run. There have
been two shutouts, both by the Yankees, and seven times teams have
scored two runs, five times in winning circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   The pitchers in this game had help from Hendry's ball and strike
calls. Torre didn't think much of those either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The balls and strikes stunk,'' he said, ``but they stunk for
both sides. I've got a bunch of pictures in my pocket. You couldn't
reach some of those pitches with a bamboo stick.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
