<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIBIAS-SPENDING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEDERAL ANTI-BIAS SPENDING IS INADEQUATE, GROUPS SAY
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By STEVEN A. HOLMES   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ With President Clinton and his advisory board on
race recommending sharp increases in programs to enforce
anti-discrimination laws, civil rights groups are expressing
disappointment that Congress has approved only modest increases for
agencies like the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent last week to House Republican and Democratic
leaders, the Leadership Conference on Civil Rights criticized
lawmakers for not allocating more money for federal agencies that
enforce laws against discrimination in employment, housing,
education and public accommodations.
</P>
<P>
   ``For agencies that are already underbudgeted and understaffed _
and in some cases have been criticized by Congress for failing to
enforce the laws _ these inadequate appropriations will have a
cumulative and devastating effect, not only on the agencies'
efforts, but on the intended beneficiaries as well,'' the letter
said.
</P>
<P>
   The letter was signed by the heads of several civil rights
organizations; among them were Kweisi Mfume of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, Patricia Ireland
of the National Organization for Women, Raul Yzaguirre of the
National Council of La Raza and Horace Deets of the American
Association of Retired Persons.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding federal anti-discrimination efforts was one of the
first suggestions made by the advisory board for Clinton's
initiative on race. The seven-member panel made that recommendation
at its November 1997 meeting in College Park, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later, the Clinton administration announced that it
was seeking an $86 million increase in financing for the Equal
Employment Opportunity Commission, the fair housing program in the
Department of Housing and Urban Development, the civil rights
division of the Department of Justice and other agencies that
investigate complaints of bias.
</P>
<P>
   So far, spending bills approved by the House and the Senate have
fallen short of the administration's request. For example, the
House has passed a $19 million increase and the Senate an $11.6
million rise in spending for the EEOC. The administration sought a
$37 million increase.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Congress approved a $10 million increase in the
budget for Housing Department's fair-housing efforts, less than
half of the $22 million increase the administration had wanted.
</P>
<P>
   Liberal civil rights leaders say Congress' unwillingness to
allocate more money to federal anti-discrimination programs is
hypocritical since many Republican lawmakers who oppose affirmative
action say what is needed is vigorous enforcement of civil rights
laws, rather than the extension of preferences to minorities and
women.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
