<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0414 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 21:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5104 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS08-COX     10-07 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS08-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Today's House vote divides Democrats
 &HT;    By Rebecca Carr
 &HT;    and Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of today's vote to let the House of
Representatives open only the third presidential impeachment
inquiry ever, Rep. John Lewis of Georgia drew a line in the sand
with his own party leaders, illustrating how difficult it has been
for Democrats to reach a consensus on the historic issue.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the Democrats' chief deputy whip, refused to help party
leaders garner support for a measure that would limit the scope and
duration of any future investigation of President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he could not in ``good conscience'' vote for such a
measure because even the Democratic proposal goes too far in
punishing the president for lying about his affair with Monica
Lewinsky, a former White House intern.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will live to regret what we are about to do here,'' said
Lewis, who said he came to his decision after knocking on doors in
Atlanta and holding an ``executive session'' with himself. ``We do
not have the right to overturn the election of President Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the day, House Minority Leader Richard Gephardt of
Missouri and Minority Whip David Bonior of Michigan met with fellow
Democrats to push an alternative to the Republican call for an
open-ended impeachment inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   And there was a hint Wednesday of just how open-ended that
inquiry could be.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter sent to the House Judiciary Committee, independent
counsel Kenneth Starr said ``matters continue to be under active
investigation and review by this office.''
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Starr wrote in his letter, ``I cannot foreclose the
possibility of providing the House of Representatives with
additional substantial and credible information arising from those
investigations that President William Jefferson Clinton committed
acts that may constitute grounds for an impeach- ment.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, Democrats were divided into three camps.
Some, like Lewis, oppose any impeachment inquiry at all. Others
support the Republican resolution. Others back the Democratic
alternative to limit the probe.
</P>
<P>
   The division among Democrats contrasted sharply with an unusual
unity among Republicans, who are strongly endorsing the measure
recommended by the House Judiciary Committee in a 21-16 party-line
vote Monday.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich (R-Ga.) probably will preside over
today's vote, which is expected to take place at 11 a.m. following
one hour of debate. Democrats will be allowed to show their disdain
for the Republican measure in a procedural vote, but they will not
be given a chance to amend the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution closely resembles the impeachment inquiry against
former President Nixon approved by the House in 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich predicted bipartisan support for the resolution, which
calls on the House to investigate Starr's allegations that the
president committed perjury, obstructed justice and abused his
presidential powers in concealing his affair with Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that 420 out of 435, 430 out of 435 members will
vote in one form or another to move forward,'' Gingrich said. ``I
think that's an amazingly unanimous agreement.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite a White House campaign to limit the inquiry and to
entice members to support a Democratic alternative, President
Clinton made an effort to distance himself from that effort on
Wednesday. Lawmakers should cast ``a vote of principle and
conscience,'' he said, on whether to approve the impeachment
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to others to decide what happens to me and ultimately
it's going to be up to the American people to make a clear
statement there,'' Clinton told reporters. ``More important than
anything else to me is they do the people's work and then let the
people decide where we go from here.''
</P>
<P>
   To that, Sen. Robert Byrd, senior Democrat from West Virginia,
offered some advice to the White House: ``Don't tamper with this
jury.''
</P>
<P>
   After a House Democratic caucus, it was clear that some
Democrats _ especially conservatives and those in tough re-election
races _ would vote for the Republican resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans in the Georgia delegation were squarely behind
the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Democratic Rep. Sanford Bishop said that he was still
unsure how he would vote. His constituents represent the entire
spectrum of thinking on the scandal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm hearing a lot of comments about this back in the
district,'' Bishop said. ``Basically, a lot of people think the
president did wrong in lying, but they want him to move on issues
like terrorism, the economy and health care. They think he should
be punished, but they are not sure if impeachment is the right form
of punishment.''
</P>
<P>
   And fellow Georgia Democrat Rep. Cynthia McKinney was quiet on
how she would vote.
</P>
<P>
   But many Democrats said they would deliver a unified front today
by voting for a more limited inquiry -- even though it is destined
to fail because of the Republican majority in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Moran (D-Va.) told a morning meeting of the Democratic
caucus he would vote for the Republican proposal after the
Democratic motion fails. Moran said he expected that three dozen of
his colleagues would follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the vote represents a partisan split, then the November
election is likely to be a referendum on the president,'' Moran
said. ``We shouldn't be afraid of the process; it's an opportunity
for the president to acquit himself.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans would like to pile up a bipartisan showing similar
to the 363-63 vote Sept. 11 to release Starr's allegations of
impeachable offenses.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
