<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 21:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5105 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TA     10-07 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANBY-THEATER-ART-2TAKES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHLY INTOXICATING WIT, SERVED STRAIGHT UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo of Everett Quinn is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
(888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11)  
 (af)  
 By VINCENT CANBY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Cairo! ... Cairo! ...'' cries the bewildered Egyptian
princess to Lord Edgar Hillcrest, the dim archeologist who has
invaded her tomb and brought her back to life after 3,500 years.
</P>
<P>
   A small world, you might think, recalling ``To Moscow, to
Moscow, to Moscow!'' and those three weepy sisters from another,
far later time and less exotic place. Yet the princess isn't
longing for the intellectual stimulus of a city that didn't even
exist when she was mummified; she is struggling to remember the
word _ and it's right on the tip of her tongue _ for the type of
doctor who treats bad backs. She finally locates the two missing
syllables: ``... practor!''
</P>
<P>
   With such irresistible gags, and with wizard performances by
Everett Quinton and Stephen DeRosa, who play all eight roles
(sometimes two simultaneously), ``The Mystery of Irma Vep,''
Charles Ludlam's 1984 Off Broadway hit, has become some kind of
sneaky all-American classic. The revival, which is at the Westside
Theater, should run as long as the actors can maintain their
breathtaking energy level.
</P>
<P>
   The director is Quinton, who costarred with Ludlam in the
original production and who, after the death of his companion and
mentor in 1987, succeeded him as the artistic director of the
Ridiculous Theatrical Company. Never having seen any Ludlam
productions, I have no idea how the Quinton work compares. From
what I have seen in the last five years, however, it is clear that
clowning of a proud and original order continues to evolve under
the direction of Quinton.
</P>
<P>
   Not all of his work has been equally successful. There was a
severely cut-down version of ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' that
didn't know whether or not it wanted to be funny. Yet there were
also a hysterically comic sendup of ``Carmen,'' with the
knobby-kneed Quinton playing the title role, often with a
long-stemmed rose clenched between two rows of numerous teeth, and
``Movieland,'' a crowd-pleasing, one-man extravaganza with Quinton
as your generic camp movie goddess.
</P>
<P>
   The production that has haunted me the most, however, is
``Phedre,'' which Quinton played more or less straight. It made
most members of the audience, who had come to roar with laughter,
increasingly uncomfortable, which is the way I feel when Robin
Williams plays straight-from-the-heart damp-eyed sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   But Quinton is something quite other: a post-modern Groucho Marx
who challenges his audience, not with insults but with a whoopee
cushion full of Racine. His Phedre wasn't a camp grotesque. She was
a doomed queen who looked like a truck driver in drag, whose
presentation of the lines was such that you heard every one of them
as if for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   This was burlesque on behalf of the kind of high culture most
post-modernists couldn't care less about. The performance was
difficult to characterize, other than it was an extremely strange
and brave occasion.
</P>
<P>
   The traditions of the Ridiculous Theatrical Company, which has
not had a recent production after losing its lease on its Greenwich
Village playhouse several years ago, continue with this superlative
new commercial staging of ``The Mystery of Irma Vep,'' subtitled
``A Penny Dreadful,'' for which movies are the principal
inspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Its provenance is long and respectable: ``Rebecca,'' ``The Hound
of the Baskervilles,'' ``Frankenstein'' and ``Dracula'' (and their
various Hammer Films spinoffs), all movies about mummies and
werewolves, ``Laura,'' ``Angel Street'' and just about anything
with Joan Crawford in her twilight years.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, of course, there was ``Les Vampires,'' Louis
Feuillade's grand, 10-part French serial made in 1915-16, which
gave us the character name of Irma Vep. The 1966 French film ``Irma
Vep'' has no relation to the Ludlam play, which defies plagiarism
and any other kind of literary larceny.
</P>
<P>
   Ludlam's setting is Mandacrest, the Hillcrest family's great
ancestral home, to which Lord Edgar (DeRosa) has brought his new
bride, Lady Enid ( Quinton).
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, Mandacrest's past closes in on the spirited
but sensitive and affectionate Enid. A palpable presence, as well
as a ghastly portrait in the drawing room, is Lady Irma Vep,
Edgar's first wife, who died under mysterious circumstances. There
are also stories of the tragic death of Edgar's young son, Victor,
fatally attacked by Irma's pet wolf, also called Victor. The house
seems to be staffed by ghosts, vampires and werewolves, who make
unreliable servants.
</P>
<P>
   Movies may be the inspiration for ``The Mystery of Irma Vep,''
but the script and, particularly, the performances move far beyond
camp to achieve a kind of overview that effortlessly embraces
nearly a century of American show business.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mystery of Irma Vep'' recalls burlesque, vaudeville,
Broadway farce of the 1920s and 30s, as well as the Golden Age of
Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Much of the joy in this production is witnessing the
split-second timing of Quinton and DeRosa as they switch back and
forth among their various characters, exiting through one door in
mid-speech to enter a beat later via another door as someone else.
A scene of signal bliss: We watch through French doors at the back
of the stage while poor Enid is cruelly ravished by a hairy
creature, part-man, part-beast, who is also played by Quinton.
</P>
<P>
   William Ivey Long is formally listed as the costume designer
but, because of the speed with which the costume changes are
effected, he might be more accurately described as the costume
engineer. There is no time to put them on; they must be walked
into, and they aren't flimsy little shmattes.
</P>
<P>
   Quinton's Enid wears gorgeously overelaborate Edwardian gowns
that look as big and heavy as horse blankets, and are almost as
becoming. His getup as the Egyptian princess would seem to require
equal attention in the donning and doffing, simply because there's
so little to it.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   This is the sort of illusion _ sometimes called magic _ that is
possible only in the theater, where the audience realizes that such
speedy transformations are close to miraculous. When they are
successful, as they are here, they have the effect of elevating the
entire theatrical experience into a sort of flying carpet ride that
happens to be very, very funny.
</P>
<P>
   John Lee Beatty's sets are also part of the fun, especially the
great Mandacrest drawing room, which looks as pinched, tacky and
basic as elegant English drawing rooms always do in B-pictures. I
assume that far more money was spent on this production than the
Ridiculous Theatrical Company could ever afford for its productions
downtown, but don't worry: nobody has sold out.
</P>
<P>
   DeRosa, who was memorably funny in the Acting Company's ``Love's
Fire,'' seen in New York in June, works beautifully with Quinton,
especially as the numbingly dense Lord Edgar. He also appears as
Jane Twisden, the ladies' maid who, like Mrs. Danvers in
``Rebecca,'' resents her new mistress, whom she dismisses as ``a
vulgarian,'' and whom she tricks into wearing _ gasp, gasp _ the
wrong gown!
</P>
<P>
   DeRosa gets to deliver some of the author's most delicious
high-calorie lines about love's being ``a kind of madness'' and
hatred ``a bottomless cup.'' Will Jane Twisden drink the dregs? I
dasn't tell.
</P>
<P>
   As the director, the star and the keeper of the Ludlam flame,
Quinton continues to be one of the most singular talents in the
contemporary American theater. His Lady Enid is demanding, rude,
passionate and forgiving. Though his Egyptian princess is not quite
as beautiful as the mummy case she comes in, she is both properly
imperious and willfully dismissive of her benefactor. Quinton is
also not at all bad as a wolfman.
</P>
<P>
   His secret is that he plays his wildly cartoonish characters
absolutely straight, never for a minute betraying the material by
winking at the audience, which would be fatal. Because he is such a
tough, disciplined performer, he makes it all look easy. You leave
the theater full of good will, walking on air. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That sense of sublime weightlessness is what is missing from
``Communicating Doors,'' Alan Ayckbourn's comedy now playing Off
Broadway at the Variety Arts Theater. The English playwright
probably knows more about play-making than anyone in the theater
today, with the exception of Neil Simon.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in this New York production, directed by Christopher Ashley,
``Communicating Doors'' seems too clever for its own good. That is,
it takes so long to set up the complicated central situation that
you may have forgotten exactly what it is by the time the payoffs
start coming along.
</P>
<P>
   The setting is an elegant London hotel suite where, by chance, a
most improbably innocent prostitute-dominatrix, who calls herself
Poopay, is summoned, not for her usual services, but to witness the
bizarre confession of a very old man. The year is 2018. The old man
claims to have ordered the murders of his two wives, the first 40
years earlier, the second 20 years later.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to get away from the murderer, Poopay runs into the next
room. By playwriting magic, she finds herself in the same suite in
1998, confronted by the woman who is scheduled to be the second of
the old man's victims, and on this very day. After a lot more
exposition, the two women set out to change the course of history,
even skipping back to 1978 to try and save the wife who was the
first to be bumped off.
</P>
<P>
   You see what I mean? Any comedy that takes this long to outline
is not going to fly without a lot of auxiliary power. Among other
things, Ayckbourn puts forth too many arbitrary rules relating to
time travel to allow the farcical situations to erupt
spontaneously.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of ``Communicating Doors'' I experienced the sinking
feeling I sometimes had in college when, after a lecture, I
realized I remembered nothing and faced a pop quiz. It's not
comedy; it's Theater of Cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   There are some comic moments in ``Communicating Doors'' but
ultimately they don't add up to much. The one bright spot:
Mary-Louise Parker, who plays Poopay. She's a charmer. Even in her
leather drag and brandishing a very small, limp whip, Ms. Parker
looks so cute, cuddly and innocent she wouldn't be out of place
walking our recently saved 42nd Street.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 2146EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
