<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 21:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5109 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-PROGRAMMING-2TAKES     10-07 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PROGRAMMING-2TAKES-$ADV11-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY IT TAKES 400 PAGES TO TELL YOU WHAT'S ON  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, OCT. 11) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 Jeff MacGregor worked in the television industry for 20 years as
writer, producer and network correspondent.  
 By JEFF MACGREGOR   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If, as Emily Dickinson says, hope is the thing with feathers
that perches in the soul, then maybe boredom is the thing in a
bathrobe that just sits around the house. It is, in any case, my
only excuse for the amazing statistical discoveries that follow.
</P>
<P>
   Finishing work the other day and having no rooftop orchidarium
in which to putter (as famous writers do) or even a basement
workshop in which to muse among the wood shavings (as midlist
writers do), I went downstairs to get the mail. There, to my
delight, I found the fall preview issue of TV Guide. An hour later,
with the help of two passing stevedores, a hand truck and a hoist,
I had the 398-page booklet safely home.
</P>
<P>
   Which put me in mind of several questions. First: Why is TV
Guide so big? Second: Is ``orchidarium'' even a word? What about
``orchidaceum''? Would either be on a rooftop? And why are writers
always writing about the smell of the wood shavings in their
basement workshops? What are they making down there? Is it a
metaphor? A simile? A spice rack? What is Joseph Conrad really
trying to say in ``Heart of Darkness''? Discuss.
</P>
<P>
   Regaining consciousness a few hours later, I made scientific
measurements of the bloated little television fanzine in an effort
to answer my initial question. At 7.375 inches long by 5 inches
wide by 3/4 of an inch thick, it weighed just over 10 ounces.
</P>
<P>
   TV Guide has a national circulation of around 13 million. This
means that the total weight, countrywide, of the fall preview issue
(despite reported advertising declines) was roughly 8.125 million
pounds: more than 4,000 tons. Stacked flat, they would form a tower
153.8 miles high; balanced lengthwise, 1,513 miles. Most
fascinating of all, if every page from every issue were laid end to
end, (italics)most of the new television shows they describe would
still be gone by Christmas.(end italics)
</P>
<P>
   One of the few traditions left in the television programming
business is the premiere of new shows each fall. Since the advent
of cable and satellite distribution, the addition of quasi-networks
like UPN and the WB, and the dispersal of the old network audience
across a wide range of other interests and technologies, there is
no longer a fixed schedule for the debut of new product.
</P>
<P>
   Shows pop up on the prime-time schedule year round now, each one
vying to find an audience, fast, in a world of hairtrigger remotes
and short attention spans.
</P>
<P>
   Time slots are rearranged from week to week to reward the strong
or cull the puny, to catch a trend or break a story or fight a
holding action until reinforcements arrive. ``For the love of God,
we need that third-to-last episode of `Seinfeld' down here again or
we're done for!''
</P>
<P>
   The beginning of the fall season, though, is still the best way
to get shows out of the gate. The children are back in school,
vacation time is pretty much over, and the audience is looking for
something fresh after a summer of reruns and one-off stunt shows
(``World's Wildest Police Animals Chase Rampaging Guinness Record
Holders'').
</P>
<P>
   Besides, baby boomers like me were long ago conditioned to
anticipate new shows with this change of seasons, and programmers
are loath to give up one of the few remaining habits of a shifting
audience.
</P>
<P>
   Since there is nothing new under the sun, or at least under the
Hollywood sign, this fall we are again reassured in our various
tastes by the scientifically researched diversity of network
offerings: Drama/sitcom. White collar/blue collar.
Married/divorced. Kids/no kids. Home/workplace. Blonde/brunette.
Lovable oddball/laughable martinet.
</P>
<P>
   Endlessly recombinant, these are the DNA strands of nightly
network entertainment. Newly discovered this year is the gene that
determines whether one lead character per show will be perceptibly
gay. The prime-time news-magazine program, an inexpensive catch-all
mutation of the last several seasons, has been cloned successfully
and will continue to provide us with a happy/sad, black/white,
hero/villain perspective on things out there in the real world. It
is, in other words, a fall season like other recent fall seasons.
</P>
<P>
   But if all shows are basically identical, even at the molecular
level (and with a notable handful of exceptions, they are), how do
we differentiate them? How do we know if the lovable oddballs in
``Will and Grace'' are better than/worse than/the same as the
lovable oddballs in ``Dharma and Greg'' or the lovable oddballs in
``Two Guys, a Girl and a Pizza Place''? Or if blond, blue-collar
``Costello'' is better than/worse than/the same as blond,
blue-collar ``Jesse''?
</P>
<P>
   That's where a hyperthyroid copy of TV Guide comes in handy.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is that television shows from season to season vary so
little (ritual formats performed by actors recycled from other
ritual formats) that the promotion of public awareness of any given
show has as much to do with the show's initial success as its
content. (Long term, of course, a show has to become a habit, like
crack, to succeed.)
</P>
<P>
   That's why network ad campaigns are generally more entertaining
(and expensive and important) than the shows they advertise. It is
also why the multibillion-dollar industry that reports on the
business of show business has grown ever larger over the last
decade.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Your TV Guide is lately the size of a regional phone book
because of the necessary symbiosis between the covered and the
coverage. It is in TV Guide's own best interests that more people
watch television, so they present as much enticing information
about it as you can lift.
</P>
<P>
   It is in network television's best interests to cooperate with
TV Guide (and buy lots of ad space), because it may be the last
place a viewer looks before making a programming choice. This is a
simple transaction in which both parties benefit from the continued
success of the other.
</P>
<P>
   It also provides a model for the now complex macroeconomy that
fuels other infotainment magazines like Entertainment Weekly and
television shows like ``Entertainment Tonight,'' ``Extra!'' and
``Access Hollywood.''
</P>
<P>
   Taken in themselves, these outlets satisfy the public appetite
for ``behind the scenes'' information about the shows we watch, the
movies we see and the music we hear. By selecting certain shows for
their attentions, they momentarily clear away some of the clutter
so that choices seem to become easier.
</P>
<P>
   They create curiosity. (``If I'm seeing it on `E.T.' it must be
worthwhile so I'll sample it.'') They also play to our love of
competition, wherein box office receipts and weekly ratings
determine in large part our impression of the product's quality.
(``If such and such finished 65th it must not be very good so I
won't try it'' becomes self-fulfilling.) Thus they become the touts
and handicappers for a race that never ends.
</P>
<P>
   At the next level of complexity, these outlets create the
appetite they strive to satisfy. In a society that long ago
replaced myth with the prurient/cautionary tales of celebrity,
where nothing is truly ``behind'' the scenes because it's all
available at all times, the more celebrities that the E! channel
manufactures, the more celebrities they'll have to cover. This,
then, is also the world's first working perpetual-motion machine.
</P>
<P>
   Most sinister, though, is the fact that these outlets are owned
and operated by the same gigantic media combines that own, produce
and distribute the entertainment. When ``Entertainment Tonight''
shows night after night of reports about ``Titanic'' for months, is
it because that movie inherently deserves our attention? Or is it
because ``ET'' is owned by Paramount, a studio with a 50 percent
interest in the movie's revenues?
</P>
<P>
   To the casual consumer of entertainment, it's almost impossible
to discern the linkages between product and promoter. Until
recently, for example, TV Guide was owned by the News Corp., Rupert
Murdoch's umbrella for his global communications company. News
Corp. also owns 20th Century Fox. And the Fox network.
</P>
<P>
   Does that account then for the substantial number of decorative
cover stories over the last few seasons devoted to ``The Simpsons''
and ``The X-Files''? What about a show like ``The Practice,'' which
was the subject of a cover story last season slugged ``the best
show you're not watching''? But that's on the ABC network, you say.
Yes, it is. But it's produced by the Fox studio, 20th Century Fox
Television.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of interdivisional logrolling has been the status quo
for some time. All the public can do in its own defense is become
more aware of the manipulation they're subject to, to who owns what
and why they might want you to watch one thing instead of another.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to the fall season and the arrival of those
Proustian TV Guides. They're your 4,000-ton tip sheet to the great
autumn network sweepstakes, a handy listing to another year's worth
of derivative long shots and formulaic dark horses.
</P>
<P>
   And if that sounds like induction day at the glue factory, it
should, because historically and statistically we know that most of
the new entries will be out of the running in the next few months.
Some will falter in weeks. A few (``Encore! Encore!'' limps to
mind) will be humanely euthanized before they can do any further
harm to themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Programming anything in the face of circumstances like these is
an act of faith as much as calculation. Network television
executives ply their trade at the complex intersection of corporate
hope and national boredom. And in millennium Hollywood, hope is the
thing with legs and the time slot opposite ``ER.'' Emily Dickinson
would be so proud.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 2149EDT &QL; 
