<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 21:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5117 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS &LR;      10-07 1274
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-SCANDAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE PRESSES WAVERING DEMOCRATS FOR SUPPORT ON EVE OF
IMPEACHMENT INQUIRY VOTE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN C. HENRY 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of a historic House vote to launch an
impeachment inquiry against President Clinton, the White House
pressed Wednesday to line up support from wavering Democrats
worried about re-election.
</P>
<P>
   With the Republican-controlled House certain to formally open an
impeachment investigation into his effort to cover-up an affair
with Monica Lewinsky, a key issue for Clinton was whether enough
Democrats would defect to allow the GOP to slap a bipartisan label
on the inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   To help keep defections to a minimum, key House Democrats worked
late Wednesday on an alternative to the open-ended investigation
proposed by the Republicans and negotiated with the House GOP
leadership for additional time to debate the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's up to others to decide what happens to me, and ultimately
it's going to be up to the American people to make a clear
statement there,'' Clinton said while posing for photographers with
visiting Hungarian Prime Minister Viktor Orban.
</P>
<P>
   The president, who acknowledged talking by telephone with
several Democrats, denied asking anyone to flatly oppose an
inquiry. Clinton said House members should cast a ``vote of
principle and conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Vice President Al Gore, first lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton and White House aides continued urging House
Democrats to oppose the Republican plan for an open-ended
impeachment inquiry. The plan comes up for a vote today.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile independent counsel Ken Starr delivered a letter
Wednesday to the House warning that his investigation of the
Whitewater land deal, alleged misuse of FBI files and the White
House travel office was not completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can confirm at this time that matters continue to be under
active investigation and review,'' Starr wrote, responding to a
request from Judiciary Committee leaders. He said he could not
``foreclose the possibility'' of submitting to Congress evidence of
impeachable offenses beyond material already provided about
Clinton's affair with Lewinsky and attempts to cover it up.
</P>
<P>
   Starr's letter is expected to undercut Democratic efforts _
which already face overwhelming opposition from the House
Republican majority _ to put a time limit on the Judiciary
Committee's impeachment inquiry or to restrict it to the Lewinsky
matter.
</P>
<P>
   House Democratic leaders dispatched Rep. Vic Fazio, D-Calif., a
retiring member of Congress, to the White House to tell the
president's strategists that wavering Democrats wanted them to back
off.
</P>
<P>
   Fazio also gave the president the latest headcount on Democrats
likely to support the GOP impeachment proposal if a Democratic
alternative, which was still being drafted late Wednesday, is
defeated as expected.
</P>
<P>
   When the Democrats vote with the Republicans, Fazio said, ``they
do so with a great deal of skepticism on one hand, but at the same
time a sense that in their case, either because of strong personal
views or constituent pressures, that that's the right thing to
do.''
</P>
<P>
   The best estimate, provided late Wednesday by two top Democratic
strategists, was that about 50 House Democrats, nearly one-fourth
of the members, will defect. If that happens, it will undercut the
White House claim that the investigation is a partisan witch hunt.
</P>
<P>
   Armed with polls showing that Democrats would not be hurt by
standing with the president against an open-ended impeachment
inquiry, the White House rebuffed requests from a small group of
moderate Democrats to radically change course and quit opposing the
Republican proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim Moran, D-Va., said that if the vote today breaks down
along partisan lines ``the November election is likely to be a
referendum on the president's conduct.'' That, he added, is not in
the ``long-term best interests of the Democratic Party.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats would be better served, Moran said, if the election
turns on issues such as education, health care and the future of
Social Security. He said the president should let Democrats off the
hook on the issue of an open inquiry. ``The president should seize
this as an opportunity to take dramatic action worthy of a true
leader, to say: `This problem is not of your making, it is mine.
None of you should suffer because of this. I'm going to take on my
accuser. I'm going to acquit myself.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic House leader said that suggestion was declined
several times in the past week by the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Sen. Robert Byrd, D-W.Va., rebuked the White House
for efforts over the weekend to derail the impeachment inquiry by
asking 34 Democratic senators to sign a letter saying they would
never vote to remove the president. ``I would suggest by way of
friendly advice to the White House: Don't tamper with this jury,''
Byrd said during a speech on the Senate floor.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican proposal sets no time limits on the investigation
and would allow the House Judiciary Committee to expand the inquiry
beyond Lewinsky matter to other issues, such as Whitewater, alleged
misuse of FBI files, White House travel office firings and campaign
fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
   The limits on duration and scope are key ingredients in the
alternative Democrats will offer when the impeachment inquiry
resolution is debated. Under House rules, each side is allowed 30
minutes to argue the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday, Democratic leader Dick Gephardt of Missouri
asked Speaker Newt Gingrich to allow up to eight hours of debate on
the Republican resolution and the Democratic alternative. The GOP
leadership responded with an offer to allow each side an hour to
debate, which Democrats quickly criticized.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm frankly appalled,'' said Rep. Sheila Jackson Lee, a
Houston Democrat who warned that Republicans could face a backlash
from voters if they ``close the shades of the United States
Congress, turn off the lights ... and not allow a full and fair
debate.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Chet Edwards, D-Waco, said the vote to launch an
impeachment inquiry is the most important decision Congress can
make short of declaring war. ``Why should we have to beg for the
time needed to let members speak on this issue?'' Edwards asked.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. John Boehner, R-Ohio and chairman of the House Republican
Conference, argued for limiting debate to an hour and not changing
the rules. ``It is typical of Bill Clinton and the Democrats that
they believe the rules apply to everyone but them.''
</P>
<P>
   After the House approves the impeachment inquiry Thursday,
members will close shop and return to their home districts.
Technically, the House will be recessed pending a call from the
Speaker to return if the Judiciary Committee votes to recommend
impeaching the president.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, chaired by Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill., is likely
begin its investigation after the Nov. 3 elections. The committee
will interrogate witnesses, including Lewinsky and, in all
likelihood, Starr.
</P>
<P>
   If a majority of the 21 Republicans and 16 Democrats on the
committee decide there is enough evidence to impeach Clinton, they
will ask for a vote before the full House. If the House approves,
the president will go on trial in the Senate, probably next year.
If he is found guilty by 67 or more senators, he will be removed
from office.
</P>
<P>
   The House has returned articles of impeachment against two
presidents _ Richard Nixon, who resigned in 1974 before he could be
tried, and Andrew Johnson, who was acquitted by the Senate in
1868. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
