<HEADER>
A5123 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-MARTINEZ-NY     10-07 0700
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-MARTINEZ-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ SPUTTERING THROUGH ANOTHER OCTOBER  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Dave Winfield tossed out the first pitch before David
Cone threw one Wednesday, which was a bizarre sight at Yankee
Stadium. George Steinbrenner once hired a known gambler to collect
disparaging information on the former Yankee. Verbal squabbles and
lawsuits followed and there has been a deep freeze in the
relationship between the owner and the future Hall of Famer,
although that is apparently thawing.
</P>
<P>
   While Winfield's presence was mostly irrelevant, there was one
way to twist and turn and make it somewhat relevant. Steinbrenner
once criticized Winfield by calling him Mr. May after he failed to
produce in the 1981 World Series. It was a cruel moniker and
Winfield was basically stuck with it until he helped the Blue Jays
win the 1992 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner has never even come remotely close to maligning
Tino Martinez, a player he adores. But Martinez is sputtering
through another October, leaving no doubt about his inability to
mimic Reggie Jackson's postseason exploits and leaving a void in
the middle of a disappointing lineup. Would Steinbrenner ever
seethe enough to call Martinez something as ugly as Mr. May? After
Wednesday's 4-1 loss to the Indians in Game 2 of the American
League Championship Series and with Steinbrenner, anything is
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had another long October day and October evening at
Yankee Stadium, going hitless in five times at-bat and stranding
three runners. He had a marvelous opportunity to knock in the
go-ahead run in the eighth, but he swung wildly at Paul Shuey's 3-2
pitch and left teammates perched on first and second. Mr. October
Martinez is not.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Martinez was also involved in a controversial play that
helped the Indians gain a wild victory over the Yankees in 12
innings. Enrique Wilson scored the second run from first base after
Martinez fielded Travis Fryman's bunt, threw it to first and it
glanced off the runner's back and rolled away. Chuck Knoblauch
argued that Fryman was out of the baseline and inexplicably did not
chase the loose ball. It dribbled toward the outfield grass because
of Knoblauch's brain lock and that allowed Wilson to barely beat
Knoblauch's throw with a dive across plate.
</P>
<P>
   The postseason has not been Martinez's favorite time with the
Yankees, even though they won the World Series in 1996. Actually,
Martinez's struggles date to the ALCS in 1995. Ever since Martinez
batted .409 with one homer and five runs batted in for the Mariners
against the Yankees in the 1995 Division Series, he is 19 for 108
with one homer and four RBIs. In the ALCS, Martinez is 7-for-53 and
in the last seven postseason series, he has not had a homer or an
RBI in six of them.
</P>
<P>
   Since Martinez is a sensitive sort, Joe Torre turned defensive
when he was asked about Martinez's disappearing offense. Torre
spoke eloquently on Tuesday about Bernie Williams being 0 for 11 in
the Division Series against the Rangers, offering some insights and
speculating that Williams was trying too hard because the
postseason can be fatal.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre was not so talkative about Martinez. He was not
talkative at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tino's fine,'' said Torre, who then asserted that he counted
David Justice's nifty diving catch in left field on Tuesday as a
hit for Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Even if that had been a hit, it would have been a bloop single.
Martinez would have taken one of those in Game 2. He would have
taken anything. Martinez rapped out to first in the second and,
with a runner on second base and one out in the fourth, he popped
out to left. After walking on four pitches in the seventh, Martinez
had a chance to erase some of the postseason frustration.
</P>
<P>
   With the score tied, 2-2, Williams was on first, Derek Jeter was
on second and Mariano Rivera was warming up for the ninth. If
Martinez managed to get a single, it would have given the Yankees a
lead and given Rivera a chance for a save. But Martinez never
looked comfortable, probably should have whiffed on a close 2-2
curveball and then missed a 3-2 pitch to kill another threat.
</P>
</TEXT>
