<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETTAX-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Senate Ready to Ban New Cyber Levies   By Jon Swartz  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
The U.S. Senate is expected today to approve a three-year ban on
any new taxes on Internet sales and services.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Internet Tax Freedom Act, which has been fiercely debated on
the Senate floor this week, would temporarily stop states and local
municipalities from creating new cyber levies. The bill would also
form a commission to advise Congress on how _ and whether _ to tax
online transactions.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a positive public policy that's consistent with our
position of global leadership in electronic commerce,'' said Hank
Barry, a computer law expert and partner at Wilson Sonsini Goodrich
&AMP; Rosati in Palo Alto. ``It strikes the right balance between the
taxation needs of the states and the national interest in promoting
development of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-authored by Representative Christopher Cox, R-Newport Beach,
and Senator Ron Wyden, D-Ore., the bill specifically would:
</P>
<P>
   _ Prohibit new taxes on Internet-access charges, such as the
roughly $20 monthly fee charged by America Online, AT&AMP;T and other
Internet service providers.
</P>
<P>
   _ Ban multiple or discriminatory taxes on electronic commerce
transactions. Consumers would pay sales tax on Internet purchases
only if the seller had a ``substantial physical presence'' (such as
offices or employees) in the jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   _ Protect against new Internet-specific taxes for consumers and
vendors, outlawing Web search taxes, e-mail surcharges and other
levies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Create a temporary Advisory Commission on Electronic Commerce
to study e-commerce tax issues and then report to Congress. The
commission could decide on a national tax rate for e-commerce
transactions or advise against virtual taxes altogether.
</P>
<P>
   _ Authorize the Clinton administration to demand that foreign
governments keep the Internet free of taxes and tariffs.
</P>
<P>
   The House has already passed a three-year moratorium on new
Internet charges; it would exempt states with Web taxes already in
effect.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, citing the Internet's key role in the
economic growth the past two years, says he supports the bill.
</P>
<P>
   High-tech companies argue that taxes or surcharges on Internet
access, e-mail and e-commerce, could choke off the growing business
use of the Web.
</P>
<P>
   ``Users of the Internet are already taxed through their
telephone service. They shouldn't be levied taxes upon taxes,''
said Ken Salaets, director of government relations of the
Information Technology Industry Council, a Washington, D.C.,
organization that represents 32 major computer-makers, including
Apple Computer, Intel, Hewlett-Packard and IBM.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that happens, it complicates things and discourages people
from using the medium,'' Salaets said.
</P>
<P>
   But some states and cities _ miffed that they're already missing
an estimated $3.3 billion a year in taxes on mail-order sales _
worry that fast-growing online commerce is eroding their finances
by avoiding traditional taxes. They claim it constitutes an unfair
tax haven.
</P>
<P>
   Senator Bob Graham, D-Fla., who opposes the bill, said it favors
Internet sellers over local retail businesses and puts a major hole
in state and local revenues. Last night, Graham engaged in a heated
argument in a last-ditch effort to derail the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The anti-tax Internet bill includes a controversial amendment
authored by Senator Dan Coats, R-Ind., that would bar commercial
Web sites from allowing anyone 17 and under access to pornographic
material deemed ``harmful to minors.'' The Senate passed the
measure 98-1 yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court last year struck down lawmakers' first
attempt to limit online smut, the Communications Decency Act, as a
violation of free-speech rights. That bill was attached to the
Telecommunications Act of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   The Coats amendment applies only to commercial Web sites instead
of the entire Internet and uses a ``harmful-to-minors'' standard
instead of a broader indecency standard. It mandates that
adult-oriented sites require a credit card or personal ID number;
if not, the sites face state and local taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The ``harmful-to-minors'' standard would allow access to
material that had redeeming social, political or artistic value.
</P>
<P>
   But the narrow interpretation, derisively dubbed ``CDA II,'' is
still opposed by civil-liberties groups and major companies doing
business on the Internet. They argue the bill would chill the free
exchange of ideas and could be interpreted in conflicting ways
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill suffers from the same constitutional problem (as the
original Communication Decency Act),'' said Chris Hansen, senior
staff counsel of the American Civil Liberties Union in New York.
``In the name of protecting children, it tries to ban speech which
is constitutionally protected for adults.
</P>
<P>
   ``Senator Coats is burning down the house to roast the pig,''
Hansen said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chronicle Technology Editor Carolyn Said contributed to this
report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
