<SLUG> BC-INTEL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 Intel Developing Several Chip Lines Simultaneously   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
While Intel Corp. develops its next-generation chip, code-named
Merced and planned for the most expensive corporate computers, the
chip giant is already working on a processor that will be twice as
powerful.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Details of the other new chip, code-named McKinley, were
revealed in a briefing yesterday at Intel's Santa Clara
headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   In a room off the Intel Museum, where visiting schoolchildren
take breaks and play board games, Intel Fellow Fred Pollack
described how the company plans to develop Merced and McKinley _
and at the same time continue to produce its best-selling Pentium
line.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, the world's largest maker of microprocessors, which are
the brains that run computers, announced last year that it would
develop its first new chip architecture in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Working with Hewlett-Packard Co., Intel will produce the Merced
chip, which will mark Intel's entry into 64-bit architecture.
Intel's chips for the past 20 years, from the 286 through the
Pentiums, have processed information in 32-bit chunks.
</P>
<P>
   Merced development stumbled this past summer when Intel
announced a delay of six to nine months.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're doing your first implementation of a new
instruction set architecture, you learn a lot,'' said Pollack, who
heads the group that plans Intel's future microprocessors. ``Those
are very painful lessons, due to the complexity. It's been taking
us longer than we thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Merced is now on track, Pollack said. Software is already being
developed for it. Samples of the chip will be sent to computer
makers next year. It should be ready for commercial use by
mid-2000.
</P>
<P>
   A separate team working on McKinley should have the chip ready
by late 2001, Pollack said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentium II Xeon, Intel's present entry in the workstation
and server market, will be followed next year by chips code-named
Tanner and Cascades.
</P>
<P>
   Those, in turn, will be followed by chips code-named Willamette
and Foster that will be on the market in late 2000 or early 2001 _
around the same time as Merced.
</P>
<P>
   That shows Intel's continuing division of its core product line
into segments.
</P>
<P>
   Intel will soon sell microprocessors for everything from small
consumer devices and inexpensive personal computers to the most
expensive servers and workstations _ machines that cost upwards of
$25,000.
</P>
<P>
   While the company said the fragmented product line is necessary
to meet a market where one size no longer fits all, analyst Rob
Enderle of the Giga Information Group said it also presents Intel
with a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``They, like Microsoft, have gone from being relatively simple
companies in their product sets to being tremendously complex
companies in brands and product breadth _ Intel much more quickly
than Microsoft,'' Enderle said. ``That's going to put them under a
lot of stress.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel's move into the rarefied air of the most expensive
workstations puts it in direct competition with Sun Microsystems,
International Business Machines and Compaq Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   As Intel develops the new chip architecture, the industry is
watching to see when the high-powered machines will trickle down to
consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Pollack said the answer was at least three years away, but he
wouldn't predict with any certainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there was any doubt out there, this road map underscores
the fact that it will be a good long while before you even think
about seeing the IA-64 on your desktop,'' said Mike Feibus, an
analyst with Mercury Research in Scottsdale, Ariz.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Enderle said he's advising companies to start getting ready
for Merced to hit the desktop in 2002, which will be ``a big year
for hardware change-out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 2159EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0432 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 22:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5138 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CORRIGAN-SFCHRON &LR;      10-07 1128
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRIGAN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  
 LSI Founder, CEO Rides Out Another Chip Industry Downturn   By Dan Fost  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
 
Wilf Corrigan has been here before.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The chip industry may be suffering from its worst downturn in
memory, but it's not the first time that business has been
battered.
</P>
<P>
   Corrigan, 60, the co-founder, chairman and chief executive of
LSI Logic, remembers the old downturns _ and he remembers the good
times, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the doom and gloom now is the dark before the dawn,''
Corrigan said in an interview in LSI's Milpitas headquarters. ``In
the next three years, you're going to see another cycle like 1993,
'94, '95.''
</P>
<P>
   With a twinkle in his eye and the lilt of his native Liverpool
on his tongue, Corrigan maintains a cheerful outlook even as the
market bumps along the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   Corrigan has earned his tough hide. When he was 3, he huddled
with his family in an air raid shelter while German bombs battered
his home during the Blitz. He remains a passionate admirer of
Winston Churchill, whose portrait adorns his office and whose books
line his shelves at home.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, he moved with his Norwegian-born wife to the United
States, ultimately taking a job with Motorola in Phoenix. By 1968,
he was a vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The following year, when Robert Noyce, Gordon Moore and Andy
Grove left Fairchild Semiconductor to form Intel Corp., Lester
Hogan left the helm of Motorola to run Fairchild. Corrigan was
among the team, known as ``Hogan's Heroes,'' who jumped to
Fairchild with him.
</P>
<P>
   By 1974, Corrigan was president, chairman and chief executive of
the revamped Fairchild Camera and Instrument, but those were trying
times for the once-proud company. That year saw him halve the
workforce, from 30,000 to 15,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   Fred Zieber was an analyst at Dataquest back then, and he
recalls Corrigan as a CEO who could swallow a bitter pill.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wrote a newsletter on Fairchild that was just brutal,
probably the worst I've ever written about a company,'' said
Zieber, now president of Pathfinder Research in San Jose. ``I took
it to Wilf, and he read the draft. He corrected one small factual
error, and said, `It's fair.'''
</P>
<P>
   Zieber said Corrigan ``kept Fairchild alive against all odds. He
inherited it with very severe problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wilf is a tough cookie,'' Zieber said. ``If there's a guy I'd
want to run my company in a downturn, Wilf would be the guy. He's
been through it all.''
</P>
<P>
   When the French conglomerate Schlumberger acquired Fairchild in
1979, Corrigan left.
</P>
<P>
   In 1981, Corrigan, Mick Bond, Bill O'Meara and Rob Walker
founded LSI Logic _ which stands for large scale integration logic
chips _ with a notion of selling custom-made semiconductors for use
in consumer devices and computers. At the time, the business of
selling such chips, known as application-specific integrated
circuits, or ASICs, was far from a sure thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``People said ASICs weren't anything, but Wilf built LSI into a
giant company,'' said Jack Beedle, the retired founder of In-Stat,
a research firm in Arizona. ``Wilf's one of the legends.''
</P>
<P>
   Next month, the Semiconductor Industry Association will honor
Corrigan and Jerry Sanders, who co-founded and still runs Advanced
Micro Devices, with the Robert Noyce Award, the industry's highest
honor. Corrigan and Sanders are among the founders of the
association.
</P>
<P>
   Among Corrigan's industry achievements, said Brian Halla, a
former Corrigan lieutenant at LSI who is now CEO of National
Semiconductor, is his leadership in negotiations in the 1980s, when
U.S. chip companies accused their Japanese counterparts of dumping
low-price memory chips in the American marketplace.
</P>
<P>
   ``He represented the whole industry in driving to successful
conclusion of those negotiations,'' Halla said.
</P>
<P>
   Corrigan said too much factory capacity in Asia has contributed
to the oversupply of chips that is a major cause of the current
downturn.
</P>
<P>
   Now in its third year, the slump has hammered company earnings
and led to layoffs of scores of workers. Although LSI has not laid
anyone off this year, it did warn Wall Street that its earnings
would be down this quarter. It reports results next week.
</P>
<P>
   LSI, which employs 6,700 people, reported revenues of $1.3
billion last year. For the first half of this year, the company has
reported revenues of $655 million, up 2.3 percent over the first
half of last year, but earnings have dropped 25.8 percent, from
$84.2 million in the first half of last year to $62.5 million in
the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
   The company's stock reflects the challenges. It closed down 50
cents yesterday at $11.38, its 52-week low. That's substantially
below its 52-week high of $30.25.
</P>
<P>
   No one is hurt by the stock drop more than Corrigan, who is the
company's largest individual shareholder, according to filings with
the Securities and Exchange Commission. In addition to his 1997
income of $1.1 million in salary, bonus and other benefits,
Corrigan holds 7.6 million shares, or 5.4 percent of those
outstanding, with an option to buy 300,000 _ at the now-high price
of $33.25.
</P>
<P>
   In the company's glory days of the early 1990s, the stock topped
$60.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called him during the midst of this downturn in the market
and said, `Not until I was CEO of a semiconductor company did I
realize how much respect I have for you,''' Halla said.
</P>
<P>
   ``His response was typical Wilf: `Where else could you have this
much fun?' He said, `If you ask a woman who's delivering a child if
she wants another when she's in the middle of the birthing process,
she'll say no, but a year later, she again wants the pitter-patter
of little feet.'''
</P>
<P>
   In the last downturn, in 1992, LSI was particularly hard hit,
and Corrigan led a major restructuring. He shifted LSI's focus from
serving hundreds of customers to becoming the ``system-on-a-chip''
company, making exclusive designs for a few trend-setting
customers, according to vice president of marketing Bruce Entin.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, LSI makes the chips for the Sony PlayStation game
console, digital cameras and digital video disc players.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Corrigan's gutsiness helped pull off one of the biggest deals
of the summer, LSI's $760 million acquisition of Symbios. Adaptec
had been all set to take over Symbios, but the Federal Trade
Commission's antitrust concerns scuttled that deal. It fell apart
on a Friday, and by Monday, LSI had cinched the purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Halla spoke admiringly of Corrigan's decisiveness. ``Guys like
Wilf tend to flower in these downturns,'' Halla said. ``On Symbios,
he was clearly very quick to move.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of reasons I left LSI,'' Halla said. ``I was going
to be the No. 2 guy forever. Wilf kept getting stronger and
stronger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
