<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 22:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5143 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-BIG-12-REPORT-TEX     10-07 1548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-BIG-12-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UT BECOMING DEFENSIVE AS SEASON GOES ON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Let's not sugarcoat the obvious. The Longhorns' defense, which
allows 444 yards and 37.4 points per game, leaks like a rusty
faucet with a worn-out washer.
</P>
<P>
   Even coach Mack Brown admits his best defensive player, at this
juncture, is tailback Ricky Williams. And his job is to keep Texas'
tacklers on the sidelines by racking up rushing yards, points and _
most important _ time of possession.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, however, the Heisman Trophy hopeful might lose his title
as the Longhorns' leading defender. That's because the Texas
defense scheduled to take the field against Oklahoma at 11:30 a.m.
Saturday at the Cotton Bowl is doing something the 1997 unit never
did: getting better.
</P>
<P>
   Each week, the Longhorns show an increased understanding of
first-year defensive coordinator Carl Reese's aggressive scheme.
Assignment busts are down. Big plays are up.
</P>
<P>
   Want proof? The Longhorns' past two opponents, Rice and Iowa
State, were a combined 10-of-31 on third-down conversions. Texas
forced seven turnovers in those games, improving to plus-2 in
turnover ratio, the most significant statistic kept by the NCAA.
The 1997 Longhorns, by contrast, surrendered 20 more turnovers than
they forced.
</P>
<P>
   Although the secondary remains suspect against the pass, the run
defense will not appear on any highlight tapes for Iowa State
tailback Darren Davis, the nation's No. 9 rusher. He managed 53
yards, less than half his season average (130.4), on 20 carries.
Against Rice, the option-oriented Owls averaged a meager 4.0 yards
per carry after gashing the Longhorns at a 6.4 clip in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   In the Big 12, you can win if you can stop the run.
</P>
<P>
   This is not to say Oklahoma tailback De'Mond Parker won't find
running room in the Cotton Bowl. He will. But don't expect him to
approach last year's 291-yard rushing total. And don't expect these
Longhorns to revert to the clueless, arm-tackling bunch we saw last
season. Or in the Sept. 5 opener against New Mexico State, for that
matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're tackling better,'' Brown said. ``We're playing harder
and with a lot more confidence. I'm pleased with our defense
against the run. We've played much better defensive games the past
two weeks against much better teams than New Mexico State.''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, these Longhorns are not a finished product. But the weekly
position changes have stopped. Freshmen playmakers Jermain
Anderson, Everick Rawls and Ervis Hill have adjusted to the speed
of the college game.
</P>
<P>
   Free safety Quentin Jammer, a converted cornerback who almost
lost his job after the first three games, recorded a team-high nine
tackles and forced a fumble against Rice. He followed with another
solid effort against Iowa State.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quentin has come so far in the last two weeks, it's
incredible,'' said Brown, who considered benching Jammer before the
Rice game. ``He'd never played the position before. When we started
the season, he was lost. Now, he's tackling well and anticipating
well.''
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said of the entire defense, which is young but
improving. A year ago, it was neither.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the season, don't be surprised if Brown has put
together a defense capable of winning games without a 300-yard
rushing day from its top ``defensive'' player.  &LR; tagtop:Jimmy Burch,
(817) 390-7760  &LR; tagbottom:jburch &LR; star-telegram.com
 &LR; subheds:QUICK HITS Ringing tribute
Texas A&AMP;M officials are rolling out the red carpet to honor the
national champions. But not the ones from Nebraska, the 18th-ranked
Aggies' opponent at 2:30 p.m. Saturday at Kyle Field.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, members of A&AMP;M's 1939 national championship team will
receive rings commemorating their accomplishment. The rings will be
awarded at a pregame luncheon, with players acknowledged during a
halftime ceremony, in which the A&AMP;M band will spell out ``1939
Champs.''
</P>
<P>
   A total of 64 rings will be presented to surviving players or
their family members. Of the 26 living players, 22 are scheduled to
attend the ceremony. Cost for the rings was covered by three
donors, with A&AMP;M president Dr. Ray Bowen chipping in $5,000 of the
$17,000 tab.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Shelton, a retired banker from Fort Worth who played
center on the 1939 team, said the response from school officials
has been ``just overwhelming'' since the day he suggested the idea
to A&AMP;M athletic director Wally Groff. In 1939, championship rings
were not issued. Players received a football medallion and a
leather travel bag, neither of which mentioned the Aggies' No. 1
ranking or 11-0 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the culmination of a great life for a lot of great
people,'' said Shelton, 80. ``It will be very emotional. I've
already seen mine and a big lump came in my throat the first time I
tried it on.''
Rankled by rankings
</P>
<P>
   Texas Tech coach Spike Dykes downplays the fact his 5-0 team,
for a second consecutive week, fell one spot short of a berth in
the Top 25. But the issue is perplexing to players, who have a
better record than 20 of the 25 teams ranked ahead of the Red
Raiders in this week's polls.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, we deserve to be in there,'' defensive end
Taurus Rucker said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not something that really bothers me, but I think we
deserve to be up in there,'' said tailback Ricky Williams. ``If we
keep winning, we'll get there.''
Many happy returns
</P>
<P>
   Among the four high-profile matchups on this week's schedule,
the most compelling subplot might unfold in Boulder, Colo. That is
where Kansas State punt returner David Allen (30.7 yards per
attempt, three TDs) will be matched against Colorado kickoff
returner Ben Kelly (30.9 per return). Both lead the Big 12 in their
respective departments.
</P>
<P>
   As a team, the Wildcats lead the nation in both punt returns
(26.4 average) and kickoff returns (33.7). Colorado ranks seventh
(17.6) and fourth (31.4), respectively. The teams have combined to
score six touchdowns on special teams, all on punt returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are maybe the best in the country at using special teams
as a weapon,'' Colorado coach Rick Neuheisel said of the Wildcats.
``And we're not bad, either. That should make the kicking game
really, really pivotal this week.''
 &LR; subheds:QUICK HITS
</P>
<P>
   Why is A&AMP;M picking this weekend to give championship rings to
its 1939 team members? While organizing the event, A&AMP;M athletic
director Wally Groff was told by Nebraska counterpart Bill Byrne
there would be no seats for the Aggies band when the teams meet in
1999 in Lincoln, Neb. That being the case, Groff told Byrne to
leave the Nebraska band at home Saturday, creating time for the
halftime ceremony. ``Besides, it's certainly appropriate that we'd
honor our national champions when the \Rreigning\S national
champions are coming to town,'' said Howard Shelton, who helped
organize the event. ... As if No. 5 Kansas State didn't have enough
things going its way, this is the week when tailback Frank Murphy
becomes eligible after serving a four-game suspension for accepting
improper benefits from a booster. Murphy was the 1997 junior
college player of the year, rushing for 1,370 yards and 26
touchdowns. Kansas State coach Bill Snyder said Murphy will play
Saturday against No. 14 Colorado, ``but I'm not sure how much.''
... Although the national trend is toward natural-grass fields, the
league's only unbeaten teams _ Nebraska, Kansas State, Texas Tech,
Colorado _ all play their home games on artificial turf. ...
Opponents have started only four drives in A&AMP;M territory this
season, all of them came in a 23-14 loss to No. 8 Florida State.
The Aggies have started 18 drives in enemy territory. ... Tech has
trailed its opponent for 12 minutes, 29 seconds of a possible 300
minutes this season. ... Because of mounting injuries on the
defensive line, Baylor coach Dave Roberts said freshmen Travis
Hicks and Kevin Stevenson might play Saturday against Kansas.
Heading into the season, Roberts said he hoped to redshirt both
players. ... Although Nebraska quarterbacks Bobby Newcombe (knee)
and Eric Crouch (hip) have taken limited snaps in practice this
week, coach Frank Solich said both have ``a decent chance'' of
playing against A&AMP;M. Responded A&AMP;M coach R.C. Slocum: ``When the
ball is snapped on game day, I'll bet neither one of those guys is
far from the action.'' ... Texas has had a 100-yard receiver in
five consecutive games, tying a school record.
WITH BURCH COLUMN
Jimmy Burch's picks Staff writer Jimmy Burch picks (against the
line) this week's Big 12 football games:
</P>
<P>
   Nebraska at Texas A&AMP;M (plus 10 1/2). Pick: Nebraska. Remember
the Alamodome? Cornhuskers offer encore performance.
</P>
<P>
   Texas vs. Oklahoma (plus 8). Pick: Oklahoma. Longhorns win, but
Sooners make them earn it.
</P>
<P>
   Oklahoma State (plus 3 1/2) at Texas Tech. Pick: Oklahoma State.
Cowboys pull upset, tighten South Division race.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas State at Colorado (plus 16 1/2). Pick: Colorado. Wildcats
prove they can win squeakers, too.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas (plus 5 1/2) at Baylor. Pick: Baylor. Jayhawks struggle
when forced to leave Lawrence.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri at Iowa State (plus 8 1/2). Pick: Missouri. Tigers'
ground game wears down outmanned Cyclones.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's record: 2-4. Season record: 23-22.
</P>
