<HEADLINE>
NFL CAPSULES FOR WEEK 6
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY FRIEDLANDER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAME OF THE WEEK DENVER (5-0) AT SEATTLE (3-2) Time: 3:15 p.m.,
Sunday Site: Kingdome, Seattle (66,400) Series: Broncos lead 26-15
Last season: Broncos 35, at Seahawks 14; At Broncos 30, Seahawks 27
Line: No line
</P>
<P>
   Broncos update: This is what it has come to. The Broncos are so
overpowering, so offensively dominant that they have turned QB
Bubby Brister _ yes, the same Bubby Brister who was run out of
Pittsburgh, Philadelphia and New York _ into the AFC's No. 1
passer. The secret is in front of him, with a line that has allowed
a mere five sacks this season, and behind him, where RB Terrell
Davis is the NFL's leading rusher (657 yards, 5.8 per carry) and
second-leading scorer (48 points on eight TDs). And don't forget
the receivers, three of whom are on pace for 1,000-yard seasons.
For Brister, a guy who was beaten up by both defenses and fans at
every other NFL stop he's made, this is a vacation. And if the
offense is this healthy running on autopilot, imagine it with John
Elway back in the saddle after resting his sore hamstrings for
two-plus weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Seahawks update: In the past, this is where the skid has always
begun. Every time the Seahawks have shown signs of moving into the
NFL's high-rent district, they get slapped back down by a real
contender or two and it destroys their entire season. Well, here we
go again, because the same team that looked unbeatable in three
early wins against the league's wretched refuse, have fallen to
earth with two consecutive losses to Pittsburgh and Kansas City.
Seattle desperately needs a win to remain within sight of the AFC
West title, and may have to get it without QB Warren Moon, who
cracked some ribs in the last game and is questionable for Sunday.
If he can't go, the burden of the offense falls on journeyman QB
John Friesz and talented but erratic RB Ricky Watters.
</P>
<P>
   Key matchup: In WR Joey Galloway, the Seahawks have one of the
premier weapons in the league, a long-ball threat who has used his
phenomenal speed to average 17.0 yards per catch and score three
TDs. On the other side is a Denver secondary that has accounted for
six interceptions and two touchdowns in its last three games. Ray
Crockett and Darrien Gordon are as good a pair of CBs as there is,
and Gordon is one of the few players who can run with Galloway
stride-for-stride.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Broncos 34, Seahawks 21 BUFFALO (1-3) AT INDIANAPOLIS
(1-4) Time: Noon, Sunday Site: RCA Dome, Indianapolis (60,599)
Series: Bills lead 31-23-1 Line: Buffalo by 2 1/2
</P>
<P>
   Bills update: Bruce Smith is apparently healthy again after
off-season knee surgery, which means quarterbacks should tremble.
The all-everything defensive end is coming off his best performance
of the year, which, not coincidentally, turned out to be the Bills'
first victory of the year, a head-scratching upset of mighty San
Francisco. But Smith's recovery isn't the only good news. The
running game by committee is racking up 132.5 yards per game, and
WR Eric Moulds has picked up for aging and injured veteran Andre
Reed. Throw in a solid plus-five turnover margin, and the Bills may
be on the way up, at least a little.
</P>
<P>
   Colts update: OK, so the run defense in still nonexistent, the
offensive line is still filled with inexperience, and QB Peyton
Manning still leads the league in interceptions. But no longer can
cynics sneer at ``the winless Colts.'' Now the task is to build on
it. Most of their hopes for the short term rest on RB Marshall
Faulk, who ranks second in the league in combined rushing-receiving
yardage. He could get help from recently signed FB Craig
``Ironhead'' Heyward, who can use his 262 pounds as a blocker to
try to improve Faulk's miserable 3.1 yards per carry average.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Bills 23, Colts 9
CAROLINA (0-4) AT DALLAS (3-2) Time: Noon, Sunday Site: Texas
Stadium, Irving (65,675) Series: Panthers lead 1-0 Line: Dallas by
7
</P>
<P>
   Panthers update: Talk about a downward spiral. In 1996, this
team pounded the Cowboys in the playoffs to advance to the NFC
Championship Game. Now it's 0-4 and sinking fast. Coach Dom Capers
has been hailed as a defensive genius, but it's tough to be that
smart when some of your best players, including LB Lamar Lathon,
are out with injuries. About all that's left is LB Kevin Greene, a
venerable pass-rush specialist whose nine sacks lead the league.
But stop the run? Not these Cats, who give up 134.8 rushing yards a
game. On the other hand, their opponents have been terrific against
the run _ Carolina ranks 28th in rushing offense.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys update: The Cowboys' walk through the park continues
with yet another date against a winless team, the second course of
Dallas' feast of creampuffs and marshmallows, a collection of six
opponents with a combined record of 5-24. Why, that kind of
schedule can even make another week or two of backup QB Jason
Garrett look good, especially with two-headed RB Emmitt Smith and
Chris Warren running with authority. That combination has lifted
the Cowboys to No. 2 on the NFC rushing list, which is why, as long
as Garrett doesn't turn the ball over, the Cowboys should roll over
the defenseless Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Cowboys 31, Panthers 17
KANSAS CITY (4-1) AT NEW ENGLAND (3-1) Time: Noon, Sunday Site:
Foxboro Stadium, Foxboro, Mass. (60,292) Series: Chiefs lead 14-7-3
Line: No line
</P>
<P>
   Chiefs update: As usual, QB Rich Gannon got the job done. And,
as usual, it's time for him to hand off that starting job, back to
Elvis Grbac after three wins in four outings that raised Gannon's
record as a starter to 8-2 over the last two years. But now Grbac
is back and he takes over the reins of an offense that has
performed nicely in a supporting role to the NFL's No. 1 ranked
defense. The Chiefs are opportunistic, leading the league with 16
takeaways, including an amazing 11 fumble recoveries. That projects
to 35 for the year, which would shatter the NFL record of 31, held
by the 1963 Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   Patriots update: If the Chiefs are masters of taking the ball
away, the Patriots are terrific at protecting it. New England went
three games without a turnover before QB Drew Bledsoe threw three
interceptions Sunday in New Orleans, breaking a string of 115
consecutive attempts without one. Even with the picks, Bledsoe is
one of the league's premier passers, a guy who can carry a team by
himself. The scary part is the Pats' defense, which last week made
New Orleans nobody Danny Wuerffel look like Brett Favre ... wait,
bad analogy ... make that Randall Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Chiefs 21, Patriots 20
PITTSBURGH (3-1) AT CINCINNATI (1-3) Time: Noon, Sunday Site:
Cinergy Field, Cincinnati (60,389) Series: Steelers lead 32-23
Line: Pittsburgh by 2 1/2
</P>
<P>
   Steelers update: It's been awfully ugly in Western Pennsylvania,
but somehow the Steelers are 3-1 and right behind Jacksonville for
the AFC Central lead. That despite a horribly anemic offense that
averages just 12.5 points per game, more than only pitiful
Philadelphia and Indianapolis, and a QB, Kordell Stewart, who has
been intercepted six times and has thrown just two TDs. The answers
have been a decent defense led by DB Carnell Lake and LB Levon
Kirkland and powerful RB Jerome Bettis, not to mention a bit of
luck.
</P>
<P>
   Bengals update: If you're looking for stout defense, don't
bother looking at Cinergy Field, because the Bengals are about as
defenseless as it gets, giving up 375 yards a game. Still,
Cincinnati is dangerous because WR Carl Pickens, the AFC receiving
leader, and RB Corey Dillon, one of the league's strongest power
runners, are legitimate offensive threats. And while no one would
mistake QB Neil O'Donnell with one of the elite passers, he owns
the league's best completion percentage at .667.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Steelers 13, Bengals 7
SAN FRANCISCO (3-1) AT NEW ORLEANS (3-1) Time: Noon, Sunday Site:
Louisiana Superdome, New Orleans (69,028) Series: 49ers lead
40-15-2 Line: San Francisco by 10
</P>
<P>
   49ers update: What the heck happened? It was like the most
productive offensive machine in football didn't bother coming to
the stadium, and the Oakland Raiders showed up instead, committing
an NFL record-tying 22 penalties in a ghastly loss to Buffalo. That
won't happen again. QB Steve Young and supremely talented WRs Jerry
Rice and J.J. Stokes against a defense ranked 29th against the
pass? Puh-leeze. Now, if only the Niners could figure out what's
wrong on defense _ no team has allowed more yards per game than San
Francisco's 377. Perhaps a date against the Saints will help that,
but we said the same thing about Buffalo, didn't we?
</P>
<P>
   Saints update: How exactly are the Saints doing it? In losing
last week for the first time this season, New Orleans nonetheless
gained a bit of legitimacy by taking New England down to the final
three seconds before falling. As usual, neither the offense nor the
defense posted impressive numbers, but there must be something to
this Danny Wuerffel guy, who seems to come up big in the clutch.
And maybe, just maybe, there's something to this Mike Ditka, who
has at least the players believing, if no one else.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: 49ers 49, Saints 17
TENNESSEE (1-3) AT BALTIMORE (2-2) Time: Noon, Sunday Site: Ravens
Stadium at Camden Yards, Baltimore (68,400) Series: Tied 2-2 Line:
Baltimore by 3
</P>
<P>
   Oilers update: Paging Mr. George. Mr. Eddie George. The Oilers
running back, who last year ran for 1,399 yards to finish fifth in
the league, is among the missing, with just 222 yards and an
average of 2.9 per rush this season. Without question, he has
dragged the Oilers' attack down with him, giving them the NFL's
worst ground game. That's far too much responsibility to push on a
defense that defines mediocrity, not to mention QB Steve McNair and
the passing game, which is a long way from scaring anyone.
</P>
<P>
   Ravens update: The QB controversy is over, and it's time for
Eric Zeier to show what he's got. Start with a .620 completion
percentage and a 102.4 rating, second in the AFC. Another thing he
certainly has is an explosive target in fleet Jermaine Lewis, whose
league-best average of 32.5 yards per catch is almost 10 yards
better than anyone else. Oh, yes, he also leads the league in punt
returns, with two runbacks for TDs. And don't forget RB Priest
Holmes, whose 173-yard debut as a starter two weeks ago was a
revelation.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Ravens 27, Oilers 16
WASHINGTON (0-5) AT PHILADELPHIA (0-5) Time: Noon, Sunday Site:
Veterans Stadium, Philadelphia (65,352) Series: Redskins lead
68-53-5 Line: Washington by 3
</P>
<P>
   Redskins update: They're calling this the Paper Bag Bowl, and
surely brown sacks with eyeholes cut out will be the attire of the
day for fans on both sides. If this game, doesn't sum up the horrid
NFC East, it can't be done. The Redskins are the NFC's most
generous team, having presented opponents with 13 turnovers, while
managing just two on their side. While hanging onto the ball is a
problem, moving it usually isn't, with budding star WR Michael
Westbrook anchoring the passing game and reliable RB Terry Allen
near the top of the rushing statistics. But the defense has
disappeared, especially in the red zone, where opponents score a
league-high 76.5 percent on the time.
</P>
<P>
   Eagles update: All in all, the Eagles would probably rather be
anywhere but Philadelphia, where the notoriously nasty fans won't
hesitate to savage the home team if they play like they've played
all year. Even five TDs in the last two weeks hasn't pushed the
Eagles out of last place in scoring, with just 53 points in five
games. The defense is next-to-last in the conference against the
run, giving up 5.0 yards per attempt, bad news against a tough
runner like Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Redskins 28, Eagles 8
 &LR; subheds:CHICAGO (1-4) AT ARIZONA (2-3) Time: 3:15 p.m., Sunday
Site: Sun Devil Stadium, Tempe, Ariz. (73,273) Series: Bears lead
52-25-6 Line: Arizona by 3 1/2
</P>
<P>
   Bears update: After breaking a nine-game losing streak with a
win that left Chicago four games out of first place just five weeks
into the season, some Bears were actually talking playoffs in the
locker room. They might have a chance if someone adjusted the rules
to eliminate the third quarter, in which the Bears have been bombed
61-0. QB Erik Kramer is finally living up to his big contract,
putting up a nice 92.3 rating, but the defense needs to hold up its
end of the bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals update: OK, so the Cards are 2-3 and are scoring fewer
than 17 points per game. In the NFC East, that's what we call a
good year. Arizona is just a game behind Dallas for the division
lead, and that's with the guy who's supposed to be its big star, QB
Jake Plummer, struggling with a passer rating of 65.4 and seven
interceptions. But the Cards are much better defensively, paced by
four sacks from precocious rookie DE Andre Wadsworth.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Cardinals 17, Bears 13
NEW YORK JETS (2-2) AT ST. LOUIS (1-3) Time: 3:15 p.m., Sunday
Site: Trans World Dome, St. Louis (66,000) Series: Rams lead 6-2
Line: Jets by 3 1/2
</P>
<P>
   Jets update: Vinny or Foley? It's hard to argue with Vinny
Testaverde's performance as the Jets' QB. In two-plus games, he has
posted five TDs, just one interception (on a half-ending Hail Mary)
and a 104.9 passer rating. But Glenn Foley was the starter until he
got hurt, and it says on page 47 of the Football Coach's Handbook
that you don't lose a starting job because of injury. Regardless of
who plays, the offense may be hurting because RB Curtis Martin is
questionable with a bruised thigh.
</P>
<P>
   Rams update: Robert Holcombe? Who's he? The latest savior of the
Rams' running game, which somehow has accounted for 120.8 yards per
game without a single recognizable back. But he put up 84 yards and
two scores in his first start two weeks ago, and the Rams will need
more of that to take some of the pressure off mistake-prone QB Tony
Banks, who has accounted for all of St. Louis' 10 turnovers thios
year.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Jets 31, Rams 21
SAN DIEGO (2-3) AT OAKLAND (3-2) Time: 3:15 p.m., Sunday Site:
Oakland-Alameda County Coliseum, Oakland, Calif. (63,263) Series:
Raiders lead 45-29-2 Line: No line
</P>
<P>
   Chargers update: Obviously, the Chargers are getting no help at
all from the QB position, what with Ryan Leaf saddled with the
league's lowest rating (36.5) and nine interceptions against just
one TD. So coach Kevin Gilbride has turned to RB Natrone Means to
drag the team along with him, as evidenced by Means' 31 carries
last week. Look for more of that as the Chargers try to weather
Leaf's growing pains.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders update: Practically everyone who's anyone on the Raiders
is hurt, beginning with QB Jeff George, listed as doubtful with a
strained groin, and RB Napoleon Kaufman, the AFC's third-leading
rusher, who's questionable with a sprained left ankle. That takes
away about two-thirds of the Raiders' offense and puts a huge
burden on a defense that has risen quickly behind DT Darrell
Russell and rising star CB Charles Woodson.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Chargers 17, Raiders 12
ATLANTA (3-1) AT NEW YORK GIANTS (2-3) Time: 7:20 p.m., Sunday
Site: Giants Stadium, East Rutherford, N.J. (77,716) Series: Tied
6-6 Line: Giants by 2 1/2
</P>
<P>
   Falcons update: The P-word _ that's playoffs _ is popping up in
Atlanta, and why not? The Falcons have the ingredients, with a
solid QB, a power running game and the NFC's No. 2-ranked run
defense. And they're a second-half team, outscoring opponents 42-10
after halftime. But history works against the Falcons, who are 3-1
for only the fifth time in their 33 seasons and have been 4-1 just
twice before. So does the pass defense, which has allowed opponents
to complete 62.4 percent of their passes.
</P>
<P>
   Giants update: If President Clinton weren't otherwise occupied,
he might check to see if the Giants' offense qualifies for federal
disaster relief funds. The Giants can't throw (QB Danny Kanell has
just 866 yards and eight interceptions), they can't run (a
league-worst 2.9 yards per rush average) and they sure can't hide
in the nation's No. 1 media market. A defense that has recorded 19
sacks, six by DE Mike Strahan, and seven interceptions has kept the
Giants afloat, but they're taking on water awfully quick.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Falcons 27, Giants 3
MIAMI (3-1) AT JACKSONVILLE (4-0) Time: 7:20 p.m., Monday Site:
Alltell Stadium, Jacksonville, Fla. (73,000) Series: First meeting
Line: Jacksonville by 6 1/2
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins update: It hadn't been done all year, but last week,
the Jets proved it's possible to run on the Miami defense. Now,
will the Dolphins allow that to happen again? Coach Jimmy Johnson
will get out his motivational bag of tricks for this one, a big
game against a Super Bowl contender from just up the coast. But to
get out of Jacksonville with a win, the Dolphins will have to run
more than the 15 times they tried last week and must play solid
inside defense to back it up.
</P>
<P>
   Jaguars update: RT Leon Searcy. RG Brian DeMarco. C Quentin
Neujahr. LG Ben Coleman. LT Tony Boselli. Remember their names,
because they are the reason the Jags are off to the best start in
their brief history. The Jags' dominating line is why QB Mark
Brunell rarely gets sacked (eight times this year), giving him time
to complete more than 65 percent of his passes. And it's why RB
Fred Taylor stepped right in with a pair of 100-yard performances
when James Stewart went down. And it's why Jacksonville is easily
the best team in the AFC Central.
</P>
<P>
   Pick: Miami 17, Jacksonville 14
</P>
</TEXT>
