<HEADLINE>
AIKMAN DONS PADS FOR THROWING DRILLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN LYONS and CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Cowboys quarterback Troy Aikman threw for
several minutes in his shoulder pads yesterday for the first time
since he suffered a fractured collarbone against the Denver Broncos
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys coach Chan Gailey said Aikman will continue to work out
in shoulder pads for the remainder of his rehabilitation. After
having his left collarbone X-rayed Monday, Aikman said he does not
expect to play again until Nov. 2 at Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just trying to get back in a groove,'' Gailey said.
``He felt pretty good about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his timetable for Aikman returning to the starting
lineup had changed, Gailey said, ``We're still on that X-ray
timetable.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys play host to Carolina on Sunday, travel to play the
Chicago Bears on Oct. 18 and have a bye on Oct. 25.
Blitzing Panthers
</P>
<P>
   Rookie offensive lineman Flozell Adams has impressed Cowboys
coaches with his physical ability and his mental awareness. While
Carolina possesses talented defenders, Adams' biggest challenge in
his first career start Sunday figures to be coping with the
Panthers' defensive strategy.
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers are one of the few teams who employ a 3-4 defense,
with three down linemen and four linebackers. In the Panthers'
scheme, any of the front seven can come on a blitz at any time.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare for the blitzing Panthers, Adams stayed late after
practice yesterday working with offensive line coach Hudson Houck.
Center Clay Shiver said it is imperative that he work with Adams on
blocking assignments to prevent mental mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked with Everett McIver and Nate Newton for a while,
and sometimes you take for granted what the calls are on the line.
You just know they know who to block on certain situations,''
Shiver said. ``I'll need to work more on my communication so Flo
will know who he's got. I have to make sure that I don't take what
\RAdams\S knows for granted.''
Irvin's message
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys receiver Michael Irvin wore a T-shirt this week with
this inscription on the back, ``We're claiming it back.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Irvin downplayed the message, saying he got the T-shirt
in training camp, the point was clear. After seeing their string of
five consecutive NFC East titles end last year when the New York
Giants won the division, the Cowboys came into 1998 looking to
regain their spot atop the East.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys (3-2) appear to be well on their way, with an
undefeated division record in three games. However, the Cowboys and
Irvin are nowhere close to being satisfied _ especially considering
that each victory so far has been followed by a loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't done anything yet,'' Irvin said. ``All we've done
is win, lose, win, lose, win. We've got to put it together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
