   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 10/07/98. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT33) MOSCOW -- Oct. 07, 1998 -- SUB-RUSSIA-PROTESTS, 10-07 --
Russian Communists and labor unionists lining up during a
demonstration near Red Square in Moscow on Wednesday to protest
Boris Yeltsin's rule. Along with a road block in Vladivostok, the
protests drew only a small fraction of the 10 million demonstrators
the Communists had expected. And while thousands of factories and
companies conducted short, symbolic work stoppages, life went on as
usual. (Gleb Kosorukov/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT32) ROCHESTER, N.Y. -- Oct. 07, 1998 -- NY-SENATE-POLL,
10-07 -- Rep. Charles Schumer in Rochester recently. Schumer and
Sen. Alfonse D'Amato are locked in an extraordinarily tight race
for the U.S. Senate. The outcome apparently rests with a small
group of undecided voters, many of whom are not yet paying
attention to the contest, a statewide New York Times/CBS News Poll
has found. (James Estrin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT31) WASHINGTON, England -- Oct. 07, 1998 --
BRITAIN-MONETARY, 10-07 -- Britain's economy is slowing down. ``We
are much more vulnerable than most other regions,'' says Hugh
Morgan Williams, head of Canford Audio, shown in his company's
warehouse. In the last year, he says, export earnings by his modest
company in this blustery factory park in northeastern England have
fallen because the strong British pound makes his products more
expensive for foreign buyers. (Jonathan Player/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT30) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 07, 1998 -- CONGRESS-SPEND, 10-07 --
With Sen. Tom Daschle at his side, Rep. Richard Gephardt, right,
criticizes Congressional Republicans on Wednesday. With three days
until temporary financing of the government expires, Republican
leaders met Wednesday night with White House officials in their
first high-level attempt to resolve dozens of spending issues and
avoid a government shutdown. (Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT29) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 07, 1998 -- CLINTON-LOBBY, 10-07 --
President Clinton signing an education bill in the White House on
Wednesday. Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton undertook the
delicate job of persuading wavering Democrats to support the
president on the vote set for Thursday to authorize a broad
impeachment inquiry without actually pleading for their votes.
(Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT28) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 07, 1998 -- ILL-SENATE-2, 10-07 --
Chicago Sen. Peter Fitzgerald posing Wednesday beneath a portrait
of Ronald Reagan in the office of the Senate majority leader, Trent
Lott. With less than a month to go, Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun is
losing ground in her re-election campaign against Fitzgerald, a
conservative Republican. And both candidates have dropped all
pretense of keeping the gloves on. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT27) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 07, 1998 -- ILL-SENATE-1, 10-07 --
Sen. Carol Moseley-Braun, at left, talking with Sen. Bill Frist,
R-Tenn., on Capitol Hill on Wednesday. The Chicago Senate race
between the incumbent Democrat, Ms. Moseley-Braun, and state Sen.
Peter Fitzgerald, a conservative Republican, has become one of the
most tensely watched campaigns in the country. (Justin Lane/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT26) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 07, 1998 -- CLINTON-FENCE, 10-07 --
Rep. Louise Slaughter, D-N.Y., in her Washington office. As much as
she would not mind seeing Bill Clinton out of office, Ms. Slaughter
worries that Congress is about to start down a path the Founding
Fathers never envisioned. ``I'm not interested in what happens to
Bill Clinton,'' she says. ``It's the country and the Constitution
I'm concerned about.'' (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT25) MOSCOW -- Oct. 07, 1998 -- RUSSIA-SCENE, 10-07 -- Andrei
Bobrov, left, and Vladimir Tyuterev, with long hair, want to see
the economy working again. ``There comes a time when you have to
show that you don't accept what is going on,'' says Tyuterev. ``The
situation now is such that that time has come.'' (Gleb
Kosorukov/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT24) NEW YORK -- Oct. 07, 1998 -- BBA-YANKS-INDIANS-3, 10-07
-- Scott Brosius of the Yankees hitting an RBI double in the 7th
inning against the Cleveland Indians on Wednesday. The hit tied the
score at 1-1 during game two of the American League Championship
series; the Yankees lead the series 1-0. (Chang W. Lee/New York
Times Photo)
