<SLUG> BC-BKN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEROT SPEEDS UP CITY FULL OF SLOW THINKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ In doing his civic homework, Ross Perot Jr. might have
inadvertently stumbled upon the best name ever for what he promises
will be the best sports arena ever.
</P>
<P>
   Call it The Belle Starr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belle was supposed to have had her bar pretty close to where
we're standing,'' said Perot, with the downtown skyscrapers only
two blocks away. ``At one time, back in the 1800s, this was known
as the wild side of town. Prostitution, open gambling, the works.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes, the city's fast lane for a past generation. But while
things do change, sometimes they really don't. A fast lane of
another kind _ not just for Dallas, but all of North Texas _ is
being planned in the legendary Ms. Starr's old neighborhood, north
of downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Before here, however, the same was happening in Arlington. And
in Grand Prairie. And in far north Fort Worth.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas, with a longstanding sordid resume by civic leaders on
understanding the business benefits of sports, now checks in last.
It won't be least, however, if Perot pulls off this arena grand
scheme.
</P>
<P>
   In the past five years, The Ballpark in Arlington has opened.
Lone Star Park at Grand Prairie has opened. The Texas Motor
Speedway has opened. In baseball, thoroughbred racing and
automobile racing, all are nationally recognized as showpiece,
best-in-the-country facilities.
</P>
<P>
   To the credit of Tex Schramm and city of Irving leaders from
three generations ago, Texas Stadium remains one of football's top
venues, 26 years later.
</P>
<P>
   The one common factor, of course, is Dallas had first crack at
the Cowboys, the Rangers, the horses, the cars. And Dallas blew it,
proving Amon Carter Sr. correct. When it comes to sports, this
place has always been a sack-lunch kind of town.
</P>
<P>
   Smart and prosperous businessmen, however, are always on scent.
They can smell money 10 miles away. The fiscal health of sports in
North Texas needs no other explanation than the entry of a Perot
and a Tom Hicks into the team ownership ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, Perot had to ask if basketball was played five
to a side _ he was asking ``after'' he had purchased the Mavericks.
At the same time, Hicks admittedly had no love or clue about ice
hockey when he wrote the check for the Stars. Both those
transactions were originally done in the name of business.
</P>
<P>
   Perot, for his part, mostly saw real estate heaven attached to
the Mavericks, as in a new downtown arena for both the basketball
and the hockey teams. A street fight of a city election in January
cleared the way for an arena _ by a mere 1,100 votes.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Perot has to deliver, and the initial step comes today at a
news conference to outline the plans for an immense urban project
including arena, retail shops, business offices, entertainment
complex and apartments. All of it right there next to the
skyscrapers.
</P>
<P>
   What Perot has promised is the best sports and concert arena in
the country. What he also plans is a massive development around the
arena, that being dependent upon market conditions. The doubters in
Dallas hound him on that development part, but those doubters
didn't want the arena either.
</P>
<P>
   Calmly, Perot stays in the fast lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want, is 10 years from now, grandfathers bringing
grandkids down here and telling them how their vote helped build
this for Dallas,'' he said. ``Even if there were a no vote in the
election, I don't want them to be able to admit it.''
</P>
<P>
   A century ago, there were probably grandfathers who also
wouldn't admit they visited Belle Starr's joint in the same area of
town. And for what it's worth, Hicks started off being strictly a
build-the-arena advocate. He cared little for the project beyond
the arena. Hicks and Perot were also at odds on most other issues,
even though their teams will share the arena.
</P>
<P>
   But two weeks ago, Hicks called Perot's development plan
surrounding the arena ``one of the best I've ever seen.'' He also
praised Perot for the design work on the arena. It would not be
far-fetched to think of Hicks as an eventual partner in the
Mavericks, plus an eventual partner in the entire real estate
project. Hicks, of course, has a business reputation of knowing
where and when to place his money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The centerpiece is the arena,'' Perot said. ``Everything will
revolve around that. From a sports standpoint, this means I have to
personally make this Mavericks thing work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tom has the Stars on the verge of a Stanley Cup, and this will
be an arena and a development designed for only the best _ only for
championship-caliber teams, not secondary teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, OK, Perot is also a dreamer. The Mavericks, at the moment,
won't even rank as one of Belle Starr's preferred customers, even
in Belle's old place.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this arena is being built to be functional for 50 years,''
Perot added.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe there's future hope, give or take a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Most amazing, however, is Perot's new Belle Starr, if
expectations are met, will finally catch Dallas up with the
Arlingtons, Fort Worths, Grand Prairies and Irvings.
</P>
<P>
   Sports-wise, the fast lane is about to arrive in a city of slow
thinkers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
