<HEADLINE>
MAKING DIVISION SERIES BEST-OF-SEVEN ON AGENDA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Baseball's general managers might advocate changing
the division series to a best-of-seven format rather than the
current five-game format.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's John Schuerholz said the subject will be discussed
next month at the general managers' annual off-season meetings in
Naples, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the right thing to do,'' Schuerholz said. ``By it's very
nature, a short five-game series doesn't give you as full a look at
the relative strengths and weaknesses of a club as a seven-game
series does.''
</P>
<P>
   The World Series has been best-of-seven since 1921. The League
Championship Series was a best-of-five until going to the
seven-game format in 1985.
Brown prefers NL
</P>
<P>
   Padres pitcher Kevin Brown is eligible for free agency after the
season and said he would prefer to pitch in the National League.
But he doesn't rule out the Rangers, who are looking to add
starting pitching in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not ruling out anybody and we're not putting any team
ahead of another,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Brown has pitched for four teams in the past five years. He won
21 games for the Rangers in 1992, but was 7-9 with a 4.82
earned-run average in 1994 before leaving as a free agent. He spent
one year with Baltimore, then flourished in the National League. He
is 51-25 with a 2.33 ERA over the past three seasons, two with the
Marlins and one with the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to say I do enjoy the game in the National League more,
because the pitchers are more involved,'' Brown said. ``We may not
hit very well, but we get to take \Rbatting practice\S and it's
fun. The style of play I do enjoy more, no doubt.''
He said it
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this business-type attitude hasn't gotten the job
done. I fully expect every time we do something good, for guys to
get off the bench. I think the team needs to thrive on these
situations and let off a little steam.'' _ Braves third baseman
Chipper Jones.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
