<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5160 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BO     10-07 0825
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCORE ONE FOR ATROCIOUS OFFICIATING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The game turned, as so many do, on a bad call by an
American League umpire. A would-be classic baseball game became
another reason to revamp the system that assigns the men in blue.
</P>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians beat the Yankees, 4-1, in 12 innings of
Game 2 of the AL Championship Series Wednesday night. There were
numerous heroes and goats as the Tribe knotted the series, 1-1, but
home plate umpire Ted Hendry _ nicknamed Heads or Tails Hendry by
one AL manager _ made himself the story when he missed a call and
opened the gates for the Indians in the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   Hendry's sin was not calling interference on Cleveland's Travis
Fryman, who failed to stay in the proper baserunning lane as he ran
out a sacrifice bunt with one on and none out in the 12th. Yankee
first baseman Tino Martinez's throw hit Fryman in the back, and
pinch runner Enrique Wilson scored from first as Yankee second
baseman Chuck Knoblauch stood arguing.
</P>
<P>
   We should mention here that umpires for the postseason are
assigned according to rotation. Merit has nothing to do with it.
You ump the playoffs simply because it is your turn. This in part
explains the continuing calamity of officiating in baseball's big
event.
</P>
<P>
   You don't have to go all the way back to Larry Barnett's gaffe
in the 1975 World Series _ a noncall of interference that helped
the Reds beat the Red Sox. You can just return to 1996 when Richie
Garcia didn't see Jeffrey Maier reach over the fence and turn a
Derek Jeter fly ball into a home run in the ALCS. Better yet, go
back to last week when Joe Brinkman lost control of the second game
of the Red Sox-Cleveland Division Series. AL umps are the most
incompetent group of officials in professional sports. They answer
only to their union chief, Richie Phillips. And their arrogance is
boundless.
</P>
<P>
   The play Wednesday night went like this: Wilson was on first
when Fryman bunted down the first base line. Martinez fielded the
ball but hesitated as Fryman ran on the infield grass toward first
base. The rule states that the baserunner has to stay on the right
side of the baseline once he gets to the halfway mark. Fryman did
not. When Martinez finally threw, the ball hit Fryman on the back
just as he was getting to the base. Knoblauch, ordinarily a
heads-up player, compounded the woe by standing and arguing with
the umps instead of chasing the ball. Wilson scored from first and
the Tribe were en route to a three-run inning.
</P>
<P>
   Yankee manager Joe Torre made no attempt to hide his disgust.
``(Hendry) gave me some kind of reasoning that (Fryman) had to get
out of those restraining lines to touch the base, but he was never
in those lines. It was so blatant. It was a terrible call. For one
guy to say what he saw and for another guy (first base umpire John
Shulock) to swear by it, and meanwhile, you have it on video. You
know the video's going to embarrass you. He was on the grass all
the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Crew chief Jim Evans, the man with whom Pedro Martinez feuded
all year, said, ``You can be in fair territory. There is nothing
illegal about going to the pitcher's mound on your way to the base.
The question is, do you interfere with a throw? If he did, then we
got a different situation. In professional baseball, if the runner
is in fair territory, then he can be called out if he interferes
with a throw that has a chance to retire the runner. In this case,
the problem happened right at the base. That is what Ted Hendry
based his ruling on _ the fact that he has a right to be in fair
territory at the base. It's not a visual obstruction-type play.
They used to teach catchers to throw and hit the runner.''
</P>
<P>
   After 10 minutes of doublespeak, Evans finally said, ``I thought
the call could have gone either way, but I thought he made the
proper call in that siutation.''
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland manager Mike Hargrove, not one to rock the boat when
the umps erred in his favor, said, ``I thought it was the right
call. I might not have thought that if I was on the other side. We
don't care how we get the win as long as it's ours.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre wasn't afraid to address the larger issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the best umpires should be here on merit,'' he said.
``The ball-and-strike stuff stunk tonight, but that stunk for both
sides. I don't think you could have reached a lot of these pitches
with bamboo sticks. He was bad on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cleveland's a good team, and you would have liked for the
thing to be clean. But you got to have better umpiring than that.
It leaves a bad taste. It's bad for baseball. That particular play
was so blatant. I'm not sure we'd have won the game, but you don't
want to lose it that way.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the series is tied. It's New York 1, Cleveland 1, Umpires
0.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
