u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-EDWARDS-BOS &LR;      10-07 0813
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-EDWARDS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RIVERBOAT GAMBLING INDICTMENTS EXPECTED SOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CURTIS WILKIE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ Former Governor Edwin W. Edwards, his son, and
several of his political associates are expected to be indicted
within days, sources close to the case said Wednesday, in
connection with a scheme to award Louisiana's last
riverboat-gambling license to a company headed by San Francisco
49ers owner Edward DeBartolo Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The action would represent the latest step in a long federal
investigation of Edwards that has roiled Louisiana's political
waters since public revelations in spring 1997 that FBI agents
seized a $400,000 cash payment from DeBartolo to Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   It would be the third time in two decades that the flamboyant
Edwards has faced federal charges. Edwards, 71, was twice tried on
racketeering charges while he was governor in the 1980s and was
found not guilty.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday Edwars maintained his innocence following a court
hearing in which DeBartolo pleaded guilty and admitted that Edwards
had demanded a payoff for his efforts to win the gambling license.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had victimized him, I would have done it for a lot more
than $400,000,'' said Edwards, who attended the hearing as a
spectator. Outside the courtroom, he called DeBartolo ``the new
Linda Tripp.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards and his son are expected to be indicted on extortion
charges in federal court in Baton Rouge, the sources said, while
several associates are to be indicted in connection with the
handling of DeBartolo's money.
</P>
<P>
   While the case provides new peril for Edwards, it also throws
the state's troubled gambling industry into further disarray.
According to transcripts of Edwards's conversations that were
captured by federal wiretaps, the former governor talked of
delivering the votes of the state Gaming Control Board.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this taint hanging over the Gaming Control Board, we
don't know what will happen,'' said C.B. Forgotston, the leading
critic of gambling in Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   The board was scheduled to rule later this month on a proposal
by a Harrah's subsidiary to reorganize after bankruptcy. A
favorable move would enable Harrah's to resume construction of a
giant casino in New Orleans. The project, once called the world's
largest casino, has been held in abeyance for nearly two years.
</P>
<P>
   When the state legalized gambling earlier in the decade,
provisions were made for 15 riverboat casinos and one huge
land-based gambling emporium here. Unlike neighboring Mississippi,
which gives licenses to all qualified applicants and operates a
gambling industry that has been profitable and relatively free of
corruption, battles for the limited number of licenses in Louisiana
have touched off political infighting and brought cries of
favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, a high-stakes gambler who is a frequent visitor to Las
Vegas and once escorted two planeloads of contributors on a
gambling expedition to Europe, presided over the legalization of
gambling in the last of his four terms as governor.
</P>
<P>
   According to documents submitted in federal court in Baton Rouge
this week by US Attorney Eddie Jordan, the governor called
DeBartolo in December 1994, reminded him of his friendship with
DeBartolo's late father, who owned a fashionable shopping center in
New Orleans, and expressed the hope that he would continue to have
what Edwards called a ``business'' relationship.
</P>
<P>
   Several conversations between Edwards and DeBartolo took place
after Edwards left office at the end of 1995, at a time when
DeBartolo was involved in a joint venture to win the state's 15th
and final riverboat license.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors say an officer of DeBartolo Entertainment Louisiana
Gaming Inc., a wing of the DeBartolo family enterprises, is
prepared to testify that Edwards and his son, Stephen Edwards,
first called for a $50,000-a-month ``sham consulting agreement''
that would funnel money to Edwards's son. Edwards also wanted a
``price-per-head'' for each customer at the prospective casino, the
prosecution papers contend.
</P>
<P>
   At a meeting with DeBartolo at a Baton Rouge hotel in March
1997, Edwards was said to have shown a sheet of paper with the
figure $400,000 written on it. According to the prosecutors,
Edwards told DeBartolo ``he needed the money before the vote, and,
if he did not receive it, there could be problems with the
application.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo agreed to cooperate with prosecutors in order to get a
light sentence, two years probation coupled with fines and
forfeitures that add up to $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, the chief prosecutor, called upon other witnesses to
board ``a train that's leaving the station, the train of justice.''
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo, meanwhile, said he hoped to be able to regain control
of the 49ers, a position he relinquished after he came under
investigation.
</P>
</TEXT>
