r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ATLANTA-SCENE-TEX     10-07 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ATLANTA-SCENE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSEUM DOCUMENTS BRAVES' BIGGEST SAVE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Braves almost blew it. There was almost no Hank
Aaron Way in Atlanta, no bust outside Turner Field and no statue
commemorating his historic home run.
</P>
<P>
   They almost let him get away to the New York Giants, where he
would have been paired with Willie Mays in the greatest outfield
ever. Who cares who would have played left field.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves had an option on the services of a 17-year-old
shortstop from the Indianapolis Clowns of the Negro Leagues. But
Braves farm director John Mullen almost missed the deadline,
sending the historic telegram 10 minutes before their option
expired. Otherwise, the Giants would have obtained his rights.
</P>
<P>
   Papers uncovered in the Braves Museum last night before Game 1
of the National League Championship Series at Turner Field document
what happened 46 years ago ...
</P>
<P>
   Sometime in 1952, while the franchise was in Boston, Braves
scout Dewey Griggs wired the following message to Mullen:
</P>
<P>
   ``Indianapolis plays two games with Kansas City at Buffalo, and
at that time, I will give you a complete story on the boy. I am
satisfied with the boy's hitting. However I want to see him make
plays to both his right and left, and slow balls he has to come in
after. Also another look at his throwing ...''
</P>
<P>
   Griggs ended his message by saying, ``This boy could be the
answer.''
</P>
<P>
   On May 25, three days before the Braves option expired, Griggs
filed the following scouting report:
</P>
<P>
   ``The 17-year-old shortstop of the Indianapolis club looks very
good. In the first game, he had seven chances, two fly balls back
of third and five hard grounders ... started one double play ...
went 3-for-5 ... two line-drive singles and a perfect bunt. ... His
only error was a low throw from deep shortstop. ... In the second
game, he accepted five chances without an error ... started one
double play. Hit 3-for-4.''
</P>
<P>
   Mullen immediately telephoned Syd Pollock, general manager of
the Clowns, and received the following message on May 27:
</P>
<P>
   ``Re: our phone conversation, lowest deal I would consider on
our shortstop would be $10,000, with $2,500 down payment, the
balance to be paid after a 30-day look and a salary of $350 monthly
...
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel this youngster is another Ted Williams in the hitting
department and can hit to all fields, as well as lay down bunts,
and his fielding right now leaves little to be desired, outside a
little bit of polishing getting off his throws ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have looked into his draft status \Ra reference to the
Korean War\S and he is apt to be drafted by next spring, therefore
cannot guarantee delivery. But for his caliber of ballplayer and
his age, he is worth waiting two years for should he be called into
the service.''
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, with only 10 minutes left before the Braves'
option expired, Mullen sent the following telegram, written in the
finest legalese back to Pollock:
</P>
<P>
   ``This will acknowledge and accept the proposition contained in
our letter of May 27, 1952, and confirmed in our telephone
conversation of this date wherein you agree to release the contract
of the player, Henry Aaron, to the Evansville club of the Three I
League for the sum of $2,500 payable to the Indianapolis Clowns
upon the promulgation of the players contract by the National
Association of Professional Baseball Leagues and a further sum of
$7,500 payable to the Indianapolis Clowns if we retain the player
under contract 30 or more days after he reports to the club.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves retained him beyond 30 days and he was not drafted.
He did not have to fight in Korea. He played in Eau Claire (Wis.)
in 1952 and Jacksonville the following year. He joined the Braves
in 1954 and spent the next 21 years with them.
</P>
<P>
   The uniform he wore and the Louisville Slugger bat he used on
April 5, 1974, are in the Braves Museum, for it was on that night
he stepped to the plate and faced Dodgers pitcher Al Downing.
</P>
<P>
   The game was on national television and, in the fourth inning,
NBC's Curt Gowdy made the call:
</P>
<P>
   ``That ball is hit deep ... deep ... it's gone! He did it! He
did it! Hank Aaron, the all-time home run leader now.''
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire eclipsed Roger Maris' single-season record in 1998,
but a quarter-century later, Henry Aaron, the 17-year-old shortstop
from the Indianapolis Clowns who could bunt, who could be the
answer, who could be the next Ted Williams, stands alone.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
