</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLL-CLINTON-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WASHINGTON STATE POLL, MOST OPPOSE IMPEACHING CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY and MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ After months of allegations and revelations in the
Monica Lewinsky affair, only a third of Washington state voters
feel that Congress should impeach President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   In a statewide poll of 810 Washington citizens, all
self-described regular voters, a combined total of 64 percent said
Congress should either censure Clinton or drop the investigation
entirely.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is we are not seeing an increase in the number
of people who would remove Clinton from office. ... These are
almost the same numbers I am getting in New York, Maryland and
Arkansas,'' said Del Ali, senior vice president of Mason-Dixon
Political/Media Research, which conducted the poll.
</P>
<P>
   But, added Portland-based pollster Tim Hibbitts after seeing the
figures, ``A third of the voters detest this man and would go for
burning at the stake if they could.''
</P>
<P>
   A solid if reduced majority, 54 percent, continued to give
Clinton good or excellent marks on his performance in office.
Another 21 percent gave the president fair marks, while 25 percent
rated his performance as poor. In a similar poll a month ago, which
asked the question differently, 65 percent said they approved of
Clinton's performance as president.
</P>
<P>
   Only 37 percent of the state's voters this time have a favorable
personal opinion of the president, a figure 5 percent lower than
Clinton's favorable rating in last month's poll, taken just before
special prosecutor Kenneth Starr's report was made public.
</P>
<P>
   The survey was conducted on Oct. 5 and 6 for the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer and KOMO-TV in Seattle. It had a margin of error
of plus or minus 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll's major findings include:
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Resignation: Sixty percent of those surveyed said Clinton
should not resign, compared to 35 percent who said he should leave
office. The figures were similar to those in the September poll. In
that survey, taken on the eve of Starr's report, 33 percent favored
resignation while 62 percent were opposed.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Punishment: Given three options, 33 percent of those
surveyed said Congress should immediately proceed to remove
President Clinton from office.
</P>
<P>
   Another 37 percent said that Clinton should be censured but
allowed to remain in office; 27 percent said the matter should be
dropped quickly.
</P>
<P>
   (BBOX)Congress and Starr: The survey showed Washington voters
evenly divided in the way that the Republican-controlled Congress
has handled issues related to possible impeachment: 45 percent
approved while 44 percent disapproved.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 44 percent said they approved of the way Starr has
handled the investigation of Clinton: 51 percent disapproved of
Starr's performance.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the divisions, Ali commented: ``This whole
impeachment thing is now partisan, which is good for Clinton.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll on Clinton's performance showed a yawning gender gap
among Washington voters. Women are opposed to resignation in
substantially greater numbers than men. And just 39 percent of
women approved of Starr's performance, while 55 percent
disapproved; 49 percent of men approved of Starr's handling of his
job and 47 percent disapproved.
</P>
<P>
   A total of 46 percent of men surveyed gave Clinton an
``excellent'' or ``good'' performance rating; 62 percent of women
gave the president high marks.
</P>
<P>
   ``On balance, women like his policies. It's not that they
approve of his behavior, but they feel on balance he has been a
decent president,'' Hibbitts said.
</P>
<P>
   Karen Aanes, 64, of Tacoma, part-owner of an electric sign
business, was one of those interviewed in the poll. ``I think he's
done a good job in his position as president,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She took a dim view of congressional Republicans who are
launching an impeachment investigation. ``They're blowing it
completely out of proportion to make a big stink in an election
year,'' she said. ``Nine out of any 10 of them have done the same
thing. They're just lucky enough not to get caught.''
</P>
<P>
   A contrasting view came from Charles Genther, 71, of Seattle,
who manages industrial property after retiring after a 37-year
career in the chemical business.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has continually obstructed justice,'' Genther said of
Clinton. ``He lied right to my face on television. If he doesn't
know the meaning of the word `is,' he shouldn't be in the White
House. ... My God, if I did that in court, I would be put in jail.
For the president to do it, again and again, the only thing is for
him to resign or, if he won't resign, to impeach him.''
</P>
<P>
   But opinions did not break down strictly by gender. Stephanie
Porcella, 52, a nurse from Bremerton, took a hard line on the
question of whether to drop the investigation, or settle for a
censure of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you drop it, you tell the whole country that it is okay to
lie under oath,'' Porcella said. ``I have four kids and I don't
want them raised that way. To sit there and censure him doesn't
deal with the problem. There is no option but to have the man
impeached.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Wilson, 74, a retired teacher from Edmonds, was more
sympathetic to the president, praising Clinton's performance in
office and arguing that Starr and the Republicans ``have just been
working until they could get something on him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They keep talking about being Christian but they will cast the
first stone no matter what,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's defenders stressed his performance in office, and
criticized Congress for devoting its time and energy to impeachment
rather than other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've wasted time chasing Clinton rather than taking care of
the budget and other issues. They haven't dealt with the business
at hand,'' said Terry Frost, 48, a mechanical designer from
Longview.
</P>
<P>
   Frost added that Clinton ``seens to work pretty good under
pressure'' and noted that the president has been under unrelenting
scrutiny since taking office in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 60 percent of those surveyed said their opinion of
Clinton will have no effect on their vote on congressional races
this November. But 15 percent said they will more likely vote
Democratic, and 25 percent said there is a greater likelihood they
will vote Republican.
</P>
<P>
   The gender gap prevailed once more. Only 7 percent of men
surveyed were more likely to vote Democratic, compared with 29
percent more likely to vote Republican. Women were split almost
evenly with 23 percent saying they are more likely to vote for a
Democrat, and 21 percent more likely to vote Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Bader, a leading Republican consultant, predicted that the
Clinton factor will be of ``marginal help'' to his party. ``It's a
mistake for Republicans to anticipate a big 1994-style anti-Clinton
backlash,'' he said. ``I do think in races that are tight, the edge
goes to the Republicans because of the scandal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
