<SLUG> BC-POLL-MURRAY-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEN. PATTY MURRAY HAS COMFORTABLE LEAD IN RE-ELECTION BID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON and JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a year when Democrats in general and female
senators in particular are running scared, Sen. Patty Murray,
D-Wash., is comfortably ahead of her re-election challenger, Rep.
Linda Smith, R-Wash., according to a statewide Seattle
Post-Intelligencer/KOMO News 4 poll.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, conducted Monday and Tuesday, found 51 percent of
likely voters plan to support Murray on Nov. 3, while 38 percent
plan to support Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found Murray, a Seattle resident first elected in 1992,
running strongly ahead of Smith among women and in the central
Puget Sound region. Smith, elected to the House in 1994, leads only
in her home base of southwest Washington and in Republican-leaning
central Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``In an nutshell, this is Patty Murray's race to lose, and I
would be shocked if she lost the race,'' said pollster Del Ali.
``Murray would have to self-destruct ... she would have to say
something or do something absolutely stupid for her to lose this.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll was conducted by Mason-Dixon Political/Media Research
Inc., which interviewed 810 likely voters from around the state.
The poll has a margin of error of 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll's findings contrast Murray's situation with that of the
two other female senators elected in 1992, the so-called Year of
the Woman. Sen. Carol Mosely-Braun, D-Ill., is widely expected to
lose her re-election bid, while Sen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., is
running neck-and-neck with her challenger.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said she is pleased by the poll results, which echoed the
findings of her own pollster.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of momentum going, and the campaign is really
moving,'' she said. ``We now have 40,000 individual contributors,
which is really heart-warming, and the issues I'm talking about _
education, the environment and safe communities _ are issues people
care about.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's campaign professed not to be concerned by the poll
findings, and both campaigns acknowledge that the race will likely
tighten in coming weeks. Smith's position against Murray in polls
has strengthened slightly over time, and polls have often
underestimated Smith's strength among voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just a snapshot in time, taken when nobody has really
examined Patty Murray's record,'' said Smith spokesman Jim Troyer.
``When people find out about Linda and her record, they are very
excited about her.''
</P>
<P>
   The Smith campaign is counting on two major factors to change
the dynamic of the race in the remaining four weeks: television ads
and debates.
</P>
<P>
   Smith went on the air this week with television ads for the
first time since the Sept. 15 primary. Murray, who has a
significantly larger campaign warchest than Smith, has been on the
air non-stop since mid-August.
</P>
<P>
   All of the advertising to date has been positive, although Smith
has been testing in focus groups an ad that criticizes Murray as
ineffective. Smith's current ad talks about Social Security, while
Murray's current ads talk about her general accomplishments as well
as her fight against Internet pornography.
</P>
<P>
   But negative ads could be a mixed blessing for Smith; the poll
found that since the primary, voters have come to view Murray less
favorably, but they also have come to view Smith less favorably.
Murray is now viewed favorably by 48 percent of voters and
unfavorably by 30 percent, while Smith is viewed favorably by 38
percent and unfavorably by 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The two have tentatively agreed to face off at one debate, on
Oct. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect the Senate race to be closer than the poll
indicates,'' said GOP consultant Brett Bader, who said undecided
voters are likely to break Smith's way. ``I expect the race will
narrow. It's unlikely undecided voters will go to the incumbent.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll found that Murray has a 56 to 33 percent lead among
women, but only a 46 to 43 percent lead among men.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why women favor her campaign, Murray said, ``I say what
they would say if they had the opportunity to be here. Like me,
they are taking care of kids and parents, and they know I bring
those issues to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Pollster Ali said that on some issues of importance to women _
education, crime and abortion rights _ Murray is stronger than
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Among overall voters, a candidate's character is the most
important issue in this election, followed by education, taxation,
the economy and health care, according to the poll. But among women
the top issue is education, an issue that Murray talks about
constantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the last few weeks of this race are about school vouchers,
abortion or guns, Smith's going to get her butt handed to her,''
Ali said. ``Smith needs to go after Murray and ask what Patty
Murray has brought to the state.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll found Murray with a huge lead among voters in the
central Puget Sound area (King, Snohomish, Kitsap and Pierce
counties), where she leads Smith 59 percent to 33 percent; an 11
percent lead in northwest Washington, and a 4 percent lead in
eastern Washington. Smith leads Murray by 9 percent in southwest
Washington, the area she represents in Congress, and by six percent
in central Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Smith will need to look for more women like Sue-Ann Mickelson, a
35-year-old bookkeeper from Battle Ground, who said, ``In the
beginning, I could see Patty Murray was a mom, and I thought she
was for some good things, but to me, she's gone way too liberal,
and supports a lot of liberal money-spending issues I do not agree
with.''
</P>
<P>
   But Murray can take heart from women like Barbara Wilson, a
74-year-old retired teacher from Edmonds, who said of Smith ``she's
just like most of the Christian Coalition people. She's too
dogmatic, too concerned about herself and her own career rather
than the needs of others.'' Of Murray, Wilson said, ``She's really
been trying to fight for a number of things helpful to us. One is
on abortion, the right for women to have a choice.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
