<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0471 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 22:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5202 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-UCLA-MITCHELL-LAD     10-07 0905
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-MITCHELL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INJURED MITCHELL HAS SUPPORT SYSTEM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Freddie Mitchell awoke from surgery at Houston's
Methodist Hospital about three weeks ago with his parents by his
side, a rod in his leg and a slew of questions about the future.
</P>
<P>
   How would he return to Los Angeles? Once there, how would he
navigate campus? What about his rehabilitation program? What
services were available to handicapped athletes? How would he eat?
Who paid for the surgery?
</P>
<P>
   His parents, Joyce and Freddie Sr., had few answers. They
weren't even sure if UCLA would pay for the flight to Houston from
their home in Lakeland, Fla. _ a flight they boarded soon after
seeing Mitchell break his left femur against Houston on Sept. 19.
Mitchell will miss the rest of the season, his absence felt even
more deeply after the suspension of tailback Jermaine Lewis for
Saturday's game against No.10 Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   In the following days, it became clear to the Mitchells: The
grotesque injury would trigger the academic, medical and social
support services available to injured athletes at UCLA and around
the country. It's a hidden aspect of college athletics, but perhaps
the most important.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did a very professional job in the total situation,
starting from the time of the incident,'' Freddie Sr. said. ``I've
been very impressed with the services provided (by UCLA and the
NCAA). It's been very humanitarian. We haven't seen any color
lines, or any racial lines. It's been all love lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Preparations for Mitchell's return began that Monday morning _
two days before UCLA assistant trainer Tony Spino would fly to
Houston and escort Mitchell back to Westwood.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Stephens, director of student-athlete services, reviewed
Mitchell's financial forms and determined he qualified for federal
aid (a Pell Grant). That enabled UCLA to reimburse Mitchell's
parents for their flight, transportation, meals and lodging in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The funding came not from the football budget, but from a
$44,000 Special Assistance Fund filtered from the NCAA through the
Pacific-10 Conference to its member institutions. UCLA's insurance
paid for Mitchell's surgery and hospital stay.
</P>
<P>
   Stephens relayed the financial information to Randy Taylor,
director of football operations, and Geoff Schaadt, the head
trainer, who were in constant communication with Mitchell and his
parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called Freddie on Sunday, talked to him for maybe 10
minutes, and by the time we got off the phone he was cheering me
up,'' Taylor said. ``The kid was amazing. He said, `Make sure you
don't recruit a receiver to take my place. I'll be back next
fall.'''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell returned eight days before the fall quarter began.
Campus housing agreed to let Mitchell and his roommate, kicker
Chris Griffin, move to their Sunset Village Apartments several days
early. (They had been living elsewhere during training camp and the
first weeks of September.) In addition, they were assigned a
first-floor room with a handicapped shower.
</P>
<P>
   Initially, Mitchell couldn't raise his leg without help. Schaadt
and his staff visited every few hours. They brought food and drink
_ until classes began, dormitory meal service was unavailable _ and
performing rudimentary therapy to contain the swelling. Cards and
flowers poured in, and so did the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every guy on the team came by at least once,'' Griffin said.
``The first day, Freddie was fine until the team came. Once they
got to talking, that's when he broke down.''
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell started with a walker, then graduated to crutches. His
therapy has expanded in turn. Schaadt uses electrical stimulation
and a series of exercises (including the Lifecycle) to increase
Mitchell's range of motion. He does not wear a cast or a brace. The
steel rod and two interlocking screws provide all the stability he
needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked terrible on replay... but I expect Freddie to be 100
percent by (spring practice),'' Schaadt said. ``Everybody talks
about him losing a step, but there's no reason he should.''
</P>
<P>
   Once classes began, Mitchell qualified for the services provided
by UCLA's Office for Students with Disabilities. (All University of
California schools have one.) The office provides counseling,
workshops, registration assistance, notetakers, support groups and
campus-wide transportation service. Each morning Mitchell eases
into a van, which whisks him from class to class, building to
building. Fearing dependency, he has taken to walking home from the
training room after physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   As the fall quarter approached, the academic services department
kicked into gear. Director Sheila Gardette adjusted Mitchell's
schedule, eliminating classes with labs, which require not only
extra time but also an additional building. Assistant director Ed
Kezirian notified the professors that a disabled student could
shuffle into their lectures a few minutes late.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell is taking science, history and music; he may add a
fourth class if manageable. He usually sits in the front row (more
leg room) but sometimes opts for the rear if a free table is
available. His tutoring is in Covel Commons, a few feet from Sunset
Village Apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have great facilities, great everything,'' he said. ``If
I need anything, I've got a lot of love and support.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
