A5216 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT &LR;      10-07 0637
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   REPUBLICANS IN AGREEMENT ON BANKRUPTCY OVERHAUL
</P>
<P>
   House and Senate Republicans agreed on a sweeping overhaul of
the bankruptcy system, making it more difficult for consumers to
walk away from their debts and handing the banking and credit-card
industries a victory.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement was reached without the consent of congressional
Democrats or the White House, and administration officials said
they would recommend that President Clinton veto the bill because
of its treatment of low-income consumers.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT UNDER THE MICROSCOPE
</P>
<P>
   A close look at Microsoft's no-holds-barred push into the
Internet software business offers a window into the ways the
company uses its market muscle to influence the behavior of
virtually every player in the industry.
</P>
<P>
   HOPE OF RECOVERY BOLSTERS NIKKEI
</P>
<P>
   The Liberal Democratic Party, the governing party of Japan,
edged closer to injecting huge amounts of money into the banking
system, and that prospect sent investors rushing into markets with
greater hope of an economic recovery. The benchmark Nikkei average
of 225 shares soared 803.97 points, or 6.2 percent, to 13,825.61.
</P>
<P>
   NO UNIFIED APPROACH TO GLOBAL CRISIS
</P>
<P>
   The world's finance ministers and its central bankers ended five
days of debate with nothing approaching a strategy to lift the
global markets out of their downward spiral.
</P>
<P>
   TALKS PICK UP ON IMF FINANCING
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration and congressional Republicans said
they were working frantically to agree on legislation to provide
$18 billion to the International Monetary Fund.
</P>
<P>
   RAYTHEON RAISES NUMBER OF LAYOFFS
</P>
<P>
   Raytheon said it would add to previously announced layoffs and
would not meet expectations for third-quarter earnings. The company
now plans to shed 14,000 jobs, or roughly 16 percent of its work
force.
</P>
<P>
   PENNSYLVANIA HOUSE AIDS ALLIED BID
</P>
<P>
   Shares of AMP rose as much as 6.3 percent as investors expressed
optimism that legislation passed by the Pennsylvania House of
Representatives could help Allied Signal in its $9.7 billion
takeover bid for the company.
</P>
<P>
   DEALS SHOW STRENGTH OF AMAZON
</P>
<P>
   Despite proposed mergers among online merchants in both books
and music, and a sharp decline in the stock price of Amazon.com,
analysts argued that it was Amazon's competition that should be
worried because of the retailer's dominance. There is increasing
concern about whether the No. 2 player can survive.
</P>
<P>
   Yahoo, the online directory, reported another quarter of robust
growth, helping restore some investor confidence to the volatile
Internet sector. Yahoo said it earned $16.7 million, or 15 cents a
share, in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   CLOSING HINTS AT CRACKDOWN IN CHINA
</P>
<P>
   China's shutdown of a prominent state-run investment company
shows that Beijing may finally be getting tough with insolvent
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN TO EXAMINE INTEREST RATES
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of England's secretive Monetary Policy Committee is
meeting as British businesses clamor for lower interest rates and a
weaker pound.
</P>
<P>
   SIGNS OF A TURNAROUND IN TECHNOLOGY
</P>
<P>
   With Advanced Micro Devices reporting a surprise return to
profitability, Motorola projecting new growth, and the
Semiconductor Industry Association reporting the first sequential
monthly sales growth since November, more voices joined the chorus
proclaiming a turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   GM BEGINNING HUGE AD CAMPAIGN
</P>
<P>
   General Motors plans to begin one of the largest advertising
campaigns ever in the auto industry, a $135 million effort to
promote a complete redesign of the company's best-selling vehicle,
the full-sized Chevrolet Silverado pickup truck.
</P>
</TEXT>
