<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0480 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 23:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5294 &Cx1f; tth-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLL-BLAME-SPI &LR;      10-07 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLL-BLAME-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLL INDICATES VOTERS BELIEVE CLINTON BROUGHT IT ALL ON HIMSELF  
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOEL CONNELLY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ While differing over whether to remove President
Clinton from office, many of the voters surveyed in a new
Washington state poll tend to agree about who is responsible for
the messy, seemingly endless investigation of the 42nd president _
Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, conducted by Mason-Dixon Political/Media Research,
asked the question: ``Generally speaking, who do you hold most
responsible for things getting to the point that they have?''
</P>
<P>
   The president was named by 43 percent of those responding. But
voters interviewed also assigned generous shares of blame to the
media as well as special prosecutor Kenneth Starr.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere in the poll, which interviewed 412 women and 398 men,
were there greater gender differences.
</P>
<P>
   Among men surveyed, the buck stops with Clinton. A total of 54
percent blamed the president, 21 percent the media, and only 10
percent Starr; 11 percent answered ``all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   With women, by contrast, just 32 percent said Clinton was to
blame. Another 28 percent faulted Starr, 21 percent blamed the
media, and seven percent answered ``all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Monica Lewinsky figures hardly at all in the ascribing of blame.
She was listed by only 1 percent of men, and 3 percent of women.
And few blamed Republicans in Congress, although there was
criticism that the investigation is being drawn out for political
purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Women have a different way of looking at blame, said Cathy
Allen, a Democratic consultant and leader of a campaign called
``Enough!'' that seeks to cap the investigation of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a measure of guys to find one villain,'' she said. ``The
nature of a woman is to find a much bigger picture. They look at
this situation as having enough blame to spread around.''
</P>
<P>
   Differences were apparent among those interviewed in the poll,
which was conducted Monday and Tuesday for the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer and Seattle TV station KOMO News 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he (Clinton) had been truthful, we would never have had
this situation. If he had been an honorable man, he would never
have become involved in a relationship like this or, if it were
exposed, he would have resigned,'' said Loren Stueckle, 51, an
optomotrist from Selah.
</P>
<P>
   But Karen Aanes, 64, of Tacoma, part-owner of an electric sign
business, argued: ``I'm of the opinion that your personal life is
your own, and I just think Mr. Starr or the Republicans are out to
get him. All they think about is causing trouble when every doggone
one of them, if they got caught in that situation, would lie.''
</P>
<P>
   Opinion did not always break on gender lines.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Harrif, 60, a horse trainer who also lives in Selah, noted
that the current scandal is rooted in a U.S. Supreme Court decision
that allowed Paula Jones to go ahead with her sexual harassment
lawsuit against Clinton. In Harrif's view, it provided Starr with
an opportunity ``to go after him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Starr) has extra power, he can do anything he wants,''
Hariff said. He argued that the investigation of Clinton ``is tying
up the country'' at a time when the president should be able to
concentrate on the international economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
   But Stephanie Porcella, 52, a Bremerton nurse, blamed Clinton.
``He covered it up,'' she said. ``He sat there, dealt from a
position of his power, and used it.''
</P>
<P>
   One respondent to the poll, who asked not to be named, denounced
what he called ``the Washington, D.C., media'' for its months-long
obsession with the Monica Lewinsky scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They cannot seem, any time and any way, to cover any issue
that is important to the average person working for a living in
this country,'' she said. ``They seem all wound up in power and
scandal, and not connected at all to the rest of us.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
