<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 23:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5250 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOBLES-EXECUTION-COX     10-07 1045
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOBLES-EXECUTION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Execution of Texas murderer complete
 &HT;    By Leah Quin
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Arms bound to a gurney, Jonathan Nobles
apologized to relatives of the Austin women he murdered in 1986 and
to the man he nearly killed in the same attack. He recited from the
Bible _ the famous ``love is patient, love is kind'' passage from I
Corinthians _ and began singing ``Silent Night.''
</P>
<P>
   Just after the line ``mother and child,'' he gasped and choked.
The lethal drugs had collapsed his lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Nobles had asked prison officials to start his execution as soon
as he began singing, an unprecedented request. Five minutes later,
at 6:25 p.m. Wednesday, he was dead.
</P>
<P>
   It was an extraordinary end to a man who became known for issues
far different from the gruesome killings that landed him on death
row.
</P>
<P>
   Nobles tried to become the first condemned prisoner to donate
his organs to strangers. His efforts attracted the attention of
Michigan doctor Jack Kevorkian, who was pushing for inmate organ
donations long before he became a national figure for presiding
over assisted suicides.
</P>
<P>
   Nobles was the first inmate executed who participated in
mediation with the mother of one of his victims. Wednesday night, a
tearful Paula Kurland, mother of Mitzi Johnson Nalley, said those
talks helped her forgive Nobles.
</P>
<P>
   On his last day, Nobles was visited by a Catholic bishop from
the Tyler, Texas, a priest from Boston and a country singer from
Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Earle, a maverick country entertainer who released the
critically acclaimed album ``El Corazon'' in 1997, has often spoken
against the death penalty. Earle gave a short statement after the
execution, calling it murder and saying if he had to die, he hoped
to do it ``half as well as Jonathan did.''
</P>
<P>
   Relatives of Nalley, 21, and Kelly Joan Farquhar, 24, who were
stabbed to death in a predawn attack at their North Austin home,
hugged each other as they watched Nobles die. Also present was
Ronald Ross, a friend of Nalley's who struggled with Nobles the
night of the attack, was stabbed 19 times and lost an eye.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at each in turn and addressing them by first name,
Nobles told Nalley's mother and sister and Farquhar's brother that
he was ``so sorry.'' He then turned to Ross.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ron, I took so much from you,'' he said. ``There's nothing I
can do to give it back to you. I love you. I love all of you.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross clenched his jaw and pressed his open left palm against the
glass separating him from Nobles.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nobles, who converted to Catholicism a few years ago, also
thanked the priests and his friends who were present. ``I'll see
all of y'all at the church later on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Kurland, Ross and Kent Farquhar, Kelly's brother,
talked to the media about Nobles' death, 11 years after the murders
that changed their lives. They've become an extended family, said
Kurland, who along with others in the room wore a photograph of
Nalley pinned to her blouse.
</P>
<P>
   Kurland said she realized two weeks ago, during the last
mediation session with Nobles, that the inmate had truly changed.
It was in his eyes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watched his eyes for 13 months at the trial,'' Kurland said.
``And I saw nothing there, they were just dead. What I saw two
weeks ago _ he had found God genuinely and spiritually.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobles was forgiven, she said, even by his victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Both of them (Nalley and Farquhar) might be talking to him
right now,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nobles was said to be calm and reserved during his final day,
which he spent visiting with friends, his lawyer and a priest. He
drank a kiwi strawberry Snapple but refused a last meal. He
received communion around 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview a month before his death, Nobles said he wanted
to donate his organs to do something positive after ``bringing so
much darkness into this world.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There are sins of commission as well as sins of omission, and
for me not to attempt to do whatever I can that's good is wrong of
me,'' he said from an interview room in the Ellis Unit, the prison
near Huntsville that houses death row.
</P>
<P>
   As Nobles' execution date neared, a Michigan attorney requested
a stay of execution until the question of death-row organ donation
could be settled. Both the stay and the lawsuit were rejected by a
federal judge in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Texas prison officials remained adamant in their assertion that
condemned prisoners are not allowed to donate organs because of
security concerns, the possibility of transmitting diseases and the
dilemma of keeping a death row inmate alive if the operation goes
awry.
</P>
<P>
   Because the chemicals used in lethal injection damage organs, an
organ transplant would have to occur before execution. A living
donor can give a kidney, bone marrow, a lung, a lobe of the liver,
and skin, doctors say.
</P>
<P>
   While the Houston judge acknowledged that the organ-donor
question should be resolved, he ruled that Nobles didn't need to
live until it is.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, Nobles entered a North Austin home and attacked
Farquhar in her bed, stabbing her more than a dozen times in the
chest, back and head with a large hunting knife. When Nalley, who
was asleep with Ross in another bedroom, came to investigate the
noise, Nobles chased her into a closet, stabbing her 28 times.
</P>
<P>
   Ross fought the assailant and was stabbed repeatedly before he
managed to turn the knife on Nobles, cutting him deeply in the arm.
When Nobles fled, Ross struggled outside, screaming for help, and
collapsed in the street.
</P>
<P>
   It was never known why Nobles, a former telemarketer and
electrician, entered the apartment. He had been staying with his
godmother on Alegria Street, less than a block from the apartment
Farquhar and Nalley shared on Sunshine Drive, near Lamar Boulevard
and Koenig Lane.
</P>
<P>
   Nobles was arrested a week later, after friends who helped him
bandage his wound called police. He confessed to the slayings,
saying he was high on cocaine and methamphetamines, but insisted he
knew what he was doing. Kurland said she never asked Nobles why he
committed the murders. No answer would have satisfied her, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
