<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-FBC-ACC-CAPSULES08 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clemson to meet Maryland on Saturday
 &HT;    By Norman Arey and Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEMSON vs. Maryland, Saturday, noon
</P>
<P>
   While Florida coach Steve Spurrier has called off his rotating
quarterback experiment, Clemson's Tommy West is just beginning his.
He said he will use Woody Dantzler and Brandon Streeter, depending
on the situation. Dantzler's option skills didn't get much
accomplished in last week's loss to North Carolina, and Streeter
came on late to take the Tigers within two yards of tying up the
contest. . . . OG Corey Hulsey (hyperextended knee) is probable,
while OG Matt Butler (sprained ankle) is questionable. . . . Former
Monroe Area standout Chris Jones is one of the bright lights on a
defensive unit that leads the ACC in rushing defense (106.2 yards)
and sacks (tied with Virginia with 15). Jones leads the team with
64 tackles (12.8 per game).
</P>
<P>
   DUKE at Wake Forest, Saturday, 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Fred Goldsmith says he's mad and not going to take it
anymore. The Blue Devils, owners of a league-record 21 straight ACC
losses, play Wake Forest, the team they beat for their last league
win. ``We're a team that's sort of mad,'' said Goldsmith. ``We were
disappointed the way we played down at Georgia Tech. Now the Devils
must face Wake quarterback Brian Kuklick, who is rated the
third-best in the ACC and for whom Goldsmith has much admiration.
``Kuklick is such a good quarterback and so many good things happen
because of him,'' Goldsmith said. ``Last year we were so worried
about Kuklick, Wake had a record-setting day running the ball
against us. Kuklick led comebacks against Northwestern two years
ago and against us last year in a game that we were ahead in.''
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA STATE at Miami, Saturday, 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   One of the big games in the country used to be Miami vs. Florida
State. Saturday, the ninth-ranked Seminoles will meet the unranked
Hurricanes in a game that's received little fanfare. FSU will be
without the services of starting free safety Dexter Jackson
(hamstring pull) and tailback Travis Minor (ankle sprain) won't be
100 percent. ``We hope Travis will be able to play,'' said coach
Bobby Bowden, ``but he's still limping in practice and you can't
beat Miami with a limp.'' Bowden says his 4-1 Seminoles have
suffered this year due to a lack of senior leadership. ``We're
probably about one year more experienced than Miami,'' he said.
``We're playing a lot of juniors and sophomores where they're
playing a lot of sophomores and freshmen.''
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND at Clemson, Saturday, noon
</P>
<P>
   True freshman Randall Jones has been declared the No. 1
quarterback, demoting preseason starter Ken Mastrole, who has
struggled. Jones was signed as a defensive back but converted
because of his speed and option-style game. ``He is ready, the team
is ready,'' head coach Ron Vanderlinden said. . . . The Byrd
Stadium crowd booed when Jones was replaced by Mastrole in the
third quarter Saturday. . . . The 24-10 loss to Florida State was
the closest for the Terrapins since the Seminoles joined the ACC. .
. . True freshman Tony Okanlawon is getting a look at first-string
cornerback behind Lynde Washington. . . . Through their first five
games, the Terps have used a total of 28 underclassmen on a regular
basis.
</P>
<P>
   NORTH CAROLINA vs. Pittsburgh, Saturday, 1:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   After beating Clemson last week, coach Carl Torbush says it was
long overdue and much needed. ``I can't remember seeing a happier
team after that win in my 11 years here,'' he said. Now Pittsburgh
(2-2) comes to Chapel Hill and Torbush says the Tar Heels will
again have their backs against the wall. ``Pitt is an outstanding
team. They've lost to Virginia Tech and Penn State, two of the best
teams in the country.'' Torbush says he plans to alternate
quarterbacks Ronald Curry and Oscar Davenport against the Panthers.
Curry received a bruised left shoulder early in the Clemson win and
Davenport played most of the game, but Curry will be ready to play
against Pitt. Receiver L.C. Stevens, who missed two games with an
ankle injury, will also be available Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   N.C. STATE vs. Ga. Tech, Saturday, 3:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   DE Greg Derrick is probable, but PK Scott Earwood will play only
as an emergency punter after limited action in a Sunday practice.
Coach Mike O'Cain said Earwood's kicking leg is still extremely
sore because of a stress fracture. . . . Although walk-on PK Daniel
Deskevich kicked four extra points and a field goal against
Syracuse, O'Cain said he hasn't decided whether to use him or
backup Kent Passingham, who was benched last week. ``Both of them
have been inconsistent,'' O'Cain said. ``We're going to continue to
see what they can do the rest of the week.'' . . . After an
agonizing 1997 season in which his job status was up in the air,
O'Cain said he doesn't feel any need to be vindicated after a
strong start this year: ``I don't believe in vindication. I'm just
very grateful to be the coach here.''
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA Off; at Ga. Tech, Oct. 17
</P>
<P>
   The unbeaten Cavaliers, who have a week off before their key ACC
game at Georgia Tech, appear to be the most dangerous team in the
league right now. Besides a strong passing game with Aaron Brooks
throwing to Terrence Wilkins, the Cavaliers lead the ACC in
rushing, averaging 227 yards. Tailback Thomas Jones leads the
conference with 107.2 yards per game, 23rd nationally. Antwoine
Womack is third in the league with a 78.6 average per game. Still
coach George Welsh isn't satisfied. He's concerned with his
receivers' inability to separate themselves from their defenders
and concerned with the lack of depth on his offensive line. ``But
we were able to give the second-team offensive line about 25-30
plays against San Jose State last week.''
</P>
<P>
   WAKE FOREST vs. Duke, Saturday, 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   So much for being ranked preseason No. 22 by Sports Illustrated.
The Demon Deacons were beaten 30-27 by Division I-AA Appalachian
State last week. The Deacons are now 2-2, their other loss 42-0 to
Air Force. Now weak-sister Duke comes calling at Groves Stadium and
the Deacons are anxious to get back on the field. . . . Wake Forest
expects to rely heavily on their pass-catching duo of Desmond Clark
and Jammie Deese. Clark has 28 catches for 361 yards and three
touchdowns while Deese has 24 grabs for 281 yards and one score.
Brian Kuklick has completed 61 percent of his passes for 908 yards
and six TDs. ``We know we've got a better team than we've shown and
I'm glad we'll get a chance to show what we can do,'' Kuklick said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
