<SLUG> BC-ATL-RAC-LEMANS08 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Petit Le Mans may help rev up sports car racing
 &HT;    By Kent Mitchell
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Drivers and racing officials alike hope Saturday's
Petit Le Mans at Road Atlanta will trigger an upturn of fortunes
for sports car racing.
</P>
<P>
   The race offers the finest, largest field of competition of its
type seen in America this year, over a newly renovated 2.6-mile
Grand Prix road course. It is the cornerstone of a Le Mans series
that will begin in full next year.
</P>
<P>
   The Petit is a scaled-down version of the 24 Hours of Le Mans.
Saturday's race will go either 1,000 miles or 10 hours, whichever
comes first.
</P>
<P>
   It features some of the best drivers and cars in sports car
racing _ World Sports Cars, Grand Tourism 1, GT2, GT3, Le Mans
Prototype _ on what has become, in the past few months of
renovation, one of the finest road-course tracks in the country, if
not the world.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 40 of the 100-plus drivers involved with the 31 cars are
European. They are here because the winner automatically qualifies
for next year's 24 Hours of Le Mans.
</P>
<P>
   The Le Mans winner this year, the No. 26 Porsche 911 GT1-98, is
entered and should be considered the favorite. Driving duties are
shared by Uwe Alzen of Germany, Yannick Dalmas of France and Allan
McNish of Scotland, the only driver from the winning Le Mans team
to have raced here.
</P>
<P>
   The WSC-class winner, an Atlanta-sponsored car, also is entered.
The No. 7 Lease Plan Ferrari 333SP, which finished eighth at Le
Mans, will be driven by Wayne Taylor of Altamonte Springs, Fla.,
Eric van de Poele of San Diego and Emmanuel Collard of France.
</P>
<P>
   Taylor trails WSC points leader Butch Leitzinger of State
College, Pa., by 10 points and might be leading except for some
problems at a race earlier in the year at Road Atlanta. Pirelli
tires used by the Ferrari were too big for the rims and kept
slipping during the race, causing control problems.
</P>
<P>
   Leitzinger also is entered in the No. 8 Ford/Riley &AMP; Scott
MkIII, along with Scott Schubot of West Palm Beach, Fla., and Henry
Camferdam of Indianapolis.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the three Team Panoz entries competed in the 24 Hours of
Le Mans. Their drivers constitute six of the top 10 in Professional
Sports Car Racing's GT1 point standings, including the top three:
Co-leaders Andy Wallace of France and David Brabham of England and
No. 3 Eric Bernard of France. The others are No. 7 Doc Bundy of
Gainesville, No. 9 Johnny O'Connell of Phoenix and No. 10 Jamie
Davies of England.
</P>
<P>
   Brabham and Wallace, who finished seventh together at Le Mans,
along with Scott Pruett of Granite Bay, Calif., will drive the No.
4 Panoz GT1; Bernard, O'Connell and Davies will drive the No. 5
Panoz GT1, and Bundy, John Nielsen of Denmark and Christophe
Tinseau of France will drive the No. 007 Panoz GT1 hybrid, which
combines a V8 engine with an electric motor, and didn't qualify at
Le Mans.
</P>
<P>
   The field also includes nine Indy 500 veterans, eight Formula
One veterans and winning drivers in the 24 Hours of Le Mans and the
Rolex 24 Hours at Daytona such as Dalmas, Hurley Haywood, Hans
Stuck, Christophe Bouchut, Mauro Baldi, Michele Alboreto and Stefan
Johansson.
</P>
<P>
   Like the man said, ``Build it and they will come.'' The drivers
are there, with their cars. On Saturday, they hope the fans will
come, too.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
