<HEADER>
A5364 &Cx1f; tad-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SIERRA-BLANCA-PROTEST     10-07 0660
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SIERRA-BLANCA-PROTEST-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hazardous waste site draws controversy
 &HT;    By Ralph K.M. Haurwitz
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A delegation of Mexican officials urged the Bush
administration and state lawmakers Wednesday to block a proposed
disposal site for low-level radioactive waste.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the delegation said the state's plan to bury waste in
the desert near the West Texas town of Sierra Blanca threatens to
pollute water supplies, sour bilateral relations and reverse
economic progress in the region.
</P>
<P>
   They also criticized Gov. George W. Bush for not meeting with
them and other opponents of the site, and for repeated assertions
that his support for the project hinges on whether it is shown to
be safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel first of all there was a political decision, that
politics decided where this site would be,'' said Jeffrey Jones, a
member of the Mexican Congress from the state of Chihuahua. ``Now
that the site is chosen, they want to shift everything to
scientific facts. This type of project seems to fly in the face of
the intent of what the free trade agreement is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   He was referring to the North American Free Trade Agreement
between Mexico, the United States and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Jones was among a dozen local, state and federal elected
officials from Mexico who met with Secretary of State Al Gonzales
and then held a news conference at the Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission is scheduled
to consider on Oct. 22 whether to grant a license for construction
and operation of the site, which would receive waste from nuclear
power plants, medical centers, universities and other sources. The
500-acre site in Hudspeth County is about 18 miles from the Rio
Grande, a major water source and a dividing line between the United
States and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was unable to meet with the Mexican delegation because of a
scheduling conflict, said Linda Edwards, a spokeswoman for the
governor. Gonzales is his representative on the issue, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The governor has met with site opponents, including elected
officials from Mexico, on several occasions, Edwards said. For
example, Bush met with the governor of Chihuahua and the mayor of
El Paso three weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush is confident the commissioners of the TNRCC will
judge the safety of the site based on sound science,'' Edwards
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two state administrative law judges have recommended that the
license be denied. The judges said the Texas Low-Level Radioactive
Waste Disposal Authority, which would own and operate the site, had
failed to provide sufficient evidence concerning its geologic
suitability and on socioeconomic matters.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is a thorny one for Bush, who has sought to cultivate
warm relations with Mexico as well as political support among
Texas' growing Hispanic population, which is mostly Democratic.
Guadalupe Rodriguez Martinez, a member of Nuevo Leon's state
legislature, said Texas' choice of a site in a low-income Hispanic
community with little political clout ``constitutes an act of
environmental racism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We call for the immediate consideration of the relocation of
this site,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The Mexican Congress has unanimously adopted a resolution
opposing the site. But three executive-branch agencies _ foreign
relations, energy and environment _ recently issued a communique
declaring that the disposal site meets Mexican and international
standards and ``does not represent a risk for the Mexican
population and environment as long as its construction, operation
and sealing are carried out as outlined in the documents.''
</P>
<P>
   Texas state Rep. Norma Chavez, an El Paso Democrat who is
secretary of the 35-member Mexican American legislative caucus,
said she would introduce a measure next year to reject the site if
the conservation commission issues a license.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
