<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA'S LEWIS FILES BATTERY REPORT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Claiming he was the victim, suspended UCLA
tailback Jermaine Lewis filed a battery report Tuesday against the
unidentified man with whom he fought early Sunday morning at a
party near campus.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis' report came a day after Elonza Malone III filed a battery
complaint against Lewis. Malone told campus police that Lewis
struck him multiple times at the party on Landfair Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   After Malone filed his report, UCLA coach Bob Toledo suspended
Lewis indefinitely for violating team policy regarding fighting.
</P>
<P>
   A Lancaster native and UCLA's leading rusher, Lewis won't play
Saturday at Arizona. He may return as early as next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My spirits are good,'' said Lewis, who declined to comment on
specifics of the incident or the investigation.
</P>
<P>
   According to team sources, Lewis told police that Malone threw
the first punch, catching Lewis by surprise, and that Lewis
retaliated in self defense. Several UCLA players eventually
separated the combatants.
</P>
<P>
   Malone claimed Lewis instigated the fight, then attacked Malone
a second time on the sidewalk, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting update: Ryan Wikert, a receiver/safety from Temecula,
orally committed to UCLA on Tuesday night. He is the second player
to commit, following Venice quarterback J.P. Losman. The Bruins
hope to sign 16-18 players in February.
</P>
<P>
   Wikert, 6-2 and 180 pounds, is projected to play free safety, a
position of need. (Redshirt freshman Jason Stephens is the only
young free safety on the roster.) He is highly regarded but lightly
recruited, according to Student Sports Magazine; San Diego State
was the only other school to offer a scholarship.
</P>
<P>
   Wiser than his years: Linebacker Tony White was named one of
four captains this week, becoming the first sophomore in the Toledo
era to be so honored.
</P>
<P>
   White was credited with six tackles against Washington State and
has 13 this season, tied for third on the team. He joins offensive
tackle Kris Farris, quarterback Cade McNown and safety Larry Atkins
as captains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's crazy to have a sophomore as a captain, but he's one of
the better leaders on defense,'' Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   That says as much about the Bruins' inexperience as it does
White's maturity. They are expected to start three seniors, four
juniors, two sophomores and two freshmen against Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Pancakes, anyone? Farris, the All-American left tackle, has
dominated smaller opponents with his 6-9, 315-pound frame.
Saturday, he'll face Arizona's quick but undersized ends, Joe
Tafoya (255 pounds) and Eli Wnek (240).
</P>
<P>
   ``If you isolate on him, he's been mauling guys the last few
weeks,'' Toledo said. ``He smothers guys. Guys are 6-3 or 6-4 and
he towers over them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
