<HEADER>
A5381 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-STARR-LETTER-     10-07 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-STARR-LETTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARR MAY HAVE NEW MATERIAL FOR COMMITTEE 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also CLINTON-IMPEACH, CLINTON-LOBBY, CLINTON-FENCE)  
 (af)  
 By JOHN M. BRODER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ On the eve of a House vote on a formal impeachment
inquiry against President Clinton, the Whitewater independent
counsel, Kenneth Starr, told leaders of the judiciary committee
Wednesday night that he might be preparing to refer to Congress
matters that could become additional grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Reps. Henry Hyde, the committee chairman, and
John Conyers Jr., the ranking Democrat, Starr said unspecified
matters remained under active investigation by the Office of
Independent Counsel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consequently, I cannot foreclose the possibility of providing
the House of Representatives with additional substantial and
credible information arising from those investigations that
President William Jefferson Clinton committed acts that may
constitute grounds for an impeachment,'' Starr wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Hyde and Conyers wrote to Starr last Friday, asking whether he
would have information ``in the foreseeable future'' beyond that
given the committee last month in his 445-page report laying out 11
possible grounds for impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bakaly III, the spokesman for Starr's office, said Starr
wanted to respond to the congressional request as quickly as
possible. The letter was not timed in any way to affect the debate
this week on authorizing an impeachment inquiry, Bakaly said.
</P>
<P>
   Bakaly declined to elaborate on what matters still under
investigation might yield additional impeachment charges.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for White House counsel's office, James Kennedy,
said, ``We have nothing to add to a letter that adds nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   While Starr's letter included the provocative suggestion that
more evidence of possible impeachable offenses might be
forthcoming, investigators said there was no expectation that there
would be anything soon, if at all.
</P>
<P>
   Starr made clear in his Sept. 11 impeachment referral that many
aspects of his long-running examination of the president and
Hillary Rodham Clinton remained open.
</P>
<P>
   Starr said then: ``All phases of the investigation are now
nearing completion. This office will soon make final decisions
about what steps to take, if any, with respect to the other
information it has gathered. Those decisions will be made at the
earliest practical time, consistent with our statutory and ethical
obligations.''
</P>
<P>
   But lawyers following the inquiry said Wednesday night that his
latest letter was probably referring to other strands of the
Lewinsky case and not items like the dismissal of seven White House
travel office employees, the initial Whitewater inquiry and the
improper handling in the White House of hundreds of FBI background
files.
</P>
<P>
   With no grand jury in Arkansas now hearing any further testimony
about the political and financial dealings of the Clintons in the
1980s, the lawyers said, they did not expect Starr to forward any
additional material about Whitewater to Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But the lawyers noted that Congress had received virtually no
material about the accusations made by Kathleen Willey, a former
White House volunteer, who has said she was groped by the president
in a West Wing encounter in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   In his testimony two months ago, Clinton denied Ms. Willey's
account, and Starr's staff has not decided whether to forward to
Congress any further report reconciling the contradictory
testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation has also not resolved other issues in the
Lewinsky inquiry, including whether any witnesses were improperly
discouraged by the White House from testifying truthfully.
</P>
<P>
   The independent-counsel law also requires Starr to file a report
about his investigation to the special three-judge court that
oversees independent counsels. Once the report is filed, it is
almost certain to be many months before the court would make it
public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-07-98 2325EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981007.0490 </DOCNO>
