<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-07 23:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5383 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     10-07 0809
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: A NO-BRAINER OF HIS OWN CREATION 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Along with the anxiety of a series taken for granted
that has suddenly turned scary comes the time-honored tradition of
the second-guess. As in: Try to guess what Chuck Knoblauch could
have possibly been thinking as he staked the outcome of a
4-hour-28-minute marathon on the assumption that an umpire's call
would go his way.
</P>
<P>
   Little Leaguers are admonished for what Knoblauch did, or didn't
do, as he waited for umpire Ted Hendry to lift his right arm in the
12th inning Wednesday night at Yankee Stadium. He stood on first
base, the ball behind him in the infield dirt, as the winning run
circled the bases. Inexcusable for a Little Leaguer. Unfathomable
for a major-league ball player, and not because he happens to earn
$6 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   So hold the confetti. Put away those brooms. The Cleveland
Indians, 4-1 winners in 12 exhausting innings Wednesday at Yankee
Stadium, will not be swept. If they can win two of three back home
in Jacobs Field this weekend, the most decorated team in American
League history will return home next week to face elimination in
Game 6.
</P>
<P>
   All right, that sounds mighty dire for a team that could just as
easily win the next three, but that's the typical playoff mind
game, day after gut-wrenching day. That's a message to those who
were going over those World Series pitching matchups with Atlanta
already. Stuff happens. Kids interfere with home run balls.
Major-leaguers suffer brain lock.
</P>
<P>
   The real postseason began Wednesday, after four games that
looked like George Steinbrenner's blueprint for his own fantasy. A
tense, fierce struggle resulted in a series of failed Yankee
opportunities, one or two debatable moves by Joe Torre and,
finally, Knoblauch's dishonoring of the most rudimentary rule in
sports.
</P>
<P>
   Did he have a case that Travis Fryman was running in the
baseline, as Fryman bunted pinch-runner Enrique Wilson to second,
with no one out in the 12th? Yes, he did, even though the crew
chief Jim Evans said Fryman was entitled to be where he was as he
hit first base.
</P>
<P>
   The replay showed that Fryman was never between the restraining
lines as he tried to beat Tino Martinez's throw from behind him.
The ball arrived as Fryman did, hit Fryman in the back, bounced 15
feet behind Knoblauch, who didn't even turn around to look for the
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a no-brainer,'' he would say, an unfortunate
choice of words from the man who amazingly stood in his tracks,
pointing at the baseline as Wilson and Fryman did what that
unofficial manual for every player, 8 and over, commands you to do:
Assume nothing, keep playing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea where the ball was, to begin with,'' Knoblauch
explained lamely, failing to acknowledge that he didn't make any
attempt to locate it until it was too late. Had he retrieved the
ball even a couple of seconds faster, he would have thrown Wilson,
who stumbled between third and home, out at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   No excuses for not playing on, Torre agreed, after lobbing a few
verbal grenades at the umps. Martinez, given the error for his
throw, admitted the call could have gone either way and decided the
Yankees had no one to blame for the defeat but themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should have won the game much earlier,'' he said, citing
his own inability to deliver Paul O'Neill from third with one out
in the fourth. Speaking of wasted opportunities, Torre let David
Cone's favorite catcher, Joe Girardi, hit against a sidearming
right-hander, Steve Reed, with runners at second and third, two out
in the seventh, the Yankees having just tied the game at 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, Cone was gone by the ninth, when the Yankees had what
was their last chance to win, when Tim Raines singled and
pinch-runner Homer Bush stole second.
</P>
<P>
   Now, I am as excited by what Shane Spencer has done as the next
guy, but these are the playoffs and this isn't Joe DiMaggio. Rather
than send up a left-hander, Jorge Posada or Chili Davis, against
the right-handed Paul Shuey, Torre let Spencer swing away. He
struck out. Posada eventually hit for Girardi with Bush on second,
Scott Brosius on first. He grounded to second for an inning-ending
double play.
</P>
<P>
   The game moved toward its ungraceful finish. The Yankees find
themselves in a series after all, now returning to where they were
ousted last season, after a game Torre said he hoped was ``out of
character.'' Probably it was, but Martinez is in a horrible slump,
the table-setter Knoblauch has set himself up for everlasting
infamy, and the Indians flew home citing history, their own
111-victory team from 1954 that lost, four straight, in the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   Stuff happens. Sound the alarms. The real playoffs have begun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
