<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LABOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS AND OWNERS FINALLY MEET AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like two schoolchildren forced to reconcile in the
principal's office, the players and owners of the National
Basketball Association will try to bridge their differences
Thursday. In a bargaining session at a Manhattan hotel, they will
meet for the first time since Aug. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the league nor the NBA Players Association expects to
make much headway toward the signing of a new labor agreement. Both
sides are pessimistic about starting the season by its scheduled
opening date of Nov. 3. But a dialogue Thursday about issues
relating to the owners' latest proposal to the players could result
in one smidgen of progress: a reason to meet again in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Hunter, the union's executive director, said he would
respond to the proposal at the next meeting. The players soundly
criticized the document delivered by the league less than two weeks
ago.
</P>
<P>
   In its quest to put a ceiling on salaries and eventually install
a restricted salary cap, the owners have proposed phasing out the
Larry Bird exception, which allows teams to sign their own free
agents for whatever they want and represents the largest stumbling
block in negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The latest proposal also deals with the abolition of the
three-year rookie scale, which allows third-year players
unrestricted free agency after their third season with their team.
Teams would instead have the right of first refusal in the fourth
and fifth seasons, a proposal that would affect the 1995 draft
class and would include players such as Damon Stoudamire, Joe Smith
and Antonio McDyess.
</P>
<P>
   To slow the growth of salaries, the league has also proposed
rolling back the automatic 20 percent raises for multiyear deals to
7.5 percent for players who have the Bird exception, and 5 percent
for all other players.
</P>
</TEXT>
