<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: GM BEGINS CAMPAIGN FOR CHEVROLET SILVERADO 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich.)  (lb) 
 By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ General Motors Corp. plans to begin one of the largest
advertising campaigns ever in the auto industry on Thursday
evening, a $135 million effort to promote a complete redesign of
the company's best-selling vehicle, the full-sized Chevrolet
Silverado pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   GM plans a barrage of network television commercials combined
with ads in 63 magazines and 339 papers and extensive direct-mail
solicitations to pickup owners, Chevrolet officials said Wednesday.
Orchestrated by Campbell-Ewald in Warren, Mich., a unit of
Interpublic Group of Cos., the technologically innovative campaign
emphasizes the greater size and power of the redesigned truck.
</P>
<P>
   According to Competitive Media Reporting, which tracks
advertising spending, the biggest auto brand campaign last year was
a $135.6 million effort for the redesigned Honda Accord, followed
by the Saturn division's $119.9 million spending. The biggest
campaign from 1994 through 1996 was a $131.3 million effort by
Saturn in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Success is critical for GM. The pickup produced 13 percent of
GM's North American sales last year, or $14 billion, making the
Chevy pickup a bigger business than Time-Warner, McDonald's,
Microsoft or Nike, said Kurt Ritter, the brand manager for the
Silverado.
</P>
<P>
   GM wants to win back some of the pickup-truck market share that
it has lost to Ford Motor Co. and Chrysler Corp. over the last
several years. But both companies have been preparing for months
for the introduction of the new Chevy pickup.
</P>
<P>
   Chrysler introduced new rebates on Tuesday on its full-sized
pickup trucks. James Holden, Chrysler's executive vice president
for sales and marketing, said Wednesday that this had partly been a
pre-emptive move aimed at the Chevy pickup.
</P>
<P>
   For all the advertising, Chevrolet's new pickup truck has one
feature that might prove a disadvantage. Its extended-cab version
has only three doors, one on the driver's side and two on the front
passenger's side, instead of the four doors that Ford and Dodge
have started to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Extra doors sell well these days _ when Ford introduced the
Windstar minivan two years ago with three doors while Dodge was
offering four, sales initially suffered, and Ford has since added a
fourth door.
</P>
<P>
   GM executives have already acknowledged that only putting three
doors on the extended-cab pickup may be a liability, and Ritter
said that Chevrolet planned to add a fourth door in the next model
year. Until then, he said, Chevrolet's marketing will emphasize
that the pickup has unusually wide doors.
</P>
<P>
   Chevy full-size pickups have held 28.5 percent of the market
through the first eight months of this year, a share that has
diminished in recent years as Dodge and Ford have moved faster to
update their models.
</P>
<P>
   The new Chevrolet ads use innovative techniques to present
familiar themes. Nowhere in sight are any families slinging
groceries or potted flowers into the bed, an approach that rival
automakers have tried in commercials and which reflects that 70
percent of full-sized pickups are now bought for personal use
instead of work.
</P>
<P>
   Chevrolet's commercials will be much more traditional, building
on the company's previous ``Like a Rock'' campaigns. The ads
reflect Chevrolet market research, which has found that
white-collar pickup buyers like the vehicle's blue-collar image.
The new ads use country music and scenes of industrial workers in
hard hats, and cowboys, but are presented with the latest computer
animation and trick photography.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Chevrolet prepared two 60-second television ads, and then ran
the first 30 seconds of each ad repeatedly on television over the
summer, with the goal of creating public interest in the new
pickups. Beginning Thursday evening, the full-length ads will
appear, allowing viewers to see how each situation works out.
</P>
<P>
   One of the ads shows molten steel being poured in a foundry in
Gary, Ind., when the steel and sparks suddenly become suspended in
midair. The workers walk around in wonderment, looking at the
sparks, and then stroll out to the factory gate, where other
mechanical activity is also frozen. At the gate, they and a few
white-collar employees marvel at something off screen that captures
their attention as the 30-second version of the ad ends.
</P>
<P>
   In the continuation of the ad, the workers see the new Chevy
pickup, and activity resumes. William Ludwig, a vice chairman and
the chief creative officer of Campbell-Ewald, said that the molten
steel was a computer graphic created using some of the software
from the movie ``Dante's Peak,'' which was about a volcanic
eruption.
</P>
<P>
   The other ad shows a cowboy on horseback who is racing alongside
a herd of horses when suddenly his mount and all the horses become
frozen. The cowboy flies off his horse and rolls to a stop, and
then goes back and looks at his immobilized horse. He then heads
with other cowboys across a pasture before seeing something off
screen that transfixes all of them as the 30-second version ends.
</P>
<P>
   In the longer version, the cowboys then come across a Chevy
pickup and the herd of horses resumes galloping when the pickup
drives past it.
</P>
<P>
   Filming that ad required the use of many cameras taking pictures
of the mounted cowboy's horse from many angles at the same time, so
as to allow the cowboy to apparently walk around the frozen horse,
Ludwig said. The actor who played the cowboy had to do more than a
dozen back flips off a trampoline and into the dirt for the
commercial _ a painful but necessary exercise, Ludwig added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
