<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE-POLL-METHOD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW THE POLL WAS CONDUCTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (See also NY-SENATE-POLL.) 
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: The following story also moved with an ``a''
category code) 
(nk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The latest New York Times/CBS News Poll of New York state is
based on telephone interviews conducted from Oct. 1 to Oct. 6 with
1,461 adults throughout the state. Of these, 1,066 said they were
registered to vote. Interviews were conducted in English or
Spanish.
</P>
<P>
   The sample of telephone exchanges called was randomly selected
by a computer from a complete list of 2,500 residential exchanges
across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Within each exchange, random digits were added to form a
telephone number, thus permitting access to both listed and
unlisted numbers. Within each household, one adult was designated
randomly to be the respondent for the survey.
</P>
<P>
   The results have been weighted to take account of household size
and number of phone lines into the residence, as well as to adjust
for variations relating to region, race, sex, age, Hispanic origin
and education.
</P>
<P>
   Results about registered voters' intended vote in November have
been weighted by the statewide distribution of ballots in recent
comparable elections from New York City (29 percent), its suburbs
(24 percent) and the rest of the state (47 percent).
</P>
<P>
   According to statistical theory, in 19 out of 20 cases, the
