</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-INDIANS-NAGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAGY PUTS PAST FAILURES BEHIND HIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Cleveland Indians' ragtag pitching staff looks as
if it were composed of scraps that could be used for a quilt when
compared with the seamless group the New York Yankees have on call.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the Cleveland staff went pitch for pitch with the
Yankees and held the Indians together Wednesday in Game 2 of the
American League Championship Series. The pitchers did it just long
enough for a bizarre game-winning play to add another page to the
Cleveland's uncanny resilience in its playoff history as the
Indians took Game 2 by 4-1 in 12 innings at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It was an unlikely finish in a game full of improbable heroes.
Charles Nagy was one of them. Of all pitchers who have tended to
put a twinkle in the eyes of the Yankees in the past, Nagy was the
starter who kept pace with the brilliance of the Yankees' starter,
David Cone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year, I couldn't get the Yankees out to save my life,''
said Nagy, who entered the game with a career record of 7-8 and a
4.56 earned run average against them. In the 1997 division series
against the Yankees, Nagy started Game 3 and picked up the loss in
a 6-1 defeat. But he did not let the past haunt him Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   When he left the game, he figured that somehow the Cleveland
bullpen would stand up to the pressure. And the pressure was thick
for those called upon, from Steve Reed to Jim Poole, from Paul
Shuey to Paul Assenmacher to Dave Burba. And well after Yankee
manager Joe Torre had chosen to lean on his closer, Mariano Rivera,
in the ninth and 10th innings, Indians manager Mike Hargrove saved
his closer, Mike Jackson, to seal the game in the 12th.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tense in the pen,'' said Burba, who picked up the
victory although he pitched just one-third of an inning.
``Everybody wanted to be the guy who was called on next. So every
time the phone rang, you'd jump. It would ring again, and you'd
jump again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say I've ever pitched one-third of an inning and
picked up a win. This win was everyone's. Every guy who was called
on contributed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians' staff held the Yankees' glamorous bats to just 7
hits in 12 innings.
</P>
<P>
   In the seventh inning, with Scott Brosius on second base after
his double scored Bernie Williams to tie the score, Reed took over
for Nagy and got Joe Girardi to bounce out to the mound and end the
inning. In the eighth inning, with Derek Jeter in scoring position,
Shuey was able to strike out Tino Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we found ourselves in a jam, we got out of it,''
Assenmacher said. ``The Yankees have an amazing lineup, and every
guy on their team can hit. We just held them off for as long as we
could.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tying the series is big for us. I'm sure the Yankees are still
the favorites. We're the underdogs, but to be going home for three
games, that's good for us.''
</P>
<P>
   To be in this position is nothing new for the Indians. Over the
past two years, they have lost the opening game of a playoff series
eight straight times. Losing Game 1 to the Yankees on Tuesday did
not faze them. It is almost as if they need the motivation to
strike back.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so in Game 2 Wednesday, there was much more gained than
just evening this series. A little mystique was rubbed off the
Yankees, and a little confidence spread over the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is that we know we can win,'' Shuey said.
``If we have to come back here and play in Yankee Stadium, we know
the confidence is there. We won't be afraid. We found a way
today.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it takes. Nagy watched the odd finish unfold from the
Cleveland locker room. With Enrique Wilson pinch-running at first
base, Travis Fryman put down a sacrifice bunt that led to a
calamity for the Yankees. They believed that Fryman, who was hit in
the back by Martinez's throw to first, ran out of the basepath and
was out. While Chuck Knoblauch argued, the ball sat on the ground
long enough for Wilson to score from home for the tie-breaking run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw Enrique running around third, and stumbling like he was
on TV bloopers,'' Nagy said. ``I was just hoping he didn't break
his nose, and that he could get up and score. I was like, come on,
come on.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we could hang around long enough, keep it close, good
things were bound to happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
