<SLUG> BC-BOMB-INDICT-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SAYS IT CAN TIE BIN LADEN TO EMBASSY BOMBINGS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Adds 400 wds. to bottom with details on bin Laden's organization
Al Qaeda and on the indictment.)  (js) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Federal prosecutors in Manhattan said Wednesday that
one of the men accused of conspiring to bomb the U.S. Embassies in
Kenya and Tanzania in August had met earlier with Osama bin Laden,
the suspected mastermind of the attacks, and ``asked him for a
mission.''
</P>
<P>
   The reported meeting between bin Laden and the accused man,
Mohamed Rashed Daoud Al'Owhali, which had not previously been
described, is the strongest allegation offered so far to link bin
Laden to the attacks, in which more than 250 people died.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting, which prosecutors said took place in 1996, is
reported in a new 48-page indictment of Al-'Owhali and three others
that a federal grand jury in Manhattan returned Wednesday. It shows
how prosecutors are continuing to build the circumstantial case
that bin Laden, a Saudi businessman in exile, was behind the
embassy bombings and other attacks against Americans stationed
abroad in the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The prosecutors did not indicate bin Laden's response to the
offer; he is not charged in the new indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment does not indicate whether prosecutors have any
evidence that bin Laden directly ordered the bombings, or whether
they may argue that he inspired a group of followers to carry out
the attacks. Bin Laden has called for attacks on U.S. and other
Western interests.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, in issuing the new charges against men suspected of
being bin Laden's associates, the government also declared more
concretely than previously that bin Laden has been a major backer
of terrorism groups worldwide. Its list of terrorist groups
includes Al Jihad in Egypt and the Islamic Group, which is led by
Sheik Omar Abdel Rahman, who was convicted in 1996 in the plot to
blow up landmarks in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment asserted that bin Laden's organization, Al Qaeda,
worked on its own and through Al Jihad, Islamic Group and others,
which ``operated under its umbrella.''
</P>
<P>
   The authorities also gave their first account of what they
called bin Laden's network of businesses and front companies in
Sudan that he allegedly used to raise money to support terrorism
and to provide cover for the acquisition of explosives, weapons and
chemicals, and the travel of his associates.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment says bin Laden tried to recruit Americans to
assist Al Qaeda, particularly for traveling in Western countries to
deliver messages, to make financial transactions and to carry out
operations.
</P>
<P>
   One of those Americans, Wadih el-Hage, of Arlington, Texas, has
been charged with lying to investigators about his role in the bin
Laden group, and on Wednesday the charges against him were
broadened to include conspiracy to kill U.S. citizens.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to al-'Owhali and el-Hage, those charged Wednesday
in the conspiracy are Mohammed Saddiq Odeh, who is also in custody,
and Haroun Fazil, who is a fugitive. Excluding el-Hage, the men
were also charged with more than 200 counts of murder, one for each
of the bombing victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``Justice will be served for every one of those victims,'' said
Mary Jo White, the U.S. attorney in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, el-Hage, who is being held without bond, sat
quietly as his lawyer complained in a brief hearing to Judge
Leonard Sand of U.S. District Court in Manhattan that his client
was being allowed only one phone call every 30 days. Sand asked an
assistant U.S. attorney who is prosecuting the case, Patrick
Fitzgerald, to look into the matter.
</P>
<P>
   In offering the most detailed assertions yet about the
operations of bin Laden and Al Qaeda, the indictment underscored
how the federal authorities are moving beyond the bombings in
Africa and focusing on Al Qaeda as if it were some kind of
organized crime family.
</P>
<P>
   The group, which bin Laden founded in 1989, is ``dedicated to
opposing non-Islamic governments with force and violence,'' the
indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   It grew out of an organization called Mekhtab al-Khidemat, which
means ``the Services Office,'' the indictment said, adding that
this group had offices in Afghanistan, Pakistan and the United
States. It said one U.S. site was the Alkifah Refugee Center in
Brooklyn, which raised money and recruited fighters for the
Afghans' war against the Soviet-backed government in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Al Qaeda's members pledge allegiance to bin Laden, who was
considered the group's ``emir,'' the indictment said.
</P>
<P>
   To finance his operations, the indictment says that bin Laden
established several businesses in Sudan after establishing his
headquarters in Khartoum in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   It said these businesses included a holding company called Wadi
al Aqiq, a construction business known as al Themar al Mubaraka, an
investment company called Ladin International, an investment
company called Taba Investments, and a transportation company,
Qudarat Transport.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, the authorities said, el-Hage moved from Sudan to
Nairobi, Kenya, where he set up a base for Al Qaeda's operations in
that country.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
